<HEADLINE>
FOR STRAWBERRY, IT'S SIMPLY BUSINESS AS USUAL
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBA-YANKS-TAMPA) 
(nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Darryl Strawberry left his house in Fort Lee, N.J.,
on Monday, drove to an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting in Manhattan
and continued to Yankee Stadium for a night game against the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry said that he begins each day with the one-hour
meetings and that they are the most important part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to take care of myself first now,'' Strawberry said.
``That's what I'm most concerned with.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 28 days since Strawberry was recalled from Class AAA
Columbus to give his crumbling career one more chance with the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   When the 37-year-old Strawberry rejoined the Yankees, General
Manager Brian Cashman discussed how the player needed to win a
post-season roster spot and Manager Joe Torre was vague about
Strawberry's future.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious that the Yankees were not holding a spot for
Strawberry. He had to convince them that he was still a threat and
that his surgically repaired left knee was fit enough for him to
play three straight days. It took Strawberry about a week to prove
he still belonged, and now speculation about the post-season roster
includes Strawberry as a definite part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I proud of that?'' Strawberry said. ``The most important
thing for me was not being worried about it. When I got the
opportunities, I knew I'd show my abilities and what I could do.
You got to remember I've been in this game a long time. What most
people don't understand is I do not press. The way things turned
out, of course, I feel good about myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He should. After Strawberry was arrested on charges of
possessing cocaine and soliciting a prostitute in Tampa, Fla., on
April 14, he was suspended from major league baseball for 113 days
and his career was placed in a tenuous position. But George
Steinbrenner showed silent support for Strawberry, who is making
his fourth comeback with the Yankees since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   With Ricky Ledee blossoming in left field, switch-hitter Chili
Davis entrenched as the designated hitter and Jim Leyritz as a
right-handed hitter coming off the bench, Strawberry had to show he
belonged. He has done that; entering Monday night's game, he had
reached base in 27 of 50 plate appearances and was batting .378
with two home runs, two stolen bases and five runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for him because, just a few months ago, he really
didn't know where he was going,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have to fight through the chemo and stuff that alters your
personality, I think it's a great story and I'm happy for him,''
Torre said of Strawberry's bout with colon cancer. ``He's been
terrific for me for the four years I've been here. I know he can
still get it going and still be a force at the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   It is incredible how Strawberry has crept into the lineup for a
team that had been in first place for weeks without him, although
Davis' prolonged slump has given Strawberry more opportunities.
Since Davis smacked five hits and had six RBIs against the Indians
on July 24, he is 27 for 144 (.188 average) with four homers and 13
RBIs and has looked like a weary 39-year-old. That is why
Strawberry, who was fighting simply to be a pinch-hitter a month
ago, will start some post-season games as the DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not thinking about it,'' Strawberry said. ``You play
the game with some knowledge and you know what you're supposed to
do. This is getting exciting now around here. This is when you want
to be out there. We're trying to get back to the Promised Land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
