<SLUG> BC-FBN-UNDERWOOD-WOUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NECK WOUND TO DOLPHINS' UNDERWOOD WAS SELF-INFLICTED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN U. BACON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ The curious case of Dimitrius Underwood has
taken a stunning turn, with the police in Lansing, Mich., saying
Monday that the neck wound that Underwood, a Miami Dolphins
defensive end, sustained on Sunday was self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood is in Sparrow Hospital in nearby Lansing, where he
underwent surgery on Sunday, and his condition was listed Monday as
fair. Underwood's family in Fayetteville, N.C., requested that no
further information be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going through a real rough time, like any family would
at a time like this,'' said Lansing Police Lt. Raymond Hall, who
added that Underwood was cooperating with the police. Hall also
said the police relied on evidence and witnesses' statements to
determine that Underwood had cut his own throat.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said a woman in a car was yelling and pointing the police
to the 22-year-old Underwood, who was running down a street near
Michigan's Capitol, covered with blood from a knife wound to the
throat. The night before he had been arrested and jailed on a
charge of not paying child support for his 17-month-old twins.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's events were the culmination of a series of
incidents going back a year. Underwood, a 6-foot-6-inch, 276-pound
player with uncommon speed, had sat his senior season at Michigan
State with a less-than-serious ankle injury. After being a surprise
first-round pick of the Minnesota Vikings, he disappeared from the
team a day after signing a $5.3 million contract. He forfeited a
$1.75 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   He later signed with Miami for $395,000 but had not played this
season because of a shoulder injury. The Dolphins had a bye Sunday
and had granted their players time off until Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood returned to Lansing, west of the Michigan State
campus, where the police arrested him about 7 p.m. Saturday on a
warrant for failing to pay child support to Chastity Dyer, the
mother of their twins, who live in Lansing. A few hours after the
police admitted Underwood to the Ingham County Jail in Mason, an
unidentified woman posted Underwood's $500 bond, but he wanted to
remain in jail.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ingham County Sheriff Gene Wrigglesworth, the woman
waited for about 45 minutes before leaving. About 11 p.m.,
Wrigglesworth said, he kicked out Underwood after finding him still
deep in conversation with a fellow prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Kay Van Ellis said Underwood was unfailingly polite.
About 11:45, the woman returned, and they drove off together, the
police said. It is not known whether it was the same woman who
alerted the police to the wounded Underwood the next day. And what
happened between 11:45 p.m. Saturday and 12:45 Sunday p.m., when
Underwood was found bleeding, is still being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Coach Jimmy Johnson, who has a history of signing troubled
players, said Monday in a statement: ``I have talked to the nurses
there and have passed on the word that we are 100 percent
supportive of him. Our No. 1 concern is his health and well-being.
He is going through some difficult times right now, and we're with
him all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood's coach at Michigan State, Nick Saban, offered similar
sentiments at his weekly news conference Monday. Yet, Saban added:
``We tried to help him last year. Dimitrius' behavior over a little
bit of time here has been unusual. I know that the Dolphins have
tried to help him now. He's a good person, and a good guy, who was
going through some hard times right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything we can do to help him, I'd love to do it.
We just hope he gets better.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Underwood quit the the Vikings, Saban said he had
told 14 National Football League teams that had contacted him about
Underwood's erratic behavior in college, which included unexcused
absences. The Vikings had not talked to Saban before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   After signing with Miami, Underwood showed up a day late, but
Johnson said: ``He had an excellent practice and without question
he's an excellent prospect. We had him rated as the top defensive
end in the draft, and nothing he did today makes us change our
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   When he walked out on the Vikings, Underwood said he was torn
between a desire to pursue the ministry and the need to support his
children. He never really explained why he decided to come back
with the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard to say,'' he said in August. ``It's probably
like Einstein trying to explain the theory of relativity to you
guys. It'd take all day and you probably still wouldn't understand
it. I know I wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a higher power than money. The NFL's a great thing,
but you've got a higher power. Everything that wakes people up in a
day is not the same for everybody. Some people wake up for the
money chase. I wake up to a different beat. I wake up to the beat
of God. I felt like that's not where He wanted me to be at this
time, but, you know, I'm here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
