<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-STICK-LADN-(SLANG     09-28 1985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-STICK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY MEMORIES BLOW IN THE BREEZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ No one was hated more at Candlestick Park than
Tom Lasorda. No one loved it more.
</P>
<P>
   In his 20 years as Dodgers manager, Lasorda was a carnival
barker at one of baseball's greatest sideshows, blowing kisses at
the harsh winds and angry mobs that are as much a part of the place
as Mays, McCovey and Marichal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's is the only Italian I ever knew who was booed in San
Francisco,'' said the late Dolph Camilli, onetime Dodgers first
baseman and Bay Area lifer. ``They loved to hate him here. He was
the perfect villain.''
</P>
<P>
   So perfect, in fact, that the Giants have asked him to return
Thursday at the end of the club's three-game series with the
Dodgers to help say goodbye to the 'Stick, which is closing for
baseball after 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda will make one last walk from the visiting clubhouse in
the right-field corner to the Dodgers dugout, where he clinched a
title in 1977 and so painfully lost one in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that the Dodgers were 180-160 at the stadium
now called 3Com Park. Since 1960, they won eight pennants to the
Giants' two. But more often than not it wasn't about the numbers.
It was the sweet but often bitter differences between North and
South that began in the Polo Grounds and Ebbetts Field and
continues from the South Bay to Sausalito.
</P>
<P>
   It was wrapping yourself in a sleeping bag in July to stay warm.
It was watching Bill Russell's cap fly off at shortstop and stick
to the outfield fence. Or Reggie Smith and Davey Lopes climbing
into the stands after getting hit by chicken bones.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you don't remember the name Mike Ivie, but here they
remember his pinch grand slam off Don Sutton in 1978 that kept the
improbable Giants in first place for one more day.
</P>
<P>
   There was a morning Old Timers Game between Dodgers and Giants
of the '70s that was played with an intensity that no one has seen
since, well, since the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Vida Blue was throwing 90 and Dusty Baker, now the Giants
manager but still looking right in a Dodgers uniform, took him
deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me to take one more walk and blow kisses to the
fans,'' Lasorda said over the weekend. ``I think it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many Pac Bell Parks they build here in homage to
the future, Candlestick always will represent memories that won't
fade even when the fog rolls in.
</P>
<P>
   Here are one man's 10. You might have 10 others. That's the
beauty. &QL; 
MORGAN'S HOME RUN &QL; 
Oct. 3, 1982
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had been eliminated the day before and knocking out
the Dodgers became the year's highlight. The Dodgers had rallied
from way back to catch the Atlanta Braves, but now they were
stumbling. In the last Dodgers games for Steve Garvey and Ron Cey,
future Hall of Famer Joe Morgan hit a three-run homer off
left-hander Terry Forster in the seventh inning to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit some pretty meaningful home runs, but the one I hit
to beat the Dodgers was right up there. One of the top two or three
in my career,'' said Morgan, a Bay Area native who grew up rooting
for the Giants. ``It meant so much to the Giants and their fans to
beat the Dodgers that day.'' &QL; 
MAYHEM &QL; 
Aug. 22, 1965
</P>
<P>
   The tension of a tight pennant race spilled over into violence
when Giants pitcher Juan Marichal struck Dodgers John Roseboro in
the head with his bat in the third inning after claiming the
catcher had nicked his ear throwing the ball back to the catcher. A
14-minute, on-field brawl ensued and police were also summoned to
restore order among the Candlestick crowd of 42,807.
</P>
<P>
   What made it more dramatic was that Willie Mays, who acted as a
peacemaker during the brawl and even wiped blood from Roseboro's
forehead, came back to hit a game-winning home run against a
flustered Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can thank Mays that there wasn't a real riot,'' Dodgers
outfielder Lou Johnson said. ``If not for him, it would have been a
lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Marichal was suspended for nine days and fined $1,750. He later
was sued by Roseboro, who received a $7,500 settlement. &QL; 
WATERED-DOWN WILLS &QL; 
Aug. 12, 1962
</P>
<P>
   Maury Wills was in the midst of his MVP season when he recorded
a then-record 104 stolen bases. The Dodgers came in with a 5{-game
lead over the Giants but got swept in three games. One reason: The
Candlestick grounds crew watered down the basepaths so severely
Friday and Saturday that it almost was unplayable. Wills was
grounded and got so angry he was ejected for Saturday's game for
arguing with the umpire about the condition of the field. Sunday,
the umpires insisted the grounds crew add sand, which made
conditions worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a cold from that day,'' Wills said last week at
Dodger Stadium. During batting practice ``We went into the
clubhouse and someone came in saying, `You guys have to see what
they are doing to the field. We went out and saw the grounds crew
without nozzles hosing down spots on the infield for three four
minutes at a time.'' &QL; 
MARSHALL FREAKS OUT &QL; 
April 21, 1987
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were on their way to a National League pennant, their
second since coming to San Francisco. The Dodgers, even with Pedro
Guerrero back from missing most of 1986 with knee surgery, were
going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But the rivalry showed its intensity _ and ugliness _ when
Giants manager Roger Craig ordered pitcher Scott Garrelts to walk
Guerrero to pitch to Marshall. Marshall hit a three-run homer into
the left-field stands to break an 8-8 tie, but he didn't stop
there. As he rounded the bases, Marshall taunted Garrelts and
pointed sharply at the Giants dugout.
</P>
<P>
   When he touched home, Marshall waved his arms at Craig. Alex
Trevino, the next Dodgers batter, never stood a chance. Garrelts
threw at his head, touching off a bench-clearing brawl. Several
Dodgers went into the stands after fans and dozens of arrests were
made. ``I didn't mean to cause a riot,'' said the usually quiet
Marshall, ``and I didn't mean to get Alex thrown at. Looking back
at it, I wish I hadn't done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his decision, Craig said, ``Mike Marshall is not a
pimple on Pedro Guerrero's butt.'' &QL; 
BEGINNING OF THE END &QL; 
Sept. 18, 1997
</P>
<P>
   Many think the beginning of Bill Russell's demise as Dodgers
manager can be traced to the day reserve Giants catcher Brian
Johnson hit a 12th-inning homer off left-hander Mark Guthrie and
shattered the season's momentum.
</P>
<P>
   After a second-half rush moved the Dodgers into first place,
they were tied with the Giants with nine games to play. They
finished second, two games back. Guthrie had been one of Russell's
most consistent relievers but was fading in September, finishing
the month with a 23.14 ERA. Johnson, a fastball hitter, hit a
fastball down the middle into an impossible wind, but the ball
carried into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big moment in my life,'' said Johnson, who has
played little since.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the homer, Russell is better known for two questionable
strategy moves that might have cost his team a chance to win. The
first was not pinch-running for Mike Piazza after he singled to
open the 10th. The Dodgers got three hits that inning but didn't
score. Giants closer Rod Beck struck out Todd Zeile. Then Russell
let slow-footed pinch-hitter Eddie Murray come to the plate. Murray
grounded into a double play and the threat was over. Less than a
year later, so was Russell. &QL; 
GREATEST GAME EVER &QL; 
Sept. 28, 1986
</P>
<P>
   That was the headline the next day in the San Francisco
Chronicle after an otherwise meaningless late-season game went 16
innings and lasted 5 hours, 45 minutes before the Giants won 6-5 on
a Bob Brenly RBI double. The Dodgers used a major-league-record 27
players, including nine pitchers. The Giants went with 25,
including pitchers Jeff Bockus and Randy Bockus in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sax, closing in on Montreal's Tim Raines for the NL
batting title, went 0 for 7 to end a hitting streak at 25 games.
The Giants scored two runs in the bottom of the ninth to tie, and
both teams scored two runs in the 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Minton, the winning pitcher, doubled in the 16th with two
outs. Brenly followed with a double and Minton, who was carrying
quite a paunch that season, thought he was going to have to take
out catcher Mike Scioscia at the plate. Scioscia stepped aside.
``There was no way I was going to leave this game,'' Minton said.
``It was my entire season.'' &QL; 
MAYS SETS NL RECORD &QL; 
May 4, 1966
</P>
<P>
   Willie Mays had been a dead pull hitter in New York because of
the 260-foot left-field wall in the Polo Grounds. But when he got
to Candlestick, strong winds made it impossible for a right-handed
power hitter. Against Dodgers left-hander Claude Osteen, Mays went
the other way and broke Mel Ott's National League record by hitting
his 512th career homer. He finished with 660, third all-time.
``What a relief it was,'' said Mays, who went 3 for 23 after
hitting No. 511 a week earlier in Houston. ``I never thought it
would come.''
</P>
<P>
   Osteen, now the Dodgers pitching coach, remembers it well: ``I
threw him a high changeup away and he hit it off the right-field
foul poll. No one took advantage of that wind the way Mays did. . .
. He was a pull hitter on the road and an opposite-field hitter at
home.'' &QL; 
TOMMY'S FIRST TITLE &QL; 
Sept. 21, 1977
</P>
<P>
   Tommy John pitched a six-hitter and Rick Monday hit an
upper-deck home run. But make no mistake. This 3-1 victory over the
Giants that clinched the National League West belonged to
first-year manager Tom Lasorda. As his players, many of whom he had
managed in the minors, sprayed him with champagne in the postgame
clubhouse, Lasorda bellowed, ``How sweet it is, how sweet it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It was particularly sweet because the Dodgers had unseated their
powerful rivals, the two-time World Series champion Cincinnati Reds
to win the Western Division. As he hugged John, Lasorda told him he
would be starting the NL playoffs against Philadelphia. Two years
earlier, John's career appeared to be over when he underwent
radical reconstructive surgery on his left elbow, a procedure that
now bears his name. He did not get along with manager Walter
Alston. Then along came Lasorda, who held the job for 20 years. &QL; 
REUSS' NO-HITTER &QL; 
June 27, 1985
</P>
<P>
   If the tradition of not talking during a no-hitter was going to
be broken, it was going to happen in Candlestick. Left-hander Jerry
Reuss, a high-ball pitcher and 14-game loser the year before when
he came over from Pittsburgh for Rick Rhoden, had not allowed a
basehit after six innings. It was then that a fan crawled over the
top of the visiting dugout and yelled, ``Way to go Jerry, you've
got a no-hitter going. Keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuss did, with a first-inning, throwing error by shortstop Bill
Russell keeping it from a perfect game. On the final out, former
Dodger Billy North tapped back to the mound and Reuss threw to
Steve Garvey. Reuss won 18 games that year, including six shutouts.
He also made the All-Star team headed by his former Pittsburgh
manager Chuck Tanner. But the no-hitter was the highlight, even if
someone tried to jinx it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I leave that guy any passes,'' he said. &QL; 
HIDEO NOMO'S FIRST START &QL; 
May 2, 1995
</P>
<P>
   Never was a visiting player cheered at Candlestick the way Nomo
was, the first Japanese-born player to pitch in the big leagues in
30 years. And though he didn't figure in the decision, lost by the
Dodgers 4-3 in 15 innings, Nomo's presence and whirling pitching
motion touched off an international sensation. He allowed no runs
and just one hit in five innings before scores of Japanese flags
among the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The game was televised back to his native Japan, where thousands
of citizens watched on big screens posted in large cities even
though game time was 4:30 a.m. Nomo went on to win 13 games and be
named National League Rookie of the Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
