<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CHECHNYA-NYT &LR;      09-28 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RUSSIA'S CHECHEN GAMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 28:
</P>
<P>
   Russia's bombing of Chechnya has been advertised by Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev as a plan to ``eliminate the bandits''
terrorizing Russian apartment dwellers and to create a zone of
Russian security around Chechnya. It is a risky battle plan _ a
pursuit of Islamic militants in the Caucasus that threatens to
create political and military havoc not only in Chechnya but in
Moscow as well.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, terrorists have killed almost 300 people,
setting bombs in apartments in Moscow and southern Russia that have
killed innocent people as they sleep. This has provoked demands for
swift action, but caused some alarming overreaction, including the
detention of thousands of dark-skinned Moscow residents in the
search for the few Islamic militants believed to be behind the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pursuit of terrorists has led to the bombing of Grozny
and other areas of Chechnya, raising questions about whether the
Russians are bombing for political reasons or as a kind of
eye-for-an-eye revenge. If the military could really pinpoint
terrorist nests, this bombing might be worth the effort. But many
of these militants, who also range into neighboring Dagestan, are
scattered through the mountains, not in the main city of Grozny.
Unlike the bombing of Belgrade, which Russians are mistakenly using
for comparison, bombing Grozny is not necessary to bring the
government to the table. Aslan Maskhadov, the moderate leader of
Chechnya, is already urging talks. Unfortunately, Russia's prime
minister, Vladimir Putin, has said he sees no use in such a meeting
at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of routing terrorists, Russian bombs and Russian troops
sealing the Chechen borders could undermine Maskhadov's efforts to
control the chaos spreading in his country. Moreover, the Russians
might not find the West as tolerant about a second Chechen war,
after a 1996 peace agreement that gave the country de facto
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier Chechen war and the peace agreement are a source of
deep anger in some segments of Russian society, in part because of
the shock at seeing the once-mighty Soviet military reduced to
incompetence. This new round of bombing, sadly, is far more
popular. With parliamentary elections in December and a
presidential vote set for next year, a second Chechen war may be
designed to give the illusion of power to a weakened Russian
government. But the first one, as many Russians and Chechens know
well, was one too many.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
