<HEADER>
A8380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CLINTONS-NYT &LR;      09-28 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HOME FINANCING FOR THE CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 28:
</P>
<P>
   President and Mrs. Clinton have reportedly given up on the idea
of financing the purchase of their new house in Westchester County
with a $1.35 million loan guarantee from Terry McAuliffe, a
Democratic fund-raiser who has raised millions for the Clintons'
legal defense fund and the presidential library. The step may not
do much to restore Clinton's record for financial appearances, but
it is a smart move for Hillary Rodham Clinton. By securing a normal
commercial mortgage, Mrs. Clinton can assure New York voters that
if elected to the Senate, she would be acting for their good rather
than for that of financial benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   As Don Van Natta Jr. of The Times reported on Saturday, the
Clintons turned to McAuliffe for this singularly personal favor
after former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and two former White
House chiefs of staff, Thomas McLarty 3d and Erskine Bowles,
declined to help. These former Clinton aides did the Clintons a
favor by not getting involved in their personal finances. Critics
of the arrangement with McAuliffe have questioned whether it
complies with the letter and spirit of federal gift and campaign
contribution laws. A tone-deaf White House has defended the deal
with technical legal arguments that miss the real point.
</P>
<P>
   By its very nature, such largess compromises the dignity and
integrity of the office. No sitting president should accept loans
or any other form of personal financing from anyone other than
close relatives or institutional lenders. The fact that former
President Reagan allowed wealthy friends to buy a house for him
while he was still in office was a regrettable precedent, not an
example to follow.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Clinton, renouncing the McAuliffe loan would be smart
politics. It would give voters fatigued by the Clintons' odd
propensity for scandal a heartening signal that, on her own, she is
ready to break from the ethical sloppiness of the Clinton White
House. A straightforward mortgage with no special favors would
allow her to start her New York residency with a cleaner slate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8382 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-HNS &LR;      09-28 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CINCINNATI _ It's another day in the heat of the playoff race, but
you would never know it by the atmosphere in the Cincinnati Reds'
clubhouse.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aaron Boone is cavorting through the room with his pants pulled
belly-button high, walking a walk that seems to belong in a skit
from Saturday Night Live. Only it's Sunday afternoon, and there's a
fairly important baseball game to be played.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pudgy reliever Dennis Reyes is flexing his muscles in
the direction of a teammate, who in his best Austin Powers voice
says, `Nah, baby!' Hans or Franz he is not.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the Reds return to their clubhouse to celebrate
another dramatic victory. The hero of the day answers to the name
Pokey.
</P>
<P>
   What a bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``From top to bottom, this is probably the loosest group I've
ever seen,'' said Reds general manager Jim Bowden, whose
personality fits that of the team he has built into a contender.
``I really believe that's the character of the manager, the coaches
and the 25 guys.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it would appear the Reds aren't taking their
improbable jaunt toward the playoffs too seriously, and why should
they? Few took them seriously back in spring training when they
fashioned themselves as playoff contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, they have everyone's attention, and they'll
have a national stage under the big top tonight when they open a
critical two-game series at the Astrodome. The Reds have won seven
of their last nine games, including five in a row, to pull into a
tie with the Astros atop the National League Central. On Monday,
they rallied from a five-run deficit to beat the Cardinals 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all like kids in a candy store,'' Reds first baseman
Sean Casey said. ``It's awesome because of the magnitude of every
game. Every day you come to the park is like the first week of the
season _ so exciting. Everyone is fired up. This is what you play
for.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Reds have been enjoying the sweet taste of victory
over and over again, the Astros have been having candy taken from
them as if they were babies, losing six of nine games on a
tummy-aching road trip to St. Louis, Pittsburgh and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets, whom the Reds were chasing for the wild card, went
on a six-game losing streak and have surrendered the driver's seat
in that race to the Reds _ and the Astros, who may have to settle
for the wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this team being very competitive in the Central
Division,'' shortstop Barry Larkin said of his preseason assessment
of the Reds, whose last postseason appearance was in 1995. ``What
does that mean? In the past, playing .500 meant you were close to
winning this division. As an organization, we have nothing to lose.
As ballplayers, we have a chance to do something really special
here, and if we don't get it done, it would be frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin's personal frustration was an issue over the past two
years, and it reached the point that he didn't know if he wanted to
remain with the team through a rebuilding process.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew the Reds would retool so quickly?
</P>
<P>
   Through some shrewd moves and clever evaluations, Bowden _
working on a shoestring payroll _ added players such as Casey, Greg
Vaughn, Denny Neagle, Juan Guzman, Mike Cameron and Michael Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   The Casey trade is last year's news, but the other maneuvers are
enough to make Bowden the front-runner for Executive of the Year,
an honor that went to Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of this team is how well we came together so
quickly,'' third baseman Aaron Boone said. ``Early on, you could
see that this was a team that comes to play every day and a team
that plays unselfishly. If you add those two ingredients to some
talent, you have a chance to do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have surprised a lot of other people, but we haven't
surprised ourselves. We're having a lot of fun right now. The
importance that each day brings is nice. Win or lose, it seems like
tomorrow is even more important. That makes it a lot of fun to come
to the yard every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the days when it's not so fun to be at the ballpark,
veteran leadership has prevailed. Bowden recalls a day earlier this
season when some of the players thought it was too hot to take
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vaughn grabbed his bat and started heading out there, and they
all followed him like little puppy dogs,'' the general manager
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds also follow the leadership of their manager, a
68-year-old, cigar-smoking baseball lifer whose ability to relate
to today's young players was questioned in some quarters. The
answer to that question can be found in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful skipper Jack McKeon has presided over the Reds' rise on
the field, creating a loose environment that has his team bringing
an almost carefree attitude to the Astrodome tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is on them; it's not on us,'' McKeon said,
referring to the Astros. ``Everyone expected them to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, few expected the Reds to be playing meaningful games
in the last week of the season, but their remarkable run has almost
everyone rooting for the underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense that a lot of people around the country are
pulling for us, and that's nice to see,'' Boone said. ``Everyone
loves the underdog, but at the same time we don't feel like
underdogs. We feel like we can play with all of (the playoff
contenders).
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what happens, we're proud of the year we had.
But every man on this team would be extremely disappointed if we
didn't make the playoffs. Anyone who thinks we're just happy to be
going out there is dead wrong. That's not the case at all. We want
to get to the playoffs, and if we continue to play well, we'll get
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
