<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8383 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     09-28 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S PAUS LIKELY TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The beleaguered Bruins received both good and bad
news Monday, when they learned starting quarterback Cory Paus is
expected to play this week but tailback DeShaun Foster might not.
</P>
<P>
   Foster sprained his right ankle early in the loss at Stanford
but continued to play and rushed for 100 yards. The ankle swelled
overnight and he's questionable for Saturday's game at Arizona
State.
</P>
<P>
   Foster has been diagnosed with a high sprain (above the ankle
bone), which takes longer to heal than low sprains. Receiver Danny
Farmer suffered the same injury in training camp and missed three
weeks, but Foster's is not as severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is he'll practice very little this week and
give it a try Saturday,'' head athletic trainer Geoff Schaadt said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Paus returned to practice after missing last week
because of bruised ribs he received in the Fresno State game. He
looked sharp, threw his usual tight spirals and is expected to
start against Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome,'' Paus said. ``I hadn't touched a ball in a
week, and I felt real good. It's a little painful when I throw
hard, but if we had to play tomorrow, I could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sneezing still hurts. But I can brush my teeth, blow my nose,
drive and do all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, second-string quarterback Drew Bennett injured his
right (throwing) elbow on the final play of the Stanford game _ it
was bent backward while in the throwing position _ and is
questionable. If Bennett can't play, sophomore Scott McEwan becomes
the No. 2 quarterback. If Bennett can't play and Paus re-injures
his tender ribs, McEwan becomes the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get (McEwan) some more reps in practice,'' Toledo
said. ``We're also an injury or two away from (fourth-stringer)
Ryan McCann being the backup. We were so lucky for four years
because Cade (McNown) never got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The injuries to Foster and Bennett come at a crucial time for
the Bruins (2-2, 0-1), who dropped from the top-25 rankings for the
first time in two years and must defeat Arizona State (1-2, 0-1) to
remain in Rose Bowl contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pivotal game for both teams,'' Toledo said. ``It's a
good game, a TV game. Basically, a bowl game's on the line. The one
that wins is in the hunt. The one that loses is out of the Rose
Bowl race. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to remain positive. We're a young team and they're
fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins can survive without Foster for a week or two because
Jermaine Lewis and Keith Brown are experienced, effective runners.
(Brown is from Phoenix and will have 55 friends and family members
at the game.)
</P>
<P>
   But the season hinges on the quarterback situation: Either Paus
plays the full game or Bennett improves his performance. He
completed 61 percent of his passes against Stanford but missed
countless receivers downfield. Farmer did not catch a pass and
Freddie Mitchell did not catch a pass in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bennett) knows the offense,'' Toledo said. ``He knows where
people are, but at times he doesn't find those people, he doesn't
pull the trigger. That's what's disappointing. It gets back to
potential and performance. Performance is what matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
