<HEADER>
A8384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EDIT-YEN-NYT &LR;      09-28 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-YEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A RUINOUS YEN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 28:
</P>
<P>
   Masaru Hayami, governor of the Bank of Japan, tantalized Western
finance officials meeting over the weekend in Washington by hinting
that the bank would begin printing more yen _ a necessary step if
Japan is to pull itself out of a decade-long slump. But the
governor issued no firm commitments. Indeed, he even denied that
his words represented a change in policy.
</P>
<P>
   That is dismaying. Bank officials resist pumping up the domestic
money supply out of a remarkable fear of inflation. But Japan's
problem is the opposite _ deflation. Japanese prices have been
falling for years, and the longer they fall the more Japanese
consumers postpone buying until prices fall even further. That
downward spiral of prices and spending can become a recipe for
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Western economists have been hammering on bank officials to
reverse course and throw lots more yen into the economy.
Repeatedly, officials said ``no.'' Over the weekend, an optimist
could say, they at least changed the answer to ``maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese economy has stagnated for most of the decade,
growing at a trifling annual rate of about 1 percent recently. Adam
Posen, of the Institute for International Economics, notes that the
Japanese have finally adopted sound fiscal and financial policies.
They are running huge government deficits and clearing bad loans
off the books of commercial banks so they can start lending to
healthy companies again. But monetary policy remains dangerously
passive.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese bank officials say they are already running a loose
monetary policy, with short-term interest rates already within an
eyelash of zero. Even so, throwing more yen into Japan's economy
could stimulate output. The Japanese could use the new yen to buy
dollars, driving the value of the yen lower and making Japanese
goods cheaper to buy. That would stimulate exports. The bank could
also buy bonds and other assets, driving up their prices and making
consumers feel wealthier. That too could stimulate consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's bank officials appear genuinely confused about setting
policy in an era of deflation. But there are also signs of a
destructive turf war. Until last year, the bank took its marching
orders on monetary policy from the Ministry of Finance. Now it is
independent and appears jealously protective of its new
responsibility. Although Finance Ministry officials want the bank
to drive down the value of a soaring yen, the bank refuses to print
new yen.
</P>
<P>
   A rising yen is not so much of a problem by itself as it is a
symptom of a dangerously tight monetary policy. If Japan were
printing enough yen to keep domestic prices from falling, it would
also be printing enough yen to keep the yen from soaring on foreign
exchange markets. Hayami insisted that his pledge over the weekend
to ``respond appropriately and timely to developments in the
economy as well as financial markets'' represented no significant
change in policy. The frightening possibility is that he is
serious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
