<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8388 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-LINCOLN-     09-28 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-LINCOLN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN TAKES OVER M'S HELM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The first order of business for new Mariners' chairman
and CEO Howard Lincoln is to prove to Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez that the team's owners are committed to rebuilding a
playoff-caliber team by increasing payroll.
</P>
<P>
   In replacing John Ellis as the front man for M's ownership, the
shift in CEOs is seen as indication that majority owner Hiroshi
Yamauchi, president of Nintendo Co. Ltd. of Koyto, Japan, is
asserting more control over the franchise. It also comes at a time
when the ballclub faces some critical business decisions, including
the effort to re-sign Griffey and Rodriguez and replace Woody
Woodward as vice president of baseball operations.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln also is expected to put a face on an ownership group
that includes 15 other owners who have various interests in the
club, which was purchased from Jeff Smulyan for $100 million plus
$25 million in operating capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very much an obligation to enunciate not only the goals
of the ownership of the franchise but to take on the job of
answering the questions of the fans and the critics,'' Lincoln
said. ``I intend to be very active in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   First up is the effort to keep the Mariners' two superstars in
Seattle and playing in Safeco Field, which Lincoln said has
increased revenue and attendance to where the team can increase its
payroll from the current $54 million to between $65 million and $70
million next year. The budget will be locked in by Nov. 1, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go in with the full expectation that payroll will be
going up in that range, and we will also go in with the full
knowledge that the ownership group has made definitive written
offers to both Alex and Ken that would make both of the players the
two highest paid players in the history of baseball,'' Lincoln
said.
</P>
<P>
   He won't make the numbers public, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously think that both of those players are very
valuable,'' Lincoln said. ``But I am not going to negotiate the
Alex Rodriguez and Ken Griffey contracts in public. I'm not going
to posture about it either. I'm going to let the fans know what we
have done, and I think it's fair to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln said the actual negotiations would be handled by club
president Chuck Armstrong and whoever is hired to replace Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey downplayed whether an increase in club payroll would
affect his decision to re-sign with the M's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to stay, I'm going to stay, whether the payroll's
$50 million, $80 million, $100 or $200 million,'' he said Monday in
Arlington, Texas, where the M's played the Texas Rangers. ``If I
don't want to stay, they can raise it to whatever they want. No
matter what they do, the decision is mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez declined to be specific about the team's offer but
said it was ``nothing that excited me. I'm not excited by dollar
signs. What excited me is bringing guys here I can play with for
the next several years. That's the motivating factor for me. This
wasn't going to excite me, no matter what the offer was.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the offer was presented to him and his agent,
Scott Boras, at a meeting with Armstrong and Lincoln over the
weekend. He also said he prefers to wait until after the season to
discuss the matter with family.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview, Lincoln offered no apologies for
the owners' decision to try to recover $60 million of the $100
million in cost overruns from construction of the $517 million new
stadium. The Public Facility District that oversaw construction has
taken the position that the M's were responsible for all cost
overruns, while the ballclub wants to tap into excess revenue
derived from the taxes that were set up to pay the $372 million
public portion of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that it was appropriate to bring it to the attention of
the public before the opening of Safeco Field,'' Lincoln said of
the dispute. ``I'm well aware that this is an unpopular,
controversial cause. It's caused all sorts of upset among the fans,
the political leadership of the county and the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in my background, I'm used to fighting for unpopular
causes. I'm confident that when all of the facts are on the table,
the public's view of what happened here will be much different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had requested that the cost-overrun dispute be put
to mediation. But the PFD rejected the move, and speculation is
that the M's will file a lawsuit to enforce their interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Concerning other front-office issues, Lincoln gave his vote of
confidence to the job that Armstrong has done in his 13 years with
the club, and said that Armstrong would be responsible for hiring a
replacement for Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not something that will be decided by the board of
directors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln joined Nintendo of America (NOA) in 1983 as its senior
vice president and general counsel and has seen the business
skyrocket during his tenure with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Because he's turning 60 next year, Lincoln wanted to step down
from his Nintendo responsibilities and take more of a role in
overseeing his other passion: the baseball team. He disclosed that
Nintendo's Yamauchi is now considered the majority owner after
major league baseball officials two years ago quietly removed a
restriction that limited his actual voting interest in the team to
49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The restriction, imposed when the club was purchased, was based
on fears from other team owners that baseball would be threatened
by a huge influx of foreign investment. Yamauchi actually paid $75
million of the original investment in the team. Lincoln's move to
CEO indicates he'll be the primary liaison between the team and its
majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm personally desirous of reducing the the amount of time I'm
spending with Nintendo, but I'm personally up to the challenge (of
being CEO) and something tells me this is going to be very, very
exiting and a difficult job,'' he said. ``I kind of like that, and
I think that I can pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln's ascension was lauded by American League president Gene
Budig, who called it a ``wise choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He replaces a person who has earned universal respect within
major league baseball,'' Budig said in a statement. ``It is
reassuring to know that John Ellis will continue to represent
Seattle on major league baseball's powerful Executive Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, 70, had hinted for several months that he was seeking to
take a less active role with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to complete the Safeco Field project and open the
magnificent facility for all the fans of the Pacific Northwest,''
he said in a statement Monday. ``With that done, I am ready to hand
over responsibility to Howard and help the Mariners in any way I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella, who has one year left on his contract, saw
the ownership move as helping to improve his ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel he's going to give the organization every opportunity
to succeed on the field,'' Piniella said. ``He's very interested in
making games at Safeco Field fan friendly, creating the best
experience he can for fans. And with it, naturally, comes the
fielding of a good competitive club that can contend.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Angelo Bruscas can be reached at 206-448-8010
</P>
<P>
   or angelobruscas &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
