<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTABILITY AT LAST WITH NEW M'S CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ First, the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez?
</P>
<P>
   If turnover continues at this rate, Mariners fans by this time
next season will be calling Freddy Garcia ``old-timer.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it can be argued forcefully that there are in the
tepid Mariner bath water precious few babies.
</P>
<P>
   In other words: It's about bloody time.
</P>
<P>
   To the average Mariners fan, Monday's long-expected change at
CEO, in which Howard Lincoln takes over for John Ellis, may not
seem significant. And from a day-to-day basis in baseball, it
isn't, especially relative to the GM job.
</P>
<P>
   But from the standpoint of accountability _ something the
Mariners have had less of than middle relief or lefty hitting _ it
looms large. The endless loop finally ends.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the question:
</P>
<P>
   Howard, are you nuts?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like a good fight,'' he said, smiling. ``I like a tough
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the Clanton brothers at the OK Corral.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln takes over at the point of highest tension in the club's
personnel history _ the pending free agency of Griffey and
Rodriguez, which is threatening to supplant the fate of salmon as
the Northwest's most over-talked, over-written subject.
</P>
<P>
   Besides that agony, Lincoln remains steadfast in ownership's
commitment to pursue tax money to cover $60 million of the cost
overruns on the Guilty Pleasure, a ploy that included holding
hostage the fates of Griffey and Rodriguez unless the demands were
met.
</P>
<P>
   As a lawyer, Lincoln is trained to defend unpopular causes. But
he would have an easier time as tobacco spokesman at Fred Hutch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the owners and organization are better off with Lincoln
at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis was merely a front man, and not a good one. In his
defense, he had to carry a lot of bad water given him by others.
But his unapologetically confrontational style, coupled with his
insincere emotional manipulations, cooked his credibility in this
town.
</P>
<P>
   As with Ellis, Lincoln has only a tiny percentage of ownership.
But he directly represents the $75 million investment of the
uninterested Hiroshi Yamauchi, boss of Nintendo of Japan and pal of
U.S. Sen. Slade Gorton, official American benefactor to the Redmond
video-game maker.
</P>
<P>
   That means Nintendo gets the biggest say in club operations,
especially since major league baseball two years ago quietly
removed its xenophobic limit of 49 percent on the Japanese
investor's vote in ownership decisions.
</P>
<P>
   So Lincoln is the majority interest in the club, and thus on the
hot seat. But he's such a lifelong baseball fan, and so eager to
live out a dream from his Bay Area boyhood, that the Cal-Berkeley
law school grad is retiring in February from his lucrative power
base in high-tech to get figuratively hacked to bits by millions of
people convinced they know his job better than he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a dream come true,'' he said Monday. ``I'm not planning
to turn it into a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   How this job is anyone's dream probably explains baseball's
illogical lure as much as anything. As with many, Lincoln was
seduced when the Mariners charmed Puget Sound and much of baseball
in the fall of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would very much like to see us back to 1995,'' he said. ``My
feeling about that is that it wasn't just a great baseball season,
it really brought the community together in a way that I had never
experienced before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that will ever happen again, but I sure as
hell would like to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the dream moves toward the nightmare of Griffey and
Rodriguez, the M's must hire a GM. For that task, Lincoln gave an
unqualified endorsement to president Chuck Armstrong. With the
departures of Ellis and GM Woody Woodward, Armstrong is emerging
from the makeover as a much larger power broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the organization is comprised of some very talented
people, starting with Chuck,'' Lincoln said. ``I have great
confidence in Chuck. I admire him, his work ethic and his
honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick will be for Armstrong to involve Lincoln, along with
Microsoft's Chris Larson, the largest minority partner, in the GM
selection without getting run over. Many in baseball will counsel
Armstrong that that camel will never stay out of the tent.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong already has allowed both to meet the first GM
candidate, Pat Gillick. The threat is that Lincoln and Larson, long
over their deference to wizened baseball seamheads, think they know
enough in seven years of ownership to make the call.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln assured his inquisitors that he had no intention to play
fantasy baseball with the Mariners, and that the Gillick meeting
was a get-acquainted informality.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he and his fellow owners once assured taxpayers that
they were picking up stadium cost overruns, no problem.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday was close enough to a first day on the job to draw
a courtesy pass, Lincoln rates the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, the law of averages says a guy's gotta keep a promise at
least once.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8009
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
