<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-RECORDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MISUSE OF DRUG TREATMENT RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 28:
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration's plan to use Medicaid billing
records to steer welfare applicants into drug and alcohol treatment
is a dangerous violation of medical confidentiality. Under the
proposal reported by Nina Bernstein in The Times, New York City's
Human Resources Administration would search its Medicaid payment
records for evidence that welfare applicants had in the past sought
drug or alcohol treatment. Applicants whose names turned up in the
records could then be forced into further drug treatment in order
to get or keep benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Federal laws prohibit the disclosure of information about a
patient's getting substance abuse treatment unless the patient
consents to its release, typically for specific purposes. But the
city thinks it can get around these rules because both the Medicaid
records and the welfare lists are kept by the same department. But
that specious argument ignores the fact that the billing records
were created for payment uses and were never intended to be used
for unrelated purposes years later.
</P>
<P>
   This abuse of confidential records is precisely what worries
privacy groups about the creation of large government data bases.
The plan could well deter people from voluntarily seeking drug
treatment if they believe that private records may be used against
them, if not in the welfare context, then in other circumstances.
Worse, there is no indication that such an egregious breach of
confidentiality would actually help welfare recipients get the kind
of treatment they need.
</P>
<P>
   The administrators say that this is a practical way to ferret
out substance abusers who might otherwise deny they have a problem.
But applicants are apt to deny their problems if they think that
the system will punish them for addiction. Welfare advocates say
that half of all people who are required to enter mandatory
treatment programs are cut from all welfare aid because they fail
to comply with program requirements.
</P>
<P>
   A large number fail because they cannot get appropriate
treatment. There are roughly 200 residential treatment slots in the
city for women with children. The administration should focus on
improving treatment options, not misusing confidential records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
