<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVISION CHAMPIONS GET PAST GARCIA, M'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Mariners' last game in Texas was their
high point this year. They shut out the powerful Rangers, moving
their record above .500 at the season's halfway mark, and left town
in second place, five games back.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, however, they had fallen to third, and they've
never risen higher. Last night, they returned to the Ballpark in
Arlington, which was freshly decorated with a ``1999 AL West
Champions'' banner above center field.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mariners scuffle to finish above .500, the Rangers are
trying to secure home-field advantage in the playoffs. They gained
ground in that effort with a 3-2 win over the Mariners last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Texas had a good ballclub all along,'' Mariners
manager Lou Piniella said. ``They've got, what, six players with
100 RBIs, for God's sake, and their bullpen is pretty deep. They've
got some talent out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, one of five Rangers with at least 98 runs batted
in, doubled and scored the first and third runs for the Rangers. In
the second, he came in on a double play grounder by Todd Zeile, and
in the eighth, he scored on a sacrifice fly by Lee Stevens,
breaking a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's eighth-inning double came with one out off Steve
Sinclair (0-1), who relieved Freddy Garcia. After an intentional
walk to Rafael Palmeiro, Jose Mesa walked Zeile to load the bases,
setting up Stevens' sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia worked seven innings, allowing two runs on nine hits and
lowering his earned-run average to 4.11, its lowest since April. He
lost a 2-1 lead in the sixth when MVP candidate Ivan Rodriguez
fouled off six pitches and grounded a single to left, scoring Tom
Goodwin from second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were holding the runner on with our shortstop, and that
created a hole,'' Piniella said. ``But, yeah, Ivan can swing the
bat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas catcher was Garcia's last batter an inning later. With
the bases loaded, Garcia induced a fielder's choice to end the
seventh. Piniella had come to the mound before the at-bat, and
Garcia convinced him he was not tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives me confidence,'' Garcia said. ``A pitcher needs
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also needs run support, and the Mariners' lack of it kept
Garcia from his 17th win, which would have tied a club rookie
record. The M's put baserunners on in every inning Texas starter
Rick Helling pitched, but they scored only in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Ibanez, whose ninth-inning homer won Sunday's Safeco Field
finale, lined a leadoff homer to right. It was Ibanez's eighth of
the year _ all in the second half _ and gave the M's a home run in
their club-record 19th consecutive game. The previous record was 16
games in a row, set in the miracle September of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gipson followed with a triple, and scored on a one-out
sacrifice fly by Alex Rodriguez. A walk and a single put runners at
first and second, but Tom Lampkin flied out to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The M's also left a runner on second in the fifth. Ken Griffey
Jr. doubled after Helling struck out Shane Monahan and Rodriguez,
but the right-hander got Edgar Martinez looking to end the inning.
That was Helling's 10th strikeout, a total he last topped two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   WATSON IN: Former New York Yankees and Houston Astros general
manager Bob Watson was at Safeco Field on Monday to interview for
the Mariners' GM job. Watson is the second candidate to interview,
joining former Toronto and Baltimore GM Pat Gillick, who did so
last week.
</P>
<P>
   MOYER SHUT DOWN: The Mariners will finish the season with a
rotation of five rookies, since Jamie Moyer will miss his final
start of the year Thursday with shoulder soreness.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hinchliffe will start in Moyer's place Thursday. Robert
Ramsay, Freddy Garcia and John Halama are scheduled to start over
the weekend in Oakland, though Ken Cloude or Denny Stark could
start instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it is, we're going to have five rookies in the
rotation,'' said manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, who led the AL with 228 innings prior to last night's
games, finished 14-8 with a 3.87 ERA. He attributed his soreness to
``wear and tear.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
