<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8394 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-MAHONEY-KENNEDYS-AZR &LR;      09-28 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAHONEY-KENNEDYS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH FILLS LATEST BOOK ON KENNEDY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - President John F. Kennedy in June 1963 went on
television without a script and asked White America to imagine life
as a Negro.
</P>
<P>
   It was the boldest statement ever by a White politician
determined to bring civil rights to all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Although the words were Jack's, the inspiration came from
brother Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   The anecdote offers a clue to the differences between the two
men _ one of style and acquired substance, the other a hardened
moralist unwavering in his passion for equality and justice, even
if that passion led to his own death and that of his brother.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Sons &AMP; Brothers: The Days of Jack and Robert
Kennedy,'' former Arizona secretary of state and Kennedy scholar
Richard Mahoney explores the complex relationships in the Kennedy
family _ between brothers, between spouses, between the children
and their omniscient but loving father, Joseph P. Kennedy Sr.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys were, and are, a family ``brilliant but greatly
flawed,'' Mahoney concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Several have paid for their mistakes with untimely deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the price of glory,'' Mahoney says.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade of research and writing went into the book,
says Mahoney, a friend of the Kennedys and scholar at the Kennedy
Library in Boston from 1987 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   He compares the literary effort with an ``elephantine
pregnancy'' that happily resulted in a live birth. He also calls it
a ``strange marriage,'' then reconsiders the metaphor in light of
his five-year marriage to Phoenix area personality Mary Jo West, a
union that ended so amicably she worked diligently on his
unsuccessful race for the U.S. Senate in 1994 and remains, he says,
his best friend.
</P>
<P>
   They share custody of their 11-year-old daughter, Molly.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney, 47, who teaches at Thunderbird Graduate School of
International Management, long has been involved with the other
family in his life, the remarkable Kennedys. He met John Kennedy in
1961, when he was 9. He met Robert in 1967 and 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney's father, a friend of Robert Kennedy, served as
ambassador to Ghana during the Kennedy administration.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney began to write his book with trepidation, aware that his
work would be just the latest in a library that already includes
about 400 titles, including Theodore White's ``The Making of the
President,'' which created the Camelot myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure where it was going or whether the world needed
another Kennedy book,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But he decided that he had something new to contribute to the
legacy, believing ``that we haven't closed the door on the Kennedy
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Every American, it seems, has been touched by the family in some
way.
</P>
<P>
   With one Kennedy book already to his credit, the 1983 ``JFK:
Ordeal in Africa,'' Mahoney began digging through documents to
explore topics he thought never had been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Kennedy books fall into one of two camps _
assassination literature or literature about the administration _
he wanted to link the two with a balanced perspective that
portrayed the brothers and their father neither as wholly
scoundrels or unwavering saints.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional views sketched them as a political ``juggernaut,''
he says, united in their philosophies and ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   But there were contradictions, Mahoney found.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant contradiction was the question of the
Mafia, the role it played in Joe Sr.'s success and in the deaths of
his two sons.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Mahoney says, it becomes clear that the same
mobsters who helped win the election for Jack in 1963 instigated
his assassination three years later as the Kennedy brothers _
especially Robert _ moved to rid America of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Killing the president was the way to stop his attorney general's
crusade against the mob, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But as Robert Kennedy doggedly pursued the cause he had begun as
chief counsel to the U.S. Senate's anti-crime McClellan Committee
in 1956, Mahoney says he was to discover Kennedy's own father's
involvement with the underworld, a relationship that had begun
during his bootlegging days in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of Joe Sr.'s capital might have constituted
ill-gotten gains and many of his acquaintances were hardly the
aristocrats that would characterize his own family, most of his
dealings were legitimate, says Mahoney, who admires the patriarch's
unwavering devotion to his children. He wrote each of them daily or
weekly letters of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   His nature was more like Bobby's than Jack's, Mahoney says.
Although Jack had style and charm ``almost in a global sense'' and
presented a more sanguine demeanor, Bobby's passions ran deep like
his father's. They loved and hated in the same way and shared an
``us against them'' outlook on life.
</P>
<P>
   The book explores the complex relationship between Jack and wife
Jackie, a flammable union fueled by love and chemistry that never
cooled, though Jack's philanderings threatened to destroy the bond.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it was Bobby, the family promise keeper, who helped shore
up the marriage. Mahoney calls him a ``tribalist'' for whom family
was paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Other revelations in ``Sons &AMP; Brothers'' include the efforts of
the Eisenhower and Kennedy administrations to murder Cuban
President Fidel Castro, the role of U.S. intelligence agents in
those efforts as well as possible links to the deaths of both
brothers and the workings of anti-Castro forces in Miami then and
now.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said he suspects that ``certain people in Miami'' will
not welcome his disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Kennedy came to office in 1961 with ``great
style,'' Mahoney says, but with questionable substance. By the time
of his death, he had grown into the job as a man of decisiveness,
especially when it came to civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of president would Robert Kennedy have been?
</P>
<P>
   ``Either great or disastrous,'' Mahoney surmises.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby would have assumed office with a great deal of experience
and power, but his radical ideas of how America had to change, to
ensure equality for all people, might have proven ill-timed and
contrary to an unshakeable status quo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, with the assassination of a second brother, the
question of that legacy is left unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys were like a war machine, Mahoney says. They took
risks in battle. When one warrior fell, another stepped in to take
his place.
</P>
<P>
   The message: ``Life is brief. Death comes along sometimes in a
hurry. There's no need to be afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney's readers will see these men as ``heroic people who were
greatly flawed,'' who ``saw their deaths as creative acts of
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is a blood sport in which ``youthful death is the only way
to be eternal.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
