<HEADLINE>
JURY AWARDS MORE THAN $40 MILLION TO WOMAN INJURED IN RAILROAD
CROSSING COLLISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Jackson County jury on Monday awarded more than $40 million to
a Sedalia, Mo., woman who suffered brain damage and more than 20
broken bones in a 1997 train-crossing accident.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors also found Union Pacific Railroad Co. liable for punitive
damages, which could add millions more to what lawyers say already
is Missouri's largest rail-crossing-accident verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific is 75 percent at fault, the jury decided, and
Amtrak 25 percent as the jurors awarded actual damages of nearly
$40.37 million. The jurors today will hear arguments in the
punitive damages phase in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Railroad attorneys declined to comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, plaintiff's lawyers accused Union Pacific
of doing nothing to install lights and gates at the crossing a
quarter-mile south of U.S. 50 near Warrensburg, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff lawyer Grant L. Davis told jurors that 34-year-old
Kimberly Alcorn lived with pain ``like a window into hell'' because
Union Pacific waited instead of paying $200,000 for lights and
gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about corporate greed,'' Davis said, ``It's about
putting dollars ahead of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials had told the company 11 months before the Aug.
29, 1997, accident that the crossing was dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific waited for government subsidies to pay for
installing lights and gates, plaintiff lawyers argued. And the
railroad kept waiting, even after an Amtrak train hit a vehicle
there four months before the accident that disabled Alcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers also cited testimony that Amtrak engineers did not apply
brakes until after the train hit the car Alcorn was in. The train
was traveling at 65 to 70 mph. The mother of two teen-agers
suffered brain damage, broken bones and disfiguring injuries, her
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams, an attorney for the railroad companies, told
jurors: ``You can see a train if you look.'' Williams told them to
blame the accident on defendant Curtis Edwards, the driver of the
car hit by the train.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, however, told jurors to remember the state report that
said the view of the train was 90 percent blocked by brush and
terrain. He said to remember, too, the testimony of an assistant
Amtrak engineer who said he had narrowly missed several vehicles at
the crossing, including a propane truck.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John Rollins represented Edwards, a friend of Alcorn's,
who was driving her back to Sedalia after they visited an
Independence mall.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins said that a sign which warned of a railway crossing was
in a ditch and that Edwards did not know he was approaching the
crossing, which had a faded crossbuck sign. Rollins cited the
testimony of several area residents who said that it was hard to
see a train even if they stopped and looked.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins said Union Pacific's attitude was ``we run the trains,
we make the money...but we're not responsible for safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that Edwards was not at fault, but that Union
Pacific had acted ``with complete indifference to or conscious
disregard for the safety of others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
