<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S ECONOMIC REBIRTH SERVES AS EXAMPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHRIS SIEROTY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Hollywood renaissance continues.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales, hotel occupancy rates and just about every other
economic indicator were higher in the Hollywood Business
Improvement District in 1998 compared to '97, according to an
economic survey released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Conducted by Los Angeles-based Economics Research Associates,
the study showed hotel occupancy increased 32 percent and rates
jumped 8 percent; office lease rates increased 12 percent;
pedestrian counts increased 5 percent; and retail and restaurant
revenue increased 4 percent and 5 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's study is exciting because it validates the
enormous financial investment Hollywood property owners are making
in their district,'' said Kerry Morrison, executive director of the
Hollywood Entertainment District.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-block property-based district was formed in December 1996
and originally extended along Hollywood Boulevard from La Brea
Avenue to Mc Cadden Place. It was expanded in August 1998 to reach
all the way to Gower Street.
</P>
<P>
   The district is composed of 240 property owners who are assessed
$2.13 million annually to pay for security, maintenance services
and marketing activities to promote the revitalization of the area.
</P>
<P>
   The district also has received $1 million from the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority and $150,000 from the city, according to
Roxanna Tynan, economic development deputy for Los Angeles City
Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg, whose 13th District includes
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   David Wilcox, senior vice president of Economics Research
Associates, called the Hollywood Entertainment District the most
successful BID operating in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is currently the only BID to ensure that its program
is properly focused by `counting the house' on an annual basis, and
our analysis indicates their efforts are paying off
substantially,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Zorehkey, a retail development consultant for Frederick's
of Hollywood, said there has been a change in attitude since the
creation of the district, which has aided in cleaning up the
neighborhood and making it safer for customers, tourists and
employees.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the company is ``committed to Hollywood,'' and is
building a 15,000-square-foot retail store and office space
adjacent to the Mann's Chinese Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the district's success, ``the rest of the investment
community has gotten real interested in Hollywood,'' said Jack
Kyser, chief economist with the Los Angeles Economic Development
Corp. ``No matter where you live in Los Angeles, what goes on in
Hollywood is important to you.''
</P>
<P>
   In five years, 94 business improvement districts have been
created in the city of Los Angeles, including at least eight in the
San Fernando Valley, said Wilcox. The Sherman Oaks district went
into effect on Monday and stretches along Ventura Boulevard from
Van Nuys Boulevard to Cedros Avenue, and along Van Nuys Boulevard
from Ventura to Hortense Street.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
