<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8406 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-28 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ONCE the playoffs begin, the Astros know what needs to change.
</P>
<P>
   The Killer B's need their sting. The big bats _ those of Jeff
Bagwell, Craig Biggio and Derek Bell _ need to act that way, and
Ken Caminiti and Carl Everett must add their much-needed punch.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made about the lack of hitting in the Astros'
recent postseason escapades against the Padres and Braves. And the
criticism has come with good reason. The hitting has stunk.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many Most Valuable Player votes Bagwell earns
after this regular season, or how high Everett's and Biggio's
batting averages climb, or how hot Caminiti's stick gets down the
stretch, they ultimately will be judged on how they hit in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   They know it. You know it. Everyone knows it.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the Astros are hoping only to get to the playoffs.
The division race is tied, the Reds are playing better baseball,
and the Astros are trying to find the magic again.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think the Astros' position atop the NL Central has
become tenuous because of a lack of hitting in big games, you need
to think again.
</P>
<P>
   As much as manager Larry Dierker and others in the organization
have lamented a lack of clutch hitting against the league's best
teams, it hasn't been the bats that have failed this club in those
big games.
</P>
<P>
   It has been, believe it or not, pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros begin their most critical series of the year tonight
at the Astrodome facing a Reds team that is indeed red-hot. Lose
this series to the Reds, and the Astros frankly would not deserve a
postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as the prevailing opinion about the Astros is that
they should be able to rely on their arms and hope the bats come
around, the reverse is true going into this critical series.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima and Mike Hampton are scheduled to take to the hill
tonight and Wednesday, and clearly both need to improve on their
performances against the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Notice: Against the league's best _ the Diamondbacks, Mets,
Braves and Reds _ hitting has not been the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' record against those teams stands at a disappointing
12-24. But in those 36 games, the heart of the regular batting
order _ Bagwell, Biggio, Bell, Caminiti and Everett _ has batted a
combined .300. All of them have driven in runs, gotten on base and
individually hit close to or better than their season averages.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell is at .320 in 36 games against the Mets, Diamondbacks,
Reds and Braves. Biggio is at .290, Caminiti at .380, Everett at
.310. And while Bell's average is lacking at a pedestrian .240,
it's roughly the same he has batted all season.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, and perhaps key to tonight's opener against the
Reds, is that it has been pitching _ the most consistent part of
the season-long drive to a hoped-for third Central title _ that has
lagged behind the norm against those four top NL teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' starting pitchers have given up 117 earned runs in
209 innings in those 36 games. That's a 5.02 ERA, compared to the
starters' season-long ERA of 3.84.
</P>
<P>
   And in 11 games thus far against the Reds, the starters have
given up 47 earned runs in 59 innings, a whopping 7.13 ERA. That's
just not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Lima and Hampton, the 20-game winners and Cy Young contenders,
are 0-2 with two no-decisions against the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   If something must improve beginning tonight, it's not the
sticks. They've been consistent all season against the Astros'
toughest opponents, and it would be difficult to ask for more from
Bags, Biggio, Bell, Caminiti and Everett than a combined .300
batting average over the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it's going to have to be Lima Time in more ways than one
tonight. It's going to have to be time for Lima to be at his best
against the best. And Wednesday, the reliable ``Bulldog,'' Hampton,
must have that glaring scowl and biting breaking ball that has made
him one of the league's best pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows what happened last year in the playoffs when the
bats went silent and so many hopes went down in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this sensational season and thought we were the best
team in the league,'' Dierker said. ``It was like a kick in the gut
to lose that series to San Diego. People were walking around in a
daze.''
</P>
<P>
   But right now the Astros can't even think about what they need
to change in the playoffs. They have to get there first. And the
pressure of nearly six months of a division race comes down to two
days.
</P>
<P>
   And two arms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
