<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MOVE CLOSER TO YANKS IN HOME-FIELD CHASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers seized the American League West
title Sunday, but their throttle remains full-steam ahead in
pursuit of home-field advantage for the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates played his regulars last night at The
Ballpark in Arlington, and the Rangers responded with a 3-2 victory
against the Seattle Mariners to move within one game of the New
York Yankees for the league's second-best record.
</P>
<P>
   The two clubs with the best records will earn home-field
advantage for the Division Series, and the Rangers must pass the
Yankees in the standings because New York owns the tie-breaker
after winning the season series, 8-4. That serves as the Rangers'
bull's eye for the final week of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the general feeling was, `Hey, guys, we're close
enough. Let's give it a shot,' '' said Oates, whose Rangers moved
30 games above .500 for the first time in history.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers rallied from a 2-1, sixth-inning deficit to gain a
game on the Yankees, who lost, 10-6, to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
last night. Designated hitter Lee Stevens, who produced only two
runs batted in during his previous 19 games, lifted a two-strike
pitch from closer Jose Mesa deep enough into left field for an
eighth-inning sacrifice fly that scored Juan Gonzalez with the
game-winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling did not figure in the decision despite
a season-best 10 strikeouts during his 5 1/3-inning appearance, but
the performance represented progress for the struggling pitcher who
will start Game 2 of the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a great deal of improvement,'' Oates said. ``He threw
more good curveballs than he had during his past two or three
outings, and he had some giddy-up on his fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling did surrender another home run _ No. 13 in his past six
starts. Yet, the 427-foot, third-inning blast by first baseman Raul
Ibanez did not spoil the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a step in the right direction,'' Helling
said. ``There were a lot of positives from my start, but there are
still some things I need to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers manufactured the tying run in the sixth inning after
center fielder Tom Goodwin drew a leadoff walk from right-hander
Freddy Garcia. Second baseman Mark McLemore advanced Goodwin into
scoring position with a sacrifice bunt, and catcher Ivan Rodriguez
delivered the game-tying single.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez established a single-season career-high with his 193rd
base hit, and that matched Joe Torre and Ted Simmons for the second
most by a catcher in one season. Mike Piazza established the
major-league record with 201 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also supplied perhaps the evening's most significant
defensive play by picking right fielder Jay Buhner off second base
with one out and two runners aboard in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Mike Munoz, who replaced Helling earlier in the
inning, retired pinch-hitter Mike Blowers on strikes to end the
Mariners' threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge gave us a big shot with the pickoff,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' bullpen again played a critical role in a victory.
Munoz provided a scoreless inning of perfect relief, and
right-hander Tim Crabtree (5-1) earned the victory by retiring all
five batters he faced. That included strikeouts of shortstop Alex
Rodriguez and center fielder Ken Griffey Jr., who swung through a
3-2 fastball up in the strike zone for the first out of the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Rangers an opportunity for victory in the bottom
half of the inning, and Gonzalez's one-out double off left-hander
Steve Sinclair (0-1) set the stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners walked designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro
intentionally, and Stevens came through with a clutch plate
appearance after Mesa issued a five-pitch walk to third baseman
Todd Zeile to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland pitched a scoreless ninth inning to
establish the Rangers' single-season record for saves with his
43rd, which also matched his career best.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a bad way for the hangover-free Rangers to begin
their pursuit of the Yankees and Indians after Sunday's postgame
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a team full of teetotalers,'' Oates said, ``but
there was much more champagne on the floor than there was in
them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
