<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-28 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Jeff Bagwell isn't surprised the Astros and Cincinnati Reds are
meeting in a high-stakes series during the final week of the
regular season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Haven't the Astros been expecting this all along?
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about this a long time ago, that it (the division)
was going to come down to this series,'' Bagwell said. ``We knew
this series would mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more than they anticipated. A two-game series against
Cincinnati beginning tonight at the Astrodome takes on increased
importance for the Astros, who now have company atop the National
League Central. The Astros dropped into a first-place tie with the
Reds following Cincinnati's 9-7 victory Monday over St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima (20-9) takes the mound for the Astros tonight in a
third attempt at his 21st victory, which would tie Joe Niekro's
club record. Pete Harnisch (14-10) pitches for the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going down to the wire,'' Astros shortstop Ricky
Gutierrez said. ``That's the way you want it in a pennant race, to
go in there and make your own destiny. If you win, you know you're
in the playoffs. If you don't, you might be going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Time is running out. The Reds pose a daunting task for the
Astros, having won eight of 11 meetings between the clubs this
season. They swept a four-game series June 24-27 at the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in two years, the Astros find themselves in a
neck-and-neck race for the playoffs. A sweep would give the Astros
some breathing room. A split still leaves them in decent shape for
the playoffs, as either the division champion or the NL wild-card
representative. Two losses would almost certainly make it necessary
for them to win at least two of three from the Dodgers in the
season's final weekend and hope the New York Mets continue their
late-season tumble.
</P>
<P>
   After reeling off a club-record 12 consecutive victories from
Sept. 3-14, the Astros lost a chance to clinch the division title
early by going 3-7 since Sept. 15 _ against teams that have losing
records. That includes six losses on their recent nine-game road
trip to St. Louis, Pittsburgh and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros would not offer fatigue as an excuse following their
disastrous road trip. But general manager Gerry Hunsicker would
like to see the club regain the high level of intensity it had
during its winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reds have been playing like a team trying to win a
championship,'' Hunsicker said. ``We're playing like a team trying
not to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Reds last came to town June 24-27, they were the
hottest team in baseball. And on the strength of a 10-game winning
streak _ all against division leaders Houston and Arizona _ the
Reds made their move in the division, shaving six games off the
Astros' lead in just more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   In that series vs. Cincinnati, the Astros hit .151 and were
outscored 26-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really hot, and we were a little beat up,'' Astros
closer Billy Wagner noted. ``Now, it's a different story. We've got
some big guns at the plate and pitchers starting to pitch well. It
will be a different story for those two games. Coming down the
stretch the last week or so, there's a lot of pressure on both
teams. Each team has a lot to play for.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after being swept at home, the Astros split a four-game
set at Cinergy Field. And even though the season had yet to reach
the halfway point, the Astros were certain this week's two games
would have playoff implications.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard the Astros have tried to distance themselves,
the Reds have refused to go away. The Astros won six straight games
in late July. The Reds responded by winning six of seven. And
despite their 12 straight victories this month, the Astros gained
only 2{ games in that stretch as Cincinnati won 10 of 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they weren't going away,'' Astros reliever Jay Powell
said. ``(In June) they put an exclamation point that said, `We're
here to stay.' They weren't going to fade, because they have a good
squad. It's been a good race. Neither team has been able to put any
substantial ground between (itself and) the other.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage last season, the Astros had already wrapped up the
division title and held a double-digit lead over the Chicago Cubs.
Two years ago, the Astros entered the final week of the regular
season with a 3{-game lead over the Pittsburgh Pirates. They won
their first division title in 11 years by five games.
</P>
<P>
   Since baseball went to the three-division alignment in 1994, the
NL Central has never been decided by less than five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been nerve-racking, especially after last year when we
had a comfortable margin during the second half,'' manager Larry
Dierker said. ``(1997) was different in the sense we were trying to
win it for the first time and weren't necessarily supposed to be
that good, so I don't think expectations were as great as they are
this year. If we don't win (the division) this year, we will have
blown it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
