<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8410 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-BUSH-AZR &LR;      09-28 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S BAND WAGON ROLLING INTO ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The handful of Arizona leaders gathered at the state Capitol on
Monday resembled wary homeowners bracing for a flood, stacking
testimonials for Sen. John McCain like sandbags in the path of the
advancing storm.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane hits town Tuesday in the person of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, who arrives with a nine-point lead in a new state
poll over McCain, the endorsement of Arizona's most popular
politician, Gov. Jane Hull, and the promise of more cash at a
Phoenix fund-raiser tonight for his already bulging campaign
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   As McCain darts across the country in a whistle-stop
announcement tour, Bush will try to solidify his hold on Arizona,
whose Feb. 22 primary is a critical early campaign test for both
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think this race is going to be one of the most
interesting, exciting, and maybe bitter in the history of Arizona
politics,'' said Bruce Merrill, an ASU journalism professor and
pollster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush can drive a silver stake into McCain if he wins
Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sensing that belief, House Speaker Jeff Groscost led a
hastily called news conference at the Capitol in support of McCain
and apparently designed to blunt the impact of Hull's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost, a paid campaign consultant to McCain, was joined by 11
state lawmakers and Secretary of State Betsey Bayless, who are
supporting the senator. Several who attended the event are close
allies of Hull, including Rep. Carolyn Allen, R-Scottsdale, and
Sen. Sue Grace, R-north Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost, R-Mesa, downplayed Hull's endorsement, Bush's
fund-raising edge, and the polls, which he said were merely
measuring name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   When it was pointed out Bush leads McCain in his home state,
Groscost responded that polls don't matter right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this was going to be an uphill battle,'' Groscost
said. ``It's not about money or polls. It's about getting our
message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's poll, which was conducted Thursday through Sunday,
found support among Republicans for Bush at 31 percent, McCain at
22 percent, and support for billionaire Steve Forbes at 10 percent.
The margin of error for the poll is 5.6 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill says the expected result would have McCain up 2-1 over
Bush in Arizona, especially since Bush hasn't yet visited the
state.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that the three-way race that is shaping up could get
heated as McCain tries to defend his turf. Throw in the fact that
Forbes has a penchant for negative campaign ads, and things could
get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain cannot afford to lose Arizona. It would be an
embarrassment,'' Merrill said. ``He is obviously going to put a ton
of money and organization into this state.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Tuesday's visit is any indication, so will Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has courted Hull's support since hosting a
$100,000 fund-raiser for her gubernatorial campaign last year. It
is unlikely he would so actively seek her endorsement only to
ignore her state's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and Bush are close politically, sharing beliefs on tax
policy, social programs and border issues. They have a good working
relationship, and Hull appears to be taking an active role in the
Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will visit former U.S. House Minority Leader John Rhodes at
his Mesa home Tuesday morning before heading to downtown, where he
will lunch with Hull at her table at Tom's Tavern, in full view of
cameras and the public. Bush and Hull will then meet in her office
before attending an evening fund-raiser at the Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will also tour the Thomas J. Pappas school for homeless
children Tuesday afternoon. &QL; 
Chris Moeser can be reached at (602) 444-8069 or at
chris.moeser(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8411 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-DYKES-H     09-28 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-DYKES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LUBBOCK _ Before his weekly session with the media Monday morning,
Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes heard sports information director Kent
Partridge say there are no sideline credentials for ``shooters''
remaining for Saturday's game against Texas A&AMP;M.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Shooters,'' Dykes said. ``Now that's encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Partridge meant photographers, of course, but in the 10 days
since Texas Tech lost at home to North Texas to fall to 1-2, Dykes
has come under fire in Lubbock like never before. Dykes is in his
13th season at Tech, where he has compiled a 77-64-1 record. He has
more victories than any coach in the school's history and has taken
the Red Raiders to seven bowls.
</P>
<P>
   But in this day of sports talk-radio rage and Internet chat
rooms, all that means little. After the loss to North Texas, Don
Williams, a columnist from the Lubbock Avalanche-Journal and sports
radio talk-show host, called for Dykes to step down at the end of
the season ``for the good of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   A local TV station had a call-in poll asking whether Dykes
should resign now or wait until the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes, 61, seems to have taken it all in stride. He is too busy
getting his team ready to host Texas A&AMP;M on Saturday to worry if
the oil is boiling and for whom it boils.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say a coach loses 10 percent of his friends every season
he's at a place,'' Dykes said. ``I've been here 13 years, so I
guess that puts me into the negative range.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is that I always consider the source (of criticism).
Now, if (former Texas coach) Darrell Royal had called me up and
said, `Spike, you're doing a horrible job,' then I'd sit up and
take notice. He hasn't done that. He might, but he hasn't yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykes has a contract through the 2000 season, which has led to
speculation that he might be nearing the end of his career at Tech,
where he has been as an assistant or head coach since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech president Donald Haragan said he was aware of
``malcontent'' among some Red Raiders fans. Haragan cited a
university policy that prohibited him from responding ``to
individuals outside of our own system of review.'' In other words,
Dykes' status will be reviewed at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Haragan told the Avalanche-Journal: ``My head's not
in the sand. I realize people are unhappy with the program. That is
something we listen to. We will make a decision after all the
data's in for this season, sit back in a very deliberate way and
make decisions about what's best for our university.''
</P>
<P>
   What some critics seem to have lost sight of is that Dykes has
brought stability and success to the Red Raiders' program _ two
things that often are lacking at programs the size and scope of
Texas Tech's. In addition, Dykes has been able to recruit star
players like Bam Morris, Byron Hanspard, Zach Thomas and Ricky
Williams to Lubbock, which isn't an easy accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   A person who asked not be identified but who has deep roots in
Texas football said Dykes is the only thing standing between Tech
turning into another Baylor. The Bears are on their third coach
since longtime coach Grant Teaff resigned in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has a 27-44 record and has been to one bowl in the
post-Teaff era. During the same span, Tech is 42-32 and has been to
five bowls. However, Tech is 2-7 since it started the 1998 season
with six consecutive victories, and that is what Dykes' detractors
are bringing up.
</P>
<P>
   What they might not be considering is the alternative to Dykes.
Attracting an established coach to Lubbock is out of the question.
What Tech likely would get would be an up-and-coming assistant
coach. If he were successful, he might leave to go to a more
established program. If unsuccessful, he would have to be replaced,
and the cycle would start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Around about that time, people probably would be saying, ``Maybe
we should have kept ol' Spike around. He wasn't such a bad guy,
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, few question whether Dykes is a good guy or not. If
Hollywood put out a casting call for a football coach from West
Texas, Dykes wouldn't get the job. He's too West Texas. You want
realism, but not this much realism.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes is comfortable in blue jeans and boots, eating barbecue
and spinning yarns about old friends and football. During the
1950s, '60s and '70s, he spent 17 years as a high school coach in
such Texas towns as Ballinger, Coahoma, Big Spring and Alice and
has stories about every stop along the line.
</P>
<P>
   During lunch Monday, he was talking about how criticism is
nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1964, I went to Coahoma from San Angelo, and the year
before they lost 10 games at Coahoma,'' Dykes said. ``We had some
real good players, and we won 11 games before we lost in the
bi-district round. That next week, my wife came home all teared up,
looking like she'd been hit in the face with a skillet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she was at the post office, and two old ranchers were
talking and one of them said, `They ought to fire that coach. If
he'd played the right quarterback, they wouldn't have lost.' Some
things never change. I guess that was kind of the talk radio of
West Texas in 1964.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the late 1990s in the Big 12 Conference, the stakes are
higher than at Coahoma. Fans had high expectations for the Red
Raiders this season with Heisman Trophy candidate Ricky Williams
and an experienced quarterback in Rob Peters.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was injured as the Red Raiders lost their opener 31-13
at Arizona State and hasn't played since. Tech beat
Louisiana-Lafayette 38-17 before losing 21-14 at home to North
Texas, a 31-point underdog. Dykes doesn't sugarcoat the
disappointment in losing to the Eagles for the second time in three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost to a team that we should have beaten, and that's no
fun,'' Dykes said. ``That kind of loss makes the wolves howl. But
we've got a lot of football left. Losing that game and the other
game (at Arizona State) doesn't take away from what we set out to
do, and that's be a contender in the Big 12 South. Nothing's
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may lose one more game or no more games or eight more
games. Now we just need to try to get this train on track and go on
down the road. We need to try to digest this last loss and put all
this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   What has changed is the way some people in Lubbock feel about
Dykes and the Tech program. Several Red Raiders said Monday they
were using all the negativity of the last 10 days to band together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised with the reaction of some of the fans,''
Williams said. ``I don't see how so many can doubt our coach. It's
two games we're talking about. We can still win the Big 12, and if
we do that I think all these people are going to be looking pretty
silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Said fullback Sammy Morris: ``We're using all of this as a
motivational thing. This is the worst (criticism) since I've been
here (1995), and it's not fair. There seems to be a lot of negative
people out there, and I don't understand it. But we're going to
stick together, and something like this where everybody's on our
case and coach's case, this just might bring us together even
closer as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykes' teams have had a history of playing well against A&AMP;M,
winning three of the last four games and losing 17-10 last season
at College Station. The last five games have been decided by seven
points or fewer, so it would not be surprising if the Red Raiders
bounced back with a strong effort Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Should they pull off an upset, the talk shows no doubt would be
full of callers wanting to give Dykes a contract extension. Dykes
understands that the ebb and flow of fan and media opinion goes
with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I should worry more about this sort of thing, but
right now I'm more worried about getting ready to play the
Aggies,'' Dykes said. ``Like it or not, the distraction is there,
but we're not going to worry about every outside deal. We can't. If
we do that, we won't have enough time to do what we're here for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
