<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     09-28 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BROOKLINE, Mass. _ One picture is worth a thousand words, and there
is the image that we all will remember from a star-spangled
afternoon when the Ryder Cup returned to the Colonies.
</P>
<P>
   It is one that shows the jubilant American team crowded onto a
tiny porch on the second floor of the men's grill, turning a piece
of the staid old Country Club into the most happening place since
the lights went out on the dance floor at Studio 54.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods wearing a grin that was worth more than the millions
from a dozen Nike commercials. David Duval hanging over the balcony
spraying the crowd down below with the foam from all those
champagne bottles. Phil Mickelson pumping his triumphant fist and
throwing his cap into the throng. Even veteran Tom Lehman going
Brandi Chastain one better by peeling off his shirt and heaving it
out as a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   This was the moment that American golf fans will remember
generations from now and one that we only hope sticks in the
memories of the U.S. golfers who make the trip across the pond to
defend the Cup at The Belfry in two years.
</P>
<P>
   This was what America had wanted to see all along from this
talented bunch, a sense of unity, a sense of passion, a sense of
team.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, it was transformed into an extraordinary day when the
red, white and blue boys staged the most incredible comeback in
Ryder Cup history and then had it all topped off by Justin
Leonard's 45-foot putt that set off a re-creation of the Boston Tea
Party with all of the whooping and hollering.
</P>
<P>
   What we must hope is that the entire experience _ the lows, the
highs, the dramatic conclusion, the hugging, the bonding, the
partying _ will now transform the young guns who will carry the
banner for the U.S. into the next millennium into more than just a
wealthy collection of mini-corporations who want to grouse and
complain about the profits from such an event rather than just
diving into it headfirst.
</P>
<P>
   We should hope that Tiger realizes there can be more to golf
than 300-yard drives and bouncing the ball off his wedge for the
cameras. We should hope that the cardboard cutout Duval now sees
that there really is something to summoning up the patriotic fervor
displayed by the Europeans for this three-day ``exhibition.'' We
should hope that Mickelson has learned that it is more fun to wrap
himself in the flag rather than bank deposit slips.
</P>
<P>
   It was a weekend when Spanish teen-ager Sergio Garcia hopped up
and down the fairways and proclaimed with a giggle: ``I love to
play for my continent.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Americans can take a cue from El Nino and come out to
try to win the next one for Canada, too.
</P>
<P>
   It only became an event to truly remember after the haughty and
heavily favored _ by themselves _ U.S. team led up to the Ryder Cup
by grumbling about the money controversy, then dug itself a 10-6
hole in the team competition before finally closing ranks and
engaging in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. players, it became a day for Old Glory and
a Fourth of July fireworks display in September only after they
listened to Alamo-inspired speeches and heard Duval stand up
Saturday night and say, ``Let's kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval mugged for the cameras and the crowd after closing out his
walloping of Jesper Parnevik, sprayed champagne on everybody in New
England, then came to the interview room and told the media that
``nobody can know how it feels except the players on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just the point, David. Everyone except the team did know
how it was supposed to feel, and that's why everything before the
Sunday rally was so disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Team captain Ben Crenshaw pleaded and cajoled them to be a team,
to keep the faith. The players, it seems, were the last ones to
understand what it was all about and climb aboard the emotional
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the credit belongs to the media that criticized the U.S.
efforts on the first two days and evidently lit the Americans'
fires. Some of the credit belongs to NBC analyst Johnny Miller for
his frankness. There was: ``Justin Leonard should go home and watch
on TV,'' and ``Tiger Woods, are you kidding me? Do something.''
Some of the credit belongs to the fans who lined the fairways and
greens and often embarrassed the U.S. players by begging them to at
least act like they cared.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when they'd had enough abuse, they did, and the result
was another American Revolution. Hearts began to beat with either
pride or indignity, blood began to boil and, at the end of the day,
they stood there on the balcony, drenched in champagne, soaked in
pride.
</P>
<P>
   And bathed, we can only hope, in long overdue understanding of
what it's all about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
