r f BC-SPRINT-KAN &LR;      09-28 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT-MCI WORLDCOM UNION FEASIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A merger of Sprint Corp. and MCI WorldCom would face scrutiny
from U.S. and European regulators. But most experts think
authorities would approve such a deal, albeit with conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and MCI WorldCom refuse to comment on reports that they
are discussing a merger, which would create a giant in almost every
area of telecommunications, from local and long-distance voice to
Internet and wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   The combination would be examined by at least three regulatory
bodies _ the Justice Department, the Federal Communications
Commission and the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these mergers can go through,'' said David Wilson of
New Frontiers Communications Consulting in Washington. ``The
question is what kinds of conditions regulators slap on them and
whether the companies think it's worth the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and European Commission primarily are
concerned with whether the merged companies would overwhelmingly
dominate a business and be able to smother competition.
</P>
<P>
   On that level, a Sprint-MCI WorldCom deal would face two
pressure points: voice and Internet.
</P>
<P>
   MCI and Sprint collectively control more than 30 percent of the
long-distance industry. That doesn't match AT&AMP;T's nearly 50 percent
share, but it's certainly enough to give regulators pause on
antitrust grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would definitely be a very steep increase in market
concentration,'' said Alan Roth, a lawyer and government relations
consultant. ``Each one becomes progressively more difficult to
explain and support. Where do we go after that _ AT&AMP;T and MCI
merging?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the market dominance of the three largest long-distance
carriers is being challenged by the emergence of new players such
as Qwest Communications, which controls a potentially higher
capacity long-distance network than either Sprint or MCI WorldCom,
even without the embedded customer base.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant long-distance carriers also face challenges from
technology such as the Internet, which has some computer users
making free long-distance calls. Once allowed into the
long-distance business, regional Bell operating companies such as
Southwestern Bell also will be potent competitive forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The usual suspects that don't like consolidation would come
out of the woodwork,'' said Wilson, referring to consumer advocates
that have opposed most telecommunications mergers. ``But voice
concentration is a difficult argument to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts think MCI WorldCom would even be willing to sell
off Sprint's long-distance network if that's what it took to get
its hand on its real target: Sprint's wireless business, Sprint
PCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major concern here with regulators is going to be
concentration in Internet backbone and connectivity,'' said Marvin
Kahn, a consultant with Exeter Associates of Silver Spring, Md.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom and Sprint are the two largest providers of
connections to the Internet, together providing more than 43
percent of Internet service providers with their connection to the
Internet, according to a recent survey by /{Boardwatch/} magazine.
</P>
<P>
   When WorldCom bought MCI last year, regulators forced the
company to sell off MCI's Internet backbone assets. A Sprint-MCI
WorldCom combination would probably face the same conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission, traditionally charged
with assuring that the merger parties could meet financial and
licensing requirements, could also weigh in on whether a merger was
in the ``public interest.'' That's a nebulous standard, but one
that the current commission has interpreted broadly as a proactive
mandate to increase competition in phone markets.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing a preliminary approval of the proposed merger of SBC
Communications, parent of Southwestern Bell, with Ameritech, the
FCC imposed a broad set of conditions that would force the parties
to move into new markets, establish separate subsidiaries for some
services and spend money to upgrade service in low-income areas.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether the FCC would exercise the same kind of
control with a merger of MCI WorldCom and Sprint. To date, it has
been far more concerned with opening competition in local telephone
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of issues that could slow a transaction
between Sprint and MCI, but nothing that MCI would fight,'' Kahn
said. ``MCI would come up with a package that would appease
regulators.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
