<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-28 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MANAGER'S QUIET TOUCH MAKES HIM MIDAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ One of Johnny Oates' most admirable traits as
a manager is too often overlooked and underappreciated: He knows
when to shut his pie hole.
</P>
<P>
   This is a dying art, particularly among managers and coaches in
virtually every sport.
</P>
<P>
   There's a budding Knute Rockne, aching to deliver his own
slobbery ``Win one for the Gipper'' speech, in every locker room
these days.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to inspire their teams, coaches have been known to eat
worms, castrate calves and drop-kick food-laden tables, scattering
spaghetti and meatballs to all corners of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   If Oates was tempted to demonstrate any of these tried-and-true
sports-management techniques before Oakland arrived for the most
crucial series of the season over the weekend, he somehow resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't anything said,'' second baseman Mark McLemore
insisted last night as the Rangers opened their final home series
of the season against the Mariners while savoring their third
division title in four years. ``No big meeting. No big speech. No
rallying the troops. We just went out and did what we had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers did was respond to Oates' silence with a
crushing three-game sweep that allowed them to clinch the American
League West flag at home and spend the final week of the season
trying to catch Cleveland and New York for home-field advantage in
the first-round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' unusual silent treatment is an oversight that could get
him thrown out of the Inspirational Speakers Bureau because, you
see, it is his second glaring offense within a 12-month period.
</P>
<P>
   He also somehow kept his trap shut last September, when the
Rangers, tied for the division lead with the Angels, traveled to
Anaheim for their most critical series of the '98 season. They
outscored the Angels, 27-3 in those three games.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody see a pattern developing here?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could have blamed Oates if he had called a dramatic team
meeting and put on an act worthy of Sir Laurence Olivier before
Friday's series opener with the A's. His team had, after all, lost
seven of its past 11 games, including four out of five, to the
flotsam and jetsam of the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, for crying out loud, beat the Rangers three out of
four. Tampa Bay and Baltimore paddled their behinds.
</P>
<P>
   There are managers out there who would have felt compelled to do
``something''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to do the opposite,'' Oates said before the Rangers' 3-2
victory over Seattle. ``So I do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having meetings in those situations just sends out warnings.
There's a time and place for everything. If you feel your problems
stem from lack of effort or lack of intensity, nonchalant play,
mentally not concentrating, yeah, that needs to be corrected. But I
didn't see any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The true test of a manager is whether or not he knows his
players. Oates does. He knew if he didn't get excited, they
wouldn't either.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you stay calm, let them know you've got confidence in them
and everything will work out,'' he said. ``The worst thing you can
do is get all panicky and scare them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young kids, you have to take them by the hand and lead them.
But when you've got a veteran ballclub like this, you just let them
go play. As long as the mental approach is there, the effort's
there, it doesn't need to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Said third-base coach Jerry Narron: ``One of the best things
Johnny does is play it even keel. He has a lot of patience. He
knows when to sit tight.''
</P>
<P>
   And when to keep his lip zipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest fault has been trying too hard, trying to hit the
ball too hard, too far, take too many bases, make a throw we
shouldn't make,'' Oates said. ``When we just let the game come to
us, we're fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Mac's hit \Rin the fourth inning of the first game
against the A's\S, we relaxed and let the game come to us. We did
that all weekend. It looked like we had fun. We just relaxed and
played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland series and last year's showdown with the Angels were
eerily similar. Last September, the Rangers had won a huge game at
Baltimore when Will Clark beat out an infield hit and Pudge
Rodriguez hit a game-winning home run, and came home for a two-game
series with the Angels, trailing by two games. They won twice to
tie the race and then headed for Anaheim for the final three-game
shootout there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most fun I've ever had in baseball,'' McLemore said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers blew the Angels away, just as they did the A's over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three games in both series were no-contest,'' Oates said.
``Everything we tried worked, everything they tried didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the other guys just weren't quiet enough.
</P>
<P>
   Silence, it seems, really is golden. \Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817)
390-7760 \Ntagbottom:revo\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
