<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8417 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      09-28 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE WADES INTO IS SUES, RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A buoyant John McCain, confident he has established himself as a
credible presidential contender, formally opened his 2000 campaign
by aggressively engaging GOP front-runner George W. Bush on the
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republican senator, who Monday began a four-day
``kickoff'' tour for a campaign he actually began in December, will
seek during the tour not only to define himself more vividly, but
to do so at the expense of Bush and presidential rival Patrick
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The national tour began with a speech in this mill town and ends
Thursday with an ``Arizona welcome party'' and rally in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   A centerpiece of the address was McCain's proposal to reform the
big-money political system, and a call to sacrifice and service. He
said special-interest money in politics is squeezing Americans out
of the political process and causing deep cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our new patriotic challenge,'' McCain said. ``It is a
challenge to each of us to join in the fight against the pervasive
cynicism that is debilitating our democracy, that cheapens our
public debates, that threatens our public institutions, our culture
and, ultimately, our private happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Red, white and blue confetti shot into the sky when he finished
the speech. Speakers blared rock music, including the classic
``Johnny B. Goode,'' with its refrain of ``Go, Johnny, go!''
Cheerleaders from the University of New Hampshire clapped along and
danced.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, joined by wife Cindy, stood on a stage at a community
park surrounded by tennis courts and a green field. The area was
papered with ``McCain 2000'' posters featuring a black-and-white
photo of McCain as a young naval aviator leaning against his plane.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was cheerful and relaxed as he began the long campaign
swing. As his chartered plane prepared for takeoff to New
Hampshire, he grabbed the cabin microphone and told reporters and
staff, ``We haven't raised as much money as we had hoped, so I'm
going to have to pilot the plane today.''
</P>
<P>
   New on Monday was McCain's more aggressive definition of his
policy positions and his personality at the expense of Bush and
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Senior McCain campaign officials acknowledged the shift, saying
the Arizonan had established himself as a credible challenger and
was ready to take the next logical step. They said it was easier to
contrast campaign ideas now that Bush has provided details on his
plans for education, defense and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's new assertiveness was evident in the 25-minute speech
he gave here to a lunch-time crowd of about 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Without ever mentioning the Texas governor by name, McCain
suggested that he, and not Bush, is better equipped for the
``solemn responsibility'' of commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to making the decision to send our young men and
women into harm's way, that decision should be made by a leader who
knows that such decisions have profound consequences,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time when our nation's leader can no longer rely
on briefing books and talking points, when the experts and the
advisers have all weighed in, when the sum total of one's life
becomes the foundation from which he or she makes the decisions
that determine the future of our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   A son and grandson of Navy admirals, McCain, 63, is a former
Vietnam prisoner of war. Bush served in the Texas Air National
Guard during the war and has had to answer reporters' questions
about whether he received preferential treatment to remain
stateside because of the influence of his father.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has pledged to abide by the so-called ``11th
Commandment,'' once heralded by former President Reagan, which
prohibits personal attacks on fellow Republicans during
presidential campaigns. McCain has said the GOP hurt itself in the
1996 presidential election by its candidates' repeated attacks on
eventual nominee Bob Dole during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain invoked the pledge in Monday's speech, promising to
``campaign with respect for the dignity of the office I seek and
the people I seek to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain, who calls Bush ``a fine man,'' believes he can
take the high road while emphasizing the candidates' principal
areas of disagreement, including campaign-finance reform and
education.
</P>
<P>
   On education, McCain aides say he wants to move more swiftly
than Bush to test a national voucher program that the senator said
Monday would ``give middle- and lower-income parents the same right
wealthier parents have _ to send their child to the school that
best meets their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of campaign finance, Bush does not want to go as
far as McCain, who wants to ban all ``soft money'' contributions by
corporations, wealthy individuals and others to national political
parties. The money is supposed to be used for party-building
efforts, but Democrats and the GOP stretched the rules in 1996 and
used it on behalf of the presidential candidates as well.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's announcement tour, originally scheduled for last April,
was postponed until this week due to the air war in Kosovo. To the
amusement of pundits, he still refers to it as a kickoff, even
though he has been stumping in his targeted primary states _ New
Hampshire, South Carolina, California and Arizona _ for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the final kickoff, or the mid-kickoff, or the
pre-kickoff?'' New Hampshire pollster Dick Bennett joked in an
interview last week when told of McCain's plans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was formally launching his campaign just as former Vice
President Dan Quayle was bowing out. The McCain campaign announced
Monday it has picked up the endorsement of Dana Edwards, Quayle's
former chairman in Keene, N.H. McCain aides said Quayle's departure
could also help fund-raising, especially in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   From here, McCain headed to New York City for a fund-raiser
Monday night, then prepared for a South Carolina education speech
Tuesday. Another key stop will be Wednesday at the Ronald Reagan
Presidential Library in Simi Valley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   There, McCain is expected to further contrast his worldview with
that of Buchanan in a speech on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was the first of the GOP presidential candidates to
sharply attack Buchanan for his book, ``A Republic, Not an
Empire,'' and subsequent comments that Hitler didn't pose a direct
threat to the United States after 1940. While Bush has said
Buchanan should remain in the GOP, McCain suggested Buchanan had,
in effect, abandoned the party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has criticized Buchanan's isolationist outlook on
trade and other matters, said in his speech Monday that
``isolationism and protectionism are a fool's errand.'' Buchanan
has said the United States is too prone to intervene in foreign
matters in which it has no legitimate stake.
</P>
<P>
   McCain treated Monday's ``kickoff'' speech is a major event, and
so did the news media. He was accompanied on the campaign plane by
reporters from the ``New York Times,'' ``Washington Post,'' ``Wall
Street Journal,'' ``Los'' ``Angeles Times'' and the major weekly
newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   All of McCain's seven children were expected to be on hand for
various portions of the trip; six of them were with him in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Before traveling to Nashua, McCain began the day with a private
address _ aides described it as informal _ to about 4,000
midshipmen and officials at the Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md. One
of McCain's former academy classmates, Adm. Charles Larson, joined
the senator for the trip to New Hampshire. &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at 1-(202)-662-7264 or at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
