<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MAVERICKS STARTERS SET, ASSISTANT COACH SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The first hint that the Mavericks are serious about
turning their fortunes around was delivered yesterday when
assistant coach Donnie Nelson announced that all five starting
positions are up for grabs heading into the opening of training
camp Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no one will automatically start just because the
Mavericks have invested a lot of money in them. And no one will
start just because they started during last year's 19-31 season, or
just because owner Ross Perot Jr. flew to another continent to meet
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is wide-open,'' Nelson said. ``We can't afford for
it not to be wide-open.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Unlike last season, when some players privately
griped that point guard Steve Nash and small forward Dirk Nowitzki
did not win their starting spots on the court, they will have to
earn spots this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not opposed to starting anyone,'' Nelson said. ``We're
going to play guys and start guys that give us the best chance to
win, regardless of what name is on the back of that jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he wants to send a message that hard work and
individual success will translate into more playing time, and that
no one will be offered an easy ride.
</P>
<P>
   But does Nelson's stance really include Michael Finley and Gary
Trent? Apparently, it does, although they probably are expected to
win their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how hard Mike has worked in Chicago, and I know his
frame of mind coming in here,'' Nelson said. ``It would be shocking
to me if Mike didn't get out of the gate big-time and really start
the season out with a major-league bang.'' No Hill deal The
Mavericks are refuting a report that the team offered Robert Pack,
John ``Hot Rod'' Williams and Ansu Sesay to the Philadelphia 76ers
for power forward Tyrone Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Philadelphia Inquirer'' reported that the Mavericks made
the offer at the NBA league meetings in Vancouver, British Columbia
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't comment on trades or speculations thereof, per team
policy,'' Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson said. ``But
that's not accurate. What you read is not accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixers general manager Bill King told the ``Inquirer'' that the
Mavericks had inquired about Hill. Jones to China Former TCU guard
Mike Jones said he plans to play basketball in China this season,
although the Mavericks are holding out hope he'll be in their
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he is scheduled to leave for Shanghai on Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully next year I can come back to the Mavericks camp and
work out again and then see what happens from there,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a 6-foot-3 guard, played last season in Poland and was a
bright spot in the Mavericks' minicamp and summer league, but he is
considered too short to play shooting guard and not skillful enough
to play point guard. Forget Rodman That nonsense about free-agent
forward Dennis Rodman possibly becoming a member of the Mavericks
is just that: nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis, in my opinion, is the wrong influence to have around a
young team,'' Donnie Nelson said. ``I don't like the message that
we send to our players, and more importantly, to our fans, by
having Dennis Rodman being a Dallas Maverick.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0039 </DOCNO>
