<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWIN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACK MOURNS DRIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Irwindale Speedway flags flew at half-staff
Monday, two days after the death of driver Keith Cowherd of Phoenix
in a Mechanix Wear Speed Truck Challenge race.
</P>
<P>
   Cowherd, to the dismay of Irwindale Speedway officials, was the
second driver to be killed at the $10 million, state-of-the-art
facility in its first six months of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Wilkings, Irwindale's outgoing chief operating officer,
noted that there were only five race-related fatalities in the 30
years that he was the track manager at Saugus Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty rare,'' Wilkings said. ``It's unfortunate that it
happened and unfortunate that it has happened twice. We may go 10
years before it might happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Diemert of Rosebud, Ore., died while practicing in his
sprint car before Irwindale's March 27 opening-night program.
</P>
<P>
   When Kevin Gobrecht died during practice for a World of Outlaws
race at I-80 Speedway in Greenwood, Neb., on Friday, it was only
the second fatality in 20 years for that series.
</P>
<P>
   When Gonzalo Rodriguez died during qualifying for the CART race
at Laguna Seca two weeks ago, it was the first death at the
Monterey road course in 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Marin in Bakersfield has not had a track-related fatality
in more than a decade, track officials said. There have been no
fatalities at California Speedway or at Perris Auto Speedway. A fan
at the Orange Show in San Bernardino died in the early 1980s when
hit by a race car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of the stark reality that this can be a dangerous
sport,'' Irwindale chief executive officer Jim Williams said. ``You
look at CART and until (La Canada native Jeff) Krosnoff died (two
years ago), it was go-go-go with nothing going wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowherd, 49, and Shawn Davidson of Mammoth Lakes got tangled up
entering Turn 1 Saturday night. Davidson hit the atteunator, a
specially designed padding on the wall at the pit area entrance,
nearly head-on. Both spun sideways and Cowherd apparently slammed
sideways into Davidson, who went from about 91 mph to a dead stop
in a matter of milliseconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding is that he suffered blunt-force trauma to
his brain stem,'' Speed Truck series co-director Jay Rutherford
said of Cowherd. The L.A. County Coroner's Office has yet to
perform an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Cowherd was transported to Santa Teresita Hospital in Duarte by
ambulance, where he was pronounced dead at 11:25 p.m.,
approximately an hour after the accident. Davidson was airlifted to
Huntington Memorial Hospital in Pasadena because of possible head
injuries, Wilkings said. Davidson was released from the hospital
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cowherd's wife, Margie, nor his three children, ages 27,
25 and 11, were in attendance Saturday night. Funeral services are
pending.
</P>
<P>
   A moment of silence will be offered for Cowherd before this
Saturday's race. A page dedicated the likable driver will be placed
in the program and a track official will attend his funeral,
Irwindale public relations director Doug Stokes said.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford said the family may donate money to fund a children's
play area at the track to honor Cowherd, who has raced in the
series for a year after giving up drag racing.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first fatality for the San Bernardino-based Speed
Truck series, which consists of identical Chevrolet S-10 trucks.
Drivers cannot tamper with the engines.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford said safety features in both trucks involved in the
accident were checked before the race and were untampered. He said
the cockpit in Cowherd's truck was undamaged, even with a wheel
pushed up to the firewall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The integrity of the chassis and the cockpit were 100 percent
intact,'' he said. ``The trucks were destroyed, but the driver's
compartment was not.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Williams and Wilkingssaid the track has taken more
precautions than any other short track to insure safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built this is as safe as we could possibly build it,'' said
Wilkings, who leaves the speedway Friday for Rebco Co. in Cummins,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The atteunator was designed by Bill Simpson. The foam substance
is the same as that used at the pit entrance to Indianapolis Motor
Speedway. The point where the atteunator is located is wider than
the main outside wall and it curves away from the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did exactly what it was supposed to do,'' Wilkings said.
</P>
<P>
   Speed Truck co-director Mike Face said his company will view
videotape of the accident today. Both cars are still in the
technical inspection area at the speedway. Defending Speed Truck
series champion Art Nevill says Irwindale Speedway is safe -- even
safer than other tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run at Phoenix, were we can get up to 150 mph,'' he said.
``One bad move and something can happen. Something happening like
this is weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevill, from Acton, was not in the race Saturday. He had
severely sprained his ankle and raced to the Southern California
Legends title earlier in the evening, but the ankle prevented him
from properly preparing his truck for racing. He said he was
leaving the facility at the time of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably a sudden stop,'' he said of what killed
Cowherd. ``I think the track is safe. There's only so much you can
do. I've raced on tracks that are not as safe. At Cajon, you have
to make an abrupt turn to get into the pits.''
</P>
<P>
   Orange Show promoter Dan White said he quickly became friends
with Coherd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a really, really nice guy,'' White said. ``He always
had top-looking equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint-car driver Diemert died when he failed to slow down in
Turn 3 when the track went to a caution or yellow flag.
</P>
<P>
   Diemert died of massive head trauma. The cage of his car hit the
outside wall after catapulting off a stalled car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first accident was pilot error,'' Wilkings said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
