<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-QUARTER-HORSE-POW     09-28 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-QUARTER-HORSE-POWERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO POWERS IN QUARTER-HORSE RACING, ONCE PARTNERS, HAVE FOUND
SEPARATE WAYS TO THE TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the equivalent of the Jerry Jones-Jimmy Johnson split
that rocked the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   When jockey Jacky Martin and trainer Jack Brooks ended their
relationship in 1993 as the most powerful combination in the
history of quarter-horse racing _ highlighted by a record six
victories in the All American Futurity at New Mexico's Ruidoso
Downs _ the entire industry was shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew what was going on between them,'' said trainer
Rodney Reed, remembering the summer of 1994 when Martin was trying
to hustle rides at Remington Park in Oklahoma City. ``I just knew
that Jacky showed up and was wanting to get up on a lot of horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell he wanted to ride and do good.''
</P>
<P>
   He has, though it has taken some time. The same thing could be
said for Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   After the split, each stumbled through a three-year slump.
Although still mostly working separately from one another, they're
back at the top and have a chance to cap off a successful year when
the quarter-horse season starts Friday at Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good opportunity. The purses at Lone Star average more
than $140,000 per day, and that's the highest of any track that
races quarter horses.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks and Martin lost their grasp on big purses during the
three years after their breakup, which stemmed from a rocky period
in Martin's personal life. For both, that stretch between 1994 and
'96 was practically their worst since they won their first All
American Futurity in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But since 1997, even though both are largely on their own, they
have found a way to get back to the top. In each case, their
per-year earnings have averaged more than any other period in their
career.
</P>
<P>
   Horses trained by Brooks, a 64-year-old who's based near Edmond,
Okla., earned $2.2 million last year. He's at more than $800,000
this year. Last year's total was the highest since his last All
American victory with Martin on Dash Thru Traffic in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has even won an All American again since then. With G.R.
Carter riding, he won last year's All American with Falling In
Loveagain.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, now living in Weatherford, almost won the All American
this year with a horse trained by Reed. After a tardy break from
the starting gates, Martin got Chicks Call Me rolling and finished
second by a nose to A Delightful Dasher in this year's All
American.
</P>
<P>
   For both of them, it's almost like the old times.
\Nsubheds:Rocky marriage, shocking split The start of the 1993
racing season at Ruidoso looked promising for Martin and Brooks.
They both teamed to win the Kansas Derby, one of the major stakes
races early in the Ruidoso meet.
</P>
<P>
   But the tension already had built around the Brooks stable.
Martin's marriage had fallen apart in nasty fashion. His
father-in-law was one of Brooks' major clients, and it was clear he
was uncomfortable with Martin's riding his horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trained so many for them that I couldn't keep riding
Jacky,'' Brooks said. ``We had it so good for so long. It was a bad
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the split. And while it shocked plenty of quarter-horse
fans, people close to the situation could see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no big fall-out,'' Martin said. ``Me and Jack didn't
have no cuss fight. But I still haven't gotten over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin wanted Brooks to put his foot down. For as long as they
had been together, Martin thought Brooks should have ``handed the
bridles over'' to his clients.
</P>
<P>
   But if Jones thought that any one of hundreds of coaches could
lead the Cowboys to a Super Bowl victory when he split with
Johnson, Brooks knew that there were plenty of jockeys who could
ride his horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had good riders that were riding second for me,''
Brooks said. ``I knew that I was in a position to do pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hating to lose Jacky. But this made him tend to
business. I know he's stronger for it. We're still real good
friends.'' \Nsubheds:Part-time reunion There are reasons for their
comebacks. Though 44 years old, Martin keeps in peak physical
condition. Unlike former quarter-horse trainers D. Wayne Lukas and
Bob Baffert, Brooks has ignored the urge to train thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the look of a quarter horse,'' Brooks said. ``I love
their speed. They're more of an athlete than a thoroughbred. That
awkwardness _ quarter horses can't have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this game, and I keep looking for an All American
Futurity winner every year.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidenced by Brooks' decision to stick with his clients when
the split with Martin occurred, the clientele means so much for a
trainer. One owner who has joined with Brooks, Pat Sorrels of
Kingsland, spent $550,000 for a yearling in September at Ruidoso.
It was the highest yearling purchase of the year. Another client
spent $355,000 for a yearling in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RThe $550,000 yearling\S looks the part,'' Brooks said. ``I
told \RSorrels\S she'd bring a half a million. She was straight
\Rlegged\S. Everything was correct. She'd likely be a runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has plenty of horses, so many that Carter can't ride all
of them. When Brooks qualified Rare King and Dashing Perfection in
the trials of the 1997 Rainbow Derby, Carter chose to ride Rare
King in the final. So Brooks asked Martin if he wanted to ride
Dashing Perfection. He did, and they won.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin has plenty of horses to ride. Instead of riding for
one trainer like he did with Brooks, he's often on horses for
trainers such as Reed, Dwayne ``Sleepy'' Gilbreath, James Lackey
and John Steinbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbreath won an All American Futurity with Refrigerator, but he
has lost enough of those races to Martin to know that if you can't
beat them, join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat me so many dang times, that I knew that if Jacky
Martin ever became available, I was gonna get him to ride for me,''
Gilbreath said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbreath wasn't the only one. Though Martin hasn't quite won
the All American again since the split, he has made another major
inroad in racing history on what was once considered an ordinary
horse.
</P>
<P>
   SLM Big Daddy once was running for a claiming price before he
won some minor stakes races in 1996. But the horse's connections
sought out Martin, and he has won quarter-horse racing's most
important race for older horses _ the Champion of Champions _ each
of the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has become the Bill Shoemaker of quarter-horse racing.
Shoemaker rode a Kentucky Derby winner in his 50s, and age hasn't
caught up to Martin.
</P>
<P>
   It's partly his physical conditioning. And it might also be that
there aren't that many young, up-and-coming riders in quarter-horse
racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a dying breed,'' said Lackey, who rode for 23 years along
with Martin. ``You go through that jock's room and there are more
older riders than younger ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said he's still looking for the next All American
Futurity winner. So's Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do take time off sometimes,'' Martin said, ``but there's
nothing I'd rather do than get on a good racehorse.''
</P>
<P>
   So he'll keep on doing it, even if Brooks isn't the trainer
giving him the leg up anymore.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8434 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS &LR;      09-28 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT ON THE BRINK FOR SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-ORIOLES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the night the Red Sox clinched at least a tie for a playoff
spot, there was a wide divergence of opinion on Pedro Martinez, the
man who brought the Sox to that point with a 5-3 win over the
Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the difference came down to this:
</P>
<P>
   From the sellout crowd of 33,477 attending the Sox' final
regular-season home game and treated to Martinez's 23d win and 12
more strikeouts in eight innings: Pedro is MVP.
</P>
<P>
   From the office of visiting manager Ray Miller of the Orioles:
Pedro is a ``skinny little (potty-mouth synonym for punk).''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was steamed because Martinez, who didn't walk a batter,
plunked Brady Anderson between the numbers with a fastball in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro my ass,'' Miller said. ``Pedro hit my leadoff hitter
right in the middle of the (indecorous adjective) back, when he's
only walked 37 batters all (same indecorous adjective) year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching this guy for 10 years and every good game
he pitches he hits some good hitter right in the middle of the
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Those comments were relayed to Martinez, who had exchanged words
with Anderson in the eighth inning, when Anderson nudged him with
an elbow while crossing the plate on a passed ball. That emptied
the benches and bullpens for some milling around, a scene spiked by
Martinez flexing his right biceps for plate umpire Gary Cederstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Said Miller of Martinez, ``If he had enough (vulgar anatomical
description) to cover home plate, he would have died right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez wondered whether Miller was aware of his whereabouts as
Anderson was crossing the plate and catcher Jason Varitek's throw
went past the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I covered it,'' he said. ``I covered the plate. I didn't even
see (Anderson). If he wanted to start something, he could have
right there. But Brady knows it's part of the game. The ball just
hit him. That's it. Brady stands right on top of the plate. He's
been hit all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Miller is just a frustrated man.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Martinez threw a doozy of a counterpunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Ray Miller has to say, he should say managing his team,''
Martinez said. ``That's a pretty damn good team to manage, and it
didn't do (pungent barnyard epithet).
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to take out his frustrations, let him take it out
managing, not at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston hasn't had an outbreak of manners this bad since . . .
well, the weekend Ryder Cup hoo-ha. Portions of the Fenway crowd,
in fact, acted at times as though they had been imported direct
from The Country Club in Brookline. Bleacherites gave the Colin
Montgomerie treatment to Albert Belle, serenading the Orioles'
designated villain on a night when Belle whiffed three times and
rolled out once, making him 0 for 11 lifetime against Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   There also were two incidents of idiots running onto the field,
one of whom nearly caused Orioles rookie Jerry Hairston, who was at
the plate at the time, to jump out of his skin. Perhaps a prudent
response, given what happened last week in Milwaukee, where
Houston's Bill Spiers suffered whiplash at the hands of a ballfield
trespasser.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he heard of Miller's comments, Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams was already freshly showered and dressed for the team's
trip to Chicago, where it can clinch the wild-card spot outright
with a win Tuesday night over the White Sox, or an Oakland loss at
home against the Angels _ which offers the scenario of a Mo Vaughn
home run putting the Sox in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just another manager's comments,'' Williams said. ``Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just try to take care of our own, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams flipped through some stat sheets on his desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that, his eighth?'' Williams asked, alluding to the
number of batters hit by Martinez pitches this season.
</P>
<P>
   Then he scanned the Orioles' stats. ``He's got a guy with 11.
(Scott) Erickson.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, in fact, was the loser Monday night, giving up a home
run and two-run double to catcher Jason Varitek, a home run to
Brian Daubach, and three hits to Damon Buford, including an RBI
double.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't hit anyone in a Sox uniform, although Nomar
Garciaparra and Trot Nixon were both hit Saturday, and Garciaparra
sat out Monday &UR;  &LR; night's game with a sore right wrist. There also
was this: Anderson, in the view of the Red Sox, had leaned into a
fastball from Tim Wakefield on Sunday, just before Mike Bordick's
two-run double in a five-run Orioles uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Payback?
</P>
<P>
   ``You said that, not me,'' Martinez said sternly. ``I knew
nothing about that. This wasn't a good night for me. I threw a
couple of pitches away from the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, who used to defend Martinez against
head-hunting accusations in Montreal, kept his comments to a
minimum when informed of Miller's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shortstop couldn't play, that's my only response,''
Kerrigan said. ``Selective memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who lowered his major league-leading ERA to 2.08 with
a yield of two runs (only one earned), threw 121 pitches before
being dismissed in favor of Derek Lowe, who gave up a run in the
ninth but came out with his team-leading 15th save.
</P>
<P>
   The win was the Sox' 90th of the season, traditionally a
benchmark of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Toronto, we won 96 games one year and went home,''
Williams said. ``The benchmark is to go to the playoffs. That's the
benchmark.''
</P>
<P>
   So, does it happen tonight in Comiskey Park?
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never make predictions,'' Varitek said. ``But we'll go
out swinging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
