<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS COACH SAYS TEAM'S IDENTITY STILL UNKNOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas football coach Mack Brown watched his Longhorns
rout Baylor, 62-0, Saturday and jump seven places in The Associated
Press poll to No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   But after five games, four of which produced victories, Brown
still is trying to figure out how good this team is.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Longhorns' wins were routs, the Baylor game and a
69-17 victory against Stanford. They also lost the opener to North
Carolina State, 23-20, suffered a letdown in the second half of a
38-21 victory against Rutgers and barely got past Rice, 18-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as bad as people thought after the Rice game,''
Brown said. ``We're not as good as people thought after the
Stanford or Baylor games. Somewhere in between is where we really
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns should find out just where they are this week,
when 13th-ranked Kansas State comes to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the last two games and how can you tell anything
about this team?'' Brown said. ``I have no idea who's going to show
up Saturday. It's hard for me to get a bead on whether we're any
good or not.''
\Nsubheds:Defensive depth The Longhorns shut out the Bears even
though linebacker Aaron Babino, safeties Quentin Jammer and Chris
Butcher and cornerback Joe Walker didn't play because of injuries,
even though defensive tackle Aaron Humphrey sat out the second half
and even though they were able to play a lot of young players
because of the big lead.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that's an indication of how much better the defensive
depth is this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play without Joe Walker, Quentin Jammer, Chris Butcher,
Aaron Babino and Aaron Humphrey last year, we would have had to
call the game off because we didn't have anybody to put in their
place,'' he said. ``That means we are making some progress. Anytime
you shut somebody out and play so many guys, that's exciting.''
\Nsubheds:Ike No. 2 Kenny Hayter, a freshman, got the bulk of the
work as the backup to Hodges Mitchell against Baylor while Victor
Ike carried just five times. But Brown said that Ike, a redshirt
freshman who carried 55 times for 214 yards in the first four
games, remains the second-string tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victor only touching it five times didn't have anything to do
with Victor,'' Brown said. ``We wanted to let Kenny get some
experience because we may need him before the year is over.''
nn
</P>
