<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AIKMAN-CARDINALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' AIKMAN SAYS CARDINALS NOT NECESSARILY ON SUPER BOWL PATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Quarterback Troy Aikman looks at the Cowboys'
opponent this week and sees a good football team, certainly a
legitimate contender for the NFC East title.
</P>
<P>
   What Aikman and his laser-repaired eyes don't see in the Arizona
Cardinals, however, is a team that is ``turning it around,''
despite a hapless-to-happy 1998 campaign that culminated with a
20-7 victory over the Cowboys in the wild-card playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, 1-2 after a 24-10 loss to San Franciso last
night, are looking to prove that the playoff victory was no upset.
And many of the Cowboys, who come off a bye week, are looking for
some payback for the season-ruining playoff loss.
</P>
<P>
   However, winning a playoff game for the first time in 51 years
is one thing. Winning consistently in the regular season, winning a
division title and ultimately winning a Super Bowl are the
differences between the Cowboys and the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tendency any time a team gets over the hump so to
speak that people want to try and say, `Do you see yourself back in
'91 or '92','' Aikman said. ``We accomplished a great deal in a
very short period of time. No one had done that before us. No one
has done it since. I think it's throwing compliments a little
prematurely.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said that he is not picking on the Cardinals and that
they are just the latest team christened as ``next year's
champions.'' Aikman pointed out that Tampa Bay lived down to such
expectations last season by not even making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of teams that they want to crown as next
year's champions or the next dynasty that never even get to that
point where you can say they're a great football team,'' Aikman
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cardinals to be great, they have to not only build on
what they accomplished last year but raise their standards to the
level of other perennial contenders like the Cowboys, Green Bay and
San Francisco, Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last year, they can look back and say `Boy, we really
made some progress; we're doing some things right','' Aikman said.
``But now this year, their standards pretty much fall in line along
with the top teams in the league. With those teams, it ultimately
comes down to whether or not you win the Super Bowl. Just winning a
playoff game is no longer the criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Cardinals won that wild-card playoff game in dominating
fashion was the foundation for the preseason talk of a changing of
the guard in the NFC East. Even though the Cardinals actually lost
two of three meetings to the Cowboys last year, the bandwagon
picked the Cardinals, led by the next-great quarterback, Jake
Plummer, to win their first division title since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys defensive back Darren Woodson, who said the loss tainted
what had been a record-setting season in which the Cowboys became
the first team to sweep their way to the NFC East title, said he
and his teammates will be looking to make a statement Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a revenge factor?'' Woodson said. ``Yes. We beat them
twice but the one loss was the last game of the season. It still
burns in our mind. Everybody looked at them as the NFC East
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, the loss ended the Cowboys' season. That's
something that lingered in the minds of many Cowboys players
throughout the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing,'' middle linebacker Randall Godfrey
said. ``They knocked us out of the playoffs. They came in and
embarrassed us in our own back yards. We owe them one. We'll be
ready for them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
