<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8445 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DIGITAL-HOLLYWOOD-2-t     09-28 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-HOLLYWOOD-2-takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET-BASED FIRMS LEADING MEDIA'S FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a sprawling, sleek warren of offices in a Santa
Monica warehouse, dozens of young people hunch over Macintosh G3
computers, busily creating the future of entertainment _ and Los
Angeles' economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, their company _ Digital Entertainment Network, or
DEN _ had just 25 employees. Today, it has more than 200, and wants
to hire an additional 100 in the next month, said company President
David Neuman.
</P>
<P>
   While a four-day conference began Monday in Beverly Hills to
show how DEN and other Internet companies can revive the
entertainment industry, a group of top business and political
leaders met at Universal City to discuss how to gird Hollywood
against runaway production and preserve its dominance.
</P>
<P>
   The old and new media exploit what Los Angeles does best:
create.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, the key is going to be content,'' Jack Kyser,
chief economist of the Los Angeles County Economic Development
Corp. ``You have all these Web sites, and they've got to have the
eyeballs come back again if they're going to survive. And content
is one thing we in Los Angeles are very, very good at.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as DEN are opening shop on the Internet and
creating good-paying jobs in whole new arenas. These new
Internet-based media companies, observers say, will help keep Los
Angeles on top of the entertainment business and even give the city
a claim as the capital of the new media age.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-based media companies are the stars of the Digital
Hollywood conference at the Beverly Hilton Hotel, sponsored by the
Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association and focusing on the
merger of the television and computer and Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On a parallel track, city officials and legislators attended a
discussion hosted by the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences to
figure out how to keep movie production in Los Angeles. Assemblyman
Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, has authored one of two bills that would
offer tax credits to California-based TV and film projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually believe we have a good opportunity to push this not
only at a state level, but at a national level. Hollywood has stood
up,'' Wildman said. ``Unlike 42 countries, in California we don't
have any incentives for the entertainment industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Shea, president of the Director's Guild of America, said
the migration of film crews could have lasting effects in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The infrastructure is here, and if it starts to wither away it
is not going to affect us right this moment, it will affect us 10
years down the line,'' said Shea, who called for federal government
intervention on a par with incentives, like labor rebates, that the
Canadian National Government offers the film industry.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Neuman is concerned, the Internet is a savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole industry is a sleeping giant that will be
an overwhelming positive for Southern California,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Southland already has some media giants _ the networks and
studios _ who are likely to get in on the action.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Tercek, vice president of technology for Columbia TriStar
who heads their online efforts, said DEN, New York's Pseudo.com and
others are perfect takeover targets for the big studios and
networks.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that the studios and networks would see such
acquisitions as a quick way to do programming in a medium where
they so far have done little.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a universe of 50,000 channels, the 500 that are going to
make it are the ones with the access to marketing muscle,'' Trecek
said. ``And the ones with marketing muscle are the studios and
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   The content that DEN (at !bold!www.den.net!off!) is creating is
essentially a new kind of online mixed media. It combines
semiweekly, six-minute video episodes similar to television with
areas where viewers can chat with each other, buy clothing and
gear, play games and more, all more or less at the same time. In
all, it's putting together 30 different kinds of programs, each
focused on a well-defined slice of youth culture, from Christian
teens (``Redemption High'') to skate punks (``Aggronation'') to
college kids (``Frat Ratz'').
</P>
<P>
   Other firms _ such as Steeplechase Media in Santa Monica,
WireBreak Networks in Venice and Spike Networks in Hollywood _ have
also sprung up in recent months, creating their own kinds of
new-media experiences.
</P>
<P>
   A series of recent national studies have placed the Los Angeles
area second only to the San Francisco-Silicon Valley area for
technology jobs. L.A. already employs more than 130,000 such
people, and observers say the business here is only going to
increase as the Internet becomes faster, easier to use and more
widely embraced, and as existing movie, music, special effects and
television companies diversify onto the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Jason McCabe Calcanis, publisher of the New York-based Silicon
Alley Reporter and its Southern California offshoot, Digital Coast
Reporter, proclaims the future belongs to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   That's because most of the Northern California Internet
companies now making headlines and billionaires create what
Calcanis calls ``plumbing,'' the machinery and computer programs
that allow the Internet to function. What they don't create is what
people increasingly will seek on the Net: entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very big market,'' said Calcanis, though
it will be at least a couple of years before large numbers of
people have the high-speed broadband connections to the Internet
that allow high-quality video similar to what people have watched
for years on television, while allowing two-way interactions that
television will never provide.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DIGITAL-HOLLYWOOD-2nd     09-28 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-HOLLYWOOD-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: will never provide. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Internet today is anemic,'' Calcanis said. ``That lends
itself to New York's strengths in publishing and music. But as we
all know, the Net is getting faster and broadband will play to
L.A.'s strengths. The truth is, the Internet means nothing but for
the creatives.''
</P>
<P>
   And while some jobs are being lost because of runaway
production, new jobs with different skills are likely to be
created. Digital training centers at UCLA, the University of
Southern California and the American Film Institute are a few of
the places where workers can get training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the resources we have,'' Kyser said. ``The idea is
that the creativity is here. You also find that creative people
like to cluster, like to talk to one another. They have a different
lifestyle, too. A lot of these other places around the U.S. may
talk a good game, but they're not that open to (that kind of
openness).''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Tercek and others say, the role of broadcast
channels and Web sites may dramatically change, with over-the-air
networks becoming ``barker channels.'' Through advertisement and
promotion they would direct their larger audiences to more
specialized Web sites of narrower demographic slices that would
appeal to top advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the networks and studios have set up Web sites to
promote programs and films but little else. Recently, Sony began
netcasting enhanced interactive versions of two of its biggest TV
properties, ``Jeopardy'' and ``Wheel of Fortune,'' and other
companies such as Viacom have announced substantial additions to
their Web presences, including a broader MTV site _ although so far
they have not created programs distinctively different from what
their broadcasts provide. Which is why they're looking at companies
like DEN.
</P>
</TEXT>
