<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8455 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f BC-GIFTEDAUTHOR-AZR &LR;      09-28 1645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTEDAUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR WRITES ABOUT GREAT BOSSES, RULES HIMSELF OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Attn: Chicago, Minneapolis, St. Louis and other users of Dale
Dauten columns   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Not all bosses are jerks. A few are great, believe it
or not, and many are simply ``a sap'' like writer Dale Dauten says
he was when he owned a thriving market-research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``My employees loved me. I was much taken advantage of. I was
overpaying them and letting them do whatever they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, they loved me,'' muses the self-styled ``Corporate
Curmudgeon,'' as he calls the seriocomic newspaper column he writes
from the office of his Tempe, Ariz., home. The weekly column on the
foibles of America's workplaces runs in 30 newspapers across the
country, including ``The Arizona Republic,'' the ``Chicago
Tribune,'' the ``Minneapolis Star Tribune'' and the ``St. Louis
Post-Dispatch.'' He also co-authors another syndicated column with
even wider circulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was  &UR; not &LR;  a gifted boss,'' Dauten says with an authority
that comes from years of exploring what, exactly, it takes to be
one.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in his fourth book, ``The Gifted Boss: How to Find, Create,
and Keep Great Employees,'' Dauten distills into little more than
100 pages of plain-spoken insight and unpretentious wit what he has
learned about transcending mediocrity _ not to mention avoiding
being a jerk or sap _ in the complex task of managing people.
</P>
<P>
   The new book, coupled with a loyal following of his columns and
wide exposure via his interactive Web site (would-be climbers of
corporate ladders can take a test at www.dauten.com to gauge their
promotability), has suddenly propelled Dauten beyond his first love
_ writing _ and increasingly onto the stage as a professional
speaker at corporate gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   He's delivering half a dozen speeches across the nation in an
eight-week period, and is a finalist for a booking in Paris. He
observes wryly that his fee of $7,500 per talk still puts him ``in
the bargain bin'' at about one-fifth the rate charged by another
Phoenix-area resident, can-do business columnist Harvey Mackay, and
one-tenth that of Tom Peters, the acclaimed guru of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't call his commentaries, which he delivers from a stool
a la Garrison Keillor, ``motivational speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I make fun of motivational speakers,'' he said. ``I believe
people are self-motivated; you can't give it to them in a speech.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Gifted,'' Dauten calls upon his alter ego, the fictional
sage Max Elmore he introduced in his 1996 book, ``The Max
Strategy,'' to impart the keys to being a superboss. Through
focused conversation and easy repartee, plus visits to a couple of
Valley workplaces, Max does so in just 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it took the 48-year-old Dauten a lot longer to get
the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Academically, he was a whiz even beyond what could be expected
of the son of an Arizona State University business professor and a
devoted homemaker mother. By age 21, he had completed bachelor's
and master's degrees in economics at ASU and was enrolled in a
doctoral program at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Not ready to commit to the professorial life, he came back to
the Phoenix area and went to work.
</P>
<P>
   Dauten admits having failed to recognize that his first boss, an
explosive executive at the Phoenix headquarters of U-Haul's parent,
Amerco, was truly gifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was terrified instead of inspired by him. His displays of
temper and other extremes of good-old-boy phenomena just left me
appalled,'' Dauten said. ``I could have learned more from him,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   When the young market researcher moved on, he fit in better at
the old Armour-Dial Inc., a subsidiary of Phoenix-based Greyhound
Corp. during the mid-1970s. He rose within a couple of years to
manager of market research for a company that was racking up
successes rolling out such products as new antiperspirants and
Coast soap. It sent him to New York for a week of specialized
training every month.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he was noticed as a star performer, or ``Wild Brain'' as
he calls it in his book, and was recruited by a national
market-research firm. That started his career in consulting, first
in Dallas and then, with another company, in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would gather all these tables of numbers around me, and they
would speak to me,'' he recalled as if from a past life.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath his numbers wizardry, however, lay a deep yearning to
write.
</P>
<P>
   By age 30, he had founded his own market-research firm in
Atlanta, become a father and somehow found time to write his first
book, ``Quitting,'' ``a study of big changes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was done in a market-research type of way,'' Dauten said,
``and it showed I needed to learn how to write. I was still an
academic _ the longer the word, the longer the sentence, the more
profound it must be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed that if I wrote a book of any substance it would
find an audience.'' It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole career has been characterized by naivete,'' confesses
the man who now finds himself giving career advice. He collaborates
with New York job counselor Kate Wendleton to produce ``Kate &AMP; Dale
Talk Jobs,'' a weekly question-and-answer column appearing in more
than 100 newspapers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm telling people how to manage, how to live their
lives?'' he asked mockingly.
</P>
<P>
   He knocks himself for not having realized years ago that the
employees of his multimillion-dollar company should have been
solving most of their work problems themselves instead of dumping
them on him. And he confesses that as a boss, he wasn't even
resolute enough to make it stick when he fired an employee he
remembers as chronically undependable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fired her half a dozen times, and she kept coming back,''
Dauten said. It was his wife, Sandy, now a leading saleswoman for
Shea Homes and a plenty dependable mother for their two teenage
boys still at home and a 19-year-old daughter who has left the
nest.
</P>
<P>
   Although his Atlanta firm had only five employees and was a
pioneer in farming out volumes of work before ``outsourcing'' was
even a common business term, it projected a big business image
through a quarterly newsletter. That helped reel in and retain such
powerhouse clients as Procter &AMP; Gamble, AT&AMP;T, McDonald's, Gil
lette, Colgate and Coors.
</P>
<P>
   Dauten says it was because he started running out of serious
ideas for the newsletter that he began writing tongue-in-cheek
commentaries. Clients were delighted, one likening them to the work
of the era's consummate curmudgeon, Andy Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the mid-1980s, Dauten authored a second book, this one
far more readable, called ``Taking Chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of his business to employees in 1988 gave the family
resources to move almost anywhere, he says. After a halting stint
in the Los Angeles area, the choice was to come home to Tempe,
where he had grown up from age 10, graduated from McClintock High
School and where he and Sandy had met at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   His love of the city eventually turned into six years of service
on its Planning and Zoning Commission. Term limits ended his tenure
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dauten's ``Corporate Curmudgeon'' column first got ink eight
years ago after Jim Fickess, now a team leader in the Business
section of ``The Arizona Republic,'' agreed to run it when he was
business editor at Tribune Newspapers in suburban Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year later, Dauten got a call from King Features
Syndicate in New York offering him a contract. Until his column
went into national syndication, it hadn't paid him a penny.
</P>
<P>
   As the Corporate Curmudgeon, doing take-offs on memos to
employees from the pompous managerial ranks of Mundane Industries,
Dauten can wield a saber as sharply ticklish as Dilbert's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The examined life is a process of peeling away the layers of
stupidity,'' he observes in ``Gifted.''
</P>
<P>
   He also is a wordsmith who, in a touching column written from an
employee's viewpoint, tells bosses everywhere, ``I only work for
people who look up to me, even from the top floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an affirmation that, hey, I'm not alone out here battling
these forces against us,'' said ardent fan Dan Hagerman, who worked
his way into management after starting 20 years ago as a
deliveryman in the food-service business.
</P>
<P>
   Hagerman discovered Dauten's columns in Minneapolis before
moving to Scottsdale three years ago, and credits them as one of
the influences behind his shift to a new career: conducting
training programs for corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   Dauten is hard-pressed to define how he came by his ability to
inspire through humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always was a wise-ass _ that much came naturally,'' he
offers with one of the impish smiles that break readily above a
sharp chin and graying goatee. It also helped that, along with many
of the rewards of business success, he had steady doses of
corporate America's euphemistic jargon and eternal politicking.
</P>
<P>
   Once, a company paid him $10,000 to research whether the prize
it would be giving away in a contest should be a teddy bear or a
unicorn.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Here's a coin; why don't you just flip it?,' I wanted to
tell them,'' Dauten says with a shrug. They had referred the
monumental question to him, he later learned, because rival
executives had differed on the choice of a prize and subordinates
were afraid to align themselves with either one until they had
market data in hand to justify their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Reader response to his columns keeps him well stocked with
material about the best and worst of the business world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a stream of letters from employees _ mostly
dissatisfied, many out of work _ and I get wonderful ideas from
managers and entrepreneurs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here in the delta of ideas and information, and I get to
pick what to write about.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
