<HEADLINE>
L.A. BRACES FOR STAPLES OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the Staples Center scheduled to open in three
weeks, Los Angeles officials were told Wednesday to expect
confusion among drivers during the first months the arena is
opened, as well as a potential parking conflict with the auto show
in January.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council's Ad Hoc Committee on the Los Angeles Arena was
assured that the city was prepared to make changes as problems
develop _ including creation of a permit parking area _ in
neighboring residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Rifkin of the city's Department of Transportation, said a
team of traffic and police officials has been formed to monitor all
traffic in and out of the arena, particularly during the first
months of operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people become familiar with downtown and the best way to
get to Staples, we think a lot of the initial problems will go
away,'' Rifkin said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there will be message boards and signs directing people
to and from the 20,000-seat facility as well as a series of shuttle
buses from remote parking.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Rita Walters, in whose district the facility is
located, voiced concern about what she saw as a lack of planning on
mass departures from the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be arriving at all different times, but they will
be leaving at the same time,'' Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they have set a time line of emptying all parking
lots within 45 minutes after the event and believe that can be met.
Emptying of Dodger Stadium takes 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Hernandez said he is concerned about the impact
on the auto show, which is one of the biggest tenants of the
adjacent Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to consider the impact on the auto show,'' Hernandez
said. ``It is a very important event for the city and, from the
very beginning, concern was expressed about the impact of the arena
on this event.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Liewecke, president of the Los Angeles Arena Co., said some
parking spaces at the Convention Center has been lost to the auto
show, but has been made up with other spaces directly across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, Staples Center will be closed during four days of
the show.
</P>
<P>
   However, a representative of the auto show complained that the
Los Angeles Clippers will play the Indiana Pacers on Jan. 8, the
first day of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mike Feuer also raised the issue of increased costs
to the city for traffic control.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Staples Center would cover any costs for areas
where traffic increases by more than 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
