<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTEDBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIFTED' BOSSES FOUND HERE AND THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Gifted Boss: How to Find, Create and Keep Great Employees 
By Dale Dauten (William Morrow and Co., $20) 
 
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Syndicated business columnist Dale Dauten's ``The Gifted Boss''
opens with a set of characteristics so uncomplicated they fit on a
single page. It's through the rest of his compact volume that the
ideals he calls ``The Six Realities of Gifted Bosses and Great
Employees'' come to life, illuminated by about 50 individuals and
companies.
</P>
<P>
   He found as many as a dozen of the examples in the balmy Phoenix
metropolitan area, where he lives, and the second-largest batch in
the Twin Cities area, where he has had business ties.
</P>
<P>
   Examples range from John Genzale, now editor of the national
magazine ``SportsBusiness Journal,'' who inspired better staff
writing by holding weekly poetry readings in the newsroom of the
Phoenix ``Business Journal,'' to Tempe-based Insight Group, whose
founding brothers built their headquarters in the shape of an X to
help ensure that employees from all sectors would cross paths.
</P>
<P>
   The book's most touching anecdote tells of the extraordinary
esprit de corps shown by Insight personnel, including Chief
Executive Eric Crown, when a key employee returned to work after
chemotherapy. Scores of co-workers, including women and the big
boss himself, had their heads shaved in solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps none of the gifted bosses Dauten writes about is a
perfect manager, he concedes, but each illustrates one or more
aspects of what it takes to be great. And sometimes, he points out,
the solution to a bad-boss trait is as simple as the advice he
quotes from former Porsche CEO Peter Schutz: ``Stop doing that!''
</P>
<P>
   The book's central message is that the highest function of a
boss is to create ``the best place for the best people to work''
and to focus unlimited attention on recruiting only the type of
people _ ``Wild Brains,'' Dauten calls them _ who immediately
become the star performers of whatever tasks they take on.
</P>
<P>
   As in Dauten's 1996 book, the equally slim and pithy ``The Max
Strategy: How a Businessman Got Stuck at an Airport and Learned to
Make His Career Take Off'' (the title was imposed on him, he says
ruefully), Dauten lets an eccentric oracle of management, the
fictional Max Elmore, serve as the agent of change. In both books,
the narrator, a middle manager who has caught a whiff of smoke from
impending burnout, represents the author himself at critical stages
of his career, Dauten says.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier book was a contemplation of career paths (skip the
rigid goal-setting exercises you read about elsewhere, because
success is ``usually an accident''); innovation (``experiments
never fail'' if you learn from them); and quality (a favorite
theme: ``Different isn't always better, but better is always
different'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``Gifted,'' retiree Max, described as ``a kid in an aging
body, fizzing with the wisdom of nearly eight decades of
curiosity,'' reconnects in Phoenix with his disciple.
</P>
<P>
   Readers will judge for themselves whether the Max persona rings
true or ultimately distracts as he repeatedly drives home points by
punching the narrator's shoulder, gripping his knee, putting a
fatherly arm around him during a stroll through downtown Phoenix or
jabbing a finger or fist into the air.
</P>
<P>
   But physicality aside, Max is one savvy interpreter of how an
earnest manager can keep everyone in an organization so blissfully
productive that the manager's own bosses ``lie awake at night and
thank the Lord that you work for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental task of the best manager is not to manage,''
he counsels. ``The job of the gifted boss is to create a magnetic
environment, one capable of attracting great employees _ the kind
who don't need management, who lift up their co-workers and even
their boss.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
