<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8461 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f BC-GIFTEDBOX-AZR &LR;      09-28 0216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTEDBOX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK'S KEY POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)   c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Six Realities of Gifted Bosses and Great Employees'':
</P>
<P>
   1. The ``talent-squared'' workplace is possible because gifted
bosses and great employees want the same things from a workplace:
</P>
<P>
   _ Freedom from management, mediocrity and morons.
</P>
<P>
   _ A change.
</P>
<P>
   _ A chance.
</P>
<P>
   2. Gifted bosses don't just hire employees, they acquire allies.
</P>
<P>
   3. Great employees don't have jobs, they have talents. They
enter the job market once (if at all), and thereafter their talents
are spotted, courted and won over.
</P>
<P>
   4. Great bosses and employees often reverse the typical job
search: Instead of the employee doing the ``hunting,'' it's the
boss. The process more resembles a ``talent search'' than a ``job
market.''
</P>
<P>
   5. While many gifted bosses have created such special work
environments that they have virtually no turnover, many others
embrace substantial turnover and become masters of ``the secret
skill'' of firing.
</P>
<P>
   6. An alliance between a gifted boss and a great employee is a
kinship of talent, often creating a bond that can last a lifetime. &QL; 
 &QL; 
From ``The Gifted Boss,'' copyright 1999 by Dale Dauten, published
by William Morrow and Co. Inc. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 0229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8469 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BAUER-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRO     09-28 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAUER-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP HOPEFUL BAUER SEES RACE GETTING NASTY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ GOP presidential hopeful Gary Bauer said Monday
that he is the target of printed gossip that a current Republican
candidate is having an affair with a younger woman _ calling it a
``devastating'' and false allegation emanating from a rival
campaign.
<P>
   The former policy adviser to Ronald Reagan and president of the
conservative Family Research Council, in an interview with The
Chronicle Monday, forcefully addressed a gossip item printed in the
New York Daily News this week and repeated Monday in the National
Journal's Hotline.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News' Daily Dish column read: ``What presidential
candidate is praying that a former secretary doesn't go public with
her claim that he's been having an affair with a twentysomething
woman? Many on the married Republican's campaign staff are already
jumping ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, whose national campaign chair Charles Jarvis resigned
last week to work for rival GOP candidate Steve Forbes, was asked
whether he was the subject of the item.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's supposed to be me. And it's disgusting,'' said
the candidate without hesitation. ``It almost makes me physically
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I have been married for 27 years. We have three
children. I have been loyal to her, and she's been loyal to me all
those years,'' he added. ``And it is depressing that in American
politics, this sort of thing can be elevated to even that rung.''
</P>
<P>
   The gossip about Bauer _ and his forceful response _ may
illustrate how ferocious the GOP presidential race is becoming,
with six months still go to before the voters even cast a ballot in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer was in San Francisco Monday to deliver a foreign policy
address to the Commonwealth Club of California. He was met by a
standing ovation from a crowd of 70 after he called for revoking
China's most-favored nation trading status because of widespread
human rights abuses there.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer also said the withdrawal of Dan Quayle from the race may
earn him support from Republicans who believe Bauer is ``a GOP
conservative alternative to the front-runner.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after his speech, Bauer did not flinch when
asked about rumors _ floated at last weekend's state GOP convention
_ suggesting that the departure of his campaign chair related to
personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said that not only would an affair be wrong, but the
gossip ``doesn't pass the straight-face test. You'd have to be a
complete idiot to do something like this in the glare of a
presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the sort of thing I hoped to avoid, because I think
it's why so many Americans are turned off about politics,'' he
said. ``It's disgusting. It's outrageous. It's trash-can
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who might be responsible for such rumors, Bauer said, ``I
think it's coming from the camp of one of my political opponents,''
but he declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis told The Chronicle last week he resigned from Bauer's
campaign because Forbes had the political muscle _ and the message
_ to become the strongest conservative in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary's a very, very skilled guy ... (but) we are talking not
about the class president. We are talking the president of the
United States, and this is a watershed election,'' Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   But some political supporters have suggested that Bauer has been
the target of a vicious whisper campaign since he placed an
unexpectedly strong fourth in the Iowa Straw Poll and issued policy
directives like his own flat-tax initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer hinted at the matter when asked by a Commonwealth Club
audience member if he has enjoyed running for president.
</P>
<P>
   He said it has been ``the most incredibly positive thing you can
imagine, because you get to go all over the country and meet good
and decent people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's also a terrible, terrible downside,'' Bauer added.
``I would shock you if I told you all of the ... rumors that are
going on, and attacks on my integrity, things that have been said
about my family and my wife. I have one daughter in tears because
of things she's heard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American politics more and more resembles the trash can,
rather than the kind of debates that Lincoln and Douglas had,'' he
told them. ``But I'm going to fight the good fight.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
