<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-RACE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL AND UNZ CONSIDER A SENATE RACE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARK SIMON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Republican Congressman Tom Campbell has been
talking with political supporters about running for the U.S. Senate
next year against incumbent Democrat Dianne Feinstein, according to
sources close to Campbell.
<P>
   Campbell, a San Francisco Bay area representative whose
tech-savvy and pro-choice background could give him a chance at
attracting the coveted ``moderate middle,'' declined to comment on
his political future Monday. But sources said he has been receiving
encouragement from Republicans alarmed that no credible challenger
would take Feinstein on next year.
</P>
<P>
   And at least a portion of Campbell's motivation for considering
the race may be an ultimatum from Stanford Law School officials
that he must return to full-time teaching or surrender his tenured
professorship. Stanford Law School Dean Kathleen Sullivan said
Monday that she and Campbell ``are involved in ongoing discussions
about how he might possibly integrate his future political and
academic careers.''
</P>
<P>
   If he decides to take on Feinstein, Campbell would enter the GOP
primary as the only moderate in a race that has attracted two other
conservatives and the possibility of a third.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide ballot initiative devotee Ron Unz, a challenger to
incumbent Gov. Pete Wilson in 1994, confirmed Monday that he is
thinking about running. San Diego County Supervisor Bill Horn has
said he will run, and Riverside state Sen. Ray Haynes formally
announced his candidacy over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But the political chatter this week here and in Washington has
focused on Campbell, whose refusal to comment, as barebones as it
might be, represents a significant shift in his public stance about
a Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several months, Campbell, who lost a Senate
Republican primary race in 1992, steadfastly has insisted that he
would run for re-election to the South Bay congressional seat he
first won in a special election in 1995, replacing retiring
incumbent Democrat Norman Mineta.
</P>
<P>
   But now, flat assertions of a run for re-election are being
replaced with statements that are more open-ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is running for re-election until he, himself, makes the
announcement that he is exploring a Senate race,'' said Kevin
Spillane, Campbell's campaign manager in the last three campaigns.
``Any announcement is off in the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Those closest to Campbell say he has been making phone calls
over the last several days, discussing with them a possible Senate
race. Washington sources also say Campbell met personally with
Feinstein last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely thinking about it,'' said one longtime
Campbell supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is what he's told me, which is that he's thinking
about it, and he needs a few weeks to make up his mind,'' said one
Republican who is a close friend of Campbell's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to do it,'' said a political insider in the high-tech
industry. ``He's making a lot of phone calls, getting a lot of
mixed signals.''
</P>
<P>
   The mixed signals include many Republican opinion leaders who
are convinced that defeating Feinstein is nearly impossible as well
as others who are growing concerned that she will face too easy a
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A Field Poll last month showed Feinstein favored by 53 percent
of the state's voters over Horn or Haynes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she'll be very, very difficult to beat,'' said Menlo
Park venture capitalist Floyd Kvamme, (CQ)  &LR; one of the leading
Republicans in the Technology Network, the principal Silicon Valley
political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is very, very popular, and on a lot of the big issues,
education in particular, she's been very good,'' Kvamme said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein's popularity appears to give some pause to Unz, a
Silicon Valley executive, who spent $750,000 on Proposition 227,
last year's successful initiative banning bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   Author of a 2000 ballot measure on campaign reform, Unz said he
has been encouraged to consider the campaign by some Republican
leaders who were worried that no credible candidate would take on
Feinstein, echoing the comments made by those who say Campbell is
being urged on for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year or two ago, a lot of names were being bandied about,
but every few months, the list keeps shrinking down more and
more,'' Unz said.
</P>
<P>
   He described Feinstein as ``the 800-pound gorilla of California
politics. ... I think she certainly would be viewed as the
overwhelming incumbent.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein was elected to the Senate in a special election in
1992 and was re-elected in 1994, narrowly defeating
then-Representative Michael Huffington.
</P>
<P>
   As her re-election approaches, Feinstein has $2 million in the
bank, according to campaign manager Kam Kuwata, who said she began
actively raising money early this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been complacent. We have felt from Day 1 we would
have a race, so Campbell's flirtation comes as no surprise,''
Kuwata said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
