<HEADLINE>
IT'S NO PASSING FANCY: COWBOYS ARE AMONG NFC'S BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Atlanta and Minnesota a combined 1-5 and with the Packers
needing miracles just to win at home, the Cowboys can make a strong
argument for being the best team in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   Though inconsistent at times, the Cowboys' offense, fortified by
the best offensive line in the league, can score points on anyone.
And despite the efforts of the Buccaneers, offense, not defense,
gets the bills paid in this league.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a long way to go. The Cowboys have two
games with the Cardinals remaining, as well as games against Green
Bay, Minnesota, Miami and New England. The truth about the Cowboys,
who trailed by 21 at Washington and struggled to defeat a Chris
Chandler/Jamal Anderson-less Falcons team, will soon come out.
</P>
<P>
   But unless Randy Moss starts acting like Randy Moss, and unless
Steve Young and Jerry Rice start playing like it's 1994 again, the
Cowboys' chances of representing the NFC in the Super Bowl are as
good as anybody else's. Off with their heads Bruce Coslet: The
Bengals coach is 17-27 in his fourth year with the club. On Sunday,
Cincinnati outgained Carolina and held nearly a 15-minute
possession advantage, yet the Bengals still suffered a 24-point
loss to the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Hitchcock: The Vikings wide receiver knew the Packers had
time for just one more play. Yet he still sat on a short route and
let Corey Bradford run by him to haul in Brett Favre's winning pass
with 12 seconds to go in the Packers' 23-20 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Brunell: On the shadow of the Titans' goal line and needing
a field goal to tie, the Jaguars quarterback forced a pass into
double coverage, which was intercepted in Jacksonville's 20-19
upset loss to Tennessee. Running with Wolf Packers general manager
Ron Wolf should get executive-of-the-year honors just for the way
his club played against the Vikings. Last year, Randy Moss had 343
receiving yards and three touchdowns against the Packers. Last
April, Wolf selected three cornerbacks in the first three rounds of
the draft to defend Moss. On Sunday, Mike McKenzie, one of those
rookie corners, helped hold Moss to two receptions for 13 yards and
a touchdown in the Packers' 23-20 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Packers quarterback Brett Favre was near tears after the
emotional win in which he completed the game-winning touchdown with
12 seconds remaining. But Wolf was just as emotional.
</P>
<P>
   It feels good not to have to come down here and talk to you guys
\Rmedia\S about how Randy Moss beat us up,'' Wolf said. On the
defensive Offensive football is the rage in the NFL. Yet there were
some clubs Sunday who reminded of how defense was played in the
1970s. Oakland held the Bears to 34 yards rushing. Buffalo held
Philadelphia to 22 yards rushing. Tampa Bay held its third
consecutive opponent to fewer than 10 first downs in defeating
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   But a team needs to score points to win. Clubs that scored at
least 24 points on Sunday were 8-0, and are 26-6 overall. Clubs
with at least 350 yards of total offense were 6-2 and are 22-11
overall. Just noticing In Buffalo, where the Eagles were held to 22
yards rushing, Philadelphia running back Duce Staley's carries went
like this: 0, 1, 0, minus-3, 1, 2, minus-1, 3, 2, 1. The Eagles, by
the way, have been shut out four times since Opening Day 1998: by
Seattle, the Cowboys, the Giants and the Bills on Sunday, 26-0. ...
In the past two weeks, the Broncos have scored one more point than
the expansion Browns (20-19). ... The Patriots-Giants game Sunday
night was the first in which neither team committed a turnover.
 &LR; tagtop:Kevin Lyons (817) 390-7237
 &LR; tagbottom:lyonsnfl &LR; star-telegram.com
Week 3 Top 5 NFL writer Kevin Lyons picks his top teams after Week
3: 1. Miami 2-0 2. Green Bay 2-1 3. New England 3-0 4. Dallas 2-0
5. Jacksonville 2-1
</P>
<P>
   Grading the NFL NFL writer Kevin Lyons gives his marks on Week 3
in the NFL. New York, New York F In successive weeks, the Jets and
Giants fell to the Washington Redskins. Throw in the struggles of
the baseball Mets, and a mosquito-borne viral disease that's going
around, and one can see it has been tough in Gotham City. Parity
B-plus Among the division leaders are Detroit (2-1), St. Louis
(2-0), Tennessee (3-0), Kansas City (2-1), Oakland (2-1), and
Seattle (2-1). None of these clubs made the playoffs in 1998. The
four clubs who made the conference finals, meanwhile _ Atlanta,
Minnesota, Denver, and the Jets _ are a combined 1-11. Eagles
travel schedule F A0fter a 26-0 loss at Buffalo, Philadelphia is
0-17-1 in its past 18 road games. The Eagles have not won on the
road since Dec. 14, 1996, when they defeated the Jets.
