<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-VOLUNTEERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volunteers from across N.C., U.S. pitch in for relief efforts
 &HT;    By Eunice Moscoso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ It came in the form of barbecued pork, warm
blankets and 10,000 loaves of bread. It arose from farm soil,
flowed in from other towns, resonated at churches and multiplied at
local stores.
</P>
<P>
   In the devastating ftermath of Hurricane Floyd, thousands of
hands softened the brutal impact. After federal, state and local
agencies moved in quickly to save lives, volunteers from all walks
of life also came to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   They cooked, cleaned, raised money, collected clothing, packed
up boxes, served meals, fed animals and faced countless other human
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   For Philip Tyson, 80, the fury of floodwater caused an
unforeseen and dangerous dilemma. Tyson, a resident of Williamston,
couldn't reach the Carolina Radiation Medicine Cancer Treatment
Center, for the treatment that could prolong his life.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who has lung cancer, was one of ten patients isolated by
severely flooded roads. ``We didn't know what would happen ... what
to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Gordon Koltis found a way.
</P>
<P>
   After calling various health officials and emergency personnel,
Koltis arranged for a military helicopter to pick up the patients
and fly them from a site near Wellcome Middle School to one near
the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were grateful to be able to get our patients in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koltis assured the somewhat hesitant cancer victims _ some frail
after weeks of treatment_ that they would not be alone on the
unusual trek.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off the chopper, the doctor held an oxygen tank in one
arm and Tyson with the other. ``He helped me on the helicopter.
Helped me off ... was with me the whole time,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army National Guard flew three of the flights and the U.S.
Marines charted another.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning that Tyson had been one of the few and the proud
in World War II, the soldiers respectfully saluted the former
Marine corporal. ``It felt good, like the old days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stories of generosity and kindness overflowed throughout eastern
North Carolina _ with the same intensity and power as the water
that destroyed so many lives.
</P>
<P>
   Local businesses joined the cascade.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery stores donated thousands of gallons of water and loaves
of bread to flood victims in Greenville, Rocky Mount, Goldsboro,
Wilson and Kinston.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown merchants in the town of Farmville, population 4,300,
offered discounts on home furnishing for those donating food and
several home improvement warehouses delivered cleanup supplies,
including brooms, mops and bleach, to stores throughout the
devastated areas.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstores held canned food drives, feed stores took care of
stranded animals and radio stations raised thousands of dollars for
relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the altruism of local communities, compassion
poured in from out of town. A stream of help came from other
states, nearby cities and dozens of rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   A group of farmers from Fairfield and Engelhard in North
Carolina's Hyde County set up shop in a Greenville parking lot with
1,400 pounds of meat, 50 gallons of potatoes and 40 gallons of
string beans and served every last morsel.
</P>
<P>
   The religious community also became a source of great solace for
thousands _ and not just for the soul. Churches of all
denominations organized food drives, set up shelters, rescued
migrant workers, and collected desperately needed supplies such as
diapers and baby formula.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers at Memorial Baptist Church in Greenville served more
than 61,000 hot meals last week in conjunction with the American
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Retired middle school teacher Natalie Brackenhoff was there
every day _ working diligently, helping as many as possible. Her
heart stopped for a moment, however, when a familiar face appeared
in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It was a former student and her family of seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lost everything,'' she said. ``That's the first time it
really hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
