A8627 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX     09-28 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chance of a lifetime will have to wait
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI, Fla. _ There's a pair of khaki shorts drooping from the
closet doorknob in my friend Jeanne's guestroom, its cargo-style
pockets filled with a hand-held tape recorder, a passport, twenty
bucks, and a clean handkerchief.
</P>
<P>
   Draped over a nearby stack of baskets is a well-worn white
shirt, its pockets stuffed with mechanical pencils, notepads,
sunglasses, and a day's dose of Dramamine. The clothes and I were
scheduled for a dawn departure aboard a friend's DC-3 bound for
Marsh Harbour in the Abaco islands, carrying much needed supplies
to that area of the Bahamas hard hit by Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   By late yesterday afternoon the venerable WW2 cargo plane waited
patiently on the ramp of a local airport, her airworthiness
certificate proudly displayed in the cockpit. Cargo doors were
flung wide, and a few windows propped open in an almost futile
attempt to beat the oppressive south Florida heat.
</P>
<P>
   Pickups brimming with donations from stores and churches backed
to her side and began offloading their life-sustaining cargo _
cases of bottled water and crates of food. Bags of disposable
diapers, clothing, and linens were shoved behind the ten generators
that had been loaded earlier, bound for Man of War Cay.
</P>
<P>
   Our truckload was filled with supplies Jeanne had cadged from a
local supermarket. The rest were bags of linens from her own
closets. She'd weighed each crate by stepping onto the bathroom
scales with it and subtracting her weight. Seven hundred pounds
she'd tallied. I watched as the pilot added this latest load to the
weights he was calculating on the side of an oatmeal box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much,'' he said shaking his head. ``We've got to drop a
couple of thousand pounds. How much do you weigh?'' He was talking
to me. I fumbled and fudged a bit knowing that an undeclared 10
pounds wasn't going to keep our tail wheel glued to the tarmac. I
wanted to mention that I'd just joined a gym and today's estimate
would soon be a reality. I didn't. A long time ago I learned that
girls aren't supposed to say dumb things to guys who lean against
airplane wings and discuss weights and balance.
</P>
<P>
   The adventure I was preparing for was a life-long dream come
true. It was the payoff for all of those '40s movies I'd sat
through _ the ones where Alan Ladd and William Bendix risked their
lives flying DC-3s into Saigon and Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
   It had begun when Jeanne's husband, a retired airline pilot,
regaled us over dinner Saturday evening with the story of a buddy
of his who owns a DC-3 and had been flying supplies to the islands.
He'd flown co-pilot with him that very morning, delivering a
planeload of generators, diapers, baby food, and other things folks
in the Abacos had been doing without since Floyd hit.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed as he described his takeoff roll _ a side to side
waggle down the runway in an attempt to see around the nose. And
how on landing he had, through force of habit, tried to plant a
non-existent nosewheel onto the runway only to be reminded by the
pilot that the third wheel was on the tail and he might ought to be
thinking of a way to get it on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Then he asked me if I wanted to go along on Tuesday's run. The
offer was no more out of his mouth than I had the first line of my
story written: ``Tuesday morning, about sun-up. I'm strapped into
the back end of an airplane almost as old as I am bound for....''
</P>
<P>
   That was Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night Tropical Storm Harvey blew across south Florida
from the Gulf of Mexico and aimed for the Abacos. It was packing
sustained winds of 50 miles an hour and gusting. The mission was
scrubbed and rescheduled for the next day, but I had an airline
ticket out. Time to head north.
</P>
<P>
   We took off about the same time on Wednesday morning _ my
friends and I. Trouble is, I was strapped into the wrong airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431. E-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
