r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN29-COX     09-28 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He'd leave education up to marketplace and the Lord
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When I hear Marshall Fritz talk about public
schools, I remember an old Cold War T-shirt slogan: ``Kill 'em all.
Let God sort 'em out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fritz believes public schools to be the Great Satan, or at least
Satan's conduit. As such, he wants them abolished. He's formed the
Separation of School and State Alliance and speaks widely.
Everywhere he goes, he asks people to sign a yellow card pledging
support for these words: ``We must end government involvement in
education funding, attendance and content.''
</P>
<P>
   He passed out his cards to an evening audience at Baylor
University last week. One didn't see a lot of obeisant scribbling
of signatures, in part because two Baylor professors provided a
spirited counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz blasts public education as raw socialism ``that destroys
both morality and education.''
</P>
<P>
   One quick impression of Fritz is that his spiel emanates more
from a quest for true government-established religion than a
government-butt-out libertarianism. He seems to pine for the good
old days of buckled shoes and witch trials.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court standing in the way of said backward leap,
Fritz and his organization call for a great exodus. The alliance
lists at least two Republican congressmen, Texas' Ron Paul and
Colorado's Tom Tancredo, as supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz and his organization are opposed to any public money at
all going to education _ including school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   What the alliance wants is a nothing less than a government
pull-out, with the resulting savings going back to the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz says that the abolition of public schools would result in
a $300 billion tax cut spread across the land, and with the
resulting savings in property taxes, families far and wide could
afford to place their children in a private school of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   That's possibly true, except when it comes to the poorest
Americans _ those who own no property and would have no discernible
savings to reap from this tax windfall. Fritz acknowledges that the
families of some 15 million children would be left without such
options.
</P>
<P>
   For those families, said Fritz, scholarships would bloom like
cactus flowers. ``All'' it would take, he said, is $15 billion to
$30 billion in private scholarship money.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``all,'' folks.
</P>
<P>
   To the assertion that his answer to dreaded socialism is social
Darwinism, with the resulting loss of quality education
opportunities for millions, Fritz responds, ``Utopia isn't one of
our choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Utopia, as I read it, is a quality education for every child. It
must be a satanic quest for government to attempt that.
</P>
<P>
   In rebutting Fritz, Mark Bateman, associate dean of the Baylor
School of Education, didn't get around fully to pointing out the
extent to which public schools have become a whipping boy for all
of society's problems, but he did point out to the audience the
danger to society of everyone retreating into their corners of
race, religion and social insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Bateman wondered aloud to what extent Fritz pines for a return
to spiritual morality at the cost of a new segregation and social
separatism.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Davis of the Baylor Institute of Church-State Studies
called public schools the ``staple of our democracy,'' with the
``vast majority fit as a fiddle.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wondered, if public schools are to blame for moral rot,
why ``every poll shows that 94 percent to 95 percent of Americans
believe in God.''
</P>
<P>
   Fritz believes that ``godless schools'' are the worst possible
environment. Any alternative is a better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave them home to watch 'Laverne and Shirley' reruns. They're
safer,'' he urges.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow cards, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(AT)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
