<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8631 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SHARKS29-COX     09-28 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARKS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jaws no more? Overfishing imperils sharks
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OFF THE GEORGIA COAST _ Brunswick business executive Dave Parks
sat on the rail of the 25-foot boat, anchored at the edge of St.
Andrews Sound, hacking up bait fish and throwing the bloody chunks
overboard.
</P>
<P>
   As Parks worked to attract sharks with the chum slick, charter
boat captain Mark Noble and his other customer, developer Frank
Deloach III, both of St. Simons Island, baited lines and cast them
into the olive swells.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sparkling late-summer day on a wild stretch of coast. A
bald eagle perched on silvered driftwood against an endless green
backdrop of salt marsh. Big tarpon rolled near the boat. Pods of
dolphin cruised past.
</P>
<P>
   St. Andrews Sound, between Jekyll Island and Little Cumberland
Island, is home to some of the Eastern Seaboard's biggest sharks:
huge hammerheads, tigers, bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Noble, 38, who holds two state shark fishing records, knows how
to boat the big ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll catch sharks today,'' he promised.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scene reminiscent of ``Jaws,'' the mid-1970s hit film
about a giant, man-eating great white shark. But if Quinn were
angling for Jaws in Georgia today, he'd probably be attacked _ not
by the monster shark but by sport fishermen trying to save the
creature's life.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal shark populations have declined so drastically in recent
years that recreational fishermen are practicing strict shark
conservation measures unheard of only a few decades ago. Although
new state and federal laws have given sharks more protection, many
recreational fishermen, conservationists and scientists are calling
for even stricter controls.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic shark populations, including large species that cruise
the Georgia coast, are down about 75 percent compared to just 25
years ago, said Dr. Bob Hueter, director of the Center for Shark
Research at the Mote Marine Laboratory in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large coastal shark species are all severely overfished,''
Hueter said. ``For some species, it's even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Noble's customers catch thousands of sharks each year but return
almost all to the sea unharmed, he said. ``Last year, we kept
probably six or eight blacktips to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   When Deloach reeled in a small bonnethead, Noble called
attention to the shark's swollen belly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a mature female, full of pups,'' he said, unhooking
the shark and letting it swim away. ``We don't want to take these
fish under any circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Noble admits his own attitude about shark fishing has changed
radically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, people caught trophy sharks to mount the
jaws. I did it myself,'' he said. ``Some people still like to catch
big sharks, but I won't offer charters for that at all any more.
Now, we try to do what's best for the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Greg Smith, 39, who operates Ducky II Charter Boat
Services Inc. on St. Simons Island, said he refuses charters from
customers who want to keep the sharks they catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My three boats haven't kept any sharks, big or small, for the
past four years,'' Smith said. ``Sharks have got enough problems
without me and my kind killing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say recreational fishing, which spiked in popularity
after ``Jaws,'' contributed to local declines in certain shark
species. But the boom in commercial shark fishing that began during
the mid-1980s is to blame for the overall population drop, most
agree.
</P>
<P>
   During the late 1970s and early 1980s, the National Marine
Fisheries Service encouraged commercial shark fishing, said Rebecca
Lent, who heads the agency's Highly Migratory Species Management
Division in Silver Springs, Md. Lent's division manages fisheries
along the Atlantic seaboard, in the Gulf of Mexico, and in the
Caribbean, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, shark was an underutilized species,'' Lent said.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial boats quickly moved into United States territorial
waters, landing millions of tons of sharks every year. Asian
customers began demanding shark fins, popular in soups, increasing
pressure on the emerging fishery. Worldwide consumption of shark
meat soared.
</P>
<P>
   In just a few years, overharvesting had left several Atlantic
shark species threatened or in danger of regional extinction,
according to the California-based Pelagic Shark Research
Foundation, a nonprofit organization that promotes shark
conservation and education worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   While sharks as a species have survived for millions of years,
they mature and reproduce slowly, making them especially vulnerable
to modern fishing methods, such as long lines and drift gill nets,
foundation researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   The Fisheries Service enacted laws in 1993 banning shark fin
fishing _ removing the fin and throwing back the carcass _ and
regulating other recreational and commercial catches, Lent said.
States, including Georgia, followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlantic shark populations failed to rebound, the service
cut commercial quotas in half in 1997 and curtailed them even more
in 1998, according to Lent.
</P>
<P>
   But a final plan to regulate commercial shark fishing, scheduled
to take effect this July, was overturned in a court suit, she said,
allowing commercial boats to return to more liberal 1997 limits. At
the same time, stricter recreational shark fishing laws did go into
effect. In most cases, they limit fishermen in federal waters to
one shark per boat per trip; state law allows two sharks per day.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the 1999 regulations for commercial boats were wiped
out by that judge in Florida,'' she said. ``It's sad that they only
apply now to recreational fishermen.''
</P>
<P>
   Charter captains like Noble and Smith say it makes no sense to
clamp down on recreational fishermen while allowing commercial
boats to continue catching sharks by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   They are especially critical of commercial drift gill netters
from other states who fish off the Georgia coast. Lent said only
about a dozen such boats operate between North Carolina and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Drift gill nets, horizontal lengths of mesh that float just
below the surface, are designed to entangle fish. Although laws
require commercial fishermen to release protected species, experts
claim most sharks die before they can be released.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he sympathizes with commercial fishermen who could
lose their livelihood if drift gill nets are banned. But he claims
they should be. ``They're an absolute horror,'' Smith said.
``They're as bad as condominiums on the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   A closer look: Sharks off the Georgia coast
</P>
<P>
   http://www.graysreef.nos.noaa.gov/tw/sharks.html
</P>
<P>
   www.graysreef.nos.noaa.gov/tw/sharks.html
</P>
<P>
   Jingle Davis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
