<HEADER>
A8643 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWMEXICO-DEADDAY29-C     09-28 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWMEXICO-DEADDAY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In New Mexico, a day to honor one's lost loved ones
 &HT;    By Sally D. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESILLA, N.M. _ Day of the Dead, my sister said, is a New Mexico
cultural experience I must not miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``People build little altars for dead relatives and friends with
their loved ones' favorite foods and other special things. They
dress up as skeletons and eat bread shaped like skulls.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought it sounded weird. My sister, Derrickson Moore, a
writer for the Las Cruces Sun News, got the arty, oddball genes in
our family. ``It's interesting and it's different. It's touching.
You'll like it,'' she said. ``I'm making an altar to remember Mom.
Come out and help me celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   So I arrived the last week in October 1998, when the annual Dia
de los Muertos activities were revving up. In Mesilla, a quaint
restored adobe village on the outskirts of Las Cruces, art exhibits
and altar-making workshops go on all month, with the big
celebrations Oct. 31 and Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   My sister had made an altar honoring ``Las Mujeres
Maravillosas,'' the Wonderful Women: Artist Georgia O'Keeffe,
Oregon psychic Tenny Hale and our mom, Doris Van Vleck Derrickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring some pictures of Mom,'' my sister said, ``and anyone
else you'd like to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   I added a favorite photo of my old dog, Satchmo, to the display,
which we set up at the plaza in the morning. We included marigolds,
the favorite Dia de los Muertos flower, and a mallard duck, symbol
of mom's love of the great outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   We put out a loaf of skull bread, complete with black olive
eyes, green pepper eyebrows and a red chile smile. Very tasty. We
saved another loaf to eat.
</P>
<P>
   My sister loaned me her black T-shirt with a smiling skeleton in
dangly earrings. Then we strolled around the plaza, meeting the
people and getting to know their dead relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Silva used a trash bin lid, marked Silva Sanitation, to
show photos and symbols of his father's life with the family
garbage collection business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's my dad when he was young, and here he is drinking
tequila with some cousins.'' Silva said. ``This little truck loaded
with cotton is for my grandfather's cotton farms.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffin-builder Lloyd Gibson displayed pine boxes, showing how
you can buy now and use your coffin as a couch, a coffee table or a
wardrobe until later. The prices were reasonable _ just $450 for
the Boothill Box, which included an epitaph: ``Think of this/As you
pass by:/That as you are/So once was I./And as I am/Someday you'll
be./Think on this./Remember me.''
</P>
<P>
   Store windows displayed cheerful skeletons in cute outfits.
Frank Sinatra got a big display at one shop, complete with a fifth
of Jack Daniels and a pack of smokes.
</P>
<P>
   Carolene de Mesilla remembered her late husband in the front
window of her Southwestern designer dress shop. ``It's funny,'' she
said. ``You fall in love all over again when you realize what you
had and what you lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives of Mesillero Ramon, a popular violinist,
had prepared a full meal of his favorite food and arranged the
tortillas, rice and refried beans on a TV tray, along with a bottle
of Metamucil.
</P>
<P>
   At dusk, fiesta-goers were called to attention by Gigante, a
model of an 8-foot-tall cowboy covered by a flowered cloth with
framework for a man to stand inside. Gigante led a candlelight
parade through the streets of Old Mesilla to the town cemetery.
There we all paused for a moment to remember our loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   A memory of Mom when she visited me in Connecticut 30 years ago
came to me. I lived in a beach house in Milford, and my daughter
Brandy was a year old. Mom and I took my dog Satchmo down to the
beach one day for a walk.
</P>
<P>
   We watched his running, dancing, prancing pursuit of the
seagulls soaring over Long Island Sound. ``He's the most beautiful
picture of utter freedom I've ever seen,'' Mom said.
</P>
<P>
   We found a bouquet of flowers beside Mom's pictures when we went
to pack up our altar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow,'' my sister said, ``Dia de los Muertos takes the
sting out of death and makes it more what it is: A part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally D. Swartz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
