<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's time to get real about retirement
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of us expect, or at least hope, that we can retire before
we reach age 65.
</P>
<P>
   Recent research, however, strongly suggests that many of the
hopefuls are talking through their hats. They haven't invested very
much, nor have they tried to estimate what income they will have or
will need. Many know little about their pensions, if they have
them. A large percentage think they will be eligible for full
Social Security benefits long before they actually will.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that the unprepared will serve a life
sentence in the salt mines. It does mean they are in for some
brain-shaker surprises if they don't start working on the problem
before they get much older.
</P>
<P>
   The chart (EDS: BELOW) shows just how important personal savings
are to elderly Americans right now _ on average, 21 percent of
their spending nd grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears certain that future retirees will be prosperous
only if they start birthing a very large nest egg.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas G. Hesse, a certified financial planner in Roswell, has
been designing retirement plans for more than 20 years. Here are
the high points of his suggestions on the moves workers need to
make now:
</P>
<P>
   _ Find out whether your aspirations are for real.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to write down your current circumstances and your
investment plans, estimate how much growth you can expect and
calculate how long that money will last if you retire at a given
age.
</P>
<P>
   ``My clients say this is the most valuable thing I've given
them,'' Hesse said. ``They know they could retire, or that they
couldn't retire as things now stand.'' Sometimes the conclusion is
that the client can retire but not any time soon. Other
alternatives might be to save more or invest more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a rough idea for free, using calculators supplied on
the Internet by mutual fund families. You can find a good one at
www.troweprice.com. Commercial software packages, like Microsoft
Money 2000, have more sophisticated versions that can be expected
to give a more reliable estimate.
</P>
<P>
   You can also hire a financial adviser to guide you through the
process. The price for this one-shot consultation could be about
$500, though some certified financial planners would do it for
less. Hesse recommends the expert, whom you would expect to be more
realistic about things like your investment prowess and your
post-retirement spending plans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check out the traditional resources.
</P>
<P>
   Your company's human resources department can give you an
estimate of how much your pension will be. ``You would be amazed
how few people know,'' Hesse said. ``Once you find out, it gives
you peace of mind. You quit fooling yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good idea to get a projection of your Social
Security benefits. The Social Security Administration will soon
start sending out annual reports to all eligible workers. If you
want one, call 1-800-772-1213.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put the maximum into tax-deferred retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   For most workers, that means individual retirement accounts and
401(k) plans. Other plans are available for the self-employed and
workers at small companies.
</P>
<P>
   These plans postpone income tax bills on the money you make from
your investments until you retire and take the money out. Often you
can deduct your contribution from the year's taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure your investments are diversified.
</P>
<P>
   If you intend to keep portions of your investments in bonds or
money markets, glorious gains in the stock market may have skewed
your allocations.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Hesse said, workers should beware of having too
much of their holdings in the stock of the company they work for.
That can happen if your employer matches 401(k) contributions with
company stock.
</P>
<P>
   Hesse has other suggestions, and most workers could think up
some for themselves. Whatever actions you to take, the point is to
get started now if you want to get happy later.
</P>
<P>
   SAVINGS IS IMPORTANT
</P>
<P>
   Elderly Americans report that investment income provides one
dollar in five of their income _ second only to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security 40.9%
</P>
<P>
   Savings 21.0%
</P>
<P>
   Pensions 18.7%
</P>
<P>
   Earnings 16.6%
</P>
<P>
   Other 2.8%
</P>
<P>
   Note: Data include persons over 65, some of whom are still
working.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Employee Benefit Research Institute
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
