<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8650 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NUTS-AND-BOLTS29-COX     09-28 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTS-AND-BOLTS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NUTS &AMP; BOLTS: Experienced do-it-yourselfers can replace medicine
cabinets
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ I don't have a medicine cabinet anymore, and I
don't miss it much.
</P>
<P>
   The house I moved into in May has a large mirror, mounted
directly to the wall above the bathroom sink, and a drawer under a
countertop where we keep razor blades, dental floss and daily
hair-care stuff. The medicines we use regularly, such as aspirin
and antacid, have moved to a shelf over the kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   The trend through the 1970s and '80s was bigger and bigger
medicine chests with coordinated light bars. Big medicine cabinets
were matched with nice vanities under the bathroom sink in most new
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Now dainty pedestal sinks are the rage, and they look better
with smaller medicine cabinets or wall-mounted mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever style you prefer, replacing a medicine cabinet is a
job an experienced do-it-yourselfer can handle.
</P>
<P>
   Medicine cabinets come in two styles: those that are attached
directly to the surface of the wall and those that are recessed
with a portion of the cabinet pushed behind the surface of the wall
between wall studs.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing a recessed cabinet with another recessed cabinet of
the same size should be fairly easy, but we all know the words
``should be fairly easy'' are the kiss of death for any home
project.
</P>
<P>
   Remove any movable shelves and look for screws through the side
walls or back of the cabinet. If the cabinet has a built-in light
fixture, cut the power to the circuit from the breaker panel or
fuse box.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the screws holding the cabinet in place and carefully
disconnect any electrical wires. Slide the old cabinet out.
</P>
<P>
   Put the new cabinet in place and see if it fits snugly in the
opening left by the old cabinet. If the opening is a little too
large, you can usually get it to fit by adding wood shims. Masking
tape can hold the shims in place while you experiment with
different shim positions until you get a good fit.
</P>
<P>
   Connect the wires to the light on your new cabinet, if it has a
light, and use screws through the side or back to hold it in place.
</P>
<P>
   You can replace a small recessed cabinet with a larger one if
your bathroom has wallboard (assuming you know how to work with
wallboard). Widening a hole in a plaster wall is probably a job for
a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the old cabinet and determine where the new cabinet will
be positioned. Find the studs behind the wall on either side of
where you want the cabinet and mark a line on the wall over the
center of both studs. Draw another line horizontally a few inches
below the bottom of where you want the cabinet to go.
</P>
<P>
   Use a circular saw with the blade depth set to match the
thickness of the wallboard. Cut along the horizontal line and along
the vertical lines from the bottom cut to the ceiling. Remove the
old wallboard.
</P>
<P>
   Using a reciprocating saw, remove sections of the wall studs
that are in the way of the new cabinet. The removed sections should
be about 3 1/2 inches longer than the height of the medicine
cabinet; cuts should line up with one another.
</P>
<P>
   Cut two lengths of stud lumber to fit between the studs on
either side of the medicine cabinet. Nail one length of lumber on
top of the studs you cut behind the wall; this will be the sill
plate on which your cabinet will rest. Nail the other board to the
bottom of the cut studs; this is your header plate.
</P>
<P>
   Cut two more lengths of stud lumber to fit between the header
plate and sill plate. Nail these into position to support the sides
of your new cabinet. These are called jack studs.
</P>
<P>
   Install a new piece of wallboard with a hole matching the hole
needed for the cabinet. Slide the cabinet in and fasten it with
screws to the jack studs.
</P>
<P>
   It's usually easier to install a medicine cabinet to the wall
surface instead of recessed. But a surface-mounted cabinet extends
further from the wall and has a bulkier look.
</P>
<P>
   Home-improvement stores tend to feature surface-mounted cabinets
because they are an easier product for do-it-yourselfers to handle.
Cabinets range from $20 for a simple metal and plastic affair to
$600 for a massive hardwood cabinet with matching light bar.
</P>
<P>
   To remove an existing surface-mounted cabinet, simply remove the
screws through the back of the cabinet and disconnect the
electrical wires.
</P>
<P>
   Locate the studs and draw lines on the wall down the centers of
the studs where the new cabinet will go.
</P>
<P>
   Most surface-mounted cabinets have a thicker area near the top
of their back wall; this is the hanger strip that will support most
of the weight of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   With an assistant holding the new cabinet in place, drill guide
holes through the hanger strip into the studs behind the wall. If
screws aren't included with the cabinet, the instructions should
tell you what size screws are needed to hold it securely.
</P>
<P>
   Drive screws through the hanger strip to hold the cabinet in
place. Additional screws through the back of the cabinet lower
along the studs will help hold the cabinet steady.
</P>
<P>
   Mirrors are installed in similar fashion. The back of the mirror
should have a bracket designed to be fastened to studs behind the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Find and mark the studs; attach the brackets; hang the mirror
from the brackets.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: Jamescummings(AT)coxohio.com; or write to the Features
Department, Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton, Ohio
45402.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
