<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, September 29, 1999 are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-SCHOOLS _ Schoolyard threats are being taken more
seriously, but is expelling kids the answer? (Atlanta
Constitution). 9.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ President Bill Clinton has dropped out as next
year's Jefferson Lecturer on the Humanities, selected by the
National Endowment for the Humanities. Academia went quite bananas
at the prospect of Clinton taking a lectern occupied in the past by
historian Barbara Tuchman, poet Gwendolyn Brooks, novelist Robert
Penn Warren and other intellectual swanks. (Teepen, Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Soliciting for tips has become a cottage
industry and, to me, ranks high in the bad taste bracket.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ MIAMI, Fla. _ The adventure I was preparing for
was a life-long dream come true. It was the payoff for all of those
'40s movies I'd sat through. I was scheduled for a dawn departure
aboard a friend's DC-3 bound for Marsh Harbour in the Abaco
islands, carrying much needed supplies to that area of the Bahamas
hard hit by Hurricane Floyd. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ When I hear Marshall Fritz talk
about public schools, I remember an old Cold War T-shirt slogan:
``Kill 'em all. Let God sort 'em out.'' Fritz believes public
schools to be the Great Satan, or at least Satan's conduit. As
such, he wants them abolished. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
