<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0928 _ While other manufacturers are applying the
ax to their small sporty coupes, Mitsubishi has turned to the
stylist's pen and computer to create an all-new Eclipse for the
2000 model year. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 4-column color photo of Mitsubishi Eclipse and a 18-pica
color photo of the car's interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 2000 Mitsubishi Eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   THE MECHANIC _ In the good old days, customizing a car for
performance or appearance was common, but the rules have changed
with the emergence of computerized engines and transaxles used in
front-wheel-drive vehicles. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
Includes 1-column color photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ A warning about the dangers of flood-damaged
cars in the wake of Hurricane Floyd. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 17. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VOLVOS-REVIEW _ Reviews of the Volvo S and V40. (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ A lot of us expect, or at least hope, that we can
retire before we reach age 65. Recent research, however, strongly
suggests that many of the hopefuls are talking through their hats.
They haven't invested very much, nor have they tried to estimate
what income they will have or will need. Many know little about
their pensions, if they have them. A large percentage think they
will be eligible for full Social Security benefits long before they
actually will. That does not mean that the unprepared will serve a
life sentence in the salt mines. It does mean they are in for some
brain-shaker surprises if they don't start working on the problem
before they get much older.Personal finance advice. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NEWMEXICO-DEADDAY _ MESILLA, N.M. _ Day of the Dead, my sister
said, is a New Mexico cultural experience I must not miss. ``People
build little altars for dead relatives and friends with their loved
ones' favorite foods and other special things. They dress up as
skeletons and eat bread shaped like skulls.'' I thought it sounded
weird. My sister got the arty, oddball genes in our family. ``It's
interesting and it's different. It's touching. You'll like it,''
she said. ``I'm making an altar to remember Mom. Come out and help
me celebrate.'' So I arrived the last week in October 1998, when
the annual Dia de los Muertos activities were revving up. (Swartz,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STROKE-MEDICATION _ Tissue plasminogen activator (TPA) has been
minimizing stroke damage by dissolving blood clots since 1996, but
it's still not widely known that people can spare themselves a
lifetime disability by hustling to the hospital when stroke
symptoms first appear. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-MILAN _ MILAN _ A. Scott Walton reports from Fashion
Week in Milan. Combo of main runway revue, notes and occasional
postcards. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-RATINGS _ Brief review/analysis of first week of network
ratings for new season. So far, big winners were as expected -
``Once and Again,'' ``Freaks and Geeks,'' ``Special Victims Unit,''
``Third Watch,'' ``The West Wing'', etc. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A gardening column by Lee May. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HOME-PICTURES _ If there's one rule when it comes to framing and
displaying art in the home, it's this: There are none. Pictures
should be framed and displayed to their best advantage while at the
same time complementing a home's decor. ``For every rule, there's
an un-rule,'' says the framer for Elton John, who by the way, will
display 200 of his 2,000 photos next year at the High Museum in
Atlanta. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
