<HEADER>
A8658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     09-28 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READ A BANNED BOOK, GIVE ONE TO YOUR CHILD TO READ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A home without a library lacks diversity of voices, opinions and
world views. When you read a book, you enter another person's
perspective. And because a reader can put the book down and think
about what the author has said, a good reader enters a dialogue
with the author or the characters created by the author. One can
reread passages and linger over thoughts or ideas or savor the
deliciousness of the language.
</P>
<P>
   Television, even at its best, lacks diversity; lacks the ability
for a viewer to carry on an inner dialogue with the speakers or the
author of the program. Books encourage thinking. A reader must
create images from the words the author has supplied, must imagine
the events described, must track the plot or the logic of the
writer and must visualize the main characters in the mind's eye.
</P>
<P>
   The book is in your hands. You can return to passages if there
is something you don't understand. You can argue with the author in
your head; you can nod in agreement. You learn, unconsciously, the
way words can fit together _ sometimes so well that they seem
inevitable and irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   The book is in your hands and so, too, is the right to read.
There are many in our nation who would restrict this right.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 1,001 adults conducted in March for the First
Amendment Center in Nashville, Tenn., indicates that the free
speech and free press rights guaranteed by the Constitution are in
jeopardy. More than half of the survey respondents believe the
press has too much freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The press includes book publishers as well as newspapers. And
nearly one-third believe the First Amendment goes too far in the
rights it guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   The American Library Association set aside the week of Sept. 25
to Oct. 2 as Banned Book Week to remind us how precious this right
to read and the right to express our thoughts are to our society.
</P>
<P>
   Reading stimulates the mind to grow, to comprehend, to adapt, to
change attitudes, to question. Studies have shown copycat behavior
that can be blamed upon a book is rare, indeed, and can only come
from the most brutish level of reading. To read, the mind must be
active _ it translates words into emotions, into doubts, into a
walk alongside the author as a friendly companion who has his or
her own thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   My brother, sister and I grew up surrounded by my father's
library. My father was a military man with over 30-years service.
He was politically conservative, but socially progressive; and read
eclectically, favoring historical fiction as well as thoughtful
novels and actual histories.
</P>
<P>
   When I, as a young boy, asked him if I could read one of the
books in his library, his advice to me was: ``If you think you can
understand it or want to, then it's yours to read.'' That was good
advice then. It is now.
</P>
<P>
   The first book I read from my father's library was Erskine
Caldwell's ``God's Little Acre,'' and then Caldwell's ``Tobacco
Road.'' Both had been banned somewhere in the United States during
those years. John Steinbeck's ``Of Mice and Men'' graced my
father's library shelves. I read it, too, while I was still in
junior high. ``Of Mice and Men'' continues to be one of the most
challenged and banned books in America _ and considered one of the
most beloved books by those who have actually read it.
</P>
<P>
   Only years later did I realize that a significant number of
those books my father allowed me to read before I had graduated
from high school had been banned in various states and educational
institutions: Thomas Wolfe's ``Of Time and the River,'' Aldous
Huxley's ``Brave New World,'' George Orwell's ``1984,'' Bram
Stoker's ``Dracula,'' Sinclair Lewis' ``Elmer Gantry,'' Mark
Twain's ``The Adventures of Tom Sawyer'' and ``The Adventures of
Huckleberry Finn,'' Sir Arthur Conan Doyle's ``The Adventures of
Sherlock Holmes,'' Ernest Hemingway's ``A Farewell to Arms'' and
``The Sun Also Rises,'' Walter Van Tilburg Clark's ``The Ox-Bow
Incident,'' Charles Dicken's ``Oliver Twist'' and Theodore
Dreiser's ``An American Tragedy.'' I tried to read all of Edward
Gibbon's ``The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman
Empire,`` but it was too tough for me at that stage of my life.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to think that any one educated in the United
States has not read most of these books and grown with the
readings.
</P>
<P>
   I read my first William Faulkner novel from my father's library,
``A Fable,'' and it began a lifelong love affair with Faulkner's
novels and his writing style _ more importantly, for me, it began
my own love affair with language. ``A Fable,'' an allegorical novel
about World War I, won the Pulitzer Prize. It wasn't banned, but
two of Faulkner's greatest works were _ ``As I Lay Dying'' and
``The Wild Palms.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the publisher Modern Library released a list it
entitled the ``100 Best Novels of the 20th Century.'' Nearly
one-third of those novels were banned at one time or another. Six
of the top 10 on the Modern Library list were threatened or removed
from bookstores, libraries and schools.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good time to celebrate our constitutional right to
read by reading a banned book. Give your child your favorite banned
book to read. Tell your child why you would miss the book that some
would ban forever. Visit your public library and check out a banned
book. It will be good for you.
</P>
<P>
   (Charles Levendosky was recently reelected to the Freedom to
Read Foundation Board, the litigating arm of the American Library
Association.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
