<HEADER>
A8688 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-BUTLER-CASSIE-HELLFIR     09-28 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-CASSIE-HELLFIRE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CASSIE' BOOK AND THE HELLFIRE HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This week, ``She Said Yes: The Unlikely Martyrdom of Cassie
Bernall'' landed on the Amazon.com ``hot books'' list. Written by
Cassie's mother, Misty, the book recounts the faith of one of the
teenagers killed in the Columbine High School massacre in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, before killing her, Eric Harris asked,
``Do you believe in God?'' Cassie responded, ``Yes.'' As he pulled
the trigger, he further tormented: ``Why?'' She could not answer.
She lay dying from a bullet in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Since the shooting, Cassie has become something of a teen idol
for conservative Christians. Cassie martyr-mania has created web
sites, T-shirts, buttons, pins and videosall fuelling a teen
revival.
</P>
<P>
   Television evangelists recount the story as a modern morality
tale. One intones solemnly, ``Satan wants to steal an entire
generation, but Cassie stood up for God. Will you?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the new sawdust trail,replete with hellfire and
brimstone. Old-time religion told through the tragedy of a blond
teenager wearing Doc Martens.
</P>
<P>
   But ``She Said Yes'' is no revival sermon as Misty Bernall
corrects the hellfire hype. In these pages, Cassie is no martyr.
She is a troubled teen who, with her parents' help, goes
straightonly to be killed shortly thereafter by a more troubled
classmate.
</P>
<P>
   Even after becoming a Christian, she struggled with feelings of
depression, hating her parents, desires for love and sexual
passion, and doubts about God. When the moment of death came,
however, she faced it with courage. She said ``Yes'' to ultimate
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the martyr narratives that shaped early Christianity,
Cassie is not endued with supernatural insight or given miraculous
visions. Nor are her parents. She is just a kid. And they are
confused parents.
</P>
<P>
   Therein is the book's power. This is not a martyr's tale. It is
a mourner's meditation-- a mother's story of the death of a
belovedand normalteeenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cassie is my daughter,'' writes Misty Bernall protectively.
``You can't turn her into Joan of Arc.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``She Said Yes,'' no one looks particularly heroic. Cassie is
deeply flawed. Her parents resort to extreme measures-- spying,
cutting off her friendships, forcing her into a Christian school
--to save their daughter. They realize the painful irony of
Cassie's life-- had they not redirected their daughter, she would
still be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, through much of the narrative, the grief-stricken Misty
Bernall tries to justify her own parental choices.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dr. Laura and Pat Robertson forward their own narrow
agendas by using Cassie, the spirituality of her story is not that
of the religious right. Instead, Cassie's story reflects a
tradition different from that of American evangelicalism --that of
Anabaptist theology and piety. ``She Said Yes'' is published by
Plough, an Anabaptist publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans confuse Anabaptists with more generic Baptists.
Anabaptists are the heirs of the 500-year-old tradition of the
peace churches,the Mennonites being the largest. Theologically,
Anabaptists emphasize discipleship and quiet faith. Their piety
runs counter to the more extroverted ``accept Jesus and get born
again'' ethos of much American Protestantism.
</P>
<P>
   ``She Said Yes'' is about discipleship,another term for the
spiritual journey of saying yes to God. Cassie's yes was not a
once-for-all. She had to keep saying it amid her troubles: Yes,
yes, and yes. These yes's transformedbut not did not perfecther
character. She was a girl in the process of becoming a better
person through saying yes.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother criticizes ``accept Jesus'' piety. She worries about
``hellfire and brimstone'' Christians. She questioned her
daughter's faith commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Misty Bernall rarely uses the exclusive ``Christ'' language of
evangelical piety. Instead, she opts to tell her readers of
Cassie's faith in ``God.'' The book is riddled with doubts -- a
pious taboo among evangelicals but an important aspect of mature
faith.
</P>
<P>
   With this counterpoint to evangelical piety, the Bernalls point
toward a vision of faith not often seen in American culture. For
them, life is an uneasy journey of commitment to God, a life of
quiet, consistent and insistent ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   However quietly said, ``yes'' is a powerful word. Sadly,
Cassie's journey ended with an unexpectedly dramatic ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   But her faith was not ``turn-or-burn.'' Rather, it was a
pilgrimage of saying yes in love: a mother's love for her daughter,
a girl's love for God, and a teenager learning to love herself. And
it is the pain of a saying yes even when a journey ends too soon.
That is a witness for all of usnot matter what our faith tradition
may be.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
