<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Sept. 29. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's Melanie Gray at (816) 234-4778.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BBQ-KANSAS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Ardie Davis has been
hitting the barbecue sauce pretty hard.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is he has probably drunk a swimming pool's worth of the
stuff over the years yet still always manages to keep enough sauce
on hand to fill up a good-sized bath tub.
</P>
<P>
   While working on The Great BBQ Sauce Book (Ten Speed Press,
$15.95), Davis was on a first-name basis with the UPS driver who
dropped off ``hundreds'' of long-neck bottles, funky flasks, clunky
moonshine jugs and mayonnaise jars containing the condiment on the
doorstep of his Roeland Park, Kan., home. 1150 words. By JILL
WENDHOLT SILVA. Story will move in the ``l'' category.
</P>
<P>
   CD-9INCH-KANSAS (undated) _ It's been five years since Nine Inch
Nails' ``The Downward Spiral'' established its mastermind, Trent
Reznor, as the poster boy for malicious electronic rock.
</P>
<P>
   That album's death-disco hit, ``Closer,'' with its unprintable
catch phrase and creepy video, was a remarkably dark point in the
already gloomy grunge scene, and it made a star out of its creator.
</P>
<P>
   Reznor finally has re-emerged with his third album, ``The
Fragile,'' a double disc that explores many of the same emotional
depths as its predecessors, but with a more refined sense of
modulation and restraint. It's a quixotic, challenging work that
cements Reznor's reputation for sound and fury, yet also gives
voice to a softer, more nuanced side of NIN. 500 words. By DEREK
DONOVAN. Story will move in the ``e'' category.
</P>
<P>
   TV-TOOYOUNG-KANSAS (Pacific Palisades, Calif.) _ It's another
pristine day at Jacqueline Kennedy High School in Southern
California, just a mile up the hill from Pacific Coast Highway. Out
on the large, oval-shaped quad, kids are tossing a football, eating
at the outdoor cafeteria, looking out from a second-story railing
toward the ocean. Here, 20-something actors pretend to be teens for
a show that a bunch of 40-something TV executives hope will draw an
audience of 12- to 34-year-olds. That's show business!
</P>
<P>
   There are eight new shows that fit that exact MO. Add in the
ones that reverse the premise _ shows about 20-somethings that
teen-agers will want to watch _ and you're easily talking a third,
if not one-half, of the new kids on the TV block. 950 words. By
AARON BARNHART. Story will move in the ``e'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
