<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-GATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN GATE BRIDGE AD IGNITES DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE CONSTANTINOU  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Texas company is offering $560,000 to pay the
tolls on the Golden Gate Bridge for a day and hang an advertising
banner on the approach to the landmark.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal by carOrder.com of Austin has turned sour in
the city on the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The company, an Internet automobile broker, wrote a letter to
Golden Gate Bridge District General Manager Celia Kupersmith asking
if the it could hang the advertising banner on the tollbooth
leading to the bridge, which is on eastern side of the Bay in Marin
County.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the bridge agency rejects commercial ventures, but
these are not normal times, said Mary Currie, the bridge district
spokeswoman. The general manager had just returned from Washington,
D.C., she said, and it didn't look as if the bridge was going to
get much federal help with the $171 million that is needed for a
$297 million project to make the span safer in earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She saw it as a significant amount of money that she just
didn't want to walk away from,'' Currie said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the bridge district and the Texas company were
negotiating. As part of their advertising gimmick, the Texas folks
wanted to pay everyone's $3 toll and have the banner read that it
was the company's treat.
</P>
<P>
   Reimbursing the bridge district for the lost tolls would cost
the company about $160,000. Then, there would be an additional
$400,000 for the privilege of bragging in a banner about paying the
tolls.
</P>
<P>
   The banner would hang at the toll plaza _ not the towers or
under the bridge span _ where another banner now advertises the
Larkspur ferry. The banner size would be about 20 feet long and 3
feet high.
</P>
<P>
   To San Francisco Supervisor Barbara Kaufman, the proposal was
like found money. Heck, why stop at just one day? How about Banner
Day once a month?
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'll pay, why not others?'' said Kaufman, who is a board
member of the Golden Gate Bridge District.
</P>
<P>
   But to fellow supervisor and bridge director Michael Yaki, the
banner idea on the beloved icon is sacrilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes are walking billboards. Every stadium is subject to
corporate sponsorship,'' Yaki said. ``Once you go down that path
... why not have General Electric sponsor the torch on the Statue
of Liberty ... or hang a sign on the mayor's balcony: `AT&AMP;T
Welcomes You to City Hall'?''
</P>
<P>
   To Yaki, any amount of money the bridge district could raise by
permitting a banner would not be enough to pay for what they feel
would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you've done is sold the bridge,'' he said. ``Why even put
a price tag on integrity, on dignity, on something that represents
California and the United States?''
</P>
<P>
   But Kaufman thinks that all this melodrama is hogwash. ``It's
not on the bridge, it's on the toll booth,'' she said. ``To say
we're desecrating the bridge is nonsense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
