<HEADER>
A8736 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SKIN-SPOTS-HNS &LR;      09-28 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-SPOTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIN DISORDER COMMON AMONG BLACKS FRUSTRATES DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The first white spots appeared on her 7-year-old
daughter's back and knee. Although they were no bigger than
quarters, Jodie Glass was worried.
</P>
<P>
   She had seen those same kinds of spots on her best friend, who
suffers from a genetic skin disorder known as vitiligo. A doctor
confirmed Glass' suspicion in July, when the white spots had spread
to her daughter's stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know, from growing up with my best friend, what it's
going to be like for her,'' said Glass, an mother of two who lives
in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Between 2 million and 4 million Americans suffer from vitiligo,
a condition in which the skin's pigmentation cells are destroyed
and no longer able to produce the melanin that normally gives the
body its color.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a patchwork of white spots that can, in severe
cases, cover the entire body, including the face and hands.
</P>
<P>
   Although vitiligo can affect people of any race or gender, it's
most noticeable and disfiguring in people of color. ``The big myth
about this disease is that it's an African-American problem,'' said
Shannon Ruesewald, director of the National Vitiligo Foundation in
Tyler, Texas. ``I think many people see the condition and don't
know what it's called or they say, `It's the Michael Jackson
disease.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the pop icon, is reported to have undergone a bleaching
treatment to even out his skin color after his natural pigment was
destroyed by the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   And while destroying the remaining pigment cells is one approach
to dealing with the disease, Glass is frustrated by the fact that
vitiligo is still an incurable disease with no known cause or good
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   While some people opt to bleach their skin, others may try to
add pigment, either with makeup or dye. Yet most insurance
companies don't cover the cost of those treatments, calling them
either experimental or cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much we can do,'' said Glass, a secretary at the
New York state Department of Health. ``Her stomach and back are
about 50 percent covered. Jessica has it behind her knees, her neck
and it's starting around her cheeks. I can't think about it without
crying.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure what triggers vitiligo but about half the people
who develop the condition show some sign of pigment loss before the
age of 20.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers believe vitiligo may be caused by a combination of
factors related to the body's genes, the immune and nervous
systems.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Vitiligo Foundation, many people
report pigment loss after a severe sunburn. Others relate the onset
of vitiligo to emotional trauma stemming from an accident, death in
the family or divorce. For others, the disease appears for no
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in my family that we know has it,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   Vitiligo doesn't usually indicate any serious medical problems,
although it has been linked to certain autoimmune conditions
associated with thyroid and adrenal gland function.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest issue is that in areas where you don't have any
pigment, you're going to sunburn and if you sunburn, you're going
to increase your risk for skin cancer,'' said Dr. Mitchell Singer,
a dermatologist in Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   Other than counseling patients on the appropriate use of
sunscreens, Singer says physicians unfortunately don't have much to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   The mainstay of treatment for vitiligo patients is a combination
of drug therapy and ultraviolet light to encourage repigmentation.
</P>
<P>
   A year's worth of treatment, however, can cost up to $6,000,
requires weekly visits to the doctor and offers only mixed results,
Singer said. ``Most people have to live with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Glass has found out with her daughter, the emotional impact
of vitiligo is especially difficult in a culture that places such
an emphasis on beauty and appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a 7-year-old to tell you, `Why do I have to be ugly?' What
can you say?'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   While the disorder sometimes goes away and the skin repigments
on its own, most people aren't so fortunate. Glass is pushing for
more research to find a cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a prayer and a medical breakthrough, Jessica just might
be able to beat this disease,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information on the disease, contact the National
Vitiligo Foundation in Tyler, Texas, 903-531-0074.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
