<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8754 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-PRAYING-FOR-CELEBRITI     09-28 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYING-FOR-CELEBRITIES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK URGES: CHANGE THE WORLD BY PRAYING FOR THE FAMOUS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Color photo of the cover of ``Praying For .... Influential
People'' is available electronically, as are black-and-white photos
of the authors.)
 &HT;    
 By Cheryl Heckler-Feltz
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A quiet couple from Oregon is rising on the charts of the
evangelical publishing world, gaining remarkable success in the
highly competitive market for devotional prayer books.
 &HT;    At the same time they have created a unique bridge between
conservative Christians and mainliners on the often divisive
subjects of prayer and scripture.
 &HT;    David and Heather Kopp are authors of the best-selling ``Praying
the Bible'' series, which Waterbrook began releasing two years ago.
The titles include ``Praying The Bible For Your Life'' ... ``For
Your Children'' ... ``For Your Marriage'' ... ``For Your Baby.''
Soon to come: ``Praying The Bible For Your Teen-ager.''
 &HT;    Praying scripture was common to ancient Israel. It was common to
early Christians. It is a concept that has defined monastic
communities for literally centuries. Monks gather daily -- starting
in pre-dawn hours -- to chant the Psalms or sing the Magnificat or
recite the creation story, all as forms of prayers.
 &HT;    The Kopps took this concept and created books that focus on an
individual's spiritual journey, relationships and family life.
 &HT;    For instance, ``Praying The Bible For Your Life'' includes 130
prayers based on bible passages from Genesis to Revelations.
 &HT;    In ``Praying The Bible For Your Marriage,'' prayers address
everything from minor spats to sexual intimacy and put heavy
emphasis on unity of spirit. ``When the winds of trouble howl,
seeking to enter through cracks in the plaster, our hearts will be
secure, and we will have no fear (Psalm 112:8). Even on stormy
days, peace will dwell within our walls (Psalm 122:7).''
 &HT;    The series is a best-seller in ``the crossover market'' of both
evangelical conservatives and mainline Christians.
 &HT;    The Kopps' newest project is as unique as their ``Praying The
Bible'' series.
 &HT;    Just released by Harvest House Publishers, ``Praying For The
World's 365 Most Influential People'' reads like an evangelical
People Magazine and has a goal of literally changing the world.
 &HT;    The devotional book admonishes Christians to join efforts every
single day next year to pray for celebrities.
 &HT;    From Leonardo DiCaprio, Lauryn Hill and Will Smith to Pope John
II, the Clintons, the Dalai Lama and even Fidel Castro, the list of
names reflects the biblical mandate to pray ``for everyone -- for
kings and those in authority.
 &HT;    As the Kopps see it, this extends also to the famous -- and
infamous.
 &HT;    From the despicable Saddam Hussein to the bizarre Marilyn
Manson, the book urges readers to cross the tidy boundaries that
often define evangelical Christianity and pray for people they'd
rather ignore -- or even curse.
 &HT;    ``Christians for the most part, write (devotions) for other
Christians, and too often there is an 'us against them' mentality
regarding society,'' Heather Kopp said. ``The power of prayer and
the need for prayer -- these are things every person of faith can
agree on.''
 &HT;    Michael Jordan, Steven Spielberg, Jim Carrey and Chris Rock join
Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire on the roster of celebrities.
 &HT;    The Kopps also included Ellen Johnson, president of American
Atheists, and went so far as to ask her for an endorsement.
 &HT;    ``I thought it'd be great if she said something like, 'You can
pray for me, but hey-- no one's listening,''' David Kopp said. ``A
little opposition is good for a prayer movement.''
 &HT;    According to David, Johnson declined to endorse the book but did
ask him directly if she was an adversary in the text.
 &HT;    ``I assured her that readers were not going to pray against her
but for God's best for her and her life,'' he said.
 &HT;    For David Kopp, the experience of praying the Bible began in
infancy. He was born in Zambia, to missionary parents, and his
father had a serious speech impediment.
 &HT;    ``He found that Bible memorization helped him overcome his
handicap,'' Kopp said. ``His prayers and his everyday conversations
were always filled with scripture. I can hear his voice when I read
my Bible.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Cheryl Heckler-Feltz
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Cheryl Heckler-Feltz writes about religion in American
culture.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
