   BRAD-PROFILE-COX
</P>
<P>
   BRAD-PROFILE-COX _ CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ Thirty-five miles south
of where it joins the Missouri River, the Mississippi churns past a
tiny spit of dirt known as Hug Farm. The river narrows here, and
the current moves swiftly, a chocolate ribbon that carves through
flat farmlands and rushes past steeply rising limestone bluffs. As
the setting sun turned the scene here to shadows earlier this
month, two touring buses rumbled to a halt and deposited Bill
Bradley and about 50 members of the press. It was the final stop on
the ``Bill Bradley for President'' home tour, a 60-minute field
trip intended to acquaint the media with Bradley's small-town
roots. With reporters scribbling notes and photographers snapping
away, Bradley explained how as a teenager he would run from Crystal
City High School to the river's edge and, standing alone, inhale
the silence. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
