<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAD-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quiet, steady Bradley rolls like the river
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ Thirty-five miles south of where it joins
the Missouri River, the Mississippi churns past a tiny spit of dirt
known as Hug Farm. The river narrows here, and the current moves
swiftly, a chocolate ribbon that carves through flat farmlands and
rushes past steeply rising limestone bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   As the setting sun turned the scene here to shadows earlier this
month, two touring buses rumbled to a halt and deposited Bill
Bradley and about 50 members of the press. It was the final stop on
the ``Bill Bradley for President'' home tour, a 60-minute field
trip intended to acquaint the media with Bradley's small-town
roots.
</P>
<P>
   With reporters scribbling notes and photographers snapping away,
Bradley explained how as a teenager he would run from Crystal City
High School to the river's edge and, standing alone, inhale the
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all of you to see the river the way I see the river,''
said Bradley, who bought Hug Farm in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But seeing the river, it turned out, wasn't all that Bradley
wanted. What attracted him to this place then and now was not the
sight of the river, but the feel of it. The quiet. The stillness.
The solitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a world where there is news on the hour and there is a lot
of instant gratification, this place, this river and those bluffs
were for me a sense of permanence,'' he told the media gaggle.
``Even with this crowd, you get a sense of the solitude.''
</P>
<P>
   On one level, Bradley's river tour was scripted political
theater, portraying a contemplative man bound by birth to one of
the most potent symbols of American greatness, the mighty
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   But the vignette also revealed much about a figure who has lived
life in the public eye since the age of 14, from his basketball
glory days in Crystal City to the 16-hour days he now campaigns for
president.
</P>
<P>
   The essential truth about Bradley is that he is pulled most
strongly to the interiors of life. Introspective and at times
reserved, he covets isolation the way President Clinton craves the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to be private in order to replenish,'' says Ernestine
Schlant, a college professor _ and Emory University graduate _ whom
Bradley married in 1974. ``He almost has to go back within himself
... and then he can go out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten months ago, Bradley entered the public spotlight once again
by becoming the only Democrat willing _ some said foolish enough _
to challenge Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1808 has a candidate successfully defeated a sitting
vice president for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, however, Bradley has obeyed an inner clock.
In 1978, he bucked the New Jersey Democratic Party by running
against the leadership's candidate in a bid for the Senate. His
only work experience was 10 years with the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Many urged him to run for president in 1988 when, four years
after a landslide re-election, he was at the peak of his
popularity. But he said he wasn't ready. He passed again in 1992,
listening to what he called an inner voice that told him the timing
was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Months after Bradley decided against a 1992 bid, his wife was
diagnosed with breast cancer. He drove her to every treatment
session. The inner voice was right.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after briefly flirting with the idea of challenging
Clinton, possibly as an independent, Bradley instead retired from
the Senate, expressing profound disillusionment with politics and
the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's back, few question his timing anymore. Tapping
into unhappiness with the Clinton administration scandals, Bradley
is finding support among Democrats who believe Gore is too tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Next to Texas Gov. George W. Bush's sudden, early dominance,
Bradley's methodically executed campaign against Gore has so far
been the biggest surprise of the 2000 sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   With aggressive fund-raising and a message wrapped around the
American Dream, Bradley has proved that he can compete with Gore.
But there's a nagging question: Is a man who treasures solitude
ready to perform the world's most public role?
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Nelson practically tackled Bradley at a Democratic Party
barbecue near Ames, Iowa, this month. Thrusting out a copy of
Bradley's autobiography, ``Time Present, Time Past,'' Nelson said,
``I have never, ever voted for a Democrat. I am this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's encounters with voters frequently begin with an
autograph. Sometimes it is one of his books; more often it is a
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The signings hark back to Bradley's days as a basketball star
with the New York Knicks, when he helped win two NBA championships,
but they are also a testament to his continuing mystique.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation of American men, the Princeton graduate and
Rhodes scholar was proof that brains and athletic skill weren't
mutually exclusive. Consciously or unconsciously, Bradley has also
cultivated an image of integrity and independence both in
basketball and in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Rivers Blackmon, a diversity specialist from St. Louis
who met Bradley at a learning center for black children, said she
first read about him in college in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that he can be introspective,'' she said. ``A
lot of politicians seem to support the system instead of what is
right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-5, Bradley towers more than most. And while he can be
professorial at times, he rarely seems to strike voters as aloof.
He succeeds, perhaps, because he talks about people, not ideology.
He tells a story about a woman he met who had no health insurance,
and another about a schoolteacher whose fourth-grade students had
no breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Such anecdotes, even if third-hand (the schoolteacher story came
from Minnesota Democrat Sen. Paul Wellstone), connect with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the one kind of president who will really care
about people,'' said Melvin Lust, a county road worker in Newton,
Iowa. ``He's the kind of man I think we could sit down and visit
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlant, a native of Germany who teaches comparative literature
at Montclair State University in Upper Montclair, N.J., likes to
introduce her husband as the ``perfect blend'' of his schoolteacher
mother and banker father.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is indeed a product of both, but his parents'
personalities produced perhaps more tension than harmony in their
only child.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's father was a Republican in a town of Democrats, a man
who believed you made your own way in life. Warren Bradley suffered
from arthritis in his back, a condition that prevented him from
driving or even tying his own shoes.
</P>
<P>
   For all Bradley's athletic prowess, he never played any sports
with his father.
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy man who took his family to Florida in the winter,
Bradley's father was also painfully reserved. At town gatherings,
he was likely to be on the periphery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked his privacy,'' recalled neighbor Red Bryant. ``Bill's
a chip off of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's mother, Susie, was the extrovert. She was a Cub Scout
den mother and a church session leader. She organized dancing
parties for Bill's friends and pushed her son to learn the French
horn. She didn't take ``no'' for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   At Bradley's high school basketball games, she yelled at
referees over bad calls. She attended all his games and marked down
every shot that he took. The next day, he would practice the shots
he missed.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Crystal City that Bradley began to seek out places to
be alone. In addition to the river, there was the jungle gym behind
the high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a couple of occasions I would just go up there at night and
just lie on that bar and look at the stars,'' says Bradley, who
turned 56 in July. ``I learned early what you need to preserve
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The span of Bradley's life has included a number of such
timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Princeton in 1965, where he was a
three-time All-American, Bradley turned down an offer from the
Knicks and instead went to Oxford, England, as a Rhodes scholar.
</P>
<P>
   The cloisters of Oxford took Bradley away from the fame he had
already established as an athlete and allowed him to indulge his
voracious curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as a Knick, Bradley would play with the team, but then go
off exploring by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the guys would go back to their rooms and sleep,''
recalls Dewey Schade, a friend whom Bradley visited in San Diego.
``Bill would go and meet people, take notes and talk to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Willis Reed, a Knick teammate, remembers Bradley as a team
player who avoided the limelight and showed little emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really appreciated his privacy,'' says Reed. ``We basically
didn't know what he did off season.''
</P>
<P>
   Between seasons, Bradley traveled abroad, indulging his need to
wander and be on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like he has to satisfy his father's part that is
in himself,'' says Schlant.
</P>
<P>
   During 18 years in the Senate, Bradley established himself as a
thoughtful, hard-working senator and something of a loner.
</P>
<P>
   He developed an expertise in taxes, water management and world
monetary policy, displaying both liberal and conservative bents.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was one of the strongest supporters of the earned income
tax credit for the working poor, but he also voted for many of the
Reagan budget cuts of the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He had a strong pro-labor voting record, but was one of the
leading champions of the North American Free Trade Agreement, a
position that the nation's manufacturing unions vigorously oppose.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, he helped President Reagan pass the 1986 tax bill,
which cut rates dramatically but made up the revenue by eliminating
tax loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   He also supported aid to the Nicaraguan Contras and founded an
exchange program for U.S. and Russian students.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is at once laid-back and at the same time one of the most
disciplined and structured people I've ever known,'' says former
Louisiana Sen. J. Bennett Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley developed a few close friendships in Congress, across
the political spectrum. Wellstone, perhaps the Senate's most
liberal member, admired Bradley's ``intellectual integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the gold standard,'' says Republican Jack Kemp, a former
congressman, Cabinet member and vice presidential candidate. ``I
would consider him among the finest public servants I've ever
known.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone connected with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him to be insensitive to the needs of people who live
in small towns and rural areas,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin (D-Iowa),
who is supporting Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley angered some Democrats when he quit the Senate in
1996 and blamed the party for contributing to public cynicism about
American politics.
</P>
<P>
   In his last term, Bradley's only child, Theresa Anne, moved from
New Jersey to live with her father in Washington and attend private
school. Bradley and Schlant agreed that one of them would be home
every night to have dinner with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget any social evenings,'' he said. ``I did my job and went
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his Senate career, Bradley grew increasingly
critical of the influence of special interests in Congress and
advocated campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he has always been an skillful fund-raiser. He
raised millions from the special interests that he condemned,
gathering a staggering $12 million for his 1990 re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley says that no one ever influenced him with money. Yet he
aggressively defended the New Jersey-based pharmaceuticals
industry, which gave him thousands in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly fought efforts to kill a tax break for U.S.
businesses in Puerto Rico, even though it was the type of tax
loophole he decried. Half the companies benefiting were
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also fought caps on prescription drug price increases
that drug companies opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is also not above the occasional flip-flop. In the
Senate, he fought ethanol subsidies as a taxpayer giveaway. Now,
running for president in Iowa, where the corn-based fuel additive
is a sacred cow, Bradley is in favor of the subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   With the earnestness of an Eagle Scout (which he was), Bradley
defends his votes in the name of some higher good. Protecting the
tax break in Puerto Rico, he says, was about preserving Puerto
Rican jobs. Voting against ethanol was saving New Jersey taxpayers
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of protecting your state's interest, I would try to
do that from time to time,'' Bradley says.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley left the Senate in 1996 sounding as though he might
never return to politics. Describing his reasons for quitting,
Bradley said in 1995 that he had become ``disgusted with the
politics of both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked for CBS News doing weekend commentaries, taught at
Stanford University and the University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, he phoned Dan Okimoto, his Princeton
roommate. Okimoto had spoken to him before about the White House.
This time, Okimoto said, he detected a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He realized that he felt ready and hungry,'' said Okimoto.
``That was always one of the questions I had, which was, Did he
really want the presidency, or was he conflicted about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley insists he's ready for the challenge, as long as he can
run on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in sequential careers,'' he jokes. ``When I'm 80,
I'm going to learn how to play the piano. When I'm 82, I'm going to
open up a piano bar. There is always something out there that you
can enjoy doing. That kind of thought has kind of kept me moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
