<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-MAO-0929-COX     09-28 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MAO-0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAO MYTH RESURFACES ON EVE OF CHINA'S 50TH BIRTHDAY CELEBRATION
 &HT;    500&AMP;ADDS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With CHINA-STATS-0929.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The myth of Chairman Mao is making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   With China transfixed by weeklong celebrations of the 50th
anniversary of Communist Party rule on Friday(Oct. 1), the face on
the movie poster outside the Chinese capital's biggest downtown
theater isn't Leonardo DiCaprio. Last year's heartthrob has been
replaced by a movie poster of a young and virile Mao Tse-tung.
</P>
<P>
   Mao's face will also get prime play in the next few days when
the People's Bank of China releases China's first new series of
banknotes in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gone will be the three old revolutionary comrades who used to
flank Mao on back of the 100-Yuan (US$12) banknote. From now on
Mao's picture will appear alone _ the first time a Chinese banknote
has depicted a single political figure since the People's Republic
of China proclaimed itself as a nation on October 1, 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every night, prime-time Chinese state television shows
yet another two-hour installment of a documentary on the
achievements of the communist state that emerged in 1949 after
Chairman Mao's guerrilla legions expelled the remnants of
Nationalist generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek's beaten armies to the
island of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   At least 55 hours of official documentaries have aired in the
last month. While Communist Party film-makers acknowledge that Mao
committed ``errors'' through his excessive zeal for communism, they
have given Mao more propaganda credit than he has gotten in a
decade for having built China into a powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that Mao jackets are back in fashion, or that
China is reverting to Marxism. Today's Chinese leaders are grasping
for symbols to inspire this country's 1.3 billion Chinese to keep
on striving into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering unemployment, angered by official corruption and
finding little solace in outmoded Marxist ideology, the Party
realizes that hundreds of millions of Chinese are looking for
something to believe in.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, Mao's reputation seemed caught in a terminal
tailspin among the official Communist Party historians.
</P>
<P>
   Year-by-year in the mid-1990s, Mao's name was mentioned less
often by the state-run Xinhua news agency. There were even a few
suggestions in China's controlled press that Mao's corpse should be
removed from its marble mausoleum in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   But now in the run-up to the 50th anniversary, some Beijing
intellectuals are dismayed that the Party's message on Mao seems to
have reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that the authorities in the current government are
trying to re-emphasize the role played by Mao Tse-tung,'' said
economic consultant Mao Yushi, chairman of the non-governmental
Unirule Institute of Economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask intellectuals, I believe more than 90 percent hold
a view very strong against Mao Tse-tung,'' said the consultant Mao
(no relation to the late Chairman). ``But if you ask the average
worker or rural people, I would say 50 percent or more still
respect Mao as a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   As the 50th anniversary approaches, China's party historians are
churning out new tomes of official history that not only recite
Mao's achievements but also lay out the latest approved versions of
where ``The Great Helmsman'' went wrong. Some of it is hard-hitting
stuff, compared with the more benign image of Mao conveyed in
official television documentaries
</P>
<P>
   and other mass media.
</P>
<P>
   One two-volume historical opus, marked for the attention of
communist party cadres, turned up this month in a bookstore open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   Authored by a party committee at the Learned Institute on the
History of the People's Republic of China, the book accused Mao of
having started the ``chaos'' of the 1966-76 Great Proletarian
Cultural Revolution through ``incorrect understanding'' of China's
political situation.
</P>
<P>
   Another new officially sanctioned book blames Mao's
``over-enthusiasm'' for causing the tragic 1958 ``Great Leap
Forward,'' a rural industrialization scheme that ultimately started
a famine which killed an estimated 30 million people. Mao's role in
causing the famine was not mentioned, nor was the toll of the food
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   One way to gauge how Mao rates these days in party propaganda is
to visit a grandiose exhibit now underway in the Beijing Exhibition
Center. Organized by a consortium of Chinese ministries, provincial
governments, the military and the Communist Party, the show is
entitled ``Glorious Course _ Exhibition of Achievements of the 50th
Anniversary of the People's Republic of China.''
</P>
<P>
   An unofficial count puts the number of photos of Mao in the
exhibit at 102, compared to only 68 for the late leader Deng
Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
   Only one Chinese leader commands as much space in the 50-year
``Glorious Course'' exhibit as Mao. That is incumbent President
Jiang Zemin, whose exploits during his relatively colorless decade
as Communist Party chief are recorded in 106 photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Mao is shown as transcending the movie poster-version of the
virile Chinese guerrilla fighter thrashing bourgeois reactionaries
and knocking the foreign devils on their ears. As depicted by the
``Glorious Course'' exhibit, Mao is also a nation-builder, a
delight for awe-struck Chinese children, a spearhead of Chinese
education, an inspiration for rocket scientists and a creator of
steel mills.
</P>
<P>
   Mao hasn't built China all on his own, of course. As the
exhibit's designers explained in a press conference, ``Glorious
Course'' is designed to let people cherish the memory of China's
accomplishments under ``three generations of collective
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Mao and his ``proletarian revolutionaries'' came first and got
China started on a path toward rapid economic growth. Following
Mao's death in 1976 at the age of 83, China was led by a ``second
generation'' under Deng that turned China on a course toward
prosperity through market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Following Mao and Deng, the exhibit gives the party's formal
imprimatur to the emergence of a new and equally important ``third
generation'' of collective leadership, this one headed by President
Jiang Zemin. Although Jiang achieved full power only after Deng's
death in 1997, now he is being put forward as a historical figure
of supreme importance.
</P>
<P>
   The job of Jiang's generation is to ``compose more glorious
historical pages of the basic realization of socialist
modernization by the middle of the next century,'' says Wang
Chunzheng, one of the chiefs of the ``leading team'' that assembled
the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
