<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Sept. 29. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   RAIL: A Jackson County jury today will hear arguments for
punitive damages, following Monday's $40 million award to Sedalia
woman seriously injured at a dangerous rail crossing near
Warrensburg. Union Pacific Railroad and Amtrak were the defendants.
Eleven months before the accident, the state found the view at the
crossing was 90 percent obstructed with no lights or gates and
trains racing by at 70 mph. Story also will address the complicated
way railroads and government address crossings and will get
industry reaction to any punitive verdict. Joe Lambe and Matt
Campbell. 25.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE: The American Royal's first event starts Wednesday with a
100-mile ride retracing some of the Pony Express trial. About six
riders will go from St. Joe to Leavenworth Wednesday and end at the
American Royal on Thursday. Lee Hill Kavanaugh. 15. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   SEAL. After more than 120 years, the official seal of the
University of Kansas is drawing objections from the ACLU. The seal,
designed in the 1870s, depicts Moses kneeling before the burning
bush. The ACLU thinks this might be a governmental endorsement of
religion in violation of the U.S. Constitution. Diane Carroll. 25.
</P>
<P>
   CDROM. Kansas lawmakers are betting $150,000 that an interactive
computer game that allows seventh- and eighth-graders to play the
role of a state senator or representative will help students learn
about Kansas history and how the Legislature works. Jim Sullinger.
22.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLE _ Missouri Gaming Commission monthly numbers &AMP; charts.
Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER _ Jerry Heaster's column.
</P>
