<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S ART CRITICISM IS ON THE MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I don't know about you, but I have problems
accepting as an art critic a guy who prances across my television
screen on ``Saturday Night Live'' wearing a Marilyn Monroe wig,
high heels, lipstick, fake eyelashes and falsies.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani (the man who once
dressed in drag for ``SNL'') seems to have a point here. The issue
is an exhibition planned for the Brooklyn Museum of Art. This show
has been in the works for months, but the mayor's two
representatives on the museum board apparently failed to alert him
before he blew a gasket last week over its content.
</P>
<P>
   It's an exhibit entitled ``Sensation: Young British Artists from
the Saatchi Collection.'' That's precisely what it has become _ a
sensation _ largely because of one piece.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a work by the London artist Chris Ofili called ``The
Holy Virgin Mary.'' I've seen only a small, printed, color image of
it, but it looks like no other representation of the Virgin Mary
that I've seen.
</P>
<P>
   The work's most disturbing components are about 120 photos of
bare female behinds and lacquered clumps of elephant manure
adorning the image. Whatever point the artist is trying to make
seems obscure, but he has a definite thing for elephant manure.
Some people use it for gardening; Ofili uses it for most of his
works of, ahem, art.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibit attracted a surging mob of people when it went on
display in London two years ago. About 300,000 art lovers trekked
through it. It's partly funded by an art collector and businessman
named Charles Saatchi, who wants to use representations of these
works to decorate a new chain of restaurants called Sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is unimpressed with most of the other works in the
exhibit, which apparently consists largely of the sort of oddball,
avant-garde self-indulgences that pass for visual art in hopelessly
hip circles. But he's so openly furious over the ``Holy Virgin
Mary'' that he's threatening to withhold millions in city money
from the museum and to throw it out of the city-owned building it
occupies.
</P>
<P>
   This position has touched off the usual howl from extreme civil
libertarians who (1) despise Giuliani just on general principles
and (2) cling to the conviction that artists should enjoy
unfettered access to public funds even when their art deeply
offends the people who pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can seriously imagine the American Civil Liberties Union
arguing against mayoral outrage over artwork glorifying Nazi
principles or denigrating Jews, African-Americans, Latinos or gays.
If the mayor ranted about public funds going to display stuff that
trashed what are thought of as oppressed groups, my guess is that
the civil libertarians would sit mute.
</P>
<P>
   But art insulting to Christian believers, especially Catholics,
who hold a special reverence for the Virgin Mary? That's fine. A
strong strain of anti-Catholicism runs through the self-styled
intelligentsia. It's that abortion business, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   A vast difference exists between a public official with police
powers proclaiming that art can't be displayed privately and a
public official saying ``Not on public property with the tax
dollars entrusted to my care.'' The first is censorship. The second
might well be politics _ Giuliani is considering a run for the U.S.
Senate, after all _ but it also can be legitimate public policy.
The museum gets public money to present ``art for all.'' That's
what it proclaims on the banner across the building's face.
</P>
<P>
   From all reports, the ``Holy Virgin Mary'' is not an work you
would want to show the kiddies. And it would bring bitter, just
tears to the eyes of your sweet old Aunt Mary Ellen, the nun.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the First Amendment doesn't require public funding
to display art that directly diminishes anybody's religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is right on this one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
