<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8830 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-PEACEKEEPERS-ART-B     09-28 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-PEACEKEEPERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONS QUESTION UN'S PROPER ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary General Kofi Annan's plea last week
for the world to help bring peace to forgotten corners of Africa
appears headed for a test as early as Tuesday with a plan to send
6,000 peacekeepers to Sierra Leone, a place scarred by a new horror
of war, mass amputations.
</P>
<P>
   And looming ahead for the UN Security Council may be a second
test, a proposal to send an astoundingly large force of 15,000 to
20,000 troops to broker a shaky peace in the Democratic Republic of
Congo, which until recently was a battlefield in which nine
separate nations or rebel forces had squared off.
</P>
<P>
   The UN peacekeeping force now numbers 13,335 troops, and the two
plans proposed for the African nations could nearly triple the size
of the force.
</P>
<P>
   Debates on these two plans _ at the same time the UN is gearing
up to administer Kosovo and East Timor, as well as possible peace
efforts in Angola and along the Eritrea-Ethiopia border _ would
help determine the outcome of wars for years to come. It may signal
whether the United Nations will become a central mediator or a
ceremonial bystander. It could clarify whether the United States,
the world's sole superpower, might be stuck as its supercop as
well.
</P>
<P>
   And, the UN debate would give Africa a fresh answer about the
depth of the commitment of the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   After Annan's dramatic appeal, President Clinton called on
nations to take a ``shared responsibility'' to end warfare because,
he said, America could not intervene everywhere. But he kept the
door slightly ajar, saying no country should be ``indifferent to
the destruction of innocents in any part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's speech, which kicked off the 54th General Assembly, grew
out of broadly felt frustrations from around the world since the
1994 genocide in Rwanda that UN and US responses were far quicker
to white people's wars and far slower to battles involving people
of color. For weeks in 1994, the United States blocked UN action in
Rwanda, where more than a half-million people were slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary general envisioned a new world order that put the
UN Security Council as the chief arbiter of disputes; nations
assuming more of an international conscience rather than strictly
following their own strategic interests; and borders offering no
defense for states that commit atrocities against its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   He had barely finished speaking from the dais before others
began the debate. Some Western leaders applauded Annan. China,
Russia and some African leaders were sharply critical, saying it
smacked of colonialism and hegemony.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's speech raised more questions than answers: Who will pay?
Is the United Nations capable of dramatically expanding
peacekeeping operations? How long should the operations last?
Should peacekeepers be given liberal rules of self-defense? Should
future UN missions take on more tasks?
</P>
<P>
   ``The world doesn't change 180 degrees overnight,'' Edward
Mortimer, Annan's chief speechwriter, said in an interview. ``The
secretary general is trying to capture a direction for change. . .
. There has to be a degree of consistency about it. If you are
prepared to pull out all the stops in Kosovo and Haiti, and you do
nothing for people in Africa, it takes the edge off of the
moralistic gloss you are are putting on your actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The test on Africa also depends on African nations, of course.
No proposal for peacekeepers in the Congo, the former Zaire, will
go forward until all the nations involved in that war give security
guarantees. And no UN force will go into Angola or the
Eritrea-Ethiopia border until there is a declared peace.
</P>
<P>
   The nerve center for peacekeeping operations is tucked into the
southeastern corner of the 32rd floor at UN headquarters. There, in
the Situation Center, intelligence specialists track what may be
the world body's most dangerous assignments.
</P>
<P>
   They conduct live video conferences on split TV screens, talk on
secure phones tucked inside briefcases, and send and receive coded
cables in the 24-hour-a-day Duty Room. After the Kosovo war, for
instance, supervisors held almost daily discussions beamed onto
their TV sets, often from Geneva, Rome, and Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations sent its first peacekeeping force to
Jerusalem in June 1948 in the midst of the Arab-Israeli war. The
United Nations Truce Supervision Organization is still there,
although its mission is far different. Now it supports UN forces in
the Golan Heights and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In the 51 years since, the Security Council has authorized 49
peacekeeping operations, 36 of them in the last 11 years. Wearing
UN blue helmets or berets, usually only lightly armed for
self-defense, peacekeepers have become far more than just a wall
between combatants. Now they are police officers, civilian
administrations, and election observers, among other things. During
an upswing in activity in 1993, the missions included 70,000
peacekeepers, at a cost of $4 billion. Current operations cost
slightly under $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many successes, including 1988, when UN
peacekeeping operations were awarded the Nobel Peace Prize. But
recent failures also loom large, including missions to Somalia and
Bosnia in which scores of peacekeepers were killed or injured.
Critics say the Security Council failed to give those peacekeepers
adequate rules of engagement, or even funds.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is last year's UN retreat from Angola. Alex
Vines, who wrote a scathing review of UN operations in Angola for
Human Rights Watch, said UN observers lost credibility there
because they refused to apportion blame for past abuses. ``The core
problem really in Angola was a lack of political will. They didn't
want to rock the boat,'' said Vines in a telephone interview from
London. ``The UN was regarded with disdain there. It turned out to
be a paper tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest problem for future UN peacekeeping missions
isn't likely to be past critiques.
</P>
<P>
   Money's the trouble. Finding enough troops also could be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are going to have a UN capable of operating
globally with all the international conflicts that we will see in
the future,'' said Richard H. Shultz, a national security
specialist at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts
University. ``They don't have the resources and capability.''
</P>
<P>
   Shultz also said that the Clinton administration will be
reluctant to commit many resources to missions in Africa in part
because deployments in Bosnia and Kosovo are likely to last years
and cost billions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the president and you're going to contribute 5,000
troops to the Congo? I don't think so,'' Shultz said. ``This is
where Kofi Annan is going to have his problems.''
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, spokesman for the National Security Council, said
Africa remains a ``key priority'' for Clinton, but said the
president has not made any decisions about sending US peacekeepers
to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the US has 376 people on UN missions, ranking No. 14
in the world. Only five of them are soldiers; most are police
officers. The United States, the largest contributor to UN
peacekeeping, lags far behind in its contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, it has paid $50 million toward a $570
million assessment. That is part of US arrears to the United
Nations, which total more than $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to make a decision on future US deployment based on
our interests, capability, and our resources,'' Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer, Annan's speechwriter, said nations will closely watch
the US role in future missions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about US reluctance to commit troops, he said, ``We have
to be a bit careful. I'm sure no American would want to imply that
it doesn't matter a how many Africans or Yugoslavs . . . are
killed, as long as no American peacekeepers are killed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
