<SLUG> BC-WILDERNESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GUARDIAN OF THE ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There must be many interesting things about the
marbled murrelet and the spotted owl, but I don't give a hoot what
they are. Both have feathers. Both fly. Both may have descended
from dinosaurs. That's all I need to know.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the famous real estate in Northern California
that these little guys inhabit _ the 7,500-acre Headwaters Grove in
Humboldt County _ interests me a lot. And I am very glad Tom Reid
of Palo Alto helped to save it for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   You thought the Headwaters redwoods were saved by Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., who got their owner, the Pacific Lumber Co.,
to accept $480 million to sell the grove, to limit logging on about
200,000 additional acres and to agree to eventually sell other
stands of old-growth redwood.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was a bunch of people behind the scenes, including
Stanford-trained biologist Reid, a trekker in cyberspace who has
made a career of saving open space while sitting at his desk.
</P>
<P>
   A month or so after Feinstein and Pacific Lumber announced that
they had reached a deal _ albeit a very fragile one _ Pacific
Lumber expressed grave reservations, stopping the hearts of tree
huggers.
</P>
<P>
   Just as suddenly, however, the company dropped its objections,
bowing to the scientific arguments made by Reid and a handful of
government biologists. The drudges put the Headwaters over the top
by virtue of their unflagging advocacy of solid scientific facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the credibility of what I'm telling people that does my
job,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   For fees of up to $135 per hour, Reid, 51, and his 12-person
staff do something few others do. They quantify the components of
land deals involving potentially conflicting commercial and
environmental components, some of which would appear to be very
unquantifiable _ bird nesting sites, coho salmon, hydraulic flows,
butterflies and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Reid's clients typically are governmental agencies. In the
Headwaters deal, it was the state Resources Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Using computers and ``geographic information system'' software _
a sophisticated program originally developed for the oil and mining
industries _ Reid is able to take mountains of information and make
it all mesh.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the information is gathered by satellites, which today
are capable of counting the number of trees and determining their
heights in areas as small as 100 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   This means that it is now possible to play chess with different
pieces of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the conservation plans I've worked on,'' Reid said,
``break down to measuring the value of something, in dollars or
birds or acres of rare plants. If you can't measure the value of
what you're trying to maintain, you can't evaluate the
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Reid, the problem with the Headwaters was that
Feinstein and Pacific Lumber boss Charles Hurwitz had agreed to the
boundaries of the land under negotiation, then directed others to
work out the details within a limited time frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disrespect to Senator Feinstein,'' Reid said, ``but from a
practical point of view, that was impossible. It didn't take a
rocket scientist to know we weren't going to be able to do it in
the time frame allowed, but nobody was willing to acknowledge this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Headwaters was only 7,500 acres and Pacific Lumber owned
roughly 210,000 acres, so there was no deal _ nothing at all _ for
most of its property.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there was no progress because the agencies involved had no
way to know the extent of the resources under planning. They didn't
have a map and the Pacific Lumber Company saw no purpose in
providing one.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there was no movement, because there was no way to see what
was in between the two positions _ the government saying you can't
cut anything and Pacific Lumber saying we can cut everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid and his biologist colleagues in government broke through
the impasse, enabling a final deal to be reached in March, by
providing concrete information _ often in the form of computerized
maps _ both sides could readily accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't at the negotiating table,'' he told the New York
Times, ``but we helped build the table back in the shop so that
others could negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   John Muir, I'm sure, is smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
