<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOLE STORY IS WORTH STICKING TO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listeners tuned in to the golf chat Thursday on WBUR's ``The
Connection'' heard guest Bob Bubka offer this tidbit: ``There've
been four hole in ones in Ryder Cup history.'' For a golf innocent,
though, the hook was not the number but the plural: Shouldn't it be
holes in one? Or did Bubka, author of ``The Ryder Cup: Golf's
Greatest Event,'' know best?
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, we explored a similar question in this
space. Reader Mary Anne McQuillan objected to the plural
sticks-in-the-mud, and I agreed that as a ``headless'' compound _
neither a kind of stick nor a kind of mud _ the word should take
the plural stick-in-the-muds.
</P>
<P>
   This judgment didn't persuade everyone. David Chang of Newton,
in a thoughtful letter on the problems of plurals, noted that his
Random House Handbook calls for pluralizing the ``significant''
word in a compound. ``Who's to say that sticks are more significant
than mud?'' Chang asked.
</P>
<P>
   But that challenge misses the point: Stick-in-the-mud derives
from the verbal phrase to stick in the mud (or, in some obsolete
variants, in clay or briers or mire), not from the noun stick.
There is no stick in stick-in-the-mud, so it has put its -s at the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Reader David Tuggy argues for sticks-in-the-mud on different
grounds. As a connoisseur of odd combinations _ ``not my bag of
tea,'' for instance _ he's happy to let a word be read two ways, as
long as communication isn't hampered. The dual meaning even
enriches the language, he says, giving such words a
``three-dimensional beauty'' that prescriptive rigidity kills.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, for once, I'm in the conservative camp.
Stick-in-the-muds reflects the real meaning of the compound; if you
understand it, you'll no more say sticks-in-the-mud than you would
call lazy kids goofs-off or your ignorant cousins knows-nothing.
It's easy to see stick as a noun, since we don't often see the verb
in such constructions _ though you probably remember Elvis singing
``I'm gonna stick like glue.'' But if the compound had been adopted
with a different form of the verb _ stuck-in-the-mud, say _ no one
would pluralize it as stucks-in-the-mud.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, stick-in-the-muds is the official plural, when
dictionary makers think to give it. True, its original meaning may
vanish, or it may have to coexist with the new one, just as ``to
the manor born'' has an independent life even though it's not what
Shakespeare wrote. But to anyone attuned to the original meaning,
the variants sound wrong, for now.
</P>
<P>
   On the hole in one question, though, there's room to maneuver.
It could come from the verb to hole (to hole out, to hole in one);
but the holes had to be there (as the noun was) before the golfing
verb could be coined. So either derivation is plausible, and either
plural defensible.
</P>
<P>
   If you suspect that hole in one descends from he holed in one,
you're with Bob Bubka: Your plural is hole in ones. If you prefer
the noun ancestry, holes in one makes more sense, since holes is
the ``significant'' word. This is the form chosen by the new
edition of the Concise Oxford Dictionary (and by the Globe). But
other dictionaries don't list a plural, suggesting the default
option, hole in ones, is right.
</P>
<P>
   So when you're pluralizing on the links, have it your way. But
when it comes to stick-in-the-muds, I've got my story and I'm
sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write her at
The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
