<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NEEDS MORE THAN MINORITY ACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ A few years back, Asian-Americans were
excited that a new television comedy featured mostly Asian-American
actors. Called ``All American Girl,'' it starred Margaret Cho, who
began her show business career in San Francisco as a standup comic.
</P>
<P>
   The show lasted one season, and I wasn't sorry to see it
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Some Asian-American friends disagreed with me, saying it was
important to support a show that had Asian-American actors in lead
roles.
</P>
<P>
   I was indifferent to ``All American Girl'' mainly because it was
artistically fraudulent. Its actors may have had Asian features,
but the show's sensibilities were more Borscht Belt than Koreatown
(Cho being a Korean-American). That show reflected its creators,
who were white.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with the quick-fix now of inserting minority
faces to satisfy complaints by the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People and others.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't true diversity. True diversity would explore all
sorts of stories from America's rich mixture of ethnicities and
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   As the fall TV season began, a coalition of minority groups
called for viewers to stop watching the four major networks during
prime time hours for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   I'm usually sympathetic to such groups, but on this one, I'm not
listening. It's not that I don't believe in the goal _ to draw
attention to the fact that most prime time shows don't have
meaningful roles for minority actors. But a brief boycott won't
teach network executives any lasting lessons. Besides, the networks
are losing viewers to cable and other mass media anyway. Even
without a boycott, TV producers are scrambling like mad to add some
color to their casts at the last minute, primarily because the
NAACP (which isn't leading the boycott) has been complaining about
a lack of diversity in TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   The networks' too-little, too-late response is laughable and
insulting. If nothing else, this cultural contretemps shows that
the NAACP still wields clout with the white-run TV entertainment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Something is missing, however, from the public discussions about
the lack of diversity on TV. Boiled down, the issue seems to be one
of jobs _ which performers get the lead and supporting parts on
shows that can generate enormous wealth and fame for those
fortunate enough to be chosen. That's terrific for the men and
women who survive the famously backstabbing world of show business.
But is fame and fortune all there is for the few black, Latino and
Asian actors who perpetuate tokenism? In our celebrity worshipping
society, what else is there?
</P>
<P>
   We're talking TV here. TV is both an entertainment and a
commercial medium. On rare occasions, it can elevate our spirits
and well-being, but mostly it dulls our senses and reinforces
stereotypes _ sometimes with a few laughs.
</P>
<P>
   One reason I am not boycotting the new season is because TV
shows are temporary diversions from work and parenting
responsibilities. I like some TV dramas, even ones that don't have
minority actors. Sure, I'd like to see more shows with greater
casting diversity, especially Asian-American faces. But that's a
pretty low threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bochco, the successful producer of TV hits like ``NYPD
Blue,'' has said, ``I don't think there's conscious prejudice on
television. ... It's unthinking. It tends to be an unmindful
reflection of self on the part of writers and developers and
networks in general.''
</P>
<P>
   The powers behind the scenes of the TV entertainment industry
are overwhelmingly white men, so all they are doing is ``reflecting
self.''
</P>
<P>
   True diversity won't be accomplished until the writers,
producers and executives look more like the real America, not the
fake one now being depicted on the four major networks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
