<HEADLINE>
BALL WILL CRYSTALLIZE TIMES SQUARE ON NEW YEAR'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tradition is old but the ball is new. When the crowds gather
in Times Square on Dec. 31 to welcome in the year 2000, they'll
watch a dazzling ball made with Waterford crystal descend at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Square New Year's Eve Ball will be a transparent
geodesic sphere, covered with an original Waterford design _ a ball
so special that it even has a name: Star of Hope. Here are some
facts about the ball that will majestically drop 77 feet to the
bottom of a pole atop the One Times Square building:
</P>
<P>
   --It weighs 500-plus pounds and is 6 feet in diameter _ about
the same weight and dimensions as the old ball.
</P>
<P>
   --The hand-crafted design consists of 504 triangular pieces of
Waterford crystal, each containing a central circle and a
seven-pointed star. The circle represents the earth and the star,
the seven continents. Deep-wedge cuts that surround each star
symbolize the diversity of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   --The crystal triangles will be bolted to 168 triangular lexan
panels. And the exterior of the ball will be studded with 168
``Philips Halogena 2000'' bulbs, designed for increased reflection.
</P>
<P>
   And here are facts about the annual celebration in the square:
</P>
<P>
   --The first ball-lowering ceremony was held in 1907.
</P>
<P>
   --The festivity draws a half-million people to Times Square
every New Year's and is telecast to more than a billion viewers
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   --This year's special festivity, called ``Times Square 2000, the
Global Celebration at the Crossroads of the World,'' will begin at
5:30 a.m. EST on Dec. 31, when the new year arrives in the South
Pacific. For 25 hours, the people and cultures of each of the
world's time zones will be celebrated using sight, sound,
pageantry, and special effects. Live video will be beamed from the
time zones to the crowds in Times Square via giant Panasonic
Astrovision screens. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of the square: Times Square now has a Web site:
Www.timessquareseek.com can tell you just about anything you want
to know about the square, with its 35 hotels, 40 theaters, 684
retailers, 268 restaurants, and 50 ``supersigns.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which is the only New York City borough attached to
the mainland? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: ``Manhattan'' comes from ``menatay,'' which is Delaware
Indian for ``island.''
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``New York's murder rate is down. Times Square is
family-friendly. New York has become your crazy drinking buddy who
got married and had kids'' _ Colin Quinn on ``Saturday Night
Live.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: In New York, it is illegal to throw a ball at
someone's head just for the fun of it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dream on: Chances of a white Christmas in New York are 1 in 4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Netting a freebie: You can visit the Web, check e-mail, and send
messages from the third-floor Sky View Bar at JFK Terminal 4.
Access to the computer work stations is free for all, but they
probably won't mind if you order a drink. Take the escalator from
the central area of the terminal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quite a community: New York City has the largest Jewish community
(1.75 million people) outside Israel (5.6 million people). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Welcome back: The venerable Russian Tea Room (known to some as the
RTR) is reopening Oct. 11 after a makeover that is said to preserve
the best of the old while incorporating the creative flair of
restaurant impresario Warner LeRoy. Also sometime in October, the
Radio City Music Hall will complete a $70 million renovation
designed to restore the Art Deco landmark to its original 1932
grandeur and at the same time modernize the facility. (The Russian
Tea Room is at 150 West 57th St. between Sixth and Seventh avenues;
call 212-974-2111. Radio City Music Hall is at 1260 Sixth Ave. at
49th Street; call 212-247-4777). And beginning Oct. 1, a
refurbished Rainbow Room, that gilded, glass-walled supper club
with its amazing views from the 65th floor high above Rockefeller
Center, will reopen for dinner and dancing on Friday nights and
brunch on Sundays. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
