<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DAIRY-COMPACT-BOS &LR;      09-28 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIRY-COMPACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDWEST DAIRY FARMERS OPPOSE N.E. SAFETY VALVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINERAL POINT, Wis. _ Dick Gorder has ``got milk,'' just as the
billboards suggest along the highway to his farm. As the owner of
50 cows in the heart of dairyland, he has also got a major problem:
the milk business in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Gorder keeps the same routine each day, herding his animals into
a milking stall every 12 hours, pumping 1,350 pounds into a steel
tank. But his paycheck is anything but predictable, rising and
falling with the whims of the milk market. Sometimes, the plant he
sells to pays $16 per hundred pounds of milk. Sometimes it's a lot
less.
</P>
<P>
   But a wildly fluctuating market isn't what's bothering Gorder.
His beef is with the Northeast Dairy Compact, formed by New England
farmers three years ago to dictate a minimum price for their milk _
and to ensure they never had to worry about the market at all.
Gorder says he is being discriminated against. And along with a
horde of angry Wisconsin farmers, dairy processors and politicians,
he is ready to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't come out and say it, but they just can't compete in
the free market,'' said Gorder, 43.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is now stirring passions on Capitol Hill, where a
number of milk disputes are coming to a head, including
authorization for the Northeast Dairy Compact, which is scheduled
to expire on Friday. Other issues involve complex pricing
structures and conflicting economic analyses, with each side
insisting its plan will result in lower milk prices at the grocery
store.
</P>
<P>
   But fundamentally, the controversy stems from the way the milk
business has changed over the last century, as refrigeration has
made it easier for dairy products to travel great distances and as
many small farms have given way to dairy conglomerates. The debate
boils down to a regional difference of opinion on a single matter:
whether or not the government should fight to keep small farms
alive and ensure each region is drinking local milk.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, when the national milk-pricing system was
established, the answer was easy. To make sure consumers everywhere
had a ready supply of milk in an era of poor refrigeration and
poorer highways, the federal government devised a formula to
encourage dairy farming in places where it wasn't profitable, such
as the East Coast and the South. The price, the government decided,
would be roughly calculated based on the distance a farmer was from
Eau Claire, Wis. The farther the farmer was from the heart of
America's dairyland, the more he would be paid for milk in any
given month.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress voted to make the system more efficient as
part of its larger farming overhaul, demanding a new structure be
established in 1999. But at the same time, the six New England
states launched a campaign to shield their dairy farmers against
the whims of the market. With Senator Patrick J. Leahy, Democrat of
Vermont, taking the lead, Congress granted a three-year program for
a 26-member commission to regulate New England milk prices,
otherwise called the Northeast Dairy Compact.
</P>
<P>
   Each month, under compact rules, the commission sets a minimum
price that processors have to pay farmers for their milk,
regardless of the federal price. The expiration date was set for
Oct. 1, 1999. And according to opponents, that's when the compact
should be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Do we develop 21st century policies to match
the 21st century realities of the dairy business?'' said Allen
Rosenfeld, an economist for the International Dairy Foods
Association, which strongly opposes compacts.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the compact, however, say it has been an
unmitigated success, helping stabilize payments to New England's
4,000 dairy farmers, who have received $75 million more during the
past two years than they would have with federal milk rates. Each
farmer has received an additional $10,000 to $13,000, said a
Vermont Senate aide.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have benefited too, compact advocates say, pointing to
a 1998 study by the Office of Management and Budget that found
consumer milk prices in New England were five cents lower than in
the rest of the country during the compact's first six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time understanding why the Midwest is so opposed
to it,'' said Jacques Couture, 49, a dairy farmer from Westfield,
Vt., during a visit to Capitol Hill last week. ``In New England, it
has proven not to do some of the things people were afraid of. The
price of milk has not gone up. The scare stories haven't
materialized. And it's not costing taxpayers any money.''
</P>
<P>
   For his farm, Couture said, ``It has taken out some of the peaks
and valleys. It's like a minimum wage, in a sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, dairy farmers in the Mid-Atlantic region and the Deep
South have looked on with envy. Faced with the same volatile price
swings that once afflicted the Northeast, an additional 21 states
decided they, too, want a compact. Now, Congress is slated to
consider allowing six Mid-Atlantic states into the Northeast
compact, as well as whether to allow 15 states, stretching from
Florida to West Virginia, to form a Southern Dairy Compact.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling coalition _ which represents 40 percent of the
dairy industry _ has incited the wrath of Midwestern officials,
creating unusual political alliances and erasing the normal
assumptions about which politicians support free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Russell Feingold and Herb Kohl, both Democrats of
Wisconsin, have teamed up with Senator Rod Grams, Republican of
Minnesota, as well as Minnesota Governor Jesse Ventura, to combat
what they term the ``price-fixing cartels.'' In Wisconsin, where
farmers produce roughly 28 percent of the nation's cheese, the
outrage is palpable.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the dairy compacts address only the price of milk,
the Wisconsin farmers say that mandated minimums would encourage
overproduction in the compact states, where the perishable excess
milk would be turned into cheese. That cheese would then flood the
market, causing prices to plummet, Midwestern farmers fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New England compact, from their perspective, is just the
tip of the iceberg,'' Rosenfeld said. Expanding the compacts, he
said, ``is the specter looming on the horizon that everyone's
afraid of.''
</P>
<P>
   With negotiations over the compacts heating up this week in
Congress, the Midwesterners have indicated they will go great
lengths to defeat their regional foes. In a letter to constituents
earlier this year, Leahy and Senator James M. Jeffords, the Vermont
Republican, compared the opposition's attitude to that ``normally
associated with wartime enemies.'' And Kohl _ who earlier this year
attached 70 amendments to a measure to reauthorize the Northeast
Dairy Compact in an attempt to kill it _ wouldn't argue with that
assessment. He said the battle ``is personal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have compacts for milk, why don't we have compacts for
other products?'' Kohl said. ``The compact expires October 1, and
that's when it should go out of business. Nobody argues it's good
economic policy. Nobody. They want to argue that it's good for
dairy farmers? Well, I come from Wisconsin, a dairy state. And I
don't think that's the case.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a substantial difference between dairy farming in
Wisconsin and Vermont, namely availability of land and cow feed.
Advocates of the compacts argue that if the free market were at
play, the nation's dairy farms would eventually consist of a few,
massive commercial operations in the Midwest _ which given their
sheer size, would pollute the environment with excess manure. And
because of the Midwesterners' de facto monopoly over the milk
market, the argument goes, prices for consumers would skyrocket in
places farthest away.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, dairy farmers outside the Midwest say they are
battling goliaths to preserve a rural way of life. Their strength
was evident last week, when the House voted against restructuring
the national milk-pricing system in favor of a plan similar to the
status quo, which more or less guarantees farmers in the East a
higher price than those in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   As with the dairy compacts, there were regional dividing lines,
but with a peculiar twist in that vote. Only five House members
from Massachusetts _ Representatives J. Joseph Moakley of South
Boston, John I. Olver of Springfield, Richard E. Neal of
Springfield and James P. McGovern of Worcester, all Democrats _
voted to retain the current pricing plan. The other five members of
the House delegation, without any dairy farmers in their district,
voted to change the system to one more market-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Gorder, for his part, isn't worried about going out of business
yet. While the fierceness of the debate suggests the Northeast
coalition is threatening the existence of the Midwestern farms, his
concern, as a member of the board of directors of the Wisconsin
Farm Bureau, is the growing coalition would gradually erode the $17
billion dairy industry in Wisconsin. He also worries about his own
farm. ``Why should I go out and spend $200,000 upgrading equipment
when the government is discriminating against me?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, it is a ``matter of principle,'' he said,
strolling from his farmhouse to the barn to shoo the cows out to
pasture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just really have a fundamental problem with the way it's
being done,'' he said. ``People in Boston should have a problem
with it. It's not that their farmers are getting too much for the
product. It's just a matter of being fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BISHOP-CANDIDATE-BOS &LR;      09-28 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOP-CANDIDATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINISTER TRAVELS IN QUEST FOR BISHOP'S SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ For the Rev. Leroy Attles, the popular pastor
at St. Paul AME Church in Central Square, campaigning to become a
bishop in the African Methodist Episcopal Church is as demanding as
running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Like a steadfast politician, Attles is making his third bid to
become one of the 19 bishops who oversee 2.5 million members
globally. They are coveted positions that typically become
available only if a bishop dies or resigns.
</P>
<P>
   And like any politician, Attles has been diligently raising
money _ about $30,000 in four years _ as well as printing brochures
highlighting his background and experience. He has a couple of
speeches memorized to try to convince AME delegates in the United
States, Canada, southern Africa, and the Caribbean that he is the
person they should vote for in the July 2000 election in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go to the backwood roads of Alabama and Georgia, to a
church with just three people in it, and they will know my name,''
Attles said in a recent interview at the church's Christian Life
Center. ``I know three times as many people now as I knew in 1992,
when I was first introduced to the general conference. The issue is
to become well known.''
</P>
<P>
   The general conference is the engine of the historically black
church, founded in Philadelphia in 1787 as a civil rights group
known as the Free African Society. It meets every four years to
handle the church's business _ including the election and
reassignment of bishops _ across international borders and the time
zones of the AME's 19 global districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like a worldwide campaign, and there is politicking and
public relations,'' said Bishop Vinton R. Anderson, who is based in
Washington, D.C., and presides over the AME's Second District,
which includes the mid-Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   In determining eligible candidates _ and, this time, women are
among the contenders _ Anderson said he and others casting ballots
look at the ``measure of faithfulness and productivity they have
shown in the local churches they have pastored. I expect them to be
a stimulus to encourage a broad ministry in the churches under
their care.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gregory G. Groover, pastor at Charles Street AME Church
in Roxbury, said Attles is indeed that stimulus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a rare pastor's heart,'' Groover said. ``His ministry,
in my estimation, is incomparable to any other church in Greater
Boston because of his social outreach. Cambridge is a better city,
particularly for African-Americans, because of the impact of (his)
church.''
</P>
<P>
   Attles is one of 26 candidates vying for two bishop slots. With
a decade of campaigning under his belt _ his first time on the
ballot was 1992 _ Attles might just make it this time, many in the
AME church say.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly has, by many accounts, an impressive resume. Since
he came to St. Paul's from New Jersey 22 years ago, membership in
Attles's congregation has blossomed from 500 to 1,400.
</P>
<P>
   And placing a premium on outreach outside the church walls,
Attles and his wife, Henrietta, both of whom hold doctoral degrees
in education, have increased enrollment in the church's Henry
Buckner School, which is open to all children in pre-school through
first grade. Attles started weekend tutoring in math and science, a
theater group, a children's choir, and liturgical dance.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Attles talked his parishioners into
redirecting hard-earned money, which had been earmarked to renovate
the church, toward remodeling the old parsonage and another house
on Columbia Street into a 14-room shelter for homeless families. A
decade ago, at Attles's prompting, the church bought and renovated
what is now the Christian Life Center for $1.6 million, a bustling
community center that houses the school, offices, an auditorium,
and a chapel. Attles also runs ministries for the deaf and for
prisoners and a radio broadcast ministry directed at East Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ogletree, a renowned Harvard Law School professor,
joined Attles's church in the 1970s as a law student and returned
in 1986 after moving back to Massachusetts. ``He has done a
tremendous job and that is evident in the number of ministers that
have trained under him,'' Ogletree said. ``He is the embodiment of
our church.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Attles continues to criss-cross the nation in his
quest for the bishop's slot. Two weeks ago he flew from Miami to
Chicago. Last week, in the span of three days, he traveled to Ohio,
Mississippi, and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happiest doing ministry,'' said Attles. As bishop, he
added, ``I can do what I have done here on a larger scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Next July 4, about 1,600 voters in the general conference will
cast ballots to fill the two bishop vacancies _ one in Capetown,
South Africa, and the other in the midwestern United States
district.
</P>
<P>
   Once the new bishops are elected, a committee will reassign all
the denomination's bishops as it sees fit, which means Attles, if
elected, could find himself heading any AME district. He would have
three months to wrap up business here before reporting for his new
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about what I will have left here,'' Attles said,
weighing his feelings about leaving _ or staying. ``I'm at peace
either way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
