<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-28 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RULES OF THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Wall Street Journal just published a list of the world's
hundred biggest public companies, and the biggest surprise was that
General Motors wasn't on it.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was number one. General Electric was second, IBM
third, and Wal-Mart Stores fourth. No surprises there.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Cisco and Lucent ahead of Royal Dutch Shell. That
raised an eyebrow or two.
</P>
<P>
   Intel ahead of Exxon, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone ahead of
AT&AMP;T, Merck ahead of Amoco. Thirteen places and no GM?
</P>
<P>
   A friend had called to share the joke. America's best business
newspaper had forgotten America's biggest automotive company _ a
major advertiser, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   We scoured the list. Perhaps some obscure concept was being
employed that ruled out auto companies. Nope, Toyota was number 23.
DaimlerChrysler was number 39 (before last year's merger, numbers
63 and 99, respectively.) Ford was number 66.
</P>
<P>
   No General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somehow nearer the end of the list than the beginning?
Have they stopped making Chevrolets? Not there either. Hopkinton's
EMC Corp. was number 80. Gillette was number 91.
</P>
<P>
   The last half dozen entries were a reminder of the polyglot
world of big business: Charles Schwab (US). TotalFina (France).
Sony (Japan). Barclays (UK). The Gap (US). AXA Group (France).
Aegon (Netherlands).
</P>
<P>
   There was no place for GM on this list.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, of course, is that the Wall Street Journal had
ranked firms according to their market value, not their sales.
</P>
<P>
   Multiply the number of GM's shares by its recent price and it
comes to about $40 billion _ around $3 billion shy of the $42.9
billion that permitted Aegon to make the list at the 100 spot.
Microsoft, at number one, was worth more than 10 times as much, at
$460.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But then why wouldn't it be? Microsoft earned $7.8 billion on
sales of $19.7 billion in fiscal 1998 _ 73 percent ahead of the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Aegon (whose business is pensions and insurance)
earned $1.5 billion on sales of $12.8 billion in 1998, a profit
margin we'd all be glad to have, but nothing like Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal chose the right yardstick, at least for
simplicity's sake. There are, of course, all sorts of ways to
describe the world's ``biggest'' companies.
</P>
<P>
   By sales? That used to be the tradition, when businesses were
much more settled into various grooves, thanks to existing
technologies, regulatory authorities, and national boundaries. And
goodness knows General Motors has plenty of sales _ $161.3 billion
in 1998, or about eight times more than Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   That's why GM was number one in the more traditional Fortune 500
ranking by sales this year _ just ahead of Ford ($144.4 billion),
Wal-Mart ($139.2 billion), Exxon ($100.7 billion), General Electric
($100.5 billion), and IBM ($81.7 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   Assets, too, can make a company large. With their huge
portfolios of loans, financial institutions top these lists:
Citigroup ($668.6 billion), ahead of BankAmericorp ($617.7
billion), Fannie Mae ($485.0 billion), and Chase Manhattan ($365.9
billion.) And employees: General Electric has 293,000 employees,
while EMC has only 9,400.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are any number of measures of profitability:
return on shareholder's equity, return on total equity (which
includes debt), rule-of-thumb measures like earnings per share.
With shareholder equity of $15 billion, GE returned 19.7 percent
this year _ a lot better than your cash-management account.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure of market values tends to wrap profitability up
in a single tidy package. A company's share price, after all, rises
and falls each day on the collective expectation of where its
fortunes are headed.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the lofty valuations accorded companies like Microsoft,
Cisco, and Lucent (Microsoft's current price/earnings ratio is 64)
reflect the shared opinion that the companies will continue to grow
rapidly, while General Motors's sorry valuation (its P/E is 9)
reflects the expectation that the troubled company will continue to
struggle and, perhaps, to continue to sink.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it makes sense to rank companies by their market
value. It highlights the news, good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
