<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WEB-INVENTOR-ART-BOS &LR;      09-28 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-INVENTOR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB MUST PROGRESS TO FULFILL PROMISE, SAYS ITS INVENTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1922, the journalist Walter Lippmann imagined a worldwide
``machinery of knowledge'' that would transform society and empower
individuals. Today, as institutions from Congress to bait shops put
themselves on line, the World Wide Web might seem to fulfill
Lippmann's utopian vision.
</P>
<P>
   But a chief skeptic of such a view turns out to be the British
researcher who invented the Web and who now guides its development
from a post at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Weaving the Web,'' Tim Berners-Lee writes
that big improvements are still needed in the Web's underlying
technology before it can give rise to what he calls ``social
engines,'' such as the staging of national elections or political
debates on line.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Berners-Lee writes, the Web is only a tool, ``at once
the great equalizer and the great divider.'' Computers are best
applied, he writes, ``if we use them to create . . . processes in
which the people do the creative work and the machine does the
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-written with Mark Fischetti and just being shipped by
HarperCollins, ``Weaving the Web'' comes out at a time of unbridled
enthusiasm for the social and economic possiblities of the new
medium and the riches it has created.
</P>
<P>
   The book combines an explanation of Berners-Lee's goals at the
MIT-based group he directs, the World Wide Web Consortium, with a
history of the codes he wrote to allow computers to exchange text
and images and the partnerships he struck that first gave rise to
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   It also introduces 44-year-old Berners-Lee as something of a
critic of the hype surrounding the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his contribution, Berners-Lee has remained apart from
the Internet gold rush. His MIT job pays a maximum salary of
$90,000, and in 1998 he won a $270,000 grant from the MacArthur
Foundation. Yet both pale beside the riches that have flowed to
founders of many companies spawned by the Web, such as portal firm
Yahoo Inc. and retailer Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Berners-Lee explains that he has turned down several offers from
the private sector because they would have limited his ability to
direct the Web's design. While he praises the success of many
Internet start-ups, he also expresses concern at the get-rich-quick
ethos of much attention given the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is maddening is the terrible notion that a person's value
depends on how important and financially successful they are and
that that is measured in terms of money,'' he writes. ``If your
requirement is to make a large amount of money, then your options
in life are rather small,'' he said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues at MIT have heard this before. Berners-Lee craves
clout more than cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not interested in being filthy rich or (in) doing the
things that are required to get there,'' said Al Vezza, formerly a
top administrator at the school and now president of Fortech
Seminars Inc. in Reston, Va. ``He's come to the conclusion that he
can be most effective by being pure. What's important to him is
having influence. That's his megalomania and his baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Berners-Lee came to MIT by way of Switzerland, where he spent
much of the 1980s as a graduate student.
</P>
<P>
   As recounted in ``Weaving the Web,'' it was at the CERN physics
laboratory in Geneva that Berners-Lee first began to write programs
designed to allow computers to exchange information via data
networks. Specifically, Berners-Lee developed the software
conventions that are key to the Web's usefulness, with acronyms
like URL (uniform resource locator) and HTTP (hypertext transfer
protocol).
</P>
<P>
   But CERN never fully supported Berners-Lee's projects, and in
1994 he agreed to set up the World Wide Web Consortium, or the W3C
as it is known in techspeak, at MIT's Laboratory for Computer
Science.
</P>
<P>
   The W3C provides a forum for Internet companies to hash out
technical disagreements over code for the Web, the graphics portion
of the Internet. Today members include 355 companies from Boeing
Co. to China Times Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Berners-Lee seems happy in his role as director, a post he took
because it left him ``free to really think about what was best for
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say the price of Berners-Lee's job satisfaction is an
organization that fudges tough policy questions. One example
relates to the variety of codes used by Web designers to ensure
that their pages will work with different Web browsers, such as
Microsoft's Internet Explorer or America Online's Netscape
Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Web pages should work in all browsers equally,
according to a format recommended by the W3C in December 1996,
known as ``Cascading Style Sheets.'' But in practice, neither
Microsoft nor Netscape browsers support all the W3C's suggestions,
and neither company has faced any sanctions as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The situation vexes some designers, who say it can cost an extra
25 percent to ensure their sites work with all browsers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like if you needed five different televisions to watch
five different channels,'' says George Olsen, who heads the Web
Standards Project, a Los Angeles lobbying group that would like the
W3C to enforce stricter rules.
</P>
<P>
   Berners-Lee acknowledges Olsen's point but says ``that doesn't
mean that W3C should play Web police,'' partly since it can't lean
on companies like Netscape or Microsoft without driving them away.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the body insist on the time-consuming process of
seeking public comment before issuing its decisions. In ``Weaving
the Web,'' Berners-Lee explains that getting agreements requires
``a balancing act, between taking the time to stay as open as
possible and advancing at the speed demanded by the onrush of the
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of the Web in recent years has made Berners-Lee
a figure of much interest in Cambridge, Mass., where he lives with
his wife and two children. Though he doesn't teach courses at MIT,
he can often be seen biking to work or wandering the halls of the
old Polaroid Corp. building that houses his corner office.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues say the scraps of personal data in ``Weaving the
Web'' mark a breakthrough for Berners-Lee, who has never been
comfortable with questions about his private life. He remains so in
many respects, declining even to name his favorite commercial sites
on the Web, except for a few newspapers from home (such as
www.guardian.co.uk or www.the-times.co.uk). He says he must be
reticent to avoid seeming to endorse on-line retailers.
</P>
<P>
   But he will say that he recently began attending a Unitarian
Universalist church, a denomination that reminds him of his ideal
of the Web as a place where ``people think and discuss, argue, and
always try to be accepting of differences of opinion and ideas,''
he writes.
</P>
<P>
   People who work with Berners-Lee say the rare times he loses his
temper involve technical breakdowns, for example, Web sites with
broken links to other pages. Some clunky bank sites also come in
for criticism because they link consumers to older, slower
mainframe systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important to him that people think the Web works
as well as the stock market,'' said Dan Connolly, a W3C technical
staffer since 1994. Once, Connolly remembers, Berners-Lee
threatened to boycott a conferences organized by a Canadian data
provider after finding its Web site wanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was nothing more serious than their contract for
hosting services had run out, but he was on the phone with them
right away after he noticed it,'' Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Berners-Lee hopes, the W3C's suggestions will enable
companies to post better Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is far from `done,' '' Berners-Lee writes in his book.
``It is in only a jumbled state of construction, and no matter how
grand the dream, it has to be engineered piece by piece, with many
of the pieces far from glamorous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
