<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKING WAGE IS MINIMUM JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even while historical documentation and solid evidence have
proven them wrong each time, Republican conservatives are still
using the ``sky will fall'' strategy to keep Congress from raising
the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts, is
leading the struggle to raise the federal minimum wage during this
session from $5.15 an hour to $6.15 an hour _ 50 cents in January
2000 and another 50 cents in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The increase would add about $2,000 to the average yearly
minimum-wage income of $10,721 for full-time work. However, the
current annual income leaves a family of three $3,200 below the
poverty line, and the proposed increase would still leave them
below the federal poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Kennedy and other backers of the bill argue, that $2,000
would at least pay for seven months of groceries to feed the
average family or pay rent for five months or pay for almost 10
months of utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The last increase in the minimum wage was in 1996 and 1997, when
it was increased by 90 cents per hour over that two-year period.
Passage of that bill, also spearheaded by Kennedy, happened only
after Republicans were permitted to add $21 billion in tax breaks
for business to help counter the dire costs the wage hike would
have upon America.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, corporate lobbyists, and conservative think tanks
predicted that the increase would destroy the economy, that it
would cost working people their jobs and thus significantly
increase unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   However, as the facts have shown, unemployment during that
period decreased, even more so among the groups most affected by
the minimum wage: minorities, teenagers, and wage-earners without
college degrees. This year, two years after that increase in the
minimum wage, the unemployment rate among African-American men hit
its lowest level ever. And the overall unemployment rate dropped to
the current low of 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Various conservative studies also argued that the wage hike
would mostly benefit teenagers from affluent families. Yet latest
Labor Department figures show that 72 percent of minimum-wage
workers are adults 20 years of age or older and that more than half
are women. About half of these minimum-wage earners are full-time
workers, and one third work at least 20 hours a week. Their average
family incomes are about $15,000 below the national average.
</P>
<P>
   And while Republicans were arguing that an increase in the
minimum wage was too costly and too dangerous for the economy,
these same members of Congress recently gave themselves a
cost-of-living raise of $4,600 a year, adding to the $141,300
salary they already receive. Yet they would deny to 11 million
workers a minimum wage increase that would be less than half of
what they gave themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's bill calls for so modest an increase that it would not
even bring the minimum wage up to the level of 1968 in purchasing
power. That year, the real value of the minimum wage was $7.49,
more than $2.00 higher than the current rate of $5.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy and other supporters of the bill see the $1 an hour
increase as a realistic goal.
</P>
<P>
   As demonstrated with the passage of the last minimum-wage hike,
there are ways of getting this bill passed despite strong
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Key GOP members in the Senate are seeking to pass a bankruptcy
overhaul bill, which would make it more difficult for consumers to
avoid paying debts by declaring bankruptcy. But Republicans
withdrew the bill when it became apparent they didn't have the
votes to prevent the Democrats from attaching the minimum-wage hike
to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some Republicans conceded that in order to get their
bankruptcy bill passed, a minimum-wage increase must be attached to
the measure. With the Democrats having enough votes to block the
bill without the minimum-wage attachment, there is an increasing
possibility that the bill will be brought back to the floor. If
there is more debate on the minimum-wage bill, it should center on
why the GOP and their business supporters fight so hard against a
minimum-wage increase.
</P>
<P>
   Lest they forget, the minimum wage, according to one report, was
established in 1938 to ensure that US workers were fairly
compensated for a day's work. It's time that Republicans and their
business allies understand the basic reason why low-income workers
deserve a minimum wage increase. They earned it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1417EDT &QL; 
