<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-28 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSFUL POLITICIANS PLAY BY THE RULES OF POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been a lot of grousing about this year's Republican
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists _ and most of the candidates _ don't like the fact
that the race seems to have been conceded to George W. Bush so
early, that Bush has raised far more money than his rivals and that
it takes so much money to mount a serious bid for the presidency.
Former Vice President Dan Quayle dropped out of the competition
Monday, in part, because he could not raise enough money. Quayle
had collected $5 million as of June, a fraction of what frontrunner
Bush had amassed.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a tip for the disgruntled politicos: If you'd been
reading the business pages the past few years, you would not find
any of these developments at all surprising. What's happening here
is that the political world is starting to play by the rules of the
business world.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical? Well, we can think of at least three important
parallels.
</P>
<P>
   1. Outcomes are anticipated far in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who follows the stock market knows this one. If the Fed
is expected to raise interest rates in two weeks, the market falls
today, not two weeks from now. If Asian economies look as if they
are going to recover, the markets will rally _ even if the actual
recovery is a year away. The market's attitude is: Why wait if you
know what's going to happen?
</P>
<P>
   Republican voters and fundraisers seem to have adopted the same
philosophy. They've decided far in advance that George W. Bush is
the strongest candidate and the likely winner and they have flocked
en masse _ with their money _ to his camp.
</P>
<P>
   The losers complain that Bush is going to win because he has so
much money. In truth, the critics have it backward: He has so much
money because he is likely to win. Like investors, campaign
contributors want to get on the winning team as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
   2. The gap between first place and second place is growing.
</P>
<P>
   The thinkers at Mercer Management Consulting, a leading
consulting firm, have a term for this. They call it the ``silver
medal syndrome.'' Pick any pair of competitors: Coke vs. Pepsi,
Nike vs. Reebok, Gap vs. The Limited, Yahoo vs. Excite. If you
calculate the stock market values in each matchup, you will find
that the number one player in the field is worth dramatically more
than the runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these situations, the value that migrates to the gold medal
performer leaves the second place player gasping for breath,''
wrote two Mercer consultants in a book called ``Profit Patterns.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar, Elizabeth Dole and John McCain? Neither has been
able to raise even half the $50 million Bush has raised, even
though both are well-known, well-established challengers. Like it
or not, we live in a winner-take-all world. Second place today is
what fourth place used to be.
</P>
<P>
   3. It takes more money than ever to build your brand.
</P>
<P>
   EToys, an on-line toy retailer, Monday announced it was
launching a $20 million advertising campaign to build awareness of
the company for the upcoming Christmas buying season. A number of
young dot.com companies have shelled out $2 million to buy a single
advertising spot during next year's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   How come? Because they are convinced that only a small number of
companies will emerge as winners in any given field and that the
winners will be those that get out front early and create brand
awareness among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have their own brands and message they want to get
across. Bush: The Compassionate Conservative; McCain: The Heroic
Maverick; Dole: The Female.
</P>
<P>
   Spreading the word costs a lot of money. According to Business
Week, 80 percent of campaign funding goes to television advertising
and the cost of a television spot has climbed 50 percent in the
course of this decade. Is it any wonder that presidential campaign
spending is expected to total $210 million this year, up from $82
million in 1992? Without the money for ads, cutting through the
clutter becomes next to impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Is the adoption of business rules a good thing for politics? We
don't have an opinion. But one thing is clear: Politicians who
expect to thrive in the current environment better brush up on
their business skills. Otherwise, like Dan Quayle, they could find
themselves in an irreversible bear market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rising tide is lifting Boatscape.com, a fledgling Boston
company that hopes to serve the boating community.
</P>
<P>
   The company Monday said it landed a $5 million investment from
(at)Ventures, the venture capital arm of CMGI Inc. CMGI, based in
Andover, has investments in dozens of Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Boatscape.com was founded by Jay Wilkins, a graduate of
Dartmouth and the Harvard Business School. Wilkins wants boaters to
use the site for buying and sailing marine items and for sharing
ideas and information with fellow boaters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
