<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WILL HELP OUR SCHOOLS _ AND WHAT WON'T 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To all presidents, senators, governors, mayors, and hopefuls
running to replace them: Please stop using our children as props
when offering silly sound bites to express your concerns about
public education in America.
</P>
<P>
   While she is certainly not alone in displaying this unfortunate
political vice, Elizabeth Dole did it most recently in
Massachusetts. The Republican presidential candidate last week drew
cameras to Melrose High School to showcase her allegedly deep
commitment to raise academic standards, promote local initiative,
and restore discipline and values in the nation's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The ``news'' of her visit boiled down to an endorsement of
searching student lockers and backpacks for drugs and weapons, as
if that would really do anything to improve public education.
</P>
<P>
   Violence in schools is terrifying. No mother wants to think that
Columbine could happen anywhere near her children. Quite frankly,
it probably won't. National crime statistics could not be clearer
on the point. Crime in schools is going down, not up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the reality of what public schools do face every day is
scary in another way.
</P>
<P>
   Reality is a letter from the father of a girl in second grade
passed on to a principal from the girl's teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having some difficulty in helping (my daughter) with
her homework,'' the father wrote.`` My wife does not not speak or
read English very well. . . . I unfortunately work from 2 p.m. to
10 p.m. in Boston and don't get home until well after 11 p.m., and
at that time (my daughter) is already asleep. I am also unable to
change my shift. . . . I wonder if there is something we can do so
that she can get the help she needs. . . . I am willing to do
whatever is possible to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality is my 8-year-old neighbor, who has Down syndrome. His
smile brings joy to his mother's life and some to mine, too, now
that he has decided we can be friends.
</P>
<P>
   All his parents want is what the law supposedly requires _ a
place in a classroom in a public school around the corner from
their home. But a seemingly simple request for inclusion is
endlessly frustrated by a public school system that would rather
exclude him.
</P>
<P>
   As much as I am rooting for this little boy, I can see why
school administrators might view him as a burden, not a blessing.
They are beaten down by politicians _ and by parents _ who want
``results.'' And the results they demand are not measured child by
child but test score by test score.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, after all, Governor Paul Cellucci recently
said that every public school in the state will be ranked on the
basis of student scores on the Massachusetts Comprehensive
Assessment System tests.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a school superintendent or a principal, would you
want the special needs of special children to stand between you and
a higher rank? Even though you know intellectually that isn't the
case, wouldn't you be tempted to make them someone else's problem?
Pressed to prove you can deliver for the majority, it is only human
to shut out the even more dire needs of the minority. Private
schools do that as a matter of course and are richly rewarded for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Today's public school reality embraces a broad spectrum of need.
In between are your children and mine. The reality for them
includes large classes, outmoded textbooks, and technology at home
that very often outstrips what is available inside their school.
</P>
<P>
   The reality for those who teach our children is often
disheartening as well: old school buildings, cumbersome paperwork
and little in the way of perks, rewards or even encouragement. In
all the corporate tents lining the Ryder Cup course at The Country
Club, it's a fair bet that public school teachers weren't in on
much of the schmoozing. But they can look forward to continued
bashing by politicians and a frustrated public.
</P>
<P>
   Education reform is a step in the right direction. But we need
more dedicated funding for technology and other classroom
enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   Most working professionals turn on computers and check e-mail
and voice mail as a matter of everyday routine. For the most part,
the means of communicating with public school teachers is as
old-fashioned as the Pony Express. You send a note in a child's
backpack and hope it doesn't get thrown away with a snack, or you
leave a message with a school secretary and hope the teacher calls
back when you are not at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   No business is run that way, but that's the way we run the
business of public education in America.
</P>
<P>
   In the business world, it's a given that it takes money to make
money. Very simply, it takes money, not photo ops with our
children, to build a better school system. The politician who is
not afraid to utter that sound bite is the one worth heeding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
