<SLUG> BC-DATELESS-MILLENNIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLES HOPE TO MARK DATE OF THE CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There are fewer than 100 days before New Year's Eve
1999. Do you have a date yet?
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Kimball doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old divorced clothing designer would like to ring in
the millennium with the man of her dreams. She would like, just
this year, to be somewhere splendid.
</P>
<P>
   She has never been one for big New Year's Eve fests. With all
the couples kissing and cooing about their future plans, she finds
these parties painful. But this year is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just once I'd like to get dressed to the teeth and go out and
celebrate the way you see on TV,'' she said. ``I'd like to be
somewhere with a lot of people, just once, and feel part of that.
I'd like to be able to tell my grandchildren that I was in Times
Square, or some place grand.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kimball is dateless, she is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Dating services and matchmakers say they are overwhelmed with
requests from singles alarmed about starting the year 2000 solo,
while their partnered friends jet to exotic destinations and
romantic celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   It's the annual angst about finding a date for New Year's Eve,
magnified many, many times.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is already on to have a date to herald in the new
millennium. And not just any date.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be able to look back 20 years from now and say you
did something really great,'' said Scott, 29, a single health care
professional, who asked that his last name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a once-in-a-lifetime thing,'' he said. ``You feel the
pressure to create a memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Some singles worry that the evening has a symbolic, or perhaps
even superstitious significance, setting the tone for a year of
love _ or loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   Scott isn't sure what his incredible experience will be. Perhaps
he'll commandeer a rooftop near Times Square in New York and
romance a lucky lady under the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Scott had hoped to be married by the turn of the century. But he
hasn't found the right person to share his life. With the stakes so
high, he, like others, is seeking professional help.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are worrying because it's almost the year 2000
and they haven't met anyone yet,'' said Elizabeth O'Malley, vice
president of The Right One, a dating service that is trying to help
Beverly, Scott, and many others find partners before the millennium
arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the Right One receives calls from singles who are
stressed out about greeting the new year alone. But the volume this
year is more than her counselors can recall ever having.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Year's Eve is always hard for single people. But this one
has a special significance,'' she said. ``They really don't want to
spend it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   For many who don't yet have dates, all the hype and
commercialism are adding to their anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere you go, you see millennium T-shirts, hats, jackets,
clocks, champagne glasses, jewelry, calendars, you name it,'' said
Michelle, 35, a divorced nurse and mother of one in Providence, who
also was uneasy about revealing her last name. ``I saw one woman
who looked like a billboard for the millennium _ and that was this
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My girlfriends say, `What are you going to do?' '' Michelle
continued. ``If you don't have something grand planned, people are
asking you: Why not? What's wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   A grand setting and a crowd of strangers don't appeal much to
Michael, a 42-year-old systems engineer who asked that his last
name not be used. He'll probably spend New Year's Eve with his
large, extended family.
</P>
<P>
   But he has higher hopes. He's stockpiling champagne and hunting
for someone special to enjoy it with him. With 94 days left in
1999, there is still time to find her, he believes.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, they have dinner and dancing, celebratory champagne,
and noisemakers with a few close friends, he said. ``But I wouldn't
argue if I found someone really special who just wanted a romantic
evening with pate, foie gras, champagne and caviar, maybe some
single malt scotch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of all the people who never got to see a millennium
turn,'' Michael said. ``We're here and we can enjoy it. If you miss
the opportunity now, you can't go back. It's like your high school
prom, only bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the unattached see opportunities for romance not just on
the next New Year's Eve but throughout the year 2000. They don't
believe the opportunities will last long, but for a few months,
perhaps, they think people may be more open, more friendly, more
receptive to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see people saying, `It's a new millenium, a clean slate,'''
said Cheryl Goodman, owner-director of The Post Club, a dating
service in Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are taking stock of their lives and hoping to start
fresh, with no mistakes this time,'' she said. ``The millennium is
giving them the push they need to make a change.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, artist Anna Maria Fraschini, who gave her age as ``60
plus,'' said she's ready to begin again.
</P>
<P>
   A divorced mother of three who has devoted herself to her
children for many years, she hopes ``to close with the past and
spend the rest of my life in a more interesting way,'' she said.
New Years' Eve is always important to her and this one has added
punch, said Fraschini, who was born in Italy and immigrated to the
United States three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She cites an Italian proverb on finding love: ``If you don't on
New Year's Eve, you won't the entire year.''
</P>
<P>
   So, like many others, she's searching for that special partner,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she paused, and reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why only one?'' she quipped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
