<SLUG> BC-TV-ALLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT`S A RECYCLED `ALLY MCBEAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ALLY 
Starring: Calista Flockhart, Lisa Nicole Carson, Gil Bellows,
Courtney Thorne-Smith, Greg Germann, Jane Krakowski 
On: Fox, Tuesday at 8 p.m. 
Rated: 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal'' is one of the most influential series on TV
right now. You can see it in the way surreal fantasy sequences are
as common as sex jokes on prime time, and you can see it in TV's
growing population of women in the legal field, from ``Family Law''
to ``Judging Amy.'' And most of all, you can see it in the
redefinition of the hourlong series, a format that was once
reserved for straight drama (not including iconoclastic flukes like
``Twin Peaks''). David E. Kelley's newfangled series has ushered in
an age of dramedic tone, one that enables TV comedy to rise above
the sitcom punchline. Love it or wish it would get flushed down the
unisex toilet, ``Ally McBeal'' has made mainstream TV into a less
easily labeled place.
</P>
<P>
   But let's hope that the latest ``Ally McBeal'' development has
absolutely no influence whatsover, that it fails so miserably and
so ``Cop Rock''-ly that no brilliant network honcho will ever
attempt it again unless he or she is secretly longing for intant
and permanent career death. Now Fox is introducing ``Ally,'' a
sorry new half-hour of programming comprised of footage and plots
already used in the hourlong ``Ally McBeal,'' as well as scenes
that were left on the cutting room floor. Unlike ``Ally McBeal,''
which weaves together a few plotlines, ``Ally'' is devoted entirely
to a single story, one that has been condensed and rearranged from
its original presentation. The network calls this approach ``a
quickie''; I call it regurgitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally'' is a contemptible idea on so many levels it's hard to
know where to begin. The most obvious place is the fact that this
new half hour is clearly designed not for creative purposes but
solely to cash in on ``Ally McBeal.'' Fox isn't even bothering to
lure the ``McBeal'' audience to Tuesday nights with a spinoff, the
kind we'll get from the makers of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and
``Party of Five'' in the next few weeks. Spinoffs are a
questionable affair, too, but they are definitely more dignified
than this lazy Reader's Digest move. At least they offer some
inventive possibility (``Rhoda,'' RIP). No, ``Ally'' is just
refried beans, a gaseous ploy both to make more money from
``McBeal'' right now, and to create a product that will easily lend
itself to a future stint in syndication _ a lucrative portion of
the life of a show. ``Ally'' represents the greedy soul of product
repurposing.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't we already oversaturated with re-TV? As the networks make
fewer new episodes of series, we are subjected to rewatching shows
two and three times a year, during ``the season'' and then again
during the summer. ``Ally'' is just so much rerun, albeit
rejiggered rerun. Of the three episodes of ``Ally'' sent to
critics, two were instantly familiar from their first incarnation
on ``McBeal.'' One has Ally's sanity under review by the board of
bar overseers after her supermarket mishap, and the second
chronicles the dispute between a minister and a choir singer played
by Jennifer Holliday. Sure, the graphics on ``Ally'' are different
from those on ``Ally McBeal,'' with fast-moving shots of Boston in
between scenes. And it's all edited together at a jauntier clip.
But it's really just stale goods in the guise of something fresh.
</P>
<P>
   What's sad about ``Ally'' is the impact it has on the mother
ship. As ``Ally'' disassembles episodes of ``McBeal'' in order to
pluck out a single strand, it demystifies ``McBeal'' and changes it
from an imaginative hour of TV into some kind of network supply
source. It makes ``McBeal'' seem less special, and more like a
factory whose product will be distributed through the week. It also
spreads the whole ``Ally'' ``McBeal'' phenomenon thin, giving us
too much time with a set of quirky characters who already run the
risk of wearing out their welcome. The proud owner of a few hours
of TV every week, David E. Kelley should have searched his soul a
little harder before signing off on this rehash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
