<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET STARTED NOW ON FALL VEGETABLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: What vegetables can I plant this time of year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sow carrot seeds right away.
</P>
<P>
   Sow several lettuce varieties now into November. Lettuce seeds
need light to germinate. Scratch the seeds into pre-moistened soil
with a rake. Cover with no more than one-eighth-inch of fine, light
soil. Mist to prevent the soil from drying. Seeds may germinate in
three to 12 days, depending on weather conditions. Thin seedlings
to eight to 12 inches apart. Toss the thinnings into a salad.
</P>
<P>
   Good lettuce choices include `Buttercrunch' and `Tom Thumb,' two
butterhead types of lettuce; and `Black Seeded Simpson,' `Oak
Leaf,' `Salad Bowl' and `Red Sails,' leaf types. Nurseries also
stock lettuce transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Add multiplying onion bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Set out broccoli transplants now through mid-October, and add
cabbage plants now into November. Sow mustard and radishes through
November.
</P>
<P>
   Sun and a loose, organically enriched and well-draining soil
will help ensure good results with vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When and how can I sow wildflowers?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ideal time to sow wildflowers is now to December. For
best results, provide good drainage, sun and seed-to-soil contact.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the area for sowing by removing weeds and other
vegetation. Rake the soil an inch down. Uniformly broadcast the
seed, then repeat in a perpendicular direction. To aid in
distribution of seed, you can combine the seed with sand in a ratio
of four parts sand to one part seed. Press the seed into the soil
with a roller or by walking across the area.
</P>
<P>
   Water after you sow if there is insufficient rain, and pull any
weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to plant herbs. I've heard fall is a good time.
</P>
<P>
   A: Fall is an excellent time to add the following herbs to the
garden: bay, bee balm, borage (seed), catnip, chamomile, chervil
(seed and plants), chicory, clary sage plants, comfrey, coriander,
costmary, cumin (seeds), curry plants, dill, fennel, feverfew,
garden sage, garlic chives, germander, horehound, lamb's ear,
lavender, lemon balm, lovage, mints, nigella (seed), pineapple
salvia, oregano, onion chives, parsley, rosemary, rue, salad
burnet, santolina, sorrel, tansy and winter savory.
</P>
<P>
   Herbs need good drainage. You'll get the best results if you
plant in a raised bed of a relatively neutral (pH 6.5-7),
organically enriched soil or in containers, generally where they
will get at least six hours of sunlight. Adequate sunlight
encourages good development of the oils in the leaves. It is these
essential oils that give the herbs flavor and fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   You can design an herb garden as an element in your landscape,
or you can plant individual herbs among shrubs, flowering annuals
and perennials. One of the most frequently used designs in herb
gardening is the knot garden, a somewhat formal style that often
uses low hedges of fragrant evergreens such as germander, santolina
or boxwood around geometric patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Herbs also are attractive along a walkway, in kitchen window
boxes, as topiaries in terra-cotta pots or bordering a bed of old
roses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to each unpublished letter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8866 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-ENTWINED-BOS &LR;      09-28 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ENTWINED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWIN BOOK LONG ON FACTS, SHORT ON ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUGLAS BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ENTWINED LIVES 
Twins and What They Tell Us About Human Behavior 
By Nancy L. Segal 
Dutton, 396 pp., $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traveling near my hometown in Maine this summer I stopped at a
roadside truck to buy fresh-picked corn and became uneasy at the
way the old woman tending the stand eyed me as she haphazardly
threw ears into a paper bag without counting them.
</P>
<P>
   Then it came. ``Are you one of the twins?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   It had been close to 30 years since anyone had addressed me this
way, and it stirred memories about how for most of my childhood and
adolescence my identity was connected to another's. I was ``one of
the twins'' _ or just ``twin'' _ to a lot of folks around these
parts. Along with the aforementioned question, there also came
``Which twin are you?'', ``Which one is older?'', and the
unanswerable favorite: ``What's it like to be a twin?''
</P>
<P>
   People's failure to see us as individuals was understandable _
my brother and I looked so much alike that even we were unable at
times to tell ourselves apart in photos _ but the curiosity and awe
we encountered daily often had a freak-show quality to it. A lot of
people didn't really want to know us, any more than they wanted to
know the dog-faced boy or the bearded lady on display at the county
fair. Yet people showed insatiable curiosity about the supposed
supernatural and sordid sides of ``twinning.'' Could we read each
other's thoughts? Did we share a secret language? When one gets
sick, does the other feel it? Could our girlfriends tell us apart,
and did we ever try to trick them (wink, wink)?
</P>
<P>
   The thirst for knowledge about twins and what they might tell us
about human behavior has increased over the years, reignited by a
spate of reports about twins who were raised apart but share eerily
similar traits.
</P>
<P>
   Though this quest for understanding twinship may be a worthwhile
pursuit, a lot of it strikes me as silly. A Minnesota study of
twins raised separately found a pair who each had been married
twice to women named Linda and Betty and who also had sons named
James Allen and James Allan. So this proves . . . what? There's a
genetic predisposition to the names we encounter in our lives?
</P>
<P>
   The latest attempt to make sense of the twin phenomenon and
explain how it applies to ``singletons'' is ``Entwined Lives,'' by
twin researcher Nancy L. Segal. Though crammed with minute details
about every biological, physical, and psychological aspect of
twindom, it might be hard for a reader to get beyond the author's
immature attraction to twins (she is director of the Twins Study
Center at California State University, and was formerly with the
Minnesota Study of Twins Reared Apart). Particularly noticeable is
Segal's curious worship of identical twins over fraternal twins,
though she is herself a fraternal twin.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly researched, annotated, and footnoted, ``Entwined
Lives'' is impressive in the breadth of its study, but its
clinical, academic delivery doesn't provide much room for twins or
parents of twins seeking advice, and the material barely lives up
to its subtitle of explaining how twin research relates to
understanding overall human behavior _ though we are reminded
nearly once per chapter that it does.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of interesting fodder here, though: the fact
that hair whorls on identical twins often go in opposite
directions, that left-handed twins frequently have higher IQs than
their right-handed siblings, that first-born twins are likely to be
heavier than the second-born. There are interviews with semi-famous
twins (Marc and Stephen V. Roberts, William and David Koch among
them), and much on what twin research tells us about athletic
prowess and how court cases involving twins have affected legal
decisons involving wrongful death suits and injury.
</P>
<P>
   But little of it is likely to reverberate with general readers,
even if much of it did catch my attention _ I am, after all, a
left-handed first-born twin (I haven't checked my hair whorl).
</P>
<P>
   Segal has an annoying tendency to state the obvious. To wit:
``Some people's lives are a monotony of misfortunes, while other
people's lives are relatively tragedy-free. Twin studies are
showing us that things do not just happen, but that personality
traits may affect the sequence of life events.'' Or this:
``Identical twins generally show greater similarity than fraternal
twins.'' Or this: ``Identical twins are not identical in every
way.'' Segal is convinced that twins are living lab rats and
actually devotes a chapter to the ``living laboratory'' of twins.
She frequently mentions how her status as researcher affords her a
``ringside seat,'' or how twins are ``a natural experiment,'' or
are ``reflecting pools whose altered images teach us how the range
of environmental influences shape developmental outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   The book even tilts toward the lurid, with a chapter on dealing
with the loss of a twin, and ventures perilously close to the
carnival sideshow with another devoted to conjoined twins _ replete
with photos of twins physically connected by various shared organs.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Entwined Lives'' may reveal more about the depth
of people's odd fascination with twins and about the author's
admitted ``reverence'' for them than it does about what twin
studies really contribute to knowledge of human behavior. Twins,
however, will learn a little and will certainly relate to many of
the anecdotes and findings _ provided they can get beyond the
feeling that their lives are being poked and prodded and observed
under a microscope as well as a circus tent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
