u e BC-TV-POPE-BOS &LR;      09-28 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-POPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS EXPLORES POPE'S IMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Pope John Paul II made his procession through Boston in
1979, the sidewalk outside my Commonwealth Avenue apartment
disappeared beneath throngs of mesmerized undergraduates who seemed
to view it as a bigger event than Springsteen and the Stones put
together.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the pope would have had stern words for the lifestyles
of the youthful spectators who cheered him so fervently. But
something about this remarkable figure has always compelled
attention, even among the many who disagree with him. In an era
when all beliefs seem up for grabs, his unblinking certitude has
made him a potentmoral force.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it has also made him a controversial political force.
Those twin strands are entwined in ``John Paul II: The Millennial
Pope,'' a ``Frontline'' documentary airing Tuesday at 9 p.m. Though
its attempt to be a ``thematic biography'' sometimes results in
missteps, overall this is an ambitious, nuanced, and absorbing
attempt to illuminate the man born Karol Wojtyla 79 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The passions John Paul II evokes are on display here: Full voice
is given to the pope's adherents and slightly fuller voice to his
critics. The former argue that he is a pope for the ages who has
forced the world to think about faith in a new way, while the
latter find him retrograde in his opposition to reproductive
rights, to the ordination of women, and to modernity in general.
</P>
<P>
   But neither camp finds it easy to understand or to explain the
scholar, poet, athlete, actor, and playwright who ascended to the
seat of the Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, Frontline producer Helen Whitney seeks an explanation in
the haunted land of his birth, Poland. As a young man, the pope
lived under two monstrous tyrannies, Nazism and communism. ``The
Millennial Pope'' suggests that experience permanently darkened his
view of the 20th century and of human nature. But as the
documentary makes clear, it also prompted him to action when he
became pope.
</P>
<P>
   To a degree matched by few, if any, popes before him, he made a
top priority of combatting anti-Semitism. He unequivocally declared
it to be a sin, became the first pope to visit the synagogue in
Rome, and journeyed to Auschwitz. Were these steps rooted in guilt
at not doing more to help Jews during the Nazi occupation of
Poland? A Jewish filmmaker from Poland describes an interview in
which a clearly tormented pope said ``No'' when asked whether he
had taken steps to help his Jewish friends during the war (even
though the filmmaker had heard stories that he had). Then the pope
``took me in his arms like a brother with a very bad guilty
feeling,'' the filmmaker says.
</P>
<P>
   The most stirring portion of ``The Millennial Pope'' chronicles
the pope's role in inspiring his fellow Poles to throw off the
shackles of communism. When he became pope, his message to them
was: ``Be not afraid.'' A year later, his jubilant countrymen
crowded the streets of Warsaw as the pope returned home for a
confrontation with General Jaruzelski, the Polish leader, whose
knees were shaking. ``And suddenly, everybody stopped being
afraid,'' says writer Adam Zamoyski. ``That gave the strength for
Solidarity and for the destruction of the whole communist system.''
</P>
<P>
   But the documentary also zeroes in on what it portrays as the
pope's contradictions, particularly his opposition to the
``liberation theology'' espoused by Latin American priests.
Whitney's point of view is clear: Having helped to bring about the
end of one kind of dictatorship, he undermined efforts to battle
another kind. ``You have to wonder what would have happened if he
had made a different choice,'' says Washington Post reporter
Roberto Suro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Millennial Pope'' also challenges the pope's view of
women, arguing that his resistance to a broader role for women in
the church runs counter to his veneration of the Virgin Mary.
Scholar Marina Warner calls the pope's views a ``ghastly sort of
stone against which we've stumbled for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary loses focus near its end, in a section titled
``Faith.'' In an attempt to create a ``spiritual encounter'' with
John Paul II _ who is not interviewed _ Whitney includes the
lengthy ruminations on faith of others, including authors Germaine
Greer and Robert Stone and cabaret performer Andrea Marcovicci. It
creates a disjointed effect.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, though, ``The Millennial Pope'' succeeds in finding
provocative ways to make you think. Not unlike its subject.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
