<HEADER>
A8868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      09-28 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CALIGULA': STILL GARBAGE, 20 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goin' back to Cali.
</P>
<P>
   Not Cali as in the LL Cool J hip-hop classic, but Cali as in
``Caligula,'' Penthouse publisher Bob Guccione's relentlessly
perverse and depraved portrait of the relentlessly perverse and
depraved Roman emperor, Gaius Caesar Germanicus. Defying taste and
reason, Guccione is re-releasing the controversial 1979 film in 12
theaters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   To which one can only ask: Why? Even in the broadest sense, this
is not a film worthy of new examination and discovery, such as
recent theatrical re-releases ``The Godfather'' or the original
``Star Wars.'' This is a film which, upon its release, critic Roger
Ebert called ``sickening, utterly worthless, shameful trash.''
``Caligula,'' he said, ``is not good art, it is not good cinema,
and it is not good porn.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not alone in his condemnation, because the film was
universally panned. A muddled, endless orgy of rape, necrophilia,
evisceration, murder, and bestiality, it wasn't lovably bad like
Edward Wood's ``Plan 9 from Outer Space,'' or so bad it was good,
like ``Mommie Dearest.'' It was so unmitigatingly horrid, Ebert
said, he walked out of the film ``disgusted and unspeakably
depressed'' about 120 minutes into its 155-minute length.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with every denouncement, public curiosity only
increased, and the film would go on to become something of a minor
cult hit. After years of the high road, I finally surrendered to
temptation when the film was shown on campus during my junior year
of college. After waiting for hours to get in, and fighting for the
best seats, people left in droves long before the final credits
rolled. Imagine just how bad a film _ especially one with lots of
unvarnished sex _ has to be to get college students to walk out.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, ``Caligula'' is the worst film ever made.
</P>
<P>
   In a year which has produced such mangy dogs as ``In Dreams,''
``Wild Wild West,'' and ``Jawbreaker,'' leave it to Guccione, the
dark prince of bad taste, to remind us of just how low abysmal
filmmaking can go. But what makes ``Caligula'' so extraordinarily
dreadful is that Guccione, who produced the film, had pretensions
of greatness. He honestly believed he was creating something as
indelible as Orson Welles's ``Citizen Kane.'' He somehow lured a
cast of A-list actors, including Peter O'Toole, Sir John Gielgud,
Helen Mirren, and Malcolm McDowell as Caligula. Gore Vidal wrote
the original screenplay, and three-time Academy Award-winner Danilo
Donati signed on as art director. And Guccione wrote every check to
finance the $17.5 million film, because no one else wanted anything
to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Because Guccione made his name as Penthouse publisher, no one
expected anything more than a high-priced skin flick. But in a
Penthouse interview prior to the film's February 1979 opening,
Guccione maintained ``Caligula'' was not a porno film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the film as being pornographic, and I certainly
didn't set out to make a pornographic movie. To me, pornography is
a work of bad art, as opposed to good art,'' he said. ``And I don't
think `Caligula' qualifies under the heading of bad art. It was a
huge commercial undertaking, and at the same time we wanted to make
a serious statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Believing ``Caligula'' would be branded with an X, Guccione
bypassed the Motion Picture Association of America, those picayune
folks who bestow ratings. An X rating, he said, would be
``demeaning and unfair,'' to the film.
</P>
<P>
   If the film had been worthy, ``Caligula'' could have been a
manifesto demanding reconciliation between serious drama and
graphic sexuality. Had Guccione created the ``landmark'' film he
deluded himself into believing he had, he would have been a
trailblazer, perhaps curtailing the ever-testy debate about the
kiss-of-death NC-17 rating (essentially as lethal as an X at the
box office), and the shoddy treatment of such adult, sexually frank
films as ``Happiness,'' ``Summer of Sam,'' and ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Guccione lived down to low expectations, although he
was right in believing ``Caligula'' did not qualify under the
heading of bad art. It's far more insidious. It's a horrifically
violent porn film masquerading as a historical epic. Void of any
merit, save for the oddity of watching the exact moment when
Malcolm McDowell's career crashed and burned, there was no other
reason to tell this story other than to revel in the Bacchanalian
excesses of a power-mad ruler who behaved like a nasty mixture of
Marquis de Sade, Ted Bundy, and Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the film's infamy will again seduce the curious, as
well as those who conclude that any film deemed so terrible must be
worth seeing, if only as a lark. Recently, Guccione said, ``Never
in the 20 years since it was released has an adult film of this
caliber been duplicated.'' Another generation of moviegoers will
soon learn why that's something we should all be thankful for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
