<HEADER>
A8872 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-COLUMN     09-28 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIT NEW MEXICO TO EXPERIENCE THE `ANCIENT ONES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANDELIER, N.M. _ Where goes the neighborhood?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows exactly what happened _ or why _ to the folks who
lived here in Frijoles Canyon, in what I like to call Beantown I
because ``frijoles'' translates as ``beans'' in Spanish, and they
were bean eaters. Like the people of Beantown II (a.k.a. Boston), a
settlement that appeared on a shore quite far to the east about 100
years after Beantown I was abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The townsfolk, Indians called Anasazi (``ancient ones'' in
Navajo), have been gone for about four centuries. Just picked up
and left their beautiful neighborhood, and wandered into history.
</P>
<P>
   How come? Were they evicted by heartless landlords who raised
the rents too high? Did they feel the beans would be greener and
taste better somewhere else? Might a mighty drought have driven
them away?
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. For rooms with status as well as a view, the deserted
penthouses along the salmon-toned canyon wall are hard to beat. I
could see a developer making a huge score here, turning them into
condos with running-everything-plus-TV-dishes. Only 45 miles from
Santa Fe, but more peaceful and lovelier.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one fortunate thing. The government got here first,
and this has been a national park among the peaks and mesas of the
Jemez Mountains since 1916. The V-shaped canyon is narrow and
green, blessed with a bustling creek, scented by juniper and
skyscraping ponderosa pine, and loaded with stillness. But the only
way to move in is to camp for a while.
</P>
<P>
   First camper, of Caucasian stock anyway, was the modern-day
namesake, Bandelier himself, amateur archeologist out of Highland,
Ill. An immigrant born in Switzerland, Adolph Bandelier was
supposed to follow his father as a banker. Instead he followed a
yen for the Southwest and cashed in spiritually. In 1880 he and a
Cochiti tribesman guide, Juan Jose Montoya, stumbled into Frijoles
Canyon and this original Beantown without much idea of where they
were going.
</P>
<P>
   But they were taken by it immediately. ``The grandest thing I
ever saw,'' Bandelier wrote. ``A magnificent growth of pines,
encina, alamos, and towering cliffs . . . the cliffs are vertical
on the north side, and their bases are, for a length, used for
dwellings.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Bandelier's early disciples was Charles Lummis, a
newspapering Harvard alumnus who, in 1884, had walked from
Cincinnati to the Pacific (3,507 miles in 145 days), and was
particularly intrigued by his perambulating through the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   They teamed up, a couple of macho men, as Lummis wrote:
``Thousands of miles of wilderness and desert we trudged, camped,
starved, shivered, learned . . . up and down pathless cliffs,
through tangled canyons, fording icy streams and ankle-deep sands .
. . no blankets, overcoats or other shelter . . . our commissary a
few cakes of sweet chocolate and a small sack of parched popcorn
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has changed. At least in terrain. But you can drive in
now, and don't have to stoic-it-out on that kind of grub. Nobody
will make fun of you if you bring a coat or tent. The ghosts of the
Anasazi, undoubtedly lurking, have been mumbling, ``There goes the
neighborhood!'' ever since Bandelier and Lummis trudged in.
</P>
<P>
   Residential foundations and leftover walls of a community called
Tyuonyi are visible amid undergrowth of the canyon floor. They were
excavated around the turn of the century by a dapper archeologist
in puttees and bow tie, Edgar Lee Hewett, who was drawn by
Bandelier's reports.
</P>
<P>
   More fascinating are the sky suites, reached by pathways and
ladders. Those are the choice locations, studio apartments and
duplexes facing south, holes in the wall favored by the sun and the
vistas, offering better security. A real estate agent's dream. Some
are permanently decorated with petroglyphs, figures of humans and
animals, by avant-garde artists of the time (circa 1300 to 1500).
</P>
<P>
   ``Better than any Trump Tower,'' says my friend, Aurelio.
``Sorry we can't get a lease. Don't you love Mother Nature as an
architect?''
</P>
<P>
   Madly. Moving closer, you see that the canyon wall isn't merely
a steep, plain barrier. Delicately pitted spires and domes arise to
accompany other rock formations, almost Gothic in some stretches,
and garnished with lavender wildflowers. The playful Spanish
architect, Gaudi, would have rejoiced.
</P>
<P>
   In the late afternoon sun the rusty rocks are becoming pink. The
place is serene and empty, although hummingbirds and ravens zip
about. Peeping into the low-ceilinged apartments, you imagine those
long-ago neighbors in their paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Whooomp! The reverie is shattered by an explosion, the
fluttering of thousands of wings. Squeaking and flapping, a brown
cloud of Mexican free-tailed bats is spewing from their living-room
crevice into the evening air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supper time, and they're going batty,'' says Aurelio. ``Or
buggy. That's what they'll dine on. Stink bugs and fungus beetles
are their meat. These bats will eat about 500 insects an hour, half
their weight. They're born with toes and thumbs so they can hang
out when they aren't eating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bon appetit!'' we shout to the crowded, disappearing cloud.
There go the neighbors, today's Beantown I inhabitants that don't
give the least damn for beans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
