<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE WILL READERS BE ON 2000 ARRIVAL? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Beverly Holmes isn't fretting about the exorbitant
cost of millennium-related events. Nor is she worried about
potential transportation snafus and Y2K computer failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing something unusual,'' writes Holmes, a Santa Fe,
Texas, resident. ``I'll be doing community service with Global
Volunteers in Mississippi from Dec. 26 to Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to be doing something useful and memorable when
the year 2000 arrives,'' Holmes continues. ``Global Volunteers will
have people working all over the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Minnesota-based company's Millennium Service Project
focuses on education, infrastructure and health-care projects
identified by people in host communities throughout the country.
(Information about specific destinations and costs is available on
the Internet at www.globalvolunteers.com/millmain.htm or by calling
800-487-1074.)
</P>
<P>
   Holmes has served twice previously in Tanzania, helping with
school construction.
</P>
<P>
   She was among readers who accepted our invitation to let us know
about their plans _ and concerns _ for millennium travel. Or
``moronium travel,'' as one reader, bound to official calendars,
dubs this celebration a year before the millennium actually
arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of responses:
</P>
<P>
   _ Most ambitious itinerary: ``I had this idea when I was in high
school in the mid-'80s and, luckily, I'll be able to make it
happen,'' writes Houstonian Pat Pearson. The agenda: ``Fly to
Australia, celebrate New Years 2000, hop on a plane early Jan. 1,
fly to Hawaii, arrive Dec. 31 (after crossing the International
dateline), celebrate New Years 2000 again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a group of nine people joining me on this little
adventure. We'll be some of the only people to celebrate two
millennium New Years. I certainly won't be around for the next
one.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Best surprise: Conroe, Texas, reader Nina Tannenbaum and her
husband, Daniel, will celebrate on Florianopolis, an island off the
Brazil coast south of Rio de Janeiro. ``We had been told that in
Brazil the custom is to wait for the New Year wearing white and
facing the ocean,'' Tannenbaum writes. ``I have therefore ordered a
white formal at a local shop. When the store called to let me know
that I needed to go in for the first fitting, the caller said ...
`for your wedding in December.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering that I have been married for more than 40 years, I
found that hilarious. I asked my husband, `Honey, would you like to
marry me all over again?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he answered with an automatic, `Sure!'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Most levity: ``I'm experiencing millennium madness,'' writes
Houstonian Lisa Bunse. ``The symptoms of my `Why 2K' illness:
dizziness (`2' many choices), acid indigestion (`2' much money')
and nervous fingers (`2' good to sound true.)''
</P>
<P>
   _ Most intriguing philosophy: Houstonian Bruce Godwin, seeking
to celebrate ``like no other party in history,'' selected Las Vegas
as the most appropriate venue. ``Where else to be but `Sin City?'''
Godwin writes. ``If it is going to be the end of the world as some
believe, the Devil himself will be riding down the strip in a
Cadillac convertible. And the casinos are not turning off those
slot machines even if Armageddon comes. If there is a power
failure, they all have generators.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Godwin continues, ``All of the hotels on the strip wanted
$700-$2,000 per night with a three-night minimum. After days of
calls and Internet searching, I found the Best Western in nearby
Henderson for $149. Granted, that's triple the normal rate, it's
kind of small and overlooks the highway but ... I guess I can
gamble the $3,000 I saved by not staying on the strip.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Biggest disappointment: ``My mother wanted our entire family
to celebrate New Year's Eve in her home on Long Island,'' writes
Houstonian Caryl Zimmerman. ``My mom and dad, their four children
and their families remarkably are still alive, and we wanted to
toast that fact together as we crossed over into the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, my husband was told that no one from his office
can leave Houston from December to January in case they encounter
Y2K computer problems. I wonder if other folks will have to accept
raising a glass to the new century with a loved one on the phone
instead of actually being there to clink it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Largest gathering: When Houstonian Nancee Sells and her
husband decided to celebrate the holiday at their condominium on
Kauai's north shore, they inquired if several friends wanted to
join them. ``We were overwhelmed by the response,'' writes Sells.
``We needed 28 units.''
</P>
<P>
   The condo resort has planned three days of festivities for the
group, including a New Year's Eve luau and fireworks display. ``Our
only complaint? Airlines,'' Sells writes. Because of unexpectedly
high air fares, some friends have canceled. ``But we still have 20
units reserved. The best part? Some of our closest friends, their
adult children and the grandchildren will be together for a truly
momentous occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Best bargain: Houstonian Sally Walker Davies and her husband
were determined to welcome 2000 in Jackson Hole, Wyo. But, she
writes, ``Prices for most properties were at least twice their
regular holiday rates. About the time we were giving up, we found
the perfect place on the Internet. It's called Teton Ranch. Two log
cabins ... 150 feet apart on a working cattle ranch, with beautiful
views of the western slope of the Tetons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The holiday rate was $350 per night for both cabins _ a
bargain. Even better, the owners are a treat. They've promised to
take us on a snowmobile to find the perfect tree; they've even
asked our son to help care for a new foal they are expecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a perfect way to end one century and begin another.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
