<HEADLINE>
THINK NEW YORK THIS FALL, WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York City is always a lively place to visit. And this fall
and winter are no exception.
</P>
<P>
   The theater scene is hot with 12 new shows opening this season
and six shows set for next spring. Thousands will make a pilgrimage
to the city for the holiday lights, shopping and shows, and, of
course, the Millennium celebration. Also on tap is the reopening in
October of the Art Deco Radio City Music Hall after a $70 million
renovation, new restaurants, and the reopening of the venerable
Russian Tea Room following a complete makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Sept. 26 at the Whitney Museum of American Art is ``The
American Century Part II,'' which traces the changing American
identity from the postwar years through the advent of Internet
technology. The New York Historical Society offers ``Cass Gilbert:
Ten Projects,'' a survey of the architect's most famous works that
have shaped the New York skyline. The Metropolitan Museum of Art
goes back to the first great era of Egyptian art with some 200
works in ``Egyptian Art in the Age of the Pyramids.'' On Nov. 20,
``Body Art: Marks of Identity'' opens at the American Museum of
Natural History. The exhibit focuses on body decoration through the
ages. On Nov. 14, the Jewish Museum opens ``Berlin Metropolis: Jews
and the New Culture, 1890-1918.'' The Morgan Library is featuring
one of the most extensive exhibitions on the life, political
aspirations, and achievements of George Washington. ``The Great
Experiment: George Washington and the American Republic'' will be
on view through Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Children will enjoy ``Body Odyssey,'' a trip through a gigantic
reproduction of the body at the Children's Museum of Manhattan.
They'll also like seeing the 300-500 free-flying tropical
butterflies at the Butterfly Conservatory, opening Oct. 9 at the
American Museum of Natural History. And don't forget Macy's
Thanksgiving Day Parade on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more going on. For the latest, call 800-NYC-VISIT
or check the Web site of the New York Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau,
www.nycvisit.com. If you need help during peak travel seasons, call
the hotel hot line at 800-846-ROOM.
</P>
<P>
   Making it easy to get around the city is the MTA Fun Pass, which
offers unlimited subway and bus access all day for $4. The Fun Pass
is available at the new Visitor Information Center (810 Seventh
Ave. at 53rd Street). Longer-stay passes are also available.
</P>
<P>
   New York City is also seeing a number of new hotels opening.
Among them are the Phillips Club (212-835-8800), a boutique hotel
on Manhattan's Upper West Side. Through Oct. 31, the hotel is
offering preview rates beginning at $270 for a junior suite; after
Oct. 31, the rate will be $400. The first Clarion Hotel in
Manhattan has opened. The Clarion Hotel Fifth Avenue (800-CLARION)
is near Grand Central Station and offers rates from $159-$350 a
night. Dylan, another boutique hotel, has opened in the former
Chemists' Club building at 52 East 41st St. Rooms begin at $295 a
night (212-338-0500). Citylife will have three hotels in the city
this fall: Habitat Hotel (rates beginning at $85, telephone
800-255-0842), near Radio City; ON THE AVE Hotel (rates begin at
$175, telephone 800-509-7598), at Broadway and 77th Street; and
Thirty Thirty, in Murray Hill at 30 East 30th St. (telephone
212-689-1900).
</P>
<P>
   While not new, the New Yorker, 34th Street and Eighth Avenue, is
promising holiday shoppers room rates starting at $149 a night,
which will leave money for shopping. Once the largest hotel in the
world, the 70-year-old New Yorker (800-764-4680) offers many rooms
with great views of the city's skyline.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're looking for yoga with an Irish touch, head for the
Fitzpatrick Family Group of Hotels (800-367-7701) _ the Fitzpatrick
Manhattan at 687 Lexington Ave. or the Fitzpatrick Grand Central
Hotel at 141 East 44th St. The hotels offer private yoga classes
for both those dedicated to the practice and beginners. The
sessions are taught by a native Dubliner, Yogi Paul Dallagham, who
uses techniques that can strengthen and calm the body.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Balloon Fiesta
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The largest ballooning event in the world takes place Oct. 2-10
in Albuquerque. The 1999 Kodak Albuquerque International Balloon
Fiesta will have more than 850 hot-air and gas balloons
participating. Three balloons will be from Massachusetts. The
fiesta has been called the world's most photographed event, with
weekends featuring more than 700 balloons in the sky at one time.
Also participating will be balloons from Canada _ the 30-foot-tall
Mountie and the Maple Leaf balloon is the only balloon to represent
a national emblem. For information, call the Albuquerque Visitors
Bureau at 800-284-2282.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vancouver exhibit
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out of the Mist, the first-ever comprehensive presentation on
the art, culture, and heritage of western Canada's Nuu-chah-nulth
nations, features more than 241 artifacts and images, many of which
have never been exhibited before. They are on view at the Royal
British Columbia Museum through April 30. The artifacts and stories
tell the history from 2000-3000 BC of the Nuu-chah-nulth aboriginal
people who lived along the West Coast of Vancouver Island. The
Empress, a Victorian landmark hotel, is offering an Out of the Mist
package including accommodations, breakfast, and exhibit tickets,
beginning at about $105. For information, call 800-441-1414.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Italy hot line
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For travelers to Italy during the Year 2000 Jubilee celebration,
the Italian Government Tourist Board has set up an information
telephone line that can be accessed daily between 8 a.m. and 11
p.m. The number is not available in the United States. The
toll-free number in Italy is 800-11-77-00. In addition, the
government has a Web site with information on both Italy and the
Jubilee celebrations: www.piuitalia2000.it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Early savings
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers heading to the Caribbean for a stay at Couples on
Jamaica or Swept Away on Negril next year can save up to $800 a
couple by booking by Nov. 24. A $500 savings is offered on bookings
made by Jan. 26. For information on these all-inclusive resorts,
call 800-COUPLES or 800-545-7937 for Swept Away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Barbecue festival
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's called the Super Bowl of barbecue competitions, and this
year it will be on Oct. 23 in Lynchburg, Tenn., a town known for
its whiskey. Lynchburg is home to the Jack Daniel Distillery,
America's oldest registered distillery. The distillery is in a
``dry'' area, so you can tour, but you can't buy a bottle of the
whiskey, except for a specially designed commemorative decanter,
allowed by a special act of the Tennessee Legislature in 1994.
While the competition is in the South, the barbecue is
international in flavor. Teams from around the country, as well as
Europe, Japan, and Canada will be competing. There also will be
games, music, and homemade Southern delectables, including fried
pies and roasted corn on the cob, for sale. For information on the
11th annual Jack Daniel's World Championship Invitational Barbecue,
call 615-340-1035.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
