<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Sept. 29:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FORTUNE (Shanghai) _ What would Mao say? Doings at the
Fortune 500 jamboree being held to mark the 50th anniversary of
Communist China, opening with speech from China's president, Jiang
Zemin. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Efforts to form a united
opposition collapse, probably killing the chance _ which was best
ever _ for the opposition to unseat PRI, the ruling party, from the
presidency in the July 2000 election. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-TOWN (Liquica, East Timor) _ News feature from deserted
coastal town secured by peacekeepers. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-REBEL (United Nations) _ An interview with the longtime
Timor independence leader and Indonesian prisoner, Jose Alexandre
Gusmo. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Dateline to kum) _ At least two Serbs are killed
and dozens wounded in a grenade attack at a Kosovo market. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-U.N. (United Nations) _ The Yugoslav foreign minister
demands $100 billion in reparations for the damage caused his
country by NATO. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-REFUGEES (Moscow) _ The refugee crisis grows as Russia
continues its attacks on Chechnya. The neighboring region,
Ingushetia, appeals to the U.N. for help with refugees. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on spending bills in
Congress. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   PATIENT-RIGHTS (Washington) _ House Republicans wrangle over the
patient bill of rights legislation. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRAYER (Washington) _ President Clinton at the prayer
breakfast: still working with spiritual counselors, and is moved by
the grace of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to take another
federalism case, one challenging the Violence Against Women Act,
which gives victims of certain types of violent attacks the right
to file civil suits in federal court. Plus a roundup of other court
action. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HMO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to take a
case from the Midwest centered on the issue of a patient's ability
to sue an HMO. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-MUSEUM (Washington) _ A century after the end of the
devastating Indian wars, a place of honor is finally extended to
the nation's Native Americans as ground is broken on the Mall for a
museum that tribal leaders vow will be filled with their
bittersweet history, ``even if it tells a sad story, even if it's a
hard story to look at.'' By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CONDORS (Los Angeles) _ Now that condors have been
reintroduced into the wild, they are causing mischief, ripping up
deck furniture and doormats, even tearing through a screen door and
into a bedroom. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BEATTY-POLITICS (Los Angeles) _ Warren Beatty will give a speech
Wednesday night in which he will announce that he will run or won't
announce anything at all. Meanwhile, his candidacy is being taken
seriously in some liberal quarters. By Todd s. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-HEALTH (Washington) _ In a major speech on heath care,
Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley offers a $65 billion
plan for universal access to health insurance that would require
coverage for all children, with subsidies for families that cannot
afford it. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-POLICY (Dateline to kum, S.C.) _ Sen. John McCain lays
out his views on the military and foreign policy. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-AIRPORT (Atlanta) _ With 73.5 million passengers last
year, Hartsfield Atlanta International is now, incontestably, the
world's busiest airport. Hartsfield has also had a reputation as
one of the smoothest-running airports. But with its phenomenal
growth have come flight delays, parking shortages and clogged
traffic. So while Hartsfield may offer a shining example of how an
airport can become a giant and how a city can transform itself into
a global crossroads, it also provides a cautionary tale about the
downside of the boom in air travel. As more and more people take to
the skies, Atlanta and other cities have little choice but to make
do with existing airports, for the economics of building new ones
are increasingly prohibitive. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-HAMBRECHT (New York) _ Chase Manhattan agrees to buy the
investment banking firm Hambrecht &AMP; Quist for $1.35 billion in
cash. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-IMPACT (San Francisco) _ What the Chase deal means for
Hambrecht and its relationship with technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-IPOS (Undated) _ Looking at developments in plans by the
New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq to offer shares to the public.
Richard Grass, chief executive of the Big Board, and Frank Zarb,
chief of the National Association of Securities Dealers, testify at
a Senate Banking hearing. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTIC-MONTHLY (New York) _ More on the Atlantic sale and who
the new owners are. Also looking at what future, if any, there is
for it and similar magazines. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Jane
L. Levere.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-CHINA (Hong Kong) _ America Online has teamed up with
China.com Corp. to start an Internet service in Hong Kong. But it
is mainland China, with an on-line market projected to quadruple
from to 16.1 million in 2003 from 3.8 million users this year, that
is clearly AOL's target, despite recent concern over what Beijing's
policy is on foreign investment in Internet companies. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANK (Tokyo) _ The Japanese government and the U.S.
investment group Ripplewood Holdings announce the $1.4 billion sale
of the failed Long-Term Credit Bank. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-TELECOM (Rome) _ Telecom Italia, under new owners
Olivetti, plans to reorganize into two operating companies. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-PAPER (Undated) _ Robert Rivard takes himself out of
consideration for top Miami Herald editing job. By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2 p.m., stocks were modestly down. The
Dow Jones industrial was off 173 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 21 and
the Nasdaq composite index down 52 points. The yield on the 30-year
bond was at 6.06 percent. European markets were also lower, with
London down 0.65 percent and Frankfurt down 1.68 percent. The
Nikkei closed up 3 percent and Hong Kong's Hang Seng ended up 0.66
percent. The dollar was at 106.41 yen. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
