<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL BLOCK WAS MENTAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one will ever know what went through the mind of Artax when
he looked up in the stretch at Pimlico during Preakness Day in May
and saw a man standing in his path. The man threw dirt at Artax as
jockey Jorge Chavez struggled to keep the 4-year-old colt, the
odds-on favorite in the Maryland Breeders' Cup, from trampling his
attacker.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more bizarre episodes in racing, the man was
arrested, and Artax, who fell back from second to fifth, was
declared by the stewards to have run for purse money only, meaning
all bets on him were refunded. Artax's running line for that race
in the Daily Racing Form reads, ``Impeded by patron at
eighth-pole.''
</P>
<P>
   If psychology could work on an equine, Artax would have been a
challenging patient. The son of Marquetry had come into the May
15th race off a sensational victory May 2 at Aqueduct in the Grade
I Carter Handicap, in which he had run one of the fastest 7-furlong
clockings in history at 1:20, shattering the track record and
earning a speed figure that was off the charts. However, after the
race in Maryland, he lost five straight times _ culminating in a
fifth-place finish in the Forego at Saratoga Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, Artax proved he had cleared his head, as he
whistled to victory for the first time since the incident, winning
the Grade I, $250,000 Vosburgh Stakes at Belmont Park by better
than 3 lengths in 1:21 3/5 for 7 panels. The old Artax was back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke a little slow, but he recovered pretty fast,'' said
Chavez. ``I knew we were setting fast fractions, but I didn't want
to fight him. He's a tough horse to ride. He dug in and proved he's
one of the best sprinters in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Artax, who is owned by Ernie Paragallo and trained by Louis
Albertrani, was off at 4-1 ($10.60 to win) and beat a top opponent
in Crafty Friend, the winner of the Forego and the 4-5 favorite in
the Carter. Crafty Friend, who was ridden by Gary Stevens, chased
Artax through a blazing half mile of :44 3/5, then faded to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole game with Artax is the break,'' said Paragallo. ``If
he breaks, they can't beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, there's a man standing in the stretch waiting
to toss a fistful of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Appeal' is successful
</P>
<P>
   Another outstanding sprinter had a big day Saturday, as
Successful Appeal captured the $250,000 Kentucky Cup Sprint at
Turfway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Away at 3-1 ($8.40 to win), with Edgar Prado aboard, Successful
Appeal powered his way past the extremely fast Five Star Day, the
3-5 choice under Alex Solis, to tally by 6 legnths in 1:09 2/5 for
6 furlongs. A 3-year-old son of Valid Appeal, Successful Appeal,
who is tained by John Kimmel, had finished third behind Forestry,
trained by Bob Baffert, and Five Star Day in the King's Bishop at
Saratoga Aug. 28. That race saw 6 furlongs run in 1:07 3/5, faster
than the track record of 1:08, on the way to a final clocking of
1:21 for 7 furlongs. But there was no stopping Successful Appeal at
Turfway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a little father back, but he went to the
leaders on his own,'' said Prado. ``He took the lead early in the
stretch, and I hadn't even asked him. He found another gear and
went right past them.''
</P>
<P>
   Five Star Day, trained by Beau Greely, has raced only six times
and remains extremely promising. ``They kept pressing him, and
wouldn't let him get away, and he got a little bit tired,'' said
Alex Solis, who rode Five Star Day, a 3-year-old son of Carson
City. ``But my colt is maturing with every start, and I'm not the
least bit disappointed in him. He's right on schedule for the
Breeders' Cup (Nov. 6 at Gulfsteam Park).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo may return Wednesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apprentice jockey Norberto Arroyo Jr. escaped serious injury in
a fall during the seventh race at Suffolk Downs Sunday, and he
hopes to return to riding Wednesday. Arroyo was aboard J.J.'s
Tarjoner when his mount was bumped while contending for the lead in
the early going of the 5-furlong sprint over grass. The horse lost
his action, and Arroyo was tossed off, taking a frightening tumble.
Arroyo was taken to Massachusetts General Hospital but released
Sunday night after X-rays proved negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very lucky,'' said Max Hall, the agent for the
20-year-old Arroyo. ``He's just real sore in the shoulder area, but
he should be back soon, and we're pointing for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He landed on his shoulder at the point of impact. We were
afraid he had broken his collarbone or dislocated his shoulder, but
the X-rays said he was OK. He's young, and he heals fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo won 14 races at Rockingham Park during the just-concluded
meeting, and Hall is hoping he'll have an outstanding meet at
Suffolk. ``I'm expecting big things from him,'' he said. ``He has a
very bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the stewards Monday suspended jockey Gary Birzer,
whose mount, Amborse Express, hit J.J.'s Tarjoner from the outside,
for 10 days ``for careless riding, causing interference, impeding
another horse, which resulted in the fall of another jockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Birzer's suspension will run from Thursday through Oct. 9,
inclusive. Birzer, who has ridden at Fonner Park in Nebraska and
the Woodlands in Kansas, had just switched his tack to Suffolk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Picking up $100,000
</P>
<P>
   Patrons will have a chance to qualify for an ultimate prize of
$100,000, as Suffolk Downs hosts a preliminary round of the
National Handicapping Contest Saturday. The contest is sponsored by
the Daily Racing Form and the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association, with the finals set for Jan. 7-8 at the MGM Grand
hotel in Las Vegas. The qualifying round consists of win wagering
only on the live Suffolk card, with bets coming from a mythical
bankroll of $1,000. Money can be managed as the players choose, and
they may bet as many as nine races or as few as one. The top four
scorers will each win a trip to Las Vegas for the finals. There is
a $2 fee to enter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from racetrack publicity departments and from the Daily
Racing Form was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
