<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-RYAN-COLUMN     09-28 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYDER CUP MAY BE OUR SHINIEST TREASURE YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The twentysomething guy at the restaurant Sunday night
spoke for multitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even a golf fan,'' he said, ``but I couldn't stop
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The overnight ratings revealed that when Justin Leonard made the
fateful 45-foot putt on the 17th hole, a staggering 42 percent of
all Greater Boston TV sets were tuned into the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The tall, well-dressed guy with a TV credential clutched his
little American flag as he watched Leonard make the big putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fantastic,'' said Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Diehard golf fans, casual golf fans, and non-golf fans all found
themselves swept up in Sunday afternoon's Ryder Cup excitement.
What took place at that expanse of heavenly Brookline real estate
reminded us why so many millions worldwide satisfy a special
emotional need through organized sport. There is a potential
exhilaration in human-vs.-human competition that simply makes one
feel alive. People not tuned into sport can lead very fulfilling
lives, but there is a certain feeling inherent in sports
competition that is simply not replicated in any other form of
human endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, the Ryder Cup was a polite, one-sided golfing
competition matching the best United States players against the
best players from Britain and Ireland. The United States so
dominated the competition that, in order to save the event from
utter redundancy, the opposing team was expanded in 1979 to include
players from any country in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The USA continued with resounding victories in 1979 and 1981,
but things began to change in 1983. In the last nine Ryder Cups,
the tally is 4-4-1, and the Europeans actually lead in total
points, 128-124. By any measure, the Ryder Cup now stands for
legitimate sporting competition.
</P>
<P>
   Few outside what was then the tight little world of golf cared
until the Americans started losing. Then came the '90s, and the
exponential growth of sports/business marriages. Golf has always
catered to a high-end clientele _ check out the ads on any Sunday
PGA Tour telecast _ and so it was only natural that as general
interest in the sport grew, the Ryder Cup, the premier
international golf competition, would become a huge marketing
enterprise, culminating in the appalling display of spending for
spending's sake we had on view at The Country Club this past week.
</P>
<P>
   As the shadows fell on one of the truly great golf courses in
the world late Sunday afternoon, however, no one was obsessing any
longer about the corporate excess, and what real good might have
been done with all those loose dollars being strewn around town
during the week. No, 100 percent of the interest was where we'd all
like to think it should be _ on the 24 superb players in question
and their fierce, dignified competition.
</P>
<P>
   There was a reason that Hall of Famers like John Havlicek, Dave
DeBusschere, George Brett, and, of course, Jordan could think of no
other place they'd rather be at that moment than at The Country
Club. Their very presence made a mockery of the golf mockers. These
superb athletes, and countless others of their ilk, have tried to
master this fiendish sport and have not been able to do so. It is
quite possible that no man on the planet who is not being paid to
do so has spent more time on the golf course in the past two years
than Jordan, arguably as fine a pure athlete as our society has
ever produced. He has not come close to being a truly accomplished
golfer. He is better than most people, but he is to the 24 men he
was watching Sunday as a second-division Italian League basketball
player is to him.
</P>
<P>
   To play this sport well, a man must have well-rounded golfing
skills and a man must be able to conquer his nerves. And the
crucible in the sport is the Ryder Cup, where what you do matters,
not just to you but to 11 other men, as well. Even the best players
find that this extra element creates exponentially more pressure on
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most emotional thing I've ever gone through in
golf,'' said Hal Sutton, who, at age 41, and with a personally
tumultuous 12 years between Ryder Cup appearances, was the
consensus team MVP by winning 3 1/2 points. ``Saturday night, I
prayed for peace of mind, and I had it on Sunday. And when it was
over, I had to fight back tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Any great golfer is a Sunday player, because that is the day
when the money is made. What we all saw two days ago was a group of
inspired Sunday players demonstrating to both the Europeans and the
gallery just who they are. They were hitting greens they weren't
hitting on Friday and Saturday and sinking putts from Cleveland
Circle and the Chestnut Hill Mall.
</P>
<P>
   As athletes and competitors, they had a lot to prove. They knew
what was being written and said (mostly by NBC's Johnny Miller)
about them. They knew what the Europeans thought of them. They
simply made up their minds to get that Cup back, if only so they
could live with themselves. Small wonder, therefore, that they
plain and simple lost it on the 17th when Leonard sank his historic
putt.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a breach of golf's rigid decorum to celebrate before Jose
Maria Olazabal was able to attempt a 20-footer that could have tied
the match and set up a dramatic 18th hole? Without question. But
was it a sin against mankind, and was it, as some Europeans
suggested, ``disgusting''? Oh, please. Some Americans might
consider the aggravatingly slow play of most Europeans
``disgusting.'' And was it the reason the noble Spaniard missed the
lengthy putt? Absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for Tom Lehman and Davis Love III, each of whom
spoke the truth by accusing all the Europeans _ players,
journalists, and fans alike _ of having predictably short memories.
The atmosphere at Valderrama two years ago wasn't exactly warm and
fuzzy for the Americans. Anyone who has ever been privileged to see
any American team in action elsewhere, whether it's the Olympics,
the World Championships, or any individual international
competition, knows that the fan behavior is often beyond appalling
and the overall conditions are so stacked against Americans that to
suggest otherwise is simply laughable.
</P>
<P>
   The European players should be flattered. The only reason the
Americans were so full of spontaneous emotion was that the Euros
were so damn hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   For so long the idea of the Ryder Cup coming right here was an
abstract. The one thing we all assumed was that anything written
beforehand would be exaggerated, because events like this almost
never live up to their billing. How wonderfully rare and precious
as sports fans it is to be proven wrong on such a fundamental
issue.
</P>
<P>
   What took place on Sunday afternoon might go down as the best
day of sport competition that will take place
(itals)anywhere(unitals) this calendar year. Twenty-four
accomplished artists made some sticks and a few dimpled little
balls into instruments that manipulated our emotions. It all
happened right here, and on a spectacular afternoon that also made
nature an active contributor to the drama.
</P>
<P>
   Really. How lucky can we get?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
