<HEADER>
A8888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-28 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN WORKS ON HIS SNAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Terry Glenn is beyond wanting to have big games. He's
now into perfection. On the 45-yard pass he caught to set up the
Patriots' only touchdown in their 16-14 win over the Giants Sunday
night, he wished that he didn't have to leap for the ball, that he
could have stayed on his feet and gone in for the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great call by (Ernie) Zampese,'' said Glenn Monday.
``We were around midfield and they were in a Cover-2. They were
pressing us and Drew (Bledsoe) did a quick count and Shawn
(Jefferson) and I ran a double post. Shawn was running it to the
inside and I was running it to the outside. I ran and took the
safety out of deep post and he jumped on Shawn and Drew made a
great, great throw. I saw it leave his hand and as it made its way
through the crowd, I said, `I've got to catch this ball.' I wish I
didn't have to leave my feet because I would have gone in.''
</P>
<P>
   So it has now come down to perfecting these big plays for Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   His health is there. His focus is there.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be, for evey Sunday is a war against another
cornerback or safety. Usually he's double-teamed, but on Sunday
night he was getting hacked by Jason Sehorn, the former All-Pro
corner, and he didn't like it one bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get past 5 yards you can't touch me, but he was
getting away with it a lot,'' said Glenn. ``At one point I went to
the ref. I'm usually not a big complainer when I'm on field because
I like to be physical as well, but he starts to chuck you beyond
that 5 yards and it's not legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really bothered me is if they let him get away with that
stuff in our stadium, what's he going to get away with in his?''
</P>
<P>
   One time Glenn got knocked off his feet _ well beyond the 5-yard
area, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to run a crossing route,'' said Glenn. ``I know I
was over the 5-yard area and the guy just pushed. That's a weak
play. If you can't play the game without pushing and shoving and
grabbing and cheating, maybe you shouldn't be out there. At least
it tells me one thing: He can't stay with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn knew that Sehorn was playing for the first time since the
1997 season (because of injuries) and wanted to take advantage, but
he also wanted to do it within the confines of the offense Zampese
had designed for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said he started beating Sehorn on slants and Sehorn was
``shaded to my outside because he didn't want me to get outside.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Glenn got the better of it.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there may not be a better receiver in the AFC,
perhaps the game. Glenn has caught 19 passes and he came within 5
yards of having his third consecutive 100-yard game.
</P>
<P>
   But the thing he wants to emphasize is that the team has won
three straight without being at its best yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 3-0, but we haven't played our best game yet,'' said
Glenn. ``We hope it'll come very soon _ next week, maybe. But it's
way too early to start thinking we're a great team. I hope my
teammates feel the same way. We're not getting too high on it. It's
so early that you can still go 3-13 if we don't keep our
composure.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn likes the fact that the offense doesn't crawl into a shell
when trailing. The Patriots have been down in all three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very important that we always be the ones who are
attacking,'' said Glenn. ``You should counterattack them at all
cost. They should be trying to stop you from doing what you want to
do. We were doing that even Sunday night. The deep post route was
an example of going right at them even though we wanted to run the
ball. As a wide receiver you want to pass the ball a lot, but when
you're running game is working, you've got to keep with it because
it can set up the pass and set up a play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll had called the Giants game a potential trap
for the Patriots, and Glenn said Sunday's matchup against the
Browns has all the makings of one as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell into it at St. Louis last year,'' said Glenn.
``Everybody's telling us it's a game we'll win easy, and when we
got down there, we got our butts worked over. We have to have our
feet on the ground and approach it like we approached the Giants
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think we've been involved in enough of these games that
we'll prepare hard and take it like any other strong NFL opponent.
Chris Palmer was a good coordinator and he did a great job here
with the quarterbacks. He gave me a couple of pointers, too. So
he's a guy we know and we can't let that affect the way we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Sunday night's game, Glenn was doing a bit of sneak
preview work on the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a good secondary,'' said Glenn. ``Guys like Corey
Fuller, Marquez Pope, Antonio Langham, they're pretty good. We have
to stay in our attack mode and take it right at them. That's what
we do best, I think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8890 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-HOLLEY-COUM     09-28 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-HOLLEY-COUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACRO EVENT WAS A MICROCOSM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)Note to all readers: After you finish this story, I would
appreciate it if you would contact your Nobel Prize sources and put
in a good word for me. Thanks. Knew I could count on you. See you
at my Nobel party.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   _ M.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Ryder Cup week changed my life, I am now ready to change
the world. If that surprises you, imagine how I feel. Until last
week, my ultimate goal was to make the cover of Time and the
National Enquirer in the same week. Now I am campaigning for a
prize that has been awarded to the likes of Albert Einstein, Toni
Morrison, and my man the Dalai Lama. This wouldn't have been
possible without my week of golf at The Country Club in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   Einstein's theory: E (EQ) mc squared.
</P>
<P>
   My theory: All square.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, I can highlight all aspects of American culture
simply by sharing my golf week, a week that ended with the 12-man
American team winning the 33d Ryder Cup from Europe, 14 1/2-13 1/2.
Through the All Square Theory (AST), you can learn about American
language, facial expressions, business, love, triumph, golf,
heroism, contradiction, cuisine, and celebration _ all while
wearing your golf shoes.
</P>
<P>
   So you will understand how Michael Jordan voluntarily sat under
a tree with George Bush, even though Jordan didn't want to be near
the former president while he was in the White House. You will know
why a nearly intoxicated man named Fluff stumbled out of the
clubhouse Sunday, kissed a female police officer, and was not
arrested. You will know why I, like thousands of golf fans in the
area, will no longer be able to function without the BBC. You will
even understand how some parking lot attendants were able to charge
_ and get _ $75 for parking spaces, even though you can park
illegally and get a ticket for the same price.
</P>
<P>
   If you let me tell you about the most recent Ryder Cup, you will
understand American culture. (Aside to high school and college
students: I'm working on getting the weeklong AST factored into
curricula so you can get credit for participation.) So, please,
read on and remember our deal. You'll make that Nobel call for me,
right? And when you come to the party, don't bring any gifts. Just
come with your clubs and we'll play 36.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The man's name is Len and he is not quite an American prophet.
He is from southeast London. He wears a plastic hat emblazoned with
the flag of Great Britain. His shirt says, ``London to Boston _
Ryder Cup.'' I sit next to Len and eight of his friends, all of
them wearing identical shirts and hats. They are jubilant as we
ride a bus from The Country Club to the Forest Hills T stop
Saturday night. Europe has a 10-6 lead over the Americans. To lose
the Cup, the Europeans will have to drop about 75 percent of their
matches the next day. That is so unlikely that Len and his friends
are singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand up if you love Eur-ope!'' one of them sings, standing up
as he does it. Len stands up and sings, too. Eventually he sits
down again and we talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were around American fans all day,'' Len says, ``and
everybody was all right. We said things to each other, but it was
all good-natured.''
</P>
<P>
   I should have warned Len: Many American sports fans, especially
in the East, are Dobermans. There are moments when they are serene,
but there is always the chance that they will turn on you. When
their teams trail badly, they often attack those they are rooting
for; when their teams are close, they remain in attack mode, but
the target becomes the opposition and opposing fans. If the
American team wins, the fans eventually feel a sense of remorse for
their behavior and overcompensate by apologizing too much. But the
contradiction is that it is not truly malicious; it just looks and
sounds that way. Especially when you see a guy with a beer in one
hand, a miniature flag in the other, foaming at the mouth, and
screaming, ``Go home, Euro.'' The same heckler could see a European
player at a restaurant and have a pleasant conversation with him.
</P>
<P>
   How could I explain all of that to Big Len? He was having too
much fun. And I loved listening to him speak. I wasn't the only one
fascinated with the British accent.
</P>
<P>
   Many people will tell you that the best investment of the week
cost $12. That was the price for a small transistor radio, which
many used to listen to the BBC broadcast of the Ryder Cup. Even
now, I am fighting the urge to use words such as ``snappy,''
``smashing,'' and ``marvelous.'' And anytime someone mentions Colin
Montgomerie, I want to shout, ``Well struck, Monty!'' If I can't
win the Nobel Prize, I'd like to have my own sports talk show on
BBC. The BBC rules.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Len and Montgomerie would eventually hear American words
that are rarely broadcast on BBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even repeat them to you,'' Montgomerie said Sunday
night. ``Some of the things said out there were disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, but not all. On Sunday, a couple of Americans had a
conversation about Andrew Coltart's lost ball on No. 9. They said
it should have never been lost. And on the BBC, American
broadcaster Charlie Jones apologized on behalf of all Americans for
rude members of the gallery and the lost ball.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, ready to test out the theories?
</P>
<P>
   1. Golf events may be for the rich, but you can get rich if
you're in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   That was true for anyone living in the Brookline area. Some lots
near Cleveland Circle charged $20 for parking. The closer you got
to The Country Club, the higher the prices went, topping off at
$75.
</P>
<P>
   2. The majority of American men like blondes.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is not a judgment, just an observation. From
Tiger Woods to Phil Mickelson to captain Ben Crenshaw, the
companions/wives were blonde.
</P>
<P>
   3. To be American is to be contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, I headed toward the Boston Globe tent. I wore a Globe
press pass. It didn't matter; I was denied by a security guard.
Imagine: Globe employee barred from Globe tent. ``Sorry,'' said the
guard, ``can't let you in.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, Jordan sat under a tree, chatted with President
Bush and his wife, Barbara, and watched Woods putt on No. 11. When
he played for the Bulls, Jordan made it known that he didn't want
to be close to Bush. A few days ago, he joked with him and sat next
to him. Keep in mind that there is no judgment in that statement,
just an example of what it means to be an American. Bush, a staunch
opponent of hardcore rap music, once had dinner with a member of
the controversial rap group N.W.A.
</P>
<P>
   4. If you think it is the way it ``should be,'' it probably will
not be.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston paid a total of $1 million for its tent and to rent
out Charles River CC. You wonder what would happen if it spent $1
million _ obviously a pittance _ on a few families that it rejected
for home loans.
</P>
<P>
   5. Sometimes it's OK to be nearly drunk in front of the cops and
to kiss them, too.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't happen often. But after the US completed its
stunning comeback, caddie Fluff Cowan was heading toward the area
used for closing ceremonies. He went over to a fan who was holding
a beer and yelling, ``God bless the USA.'' Cowan gave him a
high-five. He then walked down a path that was roped off and
guarded by police. He reversed his direction and kissed a female
officer on her cheek. She laughed and shook her head.
</P>
<P>
   6. Americans love comebacks and politics, and often draw their
inspiration from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After Justin Leonard made a 45-foot putt to clinch a half-point
for the US and, eventually the Ryder Cup, he was mobbed around the
17th green. The Americans reacted on 17 as if they were members of
a football team, celebrating a win over State U. Later, after fans
waved American flags and chanted ``USA,'' Crenshaw (a Texan) talked
about what led to his team's revival.
</P>
<P>
   The captain said he called on Texas Gov. George W. Bush to talk
with the team. The governor read a speech from the 1800s _ a speech
given at the Alamo, which is in San Antonio. Which, of course, is
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful speech,'' Crenshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked how he came to know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little kid in Texas knows about the Alamo,'' he
answered.
</P>
<P>
   7. Never fret over the menu at an American party: Have
hamburgers and hot dogs available and you'll satisfy three-quarters
of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was that the case at The Country Club, but the burgers
were $5.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, at about 12:30 a.m., a few Europeans stood outside
the Four Seasons Hotel _ where the teams were staying _ and sang a
few songs. The night before, caddies from both countries did the
same thing at the Brookline Holiday Inn. On Sunday afternoon, there
were complaints of disgusting behavior all around. By early Monday
morning, some of the same people who leveled the charges were
drinking together. That, friends, is American golf.
</P>
<P>
   All square?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
