<HEADLINE>
HURRICANES NEED STIRRING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe East Carolina should join the Big East. Then again maybe
not. After Saturday's improbable 27-23 victory over Miami, the
Pirates are 5-0 overall and 2-0 vs. Big East teams (the other win
was against West Virginia).
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes coach Butch Davis has two weeks to rebuild his team's
confidence for a trip to Tallahassee to face No. 1 Florida State
Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointed,'' said Davis in Monday's weekly Big East
conference call. ``Very disappointed. We missed an awful lot of
opportunities in the first half. And those kind of things almost
always come back and haunt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more surprising was the way the Hurricanes lost, giving up
a fourth-quarter lead. It was only the second time in 157 games
that Miami has lost after being ahead after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   After this, which followed the last-minute loss to Penn State in
the Orange Bowl two weeks ago, Davis will have to rebuild the
psyche of his team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A mountain of woes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia, coming off a 30-7 loss to Syracuse, remains in
the doldrums. ``We're killing ourselves as a team,'' said coach Don
Nehlen, who now must worry about seeing Navy's option offense
Saturday. ``We're making too many mistakes.'' The last time West
Virginia started 1-3 was 1994, when it rebounded to win six of its
next seven games and earn a bowl bid . . . Virginia Tech continues
to rise in the rankings, jumping to seventh in the coaches' poll
and eighth in the writers' poll, the highest it has ever been
ranked. It still remains the team to beat in the Big East. ``I'm
not too worried about where we are (in the polls),'' said Tech
coach Frank Beamer, whose team takes on state rival Virginia
Saturday. ``We're coming along,'' said Beamer, ever so cautious.
``We have to be more consistent on offense.'' . . . One good note
for Miami: True freshman running back Clinton Portis made his first
career start against East Carolina and rushed for 147 yards on 27
carries, the most rushing yards ever for a true freshman . . .
Pittsburgh, which was idle last week, hosts Temple Saturday. At
2-1, the Panthers already have matched their win total of a year
ago . . . Temple continues to have problems scoring. After
Saturday's 34-0 rout by Marshall, the Owls are 0-4 and have scored
a total of 15 points this season . . . Not much better off is
Rutgers (0-3), which has yet to lead for a single second this
season . . . One of the reasons Pittsburgh has won two of its first
three is its ability to protect quarterback John Turman. A year
ago, Pittsburgh had allowed 19 sacks in three games. This season,
that total is three, best in the Big East . . . Boston College has
a chance to go 4-0 for only the second time since 1992 . . . When
Syracuse faces Tulane Saturday, it will be Paul Pasqualoni's 100th
game as coach of the Orangemen. During his tenure, Syracuse has
averaged 8.5 wins per season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
