<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8916 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-28 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER CLOSE CALL FOR THE NINERS' QUARTERBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ According to the recipient, this was Concussion
Lite, a quick hit, a flash of pain and disorientation, and then
back to normalcy. Steve Young said he didn't feel groggy this time.
He didn't feel nauseated, either.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could say the same thing. When the ABC cameras showed
him lying on the ground Monday night during the San Francisco
49ers' 24-10 victory at Arizona, half-curled up on his side, eyes
closed behind his face mask, body completely motionless, my stomach
roiled.
</P>
<P>
   Is there such a thing as a mild concussion? Medically, yes.
Emotionally, for an audience watching an athlete imitate a corpse,
even for a few seconds, the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Deese, the 49ers' multipurpose offensive lineman, was on
the field when two blitzing Arizona Cardinals knocked Young out.
``I didn't see him move, so I said, `Hey, are you all right?' and
he didn't answer,'' Deese said. ``But it couldn't have been very
long. The trainers came out and said `Steve?' And he said:
`Yeah.'''
</P>
<P>
   Deese once watched a high school opponent die on the football
field _ a defensive tackle who ran into the pile, on an ordinary
play. ``Then he came out and collapsed, and he never got up
again,'' Deese said. ``Any time you see something like that, it's
frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking as a football player, as someone who has seen a
lot of fallen colleagues. The problem with football players _ and
the beauty of them _ is that they take agony for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Ask any of the 49ers to recall the worst moment they've seen in
defensive tackle Bryant Young's career, and they're sure to say the
Monday night last year when he snapped his leg and nearly lost his
career. It was a hideous moment, but for me, the worst was when he
passed out at Lambeau Field almost three years ago and didn't move.
For a second, I thought he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   For another second, I thought he might be paralyzed from the
neck down. By comparison, last year's broken leg seemed mild.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing that happens to the head or spine can really be
called ``mild.'' Steve Young says he understands that now, better
than in his foolhardy past, when he begged to be let back into a
game against Tampa Bay after his third concussion in 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get less cavalier about it (as you get older),'' the
quarterback said. He has plans for his retirement. He's even
willing to use the word now, to talk about possibly running a
legal-aid foundation, or an Internet company, or both. ``When I
retire, it's going to be wonderful. I don't want any ill effects.''
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't his own best guardian. He has a neurologist he
trusts. Just as important, he has a coach who has wised up a lot
since that dreadful day in Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mariucci, the 49ers coach, put Young back in that game two
years ago. It was his first game as a head coach in the NFL, and he
didn't know how to say no. This time, he did. When the quarterback
didn't get up, Mariucci didn't care that Young recovered his wits
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to get up right away,'' Mariucci said. ``He was
saying `Get me up, get me up, get me up.' Everybody was keeping him
down. He didn't want to make a scene. He didn't want to
overdramatize anything.''
</P>
<P>
   They let Young up, but Mariucci didn't let him back into the
game, even when the quarterback asked. The coach knew almost
immediately that he wouldn't take that chance. He wanted to be
conservative. He said that he told the team doctor as much and that
he told Young that ``I love him too much to put him back in.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were leading 17-0 at the time, so the decision seemed
easy then. But in the second half, when the offense sputtered and
Arizona pulled to within a touchdown, Mariucci said he never
wavered. ``He was not going back in under any circumstances,
whether we were winning or losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the decisions he has made as a head coach, the ones that
he second-guesses the most are the ones that put Young back into
the Tampa Bay game and Jerry Rice back on the field 3 1/2 months
after he tore his anterior cruciate ligament in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This concussion could have presented more of a dilemma. Young
did seem remarkably alert afterward, and during the first half
Monday night, he looked more precise and controlled than in the
Niners' two previous games. He didn't force things. He got decent
protection. And he opened the game with some vintage passes to
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   There was virtually no hint of the battering he took a week ago
from the Saints. He seemed refreshed. And at least once, he seemed
adolescently reckless. Scrambling up the middle, he passed the
first-down marker, then kept going, refusing to slide to safety.
Instead, he heaved himself head-first into a cluster of Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that because the offense had sputtered the last two
weeks, he had promised himself that ``we were going to move the
ball this week, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Young made another promise. If his body
needs to retire, ``I think I'll know,'' he said, slowly,
thoughtfully.
</P>
<P>
   But will he? Can a man vow to do anything to move a football,
even throw his head into a play that has already yielded a first
down, and just as fervently commit to taking care of himself?
</P>
<P>
   I don't trust Young on that second promise. He wouldn't even say
that he was knocked out on Monday night. He said he had his eyes
closed because he was ``trying to find myself.''
</P>
<P>
   So who decides how much is too much? Doctors can do some of the
work, but they can be hampered by a patient who gives rosy accounts
of his symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The news media? We all thought Young was finished in 1996, when
his head took two terrible blows over two weeks. Last season, at
age 37, he was playing some of the best football of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The coach? He knows how much his quarterback despises the
melodrama that envelopes every bashing he takes. When someone asked
Mariucci whether Young's future flashed before his eyes on that
horrible play Monday night, he said ``no,'' in true, stoic football
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   A second later, he realized how ridiculous that sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, changing his answer, no longer pretending. He
said he saw what everyone else saw, what Young couldn't _ or
wouldn't _ see. The quarterback is too tough. We just might feel
his pain more than he does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
