<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIBIOTICS-LIVESTOCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STUDIES LINK ANTIBIOTICS IN FOOD TO DRUG RESISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Studies from the United States and Europe
support the conclusion that the widespread use of antibiotics in
livestock feed is leading to drug-resistant disease in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Salmonella and campylobacter, two food-borne organisms that
sicken millions of people a year but rarely kill, are increasingly
turning up resistant to antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   And studies of samples of human stools and grocery-store
chickens in the United States found a significant proportion
containing bacteria resistant to a new class of medicine designed
to fight off microbes that have grown impervious to the treatment
of last resort, vancomycin.
</P>
<P>
   The new human drug, which health officials hope will succeed
where others have failed, is similar to virginiamycin, an
antibiotic that has been used in chicken feed for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The fear, said the authors of the study, is that continued use
of virginiamycin in animal feed could render the new human drug
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, along with several other studies focusing on the
development of drug-resistant microbes in animals, were presented
Monday at the Interscience Conference on Antimicrobial Agents and
Chemotherapy in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antibiotic-resistant bacteria in humans _ does it come from
animals? The answer is yes,'' said Stephen F. Sundlof of the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The agency believes the issue is of major concern, Sundlof said,
and is planning meetings over the next several months to develop a
way to regulate the use of antibiotics in animals to lessen the
chances of exacerbating the problem of drug-resistant diseases in
humans.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union banned four antibiotics this summer from use
in livestock feed, and is considering banning three others because
of fears the antibiotics will contribute to the spread of human
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Still, specialists say the overuse of antibiotics to treat
people has contributed far more to what is fast becoming a major
public health issue: Microbes that have been inadvertently selected
to survive attacks by most or all anti-bacterial drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are pointing the finger at animals as the source of the
problem when animals are a tiny portion of the human problem as a
whole,'' said Robin Bywater, a consultant to Pfizer, which makes
virginiamycin, one of the drugs banned by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Virginiamycin, he said, has been used in animal feed for 25
years and hasn't created a resistance problem. And, Bywater said,
even the diseases that have been associated with animal-to-human
drug resistance are not the type that cause major illnesses such as
tuberculosis or pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   But the fears of serious consequences are there. While
physicians worldwide are being urged to take steps to cut down on
use of antibiotics, attention is also turning to farmers, who
frequently use antibiotics in livestock feed to promote growth.
</P>
<P>
   By killing off much of the bacteria in the stomach, antibiotics
allow animals to absorb more food and thus grow larger with less
feed.
</P>
<P>
   A Danish study presented Monday found that chicken farmers in
Denmark, who stopped using antibiotics in feed in 1995, did just as
well or better after eliminating drugs in the food.
</P>
<P>
   The chickens ate slightly more, but also weighed slightly more
at the same point in development. Meanwhile, farmers saved money by
not buying antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Altogether, it has not been an economic disaster for the
farmer,'' said Hanne-Dorthe Emborg, the principal author of the
study.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a study by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta, researchers looked at the increasing prevalence of
salmonella that is resistant to ceftriaxone, an antibiotic commonly
used to treat salmonella in children.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance had been extremely rare _ only three cases reported
in the United States before 1996. But by 1998 cases had increased
tenfold. Nine of 12 patients identified in the study as having the
resistant strain were interviewed and none had taken antibiotics
before coming down with the illness.
</P>
<P>
   However, three had visited a farm just before becoming ill and
one had drunk raw milk, said Eileen Dunne, a CDC epidemiologist and
the lead author of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Ceftriaxone, used in humans, is very similar to ceftiofor, an
antibiotic used frequently with pigs and cows, she said. The human
drug is the primary means of treating salmonella in children, whose
less developed immune systems often have a hard time fighting it
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing the ability to use this anti-microbial is a problem,''
she said. The only alternatives are expensive, broad-spectrum drugs
that kill everything, and lead to unwanted side effects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
