<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE PESTO, ONLY NEWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one ever has too many sauces for cold poached shrimp, but
tomato is a cliche and mayonnaise types are too creamy for me. By
this time every year I am even tired of pesto. But the pesto
variation taught to me by Deborah Madison, who wrote ``Vegetarian
Cooking for Everyone'' is a different story. It's based not on
basil but on marjoram, an unheralded herb that grows well in the
Northeast and can be found in good quantity almost anywhere fresh
herbs are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Madison's version is similar to a parsley-based sauce served
with the Italian dish capon magro, which is essentially a pile of
poached fish and vegetables. Her substitution of marjoram for
parsley reminded me that all Italian-style herb pastes are
essentially the same. A large quantity of a single herb is simply
pulverized with good olive oil, garlic, salt and pepper. (It
doesn't pay to use more than one type of herb; that only muddies
the flavor.) As with traditional pesto, the idea is to preserve,
intensify and complement the flavor of the herb, rather than to
transform or overwhelm it.
</P>
<P>
   Marjoram, with its earthy smokiness, is not easily overwhelmed
to begin with. It can absorb more than the usual amount of raw
garlic. Anchovies and capers provide a briny saltiness that reduces
the need for salt to an absolute minimum. And the little bit of
vinegar heightens the flavor, counteracting the heaviness of the
marjoram. The combination is wonderful, and it graces the cold
shrimp simply and perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Marjoram is related to and resembles oregano, but its flavor is
better. Oregano is a good but not perfect substitute in this pesto.
</P>
<P>
   As for the shrimp, you can buy them peeled, but shrimp poached
in their shells have more flavor, particularly if the cooking water
is salted. If you're going to peel the shrimp yourself, it pays to
buy larger shrimp and cut down on the work. Those labeled ```U-20''
(under 20 a pound) are nice to work with and to eat, and are
usually not prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   You can add other seasonings to the poaching liquid if you want;
the easiest is a handful of pickling mix, which usually contains
peppercorns, whole allspice, bay leaf and coriander and dill seeds.
Any or all of those spices, along with a couple of cloves of garlic
or a piece of onion, will subtly improve the flavor of the shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   COLD POACHED SHRIMP WITH MARJORAM PESTO
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds shrimp in the shell
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups marjoram, leaves and small stems only
</P>
<P>
   1 large or 2 small cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers
</P>
<P>
   2 anchovy fillets, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place shrimp in a saucepan with water to cover and a large
pinch of salt. Bring to a boil, and turn off the heat; let shrimp
sit in the water about 5 minutes, then rinse in cold water until
cool. Peel (and devein if you like), then arrange on a platter.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine marjoram and garlic in a blender or small food
processor. Process until finely minced, scraping down sides with a
rubber spatula once or twice if necessary. Add vinegar and most of
the oil, and process until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add capers and anchovies, and pulse the machine on and off a
few times so that the capers and anchovies are minced but not
pureed.
</P>
<P>
   4. Stir in remaining oil, along with salt and pepper to taste.
Serve with cold shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   These are the general rules for making Italian-style herb
pastes:
</P>
<P>
   _Any herb is fair game, but the best are basil, parsley,
marjoram, oregano and mint.
</P>
<P>
   _Some oil, at least a couple of tablespoons, is needed for
creaminess. But some of the oil can be replaced by hot water.
</P>
<P>
   _Garlic, salt and pepper are almost always included.
</P>
<P>
   _Vinegar or other acidic liquids like lemon juice are optional.
</P>
<P>
   Other flavorings, always optional, include capers, anchovies,
pine nuts, chopped eggs, pitted olives or grated dry cheese like
Parmigiano-Reggiano or pecorino Romano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
