<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 MODERATELY PRICED WINES FOR AUTUMN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winemakers are harvesting their grapes this month, their heads
full of ideas for crafting wines that will come to market in a year
or so. In the spirit of such forward thinking, what better time to
freshen your wine collection for the coming months?
</P>
<P>
   Here is a handsome trio _ reds from Italy, France and California
_ that will complement hearty autumn meals. And their merits
include their moderate prices.
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Antinori's Santa Cristina 1998, Tuscany, Italy. About
$9.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Once designated a Chianti Classico, Santa Cristina was dropped
down to a table wine in 1987. This did not mean that Santa
Cristina's quality had dropped, but that Chianti Classico's was
shooting up _ a win-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   The wine, which has been in the Antinori portfolio since 1946,
is named for a family vineyard in the Chianti region. The name of
the principal grape, sangiovese, was added to the label in 1991,
probably because the United States is a good market and Americans
love grape names on their wines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Antinori edged away from the classic Chianti blend by
substituting merlot for the canaiolo grape. The blend now is 90
percent sangiovese and 10 percent merlot.
</P>
<P>
   This is a simple, straightforward and very tasty wine. It's a
good buy and is widely available.
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Pellegrini Family Vineyards Pinot Noir 1997, Olivet
Lane Estate, Russian River Valley, California. About $20.(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   As evidenced here, it's getting so that the title of some wines
is often as long _ if not as boring _ as the description. Actually,
this is a good thing. It shows that California winemakers and wine
drinkers have recognized that the vineyard is paramount, that all
the stainless steel gadgetry in a winery doesn't make much
difference if the grapes are not first-class.
</P>
<P>
   This wine has two things going for it. First, the grapes come
from the Pelligrinis' Olivet Lane Vineyard, which has provided
fruit for some spectacular wines, including some memorable Williams
&AMP; Selyem pinots that regularly turn up at auctions at staggering
prices. And it was made by Merry Edwards, a pinot noir expert who
knows how to bring the very best out in the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   At 13.8 percent alcohol, this is a big wine, particularly for a
pinot noir, but it holds together beautifully and should age well.
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Chateau Lagrezette 1996, Cahors, France. About $20.(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   No one has worked harder to put the wines of Cahors, in
southwest France, on the map than Alain-Dominique Perrin, the owner
of the magnificent Chateau Lagrezette. Perrin was for many years
president of Cartier, the jewelry house, and currently heads the
Vendome Group, which includes Cartier, Alfred Dunhill and several
other luxury-goods producers.
</P>
<P>
   From his investment over the years in Lagrezette, it's apparent
that he maintains the same high standards for his wine as he does
for his jewelry. To that end, he consults regularly with Michel
Rolland, one of Bordeaux's best-known enologists.
</P>
<P>
   Cahors wines long had a reputation for high tannins and
off-putting intensity. By adding up to 20 percent merlot to the
classic Cahors grape, the malbec _ called auxerrois in this part of
France _ Rolland has produced a full-bodied but nicely rounded wine
with a pleasant and distinctive bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Among my mail recently was a letter from Ted Conklin, the owner
and manager of the American Hotel in Sag Harbor, N.Y. Conklin, who
transformed a faded hotel into a popular inn and restaurant, and
who also has one of the most sophisticated wine cellars in the
country, took issue with a recent column that discussed the many
factors that go into the cost of a bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   The column pointed out that the lion's share of whatever the
customer pays goes to the retailer or restaurateur, with the
winemaker often receiving less than 50 cents for a bottle that can
cost the consumer 100 times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Most restaurant owners I talked to said they were merely passing
along high costs imposed on them by the distributors, or that high
wine prices were the only way to subsidize the relatively higher
costs of food and its preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Conklin noted that while price-gouging may exist, ``restaurants
either make prices fair or they fail _ in the best of capitalistic
traditions. Competition has already established the fair-market
value for wines. This is especially true for restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   He objected to any comparison of the net profit of wineries and
a wine's mark-up in restaurants, because, net profits, he said, are
calculated after such costs as salaries, land and travel expenses
are paid. Wineries, he wrote, ``are hugely capital-intensive, owned
and run primarily by the very rich or by large corporations.''
``They enjoy significant tax advantages from depreciation and
agricultural subsidy,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants, he continued, ``aren't even on the same planet.''
If a restaurant sells a thousand bottles of wine at a profit of
$33.50 a bottle, he noted, ``it has $33,500 to pay for serving (the
wine) in 3,000 to 4,000 wine glasses, a lot of which break; a
dishwasher, polishing, waiters, rent, lights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want your readers to believe,'' he asked, ``that
restaurateurs should feel guilty about their wine profits and the
consumer should sympathize with Robert Mondavi and Ravenswood?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, neither. But the fact remains that wine prices are
appallingly high. More and more money is chasing a small and
unchanging amount of fine wine.
</P>
<P>
   When the economy cools down and demand drops off, the winemakers
will lower their prices; they always do. And restaurateurs like
Conklin will surely follow suit. And all polemics aside, it can't
happen soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
