u i BC-CARDENAS-RESIGN-0929-     09-28 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDENAS-RESIGN-0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY MAYOR SUBMITS RESIGNATION SO HE CAN RUN FOR
PRESIDENT
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, Mexico City's mayor,
submitted a letter of resignation Tuesday so he can dedicate
himself to his third presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City's Legislative Assembly must approve the resignation
_ which was expected _ before Cardenas officially steps down more
than a year before his term ends in December 1999. He could leave
office as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   Running for president and managing this troubled capital of 10
million are ``incompatible,'' Cardenas told reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The likely nominee of Mexico's Democratic Revolution Party, or
PRD, Cardenas is trailing in third or fourth place in most
presidential opinion surveys.
</P>
<P>
   He is the the son of Mexico's most beloved president and a
leading figure for Mexico's left. In 1997, Cardenas became the
first mayor here to be elected by residents rather than appointed
by Mexico's president.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas also ran for president and lost, in 1988 and 1994. Many
Mexicans believe the 1988 contest was rigged and stolen from
Cardenas by Mexico's Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI,
which has controlled the presidency for 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas belonged to the PRI until 1988, when he broke with the
party and went on to form the center-left PRD.
</P>
<P>
   Since Cardenas began his tenure as mayor his popularity has
dropped steadily in opinion polls. Analysts attribute his slide in
great part to Cardenas' failure to run a modern political campaign
and satisfy citizens' demands for a dramatic reduction in crime.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's opposition parties are considering forming an alliance
that would back one presidential candidate against the PRI in 2000.
If such an alliance were formed, Cardenas' chances of becoming the
nominee are looking slimmer.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll published Tuesday, Reforma newspaper found that
Cardenas was preferred by only 19 percent of 1,215 people who were
asked for their as an alliance candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox, the candidate of Mexico's conservative National
Action Party, was preferred by 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
