<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9043 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-SPACEPORT-VISION-HNS &LR;      09-28 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACEPORT-VISION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH HOPES: EAST TEXAS COUNTY READIES SPACEPORT BID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
 
By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEPORT, Texas _ Some might accuse Brazoria County officials of
being starry-eyed dreamers in their quest to make this East Texas
county the Cape Canaveral of the commercial space industry.
</P>
<P>
   After all, most of the commercial space business _ that of
sending satellites into space _ is done overseas by the Chinese,
French and Russians. Launches in the United States are done
primarily from government bases.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brazoria County may have a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: NASA has given an aerospace consortium the go-ahead
to build the prototype for a reusable launch vehicle and find a
launch site _ not necessarily in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Texas Legislature in its last session
authorized the creation of local spaceport authorities, paving the
way for Texas counties like Brazoria to grab onto the U.S. effort
to recapture the lead in the commercial space market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of visionary right now,'' admitted Fred Welch, as he
swept his hand over the marshy, snaky coastal plain that runs from
Texas 36 in Freeport to the Gulf of Mexico. ``You have to imagine a
12,000-foot runway and 900,000 square feet of manufacturing and
administrative space.''
</P>
<P>
   As the executive director of the Brazoria County Partnership,
Welch is hoping his county can convince the consortium, led by
Lockheed Martin Corp., that it's the right place to launch the
VentureStar, a vehicle resembling today's space shuttle that could
take off and land at one spaceport.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting the project could mean hundreds of jobs, increased
tourism and associated business for the county of more than 200,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the concept of using space for commercial reasons may
sound farfetched. Yet there is increasing demand from private
industry to send payloads into space, from drug companies that want
to perform scientific experiments in space to telecommunication
companies that want to send up more satellites.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost is expensive _ about $10,000 to get one pound into
space. So NASA is sponsoring the building of a reusable launch
vehicle to provide low-cost, continual launches.
</P>
<P>
   The VentureStar project is led by Lockheed Martin, with partners
Boeing Co., AlliedSignal, BF Goodrich Co. and Sverdrup Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The group has a $1.2 billion partnership with NASA to build a
177-foot-wide, 170-foot-long vehicle that would launch vertically
from a pad and land much as the shuttle does now.
</P>
<P>
   Using lighter, reusable equipment should lower the price
substantially, said Tony Jacob, business development analyst with
Lockheed in Palmdale, Calif. VentureStar's goal is to reduce the
price of getting something to space to $1,000 a pound on weekly
flights.
</P>
<P>
   A half-size model should be finished in the first quarter of
2000, Jacob said. After test flights, VentureStar will go into
production, with the first commercial flight scheduled for 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle probably will be built close to where it will be
launched, Jacob said. It's so big that it would be hard to move it
far.
</P>
<P>
   That will mean 2,000 to 3,000 jobs initially to build the craft.
Once it's operational, the company will need between 200 and 300
employees to launch weekly flights.
</P>
<P>
   The group is looking into building as many as two vehicles in
the United States, Jacob said.
</P>
<P>
   So is Space Access, a venture-capital firm from Palmdale,
Calif., that Welch also is trying to woo to Brazoria County.
</P>
<P>
   Space Access' reusable launch vehicle looks like a jet and has
its payload in the front. The unusual design features a ``beak'' in
front, which opens up and ``spits out'' a satellite. The
330-foot-long vehicle is known as ``alligator mouth,'' said Mike
Wade, vice president of programs for the 5-year-old company.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates it will take 3,000 workers to build the vehicle and
another 250 to 300 to maintain it on a continual basis.
</P>
<P>
   However, Space Access first has to finish designing its vehicle,
and that will take some money. The company is in the midst of
trying to raise funds through a private stock placement by
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's economic development group has identified two launch
sites _ a 4,000-acre parcel owned by Dow Chemical and a 1,500-acre
parcel owned by the Port of Freeport.
</P>
<P>
   The land is sparsely populated, which is necessary for safety
reasons, _ yet close enough to Houston to attract skilled
employees. Freeport is about 50 miles south of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brazoria County faces some stiff competition. And it
can't exactly build a spaceport on speculation _ the country won't
need too many of them.
</P>
<P>
   For the Space Access project, Brazoria County is competing with
Kenedy County in South Texas, along with a site in Florida and
another in California. Wade said the company will let the areas
present incentive packages before it makes its final decision.
</P>
<P>
   The VentureStar project is looking at 28 sites in 15 states,
Jacob said. While the project has had people in Brazoria County
looking over the sites, it's still too early to narrow down the
choices, or figure out how the financing will work.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Jacob said, VentureStar will select up to two sites
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While Brazoria County has its collective fingers crossed, Tom
Moser, executive director of the Texas Aerospace Commission, a
state agency in Austin, believes Texas has a good chance to land a
spaceport.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are interested in Texas, he said, including a third
one that is secretly kicking tires around the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you who they are,'' Moser said.
</P>
<P>
   Moser and Welch said it was a great step forward when the
Legislature voted this spring to allow the creation of local
spaceport authorities. Each authority will have the power to
acquire property and issue revenue bonds. Welch estimated it will
take about $300 million in revenue bonds to build a spaceport.
</P>
<P>
   Brazoria County Commissioners Court is expected to form the
board for a spaceport authority later this fall. Welch also will be
hiring consultants to study environmental factors such as wetlands,
soils, plants and animals to determine if the land is suitable for
a spaceport.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, the United States had 75 percent of the
launch business, Jacob said. Today, that has gone down to 25 to 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, French and Russians have taken over much of the
business of sending satellites into orbit, using
government-subsidized, expendable space vehicles, Welch said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston aggressively went after aerospace/airplane manufacturing
work in the mid-1980s but never had much success, said Saadat Syal,
former vice president of economic development for the Greater
Houston Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Something that came up over and over was a concern that Houston
didn't have a work force that was used to dealing with alloys,
composite materials and high-end welding, said Syal, who is now a
property developer in the Houston area. There was a sense that the
energy industry had a different kind of work force.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't seem to be as much of a drawback this time around,
however. Both VentureStar and Space Access said they plan to buy
component parts and will deal with contractors that have experience
with aerospace materials.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Brazoria group has spent $85,000 on hiring an
engineering consultant and business strategy consultant, as well as
on meeting and travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way off, Welch admits, but if it works out, the
spaceport would be the biggest deal since Dow Chemical decided 50
years ago to build its huge chemical complex in Brazoria County.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
