<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9060 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     09-28 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN TO ROAM BATTLEFIELD, ASKING QUESTIONS ABOUT CIVIL WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year at this time, the chalky, cedar-studded hills around
Granbury, Texas, become Civil War battlefields. Hundreds of
re-enactors dressed in their finest blues and grays break out the
muzzleloaders and face off against each other in mock anger.
</P>
<P>
   The battles they re-create are those of Gen. Hiram B. Granbury,
the town's namesake. This year, beginning Saturday morning, the
troops will fall out to re-enact the 1864 battle for Atlanta, and
the Battle of Spring Hill, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the serious activity will take place the day before,
when the hills will teem with the event's liveliest audience.
Coordinators expect 500 to 600 schoolchildren from the towns of
Lipan, Tolar and Granbury to pour onto the battlegrounds Friday
morning asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give them tours of the camp,'' said Cathey
Sims, a teacher at Granbury Middle School. ``The re-enactors will
be in camp, both Union and Confederate, and they will talk with the
students about the history of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims will also have some students working at the camp. She not
only teaches history at the middle school, she sponsors the junior
historians, more than a dozen seventh-graders who enjoy studying
history beyond the textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Those students will dress in costumes and help to educate the
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on their costumes now, and they've been told to
research what it was like for children their age during the Civil
War,'' Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   She points out that, while Texas, especially the area around
Granbury, never suffered the destruction of prolonged Civil War
battles, the settlers there had their own brand of adversity.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil War called away most of the able-bodied men, leaving
women and children to tend the fields. It was not a movement lost
on the Comanches, who were still fighting to reclaim their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the women took turns wearing men's clothing,'' Sims
said. ``They did it so the Comanche wouldn't know that all the men
were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims said her students are 12- and 13-year-olds, about the same
age as the oldest children left behind during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were too young to go off to the war, so they ended up
being the oldest ones still working the farms. The heavy work fell
to them, and it was a hard way of life. They had a lot of
responsibility,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's event will focus primarily on the effect the Civil
War had on families, and women's roles on and off the battlefield.
Proceeds from ticket sales and food and craft booths will go to
Mission Granbury, a nonprofit group helping victims of domestic
violence and families in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The re-enactment grounds will be open from 8:30 a.m. to 9:30
p.m. Saturday, and from 8:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Sunday. The camps
are open for tours. The grounds are at the Prairie Creek
Battlefield, about 10 miles southwest of downtown Granbury on Farm
Road 51 South.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets at the gate are $7 for adults and $5 for seniors 65 and
older and for children 5 to 12. For more information, call the
Granbury Convention and Visitors Bureau at (800) 950-2212. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9065 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     09-28 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN TO ROAM BATTLEFIELD, ASKING QUESTIONS ABOUT CIVIL WAR
</HEADLINE>
 
(DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also moving in ``l'' lifestyle category) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
