<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, Sept. 29. The N.Y. Times News Service
night supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Talks among opposition parties
to forge a coalition and back a single candidate in presidential
elections collapsed on Tuesday, greatly increasing the chances that
the party that has controlled Mexico for seven decades will win
power once again next year. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FORTUNE (Shanghai) _ China is celebrating 50 years of
communist rule this week, among other ways, by inviting more than
300 of the world's leading capitalists to gather for a conference
in this city. But the Fortune Global Forum is unintentionally
highlighting the deeply troubled nature of China's business
dealings with the West, which remain plagued on both sides by
mistrust, naivete, misunderstanding and wishful thinking, just as
they have for decades. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-YOUTHCRIME _ Youth crime is one of the fastest-growing
criminal categories in Japan. And as schools across Japan, and
towns large and small increasingly become the theater of attacks by
gangs, sexual crimes and theft, Japanese authorities are pulling
the alarm. According to national police figures, violence and crime
by school-age children has been rising fast both in and outside of
school for several years. And the number of juveniles arrested last
year for serious crimes like murder, rape and robbery pushed above
1,000 for the third consecutive year. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FISCAL-SHOWDOWN (Washington) _ This was going to be the year
that Congress and the Clinton administration de-electrified the
third rail of American politics, putting partisanship aside to
insure the long-term viability of the Social Security system. It
never happened. Instead, Social Security proved to be as
irresistible and potent a political weapon as ever, if not more so.
And decisions by both parties to use the retirement program's
almost sacred place in the hearts of voters as a club against the
other help explain why Congress and the White House are again
headed toward a budget showdown. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday assigned
itself an important role in the debate over managed health care by
agreeing to decide whether a woman can sue her health-maintenance
organization after she suffered a ruptured appendix during an
eight-day wait for a test to diagnose her abdominal pain. The woman
maintains that the HMO's financial structure, under which doctors'
compensation depended in part on their success in holding down
costs, is a breach of a legal duty to act in its patients' best
interests. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Acknowledging that Congress cannot
pass its appropriations bills before the new fiscal year begins on
Friday, the House passed a bill on Tuesday that will keep federal
agencies functioning for three weeks while Republicans negotiate
over hundreds of billions of dollars of spending with President
Clinton. The Senate is expected to pass the bill later Tuesday
night. Passage of the stop-gap measure, called a continuing
resolution, happens almost every year in Congress. But this year
the stakes are higher. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-HEALTH (Washington) _ Democratic presidential candidate
Bill Bradley offered a $65-billion plan on Tuesday for universal
access to health insurance that would require coverage for all
children, with subsidies for families that cannot afford it. By
James Dao.
</P>
