u s BC-FBC-BLACKCOLLEGES-COX     09-28 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BLACKCOLLEGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coaching heavyweights face off in Circle City Classic
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pete Richarson of Southern University and Joe Taylor
of Hampton are regarded as two of the top coaches in black college
football.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in the annual Circle City Classic in the RCA Dome in
Indianapolis, the two long-time adversaries will oppose each other
in a game televised live on BET.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be an empty seat in the house,''
Taylor said. ``There will be a lot of interesting matchups and some
great football.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Richardson arrived in Baton Rouge in 1993 , Southern (4-0)
has posted a 60-15 record. The Baton Rouge, La., school has won
three SWAC championships and four Heritage Bowl titles.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 49, whose Pirates dominated the CIAA (34-4-1) before
moving up to I-AA, are 36-14 since joining the MEAC in 1995.
Hampton won MEAC titles in 1997 and '98 and is ranked No.1 in the
Sheridan Broadcast Network poll. Southern is No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game will be the first for Richardson and Taylor
against each other since both were in the CIAA. Richardson was at
Winston-Salem State and Taylor was at Virginia Union before leaving
for Hampton '92.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking forward to playing each for the past two or
three years,'' Richardson said. ``We're all excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton will be led offensively by Stone Mountain native Roy
Johnson, a four-year starter at quarterback and now a grad student.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy is steady _ intelligent,'' Taylor said. ``He's done
everything we've asked of him. He really knows how to put us in the
right situation offensively to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern lost 23 regulars from last season's conference and
Heritage Bowl championship team. But it opened the season by
knocking off a Northwestern State team that was ranked No. 6 in
I-AA at time, and has used balance to stay undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars have passed for 681 yards and run for 726, while
allowing 510 yards on the ground and 579 through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Entering the fifth week of play, none of nine CIAA teams has a
winning record. It will change this week, when the four teams that
are .500 will be paired in two games. Virginia State (2-2, 2-0)
visits Livingstone (2-2, 1-1) and Bowie State (2-2, 1-1) travels to
Richmond to face Virginia Union (2-2, 1-1). . . . Key game in the
SIAC: Idle last weekend, defending SIAC champion Tuskegee (3-0,
1-0) plays Kentucky State (2-3, 1-0) in Frankfort, Ky. It counts in
the conference standings for the host only. The Thorobreds, 27-20
losers to Fort Valley State last week, feature the SIAC top rusher
in Alvon Brown (129.8 ypg). . . . In the SWAC, one of two losing
streaks will end in Itta Bena, Miss., on Saturday night when host
Mississippi Valley State (0-4, 0-2) plays Alabama State (0-4, 0-2)
the week after both suffered crushing defeats. Mississppi Valley
lost to Mark Washington-led Jackson State 63-0, and the Hornets'
lost 36-13 to Southern in Mobile. Washington dismantled the Delta
Devils' defense by hitting on 17 of 23 passes for 301 yards and 5
TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
