<HEADER>
A9106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WRITING-TEST-0929-COX     09-28 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITING-TEST-0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOST STUDENTS SCORE 'BASIC' ON U.S. WRITING EXAM
 &HT;    480&AMP;add
 &HT;    With WRITING-DATA
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most American students have basic writing skills,
but fall short of being fully proficient, according to results
released Tuesday from written exams given in late 1998 to 60,000
students in grades 4, 8 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   The exams given by the National Assessment of Educational
Progress (NAEP) were scored using a new system approved by the
National Assessment Governing Board, an independent,
congressionally chartered organization loaded with blue-ribbon
policy experts.
</P>
<P>
   The board set four achievement levels _ advanced, proficient,
basic and below basic _ after a professional testing firm scored
120,000 stories, reports and persuasive essays written within a
25-minute deadline by the 60,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the board reported:
</P>
<P>
   _ The highest rating of ``advanced'' was awarded to about one
percent of the students in each grade.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``proficient'' rating, representing ``solid academic
performance for each grade assessed,'' was earned by 22 percent in
fourth grade, 25 percent in eighth grade and 21 percent in 12th
grade.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``basic'' rating, defined as ``partial mastery of
prerequisite knowledge and skills'' needed for proficient work, was
earned by 61 percent in fourth grade, 58 percent in eighth grade
and 57 percent in 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Below the ``basic'' level were 16 percent in fourth grade, 16
percent in eighth grade and 22 percent in 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   A debate over the significance of the results erupted during the
news conference at the U.S. Department of Education where the
288-page report on the results was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only about one-fourth of the students can write at the
proficient level or above,'' said Gary W. Phillips, acting
commissioner of education statistics.
</P>
<P>
   However, pointed out Secretary of Education Dick Riley,
``Compared to other NAEP reports (on reading, science and math), we
have fewer young people at the 'below basic' level, and, to my way
of thinking, that is positive.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``The vast majority of our young people are at the
basic level and many of them are very close to moving up one notch
to the proficient level.''
</P>
<P>
   Those views are simply two sides of the same coin, said board
member Marilyn Whirry, who teaches advanced writing courses at Mira
Costa High School in Manhattan Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   She said the exam results showed that ``many students are able
to write at a basic, minimally effective level, but far too few can
produce strong, coherent prose.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, none of the participants from
government, educational and research organizations was willing to
venture a guess as to why girls scored 20 points higher than boys
on the test's 300-point scoring scale. Several called for more
research and for experiments in improving the boys' scores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Students who took the test also filled out questionnaires about
their activities at home and in school. Their answers supported
those who say that good writing is a craft that is related to
reading and can be learned, rather than an inherited ability.
</P>
<P>
   Scores were higher for students who said they often discuss
their school work at home or that they come from a home with more
than 25 books, an encyclopedia or subscriptions to a newspaper or
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Scores also were higher for those who said they discuss their
writing with teachers, plan ahead before they start writing, write
more than one draft and save their writing in folders or
portfolios, noted Richard Sterling, executive director of the
National Writing Project at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is encouraging news because these broad strategies are
advocated by a wide array of researchers, scholars and teachers of
writing,'' said Sterling, whose project has trained tens of
thousands of teachers in methods of improving student writing.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government paid for the 60,000 exams in the national
test, which were conducted in a scientific sample of the nation's
public and private schools.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NAEP tested another 100,000 eighth-graders in
public schools in 35 states, the District of Columbia, the Virgin
Islands and the domestic and overseas education systems of the
Department of Defense. Those areas paid extra so that they would
have a large enough sample to compare their eighth graders to those
in other places.
</P>
<P>
   After examining the state results, lots of researchers and
policy-makers who want to learn the best ways to teach writing are
likely to be headed for the places with the highest writing scores
for eighth-graders. They were the schools in Connecticut, U.S.
military bases overseas, domestic military bases, Maine,
Massachusetts, Texas and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   All have emphasized the teaching and testing of writing skills
in recent years. Scores of their Hispanic, African-American and
poor students particularly in schools at defense facilities, Texas,
Wisconsin and Connecticut _ were significantly higher than those of
other poor, Hispanic and African-American students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing has been a strong focus within our system for several
years,'' commented Ray Tolleson, interim director of education
activity in the Department of Defense. ``If anything makes us feel
good, it is that among both African American and Hispanic students,
we were at the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
