<HEADLINE>
LOVE POGO? HOP TO IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find collections of Walt Kelly's ``Pogo'' comic
strip?
</P>
<P>
   _ P.A., Benbrook, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The comics publisher Fantagraphics has reprinted at least
nine volumes of ``Pogo'' strips. To request a free catalog, write
to Fantagraphics Books, 7563 Lake City Way NE, Seattle, WA 98115,
or visit the World Wide Web site www.fantagraphics.com.
</P>
<P>
   You might also be interested in the 1,500-member ``Pogo'' fan
club, a group founded in 1984 and authorized by Kelly's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Members receive the ``Fort Mudge Most,'' a bimontly magazine
that includes articles about Kelly, collecting tips and reprints of
``Pogo'' along with other Kelly works. To join, send $25 to The
Pogo Fan Club, Spring Hollow Books, 6908 Wentworth Ave S.,
Richfield, MN 55423.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find a tape of the Bob and Ray comedy routine,
``Slow Talkers of America''?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.W., Euless, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: That routine is included on ``Bob &AMP; Ray: A Night of Two
Stars,'' a two-CD collection sold by Radio Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night of Two Stars'' sells for $29.95 on CD (catalog No. RACD
6000) or $19.95 on cassette (catalog No. RA 1000-2). It was
recorded live at Carnegie Hall in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call Radio Foundation at (800) 528-4424 or visit the
official Bob and Ray World Wide Web site: www.bobandray.com. More
than 20 other Bob and Ray recordings are also available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the address of Henry Cisneros in California?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.J., Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Cisneros in care of Univision Communications, 1999
Avenue of the Stars, Suite 3050, Los Angeles, CA 90067.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, the former Housing and Urban Development Secretary and
San Antonio mayor, is the president and chief operating officer of
Univision. The company owns the Univision Spanish-language
television network and 21 TV stations.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, Cisneros reached a plea agreement and pleaded guilty
to one misdemeanor count of lying to the FBI when he was being
considered for a Cabinet post in 1997. He paid a $10,000 fine but
was not sentenced to jail or put on probation.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros admitted in court that he lied to FBI investigators
about the amount of financial support he gave Linda Jones after
their extramarital affair. Initially claiming he never paid Jones
more than $10,000 annually, Cisneros actually gave her more than
$250,000 from 1989 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
