<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH `IN OUTSTANDING CONDITION,' DOCTOR SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's health is as robust as his
presidential fund-raising, according to a medical report released
by Bush's campaign Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper of Dallas, who conducted Bush's annual
physical examination June 17, a few days after Bush kicked off his
national campaign, said the 53-year-old governor's fitness was in
the top 1 percent for his age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I find a man in outstanding condition,'' Cooper said
in a followup telephone interview with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The report, however, revealed for the first time that Bush
underwent surgery July 6, 1998, for the removal of two benign
polyps from his colon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was minor, and they were benign, and the governor didn't
feel like they needed to be made public,'' Bush spokeswoman Mindy
Tucker said, explaining why the colon surgery, which occurred
during Bush's re-election campaign, had not been previously
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office promptly announced arthroscopic knee
surgery that Bush underwent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who has examined Bush annually since 1989, said he has
never found any indication that Bush has ever used illegal drugs, a
nagging question that the governor has refused to answer fully in
his national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has totally abstained from alcohol during the past 13
years. He has no history of any alcohol, drug, mental or
psychiatric treatment or rehabilitation,'' the doctor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to questions about whether he used illegal drugs, Bush
has admitted making ``mistakes'' as a young man but has refused to
say whether those mistakes included experimentation with illegal
drugs. Pressed by reporters last month, Bush would say only that he
hasn't used illegal drugs since 1974, the year he turned 28.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said the governor weighed 192 1/2 pounds, a few pounds
heavier than what was considered best for his 6-foot height. But
Cooper said Bush's body weight was good.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's blood pressure was 104/80, and his pulse was 38, which
the doctor called normal for a ``highly conditioned athlete.'' His
cholesterol level was 176, which Cooper called ``outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The remainder of the physical examination was well within
normal limits, and he had no indications of any cardiovascular
problems,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   The physician rated Bush's cardiovascular fitness as ``excellent
to superior'' and said he had a ``low to very low coronary risk
profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said Bush eats a low-fat diet, runs three to four miles
five times a week and works out with free weights once a week. He
said Bush's fitness, based on a treadmill stress test administered
during his June physical, was in the top 1 percent for men in their
50s.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said he was particularly impressed that Bush,
immediately after completing the stress test, ran two miles in less
than 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper noted that Bush had a mild high-frequency hearing loss,
which he said was most likely related to aircraft noise. Bush was a
Texas Air National Guard pilot from 1968-1973.
</P>
<P>
   The only other problems that Cooper cited were some back
stiffness and minor stiffness in Bush's left knee, which the
governor attributed to his regular exercise program. Neither
problem required medication.
</P>
<P>
   According to the medical report, Bush had minor surgery to his
chest wall when he was 13 and an appendectomy when he was 10.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign said the medical summary was being released ``in
accordance with past presidential campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
