<HEADLINE>
`MARIO GOLF' KIND OF ROUGH GOING FOR MARIO GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nintendo has never wanted it any other way: Mario is for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the Donkey Kong arcade game in the '80s, the
colorful, clumsy plumber has fumbled his way through more than
two-dozen games, all of which have been geared toward young
players. Even the complicated brain-buster Mario 64 is,
essentially, a kid's game.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's so surprising that Mario Golf (Nintendo for N64,
$50, all ages) is so difficult. This is the first Mario game that,
unlike all the other Mario-theme sports titles, you can't just pick
up and start playing. Well, you can, but you're gonna have a tough
time with it.
</P>
<P>
   The premise sounds kinda fun: Mario and all his pals take to the
course. But gamers won't get much enjoyment out of this unless
they're already familiar with the headaches involved in mastering a
golf video game. You gotta get your angle right, know how much
power to use per hit and calculate everything just right or you'll
wind up in the trees or water, or not even hitting the thing; it's
just too complex for nongolf fans.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are into golf games will love it, though. The graphics
are well-done and the courses are as interesting as any PC golf
title. For the younger gamer ... hey, what about Mario Putt-Putt?
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Planet of the Apes for your 13-year-old. That pretty
much sums up Ape Escape (Sony for PlayStation, $30, all ages), the
first PlayStation game to totally utilize the system's Dual Shock
analog controller (that's another $30, mom).
</P>
<P>
   Escape pits a kid hero against a bunch of unruly baboons who
snuck out of the zoo and are bent on changing humans into Roddy
McDowell. Your job: Round 'em up.
</P>
<P>
   Graphically and game-playwise, this is a little bit like Crash
Bandicoot, only a little harder. It's so tricky, in fact, you gotta
get the strategy guide ($15) to figure everything out. So, for one
game, you're looking to spend $75. Good game, but not $75 good.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the PlayStation, Sony released more details about
its upcoming PlayStation 2 last week. The biggest news: Gamers
won't have to wait till Christmas of next year to get one. Should
be out in the United States by fall of next year. Japan gets 'em
March 4. Over there, they'll go for 39,800 yen, or about $400.
</P>
<P>
   The system will not only play games (both PlayStation 2 and
original PlayStation titles) but also music CDs and DVD movies.
Better, for $400.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
