<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC MARKETS, NOW A CLICK AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new Web site that sells ingredients for dishes from the world
over has joined with the American Red Cross to raise money and
contribute food for victims of last month's earthquake in Turkey.
When visitors to the site, www.ethnicgrocer.com, click on a Turkish
Earthquake Relief Fund icon on the home page and make a
contribution, the company matches it with a food donation of equal
value.
</P>
<P>
   The site is run by Parry Singh, 29, and Subhash Bedi, 27, who
developed it through market research in classes leading to their
MBAs at the J.L. Kellogg School of Business at Northwestern
University, in Evanston, Ill., where their headquarters remain.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for a site that sells more than 20,000 ethnic
food products and gives recipes to educate America on ethnic
cuisines came simply enough last summer. The Indian-born Singh was
visiting his brother in Burbank, Calif., north of Los Angeles, when
his sister-in-law was about to embark on an hour's drive she made
twice a month to Artesia, south of the city, where Indian food
shops are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   She made it plain even to a visitor what a chore the trip was,
and Singh began thinking of a better way. He had a bachelor's
degree in computer engineering and a master's in electrical
engineering, so the direction of his thinking was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site has food products of India, China, Japan, Korea,
Vietnam, Italy, Greece, Spain, Germany, Poland and Mexico, among
other countries. They are chosen by what Singh calls ``ethnic
czars,'' including two Indian chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are currently over 26 people and growing rapidly,'' Singh
wrote by e-mail. Indian products, for example, go from Aloo Mattar,
a vegetable curry (14.1 ounces for $3.79), to Vindaloo, a sauce (10
ounces for $2.89), and include cardamom, curry, cumin and varieties
of breads and chutneys.
</P>
<P>
   Bedi, who has largely organized the relief project, was born in
the United States but went to live in India through his teen-age
years. The food for the project is bought in Turkey as much as
possible and consists of bread, milk and other staples, not the
Turkish specialties like apricot jam and pomegranate syrup that are
sold on the site. Bedi wrote that ``based on consumer feedback and
participation, we will keep the program going through November.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A different view of ethnic specialty foods may be found at
www.chefshop.com, a Seattle-based site founded in 1995, which has
expanded and brought in Jeff Bergman, a specialty food buyer and
merchandiser. He joins Mauny Kaseburg, who has preached fresh
ingredients as the first requirement of good cooking for much of
the '90s on KOUW-FM, the local National Public Radio affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to standbys like Rustichella d'Abruzzo pastas and
Scharffen Berger chocolate, they are betting on an awakened
interest in Spanish cuisine. They have added Spanish luxury
products like Miguel &AMP; Valentino piquillo peppers at $9.99 for a
7.75 ounce jar (click on All Products, then on Pickled and
Marinated Vegetables), La Dalia sweet and bittersweet paprika from
the La Vera region (0.85-ounce tin, $6.99) and La Mancha saffron (1
gram, or 0.035 ounce, $5.59).
</P>
<P>
   A search on the site for paella recipes brings three: paella
rapida, roasted vegetable paella and a seafood and sausage version,
as well as three Kwanzaa rice dishes, which Ms. Kaseburg says are
similar to paella.
</P>
<P>
   Among other new products are Huguel Miel de Provence lavender
honey and wild mountain honey, both in 500-milliliter (16.6-ounce)
jars for $12.49. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Add to sites that sell parts for beloved old kitchen appliances
cuisineparts.com, operated by European Kitchen Bazaar in Waterbury,
Conn. The site, which specializes in Cuisinart wares, has entire
blenders and processors in addition to replacement parts. It also
carries toasters, bread machines and waffle makers.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Marsden, the company's customer relations manager, writes
that its prices are discounted. A Cuisinart ``classic style''
electronic toaster sells for $59.95. Gracious Home sells it for
$70, but Bloomingdale's has it this month for $59.99.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
