<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT     09-28 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST KITCHEN: WHISKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By AMANDA HESSER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The whisk is a wonderful invention. With rapid
swipes, you can turn a slippery puddle of egg whites into
feather-light fluff, cream into a stiff white cloud, and oil and
vinegar into a uniformly viscous liquid. And it gives you control
from the beginning to the finish, something you don't get with an
electric mixer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of the whisk is about as old as it can get,'' said
Burt Wolf, who is revising ``The Cooks' Catalog'' (Harper &AMP; Row,
1975), which he wrote with James Beard, Barbara Kafka and Milton
Glaser. And it's about as elementary as it can get. ``If you want
to multiply the effect of a stick,'' he said, ``keep cutting it
down and separating the ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Whisks come in all shapes and sizes, and for as little as $2 and
as much as $20. I tested nearly 30, applying them to classic uses
like whipped cream, mayonnaise, meringue and butter sauce.
</P>
<P>
   As I tested, two types emerged _ those for emulsifying and those
for incorporating air. Avid cooks may find they need more than one
size of each type. Trying to emulsify a sauce in a small saucepan
with a large balloon whisk, for instance, will be awkward at best.
</P>
<P>
   French whisks or balloon whisks are best for incorporating air
into ingredients like egg whites or cream. As you brush it in a
circular motion through liquid, the wide round end with overlapping
wires pulls efficiently pulls in air.
</P>
<P>
   A good whisk should have at least eight sturdy wires that are
flexible so that as you scrape it along the bottom of a bowl the
wires give a little to make it easy on the arm. The handle should
be comfortable, too, but weighted evenly with the whisk wires. Many
whisks have heavy handles and light wires, which are difficult to
control.
</P>
<P>
   The most effective French and balloon whisks are those with wire
loops of different lengths. Where they intertwine, they should be
loosely layered but not flabby.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have tried to improve upon this design, but not
always to good ends. Williams-Sonoma sells a French whisk that has
a small wire ball inside that looks like a cat toy; it is designed
to increase the volume of air that is trapped with each stroke. As
you whisk, the ball jingles around, so it is fun to use, but it
doesn't whip cream or egg whites more quickly than a good French
whisk. It also makes a mess. With each upward stroke, cream that is
caught in the cage flies out in all directions.
</P>
<P>
   The best whisk I found was also one of the least expensive,
$7.95 at Broadway Panhandler, 477 Broome St. This 14-inch French
whisk with a wood handle has flexible, well-spaced wires. Egg
whites stiffened to thick, tight foam with little effort, and
though it is a long whisk, it is perfectly weighted so that I felt
I had control over every stroke. The whisk is available in several
sizes; prices vary. It would be useful to have one that is less
than 10-inches for whisking small amounts of cream and the large
14-inch one for making a voluminous meringue.
</P>
<P>
   This 14-inch whisk, however, is not all purpose. To make a
vinaigrette or to whisk together a pan sauce with it would be like
picking up peas with chopsticks. Because it has a large round end,
very little of its surface area makes contact on flat surfaces like
a pan. Sauce whisks work better.
</P>
<P>
   Whisks that work best for sauces vary widely in shape, but the
good ones share a common denominator. They are flat, with coils
that cover a large surface in a flat pan. And, as you whisk, the
wires can emulsify a shallow pool of liquid while pulling the
liquid from all corners of the pan. I found several that I liked.
</P>
<P>
   A heat-proof whisk, made for pans with nonstick coatings, makes
sense. The OXO Good Grips flat nylon whisk is comfortable to hold
and flexible, so that as the whisk end _ a flat oval of nylon loops
_ presses into the pan, it covers a large area. But it would not
work as well in a small, straight-sided saucepan. It is $4.99 at
Zabar's, 2245 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers are also selling heat-proof nylon French and
balloon whisks, but they are unnecessary _ unless you are whipping
eggs over a heat source _ and disappointing. The ones I tried were
too soft and flexible and incorporated air poorly.
</P>
<P>
   A better all-purpose sauce whisk is made by Cuisipro Delbor.
Like the roux whisks that have been around for decades, it
resembles a large spoon with a Slinky-like coil wrapping around the
end. The coil bends to lie flat against the pan no matter what
angle you hold the handle. It's light and resilient, and the coil
is narrow enough to scrape the corners of a pan, an important point
when making sauces with cream. It is $6.95 at Broadway Panhandler.
</P>
<P>
   Of the new-age whisks, WMF's saucepan whisk has five vertical
wires shaped like triangles, and the base of the triangles is the
part that touches the pan. Because the wires cover so much of the
pan surface, it blends sauces like beurre blanc superbly. And yet,
sauces are its only use. It will not aerate a sauce and would be
useless in a bowl. It's $9.95 at Broadway Panhandler.
</P>
<P>
   A similar sauce whisk by Roesle, $19.99 at Chef Central, Paramus
(N.J.) Towne Square, looks more like a French whisk that has been
flattened on the end. Its wires are stiff so it is good for
whisking thicker sauces like bechamel and pastry cream. The flat
end and sharp corners of the whisk wires allow you to reach all
corners of a small, straight-sided saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest surprise was an 11-inch whisk that looks like a
rendering of the Sun and its planets. From a round handle stretch a
dozen straight wires with metal balls of varying sizes on the end.
Also by WMF, it is $22.99 at Chef Central.
</P>
<P>
   I put it to work in a pan, whisking butter into white wine to
make beurre blanc, and the balls swung fluidly from side to side
and in circles, swirling the liquid into a thick sauce. In a metal
bowl while making mayonnaise, the balls banged against the side
like the clip-clop of a horse as the egg soaked up the oil. Its
design may say museum piece more than cookware, but it is no joke.
My mayonnaise didn't break and my forearm did not ache enough to
have me reaching for the electric mixer _ all I really want in a
whisk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-NY-Y2K-LARDER-ART-2TA     09-28 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-Y2K-LARDER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K: WATER, OK; BATTERIES, RIGHT; CAVIAR, CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Out there in America, the fear of a Y2K meltdown
reducing the country to a pre-industrial society has driven many
folks to stockpile supplies of grains, powdered eggs, water, maybe
some guns and ammo.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, millenarians are bunkering down in their own way:
by laying in gallon jugs of Poland Spring and trying to figure out
what wines work with cannellini beans and Italian tuna.
</P>
<P>
   It's looking more and more like a long shot, but what if a Y2K
computer glitch does black out our whole technological
infrastructure? It will be bad enough going without light or heat
or water for who knows how long. But where in the name of Eli Zabar
is a person supposed to get his or her fix of fois gras and
prosciutto di Parma?
</P>
<P>
   Living up once again to its reputation for self parody,
Manhattan is now becoming ground zero for widespread foodie panic _
all right, limited neurosis _ about Y2K. In the event of a
disruption in power caused by crashing computers unable to deal
with the ``00'' date change, serious eaters do not want to be stuck
staring at an old can of chunk light tuna and sucking on a warm
soda.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Baum, a partner in the B.E. Group, which owns Windows on
the World, and his wife, Jennifer, are loading up on that other
staple of the good life: caviar. ``Any time there's a special at
Zabar's, I sort of stock up,'' Ms. Baum said. There are now 16
two-ounce jars of osetra in their refrigerator, which won't do them
any good if power lines go down.
</P>
<P>
   John Gottfried, a partner in the Gourmet Garage chain of
high-end grocers, is laying in lots of truffle butter, imported
Parmesan and, of course, Champagne. The run on French bubbly for
Y2K Eve parties has already driven up some prices. Gottfried said a
case of his favorite Champagne, Bruno Paillard, has gone from $24
to $28 a bottle in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent Gallup poll, 40 percent of adults believe
there may be food shortages due to Y2K, and 39 percent of those
said they planned to stockpile food and water.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers to magazines like American Survivalist and the
followers of the Rev. Jerry Falwell and the Rev. Pat Robertson have
been making ready for TEOTWAWKI (the end of the world as we know
it). Mormons believe in keeping a two-year supply of nonperishables
on hand anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal government has been playing down Y2K
lately, the federal Emergency Management Agency still recommends
preparing for the equivalent of a three-day storm.
</P>
<P>
   For a while there, the 45-pound buckets of wheat, sacks of
powdered milk and cans of bacon were flying out of the warehouses
at companies like Walton Feed, in Montpelier, Idaho. Steve Portela,
its director of sales, said, ``We went from 30 employees to 186 in
two years and I still couldn't keep up with my orders.''
</P>
<P>
   He sold everything from the ``30 Day Survival Unit'' ($169) to
the ``Deluxe 1 Year Unit'' ($947): four-foot-cubes of dehydrated
nutrition for the whole family. Orders were so backed up, Portela
couldn't guarantee delivery by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   But business has dropped off in the last couple of months,
either because the hard-core Y2K-phobes have fully loaded their
bomb shelters by now or people are just worrying less about what
Robertson was calling ``serious dislocations.''
</P>
<P>
   For some New Yorkers, an interruption in the heirloom tomato
supply qualifies as a serious dislocation, and the anxiety is
taking hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very serious about it,'' said Fred Plotkin, of his Y2K
larder. Plotkin is the author of several books on Italian food and
culture, and he does not intend to let his taste buds down if
something happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we're in the dark doesn't mean we're not going to
eat well,'' he said. Even without heat, because Plotkin does not
believe it is safe for people to start lighting Sterno in their
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Canned kidney beans, chickpeas, green beans and extra virgin
olive oil will make for a tasty three-bean salad. Onions are a must
for his insalata di tonno, cannellini e cipolla _ a traditional
Tuscan dish made with tuna, beans, chopped fresh onion, olive oil
and lemon.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And he will have babka. ``Given that we'll all be anxious, I
want sweet things,'' he said. ``A babka can last a good long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin's mother, Bernice Price, is taking similar precautions,
with cans of salmon and sardines, as well as powders that, mixed
with juice, provide green vegetable protein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss fresh vegetables and fruit,'' Ms. Price said. ``And
of course I'll miss takeout food and and Fairway and Zabar's.''
</P>
<P>
   She was not convinced that these vital operations would be
completely shut down. But, she said of Y2K, ``I feel it will create
a rather serious problem, knowing that under the best of
circumstances the city has trouble dealing with a rainstorm.''
</P>
<P>
   Even skeptics are hedging their bets.
</P>
<P>
   Fern Berman, who handles public relations for Le Cirque and
other New York restaurants, said: ``I'm preparing. I'm not going
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   She intends to buy 40 gallons of water (two months' worth, she
figures) and has started socking away canned vegetables: 15 or 20
tins so far of beans, fish and ``those wonderful little artichokes
in the jars.''
</P>
<P>
   She, too, has epicurean ambitions for her larder. ``On a desert
island, I would bring olives to make olive oil,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also had to buy a nonelectric can opener. ``It's not a big
deal,'' she said of reacquainting herself with this primitive
device. ``And it's easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berman said she's the kind of ``slightly neurotic person''
mocked by friends for carrying Purell and Wash'n Dri's, until they
beg to borrow hers.
</P>
<P>
   Storage space will not be a problem, she said. Her apartment has
a ``huge bathroom'' and, if that fills up, she'll stow the overflow
in her office.
</P>
<P>
   All that water does pile up. Marc Murphy, the chef at La
Fourchette, said one of his closets was now crowded with bottles
his brother _ who is in the software business _ had asked to keep
there.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy himself said he's making plenty of pate now because of a
fois gras shortage last year. Five or six terrines should cover his
New Year's Eve party, he said, and ``I'll have enough to keep me
going for a couple of weeks after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara De Silva, a freelance food writer, will be using her
balcony for storage and refrigeration. ``Unless we have 80-degree
weather, it can stand in for a root cellar,'' she said. She'll put
out Parmigiano-Reggiano, apples, carrots, ``a big chunk of
prosciutto di Parma.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this happens, we will all need good things in our mouths,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing happens, she will simply donate her surplus
prosciutto and Parmesan to charity.
</P>
<P>
   But is there really likely to be a shortage of gourmet
groceries? In Manhattan?
</P>
<P>
   Gottfried, of Gourmet Garage, said, ``Even if everything goofs
up, it can't goof up that long.''
</P>
<P>
   None of these assurances will comfort Erik Hedegaard, a magazine
writer, who sold his New York apartment at a fire-sale price,
traded his mutual funds in the middle of the biggest bull market in
history and generally obsessed over Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought all these five-pound bags of rice,'' Hedegaard said.
``Then I went on the Atkins diet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9142 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOME-PICTURES30-COX     09-28 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PICTURES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Know the rules for framing and displaying photos _ then break
them
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 30.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If there's one rule when it comes to framing and
displaying art in the home, it's this: There are none.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some basic principles apply _ choosing a mat and frame
that doesn't overpower the subject, hanging the art at eye level,
lighting the picture so that it can be fully appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for every rule, there's an un-rule,'' said Myott (who uses
only one name) of Myott's Studio, a custom framing gallery in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A grouping of photos matted and framed in a variety of sizes and
materials can be disruptive, he said. ``But then, sometimes clutter
can be different, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, he said, is pictures should be framed and
displayed to their best advantage while at the same time
complementing a home's decor. After that, think outside the frame,
er, box.
</P>
<P>
   It works for one of Myott's most famous customers _ Elton John.
An avid collector, the part-time Atlantan is loaning 200 of his
2,000 photographs to the High Museum of Art for an exhibit,
``Chorus of Light: Photographs From the Sir Elton John
Collection,'' next year. Many of John's photographs hang in his
penthouse on Peachtree Road. Myott is framing some 800 of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that many, you have to come up with something
different,'' Myott said. ``He's bought some of the most expensive
and finest pieces in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   So you wouldn't expect the British rock musician to rummage the
frame stacks at Wal-Mart. Instead, Myott is hand-gilding some
frames. Some are done in 12- and 22-karat gold. Others feature
rubbed black and warm silver finishes. Photographs as small as 1 by
2 inches have been ``enlarged'' with a mat and 5-inch wide frame.
You'd think such proportions would overwhelm the subject; instead,
they entice the eye into looking a little closer.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can afford to frame an entire collection at once.
Besides, most art is acquired over time. ``When someone starts
buying art, they usually hang pieces one by one. But if you get
addicted to it, you can't do that,'' said Jane Jackson, an Atlanta
art dealer. ``The next thing is to start grouping them together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, artwork should be planned for when building or
remodeling a home so that proper lighting can be installed, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the stage at which your photo collection falls,
here are some points to consider:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make frames secondary to subjects. While the art is the focus,
that doesn't mean you have to use the same old moldings, said
Atlanta interior designer Bill Cook, an avid collector of
photography. Be creative. Use a frame from a mirror. Ask your
framer to use your own materials, such as fabrics and wallpaper, or
ones that hold sentimental value. ``Sometimes, we'll take a wood
from somebody's barn and frame their pictures,'' Myott said. The
point is to consider more than the usual suspects. ``Ten years ago,
things were all framed in metal with simple white mats,'' Jackson
said. ``Now, there are so many interesting materials until the
framing has become an important part of the piece.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use neutral mats. Mats are sold in every color, but large
neutral ones best complement black and white photos, Myott said. By
double- or triple-matting, you can add a sliver of color that picks
up other hues in the room. ``Sometimes, we use silks because the
fine grain gives a subtle and rich texture, especially for fashions
photos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Protect your photos. Use a reputable framer who knows how to
protect photos from harmful sunlight, using archival mats,
UV-protection glass and acid-free backing paper. Photos should not
be hung in direct sunlight or near heating vents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Organize displays. Depending on how many pictures you own, one
way to organize a collection is by subject matter. Six nature
photos can make a grouping. Because the topics are related, you can
vary the materials used to frame them. (Just don't mix color photos
with black and whites.) Conversely, if the subjects are all
different, use the same frame to unify the collection. Jackson, an
art consultant to John who brought him and the museum together,
said the November 2000 exhibit will give visitors an idea of how
the star displays his photography at home. ``A lot of things are
hung from floor to ceiling with whole walls covered in
photographs,'' she said. ``One wall is all images of women. Another
is vintage 1920s, and another room has all photos by one artist.
There's definite thought into the way they're put together.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create scale with groupings. For large walls, a grouping can
be more effective than a single picture, even a large one. For
rooms with low ceilings, stack several pictures vertically to
create the illusion of height.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hang at eye level _ depending: Most people hang artwork too
high, Myott said. ``Sometimes, when I go in homes it looks like
everything's attached to helium.'' In general, the middle of a
picture should be no higher than 60 inches from the floor, Jackson
said. Yet, there are exceptions, such as in the case of groupings.
Art also should be hung in relation to what's around it, such as
the furniture below it. Pictures above a sofa, for example, should
be hung lower.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Map out a display. Before driving a nail, sketch a plan for
how the pictures will be displayed or at least lay them on the
floor in the desired pattern, Jackson said. Depending on the wall's
size, allow 2 inches between frames, or at least a consistent
amount throughout.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accent the positive. Why spend money on artwork and framing
without ensuring the piece will be properly seen? Make sure
pictures have adequate lighting, either from ceiling recessed
halogens, track fixtures or picture lamps.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't hang everything at once: If your collection is large,
consider rotating pictures in a display. By using one size mat and
frame, even individual pictures within a grouping can be changed
periodically to freshen the grouping, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't hang everything _ period: Consider unconventional
displays. Cook suggests propping photos on a mantel, shelf or
narrow wall ledge, available at photo and art supply stores. Or you
can make a ledge using a wide strip of molding. Ledges are
particularly effective in hallways where most people struggle to
fill large expanses of wall space. Large pictures also can be
placed in the seat of a chair and leaned against the back. ``In
small apartments, a lot of people just lean things on the floor
against the wall,'' Jackson said. The advantage is photos can
easily be changed _ without leaving walls looking like slices of
Swiss cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
