<HEADER>
A9143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CUNNINGHAM-BOOK-REVIE     09-28 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUNNINGHAM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK ALASKA'S JUST TOO BIG TO BAKE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af) 
By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No cookbook is more difficult to write than a primer. The author
can assume little, since novices lack the language necessary to
begin. Questions like ``Is my stove gas or electric?'' ``What does
simmer mean?'' and ``How do you strain a can of tomatoes?'' can
reduce longtime recipe writers to sputtering impotence as they try
to explain the fine points of scrambling an egg to people who
wonder how to break one open.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Cunningham, the dean of American home cooks and the
author of the current edition of ``The Fannie Farmer Cookbook'' as
well as the invaluable ``Breakfast Book'' and others, had an
inspiration a few years ago: she would invite a group of noncooks
to her house every Saturday, give them a simple recipe and let them
attack it. What did they understand? What parts were confusing?
What worried them? From this she hoped to develop a book that would
address the needs of the beginning cook.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham''
(Knopf, $29.95), and it is a qualified success. With only 150
recipes, the book is succinct, and in no way intimidating; the
beginning cook is not challenged to prepare perfect french fries.
Selections range from scrambled eggs to risotto, roast leg of lamb
to hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most daunting recipe is parchment-wrapped fish
fillets, which _ assuming foil is used in place of parchment, as it
is here _ is a perfect choice for a beginner.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the recipe selection is old-fashioned but honorable.
Smothered chicken with mushrooms, Mexican lentil soup and American
meatloaf all offer familiar but interesting flavors and procedures
that are difficult to have miscarry.
</P>
<P>
   There are other valuable touches: the inside covers feature
weight and measurement equivalents (although they are repeated in
front and back, rather than offering different information), the
vegetable section opens with an eight-page chart offering buying
and storing guidelines, and the index actually lists the very
things many beginners will search for. Turn to ``simmering,'' for
example, and indeed, it is referenced.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Learning to Cook'' is far from complete, lacking overviews
of herbs and spices, basic cooking techniques, meat and fish, and
the most common substitutions. Although Ms. Cunningham rises to
many inherent challenges, she assumes that readers will understand
a phrase like ``fillet of red snapper or other white fish.''
</P>
<P>
   She instructs the cook to stir risotto ``constantly,'' evidently
believing either that the new cook will somehow interpret this as
``nearly constantly'' or ``frequently,'' or that truly constant
stirring is necessary. (It is not.)
</P>
<P>
   Kudos to her for including brown butter sauce (beurre noisette),
an often overlooked classic. But why is it placed next to an
unrelated recipe, rather than in the ``Extras'' chapter, which
includes other sauces?
</P>
<P>
   In general, the book's design and organization contribute little
to the learning process, and sidebars are overused, muddling rather
than enhancing many pages.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, there are inconsistencies, unnecessary steps and
downright errors. A headnote says that the ``secret'' of scrambled
eggs is low heat, but the recipe uses medium heat; this will
confuse any beginner.
</P>
<P>
   Scallions are not immature onions. Beans need not be soaked
overnight before cooking. To hard-boil eggs, they need not be
cooked 20 minutes. Vegetable shortening is not the best fat for
anything.
</P>
<P>
   When a chicken is roasted to the point where its breast is at
170 to 180 degrees, it is overcooked to the point of inedibility.
Thickening curries and stews with flour is an unneeded step. And so
on.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Learning to Cook'' is friendly, warm and genuinely
encouraging. There's much to be said for a book that gets people
into the kitchen _ if only it offered better guidance once they
were there. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN MEATLOAF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { bunch fresh spinach (washed, coarse stems removed, leaves
gently pressed)
</P>
<P>
   2 slices white bread
</P>
<P>
   1 large yellow onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ground beef (about 20 percent fat)
</P>
<P>
   \ pound ground pork
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   { cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons ground allspice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Chop spinach into {-inch pieces.
Pull bread into large pieces, and place in a food processor;
process a few seconds to make crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large mixing bowl, combine spinach, bread crumbs, onion,
beef, pork, eggs and milk. Sprinkle in salt, pepper and allspice.
Using your hands, lightly mix just until ingredients are evenly
distributed. Divide mixture in half.
</P>
<P>
   3. Set portions side by side in a 9-by-13-inch baking dish. Form
each into a round, 6 or 7 inches by 2 inches high. Don't pat down.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake 25 minutes. Pierce center of a loaf with small knife; if
it is still pink, cook 5 minutes more and test again. Remove from
oven, and let rest 10 minutes. Remove to a serving platter, cut
into 1-inch slices and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
