A9144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MILLENNIUM0929-COX     09-28 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM0929-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PLANS ANNOUNCED FOR MILLENNIUM CELEBRATION IN NATION'S CAPITAL
 &HT;    With Photo
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Promising ``no ordinary party'' for ``no ordinary
time,'' First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on Tuesday invited
America to a Y2K bash in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music of our century will be rocking and rolling, swinging and
soaring through the air,'' said Mrs. Clinton in announcing details
of a three-day event called ``America's Millennium: A Celebration
for the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, actor and rapper Will Smith will host a show
at the Lincoln Memorial that will be televised live on CBS,
beginning at 10 p.m. (EST) The program will include an 18-minute
film highlighting the 20th Century that will be produced by Steven
Speilberg. Half an hour before midnight, the movie entitled ``The
Unfinished Journey'' will premiere on giant outdoor screens as an
orchestra plays an original score by composer John Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of ``America's Millennium'' said in a statement that
``great stars of the entertainment world will perform'' but would
only confirm appearances by Aretha Franklin, Chuck Berry and Mickey
Hart (former drummer of the Grateful Dead). Producer George Stevens
Jr. conceded that many top entertainers have long been booked for
millennium appearances _ Barbra Streisand, for example _ but he
predicted plenty of celebrity power at the D.C. event.
</P>
<P>
   The show will be ``extravagantly entertaining,'' Stevens vowed.
He said the show will be an ``expression of what this country is
all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the producer of the movie ``The Thin Red Line'' and the
creator of the television events ``The Kennedy Center Honors'' and
``Christmas in Washington,'' will co-produce ``America's Millennium
Gala'' with composer and musician Quincy Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said President Clinton and the first lady will attend
the Lincoln Memorial affair. The televised event in Washington will
rival the traditional Times Square New Year's Eve celebration in
New York, where Mrs. Clinton currently is an undeclared candidate
for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, Stevens and District of Columbia Mayor Anthony
Williams announced the millennium plans at the Old Executive Office
Building, next door to the White House. They said $12.5 million has
been budgeted for the national events, with funding coming from
private donations and the sale of TV rights. The celebration will
begin on New Year's Eve of 1999 and last through Jan. 2, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the national celebration, Williams said the
District will sponsor a ``Main Street Millennium'' block party
along Constitution on Dec. 31. Despite fears that the Y2K bug might
render some computers useless, the mayor vowed that ``lights won't
go out'' and ``all systems are going to work.'' He urged tourists
to book hotel rooms early.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said ``America's Millennium'' will include the
unveiling of a national time capsule that will ``show future
generations how we lived and what we valued most in our time.'' At
the Ronald Reagan International Trade Center, located near the
White House, giant screens will show millennium celebrations and
events from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the new millennium will be heralded by a
``Midnight Moment'' of fireworks and a laser light display between
the Lincoln Memorial and Washington Monument. Organizers said they
could handle a crowd of more than 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   During all three days, Mrs. Clinton said, there will be free,
``family-friendly'' events on the Mall that will reflect the theme
of the White House Millennium Council to ``Honor the Past _ Imagine
the Future.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
