<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-NY-Y2K-RESTAURANTS-AR     09-28 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-Y2K-RESTAURANTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A NEW YEAR'S EVE FOR THE AGES, SOME RESTAURANTS WILL SIT IT
OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds., also filed in ``d'' news file.) 
(jt) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jo Jo, the deluxe Upper East Side restaurant,
celebrated New Year's Eve in characteristic style last year: it
opened early and kept going until 5 a.m., offering a fixed-price
dinner of $500 a head, plus wine. The restaurant was packed, for
each of two seatings, as night turned to dawn.
</P>
<P>
   And how will Jo Jo mark the New Year's Eve ushering in the year
2000? By shutting down for the night. The chef, Jean-Georges
Vongerichten, is locking up Jo Jo and his four other New York
restaurants and flying to Bali to spend his first New Year's Eve
out of the kitchen in 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   And that is not unusual. While many restaurants are planning
extravagantly prepared and stratospherically priced meals to mark
the passing of the 1900s, a growing number of New York's best
restaurants have quietly decided to stay dark for the night.
Gramercy Tavern, Union Pacific, Union Square Cafe, Balthazar, Vong,
Mercer Kitchen, Le Bernardin, Eleven Madison, Tabla, Judson Grill,
Aquavit, the Oyster Bar at Grand Central Terminal and Verbena are
among those turning away people calling for a reservation. Other
restaurateurs are considering shutting down on one of the year's
most profitable nights, weighing the financial benefits against
this year's unusual complications.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons reflect the anxiety felt by New Yorkers in general
as they contemplate the approaching New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously, there is the fear of rowdiness and drunken
revelers harassing customers and employees, especially in
restaurants anywhere near Times Square. (The owners of Local, a
plush new restaurant on West 47th Street, are not only closing, but
even boarding up the windows to guard against hooliganism.) Beyond
that, some of New York's most experienced restaurateurs are worried
about customer expectations that can never be met, employees who
would resent having to work and the promise of high-priced
everything, Champagne, caviar, entertainment, cutting down the
profit margin and stirring the resentment of their regular
clientele because of the inevitably huge tabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We foresee a lot of problems with the night,'' said Chris
Cannon, the general manager of Judson Grill, the highly rated
restaurant on West 52d Street in the heart of the district where
streets will be closed to traffic. ``Our attitude is, how much
money can you make in one night? We have a lack of confidence in
people getting to the restaurant effectively, about how much
business are we going to do and concern for our own staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Meyer, the owner of Gramercy Tavern, Union Square Cafe,
Eleven Madison and Tabla, said he had decided to close his
restaurants after concluding that there was no way he could meet
``the overblown expectations'' that people were sure to bring in
the door. ``Somebody is not going to get the best table in the
restaurant,'' Meyer said. ``Someone is not going to like the size
of the piece of foie gras and the dollop of caviar or the band you
picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be the best night out that you've ever had in your
life, or it's a failure,'' Meyer added. ``The evening is going to
cost so much money, and people are going to feel so ripped off
anyway, so why do it? If we weren't going to make money, if we
weren't going to make our guests happy, if we weren't going to make
our staff happy, then why open?''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, word that some restaurateurs are taking the
night off (or, like Le Cirque 2000, are opening but donating the
proceeds to charity) is stirring some resentment among those
restaurateurs who are looking forward to what has always been one
of the biggest moneymaking nights of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute they say, `We're not opening, we want to be fair to
our employees,' that is a really unfair thing to do to everyone
else,'' said Drew Nieporent, whose restaurants include Montrachet,
Nobu, Layla, TriBeCa Grill and Berkeley Bar and Grill. ``Also, to
create the charitable thing, I respect that, I really do. But we
live by the adage that the show must go on. This is an important
day for us. That's the way we pay our bills. If we all wanted to
play hooky on a major holiday, what would happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, closing on New Year's Eve could not have
been an easy decision, at least to judge by the menu prices that
have been announced so far. Lespinasse is charging $2,500 a person
for its late-night dinner, including wine and service. (If that's
too pricey, there's a discounted meal of just $1,700 a head, with a
more modest selection of wines.)
</P>
<P>
   Dinner at Daniel will be $1,250, plus wine. At Chanterelle,
Karen and David Waltuck are planning a black-tie dinner, which will
include a wine from each decade of the 20th century, at a cost of
around $2,500 a head. ``This only happens once in a while, right?''
Ms. Waltuck observed.'' It's a pretty big nut to crack for our
clients. But I figured I should go all out.'' (So far, reservations
can still be booked at most of these high-price restaurants.)
</P>
<P>
   It is also doubtful that any restaurant would have any problem
selling out: letting someone else do the work has always been the
best way to have fun on New Year's Eve. Sirio Maccioni, the owner
of Le Cirque 2000, said that 1,000 people had already called to put
themselves on his New Year's Eve waiting list, even though he has
yet to announce a single detail about the night, from menu to cost.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic incentives to open are less strong this year
than usual. For one, there's the expected high cost of supplies for
the night. For another, this has been a good year in the business,
which means that owners can afford to take a night off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a great year at Aquavit,'' said Hakan Swahn, the
owner of the Scandinavian restaurant in midtown. ``I feel the least
we can do is say to our staff that worked, `It's the millennium,
enjoy yourself: we'll see you in the next millennium.'''
</P>
<P>
   And the prospective profits are being weighed against a growing
concern among business owners in New York, who are beginning to
worry about just what the streets of Manhattan will be like that
evening. ``The level of clientele that we cater to is not going to
be frequenting Times Square on New Year's,'' said Franklin Becker,
the chef at Local on West 47th Street. ``The people that are going
to be here are going to be transients. They are going to be young
kids with ill motives that aren't going to be able to afford our
restaurant. Quite frankly, to put our guests at risks or to put
anyone at risk, including our employees, for one evening, it just
doesn't make any sense for us. We're putting braces behind the
windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bastianich, an owner of Babbo, said he has not made a
decision on what, if anything, to do. ``Is the potential downside
worth the potential revenue?'' he asked. ``The danger to people? I
don't know what it's going to be like.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, for all the concern voiced by restaurant owners,
there does appear to be an ultimate factor nudging these
restaurateurs to spend the night someplace else. After all, this is
a millennial moment. Who wants to work?
</P>
<P>
   Vongerichten, for instance, is designing the menu for a
particularly large celebration at the Javits Center, but has no
plans to be near Manhattan that night. ``I never took off a New
Year's Eve,'' he said. ``I deserve it. I'm giving it to myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
