<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-VERMONT-CHEDDAR-ART-2     09-28 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-CHEDDAR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEESE WITH A KEENER NIP THAN AUTUMN IN VERMONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAFTON, Vt. _ (italics)Slap. Slap. Slap. Slap.(end italics)
It's the only sound made by the cheese makers as they go about
their work flipping 30-pound strips of glistening milk curds, the
color of rich cream, in stainless steel vats. On the first day of
autumn in this almost too perfect New England town, cheddaring is
under way at the Grafton Village Cheese Co. It is a magical process
that turns liquid into gold.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning into a vat, I catch a sweet milk aroma that has begun to
take on a slightly nutty fragrance. Scott Fletcher, the cheese
maker at the plant since it opened in 1963, lets me sample the warm
curd, and it has the soothing, delicate texture and taste of a
freshly made ball of mozzarella.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine that this mellowness will ever become the
pungent, extra-sharp, crumbly perfection that is sold as Vermont
Cheddar, America's best sharp cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Cheddar isn't just a noun and an adjective, but also a verb. In
the last instance, it describes the technique perfected in Cheddar,
in the West Country of England, for extracting the moisture (the
whey) from the solids (the curds) to make one of the world's
greatest cow's milk cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   In the dairy state of Vermont, cheddaring began in the early
1800s as a way for farmers to use up surplus milk, but today only a
few farmers are still at it. In part, this is a story of small
farms versus agribusiness, and nature versus science.
</P>
<P>
   But it does have a happy ending. On the palate.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Cheddar is different from English Cheddar, but to cheese
experts like Steve Jenkins, who wrote ``Cheese Primer'' (Workman,
1996), they are equal.
</P>
<P>
   Making Cheddar cheese begins with warming the milk and adding
rennet, which is what causes curds to form. Soon the milk resembles
custard, which firms up and then can be cut with steel wires to
form thousands of one-inch squares. The whey separates from the
curd and is drained away. The curd, now with the appearance of
cottage cheese, is pushed to either side of the vat, where it
bonds, and cut into those 30-pound slabs.
</P>
<P>
   There will be several turnings and tests for acidity before the
cheese is ready for milling, when the slabs are cut into
finger-length strips. Salting, pressing, wrapping and aging follow.
The longer a Cheddar ages, the more intense the flavor and the
greater the price it can command _ a lot depends on the skill of
the cheese maker. In the meantime, it keeps money tied up,
something today's small dairy farmers cannot afford to do.
</P>
<P>
   As long ago as the early 1900s, improvements in transportation
and delivery allowed many farmers to begin marketing milk instead
of cheese and butter. Now, after years of consolidation, only
Grafton, the Cabot Cooperative Creamery in Cabot, Shelburne Farms
in Shelburne and the Seward Family Farm in East Wallingford make
Vermont Cheddar.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, Sugarbush Farm and Butterworks Farm, sell Vermont
Cheddar made for them by others. Add one goat Cheddar and two
mild-mannered Cheddar relatives _ Colby from Crowley in Healdville,
and the stirred curd cheese from the Plymouth Cheese Factory in
Plymouth _ and you have the sum total of Vermont Cheddar cheese.
</P>
<P>
   It is a cheese in great demand. As Americans have become more
sophisticated about food, they have become more interested in the
subtlety of complex flavors. In the early 1990s Grafton's most
popular cheese was the mild one-year-old Cheddar; today it is the
sharper two-year-old. Three-year-old is coming up fast, and there
is enough demand for four-year-old cheese that it will soon be part
of the company's repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four Cheddar makers, only Shelburne Farms and the Seward
Family Farm make farmstead cheeses using their own milk. Most
farmstead cheeses in Vermont (and there are more and more each
year) come from goats and sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Grafton's cheese making falls somewhere between the entirely
automated process at Cabot's Middlebury plant and the method used
by Butch Seward: feel, touch, smell and look. At Cabot, a family
farm cooperative that merged in 1992 with the largest dairy co-op
in the Northeast, Agri-Mark, ``the milk never sees the light of day
from the time it leaves the cow,'' a point of pride for Tom Harty,
the company's consumer communications manager. Others phrase it
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabot's milk is never touched by human hands,'' said Peter
Mohn, Grafton's vice president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Cabot produces 55 million pounds of cheese a year. Grafton makes
1.2 million pounds, and by January will increase production to 1.5
million pounds. Shelburne Farms, which began making cheese in 1982,
produces less than 100,000 pounds. And the Seward Family Farm,
which has existed since the mid-1800s and has made cheese since
1938, produces only about 40,000 pounds of fresh cheese curd,
selling half of it outright and turning the rest into Cheddar.
</P>
<P>
   Grafton produced Cheddar from the 1890s until the plant burned
down in 1912. It did not start up again until the nonprofit Windham
Foundation began to restore the village center in Grafton in the
1960s. Like many small Vermont towns, Grafton went into a steep
decline as people went elsewhere in search of work. As part of the
restoration, it seemed logical to erect a cheese plant that would
help to employ people.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also restored the Old Tavern, the inn in Grafton,
and about half of the hundred-plus houses and rented them out. The
rest are privately owned, but all are freshly painted and have
well-tended lawns and flower gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The town, which now has about 600 inhabitants, is every
flat-lander's fantasy of a typical Vermont setting, in much better
shape than most of them. The modern plant is slightly removed from
the 19th-century village, down a winding road beside a stream and
just past a covered bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Shelburne Farms, on the shore of Lake Champlain, has become an
agricultural trust and also benefits from the backing of a
nonprofit foundation. Seward, the only Cheddar processor without
the resources of the big three, is barely holding on. It once had
eight vats producing two batches a day each, but is now down to one
vat every two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were once the third- or fourth-largest creamery in the
state,'' Seward said as he stirred curd in the vat. ``Now we're
down to nothing. Big business just started choking us.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the difficulty of competing, Vermont's Agriculture
Department, which helps farmers looking for any way to earn a
living that will permit them to stay on the farm, recommends that
they make their cow's milk into other cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the blame,'' said Elisa Clancy, the dairy marketing
specialist for the department. ``It's one of the reasons we don't
have a lot of farmstead Cheddars. I tell them it's easier to be the
new kid on the block with a fontina rather than a Cheddar. Why
compete with a Shelburne or a Cabot or a Grafton?''
</P>
<P>
   Grafton, in a bow to efficiency that speeds up the cheese making
process, heat-treats the milk before it goes into the vats. Purists
say this compromises the taste of the cheese because it kills some
of the bacteria and destroys some of the aromatic esters that give
subtlety to the cheese. Others say it prevents the ``off'' flavors
sometimes found in raw-milk cheese and yields a more consistent
product.
</P>
<P>
   Pasteurization, which requires a higher temperature, destroys
all bacteria and esters, leaving the cheese more one-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pasteurization is the death of milk and therefore the death of
cheese,'' said Jenkins, the cheese expert and writer.
</P>
<P>
   Shelburne's Cheddar is made from raw milk. Cabot, like Seward,
uses pasteurized milk. Harty said Cabot began pasteurizing four
years ago because of potential problems from harmful bacteria and
also to get fresh Cheddar to market earlier. Unpasteurized cheese
must be aged at least 60 days before it can be sold. Harty said
there is ``absolutely no difference in taste.'' Some processors
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Cheese makers also disagree on the bovine growth hormone
question. The state passed a law requiring all dairy producers to
label their products either ``rBGH free'' or ``contains rBGH.'' The
law was overturned in court but is still a sore subject.
</P>
<P>
   Of the big three Cheddar cheese makers, only Cabot refuses to
certify its milk as rBGH-free. Labeling cheese as rBGH-free is
``morally objectionable,'' Harty said, adding, ``It is immoral and
misleading to give consumers false assurance, because you cannot
scientifically prove or disprove the presence of rBGH.''
</P>
<P>
   Grafton, on the other hand, gets affidavits from its suppliers
swearing they use no growth hormone. Shelburne and Seward do not
use the hormone in their cows.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the aging of Vermont Cheddars is done in Cryovac
packaging because the old paraffin-lined foil wrap once used by
cheese makers is no longer available. ``I would prefer it,'' said
Mohn of Grafton, ``because aging in Cryovac may not be the best
way. Logically, when you age in Cryovac there should be some flavor
transference from the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other way to age Cheddar is in a cloth in a cave, the
method Shelburne Farms adopted two years ago. Cloth wrapping
produces a Cheddar closer to the English style, with flavors that
some consider ``off'' but that others seek out: grass, hay, corn,
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The cheeses also tend to be drier, more crumbly and sharper,
because they have been aged longer and often have bits of a grainy
substance that is some of the amino acid that develops as the
cheese ages. Shelburne charges much more for this cheese, its pride
and joy, than for its top cheese aged in plastic, because it
requires so much more handling.
</P>
<P>
   Cabot also ages 23-pound wheels in cloth for about a year and
calls them Hunter's, selling the cheese to country stores where, by
tradition, huge wheels of ``rat cheese'' have always been kept on
the counter under glass (plastic now), with wedges hacked off as
customers request them. Cabot sells Hunter's for less than its best
cheeses because it considers them less than desirable.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the Seward solution: selling salted strips of
curd before they are turned into cheese. Chewing on what is called
squeaky curd or squeaky cheese is a favorite pastime of Vermonters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you can stay in the cheese business is to have
some specialty,'' Seward said. ``The cash flow is a hell of a lot
better than putting it on the shelf for a year.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Cheddars vary widely in flavor, but the fine aged ones
should be treated like a fine Stilton. Serve at room temperature,
and savor them in small bites. Instead of port, choose either a
robust red like sangiovese or Barolo, a big cabernet sauvignon or
merlot, a spicy zinfandel, a gewurztraminer or a riesling.
</P>
<P>
   I tried a number of cheeses, and these tasting notes are in
order of preference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRAFTON EXTRA SHARP Firm and creamy; round with clear finish.
</P>
<P>
   GRAFTON GOLD Robust, acidic and very sharp.
</P>
<P>
   SHELBURNE CLOTH WRAPPED Strong, moldy English farm flavor.
</P>
<P>
   SHELBURNE FARMSTEAD Herbal; deeply flavored.
</P>
<P>
   CABOT HUNTER'S CLOTH WRAPPED Very strong and sharp; acidic.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERWORKS FARM Young, very mild and creamy.
</P>
<P>
   SEWARD FAMILY Young, pleasantly creamy and mild.
</P>
<P>
   SUGARBUSH FARM Creamy.
</P>
<P>
   CABOT PRIVATE STOCK Pleasant, but no complexity.
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT BUTTER AND CHEESE GOAT MILK CHEDDAR Goat flavor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEESE SHORTIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus chilling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound extra-sharp Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   { pound unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   A few dashes cayenne pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Using an electric mixer or food processor, cream the cheese
and butter until thoroughly mixed. Add the flour and cayenne, and
mix thoroughly. Shape into rolls 1 inch in diameter. Wrap in wax
paper or plastic wrap, and chill at least 1 hour or overnight, or
wrap in aluminum foil and freeze.
</P>
<P>
   2. To serve, preheat oven to 400 degrees. Let the frozen rolls
defrost in the refrigerator for at least a couple of hours or
overnight. Cut the thawed or chilled rolls into slices one-third
inch thick and place them on ungreased cookie sheets 1 inch apart.
Bake about 10 minutes, until light brown on bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 48 wafers.
</P>
</TEXT>
