202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-CPB-CHAIRMAN. Newly elected Corporation for Public
Broadcasting Chairman Frank Cruz said one of his top priorities is
to do what the networks aren't -- bring diversity to television.
(650 words.) By Jill Carroll
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-MUSEUM. Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colorado,
dressed in full American Indian regalia, helped kick off the
ground-breaking of the American Museum of the Indian American today
in Washington. (800 words.) By Tania Anderson
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-CENSUS. Although Florida remains home to one of the
nation's largest Hispanic populations, other parts of the South are
showing impressive strides in attracting Hispanics, according to a
recent report by the U.S. Census Bureau. (Working, 700 words.) By
Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-AUGUSTA-MORRIS. In the age of the Internet, publisher
William S. Morris III said Tuesday he is confident that newspapers
will be able to capitalize on the technological advances and keep
their hold as an invaluable information source for their readers.
As chairman of the Newspaper Association of American, Morris spoke
at a National Press Club luncheon. (12-15 inches.) By Elizabeth
Hurt
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA-WATERWAYS. Indiana will receive more than $16 million in
funding for several waterway projects in Northwest Indiana. (300
words.) By Tania Anderson
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS-SMILEY. The U.S. Postal Service will unveil a
smiley-face stamp on Friday. Designer Harvey Ball of Worcester will
be on hand. (400 words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS-CYPRUS. The Cypriot ambassador to the United
States is cautious about resolving the long-standing dispute over
the Mediterranean island. (400 words.) C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   NEW MEXICO-MUSEUM. The signature image chosen to mark the
ground-breaking of the National Museum of the American Indian came
from the talent of New Mexican Tony Abeyta -- and he wasn't the
only state citizen at the event. Dozens of New Mexican American
Indians were there, many of them involved with the museum.
(Working, about 500 words.) By Jonathan Lipman
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-BUDGET. With the new fiscal year rapidly approaching,
Wyoming lawmakers said next year's budget must maintain spending
limits and protect surplus social security funds (600 words.) By
Barney McManigal
</P>
