A9181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-HEALTH-DRUGS-COX     09-28 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-DRUGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A THIRD OF MEDICARE BENEFICIARIES SAID TO LACK PRESCRIPTION DRUG
COVERAGE
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly one-third of the nation's Medicare
beneficiaries have no prescription drug coverage, a House panel was
told Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In rural areas, the percentage of seniors without coverage is
suspected to be greater, said Michael Hash, deputy administrator
for the Health Care Financing Administration, the federal agency
that overseas Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress considering how to reform Medicare, proponents and
opponents of expanding the program to include prescription drug
coverage clashed at a hearing of the subcommittee on health and
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind it is unconscionable to ask the neediest
beneficiaries to wait for prescription drugs while we continue to
debate the broader problems facing the Medicare program,'' said
subcommittee chairman Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But Gail Wilensky, a former HCFA administrator who is now with
Project Hope, the humanitarian group, argued that to add a drug
benefit which ``would substantially increase the spending needs of
a program that is already financially fragile without addressing
other issues of reform is a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   While most Medicare beneficiaries have some drug coverage either
through supplemental ``Medigap'' policies or through
employer-sponsored benefits, the coverage is often inadequate
because of higher copayments, deductibles and premiums, Hash said.
</P>
<P>
   According to 1995 government estimates, Medicare beneficiaries
on average filled 18 prescriptions and spent $600 a year on drugs,
Laura Dummit, a Government Accounting Office analyst, told the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed a plan that would add a voluntary
drug benefit option for Medicare beneficiaries that would pay half
the patient's monthly premiums and half the cost of prescriptions
up to $2,000 beginning in 2002 and increasing to $5,000 in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the administration plan warned it would give
government, managed care groups and drug companies too much control
over what medications Americans could receive.
</P>
<P>
   Wilensky noted there is disagreement about how much the
president's plan would cost. While the administration puts the cost
at $118 billion over the next ten years, the Congressional Budget
Office estimates it will take $168 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., suggested the president put more
pressure on the Food and Drug Administration to approve more
generic drugs that would be less expensive, urge drug manufacturers
and pharmaceutical groups to provide more group discounts and speak
to physicians about providing alternatives to expensive medications
for their patients.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
