<P>
   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ A lot of us expect, or at least hope, that we can
retire before we reach age 65. Recent research, however, strongly
suggests that many of the hopefuls are talking through their hats.
They haven't invested very much, nor have they tried to estimate
what income they will have or will need. Many know little about
their pensions, if they have them. A large percentage think they
will be eligible for full Social Security benefits long before they
actually will. That does not mean that the unprepared will serve a
life sentence in the salt mines. It does mean they are in for some
brain-shaker surprises if they don't start working on the problem
before they get much older.Personal finance advice. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
