<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAD-KIDSPARTIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE DAD MAKES A CASE FOR THE SIMPLE BUT MEANINGFUL BACKYARD BASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The public-address system is an essential feature of today's
birthday parties for kids. Across the requisite loudspeaker come
messages like the following: ``Everyone here for Tiffany's birthday
party, please report to Party Room 3 for cake, ice cream and
presents,'' or some such.
</P>
<P>
   Only then do Tiffany's little friends slide from the tunnels and
pry themselves from the video games, to actually come together and
pay homage to the birthday girl. It's an obligation, this amplified
call to duty, the price a kid has to pay for free admission and a
pouch full of game tokens handed out by the party hosts. Tiffany
and her birthday are pretty much afterthoughts. How can something
so quaint compare with the adrenaline rush of killing space
invaders in the arcade?
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I feel something has been lost as birthday parties
have moved from the living room to the amusement house. Birthday
parties were once an excuse for kids to get together ``and stay
together'' in fairly large numbers _ to have a blast away from the
burdensome rules of the classroom. Birthday parties were once about
making a boy or a girl the absolute center of attention for a
morning or an afternoon, a prince or princess for a day.
</P>
<P>
   But now kids are summoned over the loudspeaker, and a stranger,
albeit a cheery teen-ager in a funny hat, lights the candles in the
party room, and the presents are ripped through so the kids can
rush back out into the amusement jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. Places like the Discovery Zone are great for
rainy days. I've spent some time in the tunnels myself. (Always use
the kneepads.) But in my book, birthday parties belong at home, or
in a park, with the kids together and a pinata hung from the branch
of a tree. It seems no small feat that the depersonalization of our
world extends to even this.
</P>
<P>
   There are downsides to a party at home. The work involved, for
one thing. Balloons to be blown up and hung with the crepe paper;
pizzas and cake ordered (or made). Then, when the proverbial dust
has cleared, the cleanup, with no perky teen-agers in funny hats
around to help.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of a party game plan, figuring out
stuff for kids to do. This was not a problem for my son's party in
July, for we are blessed with a small swimming pool in our back
yard. Ten boys were happily captive there for several hours. That,
plus a few pieces of pizza, cake and ice cream, and the opening of
presents and you have your basic boffo birthday bash, memories of
which still cause my 8-year-old to smile. All of his best buddies
were there. They played together all day. He was made to feel a
king.
</P>
<P>
   Those without pools or without other built-in diversions face a
bigger challenge. Bobbing for apples no longer is really an option
(was it ever?). Nor is pin the tail on the donkey (am I really that
old?). But there are books out there with plenty of good ideas for
home parties. Further, I'm of the opinion that if you throw 10
young friends together under one roof, or out in the back yard,
they'll think of something. Just make sure that anything breakable
is put away first.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that having your child's birthday party at
home precludes a certain amount of extravagance. I submit the
recent party of Sam, son of Steve and Julie, as an example.
</P>
<P>
   At this memorable fete, Tharpo the Clown took the place of
bobbing for apples. Mom's Hallmark moment came when Tharpo costumed
her beaming 5-year-old with a balloon hat, balloon sword and
balloon holster for the dagger, and a balloon parrot for Sam's
shoulder. For the balance of his hourlong performance, Tharpo told
jokes, juggled balls and was heckled by his young audience. Then
came the so-called big trick, which the clown performed after
repeatedly warning his audience not to try this at home. While
standing on a small teeter-totter, and balancing a glass of water
on his forehead, Tharpo juggled three machetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was in our family room,'' Steve told me later, still
incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a good bet Sam will remember being 5. He was at home,
his good friends all around, Tharpo the Clown defying death. A
prince for a day. As birthday parties go, no amusement house _ with
its PA system, its arcade, its maze of tunnels _ could possibly
compete.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
