<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SEWING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER SURVIVORS GATHER TO SEW, NOT TO WEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRIS WORRELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ They talk about blind stitches and borders. They
talk about lattice stitches and layers.
</P>
<P>
   And, occasionally, they talk about the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The eight women who have come together at Albany Medical Center
to create a large, colorful quilt have all been touched by the
disease, seven as survivors and one as a caretaker. But they don't
come to weep. They come to sew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want a group that talked about the illness,'' says
Marilyn Seidenberg, 57, a breast cancer survivor. ``I joined one
group and they really talked about what they were going through,
and I couldn't do that. I would come out depressed. Because I
didn't want to dwell on it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't talk about our illness each week here. We just
focused on this,'' she says, pointing to the beautiful wall-hanging
quilt, a lively kaleidoscope of color, ribbon, soft sculpture,
feathers and applique.
</P>
<P>
   The women are part of a workshop organized by Pen &AMP; Palette, a
nonprofit organization here that uses the visual and written arts
to raise awareness of the issues of cancer survivorship. The
project has been funded in part by a grant from the Susan G. Komen
Breast Cancer Foundation with money raised at the Albany Race for
the Cure, and by the United Order True Sisters Inc. Abigail No. 3,
a national women's charitable organization.
</P>
<P>
   The quilt, called ``Woman Healing into Wholeness,'' has 12
panels, each different from the next but all cohesive, form the
quilt, which is about 6-feet by 6-feet in size.
</P>
<P>
   At the center is a woman with six arms, a serene face and a bald
head. Water billows up from the bottom and washes onto the woman's
feet. Red and purple flowers encircle her neck and wrists. Stars
and tiny angels swirl through the ocean of pale clouds around her
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a group effort,'' says Margaret Roberts, a free-lance
designer who founded Pen &AMP; Palette in 1995 after losing a sister to
breast cancer. ``A couple of people came up with the idea of having
six different arms because it takes a lot of juggling to cope with
cancer. We thought of the woman being grounded in water and earth,
so we decided to use earth colors and blues. And we thought of her
as rising out of these more murky, chaotic shapes into an open air,
more hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   The group began the quilt last March, meeting once or twice a
month and working individually at home. And although some members
dropped out along the way, others joined, so there were always
hands ready to do the work. Each woman designed and sewed her own
panel _ some by machine, some by hand _ and incorporated symbols
that had personal meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to put gold hair on it,'' explains Jeanette
Pace, a retired art teacher who made the woman's face. ``And I
said, `I need it bald,' because the thing that bothered me more
than anything was losing my hair. It's not an easy thing to look at
yourself for so many years and then all of a sudden it's no longer
there. You're different.''
</P>
<P>
   Pace, 63, was diagnosed in March 1998 with a rare form of
leukemia. By May, she had lost all her hair from chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this means cancer: no hair,'' she says. After eight
months of chemotherapy, there was no sign of Pace's cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 80 percent chromosomes that were abnormal in March, they
were 100 percent normal in November,'' says Pace, who now has a
healthy crop of gray hair. ``I went out and bought myself a sewing
machine the very next day.''
</P>
<P>
   For these women, the quilt is a symbol of both a personal
struggle and a group triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Seidenberg says the women have a positive attitude. ``It's not
the cancer that brings us together. We don't hang around toxic
people who sit there every week and complain, `Oh, I'm going
through such hell.'
</P>
<P>
   Pace, while pinning a swatch of fabric on the quilt, shakes her
head vigorously. ``No, no. Our whole thing is, we're doers. We're
going to get this done, we're going to get other things done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who gave me a story about someone with cancer, I would
look ahead to what was at the end of it,'' continues Pace. ``And if
this person died, I wouldn't read it. I want to hear about people
healing. Because there are so many who have healed out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
