<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MAO _ BEIJING _ The Vanishing Mao. What's behind the minor
role to which Chairman Mao Tse-tung has been relegated in the
pre-anniversary propaganda. We're going to be watching: What is the
role of the man who masterminded the revolution in its anniversary
celebration? After 50 years, the cult has been quashed, the
mistakes of Mao are admitted openly (the Great Leap Forward, the
Cultural Revolution), and the great national savior has diminished.
Now he is given less credit than the late leader Deng Xiaoping.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/CHINA-STATS _ BEIJING _ Statistics that show how China has
changed since the founding of the People's Republic of China 50
years ago. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). 6. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CARDENAS-RESIGN _ MEXICO CITY _ Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, Mexico
City's mayor,
</P>
<P>
   submitted a letter of resignation Tuesday so that he can
dedicate himself to his third presidential campaign. Mexico City's
Legislative Assembly must approve the resignation before Cardenas
officially steps down more than a year before his term ends.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED at 4:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ Bill Bradley unveils his health care proposal Tuesday
to voters in California. Details of the plan, with contrasts to Al
Gore's plan outlined earlier this year. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   w/BRAD-PROFILE _ CRYSTAL CITY, Mo. _ Personal profile of Bill
Bradley. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 65. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ In South Carolina Tuesday, John McCain has breakfast in
Greenville, and another kick-off address in front of the carrier
Yorktown in Charleston. While he's in Charleston he'll have a
cyberchat with virtual children across the country. Then he'll go
to a farm outside Columbia for a barbecue. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-MONEY _ ATLANTA _ With a flurry of direct mail and a
decisive vision for the future, private citizen Newt Gingrich's new
political action committee raised more than $1 million the first
half of this year. But a July divorce declaration in Cobb County
and rumors of an affair with a 33-year-old congressional aid could
put Gingrich's future fund-raising exploits at risk. Grass-roots
donors to Friends of Newt Gingrich PAC, especially older donors,
say Gingrich's personal life disappoints them, so much so that they
aren't likely to open their pockets to his causes again. ``There's
too much monkey business out there and that just shows he's one of
them,'' said George Boomer, a 79-year-old retiree from Minnesota
who gave FONG $300 early this year. (Stanford, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in the (p) politcal category
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-DRUGS _ WASHINGTON _ Nearly one-third of the nation's
Medicare beneficiaries have no prescription drug coverage, a House
panel was told Tuesday. In rural areas, the percentage of seniors
without coverage is suspected to be greater, said Michael Hash,
deputy administrator for the Health Care Financing
Administration.With Congress considering how to reform Medicare,
proponents and opponents of expanding the program to include
prescription drug coverage clashed at a hearing of the subcommittee
on health and environment. (Schultz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WRITING-TEST _ The writing skills of public school
eighth-graders are above the national average in Texas and
Colorado, at or around the national average in Georgia and North
Carolina, and lower than the national average in Florida, according
to an embargoed copy of a NAEP report on the biggest writing test
in U.S. history, which the Department of Education is to release at
11 a.m. Tuesday 9/28. Since Ohio is one of the 15 states that
declined to pay extra for a large enough sample to get state-level
results, it will get a national lede. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   w/WRITING-DATA _ For textbox or simple graphic on national and
state results.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: No scores were compiled below the state level. (Mollison,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM _ WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Clinton unveils
plans for the Millennium celebration on the National Mall. It is
expected to rival Times Square as the focal point for Americans to
ring in the New Year and the next century. (Dart, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE _ WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration will announce
a $20 million Welfare-to-Work program to identify about 10,000
welfare recipients for employment in time for the 2000 Census.
(Lipman, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NEW-FLOODING _ More rain and flash flooding hamper cleanup,
inspection efforts. (Rocky Mount Telegram or Greenville Daily
Reflector).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-VOLUNTEERS _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ It came in the form of
barbecued pork, warm blankets and 10,000 loaves of bread. It arose
from farm soil, flowed in from other towns, resonated at churches
and multiplied at local stores. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). MOVED.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-TOBACCO _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Floyd completely flooded at
least three of Greenville's five tobacco warehouses, ruining all or
most of the leaf on the floor. With sales starting back up this
week, warehousers and farmers try to regroup. (Suggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-ARCHIVES _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Eastern office of the N.C.
Division of Archives loses records when basement was flooded.
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-SHELTERS _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Blacks and Hispanics make
up the bulk of people staying at shelters. Update on population and
numbers there. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-JOBLESS _ ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Unemployment in wake of
Floyd _ claims last week were 10 times higher than normal. (Rocky
Mount Telegram). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-TIPPER _ ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Tipper Gore, Jesse Jackson
visiting area. (Rocky Mount Telegram). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Tipper's visit is Tuesday afternoon; Jackson visit is
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE _ These are boom times in foster care and many child
advocates say the government is at fault. ``Money drives policy,''
said U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, considered on Capitol Hill to
be an expert on issues affecting children. He and others complain
that agencies have little incentive to take kids out of foster care
because of the federal government's open-ended commitment to pay
the bills no matter how long a child remains in the system. (Dayton
Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-MONEY _ ATLANTA _ With a flurry of direct mail and a
decisive vision for the future, private citizen Newt Gingrich's new
political action committee raised more than $1 million the first
half of this year. But a July divorce declaration in Cobb County
and rumors of an affair with a 33-year-old congressional aid could
put Gingrich's future fund-raising exploits at risk. Grass-roots
donors to Friends of Newt Gingrich PAC, especially older donors,
say Gingrich's personal life disappoints them, so much so that they
aren't likely to open their pockets to his causes again. ``There's
too much monkey business out there and that just shows he's one of
them,'' said George Boomer, a 79-year-old retiree from Minnesota
who gave FONG $300 early this year. (Stanford, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in the (p) politcal category
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON-BAN _ ATLANTA _Peachtree City elementary school bans
Pokemon cards at school. One-third to half of students were
bringing the cards to school. The games and trades were disrupting
things, school officials said. Some children were getting upset
over bad trades. (Donsky, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHARKS _ ATLANTA _ Shark populations that have declined by
almost 80 percent in the past few decades on the southeastern coast
worry recreational fishermen and charter boat captains, who say the
days of fishing for ``Jaws'' in Georgia are over. State and federal
laws now limit catches. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   ENCEPHALITIS _ ATLANTA _The encephalitis outbreak around the New
York City area is no longer just a local problem: Health officials
say birds flying south for the winter could spread the infection.
CDC has sent six scientists to New York to investigate the outbreak
and the threat of it spreading. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
