<HEADER>
A9207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-FINANCIAL-NEWS-ADVISO     09-28 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCIAL-NEWS-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, managing editors, financial editors:
</P>
<P>
   Beginning tomorrow, and appearing every Wednesday, The New York
Times will feature two new pages of business coverage, the
 &UR; Workplace Page &LR; , dealing with the world of work in all aspects,
and the  &UR; Management Page &LR; , with new features about managers' skills
and experiences.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Workplace Page &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This page will consist of four columns of features. There will
be one main feature of 1,000-1,200 words and a shorter feature.
</P>
<P>
   The main feature will spotlight a trend or breaking story
concerning the workplace. Some of the categories for these stories
will involve hot and cold careers, pay and benefits, job hunting,
entrepreneurs/small business, and people who switch careers.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter feature will will cover these sorts of topics:
</P>
<P>
   _ A first-person account of his or her job entitled variously
``My Job,'' ``My Worst Job,'' ``My Fantasy Job,'' ``My Career
Switch,'' ``My Commute,'' ``My Boss,'' etc.
</P>
<P>
   _ A work-life column that will essentially look at how people
juggle their work responsibilities with the demands of their
personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Management Page &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This will consist of three columns of features. There will be
one main feature of 1,100 words or so and a shorter feature of
about 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   The main feature will spotlight an issue, trend or breaking
story concerning management. Some of the categories for these
stories will involve profiles of interesting managers, new
management theories and practices, prescriptions from outsiders on
how to fix a troubled company and what's new and interesting in
business schools.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter feature will cover these sorts of topics:
</P>
<P>
   _ A first-person article entitled ``The Boss,'' which will be an
account by an executive, as told to a reporter, of some memorable
experience. The subjects could include ``my first job,'' ``my
best/worst boss,'' ``my best/worst career move,'' ``my biggest
crisis,'' ``my biggest break,'' ``the best advice I ever got,''
``my rules to keep myself sane'' and so on.
</P>
<P>
   _ A column on management issues.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move Tuesday evenings for Wednesday release
and carry an ``f'' (financial) category code. They will be
described under the Financial header on the AM-NYT-BUDGET which
moves at about 2 p.m. Eastern Time.
</P>
</TEXT>
