<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers are likely Wednesday from the central Appalachians
through the Middle Atlantic states as a potent cold front pushing
through the Ohio Valley interacts with humid air in place over much
of the East. Some of the showers will be very heavy at times. Total
precipitation amounts by Thursday morning could be as much as 3
inches, with local flooding possible.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, behind the front, an area of cold rain will
overspread the upper Ohio Valley and the eastern Great Lakes. It
will also turn noticeably cooler as brisk winds from the northwest
usher in colder, less humid air. This crisp, Canadian air mass led
to a very chilly start Wednesday morning over the northern Plains
and even led to numerous record low temperatures in the
inter-mountain west Tuesday morning. Ample sun, however, will allow
afternoon readings in the western Dakotas to become very warm.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, moisture from the Gulf of Mexico will be lifted by
the tail end of a cold front, leading to scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the Gulf Coast into interior sections of Alabama
and Georgia. Florida will remain warm and humid with isolated
storms possible. There will also be a few showers in south Texas as
tropical moisture moves north from the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Following the first snow of the season for parts of the Colorado
Rockies on Tuesday, temperatures will rebound into the 60s
Wednesday as winds descend the mountains and warm. Farther west,
offshore flow will promote very warm readings in California, while
the Northwest will remain sunny and mild. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Autumn Snow &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grassy surfaces were whitened around Denver on Tuesday, while 4
inches of snow were measured in Cheyenne, Wyo. In most years, the
first snowflakes of the winter season reach these high-elevation
Western towns during late September when the relatively moist air
of the warm season combines with the first pools of chill from
northern latitudes. During winter, when the coldest air arrives in
the region, the supply of moisture is meager. As a result both,
Denver and Cheyenne exhibit maximal snowfall in fall and spring
with a relative minimum in winter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
