<SLUG> BC-COLONY-BOOK-REVIEW-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COLONY GIRL': NEARLY 15 AND READY FOR BUST-OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is an intersession that spans late childhood, when we are
experts at life so far, and early adolescence, when expertise
crumbles trying to find a way into the mysteries threatened by life
to come.
</P>
<P>
   It can be the time of a singular brief lucidity, a flash of
undeflected light just before the cloudy refractions of growing up.
It is a great watershed, and great novels have been written around
it: ``Huckleberry Finn,'' ``The Catcher in the Rye,'' J.G.
Ballard's ``Empire of the Sun,'' Marianne Wiggins' ``John Dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Various as these are, and none entirely fitting what has just
been said, they have one thing in common. They take the
child/adolescent out of adult protection and plunge him or her,
generally alone, into a foreign or at least unfamiliar world.
</P>
<P>
   For Huck it was life and death along the Mississippi and his
encounter, half a raft-length away, with Jim and slavery. For
Holden Caulfield it was a journey both out and in, though briefer
and less adventurous. For the boy in ``Empire'' it was life without
parents in a Japanese prison camp; for the children in ``John
Dollar'' it was being marooned on an island off Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The strangeness had a function. It forced the protagonist,
unprotected and unclouded by the familiar, to name life. It is a
hieratic power. Was the important thing about Eden that Adam and
Eve lived there or that they gave names to what lived there _ a
second act of Creation? Huck, Holden and the children in ``Empire''
and ``John Dollar'' open their eyes in an Edenlike newness (and in
some cases horror) and begin naming and creating.
</P>
<P>
   Here is another dazzling namer: Eve, the girl in ``Colony
Girl.'' She is nearly 15, a little older than the others. Living in
the Colony, an isolated religious commune in Iowa ruled by an
eccentric charismatic, she developed more slowly than they did.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is ready for bust-out, and Thomas Rayfiel's winning,
original and supremely intelligent novel follows it. Eve is
explorer and adventurer in transit between two countries: the
Colony, once familiar and now, to her maturing eyes, turned
foreign; and the world just outside, which she seizes on with the
wacky lucidity of a bright visitor from very far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colony Girl'' deals with two utterly different aspects of
Eve's traveling. There is the Colony and Gordon, its leader, who
subjects his followers to Spartan discipline while indulging
himself and getting rich. A dark portrait, by rights, yet tempered
by writing's power to make a thing not only itself but something
else besides.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, while Eve struggles to figure it all out, she
keeps sneaking into Arhat, the nearby town, to puzzle out a whole
other world: men, sex, love, the dazzlements of secular America,
and her own burgeoning powers.
</P>
<P>
   It should all be too much; too forced a juxtaposition and too
vulnerable to easy comedy or melodrama. Yet for all its gaudy
pattern, ``Colony Girl'' is seamless. Its most comic, hapless or
corrupt characters _ sometimes all three at once _ are no
caricatures. Eve's incandescent eye both etches and warms.
</P>
<P>
   What the book is most truly about is not, in fact, such matters
as Eve's falling in love simultaneously with a boy and his father,
or working on a road gang, or performing a striptease in a bar, or
burrowing into the Colony's secrets and breaking free by
threatening to expose Gordon's crooked arrangements with a town
official. What it is truly about is adolescent discovery and the
corkscrew byways that lead to it.
</P>
<P>
   Tying it all together is the tittuping flow of Eve's speculative
and wonderfully discordant narration. It is a stream that makes her
mishaps and odd victories into a journey and not just sights along
the way. No Mississippi runs through Arhat, Iowa, but here as in
``Huckleberry Finn'' the real river is the narrator's voice. What a
voice it is.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are her late-night chats with Gordon, sympathetically
indulgent of her probing, as if he, the great fraud, needed
occasional infusions of innocence. (Religious belief is not his
job, he tells her: It spoils his performer's concentration. ``Did
Jesus believe? I don't think so. He was too busy walking on the
water.'')
</P>
<P>
   There is her bungled effort to ``rescue'' a teen-age friend from
marrying Gordon. There is her never-quite-consummated affair with
Joey, a hunk who arouses her sexuality but is too timid to make use
of it. Also too dumb. He had a beautifully muscled back, she
reflects; more expressive, in fact, than his face.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly odder is her crush on Joey's father, a plump,
depressed widower. Only ostensibly; when she gets sickeningly drunk
at his son's party _ her first-time escape from the Colony _ his
kindness suggests that for a refugee the world can be a refuge. As
she clings to a tree he comes over to help.
</P>
<P>
   ```Herb.' He held out his hand. `Herb Biswanger.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Eve,' I answered, and substituted him for the tree trunk,
falling against his soft side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He braced himself to take me on, but didn't actually touch or
hold me. He just stood his ground while I slid down his shirtfront.
Finally I found his belt buckle and hung there.''
</P>
<P>
   He hoists her into his toolshed for a restorative blast from the
oxygen tank he keeps for his own shortness of breath. ``Everything
snapped into focus. My head was right on top of my body. Perfectly
centered. I looked down and saw how the rest of me all led up to
it, tapering to this one precious moment of being. I was a freshly
sharpened pencil.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately she begins to calculate how soon, since he is
middle-aged, they should start having babies. Gauzily ahead of the
game, that is, yet noting Herb's quick, involuntary glance at her
body, clad in a miniskirt that she had sneaked out of the Colony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave the same sort of look to his place,'' she says of his
toolshed. ``Women have bodies, men have places.'' Native shrewdness
and much more. Naming, adventuring, construing and misconstruing,
Eve will be all right; and the reader, delighted and astonished.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `COLONY GIRL'
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Rayfiel
</P>
<P>
   279 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
