<SLUG> BC-TV-POPULAR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV REVIEW: HIGH SCHOOL HORRORS: THE COOL VS. THE UNCOOL
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review; second review, of CBS'
`Work With Me,' after production notes.) 
(nk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nicole, the meanest of the cool blond girls at school, explains
the world to a friend. ``We live in the age of Gwyneth,'' she says,
``and that is the standard by which all things are judged.''
</P>
<P>
   You're not supposed to like Nicole (Tammy Lynn Michaels); she's
evil. A lot of viewers may not want to like ``Popular,'' WB's new
hourlong teen-age drama either, but the show is doing a lot of
things right. When was the last time a series started off with nine
complicated, well-developed characters, not including the colorful
faculty (Chad Lowe as Mr. Grant, for instance, saying ``My hair is
natural _ hey, I surf'')?
</P>
<P>
   The premise of ``Popular'' is that two very different high
school girls _ the popular Brooke (Leslie Bibb) and the unpopular
Sam (Carly Pope) _ are thrown together against their will when
Brooke's father and Sam's mother quickly meet, fall in love and get
engaged. But that doesn't happen until the end of the two-part
premiere (Wednesday night at 9 and Thursday night at 8). Before
that, Brooke and Sam have other encounters, beginning as lab
partners in biology class.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere's plot is mostly about a party at Brooke's house
that not everybody is invited to, a cool football player (Bryce
Johnson as Josh) who risks geekiness by auditioning for the class
musical and an overweight girl (Sara Rue, who is outstanding, as
Carmen) who probably won't make the cheerleading squad even though
she's clearly the most talented person trying out. Just to
demonstrate some interesting gender standards, Ron Lester plays
Sugar Daddy, a boy twice Carmen's size but part of the cool crowd,
maybe because of his hip-hop look and attitude. (All the young
stars of ``Popular'' are white, by the way.)
</P>
<P>
   The series is a little too literal and instructive at times,
especially when Sam is conducting her earnest video interviews.
Characters spell out the themes more than necessary, but they're
important themes, and the stories present adolescence as the
morally complex, emotionally draining experience it is.
</P>
<P>
   The show gives even blond queen-of-the-school Brooke more than a
few insecurities. Of course, this being Hollywood television, poor,
unpopular brunette Sam is every bit as much a knockout as Brooke
is; the blonde just gets the good lighting.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `POPULAR'
</P>
<P>
   WB, Wednesday at 9 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   Created by Ryan Murphy and Gina Matthews; Murphy, Ms. Matthews,
Greer Shephard and Michael M. Robin, executive producers; Phillip
M. Goldfarb, producer. Produced by Ryan Murphy Productions,
Roundtable Ink and the Shephard and Robin Company in association
with Touchstone Television.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Leslie Bibb (Brooke McQueen), Carly Pope (Sam McPherson),
Tamara Mello (Lily Esposito), Chad Lowe ( Grant), Christopher
Gorham (Harrison John), Bryce Johnson (Josh Ford), Tammy Lynn
Michaels (Nicole Julian), Ron Lester (Sugar Daddy Bernadino), Sara
Rue (Carmen Ferrara), Lisa Darr (Jane McPherson), Scott Bryce (Mike
McQueen).
</P>
<P>
   `WORK WITH ME'
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Wednesday at 8:30 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan Better (Kevin Pollak) quits his job at a large,
prestigious Wall Street law firm, he decides to join the tiny,
laid-back practice of his wife, Julie (Nancy Travis). But his
unglamorous new office doubles as the snack room and when he asks
about voice mail, Julie shouts ``Any messages?'' to his assistant.
(Things must be tough, since voice mail at home is now about $6 a
month.)
</P>
<P>
   So that's supposed to be the joke: how different life is at a
struggling little business. And just in case that isn't funny
enough, the joke is also that Jordan and Julie are now constantly
together, at home and at work, and that their respective
assistants, Stacey and Sebastian, are secretly dating each other.
The wacky neighbor is a masseur, or relaxation therapist.
</P>
<P>
   The first episode's conflict is Jordan's jealousy over Julie's
handsome on-the-make client Murray Epstein. This gives Jordan the
opportunity to make vulgar sexual remarks and gestures and gives
Julie the chance to threaten castration. ``Work With Me'' tries
very hard but it's sadly ordinary and a little tired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
