<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS FIND CAUSE FOR CHEER; THE QUIZ-SHOW GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the perspective of one full week of new shows, network
executives have already declared the new television season a
success. The big reason: The networks are down again in viewers,
but the decline is far less steep than it was last year at this
point.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like even louder whistling than usual as the
networks try to navigate the boneyard, but they have a point.
Compared with their performance last season, when younger viewers
were fleeing the networks in such numbers that several of their
executives wanted to sue the Nielsen ratings company for
malfeasance, the networks were all but steady in that department in
this season's first week.
</P>
<P>
   This is being seen not only as solid proof of a resurgence in
Nielsen competence, but also as an indication that, if nothing
else, a new television season still seems to pull viewers back from
their summerlong dalliance with cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at those summer numbers,'' said Garth Ancier, the
president of NBC Entertainment, citing weeks when cable dominated
the repeats offered on the networks, ``and it's great to see people
coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   According to numbers released by NBC Tuesday, viewing among the
18-to-49-year-old crowd, which most of the networks are so devoted
to, was off by only 6 percent from premiere week last year. That's
for the big four networks; include the two not-as-big networks, the
drop was only 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Why is that so good? Because the executives at one network, Fox,
still don't seem to realize that it's late September and they
really should be back at school. Fox plodded away with mostly
repeats for the first week.
</P>
<P>
   And the biggest network show of all, ``E.R.,'' wasn't even on
last week, as it was in the first week last season. So that's two
big reasons why the week should have shown a much bigger falloff.
</P>
<P>
   One reason it didn't was a show that was not on last season, the
25th anniversary of ``Saturday Night Live'' on NBC. It was the
week's unqualified smash, dominating three hours of prime time
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But every network (except Fox) had some good ratings news from
new shows last week. That good news came from hourlong dramas.
Nobody was talking about the new comedies, all of which attracted
laughter only of the derisive variety.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``Stark Raving Mad,'' though it wound up the highest-rated
of the new shows, was already facing talk of being in trouble
because it fared worse than any other comedy NBC has put in the
plum 9:30 Thursday night period in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the big winners were ABC's ``Once and Again'' and CBS's
``Now and Again,'' which, besides making ``again'' the most popular
new title word of the season, were leaders in the trend toward
drama. Both shows beat all competition in their first time on the
air, truly unusual for new shows not placed between two hits.
</P>
<P>
   That ``Now and Again'' had the most young adult viewers on
Fridays at 9 was called the week's most amazing development by a
number of executives Tuesday because CBS so rarely leads in that
category.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, which was led by the extraordinary ``Saturday Night Live''
special and its remaining hits on Thursday, was the leading network
for the week in almost every category. The other boost NBC received
came from its own new dramas, three of which got off to strong
starts: ``The West Wing,'' ``Third Watch'' and ``Freaks and
Geeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The other thing that the strong batch of new dramas had in
common was mostly good critical reaction. Both ``Again'' shows got
almost all favorable reviews, as did ``Freaks and Geeks.'' NBC's
``West Wing'' and ``Third Watch'' also had a number of positive
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the shows savaged by critics, like ``Stark Raving
Mad'' and ``Mike O'Malley'' on NBC, were mostly rejected by
viewers. (And critics are rarely predictors of television success.)
</P>
<P>
   They certainly haven't been in the case of Fox's ``Action,'' the
season's most widely praised new comedy, which has all but
disappeared in three weeks on the air. On Thursday it finished in
fifth place, behind even UPN. But that's the night UPN has
wrestling, and that looks like a solid hit for that network (even
without helpful critical notices).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the generally good news for most networks last week,
there were areas of deep concern. ABC saw its Tuesday night
comedies lose badly to NBC, a development it surely did not expect.
``It's Like, You Know'' at 8:30 looks especially vulnerable because
NBC's ``Third Rock From the Sun'' made a bit of comeback and buried
it.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC's Monday comedies are nearing the life-support stage.
Both ``Suddenly Susan'' and ``Veronica's Closet'' have clearly worn
out their welcomes with viewers after years in which NBC force-fed
them to viewers. ``Susan'' looks as if it may be the most actively
disliked show on any of the big networks.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in its second try this season, it drove away almost 30
percent of its already woefully low number of viewers. The show
even trailed far behind repeats of ``That 70's Show'' on Fox. WB's
`'Seventh Heaven,'' that network's biggest hit, is also beating it
easily.
</P>
<P>
   The Quiz-Show Game
</P>
<P>
   Any time a new thoroughbred breaks out of the pack in network
television and looks like a hit, every other network wants to climb
on board _ not necessarily to ride so much as to beat the poor
horse to death.
</P>
<P>
   After ABC's success this summer with the game show ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire,'' NBC is making the first overt move in that
direction. The network said this week that it was commissioning a
pilot based on the format of the old game show ``Twenty-One.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that was one of the shows at the center of the quiz show
scandals in the 1950s, but NBC executive expressed confidence that
enough time has passed for that to make no difference with younger
viewers. For those old enough to remember, NBC seems to feel, the
notoriety just might help add an element of danger.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has tried to link the show with television's past in one
other way. Ancier said he had hired Fred Silverman, one of the
legendary programmers of television seasons past _ he made the top
program decisions first at CBS, then at ABC and finally at NBC in a
long career _ to put the pilot together.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives said the game's format would generally be as it
was in the '50s, with categories of questions, and with the level
of difficulty determining whether the question was worth one point
or as many as 10. NBC said it had not decided whether the show
would be broadcast in prime time or daytime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
