<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-NY     09-28 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE COUNSELORS' ANNUAL MEETING A GATHERING OF SUBTLE
PERSUASION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.) 
(JT) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ It is a perennial rite of college admissions
whose very existence is little known to frenzied parents and
applicants, but one so integral to the process that a prospect's
name scribbled on the back of the right business card there can
sometimes carry the weight of a high standardized test score.
</P>
<P>
   It is the annual conference of the National Association for
College Admission Counseling. And it convened here this past
weekend to provide many of the nation's high-school guidance
counselors and their counterparts in university admissions offices
with perhaps the only opportunity in the academic year to discuss
their respective wares, en masse.
</P>
<P>
   The course of those conversations _ in venues as public as a
convention hall and as secluded as a bathroom _ can affect nothing
less than an applicant's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an element of personal trust that builds up over the
years with these counselors,'' said Dr. William C. Hiss, a vice
president at Bates College, in Lewiston, Maine, who picked up a few
leads at the conference as he prepares to assemble the next class
at his school, which rejects two out of every three candidates.
``After a while, you realize certain counselors have great eyes for
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   First convened in 1945 with a handful of attendees, the
convention has ballooned in importance and size _ a record 1,500
guidance counselors and 1,400 admissions officers traveled to
Orlando _ in no small measure because the admissions gantlet has
perhaps never been more competitive or arduous.
</P>
<P>
   That competition has, at times, strained the famously clubby
atmosphere at such gatherings, with some high school counselors
complaining bitterly that their better students are not faring as
well in their acceptances as they might have several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, for representatives of lesser-known colleges, many
of them struggling just to fill their classrooms, NACAC, as the
gathering is called, offers an unparalleled chance to whisper the
names of their institutions in the ears of those who can influence
where seniors seek to spend the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   For guidance counselors, the convention represents the earliest
moment in the admissions season to talk up the names of forthcoming
applicants. And for the most selective institutions, NACAC,
pronounced knack-ack, has the feel of an informal academic draft
for top talent.
</P>
<P>
   Williams Fitzsimmons, the dean of admissions at Harvard _ who
was dutifully noting students' names, and sometimes their SAT
scores and extracurricular activities, on the backs of the
counselors' cards as they spoke _ said that the contact was
invaluable, particularly in anticipating potentially problematic
applicants.
</P>
<P>
   One guidance counselor from a California high school approached
Fitzsimmons with the name of a junior who, the counselor felt, was
``in the ballpark,'' except for a PSAT score of 1,200 out of a
possible 1,600, below the Harvard range. ``These are probably going
to go up,'' Fitzsimmons reassured, over the roar of a crowd that
sounded like a commodities market, his hands fingering a packet of
lozenges.
</P>
<P>
   Navigating between the long tables here, where 414 colleges had
draped their banners in booths no wider than four feet, Ivna
Gusmao, a college counselor at Chatsworth High School in Los
Angeles, was also on a targeted mission: she was looking for
universities with a special sensitivity to applicants with dyslexia
or attention deficit disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Veverly Arrington, a new principal in Montgomery,
Ala., was sprinkling the college tables with oversized yellow
business cards announcing that her well-regarded magnet program, a
regular feeder to Stanford and Rice, had broken away from another
high school to form its own school, called Lamp. (``We already knew
about your move,'' John Albright, the senior associate director of
admissions at the University of Georgia, told her, proudly.)
</P>
<P>
   When they weren't huddling here at the Walt Disney World Swan
and Dolphin Resort, the counselors, like those at any convention,
had plenty of other distractions to compete for their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of marketers and other businesses that hung
their shingles in an adjoining hall was the troupe Up with People,
star of Super Bowl half-time shows, which asked counselors to
encourage their students to join their company in a hiatus _ either
before entering college, or during it. Representatives from
McDonald's were there, too, looking for high-school-age cashiers
and college-graduates who might make good management trainees.
</P>
<P>
   And, if they wanted, the counselors could attend a semester's
worth of seminars, including ``Advising and recruiting the young
intellectual'' and ``Thorny conversations with demanding parents:
how to make them easier.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the attendees, the main draw was having time to make new
friends and renew old acquaintances across the divide between
secondary and higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of a huggy group,'' said Joyce F. Smith, the
executive director of the association. ``It makes it very
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes too personal. Another member of the Bates delegation
said that he had been relieved that two guidance counselors whose
candidates were rejected last year had briskly walked by his booth,
apparently without noticing him.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Poch, the vice president and dean of admissions at Pomona
College in Claremont, Calif., said that he sensed similar tensions
crackling throughout the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the hugging is genuine,'' Poch said. ``But a lot of
the times, one person is reaching around the other to put the knife
in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Poch himself said he left the conference rather angry, when he
realized that such gatherings were increasingly giving yet another
edge to private and suburban schools, which are able to afford
plane tickets and hotel reservations, while more rural and
inner-city schools had to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Their absence has left plenty of space for a legion of private
college advisers, who are paid a premium by families to get their
children just such an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need you to save a place,'' Carol Gill, a private adviser in
Westchester County, N.Y., said as she approached Fitzsimmons of
Harvard, with all the gravity of a lawyer pleading before the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for my granddaughter,'' Ms. Gill explained. ``She's just
8, but she's a champion swimmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons, who's heard countless variations of this pitch
since joining Harvard's admissions office in 1972, laughed before
suggesting that Ms. Gill check back in 10 years, when the child
would be a high school senior, to make sure he was ``still
around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
