<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYORK-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI URGES RELEASE OF ISRAELI SPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani urged President
Clinton Tuesday to free convicted Israeli spy Jonathan Pollard, a
move that could bolster Jewish support for the New York
Republican's prospective Senate campaign _ and complicate efforts
by First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Pollard deserves presidential clemency because the
life sentence for espionage given him in 1987 goes ``way beyond''
sentences given in the past to American citizens convicted of
spying for a U.S. ally.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard, a former civilian U.S. Navy intelligence analyst, has
already served a longer prison term than enemy spies who are
routinely traded by their governments, according to Giuliani, a
former federal prosecutor and associate attorney general in the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that there was an appropriate basis on which
the president could exercise his discretion and cut that particular
sentence,'' Giuliani said, adding that Pollard has ``served much
more than anyone else convicted of the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York mayor, campaigning in the nation's capital in
conjunction with his possible U.S. Senate bid, said he was
restating a position that he had taken on the Pollard case ``a
couple of years ago'' rather than announcing a new position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't reviewed it again since then but I have no reason to
change my mind about it,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration continues to review clemency for
Pollard in the aftermath of repeated requests by the Israeli
government.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who is weighing a Senate bid from New York, told
reporters earlier this month that she would await the outcome of
the White House review before announcing her view of clemency for
Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that is an issue of great concern to a number of
people,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``They have been expressing their
concern to me, including members of the intelligence and national
security community. There is a review under way at the highest
levels of national government, and I'm going to wait until I see
what that review says.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollard, who was awarded Israeli citizenship by the government
of Israel while in prison, pleaded guilty to espionage charges in
1987 for spying for Israel in the mid-1980s. Prosecutors said
Pollard sold more than 1,000 classified documents, including
satellite photographs, to Israel. Pollard admitted accepting more
than $45,000 in cash from the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
   After denying for years that Pollard had spied, Israel admitted
on May 11, 1998, for the first time that Pollard had ``acted as an
Israeli agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollard has been eligible for parole since 1995. But the
opposition of U.S. intelligence officials, including CIA Director
George Tenet, has impeded his release.
</P>
<P>
   The president rejected an appeal for clemency in 1994, saying
that the ``enormity of Mr. Pollard's crime, the harm his actions
caused to our country and the need to deter every person who might
even consider such actions warrant his continued incarceration.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Jewish organizations, including the New York-based Union of
Orthodox Jewish Congregations of America, have called on the
president to release Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish voters make up a powerful political constituency in New
York politics, accounting for 12 percent of the statewide vote in
the 1998 U.S. Senate race and 23 percent of the vote in the New
York City mayor's race in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Then-Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., toppled Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., last year in part by carrying 76 percent of the Jewish
vote. Giuliani won a second term as mayor of New York City in 1997
by winning 72 percent of the Jewish vote against his Democratic
rival.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani voiced support for clemency for Pollard as he continued
to criticize the Clinton administration for offering presidential
clemency to Puerto Rican nationalists freed from prison earlier
this month after serving long sentences. Their organization, the
FALN, has been linked with terrorist bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton freed the nationalists despite the ``uniform
opposition'' of some federal law enforcement agencies, Giuliani
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president ought to explain his rationale, Giuliani said,
adding: ``I think if the president is going to exercise the option
to give clemency or a pardon, he owes it to the American people to
release the documents on which he decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton invoked executive privilege earlier this month to keep
Congress from obtaining the documents related to his decision.
</P>
<P>
   On other issues, Giuliani:
</P>
<P>
   _ Vowed to ``evict'' the Brooklyn Museum of Art from leased city
property in connection with his criticism of an exhibition that
includes a portrait of the Virgin Mary splattered with elephant
dung.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you desecrate a religious symbol, public money shouldn't
be used to support it,'' Giuliani told a news conference. He vowed
to eliminate the $7 million city subsidy for the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has criticized the ``deeply offensive'' exhibit and
said she would not visit it. However, she said that cutting off $7
million in city funds was a ``very wrong response.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Giuliani said he would oppose moves in Congress to hike the
$5.15 minimum wage by $1 over the next two years because it might
jeopardize entry-level jobs being filled by former welfare
recipients moving into the work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take a look at whether by raising the minimum wage
you aren't putting people out of work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has come out in favor of the increase, saying a
hike would help wage earners and be good for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
