<HEADER>
A9235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-TOWN-ART-(TRIMS     09-28 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-TOWN-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CAPITAL CALM, PEACEKEEPERS MOVE TO SECURE REST OF EAST TIMOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIQUICA, East Timor _ Swooping in from above the blinding sea in
six Black Hawk helicopters, the shock troops of a still growing
multinational peacekeeping force moved into this seaside town on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The landing, completed Tuesday, was the opening of a campaign to
extend the force's operation beyond the capital, Dili, and to
subdue armed resistance throughout the territory, officers said.
</P>
<P>
   The 107 Australian soldiers, along with four armored vehicles
that drove up the winding coastal road from Dili, found a sunny
whitewashed town, filled with bird song and bright with
bougainvillea but almost entirely empty of people.
</P>
<P>
   Not a rooster crowed; not a stray dog wandered the streets.
Charred and loosened sheets of tin roofing banged in the soft sea
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard to imagine people could do this,'' said one soldier as he
carried his 100 pounds of equipment and weaponry through the town,
stopping warily at crossroads to confirm that nobody was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature of the beast,'' a second soldier replied.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Liquica, 20 miles east of Dili, the armed militia
members who had been on a killing spree in the region at the
beginning of this month fled just over a week after the force
arrived in East Timor, well before the peacekeepers' operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have secured Dili and now we are moving to go out, town to
town, to stabilize the situation so that the people can come down
from the hills and try to resume their lives,'' said an officer
here.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Liquica, the militias burned or vandalized
virtually every building. They forced the population to flee into
the mountains or to board ships, in what seems to have been an
effort to disperse much of the territory's population.
</P>
<P>
   In a signal that East Timor remains a dangerous and ugly place,
the Roman Catholic Bishop Basilio Do Nascimento confirmed Tuesday
the ambush killings on Saturday of nine people, including two nuns,
two church deacons and a seminarian. For weeks, armed men have made
priests and church workers their targets for death.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Liquica, each aircraft touched down for no more than 45
seconds here on Monday, as soldiers then ran into ruined buildings,
smashing the already broken glass from windows to take up defensive
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running movement left side,'' came a voice over the radio as
the mission's commander, Maj. Terry Dewhurst, crouched on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   And from a hovering observation helicopter, ``Two locals with
long bladed weapons moving west.''
</P>
<P>
   The major sent units in pursuit _ ``I want that man in the red
shirt'' _ but none turned out to be militia members.
</P>
<P>
   Then 11 young men appeared, dirty and wearing rubber sandals,
each holding high, in both hands, leaflets that had been scattered
in the past three days from aircraft belonging to the peacekeeping
force, known as Interfet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't shoot at Interfet helicopters or personnel,'' read one
multilingual leaflet. ``Interfet is here to help the people of East
Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   For the many people here who cannot read, the leaflets were
illustrated by bold depictions of helicopters and automatic rifles.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflets appeared to have been the advance wave of the
mission, giving a warning that cleared the militias from the city
and insuring a clean, swift, operation before the soldiers withdrew
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't leave any permanent personnel behind this time, but
sooner or later we will start positioning platoons in these
areas,'' Dewhurst said. With the peacekeeping force scheduled to
grow to no more than 8,000 troops in this territory of 800,000
people, officers in East Timor agree that there will be far too few
soldiers for a permanent security presence in every town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only come to an area for so long,'' said the major.
``We'll just keep playing leap frog until we're lucky enough to
land in a town where these guys are and give them a bloody day.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11 young men were searched, and when they were found to be
unarmed, sent off down the road toward the mountains, still holding
high their leaflets.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Later, the soldiers stopped a man with a sword and one with a
dagger, both in wooden sheaths. The men were disarmed, placed on
their knees, handcuffed, searched, questioned and, finally,
released after they had satisfied the soldiers that they were not
militia members.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Liquica is one of the prettiest and one of the most murderous
towns in East Timor, a former Portuguese territory where as many as
200,000 people have died since Indonesian troops invaded in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   For years, there were unconfirmed reports of massacres as the
Indonesians tried to use sheer brutality to pacify separatist
guerrillas. Early this year, the Indonesian government offered to
let the people in East Timor vote on independence.
</P>
<P>
   The military then created, armed and in many cases led the
militias in a new campaign of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   In early April, they carried out one of their worst massacres,
at the church here in Liquica. A local human rights group, Yayasan
Hak, estimated that as many as 60 people were shot dead.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, when the Indonesians bowed to international
pressure to let journalists visit the scene, the church had been
newly painted and scrubbed to remove evidence of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the church was locked and empty. But this time,
emboldened by the presence of the Australian soldiers, residents
came forward to tell their stories.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday morning, after camping on the grounds of the
vandalized mansion of the local governor, the troops awoke to find
hundreds of residents walking down from their refuge in the
mountains above the town.
</P>
<P>
   With the militia gone for the moment at least, they were coming
to scavenge for food and belongings to take back to the mountains,
in the same way refugees have been coming into Dili and leaving
again for the past several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The militia said they will come back and attack us again,''
said Jose Vidigal, 17. ``We will go back to the mountains today. We
are still afraid.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The soldiers set up checkpoints to pat down the villagers for
weapons. Smiling shyly, the villagers lifted their shirt fronts for
the search, then marched from soldier to soldier to shake their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   With an embarrassed smile, a boy handed over a rubber band
slingshot; smiling back, a soldier returned it to him.
</P>
<P>
   The stories they told appeared to be the stories of most of the
people of East Timor. Thousands of residents had been herded to the
beach, they said, where they camped for up to two weeks. From
there, members of the militia forced them onto ferries heading
mostly to West Timor, a part of Indonesia, where as many as 200,000
refugees now live in camps.
</P>
<P>
   Many other residents, like Jacinto Maria Lobo, 44, fled into the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, she was heading for the port where she had left
her belongings before slipping away with her family late one night.
But like many people, she found almost nothing to salvage.
</P>
<P>
   One man, eating a raw green mango, carried a handful of plastic
hangers. With him walked a man with an unopened can of paint.
</P>
<P>
   In a small girl's straw basket were several old rubber sandals,
several empty plastic bottles and a broken comb. An old woman had a
tin of rusty nails.
</P>
<P>
   One lucky man carried a stack of plastic chairs on one shoulder
and a live chicken hanging from his belt.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving town Tuesday, the troops distributed rice to
about 150 villagers gathered in the scorching noonday heat of a
soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people waiting patiently for food was Leonilde
Pereira, 11, who had salvaged from her home a book of religious
pictures, a book of Disneyland needlepoint patterns and a feather
duster.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Suzi Paula Pereira, had rescued only a Christmas
card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
