<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CLONING-EXPERT-COX     09-28 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLONING-EXPERT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for a clone: Steven Stice
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Steven Stice, a cloning expert, feels his new job
as scholar and entrepreneur at the University of Georgia would be
hard to duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   At age 37, Stice is one of the youngest in the state's stable of
32 Eminent Scholars, a special faculty of scientists and
technologists co-sponsored by the research universities and the
Georgia Research Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   An Illinois native and man of many interests, Stice came to
Athens this year from the University of Massachusetts, where he
pioneered in gene splicing. What lured him to Georgia, however, was
a chance at a bigger objective: to market as quickly as possible
the innovations he and his associates discover in the laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   But when you talk to him, it seems what pleases him most right
now is his family's easy adaptation to life in the Peach State. It
has been a soft landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved several times, my wife, the children, and I,''
said Stice, ``but this one has been the easiest. What helps my work
most is to have a good family life, and so this has been very
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Stice's family includes 11-year-old fraternal twins, a boy and
girl, as well as a 13-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps my son has made the only sacrifice _ he has had to
give up ice hockey, but he has taken to roller versions.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter Claire, who loves animals, now has her own horse,
thanks to the spacious property the family occupies. ``It was one
of the bribes that got them to move,'' Stice said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to his delight, Stice's new digs place him just steps
away from his friend and colleague Professor Clifton A. Baile,
another Eminent Scholar and Georgia specialist in biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I taught Steve nearly everything he knows,'' says Baile,
tongue planted firmly in cheek. Baile is credited with helping
persuade Stice to relocate.
</P>
<P>
   The jocular relationship underlines a central fact: That the new
environment could make Stice and his team even more productive
because of the facility and the relationships the scholar has with
academic and commercial colleagues bent on exploring the genetic
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The new animal science building, where Baile and Stice spend
their time, may be underwhelming architecturally, but it is
resplendent with the latest equipment. It includes computer-driven
machines for peering into animal cells, as well as labs that look
like medical operating rooms, which they are, for the implantation
of engineered embryos into sheep and cattle.
</P>
<P>
   The new equipment has been made possible by grants from the
Georgia Research Alliance, a partner with the universities and
research centers in attracting the Eminent Scholars to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In the same building on Georgia's South Campus are four young
businesses, each depending on the latest discoveries from the
geneticists among Stice and his colleagues. Close at hand, they can
easily collaborate with the scholars in much the same way the
pioneers of Silicon Valley collaborated with Stanford University
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Stice's own company, Prolinia, specializes in cloning for
agricultural purposes, and looks to clone pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Optimistically, the research center includes a lab specially
designed for implanting embryos in pigs, a feat no one has
accomplished so far. Stice says that one of his priorities will be
to break the barriers that block cloning and deeper study of pig
reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why pigs are harder to handle genetically than other
animals, Stice was direct: ``Beats me. Some animals are easy,
others are difficult. Cattle and sheep are easy, pigs are
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   His specialty has a number of critics, including some who
question the wisdom of cloning, arguing that the quest to get super
animals will destroy variety and leave the herds subject to serious
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a valid consideration,'' Stice said. ``But we are
mindful that we need to be careful not to decrease the genetic pool
and instead encourage variety. For instance, developing lines that
do better in the tropics, and others that are best adapted to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cloning only increases the supply of genetically superior
animals here now. We need genetic diversity to make a leap forward,
and so there is a real economic reason to keep diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   How about human cloning, or cloning of beloved family pets?
</P>
<P>
   Stice said the family dog died last year and he ``gave no
thought at all to cloning the animal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I think what we really enjoy in friends and in pets is
individuality, and I don't think we would want uniformity, even if
we could achieve it,'' Stice said.
</P>
<P>
   And on that point, he said cloning is sometimes misunderstood
and overestimated in its power to produce precise desired results.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, two cloned animals might be genetically
identical but they could have very different appearances _ one
solid color, the other spotted. These outward qualities, many of
them environmentally induced, not genetically, are what we often
desire most about animals or pets, and genetics do not produce them
reliably.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though his skills are adaptable to genetic advances that
can increase pharmaceuticals, Stice said that at the moment his
interests lean more toward agricultural improvement. He is very
interested in medical research to advance the treatment of
Parkinson's disease. But lately he has been spending much of his
time talking to farmers in Georgia about his research and their
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of issues,'' he said. ``Animal agriculture
needs more efficiency, and consistency in their products ... It is
within our capability to produce meat that can be more in line with
consumer expectations, such as steak quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the production side, we can arrive at more muscle mass, and
maybe even reduce the time cycle for producing beef and other
meats.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, he said, genetic advances can create more
cooperation among producers, processors and others in the
agricultural business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that through cloning genetics we can produce a
consistency that could price out at $250 per steer produced, and
that works out to potential boost of $10 billion in the United
States market alone,'' Stice said.
</P>
<P>
   It's that bang for the buck that has been one of the goals of
the Georgia Research Alliance, said William Todd, alliance
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Steve Stice here was one of the triumphs of our
collaborative approach to the recruiting,'' Todd said, ``and the
alliance has been pleased to provide flexibility and extra funding
that have made the project possible.''
</P>
<P>
   An overall sense of collaboration among the schools has been
another goal of the alliance and the legislative supporters of the
Eminent Scholar program.
</P>
<P>
   At least one active project at Georgia could take steps in that
direction. Stice and his colleagues are working on a project
described as DNA on a chip _ an attempt to load genetic factors
onto chips and analyze them with powerful computer programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Done the old way, we would often analyze six, eight, 10 genes
or so,'' Stice said, ``but this new technology will help us look at
10,000 to 40,000 genes at once.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Georgia State and Georgia Tech are cooperating in the
advance of the ``infomatics,'' or data analysis systems, that can
make this gene research work.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stice is getting involved in the Georgia scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have four season tickets to the football games,'' he said,
``the first time we have had a chance to be a part of a big
football program. We used to win at Illinois and at UMass, but the
scene was nothing like this ...''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We asked for, and got, no special favors _ our seats
are in an end zone, and let's say we have a rooting interest in the
opposition missing kicks wide-right so we can catch a ball!''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, in fact, may have split the uprights with a perfect
kick in recruiting Stice.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
