<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9240 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-MILAN29-COX     09-28 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MILAN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Max Mara takes a shine to glitz
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN _ Max Mara showed how to maximize the use of beads and
sequins during its spring/summer 2000 runway preview Tuesday
morning. Though known best to Atlanta women who shop the label's
Lenox Square store as a source for clothes with minimal
embellishment, Max Mara's going in an entirely different direction
with its eveningwear.
</P>
<P>
   The dressier looks were the strongest segment in the collection.
The reason: No one else, so far, has attempted to re-energize a
pattern as pedestrian as plaid by rendering it in bead. Max Mara's
sleeveless jumpsuits were jazzed up with red, black and blue bugle
beads arranged in a grid pattern. Beaded plaid halter tops were
paired with cranberry satin skirts or boot-cut pants. Satin blouses
topped knee-length, beaded plaid skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Solid-colored clothes made up the bulk of the collection
however. Navy blue blouses and belted polo shirts served as the
underpinning for an assortment of waxed cotton coatdresses, suits
and jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   There were lots of shorts hemmed at mid-thigh that weren't
especially attractive on the models' pale legs.
</P>
<P>
   And Max Mara's long, belted dresses with matching scarves that
garroted the models' slender necks didn't look quite right either.
There were so many outfits to choose from, however, that a few duds
could be forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Emporio Armani
</P>
<P>
   Ever looked through a kaleidoscope and marveled at the colors,
shapes and patterns? Well, Giorgio Armani had similar visuals in
mind while designing his lower-priced Emporio collection for spring
and summer. He said before the show that Emporio was all about
empowering women with wardrobing options. Afterward, some
detractors said there were far too many _ in terms of color, cut
and fabrication _ for the average woman to make sense of. Will
women go for Emporio's short skirts or knee-length tunics over
long, slim-fitting pants? And will they dare wear the micro-tank
tops that offer less coverage than brassieres, or the see-through
pants with just enough sequins in just the right places? The
Emporio collection's color scheme (varying shades of blue, green
and red) was invigorating and the clothes had a fierce femininity
to them. But critics noted that Armani should remember: No one
understands a kaleidoscope's intricacies as well as he who
assembled it.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   POSTCARD FROM MILAN
</P>
<P>
   Legs bared, women take the wheel
</P>
<P>
   By A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Her skirt was hiked up and her chestnut hair blew wildly in the
wind as she made her way down the Piazza Republica Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   When, I wondered, did Milanese women stop being ridden around on
motor scooters by their male companions? When did so many become
drivers?
</P>
<P>
   The city's cobblestone streets have always seemed as clogged
with scooters as compact cars. But never have so many been manned
by women (and it must be a lucrative market: One dealership's
infomercial, which airs daily, targets women exclusively.)
</P>
<P>
   Modesty doesn't prevent these motor mamas from riding in short
skirts, and their scooters seem newer, cleaner and more stylish
than the men's. Fashionably, but foolishly, fewer women seem to be
wearing helmets.
</P>
<P>
   Watching one riding sidesaddle behind her male driver Monday
made me consider that kind of motoring trust. Gives the phrase
``holding on to your man for dear life'' deeper meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the fairer sex has a firm hold on the handlebars.
</P>
<P>
   Can the days when these macho men of Milan start riding with
their arms wrapped around women's torsos be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
