A9246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN29-COX     09-28 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain takes campaign to South, chides Clinton, Congress
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ With one of the aircraft carriers his
grandfather commanded in World War II as a backdrop, Republican
presidential candidate John McCain Tuesday lambasted the president
and Congress for neglecting the nation's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that President Clinton has failed his first
responsibility to the nation by weakening our defenses. But he's
not the only one to blame,'' the Arizona senator said, standing in
front of the USS Yorktown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties in Congress have wasted scarce defense dollars on
unneeded weapons systems and other pork projects while 12,000
enlisted personnel, proud young men and women, subsist on food
stamps.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also blasted the Clinton administration for a ``feckless,
photo-op foreign policy'' which he said has left the nation's
military overcommitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States of America needs an experienced person to
steer the ship of state through dangerous waters,'' McCain said at
a breakfast stop in Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also wed campaign finance reform, an issue he's
identified with, to an idea popular among Republicans _ school
vouchers. He proposed taking $5.4 billion in sugar, oil and gas
subsidies to pay for a voucher program in the nation's poorest
schools. McCain contends the subsidies exists because of the money
business pours into the political system.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was on the second day of a campaign kick-off tour that
began in New Hampshire and will take him to Michigan and the West
Coast. He announced for president in April, but delayed the tour
due to the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The former Vietnam War POW has focused on South Carolina, which
has the highest number of veterans per capita of any state in the
nation and votes first among the Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, our campaign will rise and fall on how we do here in
the great state of South Carolina,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Answering questions from voters, McCain also said the U.S.
sooner or later will be forced to ``face down'' North Korea. And he
again criticized rival Pat Buchanan for contending in his recent
book that U.S. involvement in World War II could have been avoided,
a theory which McCain said denigrates the sacrifice Americans made
in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about Jane Fonda, McCain said he has ``tried
to put the war behind me,'' but he still thinks Fonda's actions on
a visit to North Vietnam while he and other American servicemen
were imprisoned was ``beyond any boundaries of behavior that any
decent American would engage in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate also spent part of the day on the
Internet, answering questions from students around the country as
part of the Kids Voting USA project.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
