<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9247 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WEBMD-COX     09-28 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMd, Healtheon merger might miss deadline
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD and California-based Healtheon apparently will
not meet their original goal of bringing off their much-touted
merger in September.
</P>
<P>
   As the month draws to a close, the ambitious Internet companies
are gradually negotiating their way through the thicket of
regulatory oversight, while still expecting final approval soon
from the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   William Michalak, analyst at Wachovia Securities, said the delay
is of little concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketplace for any of these Web-related companies is
moving very rapidly,'' he said. ``It's going to take a little more
time to put all the pieces together.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD and Healtheon announced a ``merger of equals'' on May 20
with plans to dominate the use of the Internet for healthcare
information. WebMD, had just called off its public offering, and
remains privately-held. On the day the merger was announced,
Healtheon stock was selling for $100 a share and the stock
combination was valued at nearly $6 billion. A day later, Healtheon
stock crested at $105 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several spikes northward, Healtheon stock has mostly
taken a slow slide, closing at $36.25 a share Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the sagging stock price cannot be blamed on any doubts about
the companies or the merger, Michalak said. ``This is just an ugly
stock market. The Web companies tend to be treated as rudely as
any.''
</P>
<P>
   In the merger of another Atlanta-based symbol of the new
economy, MindSpring Enterprises last week also announced plans for
a corporate marriage with a California competitor. The deal calls
for the new company to be based in Atlanta _ just as Healtheon and
WebMD have said their headquarters will be here.
</P>
<P>
   But MindSpring's merger with EarthLink will mean surrendering
its name to the Pasadena company. In contrast, WebMD and Healtheon
announced plans for the combined companies to be combined in name
as well: Healtheon WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Should the SEC's permission arrive as expected in early October,
the companies would likely be given a closing date in November.
</P>
<P>
   Announced plans call for WebMD's 29-year-old founder and chief
executive to be CEO of the combined company. W. Michael Long, the
CEO of Healtheon, will be chairman and chief operating officer.
James Clark, founder of Netscape and chairman of Healtheon, will be
a member of the board of directors for Healtheon WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the rest of the board, nor the rest of the management
team has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the two companies have a 1,800-person workforce,
including about 200 at WebMD. But each side of the equation is
expected to focus on its strengths. Healtheon is expected
post-merger to handle technology issues while WebMD will take the
lead on marketing and deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   And WebMD has done a ton of deal-making in the year since it
announced a $10 million investment from HBO&AMP;Co. In In February,
WebMD signed a multimillion-dollar deal with CNN in which the
company would advertise on CNN, while CNN would promote WebMD on
the air.
</P>
<P>
   In March, WebMD agreed to pay $52.5 million to become the
exclusive healthcare provider on the Internet network Lycos.com. In
April, DuPont announced a $220 million investment in WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   The Healtheon closing will actually involve a four-way deal.
Healtheon has announced agreements to purchase Mede America and
merge with WebMD, which itself agreed to buy Greenberg News
Networks and its Medcast subsidiary. All those deals are to close
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
