<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OPERA-CONDUCTOR(TRIMS     09-28 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-CONDUCTOR(TRIMS)-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CONDUCTOR, DENNIS RUSSELL DAVIES BRINGS LIFE TO A NEW OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ohio)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ An opera is built like a puzzle; separate pieces are
carved and fitted together. The music for ``A View From the
Bridge,'' an adaptation of Arthur Miller's play that will have its
premiere at Lyric Opera of Chicago on Oct. 9, was written in Ann
Arbor, Mich., by William Bolcom. The libretto was written by a New
Yorker, Arnold Weinstein; the set was designed by Santo Loquasto in
New York and built in San Diego. The singers have been rehearsing
for weeks now on a partially assembled set in a room on the second
floor of the Civic Opera House here.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, with the singers still upstairs being scrutinized by
the stage director, Frank Galati, the instrumentalists got into the
act, playing the score _ an amalgam of contemporary leaps and
dissonant chords and melodies with the sentimental sweep of show
music _ for the first time in the cavernous empty theater.
</P>
<P>
   The link among the elements is the conductor, Dennis Russell
Davies, who began receiving bits of the score from Bolcom in the
early days of composition, about three years ago. His task is to
know the work more thoroughly than anyone, from details of the
stage drama to the individual parts of the singers and orchestra
players.
</P>
<P>
   The conductor is the composer's chief ally, the guardian of the
integrity of the music against the occasional intrusions of
dramatic demands. But his advocacy is not quite so simple; he is
the director's ally as well, the intermediary between the action on
the stage and the music in the pit. And he is the singers' guiding
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do my job, prepare the drama, spend all these weeks with the
actors, but you know what?'' Galati said. ``I'm not standing on
that stage. He not only shapes the performance, he performs the
show. He is, more than anyone else, the performer of the opera.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true for any opera, but in a premiere the stakes are
higher because the conductor's role is infused with creativity and
origination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether the composer is dead or alive, you're still his
representative,'' Davies said. ``And it is always true that a
singer who stands on the stage is, in my mind, undertaking a
particularly courageous act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel a special responsibility to the piece when it's a
premiere because a lot is riding on the first time. You marshal the
forces to do a new opera and it can only be new once. After that,
it has to simply be good. If it's going to be done again, people
have to have confidence in it. And for them to have confidence, I
have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies is the music director of the American Composers Orchestra
as well as chief conductor of the Vienna Radio Symphony Orchestra
and the Stuttgart Chamber Orchestra. In appearance and manner,
however, Davies, 55, doesn't exactly wear the resume of an
internationally known maestro prototypically. He is short and
compact, gap-toothed, wears a prominent earring and keeps his head
more assiduously shaved than his chin. The British-sounding name is
misleading; he is from Toledo, Ohio, and speaks like it, affably
and unaffectedly. He lives mostly in Europe but keeps a place in
New York, and is wont to worry as often over the plight of the
disintegrating Mets as the plight of contemporary opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very cool job,'' he said of his profession, though it
bugs him a bit that the opera conductor is generally undervalued,
unlike a podium-elevated symphony conductor (who orchestra
musicians often grumble gets all the accolades).
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been involved hand in glove with the director, worked
with the composer, you spend weeks with the singers,'' he said.
``And they all appreciate it. But then during the performance,
every moment, you're essential to what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``And the irony is that you can't be seen by the audience
because you're in the pit. At the end, there'll be reviews of the
performance, and somewhere there will be a line that says, `the
orchestra, conducted by blah-blah, played blah-blah-blah.' And that
will be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on his role was that of an editor for Bolcom, offering
suggestions on the composer's drafts and acting as referee in the
modest disagreements that inevitably arise between composer and
singers. The formative period can be a tense time, but it was made
easier because the two men have known each other for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll say to me, `You didn't mean this, you meant that,'''
Bolcom said. ``And he's right.''
</P>
<P>
   When the score was completed, Davies spent several weeks
memorizing it, largely by reading, going to the piano only
occasionally, he said, to work out a particularly knotty chord or
test the emotional impact of a passage.
</P>
<P>
   How well does he know the music? ``You're driving from Chicago
to New York, and you know how to get there,'' he said. ``But you
still take a map.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``View,'' he said, preparing the score was
simplified by his admiration for it and its reflection of the text.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is a composer at the height of his powers,'' Davies said.
``And the music in this opera is quite pared down, very direct. In
the orchestration, you'll have a melody, a harmonic accompaniment,
sometimes only three or four instruments. It's very, very direct,
and that's risky because it means that it has to be carried on the
quality of the music, its beauty and invention. There are no
compositional pyrotechnics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But of course this fits the play, because Arthur's play is
direct. The story moves quickly; you know what's coming, and it
comes. The composition follows closely the movement of the play.
Bill has put his heart on his sleeve here; the moments when it's
sentimental, it's really sentimental. When it's passionate, it's
really passionate. When it's violent, there are violent sounds.
It's like hearing an illuminating voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The most intense work, however, began in the last couple of
months, when the singers and then the orchestra began to rehearse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a division of territory,'' Davies said. ``Ideally the
conductor and the stage director work hand in hand. In staging
rehearsals, without the orchestra, the director is the boss and I'm
there to support him. When we get back into the theater, with the
orchestra, I'm in charge and he's there to support me.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His multifarious roles were on display one afternoon last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bolcom was on hand to hear his score, which had existed only in
his mind's ear, brought to life at last. ``It's like the difference
between a beautiful woman and a dirty picture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the front row and watching Davies interpret him, the
composer heard a few mistakes; the computer-printed version of the
score, it turned out, had left out a couple of accidentals. But
Bolcom was beaming. Occasionally, when Davies looked back at him to
acknowledge the resolution of a troublesome moment, their smiles
were giddy.
</P>
<P>
   After Davies dismissed the orchestra, he clapped his hands and
set out to join the singers. ``OK,'' he said, turning to Bolcom.
``Let's see what havoc we can wreak upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In rehearsals with the singers, Davies generally concentrates on
consistency, conducting with the accompaniment of two pianos,
working on tempos and embedding them in the singers' minds, as he
was doing with the orchestra, so that when they are united (those
rehearsals began Tuesday, ), there will be a minimum of surprises.
That makes performance preparation easier, particularly for the
singers, who have a harder time hearing the musicians, beneath them
in the pit, than the audience does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orchestra is the horse that everybody rides on,'' Davies
said. ``When you've got a successful performance going, the
orchestra lays the track down and you, as a conductor, can
concentrate on organizing the singers so they can relax. They can't
hear as well as you can, so you have to make sure your gestures are
such that they can read the sound they're hearing. It's almost like
signing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of a run-through of the second act, which begins
with a barbershop-quartet-like number sung by drunken stevedores,
there was an immediate problem to solve. As written, the
introductory chord for the song, which was to give the singers
their entry pitch, was proving obfuscatory. The pitch notes were
there, but the rest of the chord, complex and dissonant, was hiding
them. Davies persuaded Bolcom to delay the chord, begin with the
pitch notes, allow the singers to enter and then lay on the
complications, completing his chord. Everyone was happy. The
singers had a comfortable entry; Bolcom had the sound he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Davies' strength, said Timothy Nolen, who sings the baritone
role of Alfieri, the neighborhood lawyer in the blue-collar
Brooklyn neighborhood where the play is set and who serves as
narrator, is that he allows the singers their needs.
</P>
<P>
   He added that this flexibility was particularly important for a
new piece because without the handrails of history, everyone is
creating as they go. ``As a conductor, you have to have
elasticity,'' Nolen said. ``In your mind and your arm.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a previous rehearsal Davies solved another problem before
Bolcom even knew it existed. Juliana Rambaldi, the singer playing
Catherine, the play's ingenue, had a line describing her
relationship with her overbearing uncle: ``Now he's mad all the
time.'' The score made a leap in pitch, midline, on the word
``mad,'' and the vowel sound made the high note difficult to
locate. Davies' suggestion was to change the rhythm of the sung
line slightly so the high note landed on ``all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The `aw' was easier to sing than the `ad''' Galati said. ``Who
knew? And, of course, the emphasis on `all' was better for the
sense of the line. I was delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   As the scene was rehearsed and the singers approached the line,
Galati's face registered alarm, and he hustled over to whisper a
warning to Bolcom, though he didn't get there in time.
</P>
<P>
   Bolcom heard the change. His eyebrows raised, then lowered.
Galati looked at Davies, who was looking over his shoulder at the
composer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better,'' Bolcom said. ``Great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
