u e BC-KRISTOFFERSON-REVIEW-     09-28 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRISTOFFERSON-REVIEW-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE AUSTIN SESSIONS': KRISTOFFERSON REGAINS GLORY WITH NEW CD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER COOPER   
 Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In so many ways and for so many reasons, this could have been a
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The premise _ an aging ex-star records new versions of the songs
that made him famous _ has been tried many times, nearly always
with poor results.
</P>
<P>
   Decades, money and the accumulated effects of insane amounts of
narcotics tend to dull a singer's passion for his material, even
when the songs themselves remain immediate, timeless and sometimes
brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofferson, now 63, has not lived a life so much as imbibed
one, and the chances of capturing true emotion instead of refried
sentiment on a such a ``Greatest Hits Re-Recorded'' project make
video poker odds seem downright good.
</P>
<P>
   To make things worse, Kristofferson's voice, a froggy, often
off-key croak even in his 1970s prime, hasn't improved a whit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow, throughout what could have been requisite guest
turns by Jackson Browne, Vince Gill, Marc Cohn, Mark Knopfler and
others, producer Fred Mollin captured the old silver-tongued devil
at his best. This is a superb collection of superb songs, with the
newly cut versions bettering Kristofferson's classic originals in
some cases.
</P>
<P>
   The odd thing is that ``The Austin Sessions'' may well be the
first Kristofferson album that many younger listeners and musicians
will ever own. He is known today more as a movie actor than as a
musician, and he's not in all that much demand on the silver
screen, either.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange situation, considering that Kristofferson wrote
some of the most enduring songs of the century: ``Me and Bobby
McGee,'' ``Sunday Morning Coming Down,'' ``Help Me Make It Through
the Night'' and ``Loving Her Was Easier (Than Anything I'll Ever Do
Again).''
</P>
<P>
   But, with the exception of Janis Joplin's version of ``Me and
Bobby McGee,'' none of those songs has made the transition from
blockbusters of their day to staples of modern radio.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, considering that the Beatles are not even a regular
part of so-called Classic Rock playlists anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation means that most people born after 1970 have
little familiarity with Kristofferson's man's music. That's a
shame, because he remains one of the most intriguing and unlikely
figures in 20th-century musical history.
</P>
<P>
   He was the ultimate outsider in 1970s Nashville, having been
both an Oxford scholar and a professional janitor. But a daring,
unsolicited helicopter landing on now-friend, then-stranger Johnny
Cash's property gave him an audience with the Man in Black, who
recognized profundity when he heard it and ended up recording
``Sunday Morning Coming Down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hits including Ray Price's take on ``For the Good Times'' and
Sammi Smith's gorgeous ``Help Me Make It Through the Night''
followed soon after, and Kristofferson went from cleaning up on his
janitor job to cleaning up on songwriter royalties.
</P>
<P>
   His musical and personal alignment with guitar outlaws Cash,
Waylon Jennings and Willie Nelson helped shine the spotlight on the
songwriter, and a marriage to Rita Coolidge gave him both a
talented wife and a pretty voice to offset his sandpaper vocals on
duet albums. More hits followed.
</P>
<P>
   But a fast lifestyle and the decision to move to California to
further his movie career took him away from the musical mainstream
he helped create, and his growing political awareness did not
translate to great songwriting when he attempted to write
eloquently about, for instance, Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Austin Sessions'' returns Kristofferson to the handful
of songs that put him in demand in the first place, and Mollin's
production removes the busy instrumentation that detracted from
some of the originals. This is a leaner, sparer album, at times
sounding like friends playing and singing in a living room rather
than in a soulless studio.
</P>
<P>
   In such a setting, the power of Kristofferson's lyrics moves to
the forefront, and he sings the words like he still means them.
Apparently, he still does: ``I am struck by how alive they (the
songs) are,'' he writes in the liner notes.
</P>
<P>
   The album works as a collection of songs, as a collection of
performances, or as a textbook in songwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Kristofferson, ``The Austin Sessions''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Recording
</P>
<P>
   Peter Cooper writes for The Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MET-LUCIA-NYT &LR;      09-28 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-LUCIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUCIA' RETURNS, RESTORED AND WITH FEWER FRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Sir Charles Mackerras conducts Donizetti's
``Lucia di Lammermoor'' at the Metropolitan Opera on Wednesday
night with soprano Andrea Rost in the title role, he expects that
many admirers of this opera may be a bit perplexed by what they
hear. The affable, 73-year-old conductor is performing the opera in
its original 1835 version, which has never been heard before at the
Met, nor, to his knowledge, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades after its premiere, this bel canto favorite was
subjected to cuts, interpolated embellishments and key
transpositions, what Sir Charles calls the ``so-called tradition.''
Many of the changes were introduced by coloratura sopranos singing
Lucia who lowered keys in order to impress audiences with dazzling
high notes and elaborate cadenzas. Conductors sanctioned the
changes, hoping to trim the opera's length and focus the evening on
the heroine, a young Scottish woman with a tenuous grasp on mental
stability who is forced by her family to marry against her will,
forsaking the man she really loves, the scion of the Lammermoor
clan's hated rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The original version restores the cuts, resets Lucia's arias and
duets in their intended keys and eliminates the interpolated high
notes at the ends of arias and the extraneous ornamentation that
long ago became standard practice.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the version of the opera as traditionally done is
``anachronistic, unstylish and generally to be deplored,'' as
Mackerras put it in a recent interview at the Met, does not tend to
bother the average listener, he said. ``They like to hear the top
notes and the fancy cadenzas,'' he added. ``I hope that the other
things we will bring to the opera will be appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Those other things, he explains, are expressive refinement,
formal elegance and dramatic subtlety, qualities more associated
with the Classical era than the Romanticism of the 1820s and '30s,
when Donizetti was in his prime. Mackerras points out that
Donizetti was born in 1797, the same year as Schubert, and retained
a lifelong sympathy for Classical sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   What differences might ``Lucia'' fans notice?
</P>
<P>
   For one, elaborate ornamental accretions have been replaced with
the more lyrical and less ostentatious embellishments that
Donizetti composed. For example, the long cadenza with flute that
is traditionally performed at the end of the first section of
Lucia's famous ``Mad Scene'' is not by Donizetti, but likely the
invention of coloraturas who performed concert tours with flutists,
said Mackerras. That is gone. Elsewhere in the score, where the
autograph manuscript does not include Donizetti's own ornaments,
Mackerras has sought the suggestions of the conductor and
19th-century opera scholar Will Crutchfield.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition of interpolating full-voiced high notes at the
ends of arias belongs more to Puccini's verismo style than
Donizetti's bel canto practice, Mackerras said. Those have been
omitted for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   Most listeners will probably not notice the restoration of
original keys, but it makes a big difference, Mackerras said. For
example, Lucia's first scene, her pair of arias by the fountain,
were originally in E flat and A flat, respectively. For generations
most sopranos have taken them down a half-step to D and G, then
added high notes and cadenzas. Donizetti's higher keys and gentler
ornaments are adhered to by Mackerras in his version, which Ms.
Rost also performs on a 1998 Sony recording of the opera with
Mackerras conducting the Hanover Band, an early instrument
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday night, Ms. Rost and the Met cast, which includes
tenor Frank Lopardo and baritone Roberto Frontali, will sing the
original version in five additional performances in October. In
December the production returns for four performances with Ruth Ann
Swenson as Lucia but in the traditional version, conducted by
Edoardo Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Mackerras said, the traditional ``Lucia'' is ``in general
to be deplored,'' does he think it deserves a continuing place in
the repertory? ``I'm possibly not the person to ask,'' he said.
``The traditional `Lucia' does show how beautifully and brilliantly
a soprano can sing high notes and cadenzas, and artists like Callas
and Sutherland and others more recently have shown how much real
feeling and drama can be extracted from it. But it's a funny
hybrid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1851EDT &QL; 
