<HEADLINE>
GOP-LED CONGRESS PUSHES THROUGH STOPGAP SPENDING BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Failing to complete work on Year 2000 spending
measures by the October deadline, Republican leaders were forced to
push a temporary funding bill through Congress Tuesday to avoid a
government shutdown Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to force its legislative priorities on President Clinton,
the House voted 421-2 to continue funding most federal agencies at
current levels at least through Oct. 21 in hopes of reaching some
accommodation by then on remaining spending disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved a similar stopgap measure later Tuesday,
98-1, and Clinton said he will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said when he assumed his
leadership role in January that Congress had ``an obligation'' to
complete work on all 13 major appropriations bills for fiscal year
2000 by the end of the summer. But with three days to go before the
beginning of the new fiscal year, Congress has finished only five
of those measures. Together, they account for about five percent of
the total federal budget needed for government operations next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Only two bills have been signed by the president and three are
awaiting his signature. Seven are still tied up in negotiations and
awaiting final passage, and one, a giant measure to fund the
Department of Health and Human Services, has yet to be reported out
of the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Also complicating budget matters is Clinton's threatened veto of
at least six spending measures once they reach his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delivered on the first of those threats Tuesday
afternoon. He vetoed the appropriations bill that contained $429
million for the District of Columbia because it contains a number
of Republican prohibitions on how the federal money can be spent by
local authorities. Clinton said those prohibitions would interfere
with decisions that should be made by locally elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no way to make a budget,'' declared Rep. John Spratt,
D-S.C., who led the charge by Democrats in blaming the Republicans
for using the spending measures to force their political agenda on
the American people.
</P>
<P>
   He and other Democrats accused GOP leaders of delaying passage
of some measures while they tried to find ways to pay for programs
they want while attempting to cut back on programs favored by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, said that passage of stopgap spending
measures to keep the government operational is ``a normal and
routine'' part of the budget process, as House Rules Committee
Chairman David Dreier, R-Calif., put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do our constitutional duty,'' Dreier stressed
during debate on the temporary funding bill. But he added that
other matters, such as adjournments for funerals and disputes with
Democrats over gun control and other controversial issues, had
slowed work on some budget matters.
</P>
<P>
   He and other GOP leaders blamed some of the delay on the
president for not engaging in serious budget talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked (for his input) ... He refused to do so,'' said House
Appropriations Committee Chairman C.W. ``Bill'' Young, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Young said Republicans want to avoid another repeat of the two
disastrous 1995-96 partial government shutdowns in which they tried
and failed to get Clinton to capitulate to their demands. The
public ended up putting most of the blame for those shutdowns on
the GOP leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still sorry we ever did,'' Young said in reference to
the shutdowns. ``But we're trying to avoid that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart challenged
GOP claims that Clinton has not been willing to negotiate
``acceptable areas of compromise'' on spending matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has made it very clear. He wants to work with
them ... We're going to hopefully, in the next three weeks, find
some way around the situations the Republicans have created for
themselves,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   But he stressed that Clinton will not go along with GOP budget
``gimmicks,'' such as declaring routine funding for some programs
as ``emergencies,'' to avoid breaking the 1997 agreement on
spending caps.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., conceded that ``there is nothing new''
about Congress having to pass temporary spending measures, noting
that the procedure has been used by Democratic-controlled
Congresses in years past. But he blamed the delay this year on
Republican attempts to impeach Clinton and to pass their $792
billion tax cut bill, which the president vetoed last week.
</P>
<P>
   Obey said those efforts had wasted time on partisan issues that
Congress could have otherwise spent working out differences over
budget matters.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, also reminded Republicans of their
majority status and their command of the budget and appropriations
committees in both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in control ... It's not our fault that we haven't
passed the budget by the October deadline,'' Bentsen said during
the debate. ``Perhaps what the American people should learn about
this is it's time to get rid of that control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bickering over the stopgap measure, Republican
leaders were hopeful that the remaining work on 2000 spending could
be completed in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was poised to vote Tuesday evening on a compromise
$21 billion bill that would fund energy and water projects next
year. The House approved a similar bill Monday night by a vote
327-87.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also planned Tuesday to take up a $324 billion
measure that would cover a broad range of social spending programs,
including everything from education to Medicaid payments. The bill
contains about $500 million more for education programs than
Clinton requested, but would not specifically fund his efforts to
hire another 100,000 new teachers and build more schools.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators also completed work Tuesday on a
compromise $12.6 billion foreign aid measure after they agreed to
drop a section prohibiting aid to organizations that advocate
abortion. The decision was a major defeat for anti-abortion
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill could still face a veto because it contains about
$2 billion less than Clinton requested and has no funding earmarked
for carrying through on the Wye River accords reached earlier this
year between Israel and the Palestinians with U.S. help. The bill
also falls short on funding Clinton requested to help meet U.S.
obligations to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
