<SLUG> BC-TV-ARISTOCRATS-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAYS OF RISQUE JOKES AND READING VOLTAIRE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caroline is clever, Emily is a mother to me, Louisa is an angel
and Cecilia is a child,'' says Sarah Lennox of her rich and
beautiful sisters. Asked to describe herself, she adds, ``I think I
am a disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Stella Tillyard, the author of ``Aristocrats,'' the story of the
Lennox sisters from 1740 to 1832, labels Caroline an intellectual,
Emily a keeper of secrets, Louisa an angel indeed and Sarah as the
most extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia, the baby, isn't much of a factor in the ``Mobil
Masterpiece Theater'' version of ``Aristocrats'' (a three-part
production beginning next Sunday night on PBS), but an odd,
thwarted kind of feminism is.
</P>
<P>
   An era of powdered wigs, corsets, bustles and towering plumed
headdresses may seem an unlikely place to discover strong,
intelligent women taking charge of their lives, but the second half
of the 18th century was a time of great social change in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a wonderful letter from Emily where as an old lady she
looks back to her youth in the 1740s,'' says Ms. Tillyard, who
based her book largely on the sisters' published letters. ``She
says that in those days women could lie on the couch and tell dirty
jokes; women aren't allowed to do that anymore. Even in her own
lifetime she can chart a constriction on what is possible in female
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tillyard likes to blame the French Revolution. Seeing the
bloody fate of the French aristocracy between 1789 and 1799, the
upper crust in Britain suddenly got very nervous, she explains,
about ``where license led you, where liberalism led you'' and
promptly retreated to conservative social attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tillyard also says that the Lennox sisters, daughters of the
Duke of Richmond (grandson of Charles II and his French mistress),
were unusually smart and well educated even for their class. But
from the first scenes of this BBC America and WGBH Boston
co-production, forthright women seem to be regarded as oddities.
</P>
<P>
   On a pleasant London day in 1743, Caroline (Serena Gordon), the
eldest daughter, reveals that she reads Voltaire and announces with
the sureness of youth: ``Most people do not think. They just agree
with the current fashion.'' Henry Fox (Alun Armstrong), a charming
older man, looks at her admiringly and declares, ``Because you are
young and fair, it does not follow that you are foolish.'' An
admirable sentiment but, if it has to be said, possibly a minority
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters do turn out to be quite influential, but for most of
their lives the influence comes from their husbands. Caroline
elopes with Fox, a rising Whig politician, but finds that he
devotes much more time and attention to work than to her. When the
Duchess of Richmond (Diane Fletcher) catches her second daughter,
Emily (Geraldine Somerville), reading Voltaire, she discourages it
and tempts her with a sapphire necklace instead.
</P>
<P>
   Emily soon marries Lord Kildare (Ben Daniels), the most powerful
man in Ireland, and has 22 _ yes, 22 _ children, (Some were with
her second husband.) Kildare also cheats on her regularly with the
servant girls.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa (Anne-Marie Duff), who shall henceforth be known as the
boring one, marries the richest man in Ireland (Tom Mullion) and
apparently devotes her life to good works. Then little Sarah (Jodhi
May) grows up and catches the eye of the Prince of Wales (Luke De
Lacy), the future George III.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the temperamental Duke of Richmond (Julian Fellowes)
is practically dancing around the house with joy over his daughter
someday becoming queen, the prince announces his engagement to
someone else. Sarah is talked into marrying a man who bores her
(Andrew Havill) and eventually does the unthinkable: she has
affairs and has the bad luck to become pregnant by a lover. Her
social punishment, supported and enforced by her family, makes the
scarlet letter look lenient.
</P>
<P>
   The Lennox sisters do appear to develop some real social bravery
in later years; one, widowed, marries her children's tutor (George
Anton) and basically forces London society to accept him. And the
women's political beliefs had impact; one of Emily's sons was the
Irish revolutionary Edward Fitzgerald (John Light), who is a major
figure in the show's final episode.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline always speaks her mind, urging her husband not to
profit from war, which she considers ``a disgrace to human
nature.'' But mostly, it seems, the sisters wear beautiful dresses,
walk through beautiful rooms (like those in Carton House outside
Dublin, the Kildares' real home, where some of ``Aristocrats'' was
filmed), bicker over hurt feelings, reunite tearfully and shop.
</P>
<P>
   They also endure a rigid sexual double standard. In their time
``a little gallantry'' (the word being used in the sense of amorous
intrigue) is deemed ``necessary in a man'' but ``unforgivable in a
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Caroline can comment to her husband, with casual acceptance, ``I
know fidelity is not the custom'' for people of their rank and
Emily can observe, at another point, that unfaithfulness in men is
``as common as rain.'' They might have enjoyed the Edwardian
installments of ``Masterpiece Theater'' better. Lady Marjorie could
have taught them a thing or two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
