<SLUG> BC-FBO-FEMALE-KICKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER PLAYER MAKES POINTS AS ONE OF TEXAS TEAM'S KICKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Amanda Buck of Fort Worth Southwest High
School could hear those trying-too-hard-to-whisper whispers and she
could feel those trying-too-hard-not-to-stare stares.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is she doing with pads on?'' senior center Kennon Weaver
said he remembers thinking. ``Is this a joke?''
</P>
<P>
   She teed the football at the 13-yard line _ the length of an
extra point _ took a few steps back, exhaled, approached and put
her right foot to the ball. She says she wasn't out to prove a
point; she simply wanted to prove to herself that she could make
field goals.
</P>
<P>
   The ball went up, and ... missed. No one laughed or pointed,
they only kept staring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry, you can get this,'' Raiders kicker D.W. McAbee
told her.
</P>
<P>
   Buck repeated the process four more times before she made it.
Buck has played soccer most of her life and had never tried a field
goal before that August practice.
</P>
<P>
   More than a month later, Buck has challenged tradition by
earning a spot on the Raiders varsity football team as one of their
three place-kickers and in the process has become an improbable,
but accepted, member of her team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents think I'm crazy, but I wanted to prove to myself
that I could do this,'' said Buck, a senior who also plays soccer
and runs track. ``I look around the locker room and it doesn't hit
me I'm the only girl. Not many people have a chance to do this, I
realize that, but I'm a part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she sometimes feels bad vibes from teammates, but for
the most part everyone is encouraging. Logistically, this isn't a
problem, either; she dresses in the girl's locker room and the only
time the football locker room is closed is when the boys are
dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go to games, people can't believe we have a girl on
our team, but I think it's cool,'' senior Jason Strong said. ``I
don't treat her any differently than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   First-year coach Larry Stovall said: ``I never asked her why she
wanted to do this, but I think she's enjoying it. In 27 years of
coaching, I've had three girls say they were going to come out to
play football and none ever did. I knew Amanda would because she is
capable of this.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, she's 1-for-2 on extra points, attempting both kicks two
weeks ago against Polytechnic. She's aware of the singularity of
her situation; Buck's privy to how the other half plays and works.
</P>
<P>
   She's even discovered a few misconceptions of her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls talk all the time and hug each other when they score a
goal,'' said Buck, who classifies herself as Division II soccer
material. ``Guys don't talk as much, but it shocked me the way they
encourage each other. There are some fights. They yell at each
other sometimes, and I was prepared they wouldn't care about me,
but it hasn't been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Those doubts were quelled Sept. 17 when she tried her first
extra point in the third quarter against Polytechnic. It was
blocked as a Parrots defender bowled over both Buck and holder
Billy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so nervous and had so much adrenaline going I couldn't
feel if it hurt or not,'' Buck said. ``Mostly, I was upset that I
missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the quarter, she got another chance and this time she
connected. On the sideline, Stovall grinned as teammates pounded on
her helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kicking and making a field goal is such an awesome feeling,''
she said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
