<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-FISCAL-SHOWDOWN-NYT &LR;      09-28 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISCAL-SHOWDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOCIAL SECURITY DEBATE, POLITICAL SYMBOLISM STILL RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SPEND-CONGRESS) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This was going to be the year that Congress and the
Clinton administration de-electrified the third rail of American
politics, putting partisanship aside to insure the long-term
viability of the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   ``So first and above all,'' President Clinton said during his
State of the Union address in January, ``we must save Social
Security for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   It never happened. Instead, Social Security proved to be as
irresistible and potent a political weapon as ever, if not more so.
And decisions by each party to use the retirement program's almost
sacred place in the hearts of voters as a club against the other
help to explain why Congress and the White House are again headed
toward a budget showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Conceding that Congress will be unable to pass the spending
bills necessary to keep the federal government operating after the
start of the new fiscal year on Friday, the House and the Senate
both passed a measure Tuesday to provide the necessary money for
three weeks while Republicans try to work out their differences
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In large part because of the way they chose to play the Social
Security card, the two sides are in a fiscal box of their own
making. Clinton blocked Republican efforts to enact a big tax cut
by arguing that projected federal budget surpluses should be set
aside until Social Security's long-term financial problems had been
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by the success of Clinton's strategy _ and fed up
with the Democratic Party's claims over many decades to be the one
true protector of Social Security _ Republicans tried to turn the
tables. Eager to advance their goal of reducing the size and
influence of federal government, they demanded earlier this year
that the president scale back his spending requests to avoid
dipping into the portion of next year's surplus generated by excess
Social Security revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to our constituents and our seniors to stop the raid
on Social Security,'' Rep. Wally Herger, R-Calif., said Tuesday in
supporting a nonbinding resolution passed by the House calling for
Congress not to spend the retirement system's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to cede the high ground, Clinton took the Republicans
up on their challenge this summer. But with time running out to
pull together next year's budget, neither side has a politically
realistic way of making good on its promise to keep its hands off
Social Security, at least not without resorting to wholesale
gimmickry. And both sides are largely ignoring the reality that
spending a small portion of Social Security revenues will have
little or no effect on the retirement system's long-term health or
on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be difficult for either side to gain significant
advantage,'' said Robert Reischauer, a former director of the
Congressional Budget Office who is now a fellow at the Brookings
Institution, a liberal-leaning research group. ``The Republicans
made a premature promise that was reiterated by the president. It's
something neither party could fulfill.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither party, though, is yet willing to give up, fearing that
to do so would hand the other side an explosive issue to exploit in
next year's election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they're both trying to run feeder lines from any
available source of power to make this issue even more
electrified,'' said David John, a senior policy analyst at the
Heritage Foundation, a conservative research organization. ``If you
can accuse the other side of being opposed to motherhood and the
flag, by God you'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a technical sense, spending some portion of next year's
projected Social Security surplus of $147 billion has almost
nothing to do with the longer-term issue of assuring that the
retirement system is financially sound enough to weather the
impending retirement of the vast baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   The government has spent excess Social Security revenues
routinely for decades without any substantial partisan debate. But
that was before the government moved from budget deficits into
surpluses and gained the luxury of differentiating between revenues
from general taxation and revenues generated by the payroll tax
that finances Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The government can do two things with its excess revenues, from
whatever source. It can spend them, or it can use them to reduce
the portion of the national debt held by the public in the form of
Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Because the baby boomers are in their peak earning years, Social
Security revenues will far exceed what is needed to pay benefits to
current retirees for another decade or two, and then will fall well
below what is needed to pay full benefits. Next year's $147 billion
Social Security surplus will reach $235 billion by 2009.
</P>
<P>
   If the Social Security surplus is used to reduce the national
debt, it will help keep interest rates low, spur additional
economic growth and leave the federal government in better
financial condition for the day when it has to begin borrowing
again to meet Social Security obligations.
</P>
<P>
   But spending a relatively small portion of the money would still
allow the government to reduce the national debt substantially in
coming years, something both parties agree should be a priority.
And spending the money _ in essence using it to cover a shortfall
in the government's general accounts _ would not in any way change
the retirement system's financial condition, since Social Security
revenues are not set aside on the government's books specifically
to pay benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Americans _ and more than a few policy-makers _ appear to
believe that using a portion of the Social Security surplus to
cover a deficit in the non-Social Security budget would constitute
a `raid' on Social Security, reducing Social Security's assets and
impairing its ability to pay benefits in the future,'' said a
recent report by the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a
liberal-leaning research organization. ``These beliefs, however,
are not correct and appear to be rooted in a misunderstanding of
how Social Security finances work.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, drawing a line in the sand over spending Social
Security revenues is an arbitrary way of deciding how to apportion
projected surpluses. It is more about political symbolism than
about policy or economic choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There desperately needs to be a decent, civil discussion about
what we do with Social Security and for that matter what we do with
our entire budget,'' said John of the Heritage Foundation. ``I'm
afraid 1999 and 2000 do not look like the years that is going to
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
