<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9287 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-RDP-HNS &LR;      09-28 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO REVIEW LAW ALLOWING RAPE VICTIMS TO SUE ATTACKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court delved into the area of victims'
rights Tuesday, agreeing to decide whether a U.S. law permitting
women to sue their violent attackers in federal court is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, acting six days before their new term officially
begins, also said they would rule on the constitutionality of a
Colorado law that requires abortion protestors to be at least 100
feet from a medical facility when trying to convince pregnant women
to forgo the controversial procedure. In addition, the high court
agreed to rule on whether the Constitution gives parents the right
to prevent grandparents from seeing a grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, which will begin hearing arguments again
Monday, is expected to render its decisions in these cases by July.
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, who is recovering from colon cancer
surgery, participated in the court's decision to hear these
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg was released from a Washington hospital Tuesday. The
Supreme Court's public information office said Ginsburg's cancer
was confined to her colon and nearby tissue and did not spread to
other parts of her body.
</P>
<P>
   In the rights case out of Virginia, the justices will review a
lower court's decision that Congress exceeded its constitutional
authority by enabling women to sue their attackers under the
federal 1994 Violence Against Women Act.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in ruling the law
invalid, threw out college freshman Christy Brzonkala's lawsuit
against fellow Virginia Tech students Antonio Morrison and James
Crawford. Brzonkala claimed the two football players pinned her
down on a dormitory bed and raped her in September 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the 4th Circuit rejected Brzonkala's argument
that Congress' powers to regulate interstate commerce and ensure
equal protection under the law gave federal lawmakers the authority
to permit women to sue their attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the appeals court said the congressional attempt
to discourage sex crimes had no relationship to the regulation of
commerce. The 4th Circuit agreed with Brzonkala that Congress can
ensure that states provide equal protection for residents but said
the anti-violence law seeks to control activities by private
citizens, not states.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Clinton administration, pressing Brzonkala's
argument before the Supreme Court, said the impact of sex crimes on
the U.S. economy gives Congress the interstate-commerce authority
to allow women to sue their attackers. The administration added
that violence against women drains between $3 billion and $5
billion annually from the national economy as victims often miss
work after they are attacked.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the administration argued that the Constitution's
Equal Protection Clause gives Congress broad authority to ensure
that states treat people equally. The federal law, by giving women
a chance to sue their attackers, ensures that female victims have
recourse even in states that might not provide them a day in court,
the administration said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia never charged the two men in the alleged incident.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech, however, investigated and found Morrison guilty
of having violated the school's Abusive Conduct Policy and moved to
suspend him for two semesters. But the university provost deferred
the suspension until after Morrison's college football career ended
and ordered him to attend a one-hour session with an
equal-opportunity/affirmative-action compliance officer.
</P>
<P>
   University charges against Crawford were dismissed for lack of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Colorado case, the justices will review a state Supreme
Court decision upholding a criminal law that bars people from
speaking to, distributing leaflets to or displaying signs in front
of anybody within 100 feet of a medical facility without that
person's consent. The law was aimed at abortion protesters who seek
to block the entrances to clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents, in their successful request that the court
hear their appeal, argued that Colorado's restriction violates
their First Amendment right to free speech. The protesters said the
law limits their ability to voice their concerns while standing on
a public sidewalk, a traditional arena for constitutionally
protected political speech.
</P>
<P>
   But Colorado, in its failed attempt to convince the justices to
let the decision stand, called the law a legitimate effort to
regulate when, where and how people can express their views.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment prevents the state from curtailing speech
that expresses specific viewpoints, such as opposition to abortion,
the state said. The law, however, is constitutional because it
prevents all speech within 100 feet of a medical facility, Colorado
argued.
</P>
<P>
   The case before the justices is reminiscent of the Texas Supreme
Court's July 1998 order that abortion protesters in Houston use a
``normal speaking voice'' when addressing women entering clinics,
and leave when the women they are trying to counsel indicate ``a
desire to be left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas court issued its order in upholding a $1.2 million
damage award against protesters who staged large demonstrations at
Houston abortion clinics during and after the 1992 Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In the parental-rights case, the justices will consider the
constitutionality of a Washington law that gives grandparents the
right to seek visitation rights with a grandchild if such visits
are ``in the best interests of the child,'' even if the parents
object. The Washington Supreme Court has struck down the law,
ruling that it interferes with the parents' constitutional liberty
and privacy rights to raise their children as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   The case could have widespread implications as family law judges
across the nation generally assert wide authority in matters
concerning child welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Grandparents Jennifer and Gary Troxel, in their successful
request that the court hear their appeal, said the law should be
constitutional because of the government's interest in ensuring a
child's interests are well served. In many cases, those interests
are best satisfied when children have regular contact with
grandparents, said the Troxels, who seek a court order to see their
grandchildren, Natalie and Isabelle Troxel.
</P>
<P>
   Tommie Granville, Natalie and Isabelle's mother, unsuccessfully
urged the justices to reject the grandparent's appeal. In her brief
to the justices, Granville argued that parents' right to rear their
children as they see fit supersedes the desire of grandparents to
see their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy regarding the Troxels' visitation rights arose
after their son, Brad, the father of their grandchildren, killed
himself, and Granville limited the grandparents' access to Natalie
and Isabelle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
