<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-JOBLESS-COX     09-28 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-JOBLESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unemployment claims rise in wake of Hurricane Floyd, flooding
 &HT;    By Tom Murphy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Unemployment claims in the first week after
Hurricane Floyd were 10 times higher than what's considered normal,
according to Employment Security Commission officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had between 900 and 1,200 claims last week,'' said Steve
Rogers, who manages the Rocky Mount office. ``A heavy week in
September is normally between 75 and 100 applicants. It's
heart-breaking. Businesses can't operate. People can't get to work
because they've lost their transportation. Their homes have been
destroyed. They can't find day care for their children, or they
have other problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers says the Twin Counties' unemployment rate will skyrocket
in upcoming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unemployment rate will be substantial across Eastern North
Carolina,'' he said. ``It will be even higher in the Twin Counties
because we did get hit harder. The next couple of weeks are going
to be tough at this office. The aftermath of Hurricane Floyd will
be difficult for a lot of people for a long time. Some small
businesses destroyed by floodwater won't reopen. Small farmers will
have a hard time recovering, which will definitely impact all of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Milbourne, 37, sat in a chair at the Employment Security
Commission office, waiting for his turn to apply for work or to
draw unemployment benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost everything to Hurricane Floyd,'' he said. ``I lost my
home. I lost my job at Universal Leaf in Rocky Mount. The company's
building was under 7 feet of water during the flood. They lost
everything in their building. They told me to keep in touch with
them the best I could. They say they may have some of the same type
work in Wilson, but they haven't gotten back in contact with me
yet. That's why I'm here looking into getting another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Haese, 45, a homeless person, was living by Maple Creek.
His makeshift home was flooded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's discouraging,'' he said. ``I saved some blankets. I'm
staying with my mother temporarily. I hope to find a full-time job
and get into a motel. I had a part-time job getting apartments
ready to rent before the hurricane came.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got hope,'' said Shirley Knight, 35, of Princeville. ``I
lost my car and home to the flood. I worked at International Health
Care in Tarboro. It's gone, too. All the homes my customers lived
in are flooded. I've got no transportation to go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight, like others who visited the office, said she wants to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be able to get another job,'' she said. ``But it's hard
when you've got no transportation. The lost job is my main problem.
No money is another. I haven't got any. I worked one day before the
storm came, and I haven't gotten paid for it. But I've got hope.
I'm not going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Watson, 32, of Pinetops said Floyd put him out of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hurricane cost me my job,'' he said. ``The company I
worked for constructs grain bins. I couldn't get to work. I think
I'll be able to get my job back. Right now, I need a job and money.
I've got three boys to support.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost two jobs to the hurricane,'' said Bonnie Young, 40, of
Nashville, who was employed at Bojangles in Nashville and Englewood
Baptist Church in Rocky Mount. Both the restaurant and church were
damaged by Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bojangles was under water,'' she said. ``It is being remodeled
and scheduled to reopen Oct. 20. The church said they would let me
know about my job there. My car is broken down, so in the meantime,
I hope to draw unemployment. It's tough to lose your job. It's even
tougher when you lose two and become totally unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said two types of unemployment benefits are available -
regular and disaster benefits, which are based on 1998 earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person is not qualified for regular unemployment
benefits, then we take a disaster claim,'' he said. ``It may assist
them. Once we get a claim processed, a person's first check should
come in about a week. ESC will write checks as fast as it can and
get them back as quickly as possible. Regular and disaster benefits
are for six months. Hopefully, by the time benefits expire, people
will have returned to their old jobs or found other employment
opportunities. Most of the people had rather be back at work than
be in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said ESC will attempt to meet the high demand for
assistance in a time of need.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is not a gravy train that someone is going to ride,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Murphy writes for The Rocky Mount Telegram, Rocky Mount,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
