<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-PRAYER-HNS &LR;      09-28 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRAYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, STILL IN COUNSELING, MOVED BY `UNMERITED FORGIVENESS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Making a rare mention of the Monica Lewinsky
scandal, President Clinton told religious leaders Tuesday that he
remains in counseling with ministers and feels moved by the
``unmerited forgiveness'' shown by his family and the public.
</P>
<P>
   A subdued and hoarse Clinton allowed the brief reflection at the
annual White House prayer breakfast, a forum he used last year to
offer an emotional apology, confess his ``sin'' and ask for
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was one of the most difficult years in my life, and
this occasion, because it has come to mean so much to me, was a
very difficult one. For those of you who were part of that, I want
to express my particular appreciation,'' Clinton told more than 100
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sexual affair with Lewinsky, a White House intern,
roiled Washington's political waters throughout 1998 and prompted
charges of perjury, abuse of power and obstruction of justice from
independent counsel Ken Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The House in December voted to impeach Clinton, making him the
second president in U.S. history to face removal from office. He
was acquitted by the Senate in February.
</P>
<P>
   The president offered a special word of thanks to the three
ministers who serve as his counselors: Rev. Philip Wogaman of
Foundry Methodist Church in Washington; Rev. Gordon MacDonald of
the Grace Chapel Protestant Church in Massachusetts and Rev. Tony
Campolo, a professor at Eastern College in Pennsylvania. Wogaman
and MacDonald attended the breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also want you to know that we are continuing our work. It is
interesting and not always comfortable but always rewarding,''
Clinton said of their sessions. The White House later refused to
provide more information on the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the three ministers kept their word ``both to help
me and to hold me accountable. And I have kept my word to meet with
them and to work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the scandal itself, Clinton said he has been
``profoundly moved, as few people have, by the pure power of grace,
unmerited forgiveness through grace'' from his wife and daughter,
from legions of American people and from God.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton attended the breakfast and
watched her husband intently as he gave his remarks. She also spoke
to the religious leaders, assembled in the State Dining Room, but
did not mention the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The prayer breakfast this year focused on children and violence,
especially the recent mass shootings at a Fort Worth, Texas,
church, a Los Angeles Jewish day-care center and at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The president also hinted at his own decision to seek
counseling, drawing a parallel between his situation and the
refusal of some mentally disturbed people, especially men, to ask
for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced a lot of these people are known to be
profoundly disturbed, well before they go out and kill people. A
lot of these people, especially this is true of men, I think, are
still really hung up about asking for help. I know about that.
That's a hard thing for men to do. I know about that,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he believed people would be less hesitant to seek
help from a minister than seeking counseling from a government
social office or a professional therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that the faith community can play a major role
in protecting our children from violence, in supporting
common-sense gun legislation, in participating in our campaign
against youth violence, in forming community partnerships to
identify and intervene in the lives of people before it is too
late,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton's acquittal, the White House has worked to put the
scandal behind the administration and to focus on other issues.
News surrounding the affair flared briefly this summer when Hillary
Clinton, considering a bid for the Senate from New York, suggested
the president's childhood, marked by custody fights between his
mother and grandmother, played a role in the ``weakness'' that led
him to adultery.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart declined further comment on
the president's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no further insight to what he said. I'll leave you to
interpret it,'' he told reporters. He declined to say when or how
often Clinton has met with his counselors.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart said that relations between the White House and
Congress are back to normal after the contentious impeachment
fight. ``Defining it (normal) broadly, yes. I think that what we
have now is we've got a gold, old-fashioned policy debate going
on,'' Lockhart said of the budget fight underway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
