r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     09-28 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIANNA'S READY TO GIVE OF HERSELF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Arianna Huffington &LR;  threw a luncheon recently at her Brentwood
residence for Sen.  &UR; John McCain &LR;  and his new book, ``Faith of My
Fathers,'' and to introduce the author to her best and brightest
pals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ann Louise Bardach &LR;  writes in the latest New Yorker that McCain
greeted the crowd _ including  &UR; Larry King  &LR; and  &UR; Barry &LR; 
 &UR; Diller &LR;  _ ``on a veranda that overlooked a swimming pool, and,
beyond it, a grand lawn decorated with animal-shaped topiary.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Huffington said she liked McCain. ``All the other
candidates talk about prosperity, and I'm tired of hearing about
prosperity. He's the only one who talks about sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Speaking at a luncheon in San Francisco this week,  &UR; Peter &LR; 
 &UR; Giles &LR;  of the Tech Museum in San Jose _ a natural backdrop for
political candidates who want to demonstrate commitment to
innovation _ said that only one visiting politician had his advance
team make arrangements to pay the admission fee for himself and
entourage. It was  &UR; George W. Bush &LR; , who'll be there  &LR; Thursday &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. New York magazine says that George W. has already asked
 &UR; Colin Powell &LR;  to be secretary of state, and Powell is said to have
accepted. But Col.  &UR; Bill Smullen &LR; , who speaks for Powell, told the
magazine that Powell hasn't been asked and hasn't accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unreasonable to think that such an announcement would be
made at this point in time,'' said Smullen. ``It would be
premature.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.P.S. A glance at the Amazon.com rankings of books written by
Republican presidential wannabes may be an indicator of the state
of their campaigns:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; John McCain &LR; 's ``Faith of My Fathers, No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Pat Buchanan &LR; 's ``A Republic, Not an Empire,'' No. 26.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steve Forbes &LR; ' ``The New Birth of Freedom,'' No. 1,502.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Dan Quayle &LR; 's ``Worth Fighting For,'' No. 20,246 (which
explains his dropping out).
</P>
