   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Vanity Fair contributing editor  &UR; Dee Dee Myers &LR; , who is
married to the New York Times'  &UR; Todd Purdum &LR; , and CNN's &UR; Christiane &LR; 
 &UR; Amanpour &LR; , who is married to the State Department's  &UR; Jamie &LR; 
 &UR; Rubin &LR; , are both about three months pregnant, says the Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Las Vegas recently,  &UR; Patty Warren &LR;  saw  &UR; Evel Knievel &LR;  in a
sushi bar, with his ``angular, slick black'' car _ ``It looked like
Darth Vader's helmet,'' she said _ parked outside. The car had his
initials on a plate in front, and a disability sign lying on the
dashboard. Ever the valiant gent, Knievel wasn't parked in a
disability zone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Perhaps because even lay people know how to fake laughs in
social situations, it's much harder to cry than to laugh, says
actor  &UR; Jack Willis &LR; , who plays Yvan, the Joe Schmoe role in
``Art,'' at the Curran in San Francisco. ``Crying every night is
exhausting. Faking a laugh is easier than faking a cry. You can get
a lot of kinds of laughs, a million different kinds, chuckles and
guffaws. But crying is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cotter Smith &LR; , the serious-looking guy who plays Serge, the
play's intense art lover, says his hardest job is not laughing.
``It's a very funny play.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Designer &UR; Paco Rabanne &LR;  has apologized for his prediction, a
few months ago, that the space station Mir was going to crash into
Paris and destroy it. ``I don't smoke, don't take drugs and I don't
even drink,'' he said. ``Yes, maybe my imagination gets the better
of me. But I also like to provoke people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In results that will be disquieting to anyone but only
children, McCall's says that 16 percent of 500 women surveyed said
they had a favorite child.
</P>
<P>
   _ Smart Money magazine says you shouldn't send a computer virus
with your Internet resume, which sounds like good advice, but not
so breathtakingly smart.
</P>
<P>
   _ W, a guide to what's trendy and expensive, says that  &UR; Dr. &LR; 
 &UR; Hauschka &LR; 's ``new organic makeup from Germany is the Birkenstock of
beauty products.'' This makeup is made from plants, harvested at
dawn, ``when healing properties are at their peak,'' by nonsmokers
who ``do not wear synthetic fragrances or acrylic nail polish.''
 &UR; Brad Pitt  &LR; and  &UR; Julia Roberts  &LR; are customers.
</P>
