</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-DOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLER-COASTER DOW FLIRTS WITH CORRECTION LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market dipped into correction territory Tuesday before
a surprise rebound late in the day left the Dow Jones industrial
average virtually unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow dropped 222 points and was within 82 points of 10,000 in
the early afternoon _ nearly 12 percent below its all-time high on
Aug. 25 of 11,326.04. A 10 percent decline is officially a
correction.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow bounced back like a yo-yo. At the end of the day,
the index had given up only 27.86 points, or a quarter of a
percentage point. The Dow is still up nearly 12 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index Tuesday lost
just 1.11 points, closing at 1282.20, while the technology-heavy
Nasdaq dipped 5.5 points, closing at 2756.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little roller coaster'' is how Ned Riley, BankBoston Corp.'s
chief investment officer, described the market activity.
</P>
<P>
   Riley attributed the swings partly to institutional investors
who may be selling positions as the third quarter draws to a close
and shareholder reports are due. They then buy stocks they wish to
hold during the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tuesday's recovery, investment analysts said a mood of
pessimism has clearly slipped into the US market in recent weeks
amid interest rate hikes by the Federal Reserve, rising oil prices,
and the promise of higher returns in overseas financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikkei stock index Tuesday gained an astonishing 3 percent,
or 504.64 points, after the Japanese government agreed to loosen
its purse strings to stimulate economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Doug Cliggott, stock strategist for J.P. Morgan
&AMP; Co., said a rocky ride may be in store in September and October,
typically troublesome months in the US market. J.P. Morgan does not
expect the S&AMP;P 500 index to provide much added returns through the
end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're near the beginning of what will be a trading range
market that could have some fairly violent swings, probably in both
directions,'' Cliggott predicted. ``It's a high-risk market.''
</P>
<P>
   US stocks were saved by gains in America Online Inc. and
Microsoft Corp., as the dollar strengthened against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see the yen falling and the dollar rising, people feel
more comfortable about the US equity market,'' said Arthur Hogan,
chief market analyst for Jefferies &AMP; Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks also fell sharply and then recovered. American
Express Co., for example, dipped to 130 7/8 amid the market drop
but closed at 135 13/16, up 13/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
