<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-POKEMON-COX     09-28 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School bans Pokemon cards
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's no Pokemon card with the power to stop what
school officials did recently at Huddleston Elementary in Peachtree
City: ban kids from bringing the wildly popular gaming cards to
school.
</P>
<P>
   So many students were bringing Pokemon cards every day it caused
headaches for school staff, Principal Lynda Lambeth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was beginning to disrupt the learning environment,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Children were sneaking games during class, and teachers had to
deal with distraught students who had lost cards or made unwise
trades with classmates, said Sue Cleek, assistant principal at
Huddleston. She estimated one-third or more of Huddleston's 670
students brought cards to school some days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids would be playing with the cards when they weren't
supposed to be,'' Cleek said. ``It was something everyone
noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Students caught with the game will have their cards confiscated
and returned _ to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Huddleston is not the first school to ban the game. Schools in
Iowa, Wisconsin and suburban Chicago are among those to outlaw the
cards this school year. Lambeth said several other Fayette County
schools also banned Pokemon from school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon (short for ``pocket monster'') cards have become a craze
among the pre-teen set. Pokemon began as a Japanese TV cartoon. It
became a best-selling Game Boy cartridge before the card game
version took off.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the game is to acquire various Pokemon characters
and do battle against other people's characters. Each card has a
picture of a monster with different ``hit points'' that measure how
much damage they can inflict and how much protection they have.
</P>
<P>
   A starter set of 60 cards costs $8.99, while some packs can cost
$20 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just trade, and we just look at cards and stuff,'' said
Colin Baker, 10, a fifth-grade student at Huddleston who estimates
he has about 400 Pokemon cards.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-grader Jocelyn Clarke said she was glad the game was
banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids _ they weren't doing their work. They were just
playing with the Pokemon cards,'' she said. ``Some people were
fighting about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Donsky writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
