<SLUG> BC-GANGPLANK-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MAN SUES CRUISE LINE OVER FALL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Fla.) 
 
By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Houston man has sued Miami-based Royal Caribbean
cruise line over an unexpected splash he received during a Hawaiian
vacation earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Perlmutter, 79, says in the state district lawsuit he
filed Monday that while on the trip, he discovered that he and
other passengers would have to ``negotiate a wooden gangplank'' to
enjoy the beauty of the Hawaiian islands.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Branch, Perlmutter's attorney, said the cruise ship
Legend of the Seas is too large to dock at the port of Lahaina,
Maui, where the incident happened. He said passengers are required
to walk a gangplank from the cruise ship to a smaller vessel,
called a tender, that can dock.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said that on Jan. 2, 1999, ``while (Perlmutter) was
attempting to get from the ship to the tender, (Perlmutter) fell
into the water up to his armpits and sustained serious and
permanent injuries to his body.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch said Perlmutter did not require immediate medical
attention, but he will likely need surgery on his right knee
because of damage caused by the fall. He said Perlmutter will seek
less than $75,000 but declined to say exactly how much.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney said the waters were choppy at the time because of
an approaching front, and the smaller vessel was moving around
because it was not properly anchored. He said Perlmutter did not
fall off the side of the the gangplank, which was about 8 feet wide
and 15 feet long with no handrails. The accident occurred as
Perlmutter stepped off the gangplank to get on the tender.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Perlmutter) went to step on the tender, and all of a
sudden there was no tender,'' Branch said, explaining the smaller
ship was moved by the rough seas.
</P>
<P>
   Branch said the cruise line should have had employees assist
Perlmutter off the gangplank in the choppy waters, and it should
have made sure the smaller ship was stable.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean spokeswoman Lynn Martenstein said it is the
company's understanding that Perlmutter sustained minor injuries.
She declined to comment further on the lawsuit because of the
pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   She said gangplanks are safe and are commonly used to get
passengers to ports where large cruise ships cannot dock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any other incidents when this has happened,''
Martenstein said. ``It's a routine procedure, and we have staff
assisting people.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch said he would not equate the dangers of walking the
gangplank with ``walking the plank'' on pirate ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it conjures up piracy, that's fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
