<SLUG> BC-LEFAVE-REJECTED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DAY CARE OPERATOR HEADED BACK TO JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' highest court rejected Tuesday Cheryl
Amirault LeFave's last-ditch bid for a new hearing, which means she
almost certainly will be returning to prison within a week to
continue serving time for molesting children.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Supreme Judicial Court overturned a judge's
decision granting a new trial to LeFave, who was convicted in 1987
with her late mother, Violet Amirault, of sexually abusing children
at her family's Malden day care center.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the SJC denied LeFave's request to reconsider that
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said James L. Sultan, one of LeFave's attorneys,
``I think it's a virtual certainty she's going back'' to prison.
</P>
<P>
   A Middlesex Superior Court judge is expected to reinstate
LeFave's original conviction and 8- to 20-year sentence within a
week, Sultan said. A court date had not been scheduled as of
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan also said that Harvard law professor Charles Ogletree,
director of Harvard's Criminal Justice Institute, has joined
LeFave's legal team.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave's attorneys have said they may begin a federal court
appeal of her conviction or seek clemency from Governor Paul
Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   They also have said that if LeFave is sent back to prison they
will ask for an early parole hearing, although LeFave does not
intend to admit to any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave has steadfastly insisted that she, her mother and her
brother, Gerald, were wrongly convicted. She eight years of her
sentence before being released in 1995, when a Superior Court judge
overturned her and her mother's convictions.
</P>
<P>
   During their imprisonment, LeFave and her mother, who died of
cancer in 1997, repeatedly were denied parole, apparently because
they refused to admit guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Amirault was convicted in 1986 and is serving a 30- to
40-year sentence. He has lost three appeals and remains in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
