<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9312 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY29-COX     09-28 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley unveils plan for health care changes, calls Gore's plan
'timid'
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAN NUYS, Calif. _ Presidential hopeful Bill Bradley on Tuesday
delivered on his promise to be a candidate of ``big ideas,''
unveiling a health care plan that would scrap most of the Medicaid
program for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bradley's sweeping proposal, uninsured Americans would be
able to enroll in the same private health care plans available to
federal employees and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of Bradley's plan, which would require coverage for all
children under the age 19 whose parents cannot afford it, is to
cover 95 percent of the nation's 44 million uninsured, with the
federal government subsidizing all or part of the premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's proposal would essentially take the federal government
out of the business of directly paying the medical costs of people
in Medicaid, and instead transform Uncle Sam into one of the
largest subsidizers of private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he would fund the program's $55 to $65 billion
estimated cost out of budget surpluses not generated by Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good health care is a right,'' said Bradley. ``And it is up to
us to ensure that right to every American.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seized on a potent issue in the Democratic primary
against Vice President Gore, and he used his speech here to cast
himself as a bold thinker capable of bold reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his plan would cover more people and elevate
affordable health care to one of government's primary
responsibilities. Gore's plan, announced earlier this month, would
use an existing Medicaid program to cover all children and offer
tax incentives for their parents to purchase coverage as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is between trying to do something big to deal
with a big problem that affects virtually all Americans and
continuing to be one advocating incremental change,'' Bradley said
after his speech. ``What he's proposed is definitely timid compared
to what we have proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also criticized Gore for not putting a cost estimate on
his proposal. ``A campaign proposal without a price tag is just
another politician's promise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elaine Kamarck, a policy adviser to the Gore campaign, said
Bradley had failed to address the long-term solvency of Medicare
and said his proposal would be too expensive. ``You can't afford to
do this and begin to keep Medicare solvent,'' Kamarck said. ``The
vice president's approach works. This approach doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not estimate how many new federal workers would be
needed to administer the program, nor did he address concerns that
some people would leave private plans to join the government
program.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley would end the Medicaid program for children and steer
those children into the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program,
a network of about 400 private insurers that offers subsidized
health insurance to nation's nine million federal workers.
</P>
<P>
   The government would fully subsidize the $1,200 premium for
children whose families earn up to 200 percent of the poverty
level, or $32,800 per year for a family of four, and provide
partial subsidies for families who earn up to 300 percent of the
poverty level, or $49,200 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Premium payments for all Americans would be excluded from income
for income tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley would also pay the estimated $1,800 premium for all
adults to enroll in the federal employee program, if their income
was at the poverty line. A partial government subsidy would be
available for adults earning more.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal drew immediate praise from groups advocating
universal health care coverage for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really creates a mechanism to create affordable coverage,
even to those that are at high risk,'' said Gail Shearer, director
of health policy at the Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Shearer said Gore's plan failed to offer deep
enough subsidies to insure universal coverage. But Ron Pollack,
director of Families USA, who praised Bradley's plan, nevertheless
cautioned that it might be more difficult to enact because it
involved more wholesale change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is broader and would cover more people,'' said Pollack,
whose group also advocates universal coverage. ``Gore builds more
on existing proposals and may be easier to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
