<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS TRY TO SIGN UP FOR TEST OF NEW CANCER DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hundreds of cancer patients jammed a hotline, clicked
on World Wide Web sites and applied by fax Tuesday as recruitment
opened in Boston for a few volunteers to take the most widely
publicized new cancer drug in years.
</P>
<P>
   The medical centers set to carry out the first human clinical
trials of endostatin, an experimental drug that shrank tumors in
mice with no harmful side effects, will continue to accept calls
and faxes until next Monday for the first round of tests.
</P>
<P>
   The hotline staffed by four cancer nurses opened at 8 a.m.
Tuesday, and had received more than 1,300 calls by 2:30 p.m., said
a spokesman for Dana Farber/Partners Cancer Care, which is
conducting the trial in collaboration with Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Many other patients downloaded forms from the Internet and faxed
them to a toll-free number.
</P>
<P>
   Calls were so heavy when the hotline opened that some callers
gave up, but by afternoon there was only a short wait, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who declined to give her name told the Globe that she
had called the hotline on behalf of her mother-in-law who has lung
cancer. Finally, she said, she got the forms from the Internet,
filled them out and sent them from a commercial fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been following the news ever since Dr. (Judah) Folkman
announced such good results in animals,'' said the woman, referring
to the Children's Hospital researcher in whose lab endostatin was
discovered. ``It's a very small study,'' she said of the trial that
just opened, ``but we hope it will go very well and be opened to
the public on a wider basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phase 1 study, as it's called, will enroll only 15 to 30
patients in Boston: two other studies not yet begun, at M.D.
Anderson Cancer Center in Houston and the University of Wisconsin
in Madison, will each recruit about the same number.
</P>
<P>
   The Phase 1 study is designed only to see how well patients
tolerate an escalating dose of the drug, and to check for side
effects. Effectiveness would be evaluated in later phases.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible, patients must have solid tumors that don't
respond to any treatment, but they must also be mobile and have at
least six months' life expectancy. A source said that a number of
people who called in Tuesday would not qualify for the trial
because they are currently receiving chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   The hotline number is 617-632-5100. On the World Wide Web, use
any of these sites: www.dana-farber.net/endostatin;
www.cancer.mgh.harvard.edu; or
www.bidmc.caregroup.org/endostatin/default.asp.
</P>
<P>
   The first patients will begin taking the drug in about two
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
