<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-STOCK-COX     09-28 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battered Coca-Cola trades below $50
 &HT;    By Henry Unger and Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of Coca-Cola traded under $50 Tuesday for the
first time in nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   The stock hit another 52-week low of $49.56 1/4 before closing
at $50.75, down 25 cents. The shares last traded below the $50
threshold in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's shares have had a stunning fall since July 14, 1998,
when they closed at $87.93 3/4, giving the company a market value
of $217.13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the plunging shares have erased $91.82 billion of
shareholder wealth, at least on paper. The company now has a market
value of $125.31 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Until its recent troubles, Coca-Cola had been considered by many
investors to be an unparalleled money machine. A hundred dollars
invested in the company on Dec. 31, 1993, would have turned into
$318 five years later.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, Coca-Cola was America's second-most-valuable
company, after General Electric. But with investors flocking to
technology stocks and with Coca-Cola's sales and earnings under
pressure, partly because of weak overseas economies, the company
has tumbled in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   It's now America's 17th-most-valuable company.
</P>
<P>
   About half of Coca-Cola's shares are held by individuals, with
the other half owned by institutional investors. The Robert W.
Woodruff Foundation and related family foundations own a total of
118,572,262 shares. The foundations last year reported total
combined assets of nearly $8.87 billion, most of it in Coca-Cola
stock. Those shares were worth about $7.94 billion at the end of
1998. Today, they're worth about $6.02 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in the stock's value has been more pronounced in recent
weeks, in tandem with the market's general decline. For example,
Coca-Cola's shares closed as high as $70.50 on May 5.
</P>
<P>
   But the shares also have been hurt by the company's Sept. 3
announcement that it would not meet analysts' earnings
expectations. That's partly due to this summer's European health
scare involving the company's soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 30 days, Coca-Cola's shares have lost 18.2 percent
of their value, making them the fifth-worst performer among the
giant blue chip issues that make up the Standard &AMP; Poor's 100-stock
index. Year-to-date, Coca-Cola is the ninth-worst performer of the
S&AMP;P 100, with a loss of 24.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not surprising that analysts are divided in their
opinion of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Among 16 analysts surveyed by First Call, only one rates
Coca-Cola a ``strong buy.'' Seven rate the company a ``buy.''
Another seven rate it a ``hold.'' One analyst advises investors to
``sell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a well-below-average recommendation for the S&AMP;P 500
companies right now,'' said Chuck Hill, research director of First
Call. ``Obviously, they've had a tough period here.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Andrew Conway of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter said he
remains cautious about the company in the short term. But Conway
still believes long-term investors will be rewarded for their
patience. He predicts the stock will be trading in the $75 range by
the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is this is a terrific buying opportunity in the long
term,'' added analyst Marty Romm of Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, however, Romm thinks Coca-Cola will have
trouble generating a lot of buying interest until it and several
other consumer nondurable companies start to improve their sales
and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts recently have been trimming their earnings forecasts
for Coca-Cola. The mean forecast this year is $1.30 a share,
according to IBES International. The high is $1.33, and the low is
$1.27. Coca-Cola earned about that much in 1996, when it posted
$1.29 a share.
</P>
<P>
   For next year, the average estimate is $1.53 a share. The high
is $1.60, and the low is $1.48.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's closing price, Coca-Cola's shares are trading at 39
times estimated 1999 earnings.
</P>
<P>
   At least one money manager isn't yet convinced they are a
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if it got to 30 times earnings, or close to the market
multiple, I would be attracted to it,'' said Robert Sanborn of the
Oakmark Fund, which has $5.5 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger and Robert Luke write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
