   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPENDING (Washington) _ The House of Representatives,
failing to complete work on the federal budget for 2000, approve an
interim spending plan to keep the government operating well into
October. By GREG McDONALD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRAYER (Washington) _ President Clinton appears at a
prayer breakfast where a year ago he issued an apology for the
Monica Lewinsky scandal. This year he tells the ministers that he
feels moved by the ``unmerited forgiveness'' shown by his family
and the public. By NANCY MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ The Supreme Court delves into the area
of women's rights, agreeing to decide whether a law permitting
women to sue their violent male attackers in federal court passes
constitutional muster. The justices, acting six days before their
term officially begins, also agree to consider the
constitutionality of Colorado law restraining abortion protesters
and of a Washington state decision on grandparents' rights. By
STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Houston) _ The third defendant in the dragging
death of a disabled black man speaks to Dan Rather on ``60 Minutes
II,'' blaming everything on his two co-defendants. Shawn Berry, 24,
tells his version of what happened on June 7, 1998, near the East
Texas town of Jasper. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HEALTH (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush, 53, is in
great shape, in fact in the top 1 percent of his age group and in
the top 5 percent for a 40-year-old man, his doctor says in a
medical report. And the doctor says there is no physical evidence
that the Texas governor and Republican presidential hopeful ever
regularly used drugs. By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GANGPLANK-LAWSUIT (Houston) _ A Houston man has sued the Royal
Caribbean cruise line of Miami over an unexpected splash he got
during a Hawaiian vacation earlier this year. Bernard Perlmutter,
79, says in the lawsuit that while on the trip, he and other
passengers had to ``negotiate a wooden gangplank'' to enjoy the
beauty of one of the Hawaiian islands because the cruise ship was
too large to dock at a port on Maui. By RON NISSIMOV. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACEPORT-VISION (Freeport, Texas) _ ``It's kind of visionary
right now,'' admitted Fred Welch, as he swept his hand over the
marshy, snake-filled sea grass in Freeport. ``You have to imagine a
12,000-foot runway,'' he said, pointing to the barren land that is
bordered by a dirty drainage ditch. Welch is the executive director
of the Brazoria County Partnership, and he's hoping to catch the
big one: a huge spaceport that can send satellites and other cargo
into outer space. By L.M. SIXEL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BRONCOS (Denver) _ So much for visions of a three-peat. The
Denver Broncos are just trying to win a game. And the same is true
of the New York Jets, the team that the Broncos defeated in the AFC
Championship Game last year. What has happened to these two teams
that were expected to be the class of the AFC again this season? By
JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros and Cincinnati Reds
open a crucial two-game series that likely will decide the National
League Central Division Championship tonight in the Astrodome. By
CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
