r e BC-TV-POPULAR-SPI &LR;      09-28 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-POPULAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POPULAR' MAY NOT BE, AND `WORK WITH ME' IS TOO MUCH WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where NBC's ``Freaks and Geeks'' seems so real, so accessible in
its treatment of the adolescent quest for acceptance, The WB's
``Popular'' seems so not.
</P>
<P>
   Carly Pope and Leslie Bibb, two of The WB's latest
cover-girls-to-be, play opposites in the high school spectrum. Pope
is Sam McPherson, cynical member of the out crowd; Bibb is Brooke
McQueen, reigning queen of the popular scene.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a too-long, two-part premiere that starts
Wednesday and ends Thursday night in the show's regular time slot,
Sam and Brooke discover they're about to become siblings of a sort
when Sam's widowed mom and Brooke's divorced dad announce plans to
get married.
</P>
<P>
   This subtle-as-a-brick melding of the outs and the ins is rife
with possibilities, but ``Popular'' needs to overcome some basic
problems before it answers the can't-we-all-just-get-along
question. For one thing, the writers need to assume we're smarter
than the average hubcap and quit writing clumsy expository
information into the dialogue. In one such ``exposition,'' the
school's drama coach lets us know the principal characters and
basic plot of ``South Pacific'' (presumably because The WB's young
viewers might not be familiar with it). All it does is insult the
audience and demean the performer.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the acting needs to improve. Bibb is the show's standout
as the popular girl with demons of her own, but Pope isn't entirely
convincing as the outsider harboring a secret desire to fit in.
Same goes for the supporting cast. Some are pros, notably Tamara
Mello as a feisty activist and Sara Rue as the overweight
cheerleader wannabe, but others appear to be graduates of the
``Saved by the Bell'' school of the performing arts.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Popular'' is going to be popular, it might want to crib
from ``Freaks and Geeks'' or, even better, ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer,'' which has been doing the teenage-angst thing to near
perfection for three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS comedy ``Work With Me'' has the engaging Nancy Travis
and the funny Kevin Pollak playing husband-and-wife lawyers. He
works for a stuffy Wall Street firm until he fails to make partner
and quits in a huff, burning all bridges and access ramps on his
way out. Given few options, he joins his wife's one-person ``Sesame
Street'' practice, and the story line is set: husband and wife
together 24 hours, he with an assistant who's dating his wife's
assistant, but the assistants don't want anyone to know.
</P>
<P>
   Some genuinely funny moments emerge in ``Work With Me,'' but a
big obstacle for the viewer may be accepting that Pollak and Travis
_ or Jordan and Julie Better _ are husband and wife. Somewhat
reminiscent of Paul Reiser in ``Mad About You,'' Pollak seems to be
playing his wisecracking, standup-comic self as opposed to a
character in a comedy series. Travis also seems to be playing to
the audience, not to her colleagues onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's mainly a directorial problem, the chemistry in ``Work
With Me'' could improve as it goes along. But the premise's ability
to sustain a long run remains iffy _ how many marital/workplace
dustups can we take? _ and the inevitable comparison to ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' leaves ``Work With Me'' wanting.
</P>
<P>
   True, the two supporting players in ``Work With Me'' _ Ethan
Embry and Emily Rutherfurd _ get some funny lines, but they're no
match for Sean Hayes and Megan Mullally. Viewers willing to work
with this show may get something out of it, but watching a sitcom
shouldn't have to be work.
</P>
<P>
   Popular. Hourlong comedy/drama about teens and their desire to
be popular. Starring Carly Pope, Leslie Bibb, Tamara Mello,
Christopher Gorham, Tammy Lynn Michaels, Bryce Johnson, Sara Rue,
Ron Lester, Leslie Grossman and Chad Rowe. Two-part series premiere
Wednesday and Thursday nights and The WB. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Work With Me. Half-hour comedy about husband-and-wife lawyers
who decide to work together. Starring Nancy Travis, Kevin Pollak,
Ethan Embry, Emily Rutherfurd and Bray Poor. Series premiere
Wednesday night on CBS. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
