<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9323 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BEATTY-POLITICS-2TAKE     09-28 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATTY-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SPEECH MAY _ OR MAY NOT _ REVEAL BEATTY'S INTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Minn., Calif., Ill.)  (nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM with MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Wednesday night, in a Beverly Hills hotel
ballroom best known as the site of the Golden Globes, Henry Warren
Beatty, actor, writer, producer, director and Democrat, will make a
speech on global trade, campaign finance and social justice, his
friends say. He may _ or may not _ say something about running for
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The cheerleader-in-chief for a Beatty candidacy is Arianna
Huffington, a Republican political columnist not known for
embracing McGovern Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Among his kitchen cabinet of kibitizers and wordsmiths is
Patrick Caddell, the reformed pollster and strategist who advised
Jimmy Carter and Jerry Brown and now writes for ``The West Wing,''
a television series about the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Among the media throng expected to cover the speech is George
Stephanopoulos, the former White House aide who is now a political
analyst for ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   Could Hollywood make this stuff up?
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy enough to poke fun at Beatty, a legendary
lady-killer and famously diffident star who for 40 years has been a
cocky and enigmatic presence in the popular imagination, from
``Splendor in the Grass,'' to ``Bulworth.'' He is, after all, one
of the men about whom an old girlfriend, Carly Simon, wrote
``You're So Vain.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an age in which political careers are born, live and die
in the media, in which a former professional wrestler is governor
of Minnesota, an electronics billionaire from Texas has wrought
political havoc and the official biographer of the nation's last
actor-president fesses up to fabricating an entire narrative
persona in his new book on Ronald Reagan, Beatty is hardly a
laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very responsible person, who has a genuine love for
the Democratic Party and has over 30 years of activism in the
Democratic Party,'' said Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr. of Chicago, one of
a sizable group of disaffected politicos in both parties who have
welcomed Beatty's consideration of a campaign. ``But, like me, he
doesn't like the rightward drift of the party. Drifting to the
right is not the way Democrats win and make a difference in the
lives of average Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Beatty's old friend Stanley Sheinbaum, a liberal economist
and Democratic operative here, put it: ``He's a very serious guy
politically.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasion of all the fuss is Beatty's planned acceptance on
Wednesday of the annual Eleanor Roosevelt Award of the Southern
California Chapter of Americans for Democratic Action, a civil
liberties group that had long sought to honor him. It just happens
that Beatty's remarks at the dinner will amount to his most
extensive comments on a possible candidacy since Ms. Huffington
first publicly floated the idea in her syndicated column seven
weeks ago, and he elaborated in a terse and elliptical Op-Ed piece
in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Beatty declines to be interviewed for publication,
and insisted in an informal conversation the other day that he was
still unsure what he intended to say. He has told friends and
supporters that he does not flatter himself that the frisson that
has greeted his possible candidacy reflects anything other than the
power of his celebrity to shine light on a segment of thinking in
the Democratic Party that has remained largely unexpressed since
President Clinton successfully co-opted Republican themes in his
re-election strategy of ``triangulation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He always felt there was a candidate he could support in the
Democratic Party, and he no longer feels that way,'' said Frank
Mankiewicz, Robert F. Kennedy's former press secretary and a
longtime friend of Beatty's. The two Democratic contenders, Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, are ``nibbling
around the edges,'' Mankiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a Beatty candidacy came up in July at a dinner party
at Ms. Huffington's attended by Beatty and his wife, Annette
Bening.
</P>
<P>
   When other guests begin musing on the civic disconnection in
contemporary American life, someone suggested who better to tackle
that problem than J. Billington Bulworth himself. In that film,
released last year, Beatty plays a burned out senator so sick of
mouthing poll-tested platitudes that he takes a contract on his own
life, then is suddenly freed to tell the truth about political
cynicism, corporate greed, racial inequities and the state of
American democracy.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, Ms. Huffington made the musing public, and
since then, Beatty has drawn supportive words from Washington
public interest groups and politicians of all stripes. Ms.
Huffington introduced him to Bill Hillsman, the media man for Gov.
Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, who flew out for a consultation.
</P>
<P>
   Both wings of the Reform Party have sounded him out (he says
he's not interested), and John Burton, the old-line San Francisco
liberal who leads the California state Senate has made noises about
endorsing a Beatty candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican maverick Pat Buchanan poised to bolt to the
Reform Party, Ms. Huffington said the need for someone like Beatty
to offer an opposing voice is all the greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a professional storyteller,'' Ms. Huffington said.
``We've become so atomized and candidates are just addressing
pocketbook issues. All the candidates are talking about prosperity
and nobody really does talk about the public good, about justice
and sacrifice, all those big things that we haven't heard since
John F. Kennedy. And the need for someone to do that, for someone
who can pull the nation around the fire and draw us together as
we're being pulled apart, is all the more important with the
presence of Buchanan, whom I consider very dangerous and don't
underestimate at all.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Perversely, or perhaps predictably, Beatty's potential candidacy
is greeted far more skeptically in Hollywood than in Washington.
Here his rivals grouse _ under cover of anonymity _ that Beatty is
trying to distract attention from his next movie, ``Town and
Country,'' the story of a man in a midlife crisis, about which the
early buzz is bad. They say that he is a charming but politically
unsophisticated control freak who, at 62 with an apparently
blissful marriage and a fourth child on the way, could never stand
the invasive strain of a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's taken less seriously in Hollywood than anywhere
else, because people know him,'' said one colleague of Beatty in
the film industry who admires his work and did not want to be
quoted by name. ``Because people know him, and if they know
anything, it's that he's phenomenally self-protective, risk-averse,
and indecisive. He wants to be wooed, he doesn't really want to
woo. I think he's flirting with this idea in the way that he's
flirted with hundreds of movies that he's ultimately not committed
to.''
</P>
<P>
   But, even this person adds, ``There has never been anyone more
charming.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty has put himself on the line politically before, giving up
an entire year to raise money and campaign for George McGovern for
president in 1972, managing to get Art Garfunkel and Paul Simon to
set aside their feud for a McGovern fund-raiser. But friends say he
has usually been more comfortable behind the scenes, even in the
movies, preferring to work as director and producer and amassing a
fortune through canny business dealings. In the 1970s resisted
entreaties to run for governor of California despite promising
polls.
</P>
<P>
   He declined interviews altogether for most of the period between
``Shampoo'' in 1975 and ``Bugsy,'' in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren is the maestro of his own movements,'' said Caddell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is certainly not making the case that he has some unique
experience or qualification to run for president,'' Caddell said.
``He is saying there are very important things that are not being
said, and people have come to him because they think he might be
heard. I think that his real strength is to be a vehicle for people
who think they can have no impact, and can't be heard. In a sense,
that's a candidacy, not a candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
