<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9329 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-ARCHIVES-COX     09-28 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-ARCHIVES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   County document copies destroyed by flood, but originals
salvaged
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Hurricane Floyd flooded the basement of the
Robert Lee Humber House on Martin Luther King Drive, ruining
thousands of photocopied documents housed there by the state
archives.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the original documents, land records from counties
across eastern North Carolina, remain safe at their respective
county courthouses. The destroyed copies were in the process of
being microfilmed, something the state requires of local
governments, with the help of the Division of Archives and History.
</P>
<P>
   ``The microfilm was saved, but the counties will have to recopy
all those documents, and they're not going to be happy about that
at all,'' said Scott Power, supervisor of the Eastern North
Carolina Division of Archives and History, whose offices are in the
Humber House. ``But, it's a state law.''
</P>
<P>
   Also lost at the Humber House, built in 1895, were the oak
flooring and birch wood panelling in the basement. Power said the
foot of water that remained in the basement until last weekend
caused so much damage that all of the wood will have to be torn
out.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Greenville and Pitt County already had applied
for a state grant to address pre-storm decay at the home, including
the buckling porch and leaky windows. Power is hoping they will get
the grant and
</P>
<P>
   redirect the money toward the more pressing problems caused by
Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most well-preserved Colonial Revival
buildings we have here,'' Power said.
</P>
<P>
   All other books and documents on upper floors at the Humber
House remained untouched by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone with important documents was so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Smith, head of preservation and conservation at East
Carolina University's Joyner Library, said she's talked to many
individuals and businesses coping with soaked books and papers. The
library, which itself suffered no damage, has a freeze-dryer that
can dry books and papers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got a group coming in to dry church records dating from
1800 to the present,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger problem than water is the mold it creates, Smith said.
Mold sometimes can be dried and scraped off, but sometimes it ruins
books.
</P>
<P>
   When a local business called Smith with 40 file cabinets' worth
of wet papers, she called Munter's Moisture Control. The company
will collect documents or books and send them to a large drying
center in Massachusetts, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   For information on drying books, photographs and documents, call
Elizabeth Smith at 328-0297.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
