<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-SALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE PREDICTS 1 PERCENT DROP IN SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gillette Co. said it expects its third-quarter sales to
fall 1 percent because of declining demand for some brands of
shavers and pens, problems it blamed on a strong dollar that hurts
its overseas results.
</P>
<P>
   For the same period a year ago Gillette reported revenue of
$2.53 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, coming three weeks before the company reports
earnings for three months ended Sept. 30, confirmed some concerns
on Wall Street that sales weren't on track at the Boston razor and
battery maker.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gillette said its earnings per share grew for the
quarter by 7 percent compared to the same period a year ago, when
it reported net income of $353 million before charges. For the
current quarter, the company said it still expects to report net
income of about 32 cents per share, in line with expectations of
analysts surveyed by Zacks Investment Research.
</P>
<P>
   Early warnings of troubles have become routine for Gillette,
whose stock this year has fallen from a high of $64.38 in March on
concerns about the company's profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette made its disclosures Tuesday after the close of
trading. Before the announcement, shares fell $1 to $37 apiece. The
update was ``certainly a disappointment,'' said Tony Vento, analyst
at Edward Jones in St. Louis. Vento is one of several analysts who
believes that Gillette should focus on its core businesses of
razors, Duracell batteries, and oral care products and consider
selling off its stationery and Braun appliance units.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point in time, Gillette has to ask themselves, `Do we
want to be in these businesses?','' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's stationery line, which includes such brand names as
Paper Mate, Parker, and Waterman, saw sales fall from $924 milliion
to $856 million last year. In 1998, Braun sales were roughly flat
at $1.74 billion. Total 1998 sales for Gillette were just above $10
billion. Together razor and battery sales were about a little more
than $5.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Gillette says it can still restore growth to those business.
It said its latest sales revisions are due mainly to ``economic
softness and unfavorable exchange rates'' in Latin America and
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While its razors and batters traditionally sell well in those
areas, chairman and chief executive Michael C. Hawley said that
``Recently it has been difficult to achieve this success when
those...economies take major downturns.'' Excluding exchange-rate
issues, sales grew 3 percent during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Eric Kraus said Gillette was still able to support its
profit margins by cutting production costs at factories in South
Boston and in Berlin, Germany where it makes its Mach 3 razor.
</P>
<P>
   Kraus said Gillette also benefitted from growing sales of that
razor and of its Duracell batteries, products that carry higher
profit margins than do its lines of stationary and Braun electric
shavers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by Zacks had expected Gillette would earn
$1.26 for the year ended Dec. 31. Kruas said the company was no
longer comfortable with those forecasts and said it expected to
offer more complete guidance when it releases its full results next
month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Chris Reidy contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
