<HEADER>
A9332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-PRAYER-NYT     09-28 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRAYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT PRAYER BREAKFAST, CLINTON TELLS OF A YEAR OF SPIRITUAL RECOVERY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seven months after a divided Senate found him not
guilty of impeachable offenses, President Clinton said Tuesday that
he continues to squeeze regular spiritual counseling into his
official schedule to recover from what he called ``one of the most
difficult years in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing somewhat reluctant to bring up the ghosts of the past,
the president told religious leaders at the annual White House
prayer breakfast that he was moved by the forgiveness shown to him
by members of his family and staff, the American people and God. A
year ago, with the Monica Lewinsky scandal in full furor, he used
the same forum for a tearful admission that he had sinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to say only this about that: I have been
profoundly moved, as few people have, by the pure power of grace,
unmerited forgiveness through grace,'' Clinton said. ``Most of all
to my wife and daughter, but to the people I work with, to the
legions of American people and to the God in whom I believe, and I
am very grateful to all of you who have had any role in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton attended the breakfast but steered clear
of any mention of her husband's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   At the breakfast, held in the state dining room, the president
thanked the three spiritual counselors who have regularly met with
him since last fall: the Rev. J. Philip Wogaman, pastor of the
Foundry United Methodist Church in Washington; the Rev. Gordon
MacDonald of the Grace Chapel in Lexington, Mass.; and the Rev.
Tony Campolo of St. Davids, Pa., who runs ministries for the urban
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton decided to bring up the matter Tuesday because he was
speaking to the very group of religious leaders he had addressed so
personally last September, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been strange not to bring it up,'' explained a
White House official who talked to the president about his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   While portraying the counseling as a difficult process, Clinton
seemed a long way from the dark days of last fall when his
presidency hung in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the prayer breakfast last year, the House of
Representatives made public the Starr report detailing the
president's affair. ``I don't think there is a fancy way to say
that I have sinned,'' Clinton said then as details of the report
poured out on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will instruct my lawyers to mount a vigorous defense, using
all available appropriate arguments,'' the president had said,
foreshadowing the impeachment fight that ended Feb. 12 with
acquittal in the Senate. ``But legal language must not obscure the
fact that I have done wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's discussion of his spiritual journey was the latest
twist in a case that has from the outset blended the personal with
the political.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the breakfast, Wogaman said the president
has fit the counseling sessions in between official engagements,
taking an occasional break from the nation's business to focus on
himself. Without revealing details, Wogaman said Clinton has
completed readings and engaged in detailed, personal conversations.
</P>
<P>
   His pastoral advisers have said previously that they would study
Scripture with him and advise him to seek psychological counseling
or other treatment if they determined he needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the counseling was interesting and rewarding but
``not always comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you will pray for us'' as the process continues, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal comments drew qualified praise from some of
the lawmakers who had sought his ouster on charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Christian, I always try to remember what the Bible tells
me,'' said Rep. James E. Rogan, a Republican from California and
member of the House Judiciary Committee. ``It tells me to worry
about the demon in my own eye.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
