<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-SHELTERS29-COX     09-28 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-SHELTERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shelters phase down as more people leave
 &HT;    By Eunice Moscoso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Pitt County emergency shelters continued to
decompress Tuesday as more residents moved back into previously
flooded homes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the American Red Cross planned to close the shelter
at Stokes Elementary School on Tuesday or today, said Lou Kavanau,
a Red Cross volunteer at the county's Emergency Operation Center.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 people were living at the shelter and will be moved
to other locations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter at Farmville Middle School is also getting less
crowded, with 23 people as of Tuesday, but no decision has been
made to close it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers at Pitt County's seven shelters have dropped from more
than 3,000 at the peak of the crisis to about 700.
</P>
<P>
   At Bethel Elementary, the number of shelter residents dropped
from 373 late last week to 141 Tuesday. Shelters at Ayden Middle
School and Ayden-Grifton High School are housing about 140 people
each and Ayden Elementary still has 117.
</P>
<P>
   At Wellcome Middle School, where 63 people remained living in
the gymnasium, Paola Andrades sat on a mattress with her
two-year-old daughter Kenya _ both left homeless by the wrath of
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``She keeps asking me why we don't go home. I don't know how to
tell her that our home is gone,'' Andrades said, in Spanish, as her
daughter played with a few other children also living in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Andrades and her husband lived in a trailer that completely
flooded and has been condemned, she said. They had no insurance.
``I'm not sure what to do. I guess we just have to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   But Andrades and her family can't wait there for too long. Next
week, cots and mattresses might be replaced by basketballs and jump
ropes as most local schools plan to reopen for classes.
</P>
<P>
   Kavanau said the Red Cross is working with state officials to
find new locations for temporary shelters before the schools open.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's in the planning stage right now. There will be an
alternative,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first of hundreds of campers state officials requested to
serve as temporary homes arrived at a site on County Home Road
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   County and city officials urged displaced residents to apply for
federal assistance, which could include temporary housing. Those
seeking aid should call the Federal Emergency Management Agency's
toll-free number _ (800) 462-9029 or (800) 462-7585 for the hearing
and speech impaired. FEMA has also opened a disaster recovery
center for those who want more information about the various aid
programs. It is not necessary to visit the center to get federal
help.
</P>
<P>
   Through the federal aid programs, some hurricane victims could
qualify for rental assistance or for temporary housing in hotels,
but that could prove difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a hotel room available in Greenville,'' said John
Gasper, a Red Cross volunteer and coordinator for the Pitt County
Red Cross Family Service Center.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
