<HEADER>
A9341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ATLANTIC-SOLD-BOS &LR;      09-28 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTIC-SOLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO JOBS AT RISK, ATLANTIC'S NEW OWNER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The changing of the guard at The Atlantic Monthly
magazine became official when new owner David Bradley visited the
troops Tuesday. But his message to staffers, clearly shaken by the
suddenness of the sale, was a very soothing one: Stay the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the instant I arrived, people were welling up with
tears,'' said Bradley, 46, recounting the emotional staff meeting
in which he tried to calm frayed nerves. ``The things that animate
them at the center also animate me. The North Star I'd like to set
for this group is the one they've had for 140 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all tremendously reassured. He's clearly a
thoughtful, serious, decent human being,'' said senior editor Jack
Beatty. ``He seemed to understand what we were feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Washington-based National Journal Group of
government-oriented publications, Bradley bought the Atlantic from
developer and media magnate Mort Zuckerman. The hastily announced
deal, which became public on Monday, caught many staffers by
surprise and prompted feverish speculation regarding Bradley's
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The early word from Bradley and new Atlantic editor Michael
Kelly, however, is that there are no plans to move the magazine
from Boston, no plans to change the editorial philosophy, and no
plans for a major staffing overhaul, other than the decision to
replace editor William Whitworth with Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them is at risk of their jobs,'' said Bradley. ``We're
asking them all to stay on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great magazine. I approach it first from a real sense
of awe,'' added Kelly, who was also headed for Boston Tuesday.
``The identity of The Atlantic Monthly is deeply rooted, and I am
not looking to come in there and uproot that identity or subvert
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic _ with its long essays, global range, and esoteric
commentary _ has carved out a reputation as a kind of antidote to
today's sound-bite-driven media culture. With a circulation of
about 460,000, it has a loyal following as well as critics who
believe it is too hidebound and too detached from the events of the
day. Widely believed to be losing money, it has benefited from
Zuckerman's commitment to invest in the product.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice he might have for the new owner, former
Atlantic editor Robert Manning said: ``I got a little bit more to
the cutting edge, a little closer to the currents. I'm sure he's
got plans to get more vigorous.''
</P>
<P>
   One conceivable scenario would be for Kelly, 42, to inject more
politics and policy into the Atlantic mix. Kelly, who has edited
the National Journal for about a year, is also a syndicated
columnist and vocal Bill Clinton critic. He had a brief stint as
editor of The New Republic, but he was dismissed by owner Martin
Peretz, who claimed Kelly had taken the magazine too far to the
right.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, however, Kelly was adamant that he
would not ``take this magazine and turn it into a different
creation, a creature of the Beltway or an ideological magazine or a
magazine devoted to politics. . . . This is primarily a magazine of
ideas and literary journalism. . . . Its standards are not about
buzz, its standards are about excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no thoughts here of doing anything radical with the
staff, the contributing writers, or the editorial operation,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The one major change announced thus far is the decision to
replace the 62-year-old Whitworth, who came to the Atlantic when
Zuckerman purchased it in 1980. ``We're not reassured that Bill, of
all people, is leaving,'' said Beatty. ``That's the hard part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sure (Bradley) would bring in his own guy,'' said
Whitworth. But ``I was surprised at how quickly the decision was
made.'' At dinner with Bradley on Monday night, Whitworth asked
whether that decison reflected the new owner's dissatisfaction with
the Atlantic. Bradley responded that it wasn't a matter of fixing
the magazine, but that he and Kelly had dreamed of running a
general interest magazine together.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he will accept Zuckerman's offer of a new position
elsewhere in his media empire, Whitworth said that ``my first
reaction to him is that I would rather have a very modest
retirement than a fancy new job.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the positive feeling engendered by Bradley's debut in
Boston Tuesday, few observers believe that the new regime is
indefinitely and irrevocably committed to preserving the status
quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said all the right things . . . about respect for the
traditions of the magazine,'' noted Whitworth. ``I think we're all
just taking them at their word. Obviously, things change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
