<SLUG> BC-BASEMENT-CLSOINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILENE'S BASEMENT TO SHUT DOWN 17 STORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Filene's Basement Corp., the Wellesley retail chain
that filed for bankruptcy protection last month after some vendors
stopped shipping it merchandise, said Tuesday it plans to close 17
underperforming stores over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the closings could ``impact'' the jobs of 400
full-time and 600 part-time employees who work at those stores. The
Filene's Basement chain has 3,800 employees.
</P>
<P>
   If the closings are approved by the US Bankruptcy Court in
Boston, Filene's Basement could end the year with 40 stores, 15
fewer than when it filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in
late August.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement's famous flagship store in Boston's Downtown
Crossing is not affected by the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Because most store closings are in suburban locations, it seems
Filene's Basement wants to retrench its namesake stores in urban
markets and use its new Aisle 3 chain to woo suburbanites.
</P>
<P>
   Closing underperforming stores is pretty much standard procedure
for a retailer in Chapter 11, a sort of amputation of gangrenous
extremities designed to save the life of the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement, which has been hurt by fierce competition and
changes in consumer shopping habits, had earlier announced plans to
close two other stores, neither in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 19 stores we have identified for closing represent
approximately 20 percent of our total sales revenue and a
disproportionate level of losses for the company,'' said chairman
and chief executive Sam Gerson in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Filene's Basement lost $9.5 million on sales of
$588.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remaining core of Basement stores meets the company's
strategic objectives in terms of merchandising, market position,
and revenue and profitability potential,'' Gerson said.
</P>
<P>
   The closings suggest that Filene's Basement appeals largely to
an urban customer who's still willing to invest some time in
hunting for bargains on designer clothes. Filene's Basement may
have less appeal for busy suburbanites who want stores they can get
in and out of as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to attract suburban customers, the company has been
testing a new store concept called Aisle 3, a warehouse store that
opens for business only on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the company operates four Aisle 3 stores, with plans
to soon open four more in the suburbs of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   By Dec. 31, the company expects to have 32 Filene's Basement
stores in largely urban markets and eight Aisle 3 stores in
suburban locations, company spokeswoman Carreen Winters said.
</P>
<P>
   After filing for bankruptcy protection, some retailers opt to
close unprofitable stores in phases, but Filene's Basement decided
to close its underperforming stores all at once, Winters suggested.
There are no plans at this time to close additional stores, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company, the proposed store closings have the
support of the company's unsecured creditors. As a general rule,
bankruptcy courts approve a retailer's store closing plan that has
the support of most creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever possible, full-time employees affected by store
closings will be offered transfers to other stores, Filene's
Basement said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who are not transferred will be offered severance
packages and outplacement assistance, the company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2003EDT &QL; 
