<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mrs. Gore visits flooded churches
 &HT;    (EDS: Corrects to Telegram in tagline.)
 &HT;    By Gene Metrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Tipper Gore came to Rocky Mount Tuesday to
help kick off a clean-up campaign for flood-damaged churches.
</P>
<P>
   Gore visited with members of the Metropolitan Baptist Church,
who were being assisted in their clean-up work by volunteers from
the Church of the Good Shepherd in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me you have it all together here,'' the wife of
Vice President Al Gore said. ``The thing that makes life worth
living is not only the celebration of good times, but also being
there for each other in times of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort is part of the N.C. Department of Crime Control and
Public Safety's ``Church2Church'' clean-up program, which matches
churches from undamaged parts of the state with those in flooded
areas to help restore and rebuild their damaged houses of worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government is a tool that must be used to the utmost where it
can to help people in their time of need,'' Gore said. ``But we all
know that government can not ever hope to replace the love and
embrace of someone helping to clean out your sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four feet of water had cascaded into the church, tossing
the sanctuary lectern, organ, pews and a piano through the
building. The Rev. Raymond Privott, pastor of the church, estimated
the damages at $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came in here Saturday, the pews had been ripped
up from the force of the water,'' he said. ``But lying on top of
the pulpit, still dry and open, was the Bible that had sat there
for 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the midst of all the turmoil and running water, it was a
sight to see - it was amazing, a true miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert Sawyer, pastor of the Church of the Good
Shepherd, said members of his congregation had also pledged to
donate $10,000 to help the clean-up and restoration efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also pledged to work for increased assistance in providing
counseling for flood victims, saying the mental trauma suffered by
flood victims would continue to be suffered long after physical
damages have been repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Privott said the ``Church2Church'' assistance was ``one of the
warmest things to come out of this disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts into practice that what we have been teaching in our
church - that there is good in man,'' he said. ``It means new life
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also visited families living in FEMA trailers at a
relocation site in Fountain Industrial Park.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Metrick writes for The Rocky Mount Telegram, Rocky Mount,
N.C.
</P>
