</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GINSBURG-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE GINSBURG'S CANCER WAS DISCOVERED AT EARLY STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The colon cancer diagnosed in Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg has apparently not spread, and was discovered at an early
stage by accident because the justice suffered symptoms from an
unrelated abdominal infection, the Supreme Court announced on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-year-old justice went home from Washington Hospital
Center on Tuesday, 11 days after surgeons removed her sigmoid
colon, a two-foot length of bowel that comprises the lower third of
the large intestine. Doctors have classified her cancer as being in
the second of four stages; about 75 percent of Stage Two colon
cancer patients are cured, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The justice is very lucky to have had this picked up
incidentally,'' said Dr. Harmon Eyre, chief medical officer for the
American Cancer Society in Atlanta. ``If it had been left alone it
would have advanced to another stage.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, the court's public information officer,
Kathleen Arberg, said a small tumor, measuring about two by three
centimeters, had invaded the justice's colon and entered the outer
muscle but did not penetrate through it. Subsequent tests showed no
evidence that the disease had spread to the lymph nodes or any
other organ.
</P>
<P>
   The tests results are a good sign, Eyre said, but they are no
guarantee. In some patients, ``there can be microscopic spread''
that does not turn up in early biopsies.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg became ill this summer while teaching in a law school
program on the Greek Island of Crete. Doctors at first thought she
had acute diverticulitis, a disorder of the large intestine, but
later diagnosed colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it turns out, the diverticulitis diagnosis may have been
correct after all; according to Ms. Arberg's statement, Dr. Lee
Smith, the surgeon at Washington Hospital Center who performed the
operation on Sept. 17 on Ginsburg, also discovered a perforation
higher in her bowel. The perforation, which was not malignant,
caused her abdominal infection.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her hospitalization, Ginsburg has been participating in
the court's recent work, although whether she has been involved by
telephone, written memo or in some other way was unclear. The court
on Tuesday issued a list of nine cases that it intends to hear this
term; there was no announcement that Ginsberg was absent, as is
customary when justices do not take part in deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Eyre said most patients in Ginsburg's condition need at least a
month to six weeks to recuperate from surgery, possibly longer in
her case if there are complications from the perforated bowel. She
should heal completely, he said, without any need for a colostomy,
and may not need any chemotherapy or radiation. Doctors should make
that determination after evaluating samples of her cancerous
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   The justice should be monitored closely from now on for any
evidence of a recurrence. That typically includes an annual
colonoscopy, in which doctors use a lighted scope to examine the
length of the colon, as well as periodic blood tests.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cancer of the colon and rectum is the second leading cause of
cancer deaths in the United States, after lung cancer. It is also
one of the most curable of cancers, but only if it is found in the
early stages. Although many women think of colorectal cancer as a
man's disease, that is not the case. Ginsburg is among 67,000 women
_ 4,600 more women than men _ who will have the disease diagnosed
in the United States this year, according to the American Cancer
Society.
</P>
<P>
   Because colon cancer develops slowly and has a long precancerous
stage, it is easily prevented. A tumor the size of Ginsburg's, for
instance, might take about two to three years to develop, Eyre
said, and might take three to five years before causing any
symptoms. But by that time, the disease would be more advanced, and
much more difficult to treat. The cancer society recommends regular
colon cancer screening for women and men, 50 and older.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
