u a BC-FLOODS-TOBACCO-COX     09-28 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco industry picking up pieces after flood
 &HT;    By Tom Murphy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ The reopening of the Rocky Mount Tobacco
Market on a rainy Tuesday was one sign of recovery from Hurricane
Floyd's devastation.
</P>
<P>
   A record high of $1.88 a pound was paid by buyers at Raynor and
Peoples warehouses. Tuesday was the first sales day for the local
market since Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were selling mostly leaf tobacco,'' said R.J. Raynor, owner
of Raynor Warehouse. ``The tobacco we sold today was cured before
the hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimate agricultural losses due to Floyd will
exceed $1 billion. The government is talking about loans. But
farmers say they can't pay back what they've got.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of agricultural destruction overall,'' Raynor
said. ``A lot of tobacco still in the fields was blown off the
stalk. Damage also was heavy to peanut, cotton and sweet potato
crops. Farmers have been through a devastating two weeks. We don't
need this additional rainfall. We need to dry out.''
</P>
<P>
   Raynor Warehouse sold 330,571 pounds of tobacco for $603,125.63
for an average of $182.45 per hundredweight. Stabilization received
62,701 pounds - 19 percent of the day's offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd and flood damage has extended the sales season, Raynor
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a week of sales because of the hurricane,'' he said.
``All the markets were closed from Florida to Virginia. We have
about four more weeks left in this marketing season.''
</P>
<P>
   Bart Wood, floor manager at Peoples Warehouse,, said the
majority of tobacco sold at his warehouse Tuesday came from the
packhouse or had been on the warehouse flood prior to Floyd's
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the tobacco sold had been here since Sept. 13,'' he
said. ``It was good quality tobacco. As a whole, farmers were
pretty well pleased with what happened today. They were glad no
more went to Stabilization than did (16,411 pounds or 8.6 percent
of the day's offerings). It had been upwards of 28 to 30 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said the remainder of a number of tobacco crops in the
Battleboro, Scotland Neck and Pinetops area drowned because of
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples Warehouse sold 190,538 pounds of tobacco for $350,527.58
for an average of $183.97 per hundred pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Murphy writes for The Rocky Mount Telegram, Rocky Mount,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
