<SLUG> BC-MA-REGISTRY-AUDIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT REVEALS NEED FOR `OVERHAUL' AT REGISTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Already reeling from a barrage of criticism by citizens
and state lawmakers, the Registry of Motor Vehicles came under
additional fire Tuesday as State Auditor Joseph DeNucci released a
stinging interim audit and called for ``a complete overhaul'' of
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In a soup-to-nuts critique of Registry operations, DeNucci said
Registry customers sometimes wait more than three hours for
service, Registry employees have awarded themselves pay raises and
promotions with little or no oversight, and Registry personnel have
failed to monitor sales tax collections by the state's auto
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Registry's failure to properly monitor sales tax
collections is troubling, and consumers have a right to be
frustrated by the poor service they have received,'' DeNucci said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, officials working for DeNucci said the audit,
underway for the last year, is continuing and is likely to produce
additional criticism of the Registry's use of consultants,
renovations of registry facilities and purchases of goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, newly named Registrar Daniel A. Grabauskas said he met
with DeNucci last week to discuss the audit and plans to use it as
a blueprint for revamping the agency. ``I'm all about change, and
if there's something that needs changing, I'm the agent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Grabauskas, on the job only six days, also said he hasn't
had time to determine whether solving the agency's problems will
require additional staff or a larger budget.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci, reponding to the audit, refused to
acknowledge that Registry operations have deteriorated during
nearly a decade of Republican management, citing the elimination of
some Registry fees and the opening of ``express offices'' on
Saturdays as improvements.
</P>
<P>
   But DeNucci said poor management is at the root of problems
besetting the agency. For instance, after noting that Registry
customers sometimes wait more than three hours, DeNucci said top
Registry officials lack ``a comprehensive recognition of the
staffing needs and managerial changes necessary to correct problems
that result in lengthly and unneccesary delays to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor management and a lack of oversight were also cited in the
cases of seven Registry employees who received unauthorized pay
raises or promotions, or were hired in violation of union
agreements. The audit places the cost of ``personnel
irregularities'' made during spot checks at $78,086.
</P>
<P>
   And the poor management refrain continued in the audit's finding
that Registry officials are failing to monitor state sales tax
collections by auto dealers. In some cases, the audit said, the
state is losing money. In others, customers are overcharged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
