u a BC-MUSEUM-CLASH-BOS &LR;      09-28 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-CLASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO HEAR BROOKLYN MUSEUM CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The clash between Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and the
Brooklyn Museum of Art is headed to federal court in what could be
a landmark First Amendment case.
</P>
<P>
   For a week now, the mayor has threatened to cut off city funding
to the museum if it proceeds with a show called ``Sensation,''
slated to start Saturday, which includes art works that he
considers ``disgusting'' and ``anti-Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has voiced particular outrage over a painting of the
Virgin Mary surrounded by clumps of elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   Talks to explore a compromise broke down Tuesday. At that point,
the museum's board voted to go ahead with the show and filed a
lawsuit, asking a federal judge to block the city from taking any
action against the museum.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the city is filing its own lawsuit, charging the
Brooklyn Museum with violating its lease and calling for the
eviction of the museum's director and board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The board's chairman, investment banker Robert S. Rubin, put the
suit in its loftiest context, saying it was being filed not just
for the Brooklyn Museum but ``in the interest of all public
institutions _ museums, universities, and libraries _ that are
dedicated to the free exchange of ideas and information.''
</P>
<P>
   The board's vote was unanimous, except for one dissent _ by
deputy mayor Joseph Lhota, who attended the meeting on Giuliani's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall's top lawyer, Michael Hess, who also attended the
meeting, said afterward, ``Because this board insisted on defying
everybody, we will be cutting off funding'' beginning Friday, when
the next monthly subsidy check is scheduled to go out.
</P>
<P>
   As with many other cultural institutions, the city owns the
Brooklyn Museum's building and pays $7 million a year _ about
one-third of its operating budget _ for heat, electricity, security
guards, and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Hess repeated a point that Giuliani has made recently: ``There
is nothing in the constitution that says taxpayers should pay for
an exhibition like this.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Floyd Abrams, the prominent First Amendment lawyer who
is representing the museum in this suit, countered, ``There's no
obligation for the city to fund the arts at all,'' but cited
several court cases ruling that once a city government goes down
that road, the First Amendment prevents it from stopping the money
for reasons having to do with the art's content.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, before Abrams was hired by the museum, he said
in an interview that the dispute ``could be a landmark case'' if it
went to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides had also argued in the past few days that the
museum _ by barring children under 17 from attending the show
without being accompanied by an adult _ was violating its lease
with the city. The lease, signed over 100 years ago, requires the
museum to open its exhibits to schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's board maneuvered around this potential legal
obstacle Tuesday by voting simply to rescind the restriction.
Warning signs will be posted throughout the museum, but children
will not be forbidden to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breach of lease is no longer a live issue,'' Abrams noted.
``There should be no further talk from the mayor's camp about
leases. This is now purely a First Amendment issue.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in a phone interview, Lhota said the lease also
prohibits the museum from charging admission for an exhibit without
the mayor's permission. ``They're charging admission for this
exhibit, the mayor has not given his permission, so we will take
them to court for violating their lease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Rubin had met with City Hall officials to discuss
possible compromises. In one scenario, the museum would remove the
Virgin Mary painting and move a few other offending works to
another area _ in exchange for which the city would cut only a
portion of its subsidy and only for the three months that the show
is scheduled to run.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, when told of this new argument, sighed and said, ``This
is just another frivolous arguement designed to avoid the
inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   However, museum officials denied any such compromise had been
offered or approved. By the time of the formal board meeting
Tuesday, the deal _ if there had ever been one _ was taken off the
table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
