<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES FALL SHARPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prices of Treasury securities fell sharply
Tuesday, raising the yield on the long bond to its highest level in
several days and representing the sharpest one-day rise in over two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted a variety of factors contributing to the bearish
tone and selloff, including selling by funds and dealers, supply,
technical factors and a surge in the prices of gold and other
commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Even weakness in the Dow Jones industrial stock average, which
was down more than 200 points at one point in the day, was unable
to provide much sustained support. Traders also suggested that the
supply of new debt had a hand in downward price pressures. Buying
was limited as dealers set up hedges in advance of Fannie Mae's
$5.3 billion bond sale.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to attracting investors away from Treasury
securities, government bonds can also fall during large debt sales
because dealers often sell their most liquid assets, like
Treasuries, as a hedge against losses should the market take a
downturn before the deal is completed and the debt is distributed
to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury fell a full point Tuesday, to 100 19/32,
while its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to
6.08 percent, from 6.01 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The two-part issue from Fannie Mae, the nation's largest buyer
of home loans, drew enough demand so that Fannie Mae was able to
increase its planned sale by more than 30 percent. The five-year
notes were priced to yield about 59 basis points more than a
Treasury security with a similar maturity and the 30-year bond was
priced to yield more than 81 basis points over the government bond.
A basis point is a hundredth of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Antonellis, market strategist for Briefing.com in
Burlingame, Calif., said Tuesday's Treasury market was driven by
factors that included the surge in gold prices, which affected the
longer maturities, as well as rumors of hedge-fund selling on the
long end of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Other metals, in addition to gold, also climbed, stoking
investor fears that rising prices would also increase inflation and
force the Fed into action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was decent bid to the front end, or shorter maturities
in the market due to the weakness in stocks, as investors put a
premium on shorter issues,'' Antonellis said. ``But the flight to
quality today has not been enough to keep the bond market in
positive territory because the market has been burned on so many
occasions this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury plans to sell $15 billion of new two-year notes
Tuesday. In when-issued trading late Tuesday, the notes were
offered at a price to yield 5.61 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9366 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-SLOWCOOKER-RECIPES-LA     09-28 3039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOWCOOKER-RECIPES-LAADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Runs with SLOW-COOKING)  
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARTICHOKE CHICKEN AND OLIVES
</P>
<P>
   Flavors of artichokes, olives and thyme lend Mediterranean
accent to this dish. &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds skinless, boneless chicken breast halves AND/OR
thighs &QL; 
2 cups sliced fresh mushrooms &QL; 
1 can (14 1/2 ounces) diced tomatoes &QL; 
1 package (8 OR 9 ounces) frozen artichoke hearts &QL; 
1 cup chicken broth &QL; 
1 medium onion, chopped &QL; 
1/2 cup sliced pitted ripe olives OR 1/4 cup drained capers &QL; 
1/4 cup dry white wine OR chicken broth &QL; 
3 tablespoons quick-cooking tapioca &QL; 
2 to 3 teaspoons curry powder &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon dried thyme, crushed &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon pepper &QL; 
4 cups hot cooked couscous
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chicken; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a 3 1/2- OR 4-quart crockery cooker, combine mushrooms,
undrained tomatoes, frozen artichoke hearts, chicken broth, onion,
olives and wine. Stir in tapioca, curry powder, thyme, salt and
pepper. Add chicken; spoon some of tomato mixture over chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Cover; cook on low-heat setting 7 to 8 hours or high-heat
setting 3 1/2 to 4 hours. Serve with hot cooked couscous. Makes 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Better Homes and Gardens New Flavors From Your Crockery
Cooker.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SANCOCHO PORK STEW
</P>
<P>
   This healthy stew, with its origin attributed to Panama, is
mildly spiced with chili powder and chiles. The yams or sweet
potatoes lend a complementary sweetness. &QL; 
3 medium yams OR sweet potatoes, peeled and cut into 2-inch pieces &QL; 
1 large green bell pepper, cut into strips &QL; 
1 cup frozen whole kernel corn &QL; 
1 medium onion, sliced and separated into rings &QL; 
3 cloves garlic, minced &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds boneless pork shoulder, cut into 3/4-inch cubes &QL; 
1 teaspoon chili powder &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon ground coriander &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
2 cups water &QL; 
1 can (10 ounces) chopped tomatoes with green chiles &QL; 
1 package (9 ounces) frozen cut green beans
</P>
<P>
   In a 3 1/2-, 4- OR 5-quart crockery cooker, place yams, bell
pepper, corn, onion and garlic. Add pork, chili powder, coriander
and salt. Pour water and undrained tomatoes over all.
</P>
<P>
   Cover; cook on low-heat setting 7 to 8 hours or high-heat
setting 3 1/2 to 4 hours, adding frozen green beans last 15 minutes
of cooking time. Makes 6 to 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   From ``Better Homes and Gardens New Flavors From Your Crockery
Cooker.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THAI CHICKEN SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Lemon grass is a popular herb used in Thai cooking. It resembles
a very large green onion. Use only the fibrous white bulb, which
contains a lemon fragrance and flower. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 pound skinless, boneless chicken breast OR thighs, rinsed and cut
into 3/4-inch pieces &QL; 
4 cups chicken broth &QL; 
2 cups diagonally sliced carrots &QL; 
1 large onion, chopped &QL; 
2 tablespoons grated ginger root &QL; 
3 cloves garlic, minced &QL; 
2 stalks lemon grass, cut into 1-inch pieces OR 1 teaspoon finely
shredded lemon peel &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon crushed red pepper &QL; 
1 can (15 ounces) unsweetened coconut milk &QL; 
1 medium red, yellow AND/OR green bell pepper, cut into 1/2-inch
pieces &QL; 
2 cans (4 ounces EACH) straw OR button mushrooms, drained &QL; 
1/4 cup snipped cilantro &QL; 
1/3 cup chopped roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   In a 3 1/2-, 4- OR 5-quart crockery cooker, combine chicken,
broth, carrots, onion, ginger root, garlic, lemon grass and crushed
red pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cover; cook on low-heat setting 6 to 7 hours or high-heat
setting 3 to 3 1/2 hours. If necessary, skim off fat. Stir coconut
milk, bell pepper, mushrooms and cilantro into chicken mixture.
Cover; let stand 5 to 10 minutes. Remove and discard lemon grass.
Ladle soup into bowls. Sprinkle peanuts over each serving. Makes 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Better Homes and Gardens New Flavors From Your Crockery
Cooker.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MULLED CRANBERRY CIDER
</P>
<P>
   This is a great starter for a dinner, a brunch or a simple
evening of appetizers and good cheer. &QL; 
1 small orange &QL; 
8 cups cranberry-raspberry drink &QL; 
1/4 cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
6 inches stick cinnamon &QL; 
3 star anise &QL; 
1 teaspoon whole cloves &QL; 
Orange peel strips (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Remove orange portion of orange peel using a vegetable peeler.
Cut peel into strips. Squeeze juice from orange; discard seeds and
pulp.
</P>
<P>
   In a 3 1/2-, 4- OR 5-quart crockery cooker, combine orange
juice, cranberry-raspberry drink and brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   For a spice bag, place orange peel, cinnamon, star anise and
whole cloves on a double-thick, 8-inch square of 100 percent cotton
cheesecloth. Bring corners of cheesecloth together and tie with a
clean cotton string. Add to cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Cover; cook on low-heat setting 5 to 6 hours or high-heat
setting 2 1/2 to 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, remove spice bag and discard. Ladle cider into cups.
If desired, garnish with additional orange peel strips. Makes 10
(6-ounce) servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Better Homes and Gardens New Flavors From Your Crockery
Cooker.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARAMEL-APPLE NACHOS
</P>
<P>
   Nachos get a sugar-and-spice twist. The apple mixture is served
with cinnamon-spiced tortilla crisps. Top it all off with vanilla
yogurt and toasted pecans _ yum. &QL; 
2/3 cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
1/4 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon quick-cooking tapioca &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
1 1/2 cups apple juice OR apple cider &QL; 
2 pounds cooking apples, peeled, cored and cut into 1/2-inch-thick
slices (6 cups) &QL; 
1 tablespoon margarine OR butter, cut up &QL; 
1 carton (8 ounces) vanilla yogurt &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped, toasted pecans &QL; 
1 recipe Cinnamon Tortilla Crisp
</P>
<P>
   In a 3 1/2- or 4-quart crockery cooker, stir together brown
sugar, granulated sugar, tapioca and cinnamon. Stir in apple juice.
Add apple slices and margarine; stir to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Cover; cook on low-heat setting 6 to 7 hours or high-heat
setting 3 to 3 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, divide apples and syrup among 8 dessert dishes. Top
each serving with vanilla yogurt and pecans. Serve with Cinnamon
Tortilla Crisps. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CINNAMON TORTILLA CRISPS: In a bowl, combine 4 teaspoons
granulated sugar and 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon. Cut 2 (7- to
8-inch) flour tortillas into 8 wedges each. (Or, cut 3 (6-inch)
corn tortillas into 6 wedges each.) Lightly spray wedges with
nonstick vegetable oil coating. Place wedges in a single layer on
an ungreased baking sheet. Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about
12 minutes or until crisp. (Or, bake corn tortillas about 8
minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   From ``Better Homes and Gardens New Flavors From Your Crockery
Cooker.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SY BEEF CHILI
</P>
<P>
   This is a cinch to prepare with a little assistance from canned
beans, tomatoes ad green chiles. Use it as a base for tostada
salads or as a filling for tacos or burritos. &QL; 
1 pound boneless beef round steak, trimmed of all fat and cut into
1/2-inch cubes &QL; 
1 1/2 tablespoons ground cumin &QL; 
2 tablespoons chili powder &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon seasoned salt &QL; 
3 garlic cloves, crushed through a press &QL; 
1 can (7 ounces) diced green chiles &QL; 
1 medium onion, chopped &QL; 
1 can (30 ounces) chili beans, undrained &QL; 
2 cans (15 ounces EACH) black beans, rinsed and drained &QL; 
1 can (14 1/2 ounces) diced peeled tomatoes, undrained &QL; 
1 can (12 ounces) OR 2 cans (6 ounces EACH) tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   In a 4- or 5-quart electric slow cooker, mix together beef,
cumin, chili powder, seasoned salt, garlic, chiles and onion. Add
undrained chili beans, drained black beans, undrained tomatoes and
tomato paste. Mix gently to avoid mashing beans.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook on low-heat setting about 5 hours or until beef
is tender. Makes 5 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Best Slow Cooker Cookbook Ever'' by Natalie Haughton,
Harper Collins. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PARTY BEAN DIP
</P>
<P>
   This is a great choice when you're expecting a crowd. Use any
leftovers to make the base of a tostada salad _ pile on top of a
few chips and top with shredded lettuce and cheese, chopped
tomatoes, avocado, green onions and salsa. &QL; 
1 pound lean ground beef &QL; 
1 large onion, chopped &QL; 
2 cans (15 ounces EACH) pinto beans, rinsed and drained &QL; 
1 cup ketchup &QL; 
1 tablespoon chili powder &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons ground cumin &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon garlic powder &QL; 
Pinch cayenne pepper OR more to taste &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped pimiento-stuffed green olives OR 1 can (2 1/4
ounces) sliced black olives, drained &QL; 
1 1/2 cups shredded Cheddar cheese &QL; 
Tortilla chips and fresh cut-up vegetables for serving
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, on top of stove, cook beef with onion over
medium-high heat, stirring until browned, 6 to 8 minutes. Drain off
fat.
</P>
<P>
   Turn into a 3 1/2-quart electric slow cooker. Add beans, mashing
up to 1/2 of them with a fork. Stir in ketchup, chili powder,
cumin, garlic powder, cayenne and olives until well mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook on high-heat setting 1 1/2 hours or on low-heat
setting 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in 1 cup cheese, mixing well. Top with remaining 1/2 cup
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately with tortilla chips and fresh vegetables.
Refrigerate any leftovers. Makes 4 1/2 to 5 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Best Slow Cooker Cookbook Ever'' by Natalie Haughton,
Harper Collins. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAUCY APRICOT-GLAZED CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   This is a slow-cooker rendition of the ever-popular chicken
glazed with a mixture of apricot preserves, Russian dressing and
dry onion soup mix that's usually baked in the oven. Cooked in the
slow cooker, you end up with a lot of delicious, apricot-colored
sauce to gussy up the chicken breasts. Serve over wild rice or
white rice; or try basmati or jasmine rice, cooked on top of the
stove. If you have leftover chicken and sauce, freeze and use
within two months. &QL; 
1 cup good-quality chunky apricot preserves &QL; 
3/4 cup bottled Russian dressing &QL; 
1 envelope (1.15 ounces) dry onion soup mix &QL; 
12 skinless, boneless chicken breast halves, trimmed of fat (about
3 1/2 to 4 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, mix together apricot preserves, dressing and
dry soup mix until well blended. Arrange 3 chicken breast halves in
bottom of a 3 1/2-quart electric slow cooker. Spoon 1/4 of apricot
mixture on top. Add 3 more layers of chicken with apricot mixture
in between and on top.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook on high-heat setting 1 hour. Reduce heat setting
to low and continue cooking, covered, 2 1/2 to 3 hours or until
chicken is tender and white throughout; do not overcook or chicken
will toughen. Serve sauce over chicken. Makes 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Best Slow Cooker Cookbook Ever'' by Natalie Haughton,
Harper Collins. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EASY HAM AND POTATO HASH
</P>
<P>
   Whether you serve it with scrambled eggs and English muffins for
brunch or with whole-grain bread and tossed salad for supper, this
is a delicious, no-fuss way to use leftover ham. Note: If you
forget to take the potatoes out of the freezer, microwave on high
power 4 minutes, until barely thawed. &QL; 
1 package (32 ounces) frozen hash brown potatoes, partially thawed &QL; 
3/4 cup chopped green bell pepper &QL; 
3/4 cup chopped red bell pepper &QL; 
3 cups chopped cooked ham &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1 1/2 cups milk &QL; 
2 1/2 tablespoons Dijon mustard &QL; 
1 1/2 cups chopped green onions &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon garlic powder &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon garlic pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a 4-quart electric slow cooker, combine hash brown potatoes
with red and green bell peppers and ham. Stir to mix well.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1-quart glass measure, blend cream cheese and milk. Heat in
microwave oven on high power 1 to 1 1/2 minutes or until smooth
when whisked together. Stir in mustard, 1 cup green onions, garlic
powder and pepper until blended. Pour cream cheese mixture evenly
over potatoes and ham; do not mix.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook on low-heat setting 5 to 6 hours or until
potatoes are tender. Stir gently. Sprinkle remaining 1/2 cup green
onions over top and serve. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Best Slow Cooker Cookbook Ever'' by Natalie Haughton,
Harper Collins.
</P>
<P>
   SPICY FRANKS
</P>
<P>
   This fast and easy to prepare appetizer can usually be made from
ingredients on hand. &QL; 
1 cup ketchup &QL; 
1/4 cup packed light brown sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon red wine vinegar &QL; 
2 teaspoons soy sauce &QL; 
2 teaspoons Dijon mustard &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon garlic powder &QL; 
1 pound frankfurters, cut in 1-inch pieces OR 1 pound cocktail
wieners OR smoked sausages
</P>
<P>
   Place ketchup, brown sugar, vinegar, soy sauce, mustard and
garlic in a 3 1/2-quart slow cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook on high setting until blended, 1 to 2 hours. Stir
in frankfurters. Cover and cook until thoroughly heated, 1 to 2
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Turn on low to keep warm and serve from cooker. Makes 6 to 8
appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Rival.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY PEPPER POT &QL; 
1 1/2 cups chopped red, yellow OR green bell peppers &QL; 
1 small onion, chopped &QL; 
2 garlic cloves, minced &QL; 
1 pound turkey cutlets, cut into thin strips &QL; 
1 can (14 1/2 ounces) diced tomatoes with basil, garlic and
oregano &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons dried basil leaves &QL; 
2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar &QL; 
2 tablespoons cornstarch &QL; 
Hot cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   Combine peppers, onion, garlic, turkey, tomatoes and basil in a
3 1/2-quart slow cooker. Cover; cook on low setting 7 to 9 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Combine balsamic vinegar and cornstarch and stir into liquid in
cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Cover; cook on high setting 20 to 30 minutes. Serve over hot
cooked rice. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Rival.
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED GREEN PEPPERS &QL; 
1 package (10 ounces) frozen corn &QL; 
1 can (15 ounces) red kidney beans, drained and rinsed &QL; 
1 can (28 ounces) crushed tomatoes &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped onion &QL; 
1 1/2 cups cooked rice &QL; 
1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon pepper &QL; 
4 small green bell peppers, tops removed and seeded &QL; 
2 cups shredded, reduced-fat Cheddar cheese (1/4 cup reserved)
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except green peppers and 1/4 cup cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Use mixture to stuff peppers to top. Place in a slow cooker.
(Place 3 peppers in bottom and 1 on top.)
</P>
<P>
   Cover; cook on low setting 6 to 8 hours or high 3 to 4 hours.
Sprinkle with 1/4 cup cheese in last 30 minutes. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Rival.
</P>
<P>
   SPICY CHICKEN CHOW MEIN
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds skinless, boneless chicken breasts, cut into 1-inch
pieces &QL; 
4 large carrots, thinly sliced &QL; 
4 green onions, sliced (including green portions) &QL; 
3 stalks celery, sliced &QL; 
1 cup reduced-sodium chicken broth &QL; 
1 tablespoon sugar &QL; 
1/3 cup reduced-sodium soy sauce &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon ground ginger &QL; 
1 clove garlic, minced &QL; 
8 ounces bean sprouts &QL; 
1 can (8 ounces) water chestnuts &QL; 
1/4 cup cornstarch &QL; 
1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a skillet over medium-high heat. Add chicken pieces
and cook until brown. Put in a 3 1/2- to 4-quart slow cooker. Add
remaining ingredients, except cornstarch and water; stir to
combine. Cover; cook on low setting 6 to 8 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Turn cooker to high.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, stir cornstarch into cold water until
dissolved. Stir into liquid in cooker. Place cover slightly ajar.
Cook until thickened 15 to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with chow mein noodles or rice. May be doubled for 5-quart
models. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Rival.
</P>
<P>
   SPICY BEEF ROAST &QL; 
1 to 2 tablespoons cracked black peppercorns &QL; 
2 cloves garlic, minced &QL; 
3 pound beef round tip roast OR brisket, trimmed of fat &QL; 
3 tablespoons balsamic vinegar &QL; 
1/4 cup reduced-sodium soy sauce &QL; 
2 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce &QL; 
2 teaspoons dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   Rub cracked pepper and garlic into roast. Put roast in a slow
cooker. Make several shallow slits in top of roast.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine all remaining ingredients and pour over
meat. Cover; cook on low setting 8 to 10 hours or high 4 to 5
hours. Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Rival.
</P>
<P>
   PEACH COBBLER &QL; 
1/3 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
1/2 cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
3/4 cup all-purpose baking mix, such as Bisquick &QL; 
2 eggs &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
2 teaspoons margarine OR butter, melted &QL; 
1/2 can evaporated milk &QL; 
3 large ripe peaches, mashed &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Lightly grease a slow cooker or spray with a nonstick cooking
spray.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine sugars and baking mix. Add eggs and
vanilla. Stir. Pour in margarine and milk and stir. Mix in peaches
and cinnamon, until well mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into slow cooker. Cover and cook on low setting 6 to 8
hours or on high 3 to 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm. Top with vanilla ice cream, if desired. Makes 4
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Rival.
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT BUTTER AND HOT FUDGE PUDDING CAKE &QL; 
1/2 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
3/4 cup sugar &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
1/3 cup milk &QL; 
1 tablespoon vegetable oil &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1/4 cup peanut butter &QL; 
3 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder &QL; 
1 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine flour, 1/4 cup sugar and baking powder. Add
milk, oil and vanilla; stir until smooth. Mix in peanut butter.
Pour into a 3 1/2-quart slow cooker.
</P>
<P>
   In same mixing bowl, stir together remaining 1/2 cup sugar and
cocoa powder. Gradually stir in boiling water. Pour mixture over
batter in cooker. DO NO STIR.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook on high 2 to 3 hours or until a toothpick
inserted comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm with vanilla ice cream, hot fudge sauce and top with
nuts. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Rival.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-FASHIONED PUMPKIN CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Be sure that the 2 1/2-quart souffle dish you plan to use will
fit into a 5-quart slow cooker before proceeding. To dress up this
moist cake, reminiscent of steamed pudding, top slices with whipped
cream flavored with a little orange peel or Grand Marinier. Or
sprinkle the top of the cake with powdered sugar before slicing. &QL; 
1/2 cup vegetable oil &QL; 
2 eggs &QL; 
1 1/2 cups sugar &QL; 
1 cup canned solid-packed pumpkin &QL; 
1/2 cup water &QL; 
1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
1 teaspoon baking soda &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon ground cloves &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon grated nutmeg &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon salt &QL; 
3/4 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix together oil, eggs, sugar, pumpkin and
water. Add flour, baking soda, baking powder, cinnamon, cloves,
nutmeg and salt. Blend well. Stir in pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Turin into a buttered 2 1/2-quart round souffle dish. Carefully
place souffle dish in a 5-quart electric slow cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and cook on high-heat setting 3 1/2 to 3 3/4 hours or
until a cake tested inserted in center of cake comes out clean. (Do
not attempt to cook on the low heat setting for a longer time.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove lid and turn cooker off. Leave cake in cooker until dish
is cool enough to handle. Remove from cooker. Cut into wedges and
serve warm or at room temperature. Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Best Slow Cooker Cookbook Ever'' by Natalie Haughton,
HarperCollins. &QL;
</P>
