<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-WAGE-BOS &LR;      09-28 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-WAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS LEANING TOWARD HIKE IN MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time since revamping the welfare
system, Congress appears ready to approve a significant increase in
the minimum wage, potentially affecting millions of low-income
employees who until recently did not have jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals, which would add $1 to the $5.15 minimum wage over
a two- to five-year period, have drawn objections from Republicans
and small business owners who say an increase causes low-wage jobs
to disappear. But the opposition is relatively mild, and Republican
leaders in both the House and Senate seem unwilling to wage a
fierce battle to kill the legislation, especially with so many
other issues in Congress unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said the Republican about-face is startling. Only
three years ago, House Majority Leader Richard Armey of Texas said
he would permit a minimum wage increase ``over my dead body.'' But
even after a rollicking news conference on Capitol Hill Tuesday _
featuring Hillary Rodham Clinton, Senator Edward M. Kennedy and a
series of charts attempting to prove the necessity of an increase _
few Republicans appeared interested in turning the minimum wage
issue into an ordeal. Armey, at a simultaneous news conference, did
not mention it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate has changed dramatically,'' said Rick Berman,
executive director of the Employment Policy Institute, a
Washington-based think tank that is funded by businesses and is
opposed to a minimum wage hike. ``I'm baffled by it. My guess is
that the Republicans, without enough of a margin in Congress, don't
see it as a fight worth making, even though the economics don't
make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The main proposal in the Senate would increase the minimum wage
by $1 over two years, and is almost identical to the last wage
increase in 1996, which boosted the minimum wage from $4.25 to
$5.15.
</P>
<P>
   Last time, Kennedy immobilized the Senate while pushing for the
increase and the House passed the 90-cent hike in the face of
overwhelming opposition from Republican leaders. House Majority
Whip Tom DeLay of Texas reacted in horror to the 1996 vote, saying
the Democratic Party ``is to job creation what Jack Kevorkian is to
health care.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Kennedy has threatened to shut down the Senate again,
saying he will try to attach a minimum wage amendment to any piece
of legislation that comes to the floor. But Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott indicated this week that such guerrilla tactics may not
be necessary. When Kennedy asked him when the minimum wage could be
debated, Lott invited him to his office to ``sit down and seriously
discuss a way to get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   In the House, some Republican opponents seem to be avoiding a
strategy of killing the bill outright. Instead, minimum wage
legislation is being viewed as a vehicle for accomplishing other
GOP goals, with some Republicans pushing to combine a minimum wage
increase with a package of tax cuts, aides said. Those cuts would
be aimed at small businesses most affected by a minimum wage
increase but also could include the elimination of estate taxes and
a deduction for health care.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the bill is hardly unanimous, said Trent Duffy, a
spokesman for House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer,
a Republican from Texas. ``Some conservatives will never vote for a
minimum wage increase because they just fundamentally believe in a
thing called supply and demand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the addition of tax cuts would make the increase more
appealing to moderates and even some conservative Republicans, who
are primarily concerned that jobs would be lost if the minimum wage
goes up, he said. ``The feeling is that if you attach some tax
relief to reduce the impact of the threat of that, then you might
be able to have enough conservatives vote for it,'' Duffy said.
``That's the theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Rick A. Lazio, a Republican from New York, is
expected to roll out his minimum wage proposal this week, complete
with proposals for tax cuts. Archer's own bill will be unveiled
before the session ends next month, Duffy said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans also expressed support for a proposal that
would allow states to ``opt out'' of the federal minimum wage
requirements. The bipartisan bill would not let states drop their
minimum wage lower than the current $5.15 an hour, but it would
give state legislatures the right to ignore any future increases.
Representative Charles W. Stenholm, the Texas Democrat and
co-sponsor of that bill, said it would ``give states greater
flexibility to develop appropriate strategies to respond'' to
citizens' needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you sit back and look at the real world out there, we're in
an internationally competitive marketplace,'' Stenholm said. ``And
anything we do that decreases our competitiveness is going to have
a depressing effect on jobs. I think we must be very careful before
we increase the minimum wage without providing some flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But Representative David E. Bonior, joining Clinton and Kennedy
at Tuesday's news conference, made it clear most Democrats would
fight such a proposal. ``That's like saying all drivers have to
stop at a stoplight unless they opt out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is considering a run for the Senate from New York,
said the increase would serve as a cost of living adjustment for
the poor, restoring the value of the minimum wage to what it was in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking for special favors for these millions and
millions of people, who do a lot of the work that keeps this
country going,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy drew the most applause, pointing to a recent
congressional pay increase as evidence the Republican Congress
would be hypocritical by not debating the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read the record. No opposition to increasing their own wages _
$4,600 in one year,'' Kennedy said. ``We do not believe that who
anyone who wants to work, who will work, 40 hours a week, 52 weeks
of the year, should have to live in poverty in America. This, above
all, is a fairness issue. And the American people understand
fairness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
