<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVISIBLE-CONDOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INVISIBLE' CONDOM UNDER DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someday a woman will be able pick up a tube of gel or cream at
her local pharmacy that not only protects her from getting
pregnant, but also against HIV and other sexually transmitted
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The products, which would be applied before sex, would be cheap,
over-the-counter, safe, easy to use, and unnoticeable during sex.
Called microbicides, they would be like ``invisible'' condoms, and
could be used by women whose partners refuse to use condoms.
Ideally, some would protect a woman from disease but still allow
her to become pregnant if she chose. Unfortunately, it may be a
decade before the new products come to market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once developed, this may even be better than the condom,''
said Dr. Arthur Chen, director of the AIDS Prevention and Research
Center at National Yang Ming University in Taipei. ``It's always
difficult to persuade the partner. Vulnerable groups in society
need an invention developed for them to prevent HIV,'' Chen said.
In Taiwan, two-thirds of the women who become HIV-infected are
spouses or girlfriends of HIV-infected men, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the substances researchers are working with are
derivatives of drugs that are already used against HIV, such as
AZT, or of other anti-viral and anti-bacterial drugs. One of the
most promising of these types of products is being designed at a
Cambridge-based company, Procept Inc.
</P>
<P>
   At a reproductive medicine conference in Toronto, researchers
this week revealed the latest developments in the new class of
STD-blockers. About 56 different approaches are being tried, mainly
by research institutions and small start-up companies.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, sexually-active women represent the fastest growing
portion of the HIV/AIDS population, with an estimated 13.8 million
women infected with HIV, and 85 percent of those are of
reproductive age, said Osmond D'Cruz, director of reproductive
biology at the Hughes Institute in St. Paul, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   In one study, supported by the National Institutes of Child
Health and Human Development (NICHD), D'Cruz and his colleagues
found that a derivative compound of AZT, called ZDV, which is
already known to be effective at both controlling HIV transmission
and preventing pregancy, can also work as a vaginal gel or cream.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the work in this field is, like D'Cruz's work, only
about a decade old, and still in the early stages.
</P>
<P>
   Movement has been slow, said Polly Harrison, director of the
Alliance For Microbicide Development, because there's been ``not
enough money, focus, coordination and speed.'' ``Many (projects)
are still stuck in pre-clinical stages,'' said Harrison. ``What's
causing the clogging is that big pharmaceutical companies don't
want to play yet, so we don't see the money devoted to this. That
means we have to depend on the federal government, which isn't
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Penny Hitchcock of the sexually transmitted diseases branch
of the National Institute of Allergies and Infectious Diseases said
her organization's first priority has been to evaluate currently
available spermicides. But after being tested in large numbers of
humans, the spermicides haven't shown much success as microbicides,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most promising of the microbicides is being developed
by Procept. Called Pro 2000, Procept's lead anti-infective product
is a colorless, odorless gel that is a contraceptive and an
antimicrobial barrier against herpes, HIV and chlamydia. Unlike
some spermicides, the gel doesn't irritate vaginal tissues, said
Procept Vice President Albert Profy.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Procept started an expanded safety trial of its
product with sexually active women and HIV-positive women in four
cities, Profy asid.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Max Essex, professor of virology and chairman of the Harvard
AIDS Institute, believes that the biggest problem is that
microbicides may not be able to accommodate women who want to
conceive while being protected from disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these women really want to get pregnant. I find it
hard to imagine that it will be very possible to make a vaginal
microbicide that kills HIV, but doesn't kill or damage sperm,''
Essex said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
