<HEADER>
A9376 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MELISSA-JOAN-HART-LAD     09-28 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELISSA-JOAN-HART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S SABRINA CHANNELS ENERGY INTO ROMANTIC COMEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VAL KUKLENSKI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Melissa Joan Hart says when she was 4, she wanted
to become an actress so she could hear her own name on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I wanted to be on `Romper Room' because I really wanted
my name said in the Magic Mirror, and I knew there was no way to do
that unless I was on the show because she would not say Melissa,''
Hart said. ``So I figured if I was on the show there's no way she
could get around it _ she'd have to say my name.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she hears her name all the time _ Melissa, star of
``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch'' on ABC; Melissa, co-star of the
network's new kid show, ``Sabrina, the Animated Series''; and now
Melissa, star of ``Drive Me Crazy,'' a romantic comedy hitting
theaters Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And there are behind-the-scenes beckonings as well: Melissa, an
executive producer of the prime-time series; Melissa, a partner
with her mother, Paula, in Hartbreak Films; Melissa, the big sister
and mentor to seven siblings, all of whom have worked in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   These days the 23-year-old former star of the Nickelodeon series
``Clarissa Explains It All'' is spread thinner than fat-free cream
cheese on a supermodel's Melba toast.
</P>
<P>
   She's bouncing between coasts to promote the movie, wedging in
press interviews between talk show appearances while her publicist
keeps a close eye on the itinerary and his watch. She fights back
yawns of fatigue and reminds herself that she needs to telephone a
professor at New York University this week to ask for a year's
leave of absence from her bachelor of arts correspondence program.
She'd love to keep up the studies, but there just isn't time.
</P>
<P>
   The degree in progress, begun in January 1994, is not precisely
defined yet _ ``some kind of combination of art and literature,''
Hart says, rattling off a wide range of classes she already has
completed. When will she graduate?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping in the next four or five years,'' she says,
sounding uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   All of you who have complained about plodding through school on
the five-year plan while working part time: Quit whining.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Hart says Melissa is very hands-on as vice president of
Hartbreak, keeping involved with 43 projects in development and
using her celebrity stature to open doors both with stars she would
like to cast and studio chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was little, she worked constantly,'' Paula said. ``I
found that when she was working, all of her school grades were
straight A. But when she would take a break, all her grades would
drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more pressure she has on her, the better she does. She's
one of those Type A personalities, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, about the movie. Originally titled ``Next to You,'' ``Drive
Me Crazy'' centers on Nicole (Hart), a fun-loving high school
senior intent on saving face with the popular crowd after the
school basketball star jilts her. Her neighbor, Chase (Adrian
Grenier), is a social outcast by choice who wants to get back
together with his girlfriend, and agrees to ``date'' Nicole to make
their exes jealous and win them back.
</P>
<P>
   Hart says the fact that Grenier and she are so different _ he's
the quiet, keep-'em-guessing counterpoint to her high-energy
effervescence _ was a big plus during the shoot. (Despite a
well-publicized ``thing'' they had during filming, she did not
mention Grenier or any other man when pressed about her love life.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very much like our characters, and yet we get along very
much like our characters,'' she said. ``We really have a great
relationship because we're very open to listening to the other
person about what their opinions are, about what their views are on
something. We really respect each other, basically, is where it all
comes from. We respect that we kind of come from similar places but
take different approaches to things.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually explains it a lot better than I do,'' she adds
with a touch of apology.
</P>
<P>
   The role, which calls for Hart to appear manipulative and, in
one long scene, smashed, represents a baby step toward playing
less-wholesome characters than Clarissa and Sabrina.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Hart is no Mama Rose aiming to keep her daughter in the
Dainty June costume as long as possible. In fact, she has been
propelling Melissa toward more sophisticated projects. In some
recent publicity photos, the actress turns down that high-wattage
smile for a more sultry look, camouflages her girlish freckles,
tousles her blond mane into bedroom hair and flaunts her navel
ring.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, don't look for Melissa to plunge immediately into
deeper, darker waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things I'd like to do, but I know I'm not
ready for them yet,'' Hart said. ``The next step for me would have
to be something a little bit more serious, but not too serious, not
melodramatic. A character that has dimension, that's real, that's
going through some kind of change, some challenge. It's hard to
say, but if I read it I'd know.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart enjoys nightclubbing and partying with close friends at her
Hollywood Hills home, but she remains mindful as ever of public
expectations of a celebrity branded as the girl-next-door type.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are in the public eye, there is certain
responsibility,'' she said. ``You have to walk a fine line about
how far do you go with your own life and then how far do you take
the role model thing. When do you start to do your own thing and
just live your own life?''
</P>
<P>
   Hart reflected back to 1997 when, during her first season of
``Sabrina,'' she felt ill at ease playing some of the screwball
bits the scripts demanded. ``Now that's what I love is all the
over-the-top stuff. Maybe it's because I'm so comfortable now after
four years of working with the crew and I know everybody so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever tried to do anything serious in front of those
people they'd laugh at me. They just know how goofy I am, and we
all have so much fun being idiots together.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, she says, her ``Sabrina'' friends would be very
supportive of any endeavor. ``But I just feel stupid acting in
front of them. If anyone could see right through it, it would be
them.'' A pause. ``So maybe it would be good to do it in front of
them because it would put me to the test, make me work my
hardest.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FBO-TARKENTON-COX     09-28 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-TARKENTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former football great charged with fraud; settlement announced
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (f) Financial and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hall of Fame football star and businessman Fran A.
Tarkenton was charged by the government on Tuesday with carrying
out a multi-million dollar financial fraud scheme as chief
executive of KnowledgeWare, a one-time Atlanta software company.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Securities and Exchange Commission
announced a settlement of the case under which Tarkenton agreed to
a pay a $100,000 fine and disgorge $54,187 in incentive
compensation he had been paid.
</P>
<P>
   The money will go to federal court, and former shareholders of
the company might make claims to it.
</P>
<P>
   Tarkenton and six other former KnowledgeWare executives agreed
to the settlement without admiting or denying the charges.
Tarkenton could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney issued a statement saying that ``Mr. Tarkenton is
pleased to have this matter resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC alleged that Tarkenton and the six other executives of
KnowledgeWare. ``materially inflated'' the company's reported
earnings in the fiscal year ended June 30, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Tarkenton, 59, was chairman and chief executive officer of
KnowledgeWare at the time.
</P>
<P>
   An SEC said it's not unusual for a settlement of this kind to
take five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all, KnowledgeWare reported at least $8 million in revenue
from sham software sales,'' the SEC said in its civil action, which
was part of a sweeping government move against 15 public companies.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC complaint, KnowledgeWare engaged in fraud
when it ``parked'' its products with resellers and other ``supposed
customers,'' who were given the right not to pay for the software.
</P>
<P>
   These rights were communicated to the clients orally or in
``side letters,'' which were kept separate from the company's other
sales documents reported to the government and to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``parked'' inventory was booked as actual sales, which
the SEC said was a violation of company and professional accounting
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The parking of inventory was pervasive from the quarter ended
Sept. 30, 1993, through the rest of fiscal year ended June 30,
1994, according to the SEC. The agency said sales personnel issued
more than 50 ``side letters'' for ``phony sales'' ranging from
several thousand dollars to almost $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC, Tarkenton and other company executives
``directed this financial fraud scheme and each of the other
defendants knowingly played an importanmt role in implementing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint alleged arkenton ``personally instructed'' a vice
president to generate a phony $356,500 software sale to a reseller
shortly before the end of the third quarter of fiscal 1994, after
the intended user ``had declined to purchase the software that
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospective end-user never purchased the software, and the
phony sale to the third party remained an account receivable on
KnowledgeWare's books for the rest of (fiscal year) 1994 without
any attempt at collection,'' the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott York, with the SEC's New York office, said Tuesday that
the agency's crackdown on KnowledgeWare and other companies was
intended to show that ``anyone who participates in this kind of
fraud will be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not the work of a lone employee acting in
isolation,'' he said. ``Fraud pervaded KnowledgeWare because of the
management scheme to inflate revenue and earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The events in question took place about five or six years ago
during Mr. Tarkenton's tenure at KnowledgeWare, and he has long
since moved on with his life to other business ventures,''
Tarkenton's attorney, Robert Thornton of King &AMP; Spalding, wrote in
the statement. ``Mr. Tarkenton entered into this settlement without
admitting or denying any of the allegations of wrongdoing in the
complaint and without trial or adjudication of any legal or factual
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC case was not the first legal action against
KnowledgeWare. Several shareholder lawsuits grew out of the
acquisition of the company in 1994 by Dallas-based Sterling
Software.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota financier Irwin Jacobs and some associates sued
Tarkenton in January 1995, alleging he misled investors about the
financial condition of KnowledgeWare.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's complaint said KnowledgeWare experienced a shrinking
market as U.S. companies switched from mainframe computer programs,
its specialty, to software for networks and personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced a major restructuring in the third quarter
of 1993, took a $22 million charge against earnings and laid off 20
percent of its employees. The company reported a loss of more than
$25 million in fiscal 1993 on sales of $128 million.
</P>
<P>
   But in a meeting with analysts, Tarkenton and other executives
made upbeat projections about the following year, according to the
SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said Tarkenton, Donald P. Addington, president and chief
operating officer, and Rick W. Gossett, chief financial officer,
``together with other defendants,'' engaged in a fraudulent scheme
to overstate revenue and earnings ``to give the false appearance
that KnowledgeWare had met or exceeded its projections for (fiscal
year) 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   The company announced in 1994 that it would be acquired by
Sterling Software in a deal reported at the time to be worth $143
million. A merger agreement was signed in August.
</P>
<P>
   But when KnowledgeWare announced that it expected to report a
loss for the June 30 quarter, Sterling Software withdrew its
original offer of $8.75 per share and instead offered just under $5
per share.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Software acquired the company at that price, which it
said in its annual report totaled $74.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company also set aside 20 percent of the purchase price at
the time to cover any shareholder lawsuits that might come out of
the acquisition, an amount totaling almost $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Kupp, vice president investor relations for Sterling
Software, said Tuesday that all of the money in that escrow fund
was subsequently paid out as a result of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   She emphasized that Sterling Software was not affected by the
SEC's complaint against the former KowledgeWare management.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Tarkenton, Addington, 48, and Gossett, 47, the
other executives named in the SEC complaint were Lee R. Fontaine,
34, manager of financial reporting; William E. Hammersla III, 45,
vice president for direct sales in the Northeastern U.S.; Eladio
Alvarez, 41, district sales manager in the company's direct sales
group; and Edward Welch, 55, district sales manager in the Reseller
Channel Sales group.
</P>
<P>
   All but Alvarez and Welch consented to the SEC's judgment and
agreed to pay civil fines varying from $100,000 for Addington to
$10,000 for Fontaine.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC also said it settled administrative proceedings aginst
four former KnowledgeWare sales executives charged with
participating in the financial scheme.
</P>
<P>
   They are Laura M. Drews, 35, a vice president; Stephen J. Pace,
39, vice president of direct sales for the Southern and Mid-Western
states; Robert S. Chamberlain, 41, vice pesident of direct sales in
the West; and Joseph A. Mathes, 38, a district manager.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said all four had settled the proceedings without
admitting or denying the Commission's findings. They were required
to disgorge ``excess incentive compensation'' in amounts from
$31,824 to $6,728.
</P>
<P>
   A star quarterback at the University of Georgia and Minnesota
Vikings, Tarkenton went into the software business in 1980, two
years after retiring from pro football.
</P>
<P>
   KnowledgeWare was a highflier in the computer industry at one
point, with its stock reaching $43.25 in 1991. That's when its
performance was starting to be hurt by the shift of client
companies from mainframe computers to PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
