<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA GOVERNOR ENDORSES BUSH FOR PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush raided Republican
presidential rival John McCain's home state Tuesday to pick up the
endorsement of Arizona Gov. Jane Hull.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a new poll indicates the GOP presidential
contest in Arizona will be a three-way battle between Bush, McCain,
the state's senior U.S. senator; and publisher Steve Forbes, who
won Arizona's 1996 presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Hull had been delaying endorsing a Republican presidential
candidate because there were two local residents in the contests:
McCain and former Vice President Dan Quayle, an Indiana native who
moved to Arizona a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull last Saturday told McCain she was going to throw her
support to Bush, even before Quayle announced Monday that he was
dropping out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but the highest regard for John McCain,'' Hull
said at a Capitol news conference with Bush on Tuesday. ``This
isn't against John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said she is supporting Bush because they share a vision on
lower taxes, less government and improving education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am throwing my support behind Governor Bush for several
compelling reasons. First of all is his character. Second is his
experience. And third is his vision of the future,'' Hull said.
``In baseball they call it a grand slam.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull became the 24th of 30 Republican governors to endorse Bush,
not counting the Texas governor himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called McCain _ a former Vietnam prisoner of war _ a
``legitimate hero.'' But Bush said he also plans to compete for
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to coming here to compete,'' Bush said. ``I
know I've got a lot of hands to shake, a lot of people I've got to
convince.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Bush announced his intention to seek the GOP
presidential nomination in March, his father, former President
Bush, hosted a fund-raiser for his eldest son in Arizona that
brought in more than $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush held a Phoenix fund-raiser himself Tuesday that was
expected to gather $100,000 for his campaign. When the campaign
finance deadline passes Thursday, Bush is expected to announce that
he has raised more than $50 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain has most Arizona elected officials backing him,
Hull's endorsement of Bush could serve as a psychological blow to
his campaign. McCain has been counting on scoring well against Bush
in New Hampshire and then in South Carolina and Arizona to
jump-start his campaign before the end of February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain and Bush can remember how political endorsements did
not carry the state in 1996. McCain originally supported Texas Sen.
Phil Gramm for the Republican nomination. But after Gramm dropped
out, McCain and most other Arizona politicians threw their support
to Bob Dole, the party's eventual nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that support, Dole finished second to Forbes and only
slightly ahead of commentator Patrick Buchanan in the state's
primary.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll of Arizona voters conducted last weekend by KAET-TV
and Arizona State University found Bush leading in the state with
31 percent to McCain's 22 percent, followed by Forbes at 10
percent. Other candidates in the race had less than 10 percent
support each.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also picked up the endorsement of former House Republican
leader John Rhodes of Mesa, whom McCain replaced when Rhodes
retired. Rhodes said he believed Bush was more likely to win the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife, Laura, later visited the Thomas J. Pappas
Elementary School, a privately run school for about 700 homeless
children who live in temporary shelters, abandoned buildings and
condemned motels.
</P>
<P>
   Two fifth-graders, identified only as Nick and Brent,
interviewed the Bushes for a school radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The boys asked Laura Bush was it was like to be the wife of a
future president. Mrs. Bush told them that she has a wonderful
family and that as a former teacher she likes to make school visits
such as this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to encourage you all to work hard, study hard and turn
off the television at night and study,'' Mrs. Bush told the
homeless children.
</P>
<P>
   One of the boys threw a tougher question at Gov. Bush: ``If you
become president, can you help to see that there are not as many
guns or knives to hurt people?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he wanted to prosecute people who violate laws in
selling, carrying or using guns. He said he also wanted to keep
guns out of the hands of juveniles and the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   The boys also asked how he would stop abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, remind people they should abstain from sex
until they are married,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
