<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-KICKERS-COX     09-28 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KICKERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deflating special teams: Kickers complain about new rule
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Minnesota's Gary Anderson and Atlanta's Morten
Andersen are two of the most prolific kickers in NFL history,
ranking first and second, respectively, in career field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, through three games this season, they are a combined
4-for-11 on field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The pair's struggles are a rallying cry for NFL kickers and
punters, who are criticizing the league's new ``K'' ball.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, 36 footballs arrived at a stadium the Friday before
a game, leaving kickers several hours to apply their personal
touch. Now, 12 balls aren't opened by officials until Sunday, and
they are locked up until kickoff. The balls are marked with a ``K''
by the laces and are used only for kicks and punts. Anyone caught
tampering with a kicking-only ball could be subject to a fine up to
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL implemented the rule after record-setting kicking
results last season. Anderson became the league's first perfect
kicker, making all 35 field-goal and 59 extra-point attempts in the
regular season. Minnesota's Mitch Berger had 40 kickoffs for
touchbacks in 1998, an average of 2 1/2 per game. That was a league
record for touchbacks since the kickoff was moved back to the
30-yard line, breaking the old mark by 11.
</P>
<P>
   But as more kicks sailed through the end zone the past few
seasons, resulting in fewer returns, the NFL's competition
committee took a closer look at special teams. The league moved the
kickoff from the 35-yard line to the 30. The height of the kicking
tee was shortened from 3 inches to 1. Still, none of it seemed to
take the air out of kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're asking is that the kickers kick with a regulation
NFL football,'' said George Young, the NFL's senior vice president
of football operations. ``When they complain like they have been,
what are they saying? That they've been cheating all along?''
</P>
<P>
   Since the rule was introduced, kickers have been candid about
their past attempts at turning cowhide into veal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've heard that guys were doing anything to soften the
ball and compress it a little bit,'' said Denver kicker Jason Elam,
a graduate of Brookwood High School. ``Guys would use dryers,
microwaves, saunas, hot tubs, anything to get some moisture in
there and soften the leather.''
</P>
<P>
   While some kickers have struggled this season, statistics
indicate the ``K'' balls haven't had much of an effect. According
to Elias Sports Bureau, the average kickoff return through three
games in 1998 was 22.4 yards. The average punt return was 11.4
yards. The average punt was 44.4 yards before returns.
</P>
<P>
   After three games this season, the average kickoff return is
21.5 yards. The average punt return is 8.9 yards. The average punt
is sailing 42.7 yards. In other words, returns are down, indicating
that kickers and punters are still getting quality hang time.
</P>
<P>
   And in the most noticeable area _ field goals _ kickers have
made 76.1 percent of their attempts, up from 72.1 percent at the
same point last season.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints still haven't stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kicking balls are brand new out of the box,'' Falcons
punter Dan Stryzinski said. ``If you're a tennis player and you
have an oversized racket, your sweet spot is huge. And then if you
go back to a John McEnroe, a little-bitty wooden racket, your sweet
spot is really small and it's hard to always get a good hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the footballs, when they're brand new, the sweet spot is
almost non-existent,'' Stryzinski said, ``because the leather is
really hard and there's wax on the ball. It's slick and slides off
your foot a lot. With worked balls, the wax is off the ball, so the
leather kind of softens up and expands. When you hit it, your foot
sinks in, and you get good contact with it. There's just nothing
there with the new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, who is 0 for 3 on field-goal attempts this season,
attributes the misses to mechanical mistakes and doesn't blame the
``K'' ball. But he doesn't like the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the more you use a football or any ball _ a
baseball, basketball or whatever _ I think the better it is to play
with because it gets broken in,'' Andersen said. ``Nobody wants to
play with a brand new ball. That's normal. Ask Michael Jordan if he
likes to dribble a ball that's brand new, versus one that's been
broken in a little bit. The same thing with a baseball pitcher. He
doesn't like a brand-new ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Stryzinski says he pumped up balls to 20 pounds per
square inch, seven pounds more than the 13 psi recommended by
Wilson Sporting Goods. The overinflated balls were left overnight
to stretch the leather. The next morning, Stryzinski put the balls
in a sauna for about 15 minutes. The balls were taken out and
brushed with a non-wire shoe brush to bring out the oil in the
leather and maintain the tacky feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just try to get them old by use,'' said Styrzinski, who
still works footballs thrown by quarterback Chris Chandler. ``As
long as they're not dirty and all scuffed up to the point where
they don't look new, then we'll use them in the game, because
that's how the quarterbacks and receivers like them. That's what
they've been doing for years and years, and it's never been a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Former University of Georgia kicker Todd Peterson, in his fifth
season with the Seattle Seahawks, said he used to rub balls with a
hot towel before brushing them. Peterson would over-inflate balls
twice to protrude the seams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a ball turned away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Chicago Bears kicker Jeff Jaeger was the Gaylord Perry of
the NFL. Jaeger and Bears punter Todd Sauerbrun overinflated balls
and left them sitting for three days. They would then deflate the
balls to about eight pounds and push the ends into the corner of a
table. The balls would be overinflated again, thrown into a laundry
sack with wet towels and put into a dryer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten minutes was all it would take to get them real hot,''
Sauerbrun said. ``They'd bang around in the dryer, and then we'd
brush them off.''
</P>
<P>
   If the ball needed more work, it would be deflated again and put
under hot water.
</P>
<P>
   The process got scientific last season when Sauerbrun was
injured and the Bears signed 40-year-old Mike Horan, who graduated
from Long Beach State with a degree in mechanical engineering.
Horan had a homemade contraption that consisted of a skateboard and
two-by-fours. Horan and Jaeger would repeatedly roll a 100-pound
dumbbell over the balls on the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd be almost square,'' Chicago special-teams coach Keith
Armstrong said. ``Jeff was so dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all kickers were allowed to ``juice'' balls, however,
because quarterbacks had the final say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kicker loved to go to Dallas, because Troy Aikman liked
to throw with worn balls,'' Elam said. ``Everybody hated going to
San Francisco because Steve Young likes to throw a new ball. You'd
just have to know where to go and where not to go. Before I got
here, (former Broncos quarterback John) Elway told the equipment
guy not to let the kickers touch the balls. ``
</P>
<P>
   Stryzinski says that's why the NFL isn't requiring all players
to use new balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew the quarterbacks would have a big backlash,'' he
said. ``There would be guys complaining all over the league. You'd
see a lot of fumbles, you'd see a lot of slipped passes, you'd see
a lot of guys dropping passes. Basically, the kickers are left out.
What are we going to do? Everybody would just say, 'Oh, the kickers
are whining.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
