<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' focus is increasing tempo
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Henri Crockett was talking about the annoyance of
fuzzballs on his back. He had the right idea, but the wrong
annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who saw Sunday's 35-7 loss at St. Louis knows what coach
Dan Reeves was talking about when he said the Rams played ``at a
different speed'' than Atlanta. The Falcons (0-3) looked like they
had anchors on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   So after the team's most lopsided loss in nearly three years,
the first goal on Sunday against Baltimore (1-2) is simple. ``We
got to play faster,'' right tackle Ephraim Salaam said.
</P>
<P>
   Several Falcons said they didn't sense their slow motion on the
field, but they got an eyeful _ and an earful _ watching the
replay. Atlanta looked like a team with no sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really notice until you watch film,'' Crockett said.
``It was really bad, embarrassing. I can understand what (Reeves)
means. It's almost like having lint on your back. You don't know
it's there until someone points it out to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were fresh after a bye week, and the Falcons were on
the road after losing Monday night in Dallas. Still, attitude had a
lot to do with what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to set the tempo,'' middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle
said. ``We're sitting back . . . and waiting for things to happen.
We're not the same team we were last year, and we got to figure out
what it takes to get back to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is rethinking his team's approach to practice. For
example, players had been particularly lethargic during Friday's
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you think you can throw a switch on in games,
but you can't,'' Crockett said. ``It's got to start (today) in
practice. We've got to do the same things we mean to in games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were a hunter last year; this year, they're among
the hunted. They've got to get faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat the Rams last year (37-15 and 21-10),'' Salaam said.
``They wanted to punch us in the mouth, and we just kind of stood
around and let them. We got killed. I need to get more aggressive .
. . and put it all on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons re-signed defensive tackle Shawn Swayda to bolster
an injury-riddled line and terminated the contract of 16-year
offensive lineman/deep snapper Adam Schreiber. Swayda, 25, played
for Atlanta last season and was cut after one game this season. The
move leaves the Falcons a little more than $200,000 under the
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
