<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEW-FLOODING-COX     09-28 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-FLOODING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New rainfall could delay flood inspections
 &HT;    By Travis Fain
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ City officials expect inspection teams to
finish their walk-through of damaged homes by Friday, assuming
floodwaters ebb as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Most Greenville homes south of the Tar River have been
inspected, with the exception of some apartments in Tar River
Estates and Dockside apartments, city spokeswoman Katie Veilleux
said. Roughly 650 homes had been inspected through Tuesday, she
said. Officials only inspect buildings that had more than a foot of
water in them.
</P>
<P>
   Water is pooling up in some places, unable to flow back into the
Tar River. City staff members are considering using pumps to move
the water, but no definite plans have been developed, Veilleux
said.
</P>
<P>
   County teams have not said when they expect to finish their
inspections, but had almost finished areas where the water had
receded Tuesday evening, according to Pitt County Spokesman Arlen
Holt. About three-fourths of the homes county teams inspected will
need repairs before they are inhabitable, Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Three-plus inches of rain Monday and Tuesday halted the county's
inspection process Monday afternoon, Holt said. City crews worked
through the rain, Veilleux said.
</P>
<P>
   The rain, combined with super-saturated roadsides, also caused
washouts on several Pitt County roads, some that had just been
repaired. Rocks are being used to combat erosion on road shoulders,
but are not as effective as grass, said Grady Raynor, a
transportation supervisor with the N.C. Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   DOT officials cruised the county looking for sinkholes Tuesday,
but there are probably some that have not been discovered yet,
Raynor said. He suggested people only drive if they have to and
urged caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they drive through standing water, there may not be road
under there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar River was at 21.2 feet Tuesday at 4 p.m., down just over
a foot from 24 hours before, according to readings at the
Greenville water treatment plant. It fell a tenth of a foot from 2
p.m. to 4 p.m. Tuesday, the readings show. The river leaves its
banks at 13 feet and was at more than 16 feet before Floyd hit the
morning of Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff and rescue crews had almost completed their search for
dead in the county Tuesday afternoon, Sheriff Mac Manning said. No
flood-related deaths have been discovered in Pitt County since
Ronald Russell's body was pulled from Hardee Creek Saturday
afternoon. Russell's is the fourth confirmed death in the county
attributed to flooding. A Grifton man was also discovered dead in
the Grifton area by Craven County rescue officials.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the first of about 200 expected trailers arrived
at a site on County Home Road, Rudy Hernandez, a spokesman for the
Federal Emergency Management Agency, said. State officials
requested the trailers from the Federal Emergency Management Agency
to provide temporary housing for hurricane victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to try to get at least 20 a day starting
(today),'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   County officials are securing other sites for the campers,
including one owned by East Carolina University. They hope to get
at least 500 trailers altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Most people have cooperated with law enforcement officers at
barricades barring entry into areas that haven't been inspected,
Veilleux and Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very calm, considering what they're looking at just
over the barricade,'' Veilleux said. ``People have been really
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people have complained, Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   The barricades are meant to keep people out until teams can
inspect homes for structural damage, gas leaks, water-affected
electrical wiring and other dangers, both said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who turned a house key over to inspection teams will
get a call from a city clerk to get their key back as well as a
preliminary inspection report, Veilleux said. Once the first round
of assessments is done, inspectors will be available to give a more
detailed rundown of a home's problems.
</P>
<P>
   The city's 10 inspection teams are marking homes with X's to
show they've been examined. An X with a box around it means a home
has been condemned. An X with a slash through it means residents
can go inside to get their things, but the home is not inhabitable
without repairs.
</P>
<P>
   County teams _ there are about 10 of them _ are placing stickers
on inspected homes along with a flood-damage checklist describing
problems, Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   The county is issuing permits to residents whose homes have not
been inspected allowing them to go inside during daylight hours and
at their own risk. The permits are available at the Pactolus and
Staton House fire departments, Gum Swamp Church and the Tax
Assessor's office downtown. The tax assessor's office is open from
8 a.m. to 8 p.m. The other three sites close at 5 p.m., Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary entry permits are not available in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile homes will not be allowed on residential property while
homes are repaired, according to the city. Recreational vehicles
will be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary buildings are OK at commercial sites while repairs are
underway, but also require a renewable 90-day permit, the release
said. Those structures cannot be used as residences.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officers have set up several checkpoints around
flooded areas and are patrolling others, Manning said. Military
police officers will be pulling out today and will be replaced by
state law enforcement officers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of inspections Tuesday _ and in some cases before _
Pitt residents continued to survey the devastation left by ebbing
waters. In one home north of the river, Donny Wilson stepped across
his parents' living room floor, lifting tossed about furniture out
of the way as he went.
</P>
<P>
   The room smelled of rot, its white walls stained with brown
spots to five feet. Wilson's parents had lived there almost 30
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, wooden beams sat atop a station wagon in the front
yard. They floated over a 4 1/2-foot fence to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Trees in the front yard were beginning to show their fall
colors, yellow and red. But to eight feet, the leaves hung dead and
brown, rotting off their stems.
</P>
<P>
   A wooden barn sat in the side yard. It floated there from behind
the house, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that red barn in the ditch,'' said Wilson's
5-year-old nephew Cliff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I see,'' Wilson replied. ``How'd it get there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rain took it there,'' Cliff said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Fain writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
Eunice Moscoso contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
