<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-BUICK-ADVANCE-COX     09-28 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ryder buzz not yet fading
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Forty-eight hours after The Putt, life had
turned decidely more tranquil for Justin Leonard. When his ball
rammed into the back of the cup at the 17th hole Sunday at the
Ryder Cup, triggering the type of celebration usually reserved for
3-point shots at the buzzer, most every golf fan on the globe
seemingly was tuned in.
</P>
<P>
   When Leonard reached the 18th green Tuesday at Callaway Gardens,
playing a nine-hole practice round for this week's Buick Challenge,
the grandstand contained exactly five people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty quiet atmosphere here,'' Leonard said, ``and I
think we're all kind of looking forward to that. I'll probably get
more rest here than I would being at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookline's carryover greeted U.S. players Leonard, Davis Love
III, Steve Pate and Jeff Maggert at first sight of the Mountain
View course. Tournament officials added a sign on the road to the
clubhouse parking lot that read: ``Buick Challenge Welcomes The
Ryder Cup Champions.'' Leonard and Pate got handshakes and
high-fives all over the course. Michael Bradley tapped fists with
Leonard at the 10th teebox. Skip Kendall followed with a way-to-go.
Other caddies were applauding Leonard's caddie, Bob Riefke.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard realizes it might be hard to concentrate on his game for
a few days, but he isn't complaining. It's was heart-warming to go
home to Dallas for a day to hear a phone answering machine jammed
to the maximum with messages. Oh, and The Putt, he had decided was
50 feet, not 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``My putt wouldn't have made a difference had those first
matches not gone out the way they did,'' Leonard said of a U.S.
avalanche of six consecutive victories Sunday. ``Not only did those
guys win, they won by wide margins. . . . They got the Europeans to
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate, who won a crucial match against Miguel Angel Jimenez,
still felt the effects of the party that broke up at 2:30 a.m.
``Obviously, we dug ourselves a huge hole, but I don't think
anybody in that meeting room ever doubted we could do it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbs are still filling the European tabloids regarding the
Americans' celebration after Leonard's putt. Captain Mark James
said that European players might refrain from playing in future
Cups because of the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The celebration on the 17th green) was something that
shouldn't have happened,'' Leonard said, ``but it was not that big
of a deal. I'm not bad-mouthing anybody, but every time Sergio
(Garcia) made a putt, he was hugging somebody.'' For all the hoopla
of the putt at 17, nearly overlooked was Leonard's 45-footer at the
15th hole to even his match with Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a lot of fun talking about all the matches,''
Leonard said of the victory dinner. ``We were just marveling at
some of the shots the other guys made and some of the putts that
were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: Ben Crenshaw, basking in the glow of the victory, said two
years as captain of the U.S. team was enough. A 2001 captain will
be chosen later this year. The team gave Crenshaw a signed copy of
the Cup and he took it to show-and-tell at his two daughters'
schools in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
