<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT BLAMES CO-DEFENDANTS IN SLAYING OF BLACK MAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The third capital murder suspect in last year's
dragging death of a black man near Jasper blames his two
co-defendants for the crime, saying he tried to stop them from
beating James Byrd Jr. but backed off when his own life was
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared me. I didn't know what was going on,'' Shawn Berry
told CBS correspondent Dan Rather in an interview aired Tuesday
night on ``60 Minutes II.'' ``I never saw anything like that, so I
backed away. And they grabbed him, took him to the back of the
truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 24, said he then heard his co-defendants, John William
``Bill'' King and Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., pulling a logging
chain from the back of his pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was petrified. I couldn't move,'' he said. ``And when ...
Russell kicked him and he didn't move anymore ... I wet my pants.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, June 7, 1998, Byrd's mutilated body was found.
Byrd, 49, had been chained by the ankles and dragged more than two
miles before his head slammed into a concrete culvert, decapitating
him.
</P>
<P>
   Placing the blame on his two buddies is in keeping with Berry's
first statements to police, but the television interview offers
more detail. Jasper prosecutor Guy James Gray said some of those
details conflict with Berry's earlier statements. He declined to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have to contend with the fact that he has given
varying versions of his story,'' Gray said. ``The more times a
defendant talks, the more opportunity to catch him if he's not
telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's blood was found on Berry's shirt, pants and one of his
boots. Berry contends the blood got there when Byrd brushed against
him while scuffling with King and Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sister, Mary Verrett of Houston, called Tuesday's
interview ``abominable'' and said the defendants are ``pathological
liars out to save their own skin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the truth,'' she said. ``Who started the truck, I don't
know. But all three of them were involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week at his trial in Bryan, Texas, Brewer, a 32-year-old
white supremacist, was convicted of capital murder and sentenced to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer testified for more than four hours, crying and blaming
Berry, who he said slashed Byrd's throat and then chained him to
the pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's former prison buddy and fellow white supremacist, King,
24, was convicted of capital murder and sentenced to death in
February. He did not testify.
</P>
<P>
   Berry is to be tried late next month in his hometown of Jasper
and intends to testify.
</P>
<P>
   In his interview with Rather, Berry said he and his friends were
planning to drink beer and cruise the backroads of Jasper County
when they saw Byrd walking home from a party. Berry offered him a
ride and then drove to a rural logging road in the woods east of
town.
</P>
<P>
   Before he knew what was happening, he said, King and Brewer had
jumped out and were pulling Byrd from the cab of the pickup. King
was shouting that he was going to kill the man, Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in between Bill and him. And I told Bill ... you know,
`Stop.' And he said `Back off. The same thing can happen to
(you.)'''
</P>
<P>
   He said King and Brewer were laughing and joking as they beat
and kicked Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw them chain him up. I didn't ... I don't know how
he was chained or where he was chained,'' Berry said. ``And they
started dragging him down that dirt road.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry said he was seated in the cab of the truck between King,
who was driving, and Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell had looked back one time and started laughing and
said, `Look, he's rolling,' or `He's bouncing around all over the
place,''' Berry said. ``They were having fun. They had him. They
were acting like they were having just a good old time.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he said, Brewer looked back and said that Byrd had
come undone. King stopped the pickup, and he and Brewer got out and
chained Byrd again and continued dragging him, Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I'd been able to help him,'' Berry said. ``I wish I
wouldn't have chickened out. I think I let a lot of people down.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry's attorney, Joseph C. ``Lum'' Hawthorn of Beaumont, said
Tuesday that Berry agreed to the interview in hopes of improving
his image before his trial starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn has been characterized as a racist and as a cruel and
violent person. None of those things are true,'' Hawthorn said.
``This was a good opportunity to reply to those accusations. He
wants to make sure the public understands that he is not like the
other two.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said Berry, who was interviewed Sept. 18 at the Jasper
County Jail, spent two hours with Rather and answered every
question he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Berry's story could be reconciled with Brewer's
testimony, Hawthorn said, ``I don't think the two can be
reconciled. I think Brewer was lying.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
