<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9419 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-2000-HNS &LR;      09-28 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY PROPOSES OPENING FEDERAL EMPLOYEE HEALTH PLAN TO ALL
AMERICANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Seeking to sharpen the few policy differences in
the Democratic presidential race, former Sen. Bill Bradley proposed
Tuesday to open the federal employee health plan to all Americans
so that children can be guaranteed medical care and adults
encouraged to seek coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Laying out a key plank in his bid against Vice President Al
Gore, Bradley suggested making the Federal Employee Health Benefit
Plan the nation's medical insurer of last resort. If adopted, the
proposal could quickly balloon an enterprise that currently covers
9 million Americans _ including members of Congress _ through 400
private insurance plans and make it the standard by which most
medical benefit programs are judged, designed and priced.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's plan would require parents to enroll an infant in a
health care plan, perhaps at the same time they apply for a birth
certificate, and maintain coverage until age 19. The proposal
spells out no enforcement mechanism, and Bradley said he would
``trust in the basic goodness'' of Americans. An aide said: ``No
one's going to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Adults would not be required to enroll in a health plan, but
Bradley's proposal is designed to move toward almost total coverage
without the political firestorm that met President Clinton's
attempt at universal health insurance early in his term. Bradley
said that his proposal, combined with existing plans, would result
in health care coverage for 95 percent of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he was putting forward the plan because ``we can't
afford not to provide health care to our children.'' Uninsured
adults, he said, should be allowed to ``enroll in one of the many
private plans now available to only members of Congress and other
federal employees.''
</P>
<P>
   With its implication of breaking into an exclusive realm of
politicians and bureaucrats, the comment was a sure-fire applause
line in Bradley's speech at Los Angeles Valley College. The address
was delivered as polls show Bradley gaining on Gore, especially in
early voting New Hampshire, where the two former Senate colleagues
are in a statistical dead heat. Both candidates are from the broad
center-left of their party and seem to have few substantive
differences on major government policies.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's health-care proposal differs from Gore's in that it
would provide explicit access to the federal employee's plan. Three
weeks ago, Gore made a broad pledge, with few details, to ensure
health-care coverage for all children by 2005, the year the next
presidential term ends. That's also when Bradley aides said their
candidate's plan was intended to be fully effective.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, speaking to reporters after his speech, renewed his
charge that Gore relied on ``incrementalism'' in approaching major
issues such as health care and recalled his own campaign-opening
pledge to seek to make government do ``a few big things well'' and
comprehensively.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former basketball star who represented New Jersey in
the Senate for 18 years, said that Gore's health care proposal ``is
definitely timid when compared to what we have proposed.'' In his
formal remarks, Bradley, alluding to Gore's approach, said, ``a
campaign proposal without a price tag is just another politician's
promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley predicted his proposal would cost $50 million-$65
million in its first year. He said he the new plan would be funded
from non-Social Security federal budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside questions about whether new taxes would be
required to finance the program if there were an economic downturn,
saying: ``We're in a surplus world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign charged that Bradley's plan would leave ``other
critical programs unfunded'' and provided ``not one dime'' for
ensuring the future of Medicare. Bradley said that because the
Medicare system is secure through 2018 and health care is changing
so quickly he proposed waiting a year or two before proceeding with
alterations in the major national health plan for the elderly. He
said he was unlikely to propose reforms to the program during his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides also said that by opening the federal employee plan,
Bradley's proposal could cause employers to drop current coverage.
Bradley said he did not agree with the vice president's point but
would have to review whether employers should be prohibited from or
penalized for cutting off current plans and attempting to herd
workers into the newly available federal program.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's plan also envisions a phase-out of many Medicaid
features, as the poor currently in the program would, in effect, be
transferred to the federal employees' plan. In exchange, states
would have to take over responsibility for providing institutional
long-term care for the poor, including nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley aides said states now pay $56 billion annually as their
share of Medicaid payments and that the long-term care requirement
would cost only $38 billion, an estimated $18 billion in savings.
Like many parts of the Bradley proposal, cost estimates were far
from exact and based only on a one-year outlay, without figuring
for long-term escalating costs.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley argued that the future does not necessarily hold
increased outlays for medical care, claiming instead, ``We're just
at the beginning of revolutionary cost savings.''
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Bradley said, his proposal should be seen as ``a
starting point, not a final plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The former senator proposed unlimited federal tax deductibility
of health care premiums paid by individuals and promised to retain
the current provision that employer contributions to health
insurance are treated as non-taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who in Congress argued for simplifying the federal tax
code, said special treatment of health care premiums was merited
because ``this is a big and important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Bradley's plan, children could be added to parents'
existing coverage, most likely an employer's plan, or enter the
federal employees' plan. The federal government would fully pay the
health care cost of families living in poverty, currently a family
of four with no more than $16,400 in annual income. Partial
subsidies would be available, on a sliding scale, for more
prosperous families, up to a family of four with an annual income
of almost $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidies would come through federal income tax rebates
available before the premium was due.
</P>
<P>
   Although adults would not be required to secure coverage,
Americans at least 20-64 years old could buy into the federal
employee plan at existing group rates. All poor would be covered
through the tax subsidy program, and adults in families of four
with annual income up to $32,800 would be partially subsidized.
</P>
<P>
   Plans in the government program would be required to offer
coverage regardless of a person's existing medical problems.
Bradley has demonstrated he knows the appeal of health care as a
national issue, especially when couched in terms of breaking down
walls of privilege _ such as his proposal to open a system now
available to members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bradley returned to a similar point he has made
earlier in his campaign. He said it was wrong that ``kings and
dictators can come to the country to get the best medical care in
the world while Americans two blocks away may not be able to afford
any care at all. The time has come to right these wrongs in our
health care system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
