<HEADER>
A9421 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-KIDCRAFTS-FALL-TEX     09-28 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDCRAFTS-FALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KID CRAFTS FOR THE FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, we know. Halloween is still a month away, but it's not too
early to get into the autumn spirit with some family craft
activities for the weekends ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Here are three of our favorites: one for the very young, one
appropriate for more steady hands, and one that even older kids
will find cool.
</P>
<P>
   Start now and enjoy them through October.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. Leaf rubbings
</P>
<P>
   Appropriate for: preschoolers
</P>
<P>
   You'll need: leaves, paper, chalk or pencil
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Leaf rubbings are a good way to introduce small children to
celebrating fall _ and you can turn the project into a fun outing,
if you want to head to a park to gather leaves. Find a number of
fall leaves, keeping an eye out for those with lots of veining or
texture. Put the leaves on a flat surface, place paper over them,
and rub over them with chalk or a pencil. Make room on the
refrigerator for your autumn art.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   2. Halloween luminarias
</P>
<P>
   Appropriate for: ages 6-8
</P>
<P>
   You'll need: paper bags, scissors, sand or gravel, votive
candles and holders
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kids will enjoy making luminarias to decorate the front porch or
walkway for a spooky Halloween look.
</P>
<P>
   Draw simple geometric patterns on paper lunch bags or white
paper bags. Cut along the borders of the designs. (Kids with more
advanced skills can create stencils of jack-o'-lanterns, witches
and ghosts.) Fill the bags with enough sand or gravel to weigh them
down. Put a votive candle (in a small holder) into the sand, and
set the luminarias out in the yard. Be careful _ remember the fire
risk. Be sure the paper bag is away from the candle, and never
leave the candle burning unattended. Or, to help reduce the risk,
buy bags treated to make them fire-resistant. You can find these in
the seasonal department at craft or home stores; we found them at
Garden Ridge stores.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   3. Flying ghosts
</P>
<P>
   Appropriate for: age 8 and older
</P>
<P>
   You'll need: 15-inch square of fine mesh screen (one for each
ghost), spray mount adhesive, 17-inch square of white tissue paper
for each ghost, glue, a sewing needle, clear monofilament, and
sequins, buttons, wiggle eyes or other decorations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   We found these flying ghosts in ``Halloween Treats,'' a craft
and recipe book by Donata Maggipinto.
</P>
<P>
   To make them, apply spray adhesive to a fine mesh screen, then
place a sheet of tissue paper on top and smooth it down.
</P>
<P>
   To make the ghost's head, make a fist, place the screen over it
and mold it to your hand. Then mold the screen to form the rest of
the ghost _ arms and body. Decorate your ghost with sequins or
buttons, placing eyes on it if you wish.
</P>
<P>
   To hang your ghost: Thread monofilament through a needle, then
bring the needle up through the head from the body of the ghost.
When you hang it from the ceiling or a doorway, the monofilament
will disappear and the ghost will seem to float.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
