<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9422 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-INDIAN-MUSEUM-ART-NYT     09-28 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-MUSEUM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITHSONIAN BEGINS CONSTRUCTION OF AMERICAN INDIAN MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT6 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A century after the tribal devastation of the
Indian wars, a place of honor on the capital Mall was finally
extended to the nation's Native Americans on Tuesday as
construction began on a museum that Indian leaders vowed would
celebrate their history of indomitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we return to a native place now known as Washington,''
said W. Richard West, a Cheyenne who is director of the new
National Museum of the American Indian, presiding at a ceremony
driven by exuberant drumbeats but sober reflection, too, at the
Indians' near annihilation in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still here,'' Chief Billy Redwing Tayac of the
Piscataway tribe exulted in his blessing, drawing whoops as he cast
sacred burial ground soil on the museum site at the foot of Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of tribal members and chiefs in attendance
savoring ancient ritual and hopeful speeches, the museum, scheduled
to open in 2002, was hailed as a long overdue antidote to centuries
of racist stereotyping, broken land treaties and federal
``civilization regulations'' that failed to rein in rich tribal
cultures with a policy of assimilation.
</P>
<P>
   The $110 million museum of cliff-like Kasota limestone _ the
Smithsonian Institution's 10th and final showplace museum on the
Mall _ will be a culturally busy five-story center dedicated to the
story of more than 1,000 Native American communities in the Western
Hemisphere, from the Arctic Circle to Tierra del Fuego, from
Indians' lethal struggles of the past to those of the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a story that the museum has to tell,'' Suzan Shown
Harjo, an Indian leader and scholar, insisted at a spirited seminar
on Monday night of Indian leaders envisioning a place that
participants said should be part Louvre, part Holocaust Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Under the congressional authorization, the federal government is
financing two-thirds of the cost and the museum the other third _ a
$36.7 million fund that has already been raised by 250,000 private
and corporate donors, Smithsonian officials said. Part of the
tribal visitors' pride was rooted in the fact that the largest
single donation _ $10 million _ was made by the Mashantucket Pequot
nation of Connecticut, which has become the model for a renaissance
by tribes using their sovereignty to create gambling casinos across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   If the speeches of three days of celebration are any guide, the
museum, which will be run by a 25-member board, including 16
American Indians, will not only celebrate and display continuing
tribal cultures but work to set the record straight. How possible
disputes among historians might be settled ``remains to be seen,''
said Thomas W. Sweeney, a museum spokesman. He noted that the
museum was dedicated to presentations ``from the native
perspective'' and that others were free to disagree.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's goal will be ``to show and tell the world who and
what we really are and to use our own voices in the telling,''
West, the museum director, emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they underlined such continuing problems as poverty and
teen-age suicide, the Indian leaders hailed gradual recovery and
growth and the museum's potential to be ``a cleansing and a
blessing at the same time,'' in the words of Ines Hernandez-Avila,
an Indian cultural expert at the University of California at Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In their celebration, visiting chiefs and scholars honored the
tribes' very survival, from 250,000 native Americans a century ago
_ a 95 percent withering from their pre-Colonial heyday _ to more
than two million now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great, Indians are having more babies!'' Ms. Harjo told the
seminar. ``We native people in this room and all over are here
because many white men couldn't kill all our ancestors,'' she
added, exemplifying the militant pride that energized the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at history, Kevin Gover, head of the Federal Bureau
of Indian Affairs, a Pawnee and a law professor at Yale, told the
seminar, ``The most powerful and richest nation in the world
literally turned its guns on us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see out there right now,'' Gover added, is the legacy
of ``a great deal of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the very greatest enemy the tribes have at this
point,'' he said in celebrating the ``survival culture'' that the
new museum is to explain to the nation at large. At least six
million visitors a year are anticipated at the museum, which is
being built just east of the National Air and Space Museum, the
city's busiest, with eight million tourists annually.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal leaders emphasized their long struggle ``to get our dead
relatives out of museums'' of the past that had confiscated sacred
relics and celebrated only the supposed ``end-of-the-trail'' defeat
of the tribes, as one of them put it.
</P>
<P>
   By way of contrast, tribal members focused on the priceless
artifacts to be displayed in the National Museum's centerpiece
collection, the ``magnificent obsession'' of George Gustav Heye,
the turn-of-the-century collector who searched out art and homespun
artifacts from the tribes, West noted, with the passion of a
``boxcar collector.'' Heye's old Indian museum at Broadway and
155th Street in Manhattan, overlooked across the years, is a
seedbed for the new National Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian has had the George Gustav Heye Center open to
the public in lower Manhattan for the past five years. This will
continue along with the new museum and a cultural resources center
that the Smithsonian has opened in Suitland, Md., six miles from
Washington, where much of the Heye collection of more than 800,000
artifacts is being transferred from storage in New York to be
available for Indian scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian attributed the concept for the museum, which
will have a 120-foot-high copper dome and cantilevered design, to
GBQC Architects of Philadelphia in association with Douglas
Cardinal, a noted Canadian architect of Blackfoot ancestry.
Cardinal had been dismissed as the original architect in 1998
because of delays and contractual disputes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
