<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-HMO-680&AMP;ADD-NY     09-28 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HMO-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO RULE ON PATIENT'S RIGHT TO SUE HMO OVER COST-CONTROL
EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa., Ga.)   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday assigned itself an
important role in the debate over managed health care, accepting a
case on whether an Illinois health maintenance organization
breached a legal duty to a patient whose appendix burst during an
eight-day wait for a test to diagnose her abdominal pain.
</P>
<P>
   The question in the case is whether the HMO's financial
structure, under which doctors' compensation depended in part on
their success in holding down costs, meant that its patients' best
interests did not come first, as required under a federal appeals
court's interpretation of the federal law governing
employer-sponsored health plans.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of health-care industry and other business groups
urged the court to review the August 1998 ruling by a panel of the
7th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals. The decision has broad
implications for managed care generally, because cost-containment
strategies that may limit a patient's options are the essence of
this approach to health care. The 2-1 ruling reinstated, but did
not resolve, a lawsuit that has yet to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under this decision, any cost-savings achieved by managed care
would be lost,'' lawyers for the HMO, Health Alliance Medical Plans
of Urbana, Ill., told the justices. The statement echoed one made
by a judge on the appeals court, Frank Easterbrook, in arguing
unsuccessfully on behalf of four of the court's 12 judges that the
case should get a new hearing by the full court. Under the panel's
ruling, ``the principal organizational forms through which medical
care is delivered today are unlawful,'' Easterbrook wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th Circuit based its ruling on a 1974 federal law, the
Employee Retirement Income Security Act, which governs employee
benefits such as pensions and medical care. The law, known as
ERISA, operates as a barrier to many lawsuits that would otherwise
proceed in state court, leading to the focus of the current debate,
both in Congress and in the states, on expanding patients' rights
to sue. Some 160 million people receive medical coverage through
their employment.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the 7th Circuit used ERISA not as a
shield for health care providers but as a sword for aggrieved
patients. The court said that health maintenance organizations and
their doctors are bound by a duty under one of ERISA'S provisions
to act as fiduciaries, that is, to act ``solely in the interest of
the participants and beneficiaries'' of an employer-provided
medical plan. By rewarding doctors for holding down costs, the
court said, the HMO may have placed doctors' interests in conflict
with the interests of their patients.
</P>
<P>
   While the precise holding of the 7th Circuit was unusual, the
decision was part of a trend in which courts have been finding ways
around obstacles to patients in employer-sponsored health plans
receiving redress for their injuries. An appeal by a Pennsylvania
HMO from a ruling by the Pennsylvania Supreme Court is awaiting
action by the justices.
</P>
<P>
   The court will not hear the Illinois case, Pegram vs. Herdrich,
No. 98-1949, until January, and will probably not decide it until
well into next spring. Next week, meanwhile, the House of
Representatives is to take up several competing measures that would
expand patients' rights to varying degrees. The Senate passed a
Republican-sponsored bill earlier this year, which President
Clinton vowed to veto as offering no more than ``toothless,
half-hearted protections.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is unusual for the court to inject itself into the
midst of an active legislative debate, the justices were evidently
persuaded that the 7th Circuit's approach is potentially of such
dimension that it should not be left to stand unreviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision by the court to accept the case will not
alter the debate in Congress, top Democratic and Republican aides
said. ``If anything, this will provide added impetus on this
issue,'' said John Stone, a spokesman for Rep. Charlie Norwood,
R-Ga., a sponsor of bipartisan legislation that would expand
patients' right to sue health care providers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his majority opinion for the 7th Circuit panel, Judge John
Coffey noted that ``a response to the crisis in market-based care
has come to roost in Washington, D.C.,'' and spoke in scathing
terms of ``the deleterious effects of managed care on the health
care industry.'' The majority opinion was joined by Judge
Harlington Wood. In a dissenting opinion, Judge Joel Flaum said
that although he shared the majority's concerns, judges should not
``preempt legislative and regulatory efforts in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff in this case, Cynthia Herdrich, received her
medical care through the Urbana HMO, which operates as the Carle
Clinic, under her husband's health care plan. In March 1991, she
complained of abdominal pain and was examined by one of the
clinic's doctors, Lori Pegram. Dr. Pegram found that Mrs.
Herdrich's appendix was inflamed, but told her she would have to
wait eight days for an ultrasound examination before the procedure
could be performed by the HMO staff. Mrs. Herdrich's appendix burst
while she was waiting for her appointment, leading to peritonitis
and a more complicated and dangerous medical situation than a
simple removal of her appendix.
</P>
<P>
   She sued and won $35,000 in compensatory damages under Illinois
medical malpractice law. But a U.S. District Court dismissed the
portion of her suit that was based on ERISA and that claimed that
the HMO had breached its fiduciary duty. It was this aspect of the
suit that the 7th Circuit reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   A group of health-care industry trade associations, along with
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, filed a brief urging the Supreme
Court to take the case. The brief said the 7th Circuit majority had
displayed an ``anti-managed bias'' that ``should not be allowed to
override the carefully considered decision of the legislative and
executive branches to promote the prudent and effective management
of health plans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
