<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HUFFY29-COX     09-28 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUFFY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some left in a huff as bike company rides off into sunset
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Huffy Corp.'s decision to close the last of its
American bicycle and parts manufacturing plants has officials in
the two affected cities asking themselves, ``What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Don Graber, Huffy's top executive, said it's
time to focus on the future rather than Huffy's announcement Monday
that it would close its Farmington, Mo., bike plant and a year-old
Southaven, Miss., bike parts plant. The decision will cost 600
people their jobs and Huffy bikes will be made by foreign suppliers
not owned by the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to close the bicycle plants ... was an agonizing,
difficult decision. But basically we had no alternative,'' said
Graber, blaming competition from Chinese manufacturers who make and
sell bikes at a lower price than Huffy.
</P>
<P>
   He said the decision was made on the recommendation of Huffy
Bicycle Co. managers and closure was the only alternative presented
to Graber and the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, when we closed (the) Celina (bike plant) over a
year ago we had hoped to maintain a U.S. manufacturing base,'' said
Graber, Huffy's chairman, president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But for Farmington Mayor Kevin Engler and Southaven City
Administrator Chris Wilson the high hopes they had when Huffy came
to their communities have been dashed. Their focus now switches to
finding new tenants in the buildings leased by Huffy and in helping
find jobs for 600 people who earned on average $12 hourly in wages
and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed in the closing,'' said Engler. ``I realize
that Huffy is attributing it to a lot of overseas imports and
that's probably true. At the same time there has to be some
mismanagement.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as early summer Huffy officials in Farmington talked
about adding lines to produce more bikes, he said. He's stunned the
company would have moved some of Farmington's parts production to
Southaven, spent money equipping that plant, only to close it less
than a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm on the board, wouldn't I be saying, 'Who's steering
this ship?' `` Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   Graber denied Huffy's problems are because of mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our strongest management teams is in the bicycle
business. The issue with bicycles is not a leadership issue or a
people issue,'' Graber said.
</P>
<P>
   The Southaven plant, which forms and shapes forks, frames and
handlebars for the Farmington plant, was touted as a $10 million
investment at the time it was announced in June 1998. Tom
Frederick, chief financial officer, said that number is probably
somewhat inflated but he did not know the exact investment. He said
the Farmington plant, opened in 1994, cost $24 million. Huffy will
take a pre-tax cost for plant closures and other related charges of
about $42.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Graber also elaborated on the company's decision to hire
investment banker PaineWebber to determine over the next 45 to 60
days if the company should be merged, sold, spun off or involved in
joint ventures with other companies. The goal is to improve
shareholder return on their investment in Huffy. Huffy (NYSE:HUF)
stock values dropped 49 percent between January and Monday, when
stock prices hit a 52-week low of 8 1/2. On Tuesday, prices
recovered slightly to close at 9 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the marketplace is still digesting the announcement,''
Graber said. ``Obviously a second restructuring in 16 months takes
time for the market to digest.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hulsey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
