<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ACC-SALARIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACC salaries: Friedgen tops in assistant pay
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech offensive coordinator Ralph Friedgen
isn't a head coach, but he's paid like one.
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen is earning $200,000 this season, the same as head coach
George O'Leary and Virginia head coach George Welsh, and more than
the head coaches at four other ACC schools, according to a
leaguewide salary survey by The Atlanta Journal- Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Among the seven schools responding to the survey, the only head
coach making more than Friedgen is Florida State's Bobby Bowden at
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The salaries of all coaches at state-funded universities were
obtained through requests made to the schools and from state
Freedom of Information Act requests. Duke and Wake Forest, as
private universities, are not subject to state open-record laws,
and they refused requests for their coaches' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen is the highest-paid assistant. His salary is more than
$63,000 higher than that of the next-highest paid next-highest-paid
assistant, FSU defensive coordinator Mickey Andrews ($136,985).
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Friedgen earned $82,500. He got the increase of 142.4
percent because of his years as an assistant to former Tech coach
Bobby Ross with the San Diego Chargers and the desire of Tech to
keep him on its staff.
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen was an assistant at Tech 1987-91, then followed Ross to
San Diego when Ross went there after the '91 season. When Ross left
the Chargers in 1997,
</P>
<P>
   his staff went as well, but not without an attractive severance
package. The bulk of Friedgen's income the past two years was from
the Chargers, and his Tech salary of $82,500 was part of the deal
to get him to return to the school. This year is the first the
Jackets have had to assume Friedgen's entire package.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to pay Ralph that (much) to get him to leave the pros
and come here,'' O'Leary said. ``That's about what a pro assistant
makes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to be competitive,'' athletics director
Dave Braine said. ``Is there a higher-paid assistant in the country
than Ralph? I don't think so. But I'll say that that's money well
spent. He's the best offensive coordinator in the nation, and when
you put George and Ralph and (defensive coordinator) Ted Roof
together, you've got the nucleus for a great staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Braine said he has a survey done by NCAA Division I athletics
directors and knows what every assistant makes. ``We keep up with
it,'' he said. ``I want our coaches to stay, and I want us to be
competitive in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech's staff is second to Florida State's in base compensation,
$1,830,591 to $1,044,077. Except for O'Leary and Friedgen, the Tech
staff was given a 4 percent raise this year. Faculty and
non-faculty employees at Tech also got a 4 percent raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our league is a little low on coaches' salaries,''
O'Leary said. ``I compare our staff's salaries to Georgia instead
of the other ACC teams. You have to look at the area you live in,
how much it costs to go out and eat, how much entertainment costs.
I want to make sure our coaches earn enough with the work and hours
they put in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Donnan and his staff at Georgia make $1,057,785 this year.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's coaches work an average of 55 hours Sunday through
Thursday, travel on Friday and work the game Saturday. ``If you
break it down by the hour,'' O'Leary said, ``they don't get paid
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
