<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9446 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRY-3RDTAK     09-28 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRY-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: ``an octopus.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Word of the FBI's investigation began to spread. In October
1998, John Moscow, a prosecutor with the district attorney's
office, traveled to London to meet with the National Crime Squad.
Moscow, also a veteran of the failed BCCI prosecution _ and also
viewed dimly by the bureau, where he is thought of as a conspiracy
theorist _ heard a lot in London about apparent money-laundering at
the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow relayed what he had learned to Jonathan Winer, a
specialist in international crime at the State Department. Winer,
an ally of Morgenthau's office from the BCCI days, was the first to
alert the administration to the troubling dimensions of the Bank of
New York matter, information that Winer believed should have helped
inform foreign and economic policy assessments of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting London himself in March this year, Winer returned
to the United States with a sheaf of documents and serious qualms
about the fact that the FBI had not notified the White House or any
national security specialists about the scale of the problem at the
Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   So Winer rang a few alarms.
</P>
<P>
   In March, he gave copies of his documents to National Security
Council officials and then notified the White House, the CIA and
the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The news was not well received at the FBI, where investigators
discovered to their dismay that Winer was circulating information
the bureau had passed on in confidence to British investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Other federal agencies found out about the investigation
piecemeal. The Treasury Department, which has played the leading
role in formulating U.S. economic policy toward Russia, did not
learn about the investigation until April 1999, and its knowledge
came from the Federal Reserve in New York. Even the FBI's boss,
Attorney General Janet Reno, had not received a briefing on the
investigation _ and did not until August, after the investigation
was reported in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Then the real fighting began.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau's office complained that the FBI never took the Bank
of New York matter seriously enough until it was highlighted in the
media. While the British were told that an FBI agent in New York,
Steve Chapman, was heading a task force examining the bank's
operations, the British felt Chapman was the only agent involved.
They, according to American investigators familiar with their
viewpoint, dismissed Chapman's effort as ``Task Force Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to the FBI retort that the only reason the
investigation appeared so thinly staffed to the British is because
they were not aware of its entire scope. Moreover, these people
say, Morgenthau is a media hound who never devoted serious
resources to his own investigation of Benex until it burst into the
public spotlight. These people said that if Morgenthau ever had
significant information to share about Benex or the Bank of New
York, the FBI would have welcomed it.
</P>
<P>
   A recent series of meetings was convened at the U.S. Attorney's
Office in Manhattan that, in the eyes of the FBI, was meant to seek
various law enforcement agencies' cooperation in the Bank of New
York investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan District Attorney's Office had a different take on
the meetings. Its investigators said they were told ``to get out of
the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0320 </DOCNO>
