<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA GIVES NATO $100-BILLION DAMAGE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The NATO bombing campaign last spring caused
$100-billion worth of damages in Yugoslavia, the foreign minister
in Belgrade said on Tuesday. He demanded that NATO pay the costs.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, Zivadin Jovanovic, who is at the U.N. General
Assembly, told reporters: ``Yugoslavia claims the right of full
compensation of war damages resulting from the NATO aggression,
which amount to $100 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   The figure runs considerably higher than the $30-50 billion that
some European officials have estimated that it would cost to repair
the damage in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Jovanovic said he had met ministers from more than 50 countries,
soliciting support for the contention that Yugoslavia was the
victim, not the instigator, of the Kosovo confrontation. Jovanovic
said at a news conference that he had encountered support and
understanding from many United Nations members. He mentioned solely
Russia, which was sympathetic to the Serbian-led government.
</P>
<P>
   NATO began its air strikes on March 24, after the failure of
peace negotiations for Kosovo province. Serbian troops and
paramilitary units had started to force most Kosovo Albanians, who
made up 90 percent of the province, to flee, and stepped up the
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Many were reported killed, and thousands of houses were
destroyed. NATO reported that it dropped 23,000 bombs without
losing a single pilot in the 78-day operation.
</P>
<P>
   Jovanovic said there had been an effort to remove Serbs from
Kosovo after the bombing and after NATO forces and U.N. workers had
moved in. He said that 250,000 Serbs had been expelled and that
more than 400 Serbian civilians had been killed, 600 injured and
500 kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   He also said more than 50,000 houses and apartments occupied by
Serbs had been destroyed, broken into or occupied illegally. About
200,000 people from Albania and Macedonia, Jovanovic added, have
moved into Kosovo illegally and should be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia is caring for 100,000 refugees and others displaced
from Kosovo, and it is hampered by economic sanctions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His figures are difficult to verify, but they are smaller than
the estimated human cost from the expulsion of the Kosovo
Albanians, which Jovanovic did not mention. Hundreds of thousands
of Albanians were pushed out of Kosovo, aid workers have said,
before being allowed to return under NATO protection.
</P>
<P>
   Jovanovic's statements were dismissed by State Department
spokesman James Rubin. ``The Milosevic regime has no one to blame
but itself for the NATO bombing campaign, which they provoked
through their ethnic cleansing,'' Rubin said, referring to
President Slobodan Milosevic. ``It's time for Yugoslavia to
recognize reality. So long as there's an indicted war criminal at
the helm, their cries will fall on deaf ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Jovanovic also expressed unhappiness with how a Security Council
resolution on Kosovo, approved when the war halted June 10, has
been carried out. It placed the province under ``an international
civil presence'' and set up a framework for an interim
administration that he said was biased against Serbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9450 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-TREASURY-INDICT-BO     09-28 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-INDICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7 INDICTED IN THEFT OF $9.5M FROM TREASURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Seven people were indicted Tuesday in the largest theft
of public money in state history, as the widening criminal probe
into the state Treasury snared former Treasurer Joseph D. Malone's
campaign fund-raiser and former family lawyer, Richard C. Arrighi.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly said his investigation into
the theft of more than $9.5 million is not over, and he would not
discuss whether Malone had knowledge or shared any responsibility
for the criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not in our practice to rule people in or rule people
out,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrighi, 40, of Norwood, a friend of Malone's who won bond
contracts from the Treasury while Malone was in office, was charged
with concealing $1.6 million stolen from the Treasury in a Waltham
real estate trust.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Arrighi, three former Treasury workers, two
businessmen, and another lawyer were indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said most of the money was stolen through schemes
involving false claims made to the state's Unpaid Check Fund, where
checks that have not been cashed were kept with little monitoring
or record-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   The thefts also involved two Treasury workers _ former Deputy
Treasurer Robert Foley and former director of cash management Scot
Butcher _ who hauled $300,000 to $400,000 in ``bags of cash'' out
of the old state employees bank at the Ashburton Place office
buildling, Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, 39, of Norwood, received most of that stolen cash,
according to Reilly's office.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who rode into office in 1990 as a reformer, eventually
closed the bank, though it is not clear whether he knew of the lax
controls there.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, the alleged mastermind behind the thefts, faces a
possible life sentence for his involvement in several schemes and
is under pressure to tell all to investigators, in exchange for
drastically reduced prison time, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The others indicted are: Ronald Borino, 44, a Boston lawyer from
Bedford; Treasury supervisor John ``Trixie'' Trischitta, 47, of
Stoneham; and heir finders Martin Robbins, 51, of Peabody and
Thomas Ciliberto Jr., 51, of Woonsocket, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   All are expected to be arraigned within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictments, the thefts began in 1992 when
Foley and Trischitta, who together oversaw the Unpaid Check Fund,
funneled $1.6 million from the account to a struggling Waltham
condominium project. Reilly said Arrighi and Borino knew about the
money laundering, and helped conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   That transaction touched off years of embezzlement, increasingly
elaborate schemes, and an overzealous attempt at stealing $6.5
million in one transaction from the Unpaid Check Fund, an act that
caught the attention of a BankBoston employee who tipped off the
attorney general's office last February.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, with minimal controls, was fertile ground for fraud,
Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Reilly, Trischitta and Foley allegedly stole $9
million from the account over seven years. They also allegedly
received kickbacks from outsiders known as ``heir finders,'' who
retrieve uncashed checks for those owed the money.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta and Foley would alert a select group of heir finders
to large uncashed checks, including such things as bond payments,
Reilly said. Heir finders would typically receive a cut of the
check from the rightful owners.
</P>
<P>
   But on Nov. 6, 1998, Trischitta directed his high school buddy
from Malden, heir finder Martin Robbins, to a $6.5 million
unclaimed check with vague ownership. Robbins allegedly put in a
false claim for a fictitious agency, the Cambridge Economic
Development Corp. When Robbins took the check to BankBoston to be
cashed, a teller grew suspicious and notified Reilly's office.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta kept one-third of the money. Robbins allegedly kept
the rest, at least temporarily. The attorney general's office has
recovered those funds.
</P>
<P>
   An additional $3 million, bilked from the Treasury through other
schemes, has not been recovered and may never be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the public's money,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said Robbins and Trischitta carried out a kickback scheme
until last February, sharing tens of thousands of dollars in
heir-finder fees, at least 10 percent of the uncashed check.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992 to 1997, the indictments say, Foley and Trischitta
directed $4.2 million in unpaid checks to the Reinke Group, Inc., a
R.I.-based heir-finder company run by Ciliberto, who would get a
cut of the money when he found the rightful owners. Foley and
Trischitta, the insiders, each got 25 percent of Ciliberto's
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's office believes most of the $4.2 million went to
legitimate owners, except for $812,500, which Trischitta allegedly
split with Ciliberto.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Foley, Trischitta, and Arrighi all declined to
comment. Attorneys for Ciliberto and Robbins could not be reached
for comment. Malone also did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Newly elected Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien, who took over the
office in January, has hired KPMG Peat Marwick to audit the agency
in the wake of the scandal. Coincidentally, Butcher now works for
the firm.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said Butcher worked for a KPMG division unrelated to the
audit group that has been working at the Treasury. Butcher also
contributed to O'Brien's campaign. But she said the contributions
will be returned.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne R. Murphy, representing Butcher, said Butcher would be
exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These indictments against Mr. Butcher are the byproduct of a
politically charged investigation by an elected prosecutor. These
indictments are the result of sweetheart deals with corrupt public
officials who, to gain favor in their own prosecutions, have made
material misrepresentations to implicate an innocent man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
