<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-REBEL-ART-NYT &LR;      09-28 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-REBEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSE GUSMAO: THE FOE INDONESIA NOW RESPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Through the darkest years under Indonesian
rule, one man, known by the nom de guerre Xanana, held almost
magical promise for the East Timorese. Somewhere in the wooded
hills, he led a guerrilla band far outnumbered and outgunned by the
Indonesian army.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, pursued by assorted government ministers and people
who just wanted to get a look, he was at the United Nations to help
plan the future of independent East Timor. He was recognized by his
actual name, Jose Alexandre Gusmao. His newly acquired media aides
call him president. He gets a motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao, 53, has quickly become the leader whom most governments
want to take over East Timor when elections can be held. U.N.
officials and the Indonesian government, which tragically botched
the task of protecting the East Timorese who voted for independence
on Aug. 30, said they can hardly believe their luck.
</P>
<P>
   After years of fighting, they have found in Gusmao a born
conciliator. More than that, a diplomat said on Tuesday, ``He is a
moral beacon.''
</P>
<P>
   East Timor is not only a ruined territory, but also a divided
people. Many Timorese have become Indonesians to some degree,
through education, jobs or marriage. Others joined the
pro-Indonesian militias that ravaged East Timor. Some of Gusmao's
guerrillas have begun looking for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go back, because there is a vacuum,'' Gusmao said in
an interview Tuesday, adding that as soon as it is safe, he hopes
to make his Council of East Timorese Resistance an interim
administration.
</P>
<P>
   He does not plan to make it a political party, because its
membership is very broad. Resistance leaders are not very clear
about how much room there will be for party politics in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao is inviting all people who have fled the territory this
year but still think of themselves as Timorese citizens to come
back, he said, including Chinese business families, Indonesians
from other islands and pro-Indonesian East Timorese, even those who
took part in violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they feel that what they did was wrong, they can come and
they can explain to us,'' he said. ``But we will not go to them to
kiss their feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Jones, Asia director of Human Rights Watch and a leading
authority on Indonesia, said in an interview that Gusmao ``is
clearly both willing and able to work with a variety of groups.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got qualities that are really those of a statesman, in a
way that no other Timorese leader on the ground even approaches,''
Ms. Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao said he became Xanana in the 1970s when he wanted to be a
journalist after holding a variety of jobs from electrician to
civil service worker and was looking for a pseudonym under which to
write poetry and newspaper articles.
</P>
<P>
   The name went with him into the bush in 1976. He took over the
guerrilla movement by 1979, ``after all my senior leaders were
killed or captured or surrendered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao said the Indonesians seemed to be stunned when they had
to ask for help in controlling East Timor this month. They learned,
he said, that they were not the power they thought they were in
Asia, or in the Islamic world or the nonaligned movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had kept the arrogance they had since independence,'' he
said. ``They thought nobody could impose their will on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao _ who was not included in the Nobel Peace Prize awarded
in 1996 to Jose Ramos-Horta, an exiled spokesman for East Timorese
independence, and Bishop Carlos Ximenes Belo, the spiritual leader
of East Timor's largely Roman Catholic population _ is not an
unknown quantity to Indonesian officials, civilian or military.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982-83, the Timorese-born Indonesian governor of East Timor,
Mario Viegas Carrascalao, began secret exploratory peace talks with
the guerrilla leader. The negotiations broke down a year later when
16 army engineers were killed and the military reacted with a
savage revenge massacre.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Gusmao, whose wife and two children had fled to
Australia, was captured by Indonesian forces and sent to jail in
Jakarta. Like Nelson Mandela in South Africa, he became a leader
among political prisoners. In July 1997, when President Mandela
went to Indonesia and asked President Suharto to let him meet
Gusmao, the East Timorese leader was suddenly taken from prison to
the presidential guest house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people want to compare me to Mandela,'' he said, ``but
Mandela was my teacher. And meeting with him, in Jakarta, in front
of the nose of Suharto, was a very significant event for me. It was
a recognition of our struggle and of our rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year later, Suharto was forced to resign under
popular pressure. His successor, President B.J. Habibie, reduced
Gusmao's imprisonment to house arrest this February. By then Gusmao
was a factor in Indonesian thinking about what to do in East Timor,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``An important question is: What changed the situation?'' said
John Bresnan, an expert on Indonesia at the East Asian Institute of
Columbia University. ``Clearly part of it was Habibie. But he was
reacting to a letter from John Howard, prime minister of Australia,
who wrote to him in December suggesting a referendum on autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without consulting his Cabinet,'' Bresnan said, ``Habibie
decided to do that _ and to go a step further and say that if the
Timorese didn't accept autonomy, they would be cut loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, at a news conference, Gusmao was asked whether in
retrospect he wished that the independence referendum had not been
held, considering the violence it provoked. He dismissed the
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought for 23 years for this opportunity,'' he said. ``We
faced all sorts of challenges, dangers. We faced a huge amount of
suffering, a huge death toll, just to gain the right to
self-determination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
