<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-NAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET TO STICK WITH ITS OWN NAME IN MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ BankBoston is about to have its wings clipped.
</P>
<P>
   America's oldest bank will soon bid a reluctant farewell to its
proud name and lofty corporate logo, which depicts a blue-and-white
eagle in flight below a green ``1784,'' the year the patrician
institution was founded.
</P>
<P>
   In a bold and symbolic move, Fleet Financial Group has insisted
that the new company it is forming from its acquisition of
BankBoston bear the Fleet name, according to sources familiar with
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The choice speaks volumes about where the new financial giant is
heading _ and highlights the emotions, pride, and power struggles
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Once billed as a merger of equals, with two companies on equal
footing, Fleet's purchase of its crosstown rival has quickly become
a deal dominated by Fleet's hard-driving chief executive, Terrence
Murray.
</P>
<P>
   In the corridors of the two banks, the prickly issue of names is
more than quibbling over semantics. It is also a barometer of how
two banks with two contrasting cultures _ and two radically
different leaders _ will labor to get along.
</P>
<P>
   According to senior industry sources familiar with the matter,
BankBoston's chief executive, Charles K. Gifford, struggled in
recent weeks to convince Murray to preserve the word ``Boston'' in
the new company's core name. Gifford reportedly argued that
although the new bank has operations far beyond Boston, its local
image was too significant to abandon.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray, a factory worker's son from working-class
Woonsocket, R.I., and a rough-and-tumble deal maker with ambitions
far beyond Boston, was not swayed by Gifford's arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford, the socially prominent scion of a Rhode Island banking
family, will be the number two executive in the new company under
Murray until Murray retires before 2002. Then Gifford is scheduled
to take the reins.
</P>
<P>
   For BankBoston, a 215-year-old institution founded on the shores
of the Charles River to finance merchant trade with China, the name
change is painful. The bank set up offices in Buenos Aires in 1917
to finance the New England wool trade from the Argentine pampas,
and underwrote classic Hollywood films in the 1930s, including
``Casablanca.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Names are a very sensitive issue there because of the
heritage,'' said Gerard Cassidy, an industry analyst at Tucker
Cleary, in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   In a small nod to that heritage, certain parts of BankBoston
will retain their names after they are folded into Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Murray and Gifford have agreed that BankBoston's Latin American
franchise will retain the BankBoston name, since Fleet has no
overseas business and is unknown in the region. And the crown-jewel
investment bank, which comes from BankBoston, will still be called
Robertson Stephens (but will drop the BancBoston before it). The
decisions, industry sources said, had less to do with catering to
BankBoston's pride and more with marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the company uniting all of the new bank's various parts
will be known as Fleet. The retail and commercial banking
operations, which are spread out over New England and the Northeast
and which form the bulk of the company's operations, will bear the
Fleet name.
</P>
<P>
   And the newly hefty bank, which will be the nation's
eighth-largest, with $160 billion in assets, will retain Fleet's
logo of three white sails. Murray, a notorious cost-cutter whose
office is full of nautical-themed art, was reportedly loath to
spend any money tweaking signs and corporate stationery.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's spokesman, James Mahoney, declined to comment on the new
name, saying only that the bank was awaiting a nod from state
regulators for the merger and would announce a name next week. The
Federal Reserve approved the combination last month.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston officials also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford has gone to great lengths to try to portray the
Fleet-BankBoston combination as one of equals. But as the name
struggle suggests, Murray is forcing Gifford to bend on key
matters.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the new bank's executives come from Fleet. And
Gifford has been waging what one source said was a losing battle to
keep BankBoston's mammoth legal team employed. While it is no
surprise to industry observers that Murray retained the Fleet name,
the clash with Gifford over the issd portend major battles
in coming months, as the two men wrangle over what the new bank
should look like.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Gifford has done to his previous competitors what
Murray is doing to him. When the Bank of Boston bought BayBank in
1996, Gifford temporarily called the new company ``BayBank of
Boston,'' and famously exclaimed, ``I love that name!'' Gifford
soon renamed the new company BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are combining at record pace, arguing that they must pair
up to reduce costs or face acquisition by a rival. In convincing
his competitor to sell his bank last March, Murray played ``the
Boston card,'' and persuaded Gifford of the importance of
maintaining at least one big bank based in Boston. BankBoston,
facing a battered stock price and growing skepticism on Wall
Street, had come to be viewed as a takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   In an early gesture designed to cultivate good will, Murray
temporarily christened the new bank Fleet Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray no longer needs a Boston card.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new Fleet wants to convey itself as a major national
bank,'' said one senior executive familiar with the name change.
``Terry does not feel that the word `Boston' conveys that.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray has bought eight of New England's 10 largest banks over
the past 12 years, and transformed his tiny Providence-born bank
into a regional giant. Some industry observers speculate he's not
done yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Terry's still got one more major play in him,'' said
one Boston executive, speculating Murray, 60, would buy another
bank before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Gifford, 57, who ordered up a study from New
York consultants on what the new bank should be called. The study
found that while BankBoston had terrific name recognition inside
Route 128 and to the west, Fleet was tops everywhere else. The
study shortlisted three names: BankBoston, Fleet Boston, and Fleet
Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad commissioned that study,'' quipped one source. ``And now
it's going to cook his goose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
