r s BC-RAC-OAKTREE-LADN     09-28 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-OAKTREE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA ANITA TO OPEN TODAY AFTER FACELIFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Top thoroughbreds make their return to the
L.A. metropolitan area after two months' absence when the Oak Tree
Racing Association opens its 31st season today at Santa Anita.
They're even-money to recognize the old place.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita has undergone a facelift since its long winter meet
ended in April _ the first visible changes since Frank Stronach's
Magna International purchased the 65-year-old track from Meditrust
for $126 million in December 1998 and installed a new management
team.
</P>
<P>
   __ Twin elevator towers protrude into the once-spacious paddock
gardens, partially obscure views of the track's classic marquee and
force a rerouting of the horses' walk to the track.
</P>
<P>
   __ A 50-by-43-foot video screen dominates the infield, easing
race-watching for grandstand fans, although the structure blocks
views of about 40 yards of the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   __ The area between the grandstand and the rail is transformed
with the construction of terraced standing areas and the addition
of benches and landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   __ The entrance and parking lot off Huntington Drive are
redesigned.
</P>
<P>
   __ The winner's circle is enlarged _ although workmen had yet to
lay the sod 24 hours before today's 1 p.m. opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be surprised if we're still doing some painting
and landscaping (today),'' said Lonny Powell, the new Santa Anita
president and CEO brought in from smaller Turf Paradise in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The elevator towers will serve a 1,000-seat restaurant and bar
scheduled to open in December as the three-phase renovation
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's (Stronach) spent, what, $20 million? You can see
it,'' said Bob Baffert, who will seek his third straight Oak Tree
training championship after winning a record 21 races last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see somebody put money into it. The other people
(Meditrust) said they spent $10 million. They (only) painted the
barns!''
</P>
<P>
   Track executives hope the changes _ and the changes to come in
the next two years _ will attract some curious patrons to the
track. But they concede that nicer amenities won't expand business
unless the on-the-track competition improves.
</P>
<P>
   It's generally agreed that improving racing will require drawing
larger fields. The first two Oak Tree programs produced by new
racing secretary Mike Harlow are less than encouraging. Eighty-five
horses were entered in nine races today, down from 87 on opening
day in 1998; 57 were entered in eight races Thursday, down from 79
on day 2 in '98.
</P>
<P>
   Today's card features the fillies-and-mares turf sprint formerly
known as the Autumn Days Handicap but renamed the Sen. Ken Maddy
Handicap, honoring the racing-friendly former state senator from
Fresno. Trainer Richard Mandella looks strong with uncoupled Royal
Shyness (Corey Nakatani riding) and Desert Lady (Gary Stevens).
</P>
<P>
   The 31-day meet's most popular day could be Saturday, when
female turf champion Fiji (Jerry Bailey) is scheduled to make her
1999 debut in the Yellow Ribbon Stakes, the track guarantees a $1
million pick-six pool and the annual collectible-stein giveaway is
planned.
</P>
<P>
   While Baffert defends his Oak Tree training championship, Alex
Solis will go for his third riding title in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Valenzuela is named to ride four horses today, his first
action since being suspended indefinitely at the 1997 Oak Tree meet
following another in his decade-long series of drug-related
absences. Valenzuela, 36, was granted a ``conditional'' license
after agreeing to random drug and alcohol testing and continued
substance-abuse counseling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OAK TREE RACING AT A GLANCE &QL; 
__ When: Today through Nov. 8, every Wednesday through Sunday, plus
Mondays Oct. 11 and Nov. 8; first race 1 p.m. weekdays, 12:30 p.m.
weekends and Mondays. &QL; 
__ Where: Santa Anita Park in Arcadia; exit Baldwin Avenue south
from the Foothill Freeway (210). &QL; 
__ Major races: Yellow Ribbon Stakes for fillies and mares on turf,
Saturday; Oak Tree Turf Championship, Norfolk Stakes for
2-year-olds and Oak Leaf Stakes for 2-year-old fillies, Sunday;
Goodwood Handicap, Oct. 16; California Cup races for Cal-bred
horses, Oct. 30. &QL; 
__ Phone: (626) 446-8501 for results and scratches; (626)
574-7223. &QL; 
__ Web site: www.santaanita.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
