</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITING-EDUC-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST PUPILS CAN'T WRITE WELL, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only about one-quarter of American students can write at a
proficient level, exhibiting ``solid academic performance and
competency over challenging subject matter,'' according to a report
released on Tuesday by the National Assessment of Educational
Progress (NAEP).
</P>
<P>
   Just 1 percent of the nation's students scored in the
``advanced,'' range, while 16 percent of fourth and eighth graders,
and 22 percent of 12th graders, landed below ``basic,'' unable to
even show ``partial mastery of the knowledge and skills'' expected
at their grade level. ``The typical American student is not a
proficient writer,'' lamented Gary W. Phillips, acting commissioner
of the National Center for Education Statistics, as he unveiled the
latest report card. ``These findings are important because how well
students write at the end of the 20th century is an indicator of
how well they will be able to communicate and reason in the
beginning of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorized by Congress and administered by the federal
government's National Center for Education Statistics, NAEP has
been testing students in a range of subjects since 1969, and its
results are known as the nation's report cards. The writing
assessments given to 160,000 fourth, eighth and 12th graders in
1998 are the first of their kind and thus cannot be compared to
previous writing tests, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to test narrative, informative and persuasive writing
skills, the 50-minute tests included one or two writing exercises,
such as a letter to an imaginary friend (for fourth graders), a
pitch to a network executive for an educational television show
(eighth graders), or an essay on whether it is worthwhile to
register to vote. The achievement levels were set by the National
Assessment Governing Board, and judge everything from spelling and
grammar to illustrative detail and coherent argument.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of students _ 61 percent of 4th graders, 57 percent of
eighth graders and 56 percent of high-school seniors _ landed in
the ``basic'' range, scoring between about 115 to 175 out of 300,
depending on the grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``These standards are very high,'' Secretary of Education
Richard W. Riley said at a Washington news conference. ``I think
even some of us who do a lot of writing and speaking would find the
`advanced' level very challening.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some education analysts have long criticized NAEP for
setting its standards too high, Marilyn Whirry, an English teacher
from Manhattan Beach, Calif., who sits on the governing board,
noted that in the latest exams, ``writing at the basic level _ even
at 12th grade _ is not particularly sophisticated and certainly not
powerful.'' With 23 percent of fourth graders, 27 percent of eighth
graders and 22 percent of the seniors scoring at least proficient _
the level the board believes all students should reach _ Ms. Whirry
said she found the results ``both encouraging and sobering.''
</P>
<P>
   The report card showed a significant gender gap, with girls
outscoring boys by 16 to 20 points at all grade levels, and about
twice the percentage of girls as boys scoring in the ``proficient''
level (NAEP has found a smaller, but similar, gap in reading, and
the reverse in math and science). Asian Americans and white
students performed best on the exams: 24 to 36 percent of them were
at the proficient level in various grades, compared to 8 to 11
percent of black, Hispanic and native American test-takers.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut students performed best on the exams, earning an
average score of 165 in the eighth grade, the only level for which
state results were reported. The lowest scores came from the
District of Columbia (126) and the Virgin Islands (124).
</P>
<P>
   Stanley O. Ikenberry, president of the American Council on
Education, a Washington-based association of colleges and
universities, pronounced the results ``very troubling,'' and
suggested that parents should read to their children and urge them
to write letters to their grandparents rather than watching
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``There simply are no jobs available, no roles available, in our
society, for people who cannot communicate effectively _ that
includes both reading and writing,'' Ikenberry said. ``At the
center of everything rests the ability to communicate, the ability
to speak, the ability to write.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In giving the tests, officials also surveyed students on various
habits connected to writing _ all of which they found to improve
performance. About one-third of the students said they use
computers for writing at least once a week, and 80 percent said
they are required to write drafts of their papers. More than
three-quarters of the students said their teachers talk with them
about writing, and save written work in portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   At home, 38 percent of fourth graders and just over half the
other students said they have newspapers, encyclopedia, magazines
and at least 25 books. More than two-thirds of the test-takers
reported discussing their studies at home at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Riley used the the unveiling of the newest report card as a
platform to criticize Republican proposals to cut his department's
budget. ``It's one thing to eliminate my job,'' he said, urging
restoration of $60 million for reading programs and $5 million for
writing, ``but it is something else to cut funding to help children
master the basics of reading and writing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
