<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sept. 29 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please
contact Elizabeth Ferry Slocum at the Daily News at (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   COVERUP-LAUSD (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles Unified School
District officials have routinely concealed serious environmental
hazards at campuses throughout the district, jeopardizing the
safety of thousands of students in order to avoid outside scrutiny,
the Daily News has learned. A lengthy investigative report,
commissioned by and discussed in private Tuesday by the school
board, says the nation's second largest public school system
intentionally downplayed environmental problems at school sites for
at least 10 years. By Greg Gittrich. (Will move in the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   REACT-COVERUP (Los Angeles) _ Students, parents and the teachers
union reacted with shock and dismay Tuesday to an investigative
report that alleges district officials routinely concealed and
minimized environmental hazards at schools By Sherry Crosby. (Will
move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   SUNSHINE-LANDFILL (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles City Council
postponed a vote on the expansion of Sunshine Canyon Landfill after
dozens of residents expressed their bitter opposition to what they
describe as the creation of the nation's largest mega-dump in
Granada Hills. The landfill operator has waged a vigorous lobbying
campaign and is believed to have enough votes to get the expansion
approved when the council takes up the issue again on Oct. 26. By
Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-STUMP (Los Angeles) _ Democratic presidential candidate
Bill Bradley stumped at Valley College in suburban Van Nuys, where
he unveiled a $65 billion proposal for a significant expansion of
the federal health care system. Under his plan, all Americans could
enroll in the same health care coverage provided for members of
Congress and federal employees. Polls show Al Gore and Bradley
locked in a tight race in New Hampshire, site of the nation's first
presidential primary in February. By Michael Coit. (Will move in
the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LAX-UPGRADE (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles International Airport is
going Hollywood. Mayor Riordan and other officials announced plans
for $112 million in upgrades for Los Angeles International Airport
before next year's Democratic National Convention. The program
includes distinctive 120-foot high, colorfully illuminated columns
along the Century Boulevard approach to the airport, with LAX in
40-foot letters; as well as new signs, landscaping, public art and
other functional or aesthetic improvements. This work will be paid
for by money from parking and concession fees, which are earmarked
for airport-related uses. By Beth Barrett. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KRISPY-OPENING (Los Angeles)_ Krispy Kreme Doughnuts opened the
doors and drive-thru of its second Southern California location
Tuesday, to the delight of hundreds of hungry commuters who waited
hours in advance of its 6 a.m. opening. By Chris Sieroty. (Will
move in the ``f'' financial file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
