<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: COBBLING A NEW IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Maybe women love shoes because they hear the
Cinderella story so often when they're little. With the perfect
shoe comes the perfect guy.
</P>
<P>
   But does that equation apply to presidential politics?
</P>
<P>
   I went to check out the New Gore at a fund-raiser in a Maryland
suburb. He now takes the microphone and strolls a bit, like
Elizabeth Dole. He tries to empathize, telling the well-heeled
African-American guests that when he came back from Army basic
training with shorn hair and a uniform in 1969, he got angry stares
from the flower-power crowd: ``I'm telling you, it was a Ralph
Ellison moment.''
</P>
<P>
   He cuts loose by confiding that he only pretends to have read
Stephen Hawking. He's leaner and more twangy. He wears lighter
suits and colored shirts and cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   W. has traded his cowboy boots for black loafers to look more
earnest, and Al has traded his black loafers for cowboy boots to
look less earnest.
</P>
<P>
   It's unsettling when candidates begin fiddling with their
clothes and hair and speech patterns, trying to project a different
image. They are in public life for decades and they still don't
know who they are?
</P>
<P>
   Candidates pay political consultants millions for fashion advice
so they can ``be themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   During the final weeks of Michael Dukakis' moribund '88
campaign, he began wearing an aide's brown suede jacket on the
mistaken assumption that it made him seem warmer and cozier.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, George Bush, senior, was busy shedding
his striped watchbands and half-glasses, trying not to look so
preppy. But no matter how much the late Lee Atwater babbled about
the candidate's taste for pork rinds, Bush reeked of Greenwich and
Kennebunkport, of gin martinis and J. Press blue blazers and
Topsiders. He was a Ralph Lauren moment.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Morris wrote that he fussed over President Clinton's ties
before meetings, worried that staid ties would smack of staid
thinking. He also advised him in '96 to dress more patriarchally:
``You don't look presidential in light-colored suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Panetta discouraged the jogging shorts that showed off the
president's bread-pudding thighs.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Alexander's plaid shirt failed to catch populist fire
because it was too gimmicky. The sartorial message must be
subliminal.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kennedy went to great lengths to camouflage his youth and
inexperience by dressing formally for every public occasion. He
would never do what Bill Clinton did, wear a polo shirt to a war
council. Polo was for sailing.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole tries to coordinate the color of suit and shoes
to the stage where she speaks, but the attention is so minute it
backfires and makes her seem a martinet.
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Bradley wants to evoke his past as a sports legend, he
simply pulls on those old orange and blue Knicks socks for a beach
walk.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Beschloss, the historian who compiled the LBJ tapes,
says that Lyndon Johnson used clothes in a power play with Hubert
Humphrey. Although the two men both had great stature in the
Senate, President Johnson wanted to show after the '64 election
that his vice president was a wholly-owned subsidiary. So he
dressed Hubert in a beige ranch suit and Stetson identical to his
own, and then summoned photographers to his ranch. When the tall
president and shorter, pudgy vice president posed on horseback in
their matching outfits, poor Humphrey looked like an LBJ Mini-Me.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how often you can sum up a politician's flaws or the
mood of a certain era by evoking a costume.
</P>
<P>
   FDR's cape. The hole in Adlai Stevenson's shoe. Richard Nixon
walking on the beach in wingtips. Jimmy Carter wearing a gray
cardigan during the energy crisis and collapsing while jogging in
black socks. Ronald Reagan's brown suit, which he wore boldly in a
city of navy and gray. Dukakis swerving in the tank in that Snoopy
helmet. Clinton answering the question on boxers or briefs.
Monica's DKNY beret and Gap dress, and the Zegna tie she gave
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the outside can only crystallize impressions of the inside.
Loafers won't make W. seem diligent. Boots won't make Al seem
down-home. These Princes Sometimes Charming will need more than new
slippers to get elected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
