<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-28 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   High school students took to the streets again, threatening to
renew a widespread protest movement begun a year ago. Insisting
that the government had done nothing about its promises to provide
more teachers and classrooms, student leaders called for nationwide
protests on Thursday. Last year almost half a million students
disrupted classes for several weeks to protest crowded schools and
a shortage of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SLAVE LABOR PROGRESS
</P>
<P>
   American and German officials working on a plan to compensate
victims of slave labor under the Nazis have made progress on ways
to insure that German companies that pay into a compensation fund
would not be sued again, government officials said. But Otto
Lambsdorff, chief negotiator in talks with the United States and
victims' groups, said they had not discussed an overall figure for
the compensation fund. New talks are to start on Oct. 6 in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: REICHSTAG BACK PAY
</P>
<P>
   In a letter of appeal to the president of parliament, Wolfgang
Thierse, the British architect Lord Norman Foster demanded he be
paid the $2.2 million still owed for his prize-winning work on the
renovated Reichstag building. The Berlin Federal Building Society
said it was withholding 10 percent of Lord Foster's $22 million fee
until 45 planning and construction errors are fixed.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET PLEA
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Gen. Augusto Pinochet told a London court that he
should not be extradited to Spain to stand trial on torture charges
because there was no evidence of his responsibility for the acts
and no reason for Spain to be involved in the case. Pinochet, 83,
who was the dictator of Chile from 1973 to 1990, was arrested in
London last October on an extradition request from a Spanish judge.
A verdict is expected next month.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: ANDREOTTI REVISITED
</P>
<P>
   After a brief pause to await the verdict on his trial in Perugia
last week, the trial of former Prime Minister Giulio Andreotti on
charges of collusion with the Mafia resumed in Sicily. Andreotti,
80, was acquitted of charges he conspired in the 1977 murder of a
journalist. In Sicily he is accused of having been the Mafia's
chief protector while in power. The trial, which began in 1995, is
expected to end next month.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MAYOR QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano resigned as mayor of Mexico City,
after serving just under two years, to begin his third bid to
become president in elections next July. Cardenas was the capital's
first elected mayor. The city council started the process of naming
his chief of staff, Rosario Robles Berlanga, to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: `ICE MAN' DATED
</P>
<P>
   Canada's ``ice man,'' an Indian hunter found frozen in a British
Columbia glacier last month, has been dated to around 1450 A.D.,
about 300 years before contact with Europeans. Radiocarbon datings
of samples of the man's hat and cloak indicated that the materials
were collected at the same time, between 1415 and 1445.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CELL PHONE ALERT
</P>
<P>
   Canada's largest gas station chains have started asking
customers to turn off their cell phones while at the pumps for fear
of setting off explosions. The ban started after Ontario's
Technical Standards and Safety Authority warned that tiny sparks
from inside cellphones could ignite gas vapors. But other safety
experts say there is no more chance of a cell phone setting off an
explosion than there is of static electricity causing a blaze.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   WEST BANK: WEAPONS IMPASSE
</P>
<P>
   Refugee camp leaders have banded together to reject the
Palestinian Authority's order for all Palestinians to surrender
illegal weapons. The authority is required to confiscate unlicensed
weapons as part of its latest pact with the Israelis. The
resistance is a sign of the problems facing Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, as he tries to fulfill his obligations under
the accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
