<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 29
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-GERMANY-SCHROEDER-NYT (moved on Thursday, Sept. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Sept.
16, about a speech by Chancellor Gerhard Schroder of Germany
referred imprecisely to his audience, the Parliament. It is
officially the Bundestag, though it is sometimes known
colloquially, for the building in which it meets, as the Reichstag.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NUKE-OVERSIGHT-NYT (moved on Monday, Sept. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Sept. 27,
about Energy Secretary Bill Richardson's recommendation that
President Clinton sign a $289 billion Pentagon budget bill that
revamps the Energy Department characterized the position of Senator
Carl Levin, Democrat of Michigan, incorrectly. He did not sign a
House-Senate conference report on the bill, but he voted for the
overall bill on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WOMEN-ADS-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Monday, Sept. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Sept. 27,
about awards that praised and criticized images of women in
advertising, included erroneous credits from the presenter,
Advertising Women of New York, for some ads. A commercial for Nike
Inc. that carried the theme ``We will take on the world as a team''
was created by Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners in San Francisco, not
Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore. And a campaign for Victoria's
Secret featuring women wearing lingerie was not created by Tarlow
Advertising in New York; most of the Victoria's Secret consumer
marketing is created internally.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OPERA-CONDUCTOR-NYT (moved on Monday, Sept. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Sept. 27,
about the making of ``A View From the Bridge,'' to be presented by
Lyric Opera of Chicago, refers incorrectly to the voice of Timothy
Nolen, who sings Alfieri, the neighborhood lawyer and narrator. He
is a baritone, not a bass.
</P>
</TEXT>
