<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CHAIRMAN APPEALS TO BUCHANAN TO STAY IN PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Republican National Committee
met with Pat Buchanan on Tuesday and made his own appeal not to
bolt the party and fracture Republican ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man revealed how long they conferred. But Jim Nicholson,
the party chairman, made clear that he had tried to use both
personal loyalties and matters of principle to appeal to Buchanan,
the conservative commentator.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said in a statement that he had asked Buchanan to
``consider very carefully'' before taking any actions that would
help Democrats retain their hold on the presidency
</P>
<P>
   He also reminded Buchanan, who has long been staunchly opposed
to abortion, that the next president would ``almost certainly make
several lifetime appointments to the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   And he asked Buchanan, once a high-ranking aide to former
President Reagan, ``to consider what Reagan would advise him to do
_ what Reagan himself would do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Townsend, Buchanan's campaign director, would only confirm
there was a meeting, but refused to say anything further.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans now consider it inevitable that Buchanan will
bolt and seek the Reform Party nomination. Some Republicans close
to Nicholson said that he is now more concerned with holding onto
Buchanan's conservative followers than with keeping Buchanan
himself and did not want Buchanan's followers to feel that the
establishment had forced him from the party.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's third party flirtation has caused strife in
Republican ranks, particularly after the commentator became a
political lightening rod with a new book questioning whether Hitler
had hostile intentions towards the United States or whether the
Nazis were drawn into war with the West by Britain and France's war
guarantees to Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, one of the party's presidential contenders,
challenged Republicans to let Buchanan go, calling his views of
World War II unacceptable. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who is
considered the Republican front-runner, however, said he wanted
Buchanan to remain in the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
