<SLUG> BC-FBC-LSU-COACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LSU's DiNardo keeps poise
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ When Gerry DiNardo arrived at LSU in 1995, his
motto for the Tigers was ``bring back the magic.'' Five years
later, there are growing numbers in Baton Rouge saying ``get rid of
the curse.''
</P>
<P>
   The honeymoon is officially over for the former Notre Dame star
and Vanderbilt coach. After going 26-9-1 in DiNardo's first three
seasons, the Tigers fell to 4-7 last year. DiNardo's supporters
wrote off that season as a fluke. But when LSU was steamrollered
41-7 at home by Auburn on Oct. 18, the wolves came out.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a columnist for the Purple and Gold, a weekly
newspaper devoted to the coverage of LSU sports, called for the
firing of DiNardo and athletics director Joe Dean. The student
newspaper, the Daily Reveille, called the team an
``embarrassment.'' DiNardo was asked on his weekly call-in radio
show if he ``needs any help moving out of town.'' Baton Rouge
Advocate columnist Scott Rabalais ripped the entire program, from
the administrators all the way down to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the 46-year-old DiNardo has tried to remain
upbeat and positive. And despite the barrage of criticism, he has
not lashed out at the media or the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got to continue to show the team what they're
doing well,'' DiNardo said Tuesday. ``Everyone else is telling them
what they're doing wrong _ constantly and continuously _ and so you
kind of have to do the opposite. `Hey look, you know, we're OK
here, we're doing this pretty good. We can get better.' ''
</P>
<P>
   DiNardo recognizes the reality of his situation. He knows his
team has better turn it around soon. Coaching changes are common in
the SEC, and at LSU as much as anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only guy to last in this position for more than four
years since Charlie McClendon,'' DiNardo said. ``I think we all
know what's going on. We all know this is a tough business.''
</P>
<P>
   DiNardo got a vote of confidence from the athletics director
after the Auburn game. Dean essentially reiterated what he told The
Advocate back in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gerry DiNardo doesn't have a problem here,'' Dean said. ``He
is recruiting well. He cares academically as much as anyone that's
ever been here, which is really critical to our board and to our
chancellor and to me. I think they'll have a pretty good year, but
even if they don't he'll be the coach here in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Tigers (2-1, 0-1 SEC) are facing their toughest
stretch of the season. After Saturday's game against No. 10
Georgia, LSU plays No. 3 Florida at home, then Kentucky and
Mississippi State on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs (3-0, 1-0 SEC) knocked off then No. 6 and
undefeated LSU 28-27 last year in Baton Rouge and sent the Tigers
on their present downward spiral. Conversely, a win against Georgia
could help right LSU's reeling ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're going to come up here trying to set the
course for the rest of their year,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said.
``Revenge, in sports, doesn't help you much. But I'm sure they're
going to be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   LSU's problem with Auburn was evident. The Tigers committed six
turnovers, including five in the first half. They trailed 34-0
before scoring in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers will be coming into Sanford Stadium, where they're
6-4 all time, with a new quarterback. DiNardo named sophomore Josh
Booty the starter after the Auburn game. Booty set a school record
with 58 passes in that game, completing 29 and throwing for a
touchdown and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   LSU was off last Saturday, so it has had two weeks to prepare
for the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner of the LSU-Georgia game is going to be whoever
plays the game the best,'' DiNardo said. ``I mean, we can talk
about all the other subplots and everything else but, come game
time, it's whoever plays the game the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
