<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IS IN TERRIFIC HEALTH, DOCTOR'S REPORT PROCLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Other than some stiffness in one knee, some
tightness in his back and a minor loss of high-frequency hearing,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the front runner for the Republican
presidential nomination, is in terrific health, according to a
three-page medical summary that was prepared by his physician and
released on Tuesday by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper of Dallas, who has been Bush's physician
for nearly 10 years, said a thorough examination of Bush on June 17
gave him a clean bill of health on all the important fronts.
</P>
<P>
   The tests performed on Bush, 53, showed him to have good
cholesterol levels and blood pressure, strong lungs and no
indications of prostate cancer. He was free of arthritis, the
report said. There was no visible hardening of his arteries.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing such medical information, Bush and his aides were
in one sense simply performing what has become a requisite station
of the cross for presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But aspects of Cooper's report suggested that the Bush campaign
was also trying to address _ and discourage _ some of the questions
that reporters have asked about reckless behavior in Bush's past.
Bush has refused to say whether he ever used illegal drugs as a
younger man. He has said he used to drink alcoholic beverages, but
not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In the medical report on Bush, Cooper writes, ``He has totally
abstained from alcohol during the past 13 years. He has no history
of any alcohol, drug, mental or psychiatric treatment or
rehabilitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also made Cooper available, upon request, for
interviews with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is extremely early in a presidential race for a
contender to release medical information, the Bush campaign had
fielded several requests for it from reporters, an illustration of
the degree to which Bush is being treated as the presumptive
Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The medical report reveals that Bush had two benign polyps
removed from his colon on July 6, 1998; takes no prescribed
medications; exhibits no signs of anemia or diabetes; is
far-sighted; and sticks to low-fat foods.
</P>
<P>
   That dietary discipline, coupled with 15 to 20 miles of running
every week, keeps his weight down to about 192 pounds, only five
pounds above the preferred measurement for a man who is six-feet
tall, as Bush is, according to Cooper's report.
</P>
</TEXT>
