<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-U.S.-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LIKELY TO REGAIN A U.N. FINANCE SEAT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States is likely to regain a seat on
the important U.N. budget committee, clearing one hurdle the
Clinton administration faced in getting Congress to pay back dues
to the organization, a senior American official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has been lobbying foreign
ministers for more than a week here. She was told Tuesday by the
regional group including European countries, Canada and Australia
that it would present a slate of candidates for the committee and
not demand that the United States fight for a seat alone against
considerable opposition from many delegations.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats have been arguing that Washington lost the right
to sit on the committee by falling so far behind in what it owes
the United Nations _ $1.7 billion by the organization's
calculations. They said the Americans should not return to the
committee until they are paid up.
</P>
<P>
   Albright made an end-run around foreign missions here, and
talked directly to high-level officials who have been in New York
for the opening debate of the General Assembly. A European diplomat
said her argument made sense. She told ministers that without a
seat on the budget committee, the administration would have an
impossible task persuading Congress to allocate any money. Members
of Congress had demanded that the United States be reinstated
first, a demand that infuriated diplomats here.
</P>
<P>
   But governments concerned about the future of the United Nations
decided that it was better to help the administration in getting
Congress to start paying U.S. bills than to stand on principle _
even though there is still no guarantee that Congress will provide
any significant amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, other stipulations about the work of the United
Nations are still attached to legislation. It is also likely that
the United States will not in any case pay enough to avoid losing
its vote in the General Assembly, because Congress calculates the
American debt much lower.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. assessments are treaty obligations and cannot be altered by
any member government.
</P>
<P>
   Albright was able to put her close relations with a growing
group of female foreign ministers to good use in her campaign. Some
Nordic countries were holding out against a seat for the United
States, claiming it for themselves instead. France and New Zealand
also wanted places on the committee. But there were only two
vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Two influential Nordic foreign ministers _ Anna Lindh of Sweden
and Tarja Halonen of Finland, who is also chairman of the European
Union until the end of the year _ were at a dinner Albright held
for female foreign ministers last week. Halonen's support turned
out to be crucial, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Albright was told by the chairman of the European
and others in the regional group that its members had reached
consensus on the two seats, which, unless there is an unforeseen
revolt, will go next week to France and the United States without a
vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
