<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKBOX-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS ANALYSIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
FORWARDS 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No team has a more dynamic duo than wingers Teemu Selanne and
Paul Kariya. They combined for 86 goals and 208 points last season,
so the first line should be no problem. This year, Anaheim is
hoping vastly underrated Steve Rucchin (23 goals, 62 points),
newcomer Ted Donato and Marty McInnis will form its best second
line yet. &QL; 
The young checking line of Antti Aalto, Mike LeClerc and Jeff
Nielsen figures to play a crucial role in the team's forechecking
system. Enforcers Jim McKenzie and Stu Grimson are around to
provide protection for Kariya and Selanne. &QL; 
DEFENSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks improved their skill level by trading for Oleg
Tverdovsky and drafting European veteran Niclas Havelid to go along
with power-play specialist Fredrik Olausson (16 goals, 56 points). &QL; 
Anaheim, however, must get another solid season from the
defensive-minded pairing of Jason Marshall and Kevin Haller and
continued improvement from Ruslan Salei and Pavel Trnka. This is
still their most vulnerable position. &QL; 
GOALTENDING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guy Hebert seems to be getting better with age, but coach Craig
Hartsburg hopes to keep the only remaining original Duck fresher by
cutting his work load. Last year, Hebert played in 69 games. Look
for Dominic Roussel to get more starts. &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If everybody stays healthy there's no reason the NHL's
top-ranked power play in 1998-99 shouldn't be just as powerful,
especially with the addition of Tverdovsky to play on the second
unit. &QL; 
The penalty-killing unit had its ups and downs last year and
finished 15th in the league. That group will need to step up for
the Ducks to take the next step. &QL; 
COACHING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The intense Hartsburg was just the right fit last season, even
though he didn't get the national recognition he deserved. &QL; 
OUTLOOK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fourth-place finish in the Western Conference isn't out of the
question, but while Anaheim looks to be a team on the rise, it has
a thin margin for error. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
