<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO RULE ON LAW THAT ALLOWS RAPE VICTIMS TO SUE
ATTACKERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Va., Colo., Wash.)  
 (Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, In a ruling ..., to give full name of school,
Virginia Polytechnic Institute AND STATE UNIVERSITY.)  (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking up a case with broad implications for its
continuing reappraisal of federal power, the Supreme Court agreed
Tuesday to decide whether Congress had the authority to open the
federal courts to civil lawsuits by victims of rape, domestic
violence and other crimes ``motivated by gender.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the fate of a 1994 law, the Violence Against Women
Act, which Congress passed after concluding, on the basis of four
years of hearings, that state court systems were not dealing
adequately with an epidemic of violence against women. The law
created a new federal civil remedy, permitting victims to sue their
attackers for damages, including punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling last March, the federal appeals court in Richmond,
Va., declared the law unconstitutional and dismissed a suit brought
by a student at Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University
against two fellow students, football players who she contended had
raped her in her dormitory room shortly after the start of her
freshman year in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed by Christy Brzonkala, was the first to be
brought under the law's civil damages provision, and has been
watched closely during its journey through the courts. The two men
fought the suit by arguing that the civil damages section of the
law exceeded Congress' authority to assert federal jurisdiction
over matters of traditional state concern. One defendant was
eventually punished by Virginia Polytechnic with a deferred
suspension that enabled him to complete his college football
career; the university's judicial committee took no action against
the other.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals striking
down the law was cast in very broad terms, with Judge J. Michael
Luttig, writing for the 7-4 majority, declaring that the Violence
Against Women Act ``simply cannot be reconciled with the principles
of limited federal government upon which this nation is founded.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling held that because violence against women had only
``an attenuated and indirect relationship with interstate
commerce,'' the law was not a proper exercise of congressional
authority under the Constitution's commerce clause. Nor was the law
a valid exercise of Congress' authority to enforce the equal
protection guarantee of the 14th Amendment, the 4th Circuit held,
because the law sought to regulate purely private conduct rather
than the state action at which the 14th Amendment is directed.
</P>
<P>
   Both these broad propositions place the case in the center of
the court's continuing debate over defining the boundary between
federal and state authority. In a series of decisions over the last
four years, culminating in June with three handed down on the final
day of the court's term, the court invoked principles of federalism
and sovereign immunity to circumscribe the power of Congress to
identify problems in need of uniform national solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration appealed the 4th Circuit decision, as
did the NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund, which has represented
Ms. Brzonkala throughout the case. The justices combined the two
appeals, U.S. vs. Morrison, No. 99-5, and Brzonkala vs. Morrison,
No. 99-29, and will hear the case in January. The court had already
scheduled arguments in three other federalism cases during its new
term, which officially begins next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both halves of the 4th Circuit's analysis have implications
beyond the specific law at issue. On the question of Congress'
power to regulate interstate commerce, the appeals court relied on
the Supreme Court's ruling in a 1995 case, U.S. vs. Lopez, which
invalidated a federal law that made it a crime to carry a gun near
a school. In that case, the justices said that the activity
involved did not have a ``substantial relation to interstate
commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   In passing the Violence Against Women Act, Congress found that
violence against women did affect the economy by, for example,
limiting women's participation in the labor force. However, the 4th
Circuit rejected those findings, raising the question of the extent
to which federal courts should defer to the rationale offered by
Congress for its actions.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th Circuit's limitations on congressional authority to
legislate under the 14th Amendment raises potential questions about
the validity of civil rights laws enacted under that authority,
since those also apply to actions by private individuals who are
not ``state actors.'' The Clinton administration is arguing that
because the states themselves have failed to address the problem of
violence against women, the issue is one of official behavior and
not simply of private conduct.
</P>
<P>
   While the court ordinarily waits to review a case until a
disagreement has developed among the federal appeals courts, the
justices acted Tuesday in the absence of such a conflict. The 4th
Circuit was the first appeals court to decide the constitutionality
of the Violence Against Women Act, although the law has been upheld
by 14 federal District Courts.
</P>
<P>
   The law is familiar to the justices, although they have never
ruled on it. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist criticized it both
before and after its enactment, singling it out in speeches on the
new burdens that Congress was placing on the federal courts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This case was one of nine new appeals the court accepted
Tuesday. The cases, which will be argued in January, bring the
number of cases on the court's calendar to 44, well over half the
cases the justices are likely to decide over the nine-month
duration of the term.
</P>
<P>
   These were among the other new cases:
</P>
<P>
   _ Grandparents' Rights: The court agreed to decide the
constitutionality of a Washington state law giving grandparents and
other ``third parties'' the opportunity to petition a court for
visitation rights ``when visitation may serve the best interest of
the child.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Supreme Court, in a ruling last December,
declared the law unconstitutional as violating the fundamental
rights of parents not to have the state interfere with their
child-rearing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Only where ``the state seeks to prevent harm or a risk of harm
to the child'' can the parents' fundamental right be overcome, the
state court said, adding that ``parents should be the ones to
choose whether to expose their children to certain people or
ideas.'' Even when there is a plausible argument that continued
contact with grandparents or other relatives, following a divorce
or the death of one parent, would be beneficial to the child,
``state intervention to better a child's quality of life through
third-party visitation is not justified where the child's
circumstances are otherwise satisfactory,'' the Washington court
said.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Troxel vs. Granville, No. 99-138, is an appeal by the
parents of a man who committed suicide after fathering two
daughters by a woman to whom he was not married. After the father's
death, the mother married a man who adopted the girls. The mother
and her husband then sought to limit the girls' contact with their
paternal grandparents, who invoked the state law and won regular
visitation rights under a decision that the Washington Supreme
Court then overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Most states have laws permitting grandparents and others to seek
visitation rights, and the state courts are divided over the laws'
constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   _ Abortion Protests: The court agreed to hear a challenge to a
Colorado law making it a crime to approach another person within a
distance of 8 feet, while in the vicinity of a health care
facility, for the purpose of distributing leaflets, displaying
signs or engaging in conversation unless invited to do so. The
challenge was brought by three anti-abortion protesters who travel
to abortion clinics around Colorado for what they call ``sidewalk
counseling,'' trying to dissuade patients from entering the clinics
for their scheduled abortions.
</P>
<P>
   A Supreme Court decision two years ago, in a case from Buffalo,
N.Y., invalidated on First Amendment grounds a portion of a court
injunction that had imposed such a ``floating buffer zone'' to
shield abortion clinic patients from protesters. The Colorado law
was ``indistinguishable on any substantive basis,'' the lawyer for
the three protesters told the court in the new case, Hill vs.
Colorado, No. 98-1856.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the Colorado law in light of the earlier decision, the
Colorado courts nonetheless upheld the provision on the ground that
a law was entitled to more deference than a court injunction. The
law was a ``legitimate exercise of the state's authority to
restrict threatening conduct immediately outside health care
facilities,'' the state told the justices in its brief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
