<SLUG> BC-MARKET-IPOS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN LOOMS ON REGULATION OF FOR-PROFIT NYSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Stock Exchange appears to be headed for
a showdown with the chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission over how the exchange will be regulated when it converts
to a publicly traded, for-profit business.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the SEC,
floated the idea of an independent, universal stock market
regulator, the New York Stock Exchange's chairman firmly rejected
the idea Tuesday, saying it would ``weaken investor protections and
do irreparable harm to the NYSE brand.''
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the Senate Banking Committee in Washington,
the market executive, Richard Grasso, also objected to the idea of
spinning off the exchange's regulatory function from an
investor-owned Big Board. This split would help eliminate some
conflicts of interest for its policing unit as the exchange takes
on the task of increasing shareholder returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the NYSE, our self-regulatory duties literally permeate
every part of the exchange,'' Grasso said in prepared remarks to
the committee. ``Severance of them would be both culturally and
practically impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   His seemingly unyielding position was surprising, given that the
SEC will have to approve a public offering by the New York Stock
Exchange. In fact, Levitt's concerns about the exchange's
regulatory structure emerged from its discussions about such an
offering.
</P>
<P>
   And while his refusal to compromise seemed to win Grasso friends
on the Finance Committee Tuesday, among them the chairman, Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, it could cause the New York exchange to fall
behind the NASDAQ stock market, which has announced a similar plan
to sell shares.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso's comments stood in sharp contrast Tuesday to the
testimony of Frank Zarb, chairman of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, the owner of the NASDAQ stock market, who told
the committee that he supported the idea of a single regulator.
</P>
<P>
   Having already separated its regulatory unit into an independent
organization, NASD thinks that the time is right to consider the
possibility of a single overseer of markets, Zarb said.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility was raised by Levitt, who said last week that
he was intrigued by the idea of a single self-regulatory
organization to oversee members, sales practices and all
intermarket trading for stock markets. In such a plan, each market
would maintain responsibility for the surveillance of its own
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Grasso's private beliefs may not be as rigid as his
public statements imply. In an interview after his testimony, he
said he expects that the exchange will not be able to complete its
planned conversion from mutual ownership to a publicly traded
corporation without reaching an agreement with the SEC over how the
regulatory function will be set up. Therefore, some compromise on
the issue will be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   And on another issue raised last week by Levitt, Grasso hinted
that the two of them agreed in principle, if not on all the
details.
</P>
<P>
   That issue involves what is known as Rule 390, a New York Stock
Exchange rule that prohibits Big Board members from dealing in
listed securities off an exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said that the effect of the rule is to ``distort
competition and introduce artificial costs.'' One way or another,
he added, ``Rule 390 should not be part of our future.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question about Rule 390 at the hearing, Grasso
said, ``I have no intention of removing it right now.'' But in a
later interview, he said, ``The rule today is really without any
substance,'' and in fact, ``we may drop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Might there not be similar flexibility in Grasso's stance on a
single market regulator?
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The questions over how the securities markets will be regulated
reflect the uncertainty created by the rapid changes in the
structure of the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of electronic trading networks has begun to erode
the market share of the the Big Board and NASDAQ, forcing them to
respond. But each time they say they intend to make a quick
response to those competitive pressures _ first in regard to
after-hours trading, and then in ownership structure _ their plans
succumb to longer-than-expected delays.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the New York Stock Exchange itself has pushed back
the timetable for its conversion from a member-owned institution to
an entity owned by public shareholders. Where Grasso first
predicted such a move by Thanksgiving, he now says it will not
happen until the second half of next year.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that delay is caused by the need to make sure that
member firms have adjusted their computer systems to make the
transition to the year 2000, and in part to account for the change
of stock prices from fractions to decimals, which is scheduled to
begin next July.
</P>
<P>
   But the delay can also be traced to harder questions about
conflicts of interests at the exchange: Could market-surveillance
employees, for example, who owned stock in the exchange conduct
fair investigations of trading when news of a trading scandal might
drastically affect the value of their shares?
</P>
<P>
   Grasso insists they can. And, he said in an interview Tuesday,
the exchange might well establish a ``segregated subsidiary''
responsible for market oversight, which operates behind a Chinese
wall of separation from the exchange's profit-making business.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those plans will pass muster with the SEC remain to be
seen. Almost certainly, the answers will continue to evolve for
longer than anyone expects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
