<HEADLINE>
KINGS ANALYSIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
FORWARDS 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year it was Luc Robitaille (39 goals) going it almost
alone, especially when Glen Murray (16 goals) was hurt. This
season, three-time 40-goal scorer Zigmund Palffy should provide the
left winger a boost, but No. 1 center Jozef Stumpel must return to
form. Stumpel had only 34 points last season, 45 fewer than the
season previous. &QL; 
Murray and Donald Audette (18 goals, 36 points in 49 games) are
quality wingers, but the second-line center spot remains up for
grabs. Journeyman Len Barrie, who played in Germany last year and
has only 64 games of NHL experience, has been pressing the
inconsistent Bryan Smolinski (16 goals, 40 points with the
Islanders). Ian Laperriere centers the checking line. &QL; 
DEFENSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Kings couldn't sign Aki Berg; this season they
begin without Mattias Norstrom, who remains $300,000 apart from the
team and is squabbling over contract length. That leaves captain
Rob Blake without his safety net. Blake, who is coming off a subpar
season (12 goals, 35 points in 62 games), has made it clear he's
not too happy about that. &QL; 
Berg is back and eager to play, but the rest of the defense is
questionable. Sean O'Donnell is willing but limited by his lack of
mobility. Gary Galley is 36 years old. European veteran Frantisek
Kaberle is an NHL rookie. Jaroslav Modry and Philippe Boucher have
yet to prove they are full-time defensemen. &QL; 
L.A. was counting on Jere Karalahti, a highly regarded Finnish
defenseman, but his request for a U.S. visa has been delayed.
Karalahti was convicted of narcotics possession in 1996 in
Finland. &QL; 
GOALTENDING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This should be the team's strength if Stephane Fiset (a
career-best 2.60 GAA in '98-99) and Jamie Storr (2.40 GAA) stay
healthy. &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kings ranked 24th on the power play last season and they
still don't have a proven quarterback to run it, even though Palffy
should help up front. &QL; 
The 14th-ranked penalty-killing unit was average at best, and
that's not good enough when the power play is so suspect. &QL; 
COACHING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt Andy Murray will do things his way. The
question is how long will his players listen and buy into his
detail-oriented approach, especially if the team struggles early
on. &QL; 
OUTLOOK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A playoff spot isn't out of the question, but neither is another
11th-place finish. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
