<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUIDANT-GUIDANT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 2 Rivals Get FDA OK for Medical Patches  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The Food and Drug Administration yesterday approved two different
patches, developed by Bay Area scientists, that are designed to
repair the inner walls of weak blood vessels, preventing them from
bursting and causing death.
<P>
   The patches _ called stents in medical terms _ are meant to
treat abdominal aortic aneurysms, a condition in which a section of
the body's main blood vessel swells up, threatening to rupture and
cause a deadly hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15,000 Americans, most notably actor George C. Scott, die
each year because of such ruptures. Another 45,000 people, mostly
men over 65, undergo the surgery which was the only way to treat
such aneurysms before the FDA approved the two patch technologies
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The two systems approved yesterday are the culmination of years
of tests by the rival Medtronic Inc. of Minneapolis and Guidant
Corp. of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The scientific groundwork for both patching systems was done by
Peninsula startups, AneuRx Inc. and EndoVascular Technologies Inc.,
which were acquired by Medtronic and Guidant, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Zarins, head of vascular surgery at Stanford Medical
Center, is a clinical investigator and shareholder in Medtronic. He
explained how both systems worked and how they differed from
previous treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Before yesterday's FDA approval, the only way to treat aneurysms
was through surgery, Zarins said. Surgeons would slice open the
patient's abdomen, clamp shut the aorta, cut out the bulging
portion and graft in a section of polyester tubing to replace the
weak area of the aorta.
</P>
<P>
   The Medtronic and Guidant devices would eliminate that invasive
surgery, Zarins said. In both cases, surgeons will make a small
incision in an artery in the leg, and thread a catheter through the
blood vessels leading to the aneurysm. Guided by X-ray images, the
surgeon will position the tip of the catheter at the scene of the
bulge.
</P>
<P>
   But once they get in position, the rival systems will use subtly
different techniques to patch the weakened aorta.
</P>
<P>
   According to Zarins, the Medtronic stent is a 4- to 6-inch
length of a special alloy with a unique characteristic: it enlarges
when heated to body temperature. While being maneuvered into
position, the Medtronic stent will be covered to keep it cool. Once
in position, however, the surgeon will yank off the covering and
let the metal enlarge to fill the inner blood vessel wall, where it
will be held in place by friction, Zarins said.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Cole, general manager for the Guidant division in Menlo
Park, said his company's stent has two key differences. Once in
position, the Guidant stent is inflated by a balloon that is then
withdrawn with the catheter. The Guidant stent is also anchored in
place by tiny hooks at both ends.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the FDA has approved both techniques on the same day _
a rare regulatory feat _ Medtronic and Guidant will be free to tout
their competing techniques to the 3,000 U.S. vascular surgeons who
treat aneurysms.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said Guidant plans to charge about $10,000 for its stent. A
Medtronic spokesman said its stent would be competitively priced.
Both would cost far more than the $1,000 polyester tubes used in
graft operations. But the cost of treating an aneurysm _ now
$22,000 _ may not rise because recovery from patch operations takes
two days, whereas graft surgery immobilizes patients for over a
week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
