<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUNDRY-FOUNDRY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Foundry Stock Hits Solid Gold  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A little-known Sunnyvale company whose equipment lets Internet
service providers offer fast Net access soared 525 percent in its
first day of trading, eclipsing other Net companies that have gone
public this year with record-breaking success.
<P>
   Foundry Networks, which was priced at just $25, rose $131.25 to
close at $156.25 yesterday. The stock performance gives Foundry, a
networking firm with just 208 employees, a market value of $8.69
billion.
</P>
<P>
   It was the single biggest percentage gain for any company that
has gone public this year, according to David Menlow, president of
IPO Financial Network in Millburn, N.J. Only Theglobe.com, which
went public last year, had a bigger percentage jump on its first
day _ 606 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised, I'm astounded,'' Menlow said. ``It defies
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   For all you armchair investors out there, if you had bought 100
shares of Foundry for $2,500, the investment would have been worth
a cool $15,600 by the end of trading yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Foundry's stock market success is that it plays
in the red-hot sector of Internet gear. Investors have been
clamoring to get a piece of almost any company that portends to
solve the World Wide Wait, driving the stock prices of obscure
networking companies like Juniper Networks and Alteon WebSystems to
record highs.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Alteon, which went public last week, soared almost
300 percent in its first day of trading. Mountain View's Juniper,
which went public this summer, ended its first day up by almost 200
percent and is now more than 500 percent above its opening price of
$34. Alteon makes equipment to speed up traffic at Web sites and
Juniper makes gear that sends data quickly across the Internet and
other networks.
</P>
<P>
   Foundry makes equipment _ called gigabit Ethernet switches _
that helps ISPs and other companies manage heavy traffic on their
networks. The gear allows companies like America Online, Yahoo and
AT&AMP;T to avoid bottlenecks by giving them the bandwidth they need to
support a high volume of users.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very hot area,'' said Peony Kao, an analyst with
Renaissance Capital in Greenwich, Conn. ``It was a really highly
anticipated deal (because) Foundry is in the Internet networking
area, and it provides the switches that balance traffic over data
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that gave Foundry a boost is that it's different
from most other Net companies _ it actually makes a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Foundry earned $3.3 million for the six months ended June 30, up
from a loss of $4.2 million for the same period last year. It
reported revenue of $39.5 million this year, up from just $4.2
million in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a strong company. The management is strong, it's been
profitable and they project profits going forward,'' Kao said.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded three years ago by CEO Bobby Johnson,
who is now estimated to be worth about $2 billion after yesterday's
initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also co-founded another local company, Centillion
Networks, which was bought by Bay Networks in 1995 for $140 million
in stock. Bay was bought by Nortel Networks last year for $6.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, Foundry has amassed an impressive
customer list, with companies such as AT&AMP;T, AOL, Sprint and Silicon
Graphics all buying equipment from the networking firm.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ISPs, Foundry also sells gigabit Ethernet
switches to companies like Hewlett-Packard and NBC that want to
manage their local area networks more efficiently. Companies use
the networks LANs  &LR; to enable their employees to share software,
information and applications over a common network.
</P>
<P>
   Menlow, of IPO Financial Network, said Foundry's technology is
what helped it soar yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the technology that's really at the focus here. Gigabit
Ethernet is the wave that is overtaking the marketplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the one-day success may make investors drool at the
prospect of more Net riches, Menlow cautioned people against a gold
rush mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foundry's performance is an incredibly positive statement for
the appetite of investors but it will also serve to give a sense of
confidence _ falsely so _ that all Internet stocks are of the same
ilk, and that's not the case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
