<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ECUADOR ALLOWED TO DEFAULT AS WARNING FOR MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's decision to let Ecuador default on
its debts is being interpreted as a message from Lawrence H.
Summers, the Treasury Secretary, that a little fear would be good
for the markets. That message, China's possible entry into the
World Trade Organization and more aid for Russia are among the
topics for the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   SHOWDOWN SEEN OVER STOCK RULES
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange appears to be headed for a showdown
with the chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission over
how the exchange will be regulated when it converts to a publicly
traded business.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS REBOUND; END DOWN SLIGHTLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks staged a late-session rally, with the Dow Jones
industrial average gaining nearly 200 points in the last two hours,
to close down 27.86 points, to 10,275.53. The Nasdaq composite
index fell 5.50 points, to 2,756.25. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index declined 1.11 points, to 1,282.20.
</P>
<P>
   The prices of Treasury securities fell, sending the yield on the
30-year bond to 6.08 percent, from 6.01 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   GOLD PRICES RISE 9 PERCENT, TO $308
</P>
<P>
   The price of gold surged $28.20, or 9 percent, to $308.10 an
ounce, the biggest one-day rally in almost two decades.
</P>
<P>
   COMPETITION ON INTERNET ADDRESSES
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions, which has held a monopoly on registering
Internet addresses for six years, agreed to open the process to
competition _ but only after winning a key concession from the
Clinton administration that effectively limits the authority of the
Internet's new governing body.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL OPENS CORPORATE ONLINE UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Intel started a unit that will operate corporate computing
systems over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA SHARES COME UNDER PRESSURE
</P>
<P>
   Aetna shares dropped $5.1875, to $61.75, on doubts that it got
its money's worth when it bought the Prudential health care
business last year. The decline followed Aetna's meeting with
analysts, who contended that Aetna failed to explain how the deal
would deliver the immediate increases in profits that Aetna had
projected.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN APPROVES TAKEOVER OF BANK
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government granted an American-led investor group
the right to acquire the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, a former
financial giant hobbled by bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI MOVES TO EASE DEBT LOAD
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti, the Italian company that gained control of Telecom
Italia in May, is revamping the telecommunications giant in a move
that would help it repay the debt it took on to acquire its larger
domestic rival.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF FOUNDRY NETWORKS SURGE
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Foundry Networks, a three year-old designer of devices
to manage Internet traffic, rose $131.25 from the initial public
offering of $25, to $156.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
