<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DHL-DHL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Lure of the Open Road _ Advertising  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Are there too many companies jostling for attention on the small
screen? DHL Worldwide Express, the Redwood City package courier,
thinks so and is responding by shifting its ads from the airwaves
to the highways.
<P>
   As part of efforts to commemorate the company's 30th anniversary
today, DHL said it will abandon image-building TV ads and instead
focus its marketing on brightly colored graphics plastered to the
sides of its 3,000-vehicle U.S. fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to break through the advertising clutter,'' said
David Fonkalsrud, a company spokesman. ``The consumer has become
desensitized to traditional ads. We're trying to reach them with
new forms of advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   DHL, of course, isn't alone in this effort. Golden Gate Bridge
directors are mulling an offer from CarOrder.com, an online car
dealer, to hang a marketing banner over the toll plaza in return
for paying all tolls one day a month, plus an extra $400,000 for
the bridge's coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Another online enterprise, Adauction.com, is looking to get at
commuters from a different angle _ from a floating billboard
dragged along the bay near Highway 101.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly innovative firms have taken to hauling billboards
around city streets from the backs of trucks, dressing up taxi cabs
and buses in loud corporate colors, and slapping their logos on all
manner of cheap freebie giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making new clutter,'' said Felipe Rubio, president of
Results Marketing Consultants in San Francisco. ``They're not
cutting through the clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rubio does see merit in in-your-face ad campaigns, he said
limits need to be set on how, and where, corporate pitch making is
conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise,'' he said, ``there's going to be billboards
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   DHL is taking a slightly different tack. The privately held
company is trying to emphasize its status as a leading carrier of
international packages _ Federal Express is tops for domestic
shipments _ by highlighting overseas destinations on its trucks.
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, about three-quarters of the company's U.S.
vehicles will bear the name of some international locale, plus a
related image like Big Ben or the Eiffel Tower. A
pump-up-the-volume color scheme will ensure that the trucks get
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two years now, we've seen declining effectiveness for our
TV advertising,'' Fonkalsrud observed. ``It just wasn't having a
significant impact on customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, DHL will stick to some conventional marketing
techniques, such as ads in trade magazines.
</P>
<P>
   It will cost DHL about $800,000 to dress up its fleet _ a mere
fraction of the millions of dollars routinely spent for a
nationwide TV campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Fonkalsrud said the savings will be applied to purchases of new
aircraft and development of new shipping facilities.
</P>
<P>
   So is this blitz of new marketing ploys finally reaching
critical mass? Don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will only get worse,'' said David Roberts, head of
Strategic Marketing Communications in Redwood City. ``It's not
going to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that the typical American is bombarded by as many
as 3,000 corporate messages each and every day, according to recent
studies. This places the burden on companies to keep coming up with
unexpected ways to stand out from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are kind of immune to the standard advertising
sources,'' Roberts said. ``But when they're confronted by
unexpected sources, they notice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
