<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS   Pluses of Independent Contractors 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Q: When should a business hire an independent contractor instead
of an employee, and what are the benefits?
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It often is a good idea to hire an independent contractor if you
have a short-term project or job that requires a narrow set of
skills. For example, that could be a computer consultant to assess
your needs, set up your hardware and software and then come in to
service it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of independent contractors is that you have great
flexibility to do things,'' said Richard Harroch, a San Francisco
attorney and author of ``Small Business Kit for Dummies'' (IDG
Books, $24.99). ``You can bring in someone with specific expertise
for a specific period and you don't have to withhold taxes or give
them benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Tax laws allow you to treat employees and contractors
differently, and lower tax liability is one of the biggest
benefits. For independent contractors, employers do not have to
make Social Security and Medicare contributions, withhold taxes,
carry workers' compensation insurance, pay overtime or grant job
benefits such as vacation, sick leave or and  &LR; medical care.
</P>
<P>
   But don't try to classify regular workers as consultants or
contractors. ``If they look like other employees and the employer
has total control of and what they do and where they work and how
they work, you have to treat them like employees.
</P>
<P>
   To determine whether a worker is an employee or independent
contractor, the Internal Revenue Service offers guidance in IRS
Publication 1976. If you misclassify an employee as an independent
contractor, the IRS can make you pay not only unpaid taxes but
impose penalties and fines up to $100,000 and even send you to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Harroch notes that there are a few disadvantages in hiring
independent contractors. They can be expensive. You have limited
control over them and they lack the continuity that comes with a
more permanent relationship. Also, you are bound by terms of any
contractor agreement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COMMUNITY VENTURE CAPITAL &QL; 
Most venture capital firms spend their time and money banking on
proven entrepreneurs with sterling track records and all the right
academic and business connections. But Silicon Valley Community
Ventures is a new nonprofit organization with a different tack.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of investing in high-tech startups, the San Francisco
organization is providing management advice and money to help
entrepreneurs grow businesses and create jobs in low-income
communities.
</P>
<P>
   SVCV is the brainchild of Bud Colligan, a partner with the VC
firm Accel Partners and former CEO of Macromedia, and it is backed
by some of the biggest stars in the VC firmament. Its board of
advisers includes John Doerr of Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers,
Dick Kramlich of New Enterprise Associates and Gib Myers of
Mayfield Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, wealthy entrepreneurs have contributed about $5
million to the nonprofit investment fund. As important as the
money, about 30 top executives have counseled 14 inner-city
entrepreneurs on how to build their businesses. For example:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seth Halio, vice president of finance for Spectra-Physics
Lasers, and Bob Serata, president of his own strategic marketing
firm, worked with Latte Dah Cafe, a drive-through espresso cafe in
East Palo Alto. SVCV has committed to make a $150,000 loan to the
cafe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ron Yara, co-founder of S3 and Chips &AMP; Technologies, joined several
other executives to help Apple-10 Products USA of San Jose develop
a business plan for making health and beauty products for African
Americans. SVCV loaned $25,000 to help develop its first product,
an aftershave lotion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Venture capitalist Cullen Coates advised Now and Zen, a vegan food
company in San Francisco's Bayview district that plans to
distribute its ``BBQ Un-Ribs'' and other products nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Wells Fargo Bank invested the first $5 million in a
new fund to provide equity financing to entrepreneurial, for-profit
companies in low-income communities in the Bay Area. The fund is
expected to grow to $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   SVCV President Penelope Douglas, a former Odwalla executive,
said the organization's goal is to provide ``one-on-one mentoring,
capital and others resources to target communities throughout the
Bay Area.'' It also works with other organizations that make loans
in low-income communities, such as the Small Business
Administration and Lenders for Community Development. For more
information, visit Web site, www.svcv.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEW BIZ SITE: &QL; 
Each week, someone new announces a one-stop online business
resource specifically for entrepreneurs and small businesses. The
latest is &QL; 
www.bizzed.com created by financial services leviathan Citigroup.
Yes, the new site refers visitors to the usual array of services
from ``trusted bands,'' of companies that are primarily Citigroup's
business partners. But it also has some good information, such as a
primer on venture capital and 12 things that can kill a deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
