<HEADER>
A9499 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MUSIC-MUSIC_SFCHRON &LR;      09-28 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MUSIC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Music Store's Different Drummer  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
As a 21-year-old college student, Don MacKinnon was the guy down
the hall who sought out obscure recordings and spent his free time
mixing tapes for friends.
<P>
   As a 31-year-old entrepreneur, MacKinnon has become the grown-up
equivalent of that dormitory mix-master. While music megastores and
mall retailers push predictable Top 40 releases, MacKinnon's five
Hear Music shops promote a tasteful selection of limited-edition
jazz albums, underground rock 'n' roll, folk songs from Madagascar
and 11th century chant.
</P>
<P>
   Pop stars like Ricky Martin and the Backstreet Boys are there,
too, but tucked discreetly in a corner, like pornographic magazines
at a family drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is so silly _ it's all about selling Ricky Martin
to teenagers,'' says the good-natured MacKinnon, who resembles a
thirtysomething Campbell's Soup Kid. ``There's no mechanism for
creating an album 15,000 people might love. The whole thing is kind
of broken.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKinnon's antidote is Hear Music. Unlike other music stores,
which are laid out strictly by category _ rock, classical, country
_ Hear, which is based in San Francisco, uses cross-genre
techniques to introduce people to recordings that they might not
otherwise come across.
</P>
<P>
   Listening booths around the store are arranged in themes, such
as Cowboy Music or Rainy Day Songs. Staff-written write-ups
accompany many offerings, adding a strong educational aspect to the
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Hear also has recruited well-known artists to introduce shoppers
to new selections. At each store's Artist's Choice booth, fans of
singer Tom Waits, for example, can listen to Waits' favorite CDs
and read his musings. (Describing the first time he listened to the
aria ``Nessun Dorma,'' Waits says, ``It was like giving a cigar to
a 5-year-old. I turned blue. I cried.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this store,'' says Deanna Dawson, a Web site producer,
interviewed recently in the San Francisco Hear. ``They pick out the
CDs and leave you to (explore). If I want to find something new, I
come here.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKinnon and his 12-person staff have spent more than two years
preparing a new, technologically savvy store concept, which debuted
in June in San Francisco's Metreon shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,500-square-foot shop features a long listening bar
equipped with digital scanners and computer screens.
Headphone-wearing shoppers can play any CD by waving it across the
scanner; simultaneously, write-ups of the CD and links to related
recordings appear on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Hear had established four stores, but further expansion was
stalled for several years as it worked with Sony Corp. to build the
listening bar's server technology. The same server will power an
ambitious Web site that launches today at www.hearmusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   Now MacKinnon is focusing on the company's next stage of growth:
expanding to between 75 and 100 stores nationally and a similar
number internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Hear Music's journey to the brink of the big time has been
something of a ... well, long and winding road. MacKinnon
co-founded the company as a music catalog in October of 1990, a few
months after graduating from Williams College in Massachusetts with
a degree in English literature. MacKinnon picked the featured
recordings and wrote the catalog's text. His partners, Kevin
Sheehan and Andrew McKee, recent Harvard Business School graduates,
handled the business side.
</P>
<P>
   While the catalog attracted a small, loyal following, the cost
of renting mailing lists proved too much of a burden for the
startup, then based in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The company also suffered from a fundamental problem: Because
most of the music it sold was by definition obscure, potential
customers had little idea what they might be buying. That made
mail-order much more difficult than for merchants of popular hits
or classical standbys.
</P>
<P>
   Music students armed with boom boxes staffed Hear's toll-free
line, playing tapes over the phone to interested customers. But no
amount of enthusiasm could overcome the hurdles _ or pay
MacKinnon's mounting credit card bills. The only way to make the
concept work was to open stores with listening booths, the founders
decided.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Hear Music, which at the time had 45 investors, was
acquired by CML Group, a retail conglomerate in Acton, Mass. CML
owned a fleet of well-regarded businesses including the Nature Co.,
Smith &AMP; Hawken and NordicTrack. Hear's young founders planned to
learn the art of retailing from CML and to share planning, stocking
and accounting resources with Nature Company of Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like a good idea at the time. But three years and 10
stores later, CML was in trouble and so was the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   While several street-front locations were quite successful,
including the original shop on Berkeley's Fourth Street and the
second location in Palo Alto, both of which still exist, others
were a disaster. CML, which since has folded, opened several
locations in suburban shopping malls that didn't attract Hear's
more urbane customer base.
</P>
<P>
   MacKinnon, who by that time had become Hear's chief executive,
found an outside investor, and the two bought Hear Music from CML
in October 1996, paying $371,000. They quickly closed several
stores, leaving just two in the Bay Area and one each in Santa
Monica and Chicago. Shortly thereafter, they began working on the
Metreon prototype.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is headquartered over an IHOP restaurant in a
grungy block of Mission Street, also signed a licensing deal with
Chapters, a book superstore chain in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year-and-a-half, Chapters has opened 12 Hear Music
boutiques within its bookstores. MacKinnon expects 25 more to open
north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Hear's mass rollout may be undertaken independently or with
partners. Sony intends to open three to five additional Metreons in
the United States and two or three abroad, which likely will
contain Hear Music stores, said Michael Swinney, president of Sony
Development.
</P>
<P>
   As a privately held company, Hear doesn't release financial
statements, but MacKinnon said total revenues hit between $5
million and $10 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales per square foot at its U.S. locations came in at about
$700, which is two to three times the industry average. Meanwhile,
sales at the stores open at least a year rose a healthy 5 percent
last year and typically increase between 5 and 10 percent annually,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hear is not currently profitable due to the expense of launching
the Web site, MacKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   As it contemplates a mass rollout, one obvious option for Hear
is to go public _ particularly if the Web site proves successful.
But Porter, the chairman of Telos Group, a conglomerate based in
Ashburn, Va., says that may or may not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of capital if it's required,'' said Porter, a
Brit. One challenge the chain faces is a perception that its prices
are high. Several shoppers interviewed recently said they believe
Hear is more expensive than other stores, but a random comparison
with a nearby Virgin Megastore found that the stores' prices are
comparable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a frustration of mine that people think we're
more expensive, and I think it's because it's such a nice store,''
said MacKinnon. At Hearmusic.com, prices will be somewhat lower to
compete with Web merchants and to help offset the cost of shipping,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   As for MacKinnon's future, Porter said he has no intention of
replacing the young entrepreneur with a more seasoned executive _ a
typical strategy when small companies face quick growth.
</P>
<P>
   MacKinnon is a smart businessman who exhibits the passion for
music that is necessary to maintain Hear's ``soul,'' Porter said.
``To get Hear to scale takes a lot of elbow grease and love and
care, and that's what Don puts in,'' Porter said. ``He completely
motivates his team.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who work with MacKinnon, who grew up in Short Hills,
N.J., also speak highly of him. ``Most of this time, he exudes this
childlike enthusiasm, but he has a command of numbers you don't see
until you get to know the deal side of him,'' said Swinney, who
worked closely with MacKinnon on the Metreon store.
</P>
<P>
   Music-industry experts say that despite the plethora of music
megastores in this country, there appears to be room for more Hear
Musics, particularly in cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've grown and been able to survive in a very competitive
market,'' said Saul Shapiro, vice president, sales and marketing
for Blue Note Records, a jazz label in New York. ``Despite growing
competition, they've been able to carve out their own little
niche.''
</P>
<P>
