<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9502 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BEATTY-POLITICS-1STLD     09-28 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATTY-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SPEECH MAY _ OR MAY NOT _ REVEAL BEATTY'S INTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS lede to delete `Henry'; he was born `Beaty,' but added a
second `t' and dropped his first name later; tightens quotes
elsewhere.) 
(ATTN: Minn., Calif., Ill.)  (nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM with MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Wednesday night, in a Beverly Hills hotel
ballroom best known as the site of the Golden Globe ceremonies,
Warren Beatty, actor, writer, producer, director and Democrat, will
make a speech that his friends say will touch on global trade,
campaign finance and social justice. He may, or may not, say
something about running for president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The cheerleader-in-chief for a Beatty candidacy is Arianna
Huffington, a Republican political columnist not known for
embracing McGovern Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Among his kitchen cabinet of kibitizers and wordsmiths is
Patrick Caddell, the reformed pollster and strategist who advised
Jimmy Carter and Jerry Brown and now writes for ``The West Wing,''
a television series about the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Among the media throng expected to cover the speech is George
Stephanopoulos, the former White House aide who is now a political
analyst for ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   Could Hollywood make this stuff up?
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy enough to poke fun at Beatty, a legendary
lady-killer and famously diffident star who for 40 years has been a
cocky and enigmatic presence in the popular imagination, from
``Splendor in the Grass,'' to ``Bulworth.'' He is, after all, one
of the men about whom an old girlfriend, Carly Simon, wrote
``You're So Vain.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an age in which political careers are born, live and die
in the media, in which a former professional wrestler is governor
of Minnesota, an electronics billionaire from Texas has wrought
political havoc and the official biographer of the nation's last
actor-president fesses up to fabricating an entire narrative
persona in his new book on Ronald Reagan, Beatty is hardly a
laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very responsible person, who has a genuine love for
the Democratic Party and has over 30 years of activism in the
Democratic Party,'' said Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr. of Chicago, one of
numerous disaffected politicians in both parties who have welcomed
Beatty's consideration of a campaign. ``But, like me, he doesn't
like the rightward drift of the party. Drifting to the right is not
the way Democrats win and make a difference in the lives of average
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasion of all the fuss is Beatty's planned acceptance on
Wednesday of the annual Eleanor Roosevelt Award of the Southern
California Chapter of Americans for Democratic Action, a civil
liberties group that had long sought to honor him. Beatty has the
opportunity at Wednesday's dinner to give his most extensive
comments on a possible candidacy since Ms. Huffington first
publicly floated the idea in her syndicated column seven weeks ago,
and he elaborated in a terse and elliptical Op-Ed piece in The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Beatty declines to be interviewed for publication,
and insisted in an informal conversation the other day that he was
still unsure what he intended to say. He has told friends and
supporters that he does not flatter himself that the frisson that
has greeted his possible candidacy reflects anything other than the
power of his celebrity to shine light on a segment of thinking in
the Democratic Party that has remained largely unexpressed since
President Clinton successfully co-opted Republican themes in his
re-election strategy of ``triangulation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He always felt there was a candidate he could support in the
Democratic Party, and he no longer feels that way,'' said Frank
Mankiewicz, Robert F. Kennedy's former press secretary and one
friend of Beatty's. The two Democratic contenders, Vice President
Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, are ``nibbling around the
edges,'' Mankiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a Beatty candidacy came up in July at a dinner party
at Ms. Huffington's attended by Beatty and his wife, Annette
Bening.
</P>
<P>
   When other guests begin musing on the civic disconnection in
contemporary American life, someone suggested who better to tackle
that problem than J. Billington Bulworth himself. In that role,
Beatty plays a burned out senator so sick of mouthing poll-tested
platitudes that he takes a contract on his own life, then is freed
to tell the truth about political cynicism, corporate greed, racial
inequities and the state of American democracy.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, Ms. Huffington made the musing public, and
since then, Beatty has drawn supportive words from Washington
public interest groups and politicians of all stripes. Ms.
Huffington introduced him to Bill Hillsman, the media man for Gov.
Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, who flew out for a consultation.
</P>
<P>
   Both wings of the Reform Party have sounded him out (he says
he's not interested), and John Burton, the old-line San Francisco
liberal who leads the California state Senate has made noises about
endorsing a Beatty candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican maverick Pat Buchanan poised to bolt to the
Reform Party, Ms. Huffington said the need for someone like Beatty
to offer an opposing voice is all the greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a professional storyteller,'' Ms. Huffington said.
``We've become so atomized and candidates are just addressing
pocketbook issues. All the candidates are talking about prosperity
and nobody really does talk about the public good, about justice
and sacrifice, all those big things that we haven't heard since
John F. Kennedy. And the need for someone to do that, for someone
who can pull the nation around the fire and draw us together as
we're being pulled apart, is all the more important with the
presence of Buchanan, whom I consider very dangerous and don't
underestimate at all.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Perversely, or perhaps predictably, Beatty's potential candidacy
is greeted far more skeptically in Hollywood than in Washington.
Here his rivals grouse _ under cover of anonymity _ that Beatty is
trying to divert attention from his next movie, ``Town and
Country,'' the story of a man in a midlife crisis, about which the
early buzz is bad. They say that he is a charming but politically
unsophisticated control freak who, at 62 with an apparently
blissful marriage and a fourth child on the way, could never stand
the invasive strain of a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's taken less seriously in Hollywood than anywhere
else, because people know him,'' said one colleague of Beatty in
the film industry who admires his work. ``Because people know him,
and if they know anything, it's that he's phenomenally
self-protective, risk-averse, and indecisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty has put himself on the line politically before, giving up
an entire year to raise money and campaign for George McGovern for
president in 1972, managing to get Art Garfunkel and Paul Simon to
set aside their feud for a McGovern fund-raiser. But friends say he
has usually been more comfortable behind the scenes, even in the
movies, preferring to work as director and producer and amassing a
fortune through canny business dealings. In the 1970s resisted
entreaties to run for governor of California despite promising
polls.
</P>
<P>
   He declined interviews altogether for most of the period between
``Shampoo'' in 1975 and ``Bugsy,'' in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren is the maestro of his own movements,'' said Caddell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is certainly not making the case that he has some unique
experience or qualification to run for president,'' Caddell said.
``He is saying there are very important things that are not being
said, and people have come to him because they think he might be
heard. I think that his real strength is to be a vehicle for people
who think they can have no impact, and can't be heard. In a sense,
that's a candidacy, not a candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-REACT-NYT &LR;      09-28 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE TO THE BATTLEFIELD: CULTURAL DEFENDERS OF THE FIRST
AMENDMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (with NY-MUSEUM) 
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was until Tuesday, as you may have noticed, a
conspicuous silence on the part of almost all of the city's art and
cultural institutions about the Brooklyn Museum of Art debacle. The
directors of two museums, the Whitney and the Guggenheim,
previously made remarks generally supporting the notion of freedom
of expression _ while carefully avoiding any direct criticism of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ but their statements were drowned out by
the noise from City Hall and the sounds of stumbling feet in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney and the Guggenheim, admirable though they are, are
also not the Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Museum of Modern
Art, the two biggest art museums in town, whose refusal to comment
was, in effect, louder than anything that their smaller museum
colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, they finally denounced the ``chilling effect'' they
said was caused by the mayor's threats. But as the days had passed
and the debacle had grown into front-page news of an increasingly
familiar brand, their silence had become all the more striking. The
issue was becoming the sort of First Amendment battle that usually
provokes a pro forma reaction from the people whose livelihood is
culture _ even when some of those people may privately find the
exhibition in question, or parts of it, cynical and distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   Is it going too far to think that the general silence
contributed to the incident Monday, when Brooklyn Museum chairman
Robert S. Rubin seemed to entertain with city officials the notion
of withdrawing one of the disputed works from the exhibition?
Tuesday, as the museum instead decided to sue the city, Rubin
defended the show ``in the interests of all public institutions _
museums, universities and libraries _ that are dedicated to the
free exchange of ideas and information.'' But that was after some
twists and turns that were unexpected from a museum chairman.
</P>
<P>
   As Rubin, an investment banker, met with City Hall
representatives he may not have fully understood a basic,
uncompromising principle of cultural institutions, not to mention
the recent history of those institutions that have bowed to outside
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   When the Manhattan Theater Club, in the face of similar
criticism from the Catholic League _ and actual physical threats _
announced last year that it would delay its production of Terrence
McNally's ``Corpus Christi,'' it became a pariah of the theater
world until it reversed its decision. A decade ago, the Corcoran
Gallery in Washington was ostracized for canceling a Robert
Mapplethorpe exhibition after the show was criticized by members of
Congress. Perhaps if New York's cultural institutions had spoken up
sooner, Rubin might have grasped more clearly what was at stake and
would not have even discussed a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   There is always a moment when the terms of a public debate are
framed. For nearly a week, including the period of Rubin's
discussions with city officials, the mayor had been allowed to
frame the current issue almost by himself, an extraordinary gift to
a politician. Why did it take so long for the Cultural Institutions
Group, which includes the Metropolitan Museum and 32 other
city-financed institutions, to issue any rebuttal?
</P>
<P>
   Private e-mail among the group's members, provided by someone at
one of the institutions who wanted a stronger response, reveals a
mixture of timidity and confusion in the face of a notoriously
testy mayor, along with the desperate hope that the affair would
blow over. Publicly, a few members of the group said last week that
they did not want to interfere in negotiations between City Hall
and the Brooklyn Museum, but the e-mail shows that the group knew
from the museum's director that no discussions were under way then.
</P>
<P>
   There's a particularly arresting reference in one e-mail to City
Council Speaker Peter Vallone, who, having spoken out against the
mayor last Friday, was evidently shocked to find that the group had
not joined him. Its chairman, Alan Friedman, wrote last Friday that
he had called Vallone and told him privately how grateful several
members of the group were for his stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he appreciated that,'' Friedman reports, ``but he felt
very lonely. He was astonished that we had not acted in concert.''
Vallone warned him that the mayor's attack ``would set a precedent
for this mayor or any future mayor to cut off funding for any
institution which displeased him for any reason at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   But members of the group were too busy fretting about
retribution, with one of its advisers, Marty McLaughlin, remarking
in the e-mail that Giuliani tends to regard ``those who disagree
with him as enemies to be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   And it can't go without notice that, apart from its usual
funding, the Metropolitan, for example, has lately received $14.8
million from the city toward the renovation of its Greek and Roman
galleries and is currently promised an additional $30 million. The
Modern, which is not a member of Cultural Institutions Group but
signed Tuesday's statement, has received a promise of $65 million
toward its $650 million expansion.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt many institutions may have been uncomfortable with
defending an exhibition they didn't like. ``Sensation'' was shopped
to at least one other American museum, which declined it. Apart
from the issue of taste or morality that some works in it raise,
the show consists of art owned by a single private collector,
Charles Saatchi, the London advertising executive. The Brooklyn
Museum is, in essence, lending its imprimatur to Saatchi's
investments, which, should he wish, he could sell at any time. The
show's sponsor, by the way, is Christie's, the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern, by contrast, never presents any exhibition of a
private collection unless the collection is promised to the museum,
precisely to avoid this situation. One may imagine that the Modern,
and other institutions, wanted to be disassociated from an
enterprise that they regarded as commercial, not to mention tacky;
``Sensation'' has been promoted by the Brooklyn Museum with a
warning that its contents may cause shock, vomiting and confusion,
which among other things misrepresents and cheapens the good art in
it.
</P>
<P>
   To institutions like the Modern, the scenario was this: Giuliani
would win points with the conservative Roman Catholic constituency
that he wants for his Senate campaign. The Brooklyn Museum would
have lines around the block. Saatchi would reap profits from all
the publicity. Meanwhile, cultural organizations around the city,
embarrassed into defending the exhibition on First Amendment
grounds, would jeopardize their relations with a touchy City Hall
and alienate some of their own visitors and donors, who might
privately agree with the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, First Amendment battles don't always involve
clear-cut causes. Sometimes they require a little nose holding. The
culture wars are fought ultimately on principles that 18 members of
the Cultural Institutions Group, along with six co-signers, finally
articulated Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed actions,'' their statement said, ``would set a
dangerous precedent for any mayor to revoke funding if he or she
finds even a single element of an institution's programs offensive:
one painting in an art museum, one exhibit in a science museum, one
performance in a theater, or even one book in a library.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether a pointed remark made so late in the
debate comes just too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
