<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9505 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BOYS-DON'T-CRY-FILM-A     09-28 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-DON'T-CRY-FILM-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROLE WITHIN A ROLE: A GIRL WHO BECAME A BOY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 Ted Loos' most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
re-release of ``Caligula.''  
 By TED LOOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most actresses know that their careers are largely dependent on
their looks. But last year, Hilary Swank had to worry about her
appearance both as actress and actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely amazing what happens when a woman chops her
hair off,'' said Ms. Swank, who cut hers to play a woman passing as
a young man in the film ``Boys Don't Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a haircut was the easiest part of the transformation she
had to pull off. In what is already one of the season's most
talked-about performances, Ms. Swank does more than convincingly go
male. She finds both the innocent and the rogue in Teena Brandon, a
young woman from Nebraska who abandoned her identity to embark on a
new life as Brandon Teena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys Don't Cry,'' opening on Friday, tells the tale of
Brandon, a true story that ended in 1993 when she was murdered by
two male friends enraged by the deception.
</P>
<P>
   The film's director and co-writer, Kimberly Peirce, said she had
searched for two-and-a-half years to find an actress who was right
for the part. ``There was no guarantee I could find someone who
could do what Brandon did,'' Ms. Peirce said, ``not only passing as
a man, but possessing the humor and bravado that Brandon did.''
</P>
<P>
   Casting the movie, which also stars Chloe Sevigny as Brandon's
girlfriend, made clear just how remarkable an actor the real-life
Brandon was. ``A lot of girls could act but not pass, and the rest
could pass but not act,'' Ms. Peirce said. The nature of the story
also kept some performers away. ``A lot of agents wouldn't send
their clients for the part,'' Ms. Peirce said. ``There was a stigma
attached.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Swank, an earnest 25-year-old who has been acting since
she was 16, the role represented a coming of age. She wanted it
precisely because it was leagues away from anything she had ever
tried.
</P>
<P>
   Her first movie part was the bubbly cheerleader who uttered the
immortal line ``That is (italics)so(end italics) five minutes ago''
in ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (1992). Then she saved her high
school from villainous jocks as the lead in ``The Next Karate Kid''
(1994). More recently she had a seasonlong stint as Carly Molloy, a
single mother, on ``Beverly Hills 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in jeans and a black leather jacket to talk about ``Boys
Don't Cry'' over breakfast in a midtown Manhattan hotel, Ms. Swank
recalled paying her own way to New York to audition. ``I really
wanted to play this part,'' she said, flashing a wide smile.
</P>
<P>
   Once she had got the role, she threw herself into preparing for
it, losing weight to make her facial structure more prominent and
working out to bulk up. She also practiced strapping and packing _
flattening her breasts and stuffing her pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took two months until I felt I was ready to play the
role,'' said Ms. Swank, who bears a remarkable resemblance to
Brandon on screen.
</P>
<P>
   But she did not stay at home in front of the mirror. She
ventured out in her Santa Monica, Calif., neighborhood in disguise,
introducing herself in a low voice as ``Hilary's brother James,''
not coincidentally the name of one of her grandfathers.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, the actor Chad Lowe, sometimes accompanied her,
gauging the reactions of friends and strangers. A husband from
another profession, she said, might not have understood. ``He was
really supportive; it was not an easy thing to go through,'' Ms.
Swank said. ``Once I got into it, I was fully there. I felt like I
lost every ounce of my femininity.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience of passing as a boy gave her a sense of the
confused emotions that might have motivated the killers. ``I was
treated so differently in public,'' said Ms. Swank, who noticed
that shopkeepers watched her suspiciously when they thought she was
a boy. ``If people couldn't define what I was, they didn't want to
have anything to do with me.''
</P>
<P>
   During the film's five-week shoot, which included violent scenes
in which Brandon is stripped and raped, Ms. Swank's fellow actors
were impressed by her commitment. ``I've done things for roles, but
that's further than I've ever gone,'' said Peter Sarsgaard, who
plays Brandon's friend-turned-murderer in the film. ``She really
lived it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Swank had trouble getting oud of character.
``Sunday would come, our day off, and I would put on makeup and try
to be Hilary,'' she said. ``But I just looked androgynous. I
thought I was never going to be me again.''
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth week of filming, in Texas, Ms. Swank had to call
her husband and ask him to join her on the set. ``I told him I was
having a really hard time getting through this,'' she said. ``I had
to keep a little bit of distance from the fact that this actually
happened to someone.'' She said it had taken about three weeks of
rest among friends and family before she could ease herself out of
the role.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Swank connected to Brandon's story from the start. ``It
really hit home,'' she said of her first reading of the script.
``Here I am pursuing my dream of acting, and she was murdered for
her dream. Everyone can relate to that.'' Like others associated
with the film, Ms. Swank alternated between male and female
pronouns when discussing the character.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a coincidental connection to the story. Ms. Swank
was born in Lincoln, Neb., the city Brandon fled for Falls City,
Neb., in the hope of building a new life as a boy. Ms. Swank still
has family in Nebraska and Iowa, and she enlisted a cousin in Des
Moines as a dialect coach: he taped himself reading books to help
her acquire a a flat Midwest accent.
</P>
<P>
   Though she was raised mostly in Bellingham, Wash., Ms. Swank was
16 when she moved with her mother to Los Angeles to pursue acting.
``We lived on our Mobil card, eating at mini-marts,'' Ms. Swank
said of their journey south. But she soon landed the role in
``Buffy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she is looking forward to transforming her career. She is
already receiving scripts as a result of the favorable buzz about
her work in ``Boys Don't Cry,'' which was well received at the
Toronto International Film Festival and is part of this year's New
York Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, as an actor, you have to do some jobs to pay the
bills,'' she said of her experience moving from ``90210'' to a
serious independent film. ``But my next movie has got to be
something that I really love, now that I've gotten a taste of what
that's like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
