<SLUG> BC-FORBES-INTERVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES AIMS AT STRENGTHENING HIS GROUND TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Wealthy publisher Steve Forbes was the hare of the
1996 Republican presidential race, an idea-laden late-starter who
poured money into TV spots, but had no solid base of volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is running as a tortoise four years later, working the
GOP faithful while Texas Gov. George W. Bush flies high in the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``My object is to get the ground forces,'' Forbes said in an
interview Tuesday in the latest of a series of Seattle visits
stretching back to December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   His goal is to win over what Ronald Reagan called the
``conviction conservative'' in the GOP, unite the right, and go
head-to-head with Bush in such early tests as the caucuses in Iowa
and Alaska, the New Hampshire primary and Washington's primary and
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be a contest of the Republican establishment,
the capital lobbyists and commentators and insiders, versus a
principled outsider with a message,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has picked off organizers from former Rep. Linda Smith's
statewide organization, the right-to-life movement and other
conservative activists who have dominated GOP presidential politics
in Washington state for nearly a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' message still centers on his 1996 proposals for a
flat-rate income tax, and phasing in a new Social Security system
of retirement accounts that would let younger workers invest their
retirement money.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, however, Forbes has developed a
sensitivity to concerns of Republican conservatives to whom he was
suspect as a newly minted, libertarian-minded candidate in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' litany of American freedoms now includes the ``freedom
to be born,'' with a proposal for the eventual criminalization of
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' advocacy of free trade includes a proposal for tough
conditions in U.S. dealings with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (Clinton) administration wants us to think the only
options are appeasement or a new cold war,'' he said. ``I want to
see rules of engagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first is that we are going to stay in Asia, and are not
going to let them run us out,'' he said. ``We will hold them to
their promise not to use force in settling disputes with Taiwan. We
will continue to be critical of them on human rights. It is part of
our heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will tell China to reduce its own trade barriers, that
trade is not a one-way street. If China wants to sell nuclear
technology to rogue states such as North Korea, a price will be
paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, the publisher of Forbes magazine, is perhaps the only
GOP candidate with resources to match Bush's $50 million warchest.
There have been signs he is looking to turn assets into cash. An
island in Fiji, purchased by his flamboyant father, has gone on the
selling block.
</P>
<P>
   But there are indications his strategy is starting to work. He
finished a strong second behind Bush in Iowa Republicans' straw
poll. Forbes has lately welcomed a key convert, the national
campaign chairman, from the rival campaign of Christian
conservative activist Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, also running on a
unite-the-right strategy, quit the GOP race on Monday. Commentator
Pat Buchanan is flirting with a run for the Reform Party
nomination. A key Buchanan backer in this state, Kay Regan, signed
up with Forbes on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes scoffs at opinion surveys showing Bush far ahead _
``Polls are impressionistic, they don't mean anything'' _ and
lampoons television commentators who say the GOP nomination is
wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, as in business and finance, pundits are a lagging
indicator of trends ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spent Tuesday's Seattle visit at a private luncheon and
meeting with supporters. He went on to Anchorage to court
conservative activists who dominate Alaska's Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   GOP activists will play a major role in selecting Washington's
delegation to next year's Republican national convention in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Only one-third of GOP convention delegates will be determined by
the outcome of the state's Feb. 29 presidential primary. Two-thirds
will be determined by March 7 precinct caucuses, historically a
stronghold of Christian conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has been the most frequent Washington visitor among GOP's
eight remaining presidential hopefuls. But he is getting
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain will kick off his campaign in the state
with a breakfast Thursday at Boeing Field. It will be McCain's
fourth Seattle stopover in the past five months.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will return to the state next month for a convention of the
National Federation of Republican Women, and be featured attraction
at an Oct. 16 Safeco Field fund raiser for Sen. Slade Gorton and
the National Republican Senatorial Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole will also attend the GOP womens' convention, as
will Forbes and McCain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
