<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9510 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DREAM-OF-LIGHT-VIDEO-     09-28 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAM-OF-LIGHT-VIDEO-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DREAM UNFOLDS UNHURRIEDLY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Skedded earlier as ALEXANDER-NEVSKY-VIDEO) 
 (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DREAM OF LIGHT (QUINCE TREE OF THE SUN) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Victor Erice. 1990. Facets Multimedia. $79.95. 138
minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spanish with English subtitles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certain things can be expected from a director who makes three
films in 30 years. Haste isn't one of them, nor is the slightest
deviation from detail. Victor Erice, a master of Spanish cinema,
needs almost two and a half hours to present his painstaking
creation, which in turn is the story of another creation that is
every bit as meticulous. Once one gets used to the fact that
there's no hurrying matters, there could well follow a desire to
give the film its head and let it go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   Erice prefers the English title, ``Quince Tree of the Sun,'' to
the American ``Dream of Light.'' Either way, his luminous
documentary, set in Madrid, goes into the back yard of the painter
Antonio Lopez Garcia to scrutinze the artist as he renders first a
painting and then a drawing of the tree and its fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, we learn, is in pursuit of a dream he had in childhood
about a mysterious group of people and quinces withering on a tree.
In the strong September light he sets up his easel close by the
tree and uses string to mark the plumb line and determine quadrants
on his canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny hash marks of white paint are carefully dabbed on the
leaves and the quinces. Later we learn that the marks indicate
precisely the original position of the leaves and fruit, which will
change as the quinces grow heavier and droop. Spikes are driven
into the soil, and every moment he is at work, Lopez plants the
toes of his shoes against them to be sure he remains the exact same
distance from his subject.
</P>
<P>
   September dissolves into October. We meet the artist's wife,
Maria, who is also a painter. Another artist drops by to discuss
the work in progress and to share tales of youthful experiences. As
his work forms on the canvas, Lopez himself emerges as a man with a
keen awareness of what he is about and after: the cycle of life.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to capture the fruit at the exact moment of early autumn
light he remembers from long ago _ ``You can't believe how lovely
it was,'' he says _ he nevertheless refuses to hurry himself. As
the days pass, the light leaves. No matter. He starts all over
again with a drawing.
</P>
<P>
   As the new work takes shape, we watch him close in on a vision.
Visitors to the yard wonder about his obsession with physical
space. With warm fondness they lead him off to other pursuits, at
least for a little while. Later, Lopez has a young assistant prop
the leaves and fruit into position with a bamboo pole. His toes are
flush against the spikes in the ground. The pole brushes his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Should he look over or under it? Late fall arrives and the fruit
falls to the ground. Some of it is eaten by family and friends. The
rest withers, as it did long ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
