<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9514 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JAMMESES-PHOTOGS-$ADV     09-28 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMMESES-PHOTOGS-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A LITTLE SHOP OF RARITIES IN PARIS: 2,000 PHOTOS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For decades, curators, collectors and dealers from
throughout the world came here to an antiquarian bookshop on the
Left Bank, the Librairie P. Jammes, where they climbed the circular
staircase to meet the owners, Andre Jammes and his wife,
Marie-Therese. They came to share the couple's expertise on
photography, a private passion that they pursued for more than 40
years, forming one of the finest collections anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a series of gifts and sales of their treasures to the
Bibliotheque Nationale and the Musee d'Orsay in Paris as well as to
the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles, and the Metropolitan
Museum of Art in New York, the Jammeses have sent to auction much
of what is left of their ``magnificent obsession,'' said Philippe
Garner, the director of the photography department at Sotheby's in
London.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty of the most important photographs and albums are on
exhibit through Tuesday at Sotheby's in New York. The sale of the
collection, 2,000 images in 280 lots, will take place on Oct. 27 in
London. Sotheby's expects that the sale will total as much as $4.8
million, a record at auction for photography.
</P>
<P>
   But when Mr. and Mrs. Jammes began acquiring photographs,
neither they nor anyone else realized how prescient they were. ``In
1955, after a beautiful lecture on Nadar, we discovered that there
were no collectors and very few serious books on the history of
photography,'' said Jammes, 72. ``That was shocking for us.'' So
they decided to acquire early French photographs as a study
collection. Then the Jammeses documented the photographs as
thoroughly as they did the early printed books stocked in their
shop.
</P>
<P>
   They concentrated on 19th-century French photographers _ Nadar
(born Gaspard-Felix Tournachon), Edouard Baldus, Hippolyte Bayard,
Gustave Le Gray and Henri Le Secq. But they soon broadened their
focus to include other masters from the first century of
photography _ the Britons William Henry Fox Talbott and Julia
Margaret Cameron and the Americans Edward Steichen and Alfred
Stieglitz, along with foreign-born artists who worked in Paris:
Andre Kertesz, a Hungarian, and Man Ray, an American.
</P>
<P>
   Jammes became the collector, acquiring vast quantities of
photographs from booksellers as well as from photographers, their
estates and their families. Mrs. Jammes was the archivist,
recording the history, provenance and printing techniques used on
each photograph.
</P>
<P>
   They began to exhibit their collection in 1965, lending Man Rays
to an exhibition at the Musee des Arts Decoratifs in Paris. (Among
them was an album of 12 Rayograms that had once belonged to the
Dada poet Tristan Tzara.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, they sent many 19th-century works to a show at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art, and in 1977, the Art Institute of
Chicago did a major exhibition of their collection, ``The First
Century of Photography.'' In 1983, the Jammeses sent 19th-century
calotypes, images from paper negatives, to Princeton University for
an exhibition that coincided with the publication by Princeton
University Press of ``The Art of French Calotype,'' a book by
Jammes and the art historian Eugenia Parry Janis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Daniel Wolf, a New York photography dealer, persuaded
the Jammeses, along with eight other collectors, to sell part of
their collection to an unnamed client that the Jammeses guessed was
the Getty Museum. ``We bought several thousand photographs from the
Jammes collection,'' said Weston Naef, the Getty's curator of
photographs. ``We got a little bit of everything _ French, British,
American photographs _ all, except their 20th-century pieces, that
most people did not know about then.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple also sold their collection of photographs by Nadar,
the pre-eminent French portrait photographer in the 19th century,
to the Musee d'Orsay. And in 1990, the Getty returned and bought
200 images by Eugene Atget.
</P>
<P>
   While Sotheby's auction offers none of Atget's poignant
photographs of simple landscapes, formal palaces and gardens and
eerie reflections in shop windows, the works of most other
photographers in the Jammes collection are represented in the sale.
The finest of the 16 images by Nadar are two portraits from 1855:
one depicts the illustrator Gustave Dore as a dashing fellow in a
checkered scarf; the other shows the mime Paul Legrand as an
astonished clown.
</P>
<P>
   Each is expected to bring up to $28,800. Two albumen prints by
Le Gray from 1855 are nature studies: in ``Beech Tree,
Fontainebleau,'' a huge, gnarled tree seems to swallow the
landscape, and in ``Seascape in Sete'' the sun expands both the sky
and sea. Each is expected to sell for as much as $96,000. The power
in Bayard's self-portrait from 1850-55 is in the tightly controlled
setting showing him at work with his camera.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest photograph in the sale, the bluish ``Pantheon,
Paris'' by Vincent Chevalier, is a whole-plate daguerreotype that
Daguerre's longtime lens-maker tok on Oct. 2, 1839. It was just
six weeks after Daguerre's photography process was announced to a
crowd in front of the French Academy of Sciences in Paris.
Sotheby's expects that the photograph will bring as much as
$32,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sale has the wonderful feel of an insider's collection,''
Naef said. ``It turns back the clock to the late '70s and '80s,
when so many early photographs were being exported from France. And
that makes it seem very refreshing and exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9516 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-JAZZ-MUSICIANS-3TA     09-28 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JAZZ-MUSICIANS-3TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSSING MUSIC'S BORDERS IN SEARCH OF IDENTITY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM SHATZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is jazz? Throughout the 1980s, New York's
downtown improvisers delighted in dancing around this question. Not
that it should ever have been posed to them.
</P>
<P>
   Although inspired by free jazz, the saxophonists John Zorn and
John Lurie, the songwriter Arto Lindsay and the guitarists Marc
Ribot and Bill Frisell were not quite jazz musicians. They were
installation artists whose raw material was sound; they scavenged
for quotations from their vast record collections and from the
city's musique concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Performing at clubs like the Knitting Factory, Roulette and the
Gas Station, these musicians created a deliriously referential,
post-modern pastiche of genres that ranged irreverently across free
jazz, punk rock, classical modernism and B-movie soundtracks and
that collapsed the boundaries between high and low culture at a
time when those boundaries still meant something. Their music was
identifiable mainly by its sly repudiation of a genre-based
identity.
</P>
<P>
   All that is now history. In the last few years, the New York
downtown school has undergone a startling mutation, albeit one not
immediately audible to the innocent ear. Clubs like the Knitting
Factory and Tonic still feature many of the usual suspects, some of
them now approaching 50.
</P>
<P>
   The music has largely retained its brash, collage-driven spirit.
But beneath the appearance of continuity, a paradigm shift has
emerged. Once known for their rootless cosmopolitanism, downtown
musicians are now passionately searching for roots _ not
necessarily their own.
</P>
<P>
   The prime architects of the new sensibility are Zorn, who now
considers himself a Jewish composer, and Lindsay, whose new record,
``Prize,'' is the fourth in a series of albums inspired by
Brazilian popular music. But these are just two examples of the
intense curiosity about ethnic music that has gripped the downtown
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban popular music has served as a major source of inspiration
for downtown veterans like Ribot, now the leader of a band called
Los Cubanos Postizos, and the producer Bill Laswell, who has just
released an album of remixes called ``Imaginary Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Hwang, a Chinese-American free-jazz violinist who used to
play with the saxophonist Henry Threadgill, has formed a pan-Asian
improvising group, the Far East Side Band. The folk styles of the
Baltics and the Middle East, meanwhile, have strongly influenced
downtown musicians in their 20s and 30s, like the guitarist Brad
Shepik, the clarinetist Chris Speed, the drummer Jim Black (who
form the trio Pachora) and the ubiquitous trumpeter Dave Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the examples are analogous, of course. Some of these
musicians are investigating their ancestral traditions, while
others have no personal connection to their adopted styles. But
what unites them is an interest in music that evokes a community of
listeners bound by region, nationality or religion _ music that has
an identity.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown music has changed partly because New York has. Even
below 14th Street _ no, especially below 14th Street _ Manhattan is
no longer the edgy place depicted in Martin Scorsese's 1985 film
``After Hours,'' in which Starbucks wasn't ubiquitous and the
streets gave off a nervous spark.
</P>
<P>
   The Knitting Factory, now a mini-empire in TriBeCa, is part of
the arts establishment; ``Knitting Factory music'' denotes a period
style that is about as provocative today as Keith Haring's graffiti
murals.
</P>
<P>
   The aging of the downtown scene, along with its gentrification,
has led musicians to find new, unco-opted forms of energy in world
music. The current explosion is somewhat reminiscent of rock in the
1980s, when white stars afflicted with wanderlust surrounded
themselves with musicians from the Middle East (Peter Gabriel),
Brazil (David Byrne) and South Africa (Paul Simon). The difference
is that downtown musicians don't have the same obsession with
authenticity; their work is pointedly hybridized.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they are trying to tap into the almost magical
power that cultural identity possesses today.
</P>
<P>
   When Zorn performs with his free jazz band Masada at a synagogue
on the Lower East Side, or when the Brazilian-reared Lindsay sings
in Portuguese before an audience of samba fans and Brazilian
emigres, there is an almost palpable feeling of intimacy among
strangers, of community, that goes beyond esthetic pleasure. Such
music reflects an effort to provide audiences with a home in the
world, a coherent sense of place in a musical scene that has grown
bewilderingly global.
</P>
<P>
   And not just audiences, apparently. Zorn and Lindsay, who are
both in their late 40s and who occasionally play together, have
sought to find themselves _ and to moor themselves _ in the house
of ethnic identity. Their convergence is doubly significant, since
both musicians have an uncanny knack for predicting the next wave
and the power and influence to direct it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the downtown school's best-known musicians,
Zorn and Lindsay are its pacesetters, translators, ambassadors and,
not least, its savviest entrepreneurs. Zorn runs an experimental
music label, Tzadik (Hebrew for righteous man). Lindsay has
performed with Tom Ze, the Tristan Tzara of Brazilian Tropicalia,
and Vovo, the leader of the black nationalist carnival band Ile
Aiye; Lindsay has also produced recordings by Caetano Veloso,
Carlinhos Brown and Marisa Monte.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what led Zorn, a secular Jew from Queens, to his
awakening. In interviews, he has spoken vaguely of getting hostile
looks in Germany and of his father's death. What is certain is that
Zorn's study of Jewish history has transformed him and his music,
with results that are at once captivating and disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish themes have inspired some of his best, most rounded work.
The exuberantly ironic jump-cutting compositions that made Zorn's
reputation in the 1980s, notably ``Spillane'' and ``Godard,'' had
no central narrative, apart from the city's teeming energy.
</P>
<P>
   With Jewish identity, Zorn has hit upon something that holds and
concentrates his attention. In improvisational chamber works like
``Bar Kohkba'' and ``Issachar'' that conjure up the vanished world
of the shtetl with wit and sorrow while suggesting the affinities
between jazz and Jewish folk music, Zorn is a fine, patient
storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   He is by no means the first composer of Jewish ancestry to
examine his heritage: Leonard Bernstein did so in ``Kaddish,''
while Steve Reich has addressed the Holocaust and the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict in, respectively, ``Different Trains''
and ``The Cave.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zorn stands out in his attempt to cultivate a
self-consciously Jewish tradition. His band Masada is named after
the hill fortress where a group of first-century Jewish warriors
committed suicide rather than surrender to the Romans. The titles
of his compositions often evoke Jewish victimhood _
``Kristallnacht'' being a particularly explosive example.
</P>
<P>
   As a producer, he has presided over a thriving subgenre of
``radical Jewish music,'' including the trumpeter Steve Bernstein's
coyly atmospheric arrangements of cantorial songs and the
avant-garde klezmer of the clarinetist David Kracauer.
</P>
<P>
   Zorn's Jewish music reflects a deeper trend in the Jewish
community described by the historian Peter Novick in his new book,
``The Holocaust in America.'' Novick argues that an
``integrationist ethos'' that emphasized what Jews had in common
with other Americans has given way to a ``particularist ethos,''
emphasizing group identity, Israel and Holocaust memory.
</P>
<P>
   From his klezmer borrowings to the Hebrew-lettered shirts he
wears in concert, Zorn repudiates assimilation and dramatically
departs from the way American Jewish musicians have handled the
question of their identity.
</P>
<P>
   Among American minorities, only blacks have shaped this
country's musical culture more than Jews. But Jews like Irving
Berlin, George Gershwin and Stephen Sondheim have used music
primarily as a vehicle of Americanization rather than ethnic
self-assertion. Jewish jazzmen like Stan Getz and Steve Lacy have
regarded themselves not as ``Jewish musicians'' but as white
practitioners of an art largely created by blacks _ as participants
in one of America's few genuine experiments in cultural
integration.
</P>
<P>
   Until Zorn discovered klezmer, the only jazz musician to show
much interest in Eastern European soul was the black clarinetist
Don Byron.
</P>
<P>
   Zorn hopes to simplify the problem of ``Jewish music'' by
invoking an atavistic form of identity politics. Under the heading
``Great Jewish Music,'' for example, he has compiled album-length
tributes to musicians whose Jewish ancestry is incidental, if not
irrelevant, to their work, notably the French chanteur Serge
Gainsbourg and the proto-punk guitarist Marc Bolan.
</P>
<P>
   In part this is something of a prank, like Lenny Bruce's skit
about the spread of the Jewish urban sensibility. (``If you live in
New York, you're Jewish, even if you're Catholic. If you live in
Butte, Montana, you're goyish, even if you're Jewish.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Zorn's celebration of Gainsbourg and Bolan ultimately rests
on a racial definition of Jewish music that Jews have battled since
Richard Wagner published his notorious tirade ``Judaism in Music,''
in 1849. The fact that this definition is now being pressed into
the service of tribalism rather than anti-Semitism is little
consolation.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Zorn has spoken in almost hallucinatory tones about
what it means to be Jewish in America. Using language better suited
to 1920s Weimar than 1990s Manhattan, he has portrayed Jews as
``the world's outsiders,'' adrift in ``host cultures'' that will
never accept them.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine that Zorn, a consummate insider who is
nearly as powerful downtown as Wynton Marsalis is uptown, sincerely
believes that New York, the cradle of postwar Jewish culture and
power, is a ``host culture'' to Jews. The corollary to this view,
of course, is that the only authentic Jewish life is in Israel, a
conclusion that the composer, who is a longtime resident of the
East Village, apparently rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Zorn is committed to the idea of Jews as an eternal pariah
class, even in the face of considerable evidence to the contrary.
In a recent interview with the jazz magazine Jazziz, he exhorts his
fellow Jews to ``identify themselves as Jews'' and stop ``passing
for white,'' oddly echoing the rhetoric of some black jazz
musicians in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that for Zorn, Jewishness answers to a deeply felt
desire _ a desire not to be a white jazz musician. By invoking his
own history of oppression, he can assert his right to play the
blues, without the racial envy that often burdens white musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, his attempt to recast Jewishness as a defiantly
marginalized identity _ to claim victim status _ has an air of
calculation about it that overpowers his music. Ultimately, Zorn's
Jewishness will be primarily of interest to scholars of ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
