<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACTERIA-DEATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLESH-EATING BACTERIA' DEATH LINKED TO HEROIN USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A 39-year-old woman from Walla Walla died this weekend
at Harborview Medical Center from a ``flesh-eating'' bacterial
infection brought on by heroin use, public health officials have
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Despite surgical removal of dead and infected tissue from both
her arms, Linda Key died Sunday from a systemic infection that
could not be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Timothy Pohlman, the Harborview surgeon who attempted to
save Key, said half of all patients stricken with this rare but
severe and life-threatening infection _ more accurately known as
``necrotizing fasciitis'' _ appear to acquire it through injection
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be useful to know if it turns out there's a higher
association among this particular group of people,'' said Pohlman,
noting that injection drug use appears to be increasing in the
Puget Sound region.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, San Francisco public health officials dealt with a
rash of cases of necrotizing fasciitis, and deaths, among
intravenous drug users. Bacterial contaminants in injectable drugs
such as black tar heroin and methamphetamines were blamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This death is a real scare because we thought we didn't have
the problem they've been having in San Francisco,'' said Ron
Jackson, director of Evergreen Treatment Services, which provides
treatment for heroin addicts.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, a group of heroin users in Seattle were admitted to
Harborview with this life-threatening infection acquired through
bacterial contaminants in the drug. They survived, Pohlman said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not known how the Walla Walla woman became infected,
whether through a dirty needle, tainted drug or simply by bacteria
on her skin that entered her body through the puncture wound.
Authorities also don't know if any other drug users may be at risk
from a bad batch of heroin, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to know unless you track this,'' Pohlman said.
Key was the first of his patients to die from the infection among
those known to be addicts, he said. A spokesman for the King County
Medical Examiner's office, however, said there have been previous
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Hard numbers are hard to come by because unlike HIV, hepatitis
or E. coli O157, doctors are not required to report necrotizing
fasciitis to public health authorities.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, not much is known about the link between heroin
use and necrotizing fasciitis beyond the anecdotal reports and
personal experience of people like Pohlman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean we don't take it seriously or respond to a
cluster of cases,'' said Dr. John Kobayashi, senior epidemiologist
for the state Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with cases of ``flesh-eating bacteria,'' Kobayashi
said, is that they are very rare and seldom related because of the
typically non-communicable nature of this illness.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual cluster of five fatal cases identified in Spokane
last January all caused by streptococcal bacteria were investigated
by public health officials as a possible outbreak, he said. But
genetic analysis showed they were unrelated, he said, so it was
simply a tragic coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a dozen or two cases that occur in Washington
state every year,'' Kobayashi said. There can be a variety of
bacteria involved, he said, because the illness is caused not by
any particular type of organism but by where the bacteria infect in
the body.
</P>
<P>
   Necrotizing fasciitis can result when bacteria like strep or
staph are introduced into a blood-poor region of the body known as
the fascia, the connective tissue between skin and muscle. If an
infection takes hold, tissue dies off rapidly because of poor blood
flow and an inability to fight off the rapid bacterial progression.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ``flesh-eating bacteria'' when it was first reported in
the media, the infection can destroy tissue at the rate of an inch
per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Two other people have been reported hospitalized in Seattle with
necrotizing fasciitis, neither of them known to be associated or
linked in any way with the Walla Walla woman who died.
</P>
<P>
   One is a 31-year-old woman from Goldendale at Harborview who
remains in serious condition. A man, whose family asked that no
details be released, was transferred from an Olympia hospital to
the University of Washington Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   While any case of ``flesh-eating bacteria'' is of serious
concern, some contend those cases linked to injection drug use may
warrant special attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among injectors, the potential for rapid spread is great,''
said Michael Hanrahan, coordinator of the seven hypodermic needle
exchange programs operated by Public Health - Seattle and King
County.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Hanrahan said, it would be better if people stopped
using illicit drugs or at least used clean needles. But given the
reality, he said, there may be reason to track outbreaks of this
infection if only to try to prevent its further spread among drug
users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
