<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9521 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-JAZZ-MUSICIANS-3RD     09-28 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JAZZ-MUSICIANS-3RDTAKE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: of ethnicity.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike Zorn, the guitarist and songwriter Arto Lindsay gives the
sociologists little to chew on. Pleasure, rather than pedagogy, is
the aim of his erotically charged love songs in which fractured
poetry floats over a lush, perpetually mutating backdrop of
Brazilian popular music, guitar noise and drum-and-bass.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay is not Brazilian, but he spent his formative years in
Brazil, where his parents were Roman Catholic missionaries. He grew
up bilingual and absorbed early on the influences of Caetano Veloso
and Gilberto Gil. As a co-leader (with Peter Scherer) of the art
rock group Ambitious Lovers, he wrote a few songs in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until his 1996 recording ``O Corpo Sutil'' (``The
Subtle Body'') that he began mining the music of his Brazilian
childhood. After four such albums, each more daring than the last,
it's clear he made an inspired decision.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay isn't much of a guitarist, or even a musician, as he
himself admits with more than a touch of pride. (As a member of the
pioneering ``no wave'' band DNA in the early 1980s, he deftly
turned this defect to his advantage, earning a certain cachet for
the only sound he could reliably produce, a screeching distortion
now officially known in experimental music lingo as skronk.)
</P>
<P>
   But he is a stylish lyricist with a fine, deadpan voice, a
superb ear and a gift for assembling talent. On his last few
records, he has recruited an international dream team that includes
the Venezuelan producer Andre Levin, the bassist Melvin Gibbs of
Henry Rollins' band, the guitarist Vinicius Cantuaria (whose career
he has in turned helped to relaunch) and the Japanese keyboardist
and composer Riyuichi Sakamoto.
</P>
<P>
   The result is inadvertently but aptly described by a song on his
new record, ``Prize,'' as a ``subatomic machine where influences
breed.''
</P>
<P>
   The music on Lindsay's most recent albums occupies the border
between Brazilian and American pop, but then so does the music of
Brazilians like Carlinhos Brown. Lindsay's originality does not lie
in the fact that he crosses borders, but in his graceful,
unpretentious way of moving back and forth between his two
homelands.
</P>
<P>
   In albums like ``Mundo Civilizado'' and ``Prize,'' he has
seamlessly blended bossa nova and samba rhythms with rattling drum
samples, jazzy horn arrangements and the occasional skronk
explosion. As a lyricist, he doesn't seek to unveil the truths of
Brazilian or bicultural identity, whatever these might be.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers more personal (often sexual) kinds of illumination.
The songs on ``Prize,'' by turns clever and naked, suggest someone
torn between painful self-consciousness and a desire to surrender
to pure feeling (``Don't take fear too far/Let love be salacious,''
goes the chorus of one song.) Could this be the predicament of a
missionary's son in the tropics? Perhaps, but that hardly does
justice to Lindsay's acute, funky portraits of urban rapture in all
its beauty and violence.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem contrived that Lindsay, who would never be mistaken
for a Brazilian, sings a great deal of his material in Portuguese.
But he is not doing so for novelty's sake or to strike a pose. It's
simply a language in which he enjoys expressing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prize'' is stamped by its creator's identity, but it's not the
kind that turns up in census reports. Like the best pop, Lindsay's
neo-Brazilian music carves out its own figurative landscapes of the
soul. It comes from ``way down inside/in some interior life,'' as
one of his new songs says. The urgency of his exploration of
identity is musical, not ideological.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Zorn, Lindsay understands that it is not enough to affirm
one's roots; one must make something of them. Like all source
material in improvised music, identity is no more than a point of
departure. When it becomes the destination, as in Zorn's music, the
result is simply radical kitsch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
