<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9522 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DAME-EDNA-THEATER-2TA     09-28 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAME-EDNA-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAME EDNA SPEAKS HER MIND, AND YOURS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She sat alone at a small round table in what Barry
Humphries would later call ``that strange spooky room above
Sardi's,'' dressed in a sequined frock that had more going on than
the Times Square redevelopment project.
</P>
<P>
   The facade of Radio City Music Hall was appliqued on one
shoulder, an embroidered Broadway zoomed up the other, and her
eyeglasses _ the so-called face furniture that is so much a part of
her look _ were reminiscent of another imported lady, the Statue of
Liberty. With a torch at one temple and a row of spikes at the
other, the glasses make air-kissing an extreme sport. This was, of
course, her idea of New York day wear. At night, Dame Edna Everage
goes all out.
</P>
<P>
   The Melbourne, Australia, housewife turned international
megastar _ who may or may not be Humphries in drag (she says no, he
says yes) _ had shown up for lunch that day to discuss her
not-quite-one-woman show ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   In previews at the Booth Theater, where it opens on Oct. 17,
``Dame Edna'' is the Broadway debut of a cross-dressing character _
one must side with Humphries' version of the story _ whose
``natural wisteria'' hair color, and penchant for gladioli and
calling her audience possums are more famous in Britain and her
homeland than the drag queen Ru Paul is here.
</P>
<P>
   Although less well-known in America than in any other
English-speaking part of the world, Dame Edna has so far had no
trouble drawing a celebrated audience. ``I'm a luxury item. I'm
caviar. A special interest for the discerning few,'' she said of
her stateside status. Sylvia Miles, Monique Van Vooren, Michael
Feinstein and Isaac Mizrahi _ celebrities of a certain quirky ilk _
have already been to the Booth to see her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was determined to find a rhyme for Mizrahi,'' said
Humphries, 65, in an interview separate from Dame Edna's, a few
days after the fashion designer had been in his audience. As her
pianist, Andrew Ross, played ``Any Friend of Kenny's Is a Friend of
Mine,'' an anthem of motherly pride for a possibly gay son, Dame
Edna ad-libbed, ``I have to say so far, he hasn't met Isaac
Mizrahi.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, Mizrahi was likely to have heard Dame Edna talk of
her late husband, Norm, who met his maker only after years in an
``iron prostate,'' and of her mother, an albatross long confined to
a ``maximum security twilight home.'' There are Edna's children to
talk about, too _ her beloved son Kenny, a dressmaker who recently
relocated to the Chelsea section of Manhattan; his brother, Bruce,
a feng shui specialist, and Edna's estranged daughter, Valmai, who
now lives with a former East European tennis player and breeds pit
bulls in Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   All are characters in the Dame Edna mythology, a meticulously
detailed, carefully spun yarn that filled 284 pages of a 1989
``autobiography'' called ``My Gorgeous Life.'' Humphries'
autobiography, ``More Please,'' was published in 1992. Both life
stories continue to evolve.
</P>
<P>
   But when Humphries showed up at Oscar's restaurant in the
Waldorf-Astoria for a recent brunch _ nattily dressed in a gray
made-to-measure suit and a blue zigzagging tie _ it was a member of
his audience less celebrated than Mizrahi about whom he was
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other night I scared a very nice woman who looked like she
was from Long Island,'' he said. ``I don't think she was ready for
it. By intermission, she was gone.'' This doesn't usually happen,
even when Dame Edna tells a woman in the third row, ``I used to try
to make my own clothes, too.'' Or when she lambastes a latecomer
with ``I came all the way from Australia and I got here on time.''
``The ones who get away are few, but they do distress me,''
Humphries said.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Edna has that shriveling effect on the weak willed because
she often says what others feel guilty about even thinking. ``I
don't know how Edna does it,'' Humphries said of his creation's
candor. ``But she is sure that people hear the caring in her
voice.'' In other words, everything Dame Edna says, she says from
love. Her motto is ``I'm sorry, but I care,'' a belief that once
justified her imploring Jane Seymour, ``Tell me the secret of your
successful marriages.''
</P>
<P>
   Dame Edna's classic television moment, however, came when she
asked Roseanne, ``Is there anything you wish you hadn't eaten?''
That clip, along with a glimpse of Edna's long-suffering sidekick,
Madge Allsop, her 93-year-old bridesmaid and sometime Ed McMahon
counterpart, appear in a video montage detailing Edna's rise to
megastardom at the opening of ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Humphries recalls, Edna began when, as a member of
an Australian acting troupe, he wrote a housewife sketch. ``She was
a character created in 1955 for a revue that was going to last a
couple of nights,'' he said. ``The character was not intended to
have legs. I really wrote it for Zoe Caldwell to do.'' But his
reading was funny and the director suggested that Humphries go on
in drag. ``If Zoe had played it, she'd be doing the show at the
Booth and I'd be doing `Master Class,''' he mused.
</P>
<P>
   When Humphries moved to England in the 1960s, he temporarily
dropped his Australian act, which included such characters as Les
Patterson, a ``prodigiously endowed'' Australian cultural attache,
and Sandy Stone, an old man of the suburbs who, he said, is Edna's
male counterpart. As an actor, he played Fagan in a 1967 revival of
the musical ``Oliver'' in London.
</P>
<P>
   He reprised his duties when the musical opened on Broadway, at
the same time moving into a cold-water flat in Greenwich Village
and befriending some of the era's best known bohemians, including
Jack Kerouac. In 1972, he appeared as Edna Everage in Bruce
Beresford's first film, ``The Adventures of Barry McKenzie,'' based
on a cartoon strip that Humphries had written.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Edna first came to the New York stage in the 1970s. ``She
was looking more like a star and less like a housewife,'' Humphries
noted. Although she had made her name in various one-woman shows in
London, she was an unknown commodity here.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I came to Theater Four, it was like starting in
England again,'' Humphries recalled. ``I got a marvelous review
from Rex Reed, but it came out after the show closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dame Edna, of course, blames the auditorium and the audience.
``It was off off off off off Broadway,'' she said, adding, ``There
was a time when I was a bit too complex for America. I was
vulnerable in private before Barbra Streisand was vulnerable in
private.'' Today, however, Dame Edna feels audiences are ready for
her. ``I'm ready to expose myself to the majority,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While Dame Edna insists she is not Barry Humphries, Humphries is
more forthcoming. ``I think of it as a game and I think of it as
fun,'' he said of his creation's independence. ``Dame Edna insists
on being Dame Edna and regards crass assertions that she's a
cross-dressing weirdo from Australia as scurrilous and
actionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Edna does acknowledge knowing Humphries. ``You know a person
inside out,'' she said that day at Sardi's. When, as a Melbourne
housewife, she met him, Dame Edna remembered, ``He was dressed up
as a woman, which is a bit unsavory.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she considers Humphries a bit of a hanger on. When she
heard, for example, that six episodes of ``Dame Edna's Neighborhood
Watch,'' a British game show for which she served as host in 1992
on the BBC, are now available on videotape in America, she
criticized him as an opportunist ever eager to make money off her
talents. Still, she said, ``If it hadn't been for him, I wouldn't
be where I am today.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is gay-friendly and a bit of a dandy, Humphries is
not a drag queen. He thinks of himself as a character actor and
Edna as a role. He is married to Lizzie Spender, daughter of the
British poet Sir Stephen Spender, and has two sons and two
daughters, some of whom have come to New York to be with him during
the run of ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who don't believe a straight man could do such a
convincing job of playing a woman, Humphries says: ``Acting is
dressing up. Do they think Laurence Olivier was Danish because he
played Hamlet?'' Besides, he maintains that Dame Edna is not a drag
act: ``If Edna were doing a drag act, she'd have to dress up as a
man, wouldn't she? And she's never sung `Over the Rainbow' in her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from an extended run of the show in San Francisco _ ``the
Proclivity City,'' Dame Edna called it _ Humphries usually saunters
over to the Booth about an hour before curtain time. ``I check the
gladioli when I get to the theater,'' he said. These flowers, one
of his signatures, will eventually be thrown at the audience, an
idea he says he borrowed from the the soprano Joan Sutherland
decades ago and has never abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stagehands say, `The gladdies are looking good tonight,'''
an amused Humphries said. Then he proceeds to his dressing room to
do his own makeup. ``I like a moment when I can think quietly'' he
said. ``I'm moving from one life to another. As soon as the glasses
go on, I cease to be myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Dame Edna, he noted, owns about a hundred pairs of glasses that
Elton John would have envied in his prime. ``Edna has to dazzle,''
Humphries said. ``She's a bird of paradise to some extent, or a
vulture.''
</P>
<P>
   Onstage as the old bird, Humphries converses with the audience,
making up much of it as he goes along. ``As Barry, he's not funny
offstage,'' said Leonard Soloway, a producer of the show. ``It's as
if he turns a key in his brain and comes up with this stuff. The
other night he said, `I think I'm going to have a heart attack.
Maybe I should call this `The Angina Monologues.' He doesn't write
any of it down. He just does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphries says that some people have warned him about trying to
bring his particular brand of humor to America: ```You're going to
America,' they say. `Is that wise? They have no sense of humor, no
sense of irony.' It's usually a statement made by British comics
who have had terrible receptions here. They are constantly
underestimating the quick-wittedness of American audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he said, the funniest television _ save for ``Absolutely
Fabulous'' and ``Fawlty Towers'' _ is made in America. He has a
fondness for ``Friends'' and ``The Larry Sanders Show.''
</P>
<P>
   His own American television specials, while admired by
Edna-philes, never captured the audiences his British specials and
series did. ``The American television people were so nervous about
what Edna was going to say, it cramped my style,'' Humphries said.
Not surprisingly, he rails against the concept of political
correctness. ``It's fascism posing as liberalism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges, though, that his show is a bit strange for
American audiences: ``It's a character actor dressed up as an
Australian housewife who thinks she's a mixture of Barbra Streisand
and Jocelyn Wildenstein, with a little bit of Susan Sontag and
Martha Stewart thrown in. But I feel there's an audience for what I
do. People all over the world want to be entertained.''
</P>
<P>
   Dame Edna seems to have her Broadway debut in perspective. ``Not
everyone gets the point of me,'' she acknowledged, ``or I would
have to be playing Madison Square Garden.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
