<HEADER>
A9525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-BANKS-NYT &LR;      09-28 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN GIVES AMERICAN-LED GROUP RIGHT TO ACQUIRE BIG BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a landmark decision that gives foreigners the
go-ahead signal to take control of a Japanese bank, the government
on Tuesday granted an American-led investor group the exclusive
right to acquire the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, a former
financial giant hobbled by bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Reconstruction Commission, which regulates
Japanese banks, said that the group led by Ripplewood Holdings LLC,
a private investment firm in New York, had begun negotiations to
buy Long-Term Credit. Both sides said they expected to reach a
formal agreement by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A Ripplewood deal for the bank had been expected since last
week, when word began to circulate in Tokyo that the American
company was close to receiving Japan's approval to proceed. If the
deal is completed, Long-Term Credit would be the first Japanese
bank to be controlled by foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   The bank once was one of Japan's largest and most prestigious,
and it helped to finance much of the country's rapid recovery and
economic resurgence after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the government took control of the bank because of
enormous losses on loans that were not being repaid.
</P>
<P>
   Like many banks in Japan, Long-Term Credit made extensive
speculative loans in the 1980s that contributed to Japan's bubble
economy. Much of that speculation was in the real estate market,
which collapsed in the early 1990s, leading developers and
borrowers to default.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Financial Reconstruction Commission, Hakuo
Yanagisawa, said at a news conference on Tuesday that the
Ripplewood group had been chosen from a wide field of prospective
buyers because it best fit the government's criteria for
restructuring the financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Ripplewood group includes Deutsche Bank, ABN Amro of the
Netherlands, the Bank of Nova Scotia, Mellon Bank, the GE Capital
unit of the General Electric Co., Citigroup and Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   While some analysts have speculated that Ripplewood's real
intention in acquiring Long-Term is to liquidate its assets,
Timothy C. Collins, the firm's chief executive, said here Tuesday
that he was committed to returning the bank to its past prominence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We first started looking at the Japanese economy two years
ago,'' Collins said, ``and we concluded that while there were some
serious structural problems, it was still the second-largest
economy in the world, and that it would emerge from this situation
more powerful than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a memorandum of understanding signed Tuesday, the
international consortium will buy the common stock of Long-Term
Capital from the Deposit Insurance Corp., a government agency, for
1 billion yen, or about $9.4 million at current rates, and then
invest an amount equivalent to $1.13 billion in the newly created
bank.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will request a little more than $2.25 billion in public
funds from the Japanese government, the banking commission said,
adding that the government plans to pump a further $9.4 billion in
public funds into Long-Term Capital to cover the bank's leftover
bad-loan losses.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will be headed by Masamoto Yashiro, who is known for an
aggressive management style and for his success in running Citibank
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Yashiro said Tuesday that the new bank's viability would be
determined by how it provides Long-Term Credit's customers with
services and products they are now seeking from other international
banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
