<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9528 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSICALS-DANCING-ART-     09-28 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-DANCING-ART-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDISCOVERING AN OLD DRAMATIC PARTNER: DANCE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 Mindy Aloff is the dance critic for The New Republic.  
 By MINDY ALOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the last couple of seasons, the musical theater,
both in New York (``Fosse,'' ``Footloose'') and in London
(``Oklahoma!,'' ``Swan Lake'') seems to have rediscovered dancing _
not as an ornament or a practical interlude to entertain the
audience while the actors or singers change costume, but as a
resource in itself that can help advance the themes or story of a
show, or, in the cases of ``Fosse'' and ``Swan Lake,'' embody them
fully.
</P>
<P>
   How long this interest will last is anyone's guess. Still, for
Broadway habitues who remember the heydays of Jerome Robbins, Bob
Fosse, Michael Bennett and Tommy Tune, or even of George
Balanchine, Agnes de Mille, Helen Tamiris and Hanya Holm, all of
whom animated Broadway musicals to audiences' delight, the current
generation's attempt to reinvent the wheels within wheels that once
made Broadway choreography a distinctive and useful contribution to
the lyric stage is a touching effort. And, given the sea change in
American culture over the last two decades, a daunting one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The idea that innovation has meaning only in reference to a
tradition about which the innovators are thoroughly informed is a
classical perspective on art that has given rebirth to, for
example, Richard Wagner through Richard Rodgers and Giacomo Puccini
through Andrew Lloyd Webber. A love of the past, sensitively built
into an engagement with the present, can actually translate into
wide popular appeal, i.e., into box-office receipts, by speaking to
frames of reference that audiences already know, thereby drawing
them into new material.
</P>
<P>
   This love is different from pure imitation, which rarely
survives, and from appropriation, which tends to brutalize its
sources, and also to have a short shelf life. All styles of dancing
that have any staying power build on the past in a deeper, organic
way and turn their practitioners into scholars and historians by
default. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fascination with dance history and its attendant elements of
retrospection and perfectionism _ that anxiety to get all the
details reasoned out and clearly realized, because the gods one
internalizes as well as the ticket buyers one hopes to attract will
be watching _ is of some critical importance to at least three
forthcoming Broadway shows that feature dance.
</P>
<P>
   The shows, in various phases of production, are ``Contact''
(opening on Thursday at the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater), ``Saturday
Night Fever'' (Oct. 21, at the Minskoff Theater) and ``Swing''
(Dec. 9, at the St. James Theater). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its origins and working process, ``Contact'' _ essentially a
theater ballet in three parts, with direction and choreography by
Susan Stroman and a (largely tacit) book by John Weidman _ may be
the least dependent on historical particulars. In fact, its
underlying mechanism is not dance but rather a wordplay on the term
``swing'': swing dance and music, swingers in a sexual sense, the
act of swinging (as in the painting ``The Swing,'' by Jean-Honore
Fragonard, which provides the point of departure for the setting
and the choreographic conceits of the first section). Still,
dancing is the central language.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman's resume includes premieres for the New York City
Ballet and the Martha Graham Dance Company, as well as choreography
for the lamentably short-lived Kander and Ebb musical ``Steel
Pier,'' for the recent London revival of ``Oklahoma!'' (which she
reconceived with Trevor Nunn) and for the Tony Award-winning
``Crazy for You'' and ``Show Boat.'' So she appreciates both the
niceties of the concert stage and the theatrical necessities of
commercial enterprises. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I come from the theater, all of my choreography comes
from plot and characters,'' Ms. Stroman said in a recent interview.
``We now refer to `Contact''' _ the title of both the show as a
whole and of the third part on its own _ ``as a dance play. That
is, we took a company of dancers who act and actors who dance and
created a piece for them that has dance all the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was the ``Contact'' within ``Contact'' _ the section
most resembling a play with dancing, rather than a dance with
dialogue _ that Ms. Stroman and Weidman conceived first and that
Lincoln Center offered to produce as a self-contained entity at the
Newhouse, unless the collaborators had other ideas up their
sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Although they certainly did, and created ``Swinging'' and ``Did
You Move?'' as companion pieces, the third section remains for them
quite special, both the seed and the heart of the evening. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story of a disillusioned man who saves his own life through
the discovery of the joys of dancing _ in his case, of contemporary
swing dancing _ ``Contact'' incorporates Ms. Stroman's memory of
having visited a late-night dance club in New York's meat-market
district and observing there ``a girl alone in a yellow dress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew somebody was going to dance with this girl,'' Ms.
Stroman said, ``and that she was going to change someone's life.''
The Girl in a Yellow Dress (Deborah Yates) and the guy whose life
gets changed, here an advertising executive, are fantasized by Ms.
Stroman and Weidman into nightly reality. The swing dancing they
learn to do together is also the product of an idea, in Ms.
Stroman's words, ``of people connecting and touching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The real story of `Contact' is about someone who takes a
chance in unfamiliar territory,'' she said. ``Boyd Gaines'' _ the
ad exec _ ``as an actor who had to learn to dance for this show, is
also taking a chance. When he gets a panicked look in his eye as he
holds out his hand to the girl, it's not far from the truth.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weidman, who describes himself as ``dance-ignorant, an escapee
from Miss Komar's dance class in 1955 who has not looked back,''
emphasized that in all three parts of ``Contact'' (the show), he
and Ms. Stroman devised the story before undertaking the
choreography, although sometimes the rehearsals with the dancers
brought forward a plot element no one had thought of on paper.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in a stunningly wicked role-reversal finale for
``Swinging,'' a quartet for three dancers and a garden swing set in
pre-Revolutionary France, Weidman ``wrote a two-page description of
the events that would occur.'' Still, he said, the story felt
incomplete: ``The role reversal at the end, which I see as the
French Revolution, came out of the rehearsal process.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the spectrum _ in terms of its mission,
the length of its development (eight years), and its challenge to
overcome an ``original version'' _ is ``Saturday Night Fever,''
which has sought to translate to the stage the dramatic events,
characters, music and dance imagery of the 1977 film that managed
to catapult its composers (Barry, Robin and Maurice Gibb, aka the
Bee Gees), its star (John Travolta) and its dance focus (the
Hustle, a complicated relative of the mambo) into the Valhalla of
collective popular memory. (A new print of the film is scheduled
for release soon.)
</P>
<P>
   The show, a project dear to its conceiving producer, Robert
Stigwood, who also produced the film, has already been playing in
London for more than a year to capacity audiences, many of them
children, according to the director-choreographer Arlene Phillips,
whose work is familiar to New Yorkers from ``Starlight Express''
and ``Lord of the Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The dancing in this show goes much further than it does in the
film,'' Ms. Phillips said. ``In the film, they do more line dances
than actual Hustles. Also, in the film, the competition dancers who
surround the main character, Tony Manero, aren't trained dancers;
they're club dancers. In the 1990s, people know a lot more about
dance: their experiences of doing it and seeing it are much broader
than they were 20 years ago. We've taken what, in the film, was the
most important thread _ the dancing _ and have made big dance
numbers that reach a peak. In the show, we use the dance to
celebrate what dancing did for people of that time. It made every
person in the world feel that if he could walk or move, he could
dance. Robert Stigwood wanted to capture that feeling again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Phil Edwards, who is in charge of the dance and vocal
arrangements, notes that the Gibb brothers have written two new
songs for the show, and that the beloved songs from the film have
been ``subtly'' altered, through the addition of extra drum beats
and reworked keyboard patterns, to give the sound a ``subliminal
contemporary flavor.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As in all the shows, the dancing in ``Fever,'' which will have
an American cast in New York, is meant to function as a metaphor of
how a life can be beneficially transformed through the study and
practice of disciplined movement to music. And as in ``Contact,''
the challenge is to mix trained dancers, who can really do the
material justice, with actors who, though they are dance novices,
may be center stage in the stories.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phillips says her responsibilities as a director and as a
choreographer ``fight all the time.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As a director,'' she said, ``you want to bring out the dark
side of the story, the depth, the harsh truth. As a choreographer,
you're celebrating the magic and the dance. Sometimes, I've got to
pull down the dance, even though the dancers are doing a very
exciting move in a particular number, because James Carpinello, who
plays Tony, has a dance background but not a life in dance, and, as
he's on stage so much of the time, he physically couldn't go that
far in an evening.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With ``Swing,'' on the other hand, it seems as if nothing is
being spared to showcase bravura dancing, which will be crucial to
that show, as it doesn't have a proper book. Performing in it will
be some of the most heralded contemporary exponents of various
facets of swing dancing, from the Lindy Hop to hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's more than a revue,'' said Lynne Taylor-Corbett, the
director and overall choreographer. ``There's no Talmudic
dissertation or sociological material, but there is a message about
swing dancing, which is that you can't do it alone. What we know
about swing dance, which was especially popular between the 1920s
and the 1940s and is enjoying a comeback now, is that it never went
away. It underlies rock-and-roll, and it keeps morphing. No one
wrote something out and said, `Let's put this up,' but in the
course of developing the show, we began to group the dances and
musical numbers. Some of the groupings are shorter anecdotes, and
some are in a longer form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also knew that what would make the show really exciting was
to be as inclusive of as many styles of swing as I could find, and
to find as many championship couples to do it as I could. We have
Lindy Hopping, jive, Western, hip-hop. I'm putting them together as
a kind of privileged curator and theatricalizing the arcs of these
different dances.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In acting as a curator, Ms. Taylor-Corbett _ a veteran
choreographer of ballet and modern dance as well as of Broadway's
``Titanic'' and Hollywood's ``Footloose'' _ is working with a team
of associates and experts to construct the dances in the studio;
and she insists on giving them credit.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Manning, considered the inventor of the Lindy's aerobic
airsteps, contributed to them here, for instance. Rod McCune, the
dance captain, helped devise the adagio lifts, for which his
background as a cheerleader _ where he learned about thrown lifts _
came in rather handy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Fowler, the son and grandson of dancers, served as Ms.
Taylor-Corbett's associate choreographer. His job, he explained in
a recent interview, was ``to show where a step or a number can go,
and to be there as another brain.'' Fowler began to study tap, at
the age of 4, with his uncle (who danced for years with Fowler's
father in a tap act called the Fowler Brothers); in choreographing
one of the show's tap numbers _ Ms. Taylor-Corbett doesn't tap _ he
thought about his father and his uncle, using their up-on-the-toes
style of tapping.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his regard for Ryan Francois' and Jenny Thomas'
coaching of the company in refinements of the Lindy, Fowler said:
``As Broadway dancers, we go from show to show; we rarely are able
to perfect a specific act. Here, we even do ballet warm-up class. I
haven't done that since `Jerome Robbins' Broadway,''' in 1989. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The musical director Jonathan Smith, a former student of the
jazz pianist Ellis Marsalis, explained that the spirit of
perfectionism and authenticity extends to the songs (sung by Ann
Hampton Calloway, making her Broadway debut) and instrumental
numbers. The band, the Gotham City Gates, will be center stage.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate the connoisseurship that runs through ``Swing,''
consider that one musical number, ``Swing It, Brother, Swing,'' by
Raymond Bishop-Williams, was a trouve of a band member, Casey
MacGill, who heard it on a 1937 recording of Billie Holiday singing
it during an air check, and whose arrangement is based on her
distinctive performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In itself, connoisseurship _ that is, the levels of remembrance
built into theatrical imagery _ is not a predictor of commercial
success. Indeed, lacking a context of high originality and
friendliness toward the audience, it can prove a drawback. Still,
without it, musical theater is lost as a creative enterprise: its
practitioners grow cynical, manipulative and cold, and that is what
they teach their audiences to become, too.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for the teaching to take root, a student must be
complicit, either through laziness or fear of independent thinking
or of making some kind of mistake. Great audiences _ that is, those
who know what they feel and think _ may be blind on occasion, or
mix up details, yet they are never mistaken in what matters most:
they want transporting art, and sometimes they get it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
