<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9537 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LIMON-DANCE-$ADV03-NY     09-28 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMON-DANCE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIFFERENT PATHS OF GIANTS, CROSSING AT LAST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Susan Reiter's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
dancer-choreographer Robert La Fosse.  
 By SUSAN REITER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a dance student at the Juilliard School in the
1960s, Carla Maxwell studied with both Jose Limon and Antony Tudor,
two of the century's seminal choreographers. Aside from their
Juilliard connection, the two _ the first a pillar of midcentury
American modern dance, the other a master of subtle,
psychologically astute classical ballets _ were not likely to find
their paths crossing.
</P>
<P>
   But they will now. Works by these choreographers will share a
program when the Limon Dance Company, of which Ms. Maxwell is the
artistic director, comes to the Joyce Theater starting Tuesday for
a two-week season. The troupe will perform Tudor's 1937 masterwork
``Dark Elegies'' alongside Limon's ``There Is a Time,'' from 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maxwell calls the troupe's acquisition of ``Dark Elegies'' a
dream come true. ``When I first took over the company in 1978, we
thought it would be incredible to have a Tudor work,'' she said.
``But I don't think we had the company then. We were in transition.
Our present company is more suited to doing his work; there's a
different training, a different attitude. We're in a more stable
situation, and more able to hold onto the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Repertory choices have been a paramount concern during Ms.
Maxwell's tenure as director. Beyond maintaining the acclaimed
dances by Limon (who died in 1972) and his mentor Doris Humphrey
that had always been the company's raison d'etre, she has sought
out works, both old and new, to complement these standards and
challenge the company's dancers and audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The Joyce programs reflect this delicate balance between past
and present. In addition to ``Dark Elegies,'' the two major
additions to the repertory, both made possible by the company's
American Choreographers' Initiative, are Doug Varone's new ``The
Plain Sense of Things'' and a reconstruction of ``Champion,'' a
1948 piece by Sophie Maslow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Jose passed away, our mission has been to present
existing masterworks, dances by contemporary masters and new
choreography by the younger generation,'' Ms. Maxwell said recently
at the company's bustling studios and offices on lower Broadway. As
she talked, she removed the long, full practice skirt she had been
wearing for a rehearsal of Limon's ``Moor's Pavane''; she continues
to be a leading dancer with the company, which she joined in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Deftly switching into her artistic-director mode, she continued,
``We thought it would be exciting to explore works outside of our
own legacy, to see what works by other choreographers of that time
we could include.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maslow's ``Champion,'' based on a Ring Lardner short story
about a prizefighter and not seen since the early 1950s, became the
first such work the company acquired through the initiative. Donald
McKayle, who, in addition to his own choreographic and teaching
activities, has been the Limon troupe's artistic mentor and
resident choreographer since 1996, provided the crucial link. As an
18-year-old dancer, he performed in the original cast of
``Champion,'' and he suggested the piece to Ms. Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt it would be appropriate for our dancers because it was
dramatic (and that's our meat and potatoes) and had some humor in
it,'' Ms. Maxwell said. ``He felt we had the dancers who could make
it shine. I think he made a very astute choice; the range and
weight of the work suit our company.''
</P>
<P>
   No film or notation of ``Champion'' exists; there are only a few
photos and some contemporary reviews to draw on. The reconstruction
depended on the memories of Ms. Maslow and McKayle, working from
Samuel Matlowsky's original score, which has been adapted by David
LaMarche and will be performed live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had things I remembered in a rather broad way, and Donald
McKayle was a great help,'' Ms. Maslow said in a telephone
interview. An early member of Martha Graham's company who went on
to choreograph and perform with the Dudley-Maslow-Bales Trio (under
whose auspices ``Champion'' had its premiere), she is now in her
80s but vividly recalls the making of the dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite excited by the Lardner story,'' Ms. Maslow said.
``The people in it are not defined very clearly, except for the
Champion, who goes through life beating up everyone he has contact
with. ``I went to Stillman's Gym on Eighth Avenue to see how the
boxers trained,'' she recalled, explaining the source for the
dance's explosive second ``round,'' in which the boxers work out
while the women look on admiringly. She noted with surprise that in
present-day classes, ``most of the people doing it are women.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things may have changed since 1948, but the theme of
``Champion'' should still ring true: the less-than-admirable
private life of someone who is publicly touted as a hero. ``It's
the Mike Tyson story,'' Ms. Maxwell said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The muted, somber ``Dark Elegies'' draws on a completely
different side of the dancers. ``It is a great challenge because of
its formalism,'' Ms. Maxwell said. Sally Brayley Bliss, the
executor and trustee of the Antony Tudor Ballet Trust, encouraged
the company to add this work to its repertory, making it the first
modern-dance troupe to perform a Tudor ballet.
</P>
<P>
   She has approved their slightly different version, in which the
women are not on point, there is no set and the costumes are
adapted from the original designs. Ballet companies like American
Ballet Theater have had the score, Mahler's ``Kindertotenlieder,''
performed live by an onstage baritone with orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The Limon production, staged by Donald Mahler, uses a 1950s
recording featuring the contralto Kathleen Ferrier.
</P>
<P>
   While this season, which also includes a new 50th-anniversary
production of Limon's ``Moor's Pavane,'' pays considerable homage
to the past, the Varone premiere looks toward the future. Set to
Philip Glass's Saxophone Quartet and inspired by the paintings of
Edward Hopper, it reunites Varone with the first professional
company in which he danced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels very strong ties to the Limon legacy, and it has
inspired his own work,'' Ms. Maxwell said. So even this newest
addition to the repertory has links to tradition, just as the older
works will help push the company and its dancers in new directions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
