<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHASE-HAMBRECHT-ART-8     09-28 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-HAMBRECHT-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE AGREES TO ACQUIRE HAMBRECHT &AMP; QUIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN and PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Corp. agreed Tuesday to buy San Francisco-based
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist for $1.35 billion, giving one of America's
dominant traditional banks an entree into the world of Internet
start-ups and bringing it a step closer to becoming a full-service
financial concern.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed cash deal pairs two financial companies _ Chase,
the heavyweight banker for large corporations, and Hambrecht, a
boutique catering to Silicon Valley entrepreneurs _ that had begun
to look like lonely singles at a swinging square dance. Chase's
major competitors have all bought or merged with investment banking
firms. Hambrecht is the last of its class of finance firms that
catered to technology companies to find a larger and
deeper-pocketed partner.
</P>
<P>
   But the marriage, if it's consummated, falls far short of the
megamerger that Chase executives, and many on Wall Street, have
talked about for more than a year. The New York-based bank, the
third-largest in the United States, has made no secret of its
desire to complete a ``transformative'' deal that would create the
world's most potent competitor in everything from bank loans to
initial offerings of stock. Chase officials were quick to point out
that Tuesday's purchase did not fulfill those ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to say what this deal is and what it isn't,''
said Marc Shapiro, a Chase vice chairman. ``What it is is an
investment in the new economy. But as a total solution to the
global platform we are looking for _ we have not crossed that
bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hambrecht deal seemed to some analysts to be tacit admission
that Chase's recent overtures to Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter and Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., the three biggest Wall Street
firms, had been unrequited, at least for now. But many said that
they expected the consolidation in the financial industry to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we wake up one morning and find that Chase has merged
with Merrill? I don't think this changes that possibility,'' said
David Berry, a bank industry expert at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods.
``But for some reason, there's been no big deal for Chase so far.
And at some point you have to get on with life. This makes sense
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility, bank analysts said, is that Chase's pursuit of
Hambrecht signals its willingness to build a stock-underwriting
franchise brick-by-brick, rather than shelling out at least $30
billion to buy one of the top three Wall Street firms. That
suggests that Chase could try to buy a midsize underwriter like
Lehman Brothers or Paine Webber next.
</P>
<P>
   Though it leads the pack in the traditional lending business,
Chase had been slow to seize on the opportunity to expand into
stock underwriting. Competitors including Citigroup, Bank of
America and BankBoston have been quicker to snap up stock
underwriters when Depression-era laws that separated banks and
brokerages began being eased several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Hambrecht match also underscores the increasing importance
to the financial world of what analysts call the ``new economy'' _
high-tech and Internet companies that, at least in their early
years, are too small or lose too much money to do business with the
likes of Chase. Such start-up companies have often traditionally
relied on specialist firms like Hambrecht for financial guidance
because they were ignored by large banks and most Wall Street
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht's roots in the technology banking business run deep.
Daniel Case III, the chief executive, is the older brother of Steve
Case, chief executive of America Online. Hambrecht's reputation for
picking small but promising winners was made in 1980, when it
brought Apple Computer to market, and sealed in 1995, when it
backed Netscape's initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   For Hambrecht _ its name would change to Chase Securities West
if the deal is completed, as expected, by the end of the year _
Chase seems an ideal match after a long search. Case has talked to
numerous potential banking partners in the past, including the
German banks Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank, as well as Merrill
Lynch, bankers said. Hambrecht's relative position in
high-technology investment banking had slipped behind Goldman,
Sachs, Morgan Stanley and other top Wall Street firms in the past
several years, in part because it did not have the range of
services as its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our little entrepreneurial part of the economy has become the
dominant part of the total economy in the 1990s,'' Case said in a
interview at his headquarters, a distinctive steel and glass
structure designed by Mies van der Rohe in San Francisco's
financial district. ``But our ability to serve our clients has been
narrowed by products and geography. Now we can grow with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale is also a financial coup for Hambrecht executives.
Chase will pay $50 a share to buy the firm, 22 percent more than
Monday's closing price of $41.0625. It will also set aside $200
million in stock to retain key bankers at the combined firm. Shares
of Hambrecht rose $7.625 Tuesday, to $48.6875, a record high; Chase
fell 31.25 cents, to $73.8125.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht could bargain from a position of relative strength
this year after its underwriting business slumped in 1997 and 1998.
It underwrote 17 initial public offerings valued at $972 million by
Securities Data Corp. so far this year. That's almost exactly what
it underwrote in 1996, though its share of the business is less
than 5 percent now, compared with 15 percent three years ago. It
stock has more than tripled in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   For Chase, the benefits of Hambrecht are less certain. Their
main clients are on almost opposite poles of the economy. Chase
serves large corporations that have sophisticated banking needs and
proven profit records. Hambrecht prides itself in spotting new
companies that would not qualify for a bank loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely a substantial difference in the size of
our clients,'' said James Lee, a Chase vice chairman who heads the
bank's investment banking arm and sat next to Case to explain the
merger to Hambrecht employees Tuesday. ``But the wonderful thing
about the tech business is that those companies grow fast.''
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Chase has been trying to extend its franchise
into investment banking, with mixed success. It is the No. 1
provider of syndicated loans, one of the top three underwriters of
junk bonds and a top 10 player in mergers and acquisitions. But it
has yet to make a mark in equities, the core investment banking
business.
</P>
<P>
   Chase is not the first New York bank to go West to take
advantage of the prolonged boom in technology stocks. Two years ago
Merrill Lynch came very close to buying Hambrecht amid a spree of
acquisitions of midsize investment banks. Morgan Stanley and
Goldman, Sachs have also beefed up their West Coast presence and
grabbed larger shares of the technology investment banking
business. In terms of technology company underwriting, Goldman,
Sachs and Morgan Stanley are now No. 1 and No. 2, respectively, by
a wide margin. So far this year, Hambrecht ranks No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   A buyout by Chase would end the independence of the last
remaining member of a quartet of smaller technology-focused
investment banks based outside of New York that was known on Wall
Street as the HARM group. The group included Hambrecht, Alex. Brown
&AMP; Sons, Robertson Stephens, and Montgomery Securities. Within the
last two years, each of those firms has been gobbled up by a large
commercial bank and each of the acquisitions has been followed by
defections of large numbers of investment bankers and other key
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable example of post-merger conflict came after
NationsBank Corp. bought San Francisco-based Montgomery Securities
for $1.2 billion. A year later, Thomas Weisel, who had run
Montgomery, left to start a new firm and recruited several of his
highest-ranking colleagues to join him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are cultural _ the bureaucracy of a larger bank
being superimposed on an entrepreneurial shop,'' Weisel said
Tuesday, reflecting on his experience at NationsBank. Weisel said
he had respect for Chase executives, but predicted that they would
also face obstacles integrating Hambrecht.
</P>
<P>
   Case and Lee acknowledged that there was not a particularly
successful model for the sort of deal they are proposing, but they
said they expected a different result. ``This is about a lot more
than just a successful integration, but without a successful
integration nothing else matters,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chase is setting aside $200 million of stock to retain a
pool of Hambrecht's key employees. Case declined to say how many
people would share that money but he said it would be distributed
``broader and deeper'' than in other acquisitions in keeping with
the ``egalitarian'' culture of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said those extended payouts would not be the key to making
the integration work. ``Money can't fix a bad cultural fit,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Case and the man he referred to as ``my new boss,'' Lee, are a
study in contrasts. Case, tall and slim at 41, still looks the part
of the wunderkind he once was. A Princeton University graduate, he
joined Hambrecht after completing a Rhodes scholarship at Oxford
University. He was named co-chief executive in 1992 and sole chief
executive two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 46, in French cuffs and suspenders, looks and talks more
the part of the powerful New York investment banker. Chase
executives said the Hambrecht deal increased his responsibilities
within the bank. Lee already oversees Chase's substantial
syndicated lending and merger and acquisitions businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-VIRUS-ART-NYT     09-28 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FEARS ABOUT DEADLY VIRUS RISE, EXPERTS FIND ANSWERS ELUSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Mass., Wis.)  (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 BY JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While the discovery of the mosquito-borne West Nile
virus in the New York region has been fascinating for scientists
and public health experts, the concern among the general public is
more basic: People want to know if they are at risk for contracting
it, and they want to know where the virus is headed.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the exotic and inscrutable nature of West Nile
virus _ it had never been seen in the Western Hemisphere before it
was found in birds and humans in New York last Friday _ it is
impossible to completely evaluate its threat. Scientists and health
care experts have no idea how this disease even got to the United
States; theories range from smuggled birds to a single sick person
coming into the country.
</P>
<P>
   Given the mosquito spraying and cooling temperatures, it appears
that the chances of new transmissions to humans are relatively
small. But scientists confess that they are flummoxed by West Nile
and warn that too little is known about the virus and how it will
behave in its new home to give assurances. Its symptoms _ which
include fever and headache _ seem similar to those of St. Louis
encephalitis. Elderly people, young children and people with
weakened immune systems are most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hesitate to assign risk,'' said Andrew Spielman, a
professor of tropical public health at Harvard whose expertise is
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows, for instance, how long this region's birds,
which have never been exposed to the disease, can live with it.
That fact would determine, among other things, how many mosquitoes
can bite an infected bird, and how far the virus might travel.
``Obviously, this is a high-priority question,'' Spielman said. An
outbreak of West Nile is occurring simultaneously in Russia,
another area of the world where it had never been reported before.
</P>
<P>
   There have been well over 1,000 reports of birds dying suddenly
around the region since late July, and municipal health departments
have been receiving calls by the hundreds over the last week. Each
state in the region has been collecting bird samples and preparing
them for study at the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention; more than 50 birds from New York state have a
``presumptive'' diagnosis of West Nile, said Ward Stone, the state
wildlife pathologist.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hundreds of birds already collected will undoubtedly
have died from other causes. But local governments have become
alarmed and stepped up spraying campaigns. ``That's an
extraordinary number of bird carcasses to see in Bergen County,''
said William Schuber, the Bergen County, N.J., Executive, about the
80 dead crows found in his region over the last few days. ``We do
have concern. Finding one dead crow is unusual. To find so many is
very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's Department of Health has asked eight northern
counties to continue spraying insecticide until further notice.
Nassau and Suffolk counties sprayed one village each Tuesday night
and New York City officials said they would spray as needed.
Westchester County has halted spraying for the time being and
Connecticut began aerial spraying this week.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife experts became aware at the end of August that a
strange disease was infecting the bird population, because birds
were dying in large numbers. The experts ruled out St. Louis
encephalitis, because generally that illness does not kill the
birds that carry it. But in many ways, the clues stopped there. How
long can a bird live with West Nile before dying? Long enough to
fly far and wide and potentially spread the illness around via
mosquitoes that bite it? How long does it have to have been
infected for a mosquito that preys upon it to pick up the disease?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously one of the concerns is the widespread mortality, and
in more than one species,'' said Kathryn Converse, a
wildlife-disease specialist for the National Wildlife Health Center
in Madison, Wis., which is also evaluating dead birds from this
region. ``At this time, migrating birds are on the move, so we are
very concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Crows, which make up the majority of dead birds, tend to stick
close to home in the winter, though they can fly to other regions
if they need to. But they are not the only birds dying. Several
exotic species of birds at the Bronx Zoo have died in the last
month from West Nile virus. And common birds like sparrows,
starlings, robins and blue jays _ which tend to fly out of the
region in the fall and winter _ have been reported dying in unusual
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, in regions where West Nile is common, plenty of
birds live with it and never die, said Dr. Mahfouz Zaki, the
director of public health for Suffolk County and an expert on West
Nile virus. And because birds tend to carry the virus in their
blood longer than humans do, the time frame for mosquitoes to bite
them is long, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question of mosquitoes. All of the region has
been aggressively spraying for them and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, for
one, has said that this should keep residents mostly out of harm's
way.
</P>
<P>
   But Spielman of Harvard's School of Public Health said that
outdoor spraying _ which has been carried out during the day or
early evening _ was most effective around midnight, when mosquitoes
feed. There is also, he said, an indoor type of mosquito that
carries West Nile that is not being killed by outdoor spraying,
although an indoor mosquito would also be unlikely to bite infected
birds. And experts have no idea of the effect of cold weather on
this illness.
</P>
<P>
   In a final twist, it is possible that West Nile was already part
of the American landscape, and has been discerned only because of
the current outbreak. ``The big question is whether this virus will
perpetuate itself in the U.S.,'' said Spielman. ``It's an extremely
complicated issue. We just have no idea what might be going on
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
