<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GRAZIA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FIRE GRAZIANO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bob Graziano, hand-picked by Peter O'Malley to
take the Los Angeles Dodgers into new ownership and the new
millenium, has been fired as club president after less than two
turbulent years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano, who rose through the Dodgers finance department to
become the club's first CEO, oversaw the Fox-mandated trading of
Mike Piazza, the firing of manager Bill Russell and GM Fred Claire,
and the structuring of an $80 million payroll. He is the first of
many expected changes on the field and in the front office during
the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Welts, the head of Fox Sports who announced Graziano's
ouster, said the club will move quickly to name a successor,
although sources said Tuesday that Welts could wind up with the
job. He added that general manager Kevin Malone would be back for
the 2000 season despite the club's poor performance on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for the organization,'' said Welts, a former
NBA marketing whiz hired by Fox two months ago to oversee its
sports entities. ``But professional sports in the year 2000
requires a great range of skills. Bob's area is in finance, but
there are so many different elements that go into the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the turmoil that has surrounded the Dodgers since Fox
purchased the club in March 1998, Welts said he hopes fans realize
the team's lofty payroll and the scheduled $40 million in privately
funded renovations to Dodger Stadium are proof of a commitment to
bring a winner to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the final home game last Sunday, the
organization began the construction of more than 40 luxury boxes on
the press-box level that will be ready by opening day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a growing plan to generate more revenue for the
club, which has lost a reported $45 million the past four years. As
club president, Graziano, 41, was responsible for the business side
of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   And as the club began a three-game series against the Giants in
San Francisco on Tuesday, Malone had scheduled meetings with his
lieutenants to determine the fate of manager Davey Johnson's
coaching staff. Like Malone, Johnson's job appears safe. A
decisions on the coaches is expected before next Sunday's final
game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the front office also could be forthcoming. Graziano
hired or promoted department heads in business, finance and
accounting, and human resources.
</P>
<P>
   But to fans, the most significant difference next season will be
on the field, where the team was eliminated from the National
League Western Division race two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are committed to $66 million in salaries for next
season. But Graziano was told last month by Fox that he would be
allowed to absorb several guaranteed contracts if it made the team
more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The firing, which had been rumored since July when Graziano did
not receive a vote of confidence from Fox, was Welts' decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Graziano also met Sunday with Fox president Peter Chernin.
Fox was hoping to announce a successor when Graziano was removed,
but with so many people invested in his regime, Graziano insisted
on addressing Dodgers employees Tuesday morning in the Stadium
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed,'' Graziano said. ``I know there has been a
lot of rumors about my position with the company since the All-Star
break. With rumors, there usually is some basis to them. This
wasn't a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   But it clearly was difficult for Graziano, who had been with the
organization since 1986. Asked his opinion on the qualifications of
his successor, Graziano said reluctantly, ``I think if I did, I
would give you a description of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fox was impressed early on, Graziano, a USC graduate
and lifelong L.A. resident, never really shook his ties to the
O'Malley family, which owned the club for 46 years.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that the Dodgers had three managers and a losing
record during Graziano's presidency. But he stumbled attempting to
secure a long-term spring-training site after the club's longtime
spot in Vero Beach became financially untenable.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Graziano and Malone also flew to the Dominican
Republic to offer a three-year, $4.5 million contract for Montreal
manager Felipe Alou, who used it as leverage to secure a better
deal with the lowly Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Welts said Graziano's record had nothing to do with the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about lack of ability,'' Welts said. ``It is about
our vision of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Welts also spoke about reaffirming the team's commitment to
community service and preservation of the club's rich history.
</P>
<P>
   Then when asked if Fox had done more to undo the tradition of
the organization, Welts said, ``If installing luxury boxes is a
break with tradition, then we plead guilty. We had the opportunity
to buy a lot of teams, but we bought this one because we were
interested in its history.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziano was in charge of the transition from the O'Malley
family to Rupert Murdoch's media empire and acknowledges it wasn't
smooth behind the scenes. He didn't name names but said
philosophies between the old guard and new management often
clashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to understand the Dodger tradition because it is a
special character, a special set of values that set it apart,'' he
said. ``Growing up around them in Los Angeles, you see that
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that character, that integrity, that morality can be
difficult to maintain when there are so many new faces. I'm not
saying it's better, it's just different. But I hope the new person
understands that is what has set us apart from the rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
