<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Swooning Mets give little fight
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shea Stadium. What a perfect place for a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   To the roar of planes flying into LaGuardia Airport next door,
the Mets continued their crash and burn that started a week ago in
Atlanta. The three-game sweep at Turner Field all but won the
Braves the NL East title. Their 9-3 win in the first of a
three-game series here Tuesday night just rubbed it in Mets faces,
making their wild card hopes that much dimmer.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have won four in a row over the Mets, bringing their
record against New York to eight of 10 this season and 17 of 22 the
past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who continued one of the worst nose dives in baseball
history with their seventh consecutive loss, desperately needed
this one and the remaining two for their wild card hopes. Just when
they thought it couldn't get any worse, it did.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser was nothing but a target on the mound as the
Braves tagged him for five hits and four runs in the first inning
before he was pulled facing the eighth batter of the game. The sole
out Hershiser collected in the shortest outing of his 16-year
career was a Brian Jordan sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last of three RBIs collected by three Braves
hitters in the inning before the first pitch of Hershiser's relief
from Octavio Dotel, a wild one, allowed Ryan Klesko to score from
third. The Braves batted around before leaving the bases loaded on
Gerald Williams' fly-out.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones kept his personal MVP rampage against the Mets to
a dull roar, with two singles in his first four at-bats. Every
batter in the Braves' starting lineup reached base, seven of them
in the decisive first inning. Jordan homered for the first time in
125 at-bats going back to Aug. 15 to add a run in the third inning
and finished with three RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine, who moved to 13-11, beat the Mets in consecutive
starts for his first back-to-back wins since the last time the
Braves went on a Montreal-New York road swing in late June and
early July. Glavine spent most of the night dominating hitters with
a pinpoint fastball and mixing in breaking balls.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' offense, which was one of the best in the National
League by the books, has been amazingly bad for the past week. In
the first six games of this losing streak, the Mets had gone
5-for-40 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
