<HEADER>
A9547 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     09-28 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX CONTINUES TO PUT ITS MARK ON DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The latest personnel move by the Los Angeles
Dodgers is best summarized by the subtitle of Fox's ``X-Files''
movie:
</P>
<P>
   Fight the Future.
</P>
<P>
   The team owners at Fox continue to put their own mark on the
franchise _ it looks like a footprint _ by getting rid of anything
and anyone remotely connected to the former owner, Peter O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   Firing Dodgers President Bob Graziano, as the club did Tuesday,
hardly ranks with trading Mike Piazza for some bad fish or shoving
Tommy Lasorda into a corner office and telling him to stay out of
the dugout. But it certainly is the latest episode in an
increasingly gory drama.
</P>
<P>
   How is a Dodgers fan supposed to look at this and not feel
queasy, or queasier, about the team's future? Graziano was the
Dodgers' point man on all of the intimate financial details of the
sale and the stormy transition period.
</P>
<P>
   He had his critics, who viewed him as Fox's front man for the
changes of the last two seasons and potential changes down the
road. But he did understand the very unique character of the
franchise and its even more unique relationship with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he was asked about the wrenching changes in the
organization and the possible issues forthcoming, like ticket
prices and a new stadium, you didn't feel he was paying lip service
to the questions.
</P>
<P>
   That can't be said of the Foxies running the team, whose actions
speak for themselves _ the Piazza trade, all the dead bodies in the
1998 front office purge, and the hiring of outsiders (Kevin Malone,
Davey Johnson) with little understanding of the team's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Welts underscored that fact by his comments Tuesday. He's
the President of the Fox Sports Enterprises unit that oversees the
club, the fellow who ominously moved into the Dodgers offices, and
above Graziano in the food chain, earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was looking for a team president who understood the
revenue challenges of owning a baseball team in the 21st Century
and ``someone who understands the heritage of the organization, who
has the ability to weave the history of the Dodgers into future.''
</P>
<P>
   My personal B.S. detector alarm clanged loudly upon hearing
that. Based on that description, I asked Welts if that meant
Graziano's replacement would have personal, hands-on experience
within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``There are candidates who fall into that
category, but someone doesn't necessarily have to have been part of
the organization to grasp what its history means.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the perfect answer, of course, because it allows Fox to
put just about anyone in charge and say he understands the
franchise. That's essentially the Fox modus operandi. All of Foxies
in charge _ Welts, Chase Carey and Peter Chernin _ say they
understand the team, even though they never came closer to the team
than a box seat before the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Under this criteria, I would be an excellent candidate for team
president. I have scrapbooks going back to 1958, can name all 25
members of the 1959 World Series team, including Chuck Essegian
Chuck Churn, and have been a member of the carping L.A. press since
the World Series team of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   While I sat ringside for the A's beating of the Dodgers, Welts
was a ballboy for the Seattle SuperSonics and Carey was an
undergraduate at Colgate. But they understand the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what Graziano had failed to do as president, Welts,
who spent 17 years in the NBA's marketing department before joining
Fox, did a pump-fake in the lane. ``Bob had different experiences
than I thought we needed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running teams in the year 2000 are different and more
challenging than they used to be. For any franchise, this is a very
complicated job which requires a tremendous range of skills.''
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking baseball skills here. The skills Welts means
are all the things that strike fear in fans _ selling name rights
to stadiums, raising ticket prices, finding ``new sources of
revenue'' (translation: new ways of digging deeper into your
pocket), negotiating public subsidies and positioning teams for new
stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano was disappointed, but he refused to criticize Welts or
anyone at Fox, other than saying he doesn't think the kind of
person Fox describes _ other than himself _ actually exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went searching for a General Manager, I didn't find
anyone out there who has (that) the kind of baseball and business
experience,'' said Graziano, who will stay with the club for a
brief period during this transition. ``I'm not saying he doesn't
exist, but I haven't met that person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is very hard to understand Dodgers tradition and
character. The organization has always had a special sort of
values, and I think you have to experience that closely to know
what that means. Having been with the team for 14 years, I think I
understood what it means.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Dodgers' sake, I hope they're successful in finding
that kind of person.''
</P>
<P>
   Welts wouldn't name names when asked for candidates. But it
would be a shock if Fox didn't talk to 1984 Olympic chief and
former commissioner Peter Ueberroth, who has the combination of
business sense and sports experience that fits the job description.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you won't recognize any other names. Many baseball
owners serve as their own team president (San Francisco's Peter
Magowan, Baltimore's Peter Angelos), and those that don't usually
hire presidents who can read an annual report but couldn't score
game. The sports experience of the Angels' Tony Tavares, for
example, was limited to facility management before being put in
charge of the Angels and Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around a lot of sports teams and watched some good
organizations,'' said Welts, ``and success never comes without
change. But the Dodgers need change and need to improve. If you
want to characterize that change as turmoil, I guess you can.''
</P>
<P>
   And we will, until Fox proves us wrong or the team moves back to
Brooklyn, whichever comes first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
