<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOL-NISHI-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISHIMOTO MOVES TO HEAD OF CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KERRY MURRAY  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Five years ago, Keri Nishimoto stood in a
line filled with other high school players at the Long Beach State
volleyball camp.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, each player would go through a drill and then jog to
the back of the line, chatting and laughing as he or she waited to
go again.
</P>
<P>
   Nishimoto, though, was different.
</P>
<P>
   She made a mistake and assistant coach Debbie Green corrected
her. Nishimoto then jogged to the back of the line like the rest of
her fellow campers. But unlike the others, she began practicing
what Green had just told her.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Green knew she wanted the 5-7 setter from
Redlands High School to play for LBSU in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Brian Gimmillaro was skeptical at first, but Green said
she saw something in Nishimoto that would set her apart from the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   No, she was not a Sheri Sanders, the All-American who set with
such athletic grace for the 49ers in 1988 and 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was she a Sabrina Hernandez, the ultra-competitive 49ers'
setter of the early 1990s, and an All-American in '92.
</P>
<P>
   And Nishimoto knows that she does not possess the skills that
two-time AVCA Player of the Year Misty May revealed in her tenure
at Long Beach, dominating the entire court with her athleticism and
play above the net.
</P>
<P>
   What Nishimoto has to offer is different a trait that she not
only uses on the court, but in every other aspect of her life as
well.
</P>
<P>
   To state it simply, Nishimoto is smart, and after two years of
serving as back-up setter to May, the redshirt sophomore is finally
getting the chance to showcase just what her brainpower can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is much easier if you're able to use your
intelligence in competition,'' Gimmillaro said. ``And Keri is a
very bright player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright is right.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Nishimoto earned a full scholarship not for volleyball,
but for her academic success. She was a class valedictorian at
Redlands who scored so well on her college entrance exam that she
was named a National Merit Scholar.
</P>
<P>
   Nishimoto probably could have applied to any school in the
country, but the setter had her sights set on playing volleyball
for Long Beach State.
</P>
<P>
   Each summer, she continued to attend the volleyball camps put on
by Gimmillaro and his staff, and by her junior year she decided to
make an oral commitment to the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, she found out that she was selected as a
President's Scholar at Long Beach, an honor that included an
academic scholarship to cover her education costs.
</P>
<P>
   The President's Scholar Program, started by Long Beach State
President Robert C. Maxson in 1995, awards National Merit students
and valedictorians with a scholarship package that includes
tuition, general student fees, books and paid housing in the dorms.
Eligible students are asked to write essays, which are then
considered by a committee.
</P>
<P>
   Since the program's inaugural year, there have been 308
President's Scholars, 12 of whom have been student-athletes.
Nishimoto is the only women's volleyball player to carry the
prestigious title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come here for volleyball and if I could get a
scholarship that way it would mean one more scholarship for the
team,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During her senior year at Redlands, Nishimoto did receive other
volleyball offers - most notably an invitation from Pacific, now
the No. 1 team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   She said the decision difficult, but ultimately she and her
parents believed she would receive the best training at Long Beach
State.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who predominantly works with the 49ers setters, said many
of the girls from Nishimoto's class shied away from Long Beach
since May was only half way though her stay with the 49ers and
still going strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many would see setting behind Misty as a wasteful year,''
Green said. ``Keri saw it as an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the highly awarded May is gone, Gimmillaro has gone
back and forth between using Nishimoto and true freshman Brittany
Hochevar at the setting position.
</P>
<P>
   Hochevar got the start for the first three matches, but
Nishimoto made her debut in the second game of the USC match
(fourth match of season).
</P>
<P>
   Since that victory, Gimmillaro has tended to use Nishimoto in
some of the bigger matches, including matches against Hawaii and
Colorado. Hochevar got the start against No. 1 UOP last Saturday,
but after a game and a half, Gimmillaro once again turned to
Nishimoto.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has great emotional control,'' Gimmillaro said. ``I can
tell her something in the middle of the emotions of the match and
she can understand what I'm saying and execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nishimoto said the switching of the setters has been frustrating
because it can be difficult to get in synch with the team, but said
she knows that both her and Hochevar's different skills are needed
at different times.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who ultimately claims the position though, Nishimoto
said she plans to stick around and use all four years of her
eligibility. Although she is a sophomore as far as volleyball is
concerned, Nishimoto is nearing the point of senior status in her
academics.
</P>
<P>
   Graduate school, she said, is always an option. Meanwhile, she
just plans to continue hitting the books to maintain her almost
perfect GPA (Nishimoto has only one B) and focus on volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Misty May and I'm not trying to be,'' Nishimoto said.
``I bring something different to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   So even if the 5-7 setter doesn't carry on the All-American
tradition at Long Beach, Nishimoto will leave the program with a
fully paid college education, and a reputation for high
intelligence, both on and off the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
