<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANKIEL-ARREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials: Ankiel worked for Bahamian smugglers
 &HT;    By Michael Van Sickler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ Richard Ankiel, the father of rookie St.
Louis Cardinals pitcher and Port St. Lucie High standout Rick
Ankiel has been linked with a sprawling Bahamian smuggling network
widely known as the Captain Jump-Off gang.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Ankiel, 42, and three others were charged by the U.S.
Attorney's Office with conspiracy to distribute marijuana and
cocaine. Ankiel faces a maximum prison sentence of 80 years and $4
million in fines on both charges.
</P>
<P>
   The federal charges were filed Sept. 22 against Ankiel; Phillip
W. Kennedy, 25, and Cindy L. Rohn, 42, and Dale Jackson, 41, both
of Fort Pierce. They are accused of moving ``vast quantities'' of
drugs for the smuggling ring, said Al Westerman, a U.S. Customs
Service agent in Fort Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel and the others were not arrested, Westerman said. They
are scheduled for a first appearance today in federal court in West
Palm Beach in front of U.S. Magistrate Linneas Johnson. Neither
Ankiel nor his son or other family members could be reached for
comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The charges are the result of a yearlong investigation into a
drug-smuggling operation led by Richard Barker, also known as
Captain Jump-Off. Barker, who was sentenced to life in prison in
June for drug smuggling, acquired the nickname Captain Jump-Off for
smuggling illegal immigrants and forcing them into the water at sea
rather than ferrying them safely to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens arrested as a result of the investigation were
a U.S. Coast Guard petty officer in June and a Fort Pierce
volunteer police officer in late July.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel has a criminal history dating to four years before the
birth of his son. In 1975, Ankiel was found guilty of marijuana
possession and served 30 days in jail. Over the next 24 years, in
between Little League games and fishing trips with his son, Ankiel
was arrested 14 times on charges including burglary, carrying a
concealed weapon, aggravated assault, fleeing police, and hit and
run with an injury, according to Florida Department of Law
Enforcement records. Those records show he has at least six
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   In December, St. Lucie County sheriff's deputies responded to a
domestic battery call from the home of Cindy Rohn. She had a large
bump over her left eye and accused Ankiel of throwing her on the
tile floor. Ankiel, who is married, told deputies he was Rohn's
boyfriend, according to deputies' reports. Ankiel said he had been
in a tussle with his son and that he accidentally knocked into
Rohn. The charge was dropped the next day.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, Ankiel was charged with driving under the influence.
He has an Oct. 12 court date on that charge.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Rohn, the others charged along with Ankiel
have extensive criminal records, according to Florida Department of
Law Enforcement records.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy has been arrested 28 times in six years, including
charges alleging marijuana possession, purchasing and possession of
cocaine, shoplifting, rape, car theft, and burglary. He has four
felony convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has been arrested 16 times over more than 25 years on
charges including hit and run, illegal use of a fishing net, and
possession of explosives with the intent to harm. He has one felony
conviction and numerous misdemeanor convictions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Jackson was arrested with 12 others who federal drug
agents said belonged to a Palm Beach County drug ring called the
Pinder Ring. The ring was named after Claude Avon Pinder, nicknamed
``Kingfish,'' who pitched a no-hitter for the 1957 Palm Beach High
School team and was scouted by the Yankees. Instead of pitching,
Pinder formed an extensive drug ring. He was sentenced to 30 years
in federal prison in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who was 30 at the time, was nicknamed ``Offload''
because he supposedly unloaded marijuana shipments. When he was
brought into the Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office in 1988 for
questioning, he wore a ``Lanie Norvell for Sheriff'' baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Van Sickler writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Thomas R. Collins contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
