<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-AD-COLUMN-835&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AT ATLANTIC MONTHLY, TENSE STAFF MEETS NEW OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At The Atlantic Monthly in Boston on Monday afternoon, staff
members huddled around to hear the grim news.
</P>
<P>
   There was the crackle of interstate static. Then, the
disembodied voice of Mortimer Zuckerman, the New York real estate
baron who has owned the magazine since 1980, wafted tinnily through
the room: He was selling the magazine, a 142-year-old cultural
institution that printed the first published words of Emerson and
Thoreau.
</P>
<P>
   The news did not go over well _ partly because it was delivered
by Zuckerman via speakerphone, ``which was truly a postmodern
experience,'' one staff member said with a sniff. More important,
though, the staff was upset to learn that William Whitworth, the
editor who has steered the magazine for two decades, would be
replaced by someone unknown to them, a Washington editorial
upstart, Michael Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   But the tension was eased considerably by the soothing presence
of the new owner of the noble, barely profitable monthly. He is
David Bradley, chairman of a little-known research company, the
Advisory Board, and a little-known media company, the National
Journal Group, both based in Washington. A self-effacing
multimillionaire, Bradley, 46, speaks in tones so dulcet he sounds
more like a sympathetic psychotherapist _ or the sweet-natured
Rogers of television fame, perhaps _ than the ferocious new media
mogul on the block.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the magazine's headquarters Tuesday to
confront a tearful staff at a noontime meeting, Bradley smoothed
ruffled feathers with such expertise and assurance that the
managing editor, Cullen Murphy, said employees who had been angry
or fearful were suddenly smiling. Bradley promised not to change
the editorial direction of the magazine; he also said he had no
immediate plans to change the makeup of the staff or move the
offices to Washington. ``Everyone felt a lot better after the
meeting,'' Murphy said. ``I did not expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when most magazines that purport to address any
intellectual subject _ The New Republic, The Nation, Harper's, The
Atlantic Monthly _ are either supported by foundations or eke out a
small profit, Bradley may turn out to be the cowboy in the white
10-gallon hat. If he can turn The Atlantic Monthly into a
profitable venture that retains its original sense of mission _
delivering poetry, criticism and literature along with provocative
international and political reporting, a mixture that has earned it
nine prestigious National Magazine Awards in two decades _ he may
prove that magazines with an intellectual bent have a chance of
economic survival.
</P>
<P>
   Under Zuckerman's watch, an executive who works for his real
estate company said, The Atlantic Monthly typically lost $500,000
in a bad year and earned $500,000 in a good year. But Bradley, who
with a law degree from Georgetown University and an MBA from
Harvard is at his core a businessman, did not spend $17 million _
the figure cited by executives on both sides of the transaction _
to produce a magazine that loses money.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seemed an unlikely candidate for media stardom until
just a few years ago. The Advisory Board, the company that he
founded in 1979 _ equipped with four card tables and four Princess
telephones, in his mother's Watergate apartment _ is, in Bradley's
words, ``a for-profit think tank.'' The company gathers research
for 3,000 American corporations in fields ranging from banking to
universities to health care.
</P>
<P>
   It was his purchase of the National Journal Group from Times
Mirror Co. in 1997 that transformed his growing empire from one of
policy research to one of politics and media savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the publications owned by the group are National Journal,
a weekly magazine of government and politics that has won two
National Magazine Awards; Government Executive, a monthly magazine
of government management; The Almanac of American Politics; The
Hotline, a daily Web-based publication covering political
reporting, and Congress Daily, a daily report from Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   National Journal, with a circulation of 7,000 and an annual
subscription price of $1,047, has a tiny audience. But since
Bradley raised the editorial budget by 50 percent and hired Kelly,
the deposed editor of The New Republic, to be editor in chief,
National Journal has attracted well-known writers like the legal
analyst Stuart Taylor; William Powers, who had been a press critic
for The Washington Post, and Carl Cannon, a former White House
correspondent for The Baltimore Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a safe test of entering into the magazine field,''
Bradley said, speaking of National Journal. ``It's got a
significant but limited readership. So you can make mistakes and
people will still be forgiving. But how do you step forward into a
much more frightening space? The Atlantic Monthly is a retail
magazine where you're not allowed to charge a thousand dollars for
a subscription and when you make mistakes you will be a source of
joy to people who like to read about stumbling.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   National Journal had one such moment in April, when Taylor found
himself in a conflict-of-interest battle after it was disclosed
that he had considered going to work for Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel. Taylor made apologies on every talk show in
existence, turning his stumble into an unwitting public-relations
coup for the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Bradley took part of his company public, netting
him $142 million. With his status as multimillionaire, and with the
National Journal Group and The Atlantic Monthly under his belt, he
has assured his spot in media moguldom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodness!'' he shrieked in a telephone interview Tuesday.
``How can you say that? What is fair to say is that I have
increased my share of interests in magazines. But look, Henry Luce
started Time when he was in his early 20s. I'm 46.'' So? ``I think
you need to start younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who will be editor in chief of The Atlantic Monthly, said
he had no plans to change anything. ``Making a business out of
creating and selling a great magazine _ a magazine that consciously
exists on a pretty high plane and does not dumb itself down or tart
itself up _ is a pretty tough row,'' he said. ``The identity of The
Atlantic Monthly is about literature and about journalism that
aspires to the level of literature. It is about the serious,
untrendy, un-buzz-driven discussion of ideas. All of those things
have to continue. That is what the magazine is.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the world of magazines depends for much of its revenue on
the world of advertising _ an industry known for its love of that
mysterious blend of public relations and cocktail-party chatter.
Alan Jurmain, the media partner at Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS, said: ``You
need some form of buzz. You'd like buzz to be something that comes
from within, that is authentic, and I think they have a terrific
product but they haven't had the wind at their back for a long
time. If this guy can create a breeze, they can be on their way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said he would begin spending a lot of time with the
magazine's staff in Boston. As for Bradley, the staff of The
Atlantic Monthly is still trying to figure out just who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't there a novelist named David Bradley?'' said Murphy, the
managing editor. ``I guess that just shows where my head is at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
