u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS--1STL     09-28 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS--1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN OPPOSITION PARTIES FAIL TO UNITE BEHIND ONE PRESIDENTIAL
CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (inserts Cardenas quote after 7th graf)   (bl)  
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Talks among opposition parties to forge a
coalition that would back a single presidential candidate collapsed
on Tuesday, greatly increasing the chances that the party that has
controlled Mexico for seven decades will win power once again in
elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown of talks to form a coalition is a huge setback for
Mexican voters who hoped to see an opposition leader take the
presidency and its vast powers away from the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, which has elected every president since the
1920s. The results of recent opinion polls as well as most state
elections across the country show that these voters are in the
majority.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition could handily beat the governing party, or the
PRI, in the vote on July 2, 2000, if the parties and factions
joined forces. But if the opposition is divided among two or more
candidates, as will now be the case, each one will face an uphill
battle.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown came after four months of nearly round-the-clock
negotiations between the right-of-center National Action Party,
known as the PAN, and the other main opposition group, the
left-leaning Party of the Democratic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the PAN and its presidential candidate, Vicente Fox
Quesada, made the decision to reject the coalition. The PAN, a
pro-business party, could not muster enough trust in the Party of
the Democratic Revolution, which has often been its fierce
ideological opponent, to accept a face-off in a nationwide primary
to select a single candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The issue on which the coalition foundered was the rockiest one.
The two parties could not agree on how to choose between Fox, who
initiated his quixotic quest for presidency two years ago, and
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, the leader of the leftist party.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas resigned on Tuesday as mayor of Mexico City to launch
his third bid presidential bid. He is believed to have won once, in
1988, only to have it stolen from him by fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just shows that the PAN is not willing to submit a
historic decision to a popular vote,'' Cardenas said. ``It shows
that they are not ready to join the authentic opposition to the
PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The opposition parties named a council of 14 distinguished
citizens to come up with a method to break the deadlock. The
council suggested a hybrid approach combining proposals from the
two parties. It called for a primary of pre-registered voters to be
held with 12,000 polling stations across the country (far fewer
than in a regular national election), whose results would be
reninforced by opinion polls before the balloting and exit polls
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The Party of the Democratic Revolution as well as six other
small opposition parties that participated the coalition talks
accepted the council's plan.
</P>
<P>
   But in announcing the PAN's decision on Tuesday, Diego Fernandez
de Cevallos, a veteran PAN leader and its lead negotiator in the
talks, called the plan ``simply aberrant.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary ``is based on no electoral law and has no
authorities to monitor it and guarantee its fairness,'' Fernandez
de Cevallos said. ``Frankly, we are not interested in participating
in something so irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled an election Cardenas' organization held in March to
choose its own president. The first time around, the election ended
in chaos as the contenders loudly accused each other of vote
tampering. That election had to be canceled and a new, better
organized one held two months later.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez added that the citizens' council had failed to clarify
what would happen if the primary gave one result and the polls
turned up another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico doesn't come to an end if there is no alliance,'' he
said dismissively in a television interview early Tuesday. ``Mexico
will still be here.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the height of its powers in the 1960s and '70s the PRI faced
no serious opposition and won most elections by huge margins. But
the party's popularity eroded in the '90s as extravagant corruption
by its leaders came to light while millions of Mexicans were driven
into penury by its disastrous economic management.
</P>
<P>
   In recent elections, the PRI has shown it has the solid support
of about 40 percent. Consistent support for the PAN is slightly
below 30 percent, as is the showing for the Party of the Democratic
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans overwhelmingly wanted the opposition to join together.
In a national poll published on Tuesday morning by the daily
newspaper Reforma, 63 percent said they were in favor of the
opposition coalition while 24 percent were not.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also showed the chasm that has opened among voters. Fox
was favored to be the coalition candidate by 60 percent of those
interviewed, while only 19 percent favored Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles to a partnership between the two big opposition
parties were legion. Many PAN followers are fervent Catholics. The
party favors free trade and independent entrepreneurs and is
opposed to a dominant role for the state in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Party of the Democratic Revolution, by contrast, descends
from the tradition of Cardenas' father, the fondly-remembered
president who nationalized Mexico's oil industry. Its members
believe strongly in the country's strict separation of church and
state.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties have waged angry policy battles over the $96
billion bank bail-out and plans to privatize the electrical
industry, among other hot debates.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The coalition was also hampered by a restrictive federal
electoral law, written by the PRI, which makes alliances all but
impossible. In order to run a single presidential candidate, the
opposition parties also had to settle on one candidate for every
one of the hundreds of seats in the federal legislature, which also
has elections next year, and reduce television air time and
campaign spending to fit the limits for one party. The opposition
battled unsuccessfully to relax the law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, the coalition must register formally by Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fox's calculation was that he could continue to build his lead,
PAN officials said. If he is still ahead of Cardenas by an
indisputable margin as the election draws near, the law allows
Cardenas to step aside and deliver his voters to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   PAN officials said they feared that the rank-and-file of
Cardenas' party or the PRI would rig the election against Fox. They
were afraid that an ugly opposition feud over the results in
November, when the PRI is holding its own primary, would sink the
chance for any opposition candidate to win next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't make good sense to accept this proposal because the
risks were just too high,'' said Santiago Creel Miranda, who had
been the most devoted proponent of the alliance within the PAN.
</P>
<P>
   But many Mexicans were saddened by the sense that a historic
opportunity had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Camacho, the head of one of the smaller opposition
parties, said, ``If Vicente Fox is not capable of facing a primary
election when he has a two-to-one advantage, he doesn't deserve to
be the leader of the opposition _ or of Mexico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
