<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9562 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-1STLD-WRITE     09-28 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM FILES FIRST-AMENDMENT SUIT OVER GIULIANI'S THREAT TO END
FUNDING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add 16 grafs in form of 2nd take)  (bl)  
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a pronounced escalation of the political and
cultural conflict over an impending art exhibition, the Brooklyn
Museum of Art on Tuesday filed a lawsuit in federal court accusing
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of violating the First Amendment by
threatening to withdraw city funds from the museum because he finds
some of the artworks offensive and insulting to religion.
</P>
<P>
   In taking the action, the museum abandoned its recent efforts to
resolve the dispute through some form of negotiated compromise;
indeed, the museum's board of trustees voted overwhelmingly Tuesday
to reject Giuliani's request for another day of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   There was no more talk of removing or otherwise segregating
those works that the mayor deems most troubling. By preemptively
filing a lawsuit, museum officials said that they hoped to thrust
the dispute into the constitutional arena of free speech and
expression, thereby undercutting the city's legal strategy of
challenging the exhibit on the narrow grounds that it violates the
museum's lease with the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This litigation is not just about the Brooklyn Museum of
Art,'' said Robert S. Rubin, the chairman of the museum's board of
trustees, during a tense late-afternoon press conference in the
museum's lobby. ``It is being undertaken in the interests of all
public institutions _ museums, universities and libraries _ that
are dedicated to the free exchange of ideas and information, and in
the interests of the people they serve.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The response from City Hall was swift and angry. Although
Giuliani was traveling Tuesday on a political trip to Washington,
D.C., and Las Vegas, Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota described the
mayor's reaction this way: ``The mayor was not surprised by the
level of arrogance shown by the board of the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani immediately ordered city officials to cancel the city's
next scheduled payment to the museum _ $497,554 _ which is due Oct.
1.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he did not appear willing to take more drastic steps to
prevent the exhibition from going forward as planned Saturday. City
officials instead focused their immediate efforts on seizing
control of the museum through what they predicted would be
protracted litigation.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This board has decided to violate state law, violate the
provisions of their lease with the City of New York, and more
importantly violate the bylaws that they operate under,'' said
Lhota, who attended Tuesday's meeting of the museum board along
with city Corporation Counsel Michael Hess. Museum director Arnold
Lehman gave one indication of the museum's newly aggressive posture
when he politely but firmly evicted Hess and Lhota from a podium in
the museum's lobby, where they had paused after the board meeting
to answer reporter's questions. A short time later, Hess summed up
the rising emotions on both sides in a conversation with three
officials outside City Hall. ``We've got a big mess,'' he said.
``We've got World War III now.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, other religious and cultural organizations
joined the fray, staking out positions in a fight rich with
political implications for Giuliani's expected Senate race against
Hillary Rodham Clinton, as well as with legal implications for
publicly-funded art institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the mayor was the Orthodox Union, the nation's
largest association of orthodox Jewish organizations, which issued
a statement Tuesday condemning the exhibit, especially a
dung-stained portrait of the Virgin Mary by the acclaimed British
artist Chris Ofili. ''Displaying a religious symbol splattered with
dung is deeply offensive and can hardly be said to have any
redeeming social or artistic value,'' the organization said.
``Today the offense is perpetrated against a Christian symbol;
tomorrow it might be a Jewish ritual item, and then of another
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Backing the museum was the Cultural Institutions Group, made up
of 33 city museums and arts organizations, which sent a letter to
the mayor Tuesday warning that his actions will have a ``chilling
effect'' on all city-funded museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation that New York City's government-assisted
institutions must make sure that city officials find inoffensive
every future exhibition or performance would cause lasting damage,
not only to the Brooklyn Museum of Art , but to all of our cultural
institutions, and to our City,'' said the letter, which was signed
by such leading cultural figures as Philippe de Montebello,
director of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, and Glenn Lowry,
director of the Modern Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The museum's lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn,
seeks a court order declaring that Giuliani ``may not inflict any
punishment, retaliation or sanction of any kind'' against the
museum for staging the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Such punishment, the suit said, includes terminating the
museum's lease, seizing the museum building, cutting off funding,
or firing the museum's Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is represented by Floyd Abrams, one of the nation's
best-known First Amendment lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether city officials are obligated to finance artwork
they believe to be offensive, Abrams replied: ``There is no
obligation from the city to fund the arts. But the First Amendment
says, according to a wide, sustained, continuing body of case law,
that the funding process may not be used to coerce institutions
such as this to do the bidding of its political leaders. So while
New York never has to fund any museum, once New York starts down
that road, it cannot violate the First Amendment by a process of
coercion, sanction, threats, retribution and the like.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Hess, the corporation counsel, said, ``There's nothing in
the Constitution that says taxpayers should pay for an exhibit like
this, with some of the really disgusting-type paintings that are
being shown.''
</P>
<P>
   In planning its legal attack, the Giuliani administration has
focused on the city's lease with the museum, which dates to 1893
and was signed by the mayor of Brooklyn. The lease requires that
the museum ``shall at all reasonable times be free, open and
accessible to the public and private schools of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have argued that the museum violated that
language by prohibiting children under 17 from attending the
exhibition without adult supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to deflate that argument, the museum board voted Tuesday
to eliminate the age restriction and instead simply post warning
signs advising parents ``of the challenging nature of certain of
the works.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams said: ``There is no denial of access on any theory at
all, and there should be no further talk from the mayor's camp
about leases or 105-year-old documents. This is a First Amendment
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's major cultural institutions have spent days debating
how best to respond to the mayor's threats, according to a series
of e-mail memos describing discussions among members of the
Cultural Institutions Group. The e-mail was provided by a person
who works for one of the institutions and who thought the group's
response should be stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The memos, drafted by the group's chairman, Alan Friedman,
showed that while most of the group's 33 members favored sending a
joint letter to the mayor warning that his actions would set ``a
dangerous precedent,'' other members argued that the group should
remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   Several members, Friedman wrote, noted that ``the mayor tends to
take those who disagree with him as enemies to be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   An administrator of one arts organization that belongs to the
group said Carnegie Hall and the Studio Museum in Harlem were among
those who were reluctant to sign a letter of protest. Officials
from both institutions did not return calls on Tuesday night
seeking comment. Neither institution signed the letter. Friedman,
director of the New York Hall of Science in Queens, argued for
immediate, united opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is challenging the basis of all of our operating
agreements with the contention that if he finds even a single
element of our operations offensive, he is justified in revoking
our funding and our license to use a city-owned building,''
Friedman wrote to members Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Friedman gave this description of his efforts
to forge a consensus among the local museums: ``It's like herding
cats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
