<SLUG> BC-ITALY-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVETTI REJIGGERING TELECOM ITALIA TO PAY DEBT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Olivetti S.p.A., the Italian company that gained control
of Telecom Italia in May, said Tuesday that it was reshuffling the
telecommunications giant in a move that will help repay the debt
Olivetti took on to acquire its larger domestic rival.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Colaninno, the Olivetti chairman who engineered the
takeover, said that Telecom Italia would shift its 60 percent stake
in Telecom Italia Mobile, a lucrative mobile phone unit, to Tecnost
, an Olivetti gambling machine subsidiary. Olivetti owns about 52
percent of Telecom Italia, and Colaninno said that minority
shareholders in Telecom Italia would receive Tecnost shares in
exchange for Telecom Italia Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti had parked the $15.6 billion of debt it took on to
acquire Telecom Italia in Tecnost. But rising interest rates since
the takeover have increased the burden on Tecnost and helped drive
down Olivetti's stock price about 22 percent since its offer for
Telecom Italia shares closed.
</P>
<P>
   Colaninno, announcing the moves at a news conference in Milan,
described them as `'industrial, not financial,'' and said they
would better enable Telecom Italia to aggressively pursue its
business around fixed-line data and Internet transmission, while
Telecom Italia Mobile could expand its thriving cellular phone
business.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile phone unit has been the group's cash cow, making up
for a slower fixed-line phone business. This year, the number of
cellular phones in Italy surpassed the number of fixed-line phones
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Tuesday night after the boards of
Olivetti, Tecnost and Telecom Italia approved the plans at meetings
in Milan, the companies said that Telecom Italia's minority
stockholders would receive between 1.5 and 1.65 Tecnost shares for
each of their own shares in payment for Telecom Italia Mobile. At
current market prices, the 60 percent stake held by Telecom Italia
is worth about $24 billion, so each share of Telecom Italia Mobile
is worth roughly 2.4 Tecnost shares.
</P>
<P>
   To sweeten the offer, the companies said Telecom Italia would
begin a $4.6 billion buyback of up to 742 million of its nonvoting
shares at a price of 6 euros, or $6.30, each. That price, they
said, represents a 12 percent to 14 percent premium over the
average share price of the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   The reshuffling is intended at least in part to route some of
Telecom Italia's cash flow to Tecnost to help pay the debt. Tecnost
is 70 percent-controlled by Olivetti, but the move would cause that
to drop to a level between 41 percent and 43 percent, the companies
said.
</P>
<P>
   The potential losers would be minority shareholders in Telecom
Italia, who would be compensated with the smaller number of Tecnost
shares than the market value of what they are giving up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
