<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTEDBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIFTED' BOSSES FOUND HERE
 AND THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
 
The Gifted Boss: How to Find, Create and Keep Great Employees 
By Dale Dauten (William Morrow and Co., $20) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Syndicated business columnist Dale Dauten's ``The Gifted Boss''
opens with a set of characteristics so uncomplicated they fit on a
single page. It's through the rest of his compact volume that the
ideals he calls ``The Six Realities of Gifted Bosses and Great
Employees'' come to life, illuminated by about 50 individuals and
companies.
</P>
<P>
   He found as many as a dozen of the examples in the balmy Phoenix
metropolitan area, where he lives, and the second-largest batch in
the Twin Cities area, where he has had business ties.
</P>
<P>
   Examples range from John Genzale, now editor of the national
magazine ``SportsBusiness Journal,'' who in spired better staff
writing by holding weekly poetry readings in the news room of the
Phoenix ``Business Journal,'' to Tempe-based Insight Group, whose
founding brothers built their headquarters in the shape of an X to
help ensure that employ ees from all sectors would cross paths.
</P>
<P>
   The book's most touching anecdote tells of the extraordinary
esprit de corps shown by Insight personnel, including Chief
Executive Eric Crown, when a key employee re turned to work after
chemotherapy. Scores of co-workers, including women and the big
boss himself, had their heads shaved in solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps none of the gifted bosses Dauten writes about is a
perfect manager, he concedes, but each illustrates one or more
aspects of what it takes to be great. And sometimes, he points out,
the solu tion to a bad-boss trait is as simple as the advice he
quotes from former Porsche CEO Peter Schutz: ``Stop doing that!''
</P>
<P>
   The book's central message is that the highest function of a
boss is to create ``the best place for the best people to work''
and to focus unlimited attention on recruiting only the type of
people _ ``Wild Brains,'' Dauten calls them _ who immediately
become the star per formers of whatever tasks they take on.
</P>
<P>
   As in Dauten's 1996 book, the equally slim and pithy ``The Max
Strategy: How a Businessman Got Stuck at an Airport and Learned to
Make His Career Take Off'' (the title was imposed on him, he says
rue fully), Dauten lets an eccentric oracle of management, the
fictional Max Elmore, serve as the agent of change. In both books,
the narrator, a middle manager who has caught a whiff of smoke from
impending burnout, rep resents the author himself at critical
stages of his career, Dauten says.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier book was a contempla tion of career paths (skip the
rigid goal-setting exercises you read about elsewhere, because
success is ``usu ally an accident''); innovation (``ex periments
never fail'' if you learn from them); and quality (a favorite
theme: ``Different isn't always better, but better is always
different'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``Gifted,'' retiree Max, described as ``a kid in an aging
body, fizzing with the wisdom of nearly eight decades of
curiosity,'' reconnects in Phoenix with his disciple.
</P>
<P>
   Readers will judge for themselves whether the Max persona rings
true or ultimately distracts as he repeat edly drives home points
by punching the narrator's shoulder, gripping his knee, putting a
fatherly arm around him during a stroll through down town Phoenix
or jabbing a finger or fist into the air.
</P>
<P>
   But physicality aside, Max is one savvy interpreter of how an
earnest manager can keep everyone in an organization so blissfully
productive that the manager's own bosses ``lie awake at night and
thank the Lord that you work for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental task of the best manager is not to manage,''
he counsels. ``The job of the gifted boss is to create a magnetic
environment, one capable of attracting great em ployees _ the kind
who don't need management, who lift up their co-workers and even
their boss.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BOOK'S KEY POINTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``Six Realities of Gifted Bosses and Great Employees'':
</P>
<P>
   1. The ``talent-squared'' workplace is possible because gifted
bosses and great employees want the same things from a workplace:
</P>
<P>
   _ Freedom from management, mediocrity and morons.
</P>
<P>
   _ A change.
</P>
<P>
   _ A chance.
</P>
<P>
   2. Gifted bosses don't just hire employees, they acquire allies.
</P>
<P>
   3. Great employees don't have jobs, they have talents. They
enter the job market once (if at all), and thereafter their talents
are spotted, courted and won over.
</P>
<P>
   4. Great bosses and employees often reverse the typical job
search: Instead of the employee doing the ``hunting,'' it's the
boss. The process more resembles a ``talent search'' than a ``job
market.''
</P>
<P>
   5. While many gifted bosses have created such special work
environments that they have virtually no turnover, many others
embrace substantial turnover and become masters of ``the secret
skill'' of firing.
</P>
<P>
   6. An alliance between a gifted boss and a great employee is a
kinship of talent, often creating a bond that can last a lifetime. &QL; 
 &QL; 
From ``The Gifted Boss,'' copyright 1999 by Dale Dauten, published
by William Morrow and Co. Inc. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-28-99 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990928.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-28 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      09-28 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS NEVER GET STARTED, BUT SURE LOOK FINISHED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sweat had barely beaded around Orel Hershiser's
nose when he slinked back to the dugout, but the blankness in his
face indicated a complete lack of understanding of how this fiasco
could happen _ a helplessness with which the Mets have grown
terribly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The end came quickly and painfully for the Mets on Tuesday
night, much as their season appears to be headed for an abrupt and
galling conclusion. The Atlanta Braves, who began this reign of
terror a week ago, came to Shea Stadium to meet the staggering Mets
and all but dropped an anvil on their heads with a 9-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Mets' seventh loss in a row and kept them a game and
a half behind Houston for the wild-card playoff spot with five
games to play. The Reds beat the Astros, 4-1, in Houston to take
over first place in the National League Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   It tells you something about the quality of a game when the
first spike of excitement is for an enraged relief pitcher, Dennis
Cook of the Mets, who was ejected in the eighth inning for
screaming at the home-plate umpire after he was yanked by the Mets.
Before Cook left the field, he carefully nudged dirt onto home
plate, an act of passion and defiance the Mets only wished they
could replicate at bat.
</P>
<P>
   If the previous six losses were frustrating, then this one _ all
but decided in the first half of the first inning _ was
humiliating. The Mets, who only a week ago were regarded as among
baseball's elite, looked like a team that has hopelessly lost its
way and, occasionally, some of its will, too. Now the Mets must
hope the Reds or Astros, who are battling for the Central title,
drop below them or else they will face an ignominious ending that
will easily eclipse last year's collapse.
</P>
<P>
   With the offense slumping on the Mets' debacle of a road trip,
superb pitching had kept the Mets in every game. But Tuesday night,
Hershiser hadn't been on the mound long enough to even warm up.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Hershiser has typically been good for six innings
and in his previous 10 starts, his earned run average was 3.78.
This time, Hershiser wasn't good for six outs.
</P>
<P>
   His control missing from the beginning, Hershiser plunked Gerald
Williams, the first batter of the game, on the back with his third
pitch. And that was the best Hershiser would do. He fell behind the
rest of the Braves he faced. On a 2-1 count, Bret Boone slapped a
single to right field and Williams, running with the pitch, went to
third. That brought up Chipper Jones, who almost single-handedly
swept the Mets in Atlanta last week. On a 3-2 pitch, he hit a
broken-bat single to right field to score the first run. Such
little damage is considered a victory against Jones these days.
</P>
<P>
   But with runners at the corners, Ryan Klesko, on a 1-0 count,
hit another soft single, this time in the gap between third and
short to score Boone. That was when the boos began. Brian Jordan,
who had been questionable to play because of the sore hand that has
hampered him for week, hit a shallow fly in left field. Rickey
Henderson's throw was off-line, drawing catcher Mike Piazza up the
first-base line, and Jones scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were already down by 3-0, and there was still only one
out. Next up was Andruw Jones. On a 1-0 count, he singled to right
to move Klesko to second. Greg Myers, batting eighth, dinked a 3-0
pitch to short left field to load the bases. The shortstop Jose
Hernandez was next and Hershiser delivered a first-pitch ball.
</P>
<P>
   That was all. The pitching coach Dave Wallace scurried to the
mound and removed Hershiser. No Mets greeted him at the steps of
the dugout. It was the briefest outing of Hershiser's 16-year major
league career _ only one-third of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   When the rookie Octavio Dotel, the reliever, threw a wild pitch
on his first heave, the fourth run of the inning scored. With the
count at 3-0 to Hernandez, Dotel was the recipient of three
straight generous strike calls from the home-plate umpire Alfonzo
Marquez, one of the recently hired umpires. After he walked pitcher
Tom Glavine to load the bases again, Williams _ who had led off the
25-minute half-inning _ flied out to right field, the hardest hit
ball of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser had allowed four runs on five hits, a nightmarish
outing not only for him, but for a team that had scored 12 runs in
its last six games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets finally managed one run in the sixth inning, and had
another chance in the eighth. But that inning was a microcosm of
everything that has gone wrong. The inning opened with a Henderson
double and Shawon Dunston single, but John Olerud flied out, Piazza
grounded out to score the run and Edgardo Alfonzo flied out to end
the inning. One more run, but essentially an act of futility. A
fitting symbol for the Mets long spiral down.
</P>
</TEXT>
