<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WILD CARD CONFUSED THE METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBN-METS-BRAVES) 
(nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While watching the Mets plod, like sleepwalkers on
their way toward an open window, I have wondered why they did not
show more of a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't they get it? They were blowing their whole season,
potentially going down in history for two consecutive late-season
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   At first, I attributed the Mets' serenity to maturity and
professionalism, both admirable traits, and maybe that is true.
They were not playing that terribly, just zombie-like enough to
lose _ and besides, I never use the word ``choke.'' I think it is
an athlete's word, not a journalist's.
</P>
<P>
   But the more I think about it, the Mets have been caught in a
twilight zone between a pennant race and a wild-card race. They
didn't know which way to look.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets look like me on jet lag whenever I go to England. I
step off the curb, look left and nearly get smeared by one of those
double-decker buses bearing down on my right.
</P>
<P>
   In danger of being run down by history, the Mets went catatonic
Tuesday night and rode their losing streak to seven games with a
9-3 loss to Chipper Jones and the other big bullies from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As best as I can figure it out, the Mets' identity crisis is a
result of baseball's expanding the post-season in 1995, adding a
wild-card slot to three divisions in each league.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days it was win the pennant, or else. When Richie
Ashburn threw out Cal Abrams at home and Dick Sisler hit a home run
on the last day of the 1950 season, the Phillies won the pennant
and the Brooklyn Dodgers most emphatically did not. None of this
namby-pamby wild-card business. Sorry, boys of summer. Go home and
sell insurance or tend bar.
</P>
<P>
   Even when baseball went to four divisions in 1969, teams could
put together wonderful seasons, but on the last home game of the
regular season all they could do was wave to their fans and thank
them for their patronage. Tough. I remember Whitey Herzog laughing
after the 1985 season, because Herzog was going to the post-season
and the Mets, who had chased his Cardinals gallantly down the
stretch, were not.
</P>
<P>
   Since baseball got permissive and opened up the post-season from
four teams to eight in 1995, dozens of teams are contenders for the
wild-card spots. This surely adds excitement for the teams on the
fringe. I will never forget good old Donnie Baseball raging at the
suggestion that a wild-card berth wasn't good enough for the 1995
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   I forget the captain's exact words, but the gist of it was:
``Are you people out of your minds? Winning is winning. The whole
thing is getting into the playoffs.'' And Mattingly had the right
to his passion, never having been in the post-season before. The
Yankees did make it, and conducted that epic five-game series with
Seattle, one of the best post-season series I have ever covered,
which more or less justified the wild card in my mind ever since.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a difference between the 1995 Yankees, who
knew they were playing for a wild-card spot, and the 1999 Mets. We
won't get into the leadership skills of Mattingly and Cone, as
opposed to the apparently passive Mets.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Keith Hernandez showed up on the field before last
night's game _ one fan behind the dugout waved a ``17 Hernandez''
shirt _ and undoubtedly the fans would have liked to bottle some of
his urgency and slip it into the veins of these vanilla Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, a transfusion from Knight, Mookie, Lenny,
Wally, Raffy, Bobby O, Roger and the Kid wouldn't hurt, either.
(You ask: How many pennants did that bunch win? Fair question.
Exactly one. But they were a swashbuckling lot, all the same.)
</P>
<P>
   These current blokes obviously wanted to beat the Braves and get
into first place last week, but who is to say they were not
laboring under a false sense of security: Hey, if we can't beat
Chipper Jones, there's always the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets lost three in Atlanta, they fell into a lethargic
groove in Philadelphia (and don't forget, Rickey Henderson was
easily distracted when he was 25 and 30 and 35, too.) Meanwhile,
those delightful small-market, small-budget Reds roared right past
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets can't snap out of it, they will merely be blowing a
wild-card spot, like some marginal hockey or basketball team with a
so-so record. They may never demonstrate the ghastly pall of some
old-time team that knew it had blown a pennant down the stretch.
The fans _ and history _ just might judge the Mets a bit more
harshly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
