<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS EXTENDS SPENDING BY 3 WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to delete `$4.7 billion' from last graf)   (bl)  
 By TIM WEINER  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unable to pass its appropriations bills before the
new fiscal year begins on Friday, Congress resolved on Tuesday to
keep federal agencies functioning for three weeks while Republicans
negotiate with President Clinton over hundreds of billions of
dollars of spending.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the stop-gap spending measure, called a continuing
resolution, has become a nearly annual event. Congress has met the
fiscal deadline only four times in the past 22 years. But this
year, the stakes are higher.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders vowed repeatedly to pass the spending bills
on time, keep them within spending limits Congress imposed in 1997,
and abstain from spending surplus Social Security money to run
government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The first of those promises is now broken. The second will be
broken soon, according to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. And
the third _ the pledge to keep Congress' hands off Social Security
_ is very much in doubt, even though the House on Tuesday passed,
by a 417-2 vote, a non-binding resolution vowing not to spend the
retirement money.
</P>
<P>
   After that vote, Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., one of the staunchest
fiscal conservatives in the Republican ranks, said it was still
possible to keep Congress from spending Social Security surpluses.
``We have a strategy,'' Coburn said. ``We're working on it. We
don't know if it's going to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who routinely spent surplus Social Security money to
run government operations during most of the years from 1955
through 1994 when they controlled the House, where spending bills
originate, ridiculed the non-binding resolution, though almost all
of them voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt compared it to ``saying
we're going to quit smoking while we're having a cigarette.''
</P>
<P>
   Debate on the continuing spending resolution was short and
occasionally bitter. Republicans said little as Democrats chided
them for the failure to pass the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., the ranking minority member on the
House Appropriations Committee, said the Republicans' rhetoric
about spending and Social Security was a form of fiction designed
to delude the American people. ``If it isn't a public lie, it is
the largest fib I have seen in a long time,'' Obey said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla., the chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, who has worked hard but unsuccessfully
this year to keep the spending bills from being mired in politics,
said, ``Sometimes I wish that this were fiction, but it is not.''
</P>
<P>
   The continuing resolution passed the House by a 421-2 vote and
immediately went to the Senate, which approved it, 98-1, after an
equally desultory debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years I've been here,'' said Senate Minority Leader
Tom Daschle, ``I don't recall a time when there's been greater
appropriations disarray than there is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Republican Congress and the White House must spend the
three weeks covered by the continuing resolution in the political
equivalent of hand-to-hand combat, fighting over how to spend
roughly half a trillion dollars of public money.
</P>
<P>
   As the continuing resolution was sent to Clinton, senior
Republicans in the House and Senate sought ways to find billions of
dollars to finance spending bills without tapping into Social
Security money.
</P>
<P>
   They still plan to take back $3 billion in welfare money from
the states, even though the nation's 50 governors _ 31 of whom are
Republicans _ oppose the idea and say Republican leaders promised
them this year that they would not touch the money. ``Congress is
breaking the commitment it made,'' the National Governors'
Association said on Tuesday in a letter to House leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And House Majority Leader Dick Armey said Congress could recoup
$8 billion by changing the way it pays out the earned-income tax
credit. He said the money could be saved by meting out this federal
tax break for working-class wage-earners in monthly payments
instead of in an annual lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senate and House negotiators wrangled over a Pentagon
spending bill of nearly $270 billion, with Lott working to convince
the House to finance construction of a $1.5 billion ship in his
home state.
</P>
<P>
   Congress sent a measure financing energy and water projects to
the White House, completing work on the fifth of its 13 spending
bills this year. And Clinton issued the first of seven vetoes he
and his advisers have threatened against those bills, rejecting a
measure financing federal operations in the District of Columbia,
saying Republican amendments to the bill violated the principle of
home rule for the capital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
