<HEADLINE>
FOUNDRY NETWORKS SHARES UP SIXFOLD IN 1ST DAY OF TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of Foundry Networks Inc., a three-year-old designer of
devices to manage Internet traffic, rose more than sixfold Tuesday
in their first day of trading, the second-sharpest rise ever for a
new stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had predicted a scorching debut for Foundry. The
company is in a fast-growing market that has been extremely
lucrative for investors and, unlike most new Internet businesses,
is already profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the gains were stunning, giving the company a market
capitalization of $8.7 billion. Foundry's shares closed at $156.25,
up $131.25 from the offering price of $25. Just over 5 million
shares were offered, and trading volume topped 12 million on
NASDAQ. The shares peaked at $166.56 in mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The only initial offering to have outpaced that 525 percent gain
was the one of theglobe.com, whose stock jumped 606 percent from a
$9 opening to $63.50 on its first day of trading in November.
Foundry's arrival was more impressive to some analysts because its
initial price was relatively high, with the price set at $25 by the
underwriter, Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the day traders and momentum players are focusing on
it,'' said Mark Basham, Standard &AMP; Poor's new issue stock analyst.
Basham had recommended the offering to investors, predicting that
it would ``double or triple'' on the first day.
</P>
<P>
   Foundry, based in Sunnyvale, Calif., was founded by veterans of
Centillion Networks Inc., a maker of local area network switches
that was sold to Bay Networks in 1995. Bobby Johnson, the chief
executive, president and chairman, holds 21.7 percent of the stock,
worth about $1.89 billion, after the offering, and directors and
officers as a group have 49 percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
   Crosspoint Venture Partners of Woodside, Calif., is the leading
venture firm backing the company, with a 16.1 percent stake now
valued at $12.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Foundry is the latest public offering from a string of young
companies that aim to make Internet business more efficient. Its
major customers include America Online, Hewlett-Packard (which
distributes Foundry products under its own name) and Mitsui.
</P>
<P>
   Foundry's data-switching products work like traffic cops on the
increasingly complicated computer networks used for various
business tasks, especially on the Internet. By parceling out
demands for information efficiently to the many servers that can
fulfill them, they allow businesses to produce more sophisticated
applications, like video and live chat rooms, more quickly for more
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for such services is rising so rapidly that analysts like
Basham project Foundry's revenues, which were just $17 million last
year, will top $110 million this year and double the next year. For
the first six months of the year, the company had net income of
$3.27 million on $39.5 million in revenues. But Foundry hardly has
the field to itself. It must compete with established giants like
Cisco Systems, 3Com and Nortel Networks, along with many start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Some start-ups have been enormously popular with investors
despite their lack of profits. Juniper Networks, which went public
in June at $34, jumped to $98.88 on its first day and ended Tuesday
at $197.25.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Alteon Websystems rose from an initial price of
$19 to $74.94 on its first day of trading last Thursday. It closed
Tuesday at $93.25, down $18.81 in a correction that underscored the
volatility of the new issues. Analysts said Foundry could also
bounce violently in the coming days, but the overall message was
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet networkers are very hot,'' said Peony Kao, an analyst
with Renaissance Capital Corp., a Greenwich, Conn., research firm
for institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Basham said it was hard to justify Foundry's valuation at the
end of Tuesday's trading but that investors need not rush to take
profits since insiders are barred from selling their shares, which
amount to 90 percent of the outstanding stock, for six months. The
short supply of shares could send Foundry's stock still higher in
the near term, he advised.
</P>
</TEXT>
