<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS NOT IN TOWN YET, BUT PROTESTERS ON THEIR WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ There goes the neighborhood. President and his
wife, Hillary, have not even closed the deal on their house here,
and already the first protest march is scheduled for Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In a plan that has both bewildered and annoyed residents here,
representatives from Westpac, a White Plains group that describes
itself as ``an organization working for peace, social justice and
the environment,'' plans to hold a vigil in front of the Clintons'
future home to protest mass killings in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the town of New Castle, which includes this hamlet,
said that they had expected demonstrations after the Clintons had
moved in, but were perplexed about the timing of the event on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they marching in front of the Weisbergs' house?''
Clinton Smith, the Town Supervisor, said, referring to Dr. Jeffrey
Weisberg and his wife, Cheryl, the current owners of the $1.7
million Dutch Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of pitiful,'' Smith said. ``They're protesting in
front of a private residence that has only a tangential
relationship to the president, and they're protesting about a
condition that now is being addressed, with U.N. peace-keeping
forces going into East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jacobs, Westpac's director, said that he was confident the
Clintons would hear about the protest, even though they do not yet
live at the house. He added that he expected 35 to 50 demonstrators
clad in black clothing and carrying candles to march from a
supermarket in town, down a winding state road and onto Old House
Lane to the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very intentionally chosen the most respectful and
quiet form of protest,'' he said, ``without any yelling or hoopla,
in order to disturb the residents of Chappaqua and the soon-to-be
neighbors of President Clinton as little as possible. But we feel
the importance of this message outweighs the inconvenience of the
people of Chappaqua.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that Westpac applied for a permit, which was granted.
But he said it was wrongheaded for protesters to march in the dark
wearing black. There are no sidewalks on Route 117, which was
closed Tuesday for culvert repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Mr. Jacobs wants his message to be heard,'' Smith said.
``I'm sure it will be heard by Dr. and Mrs. Weisberg and the other
residents of Old House Lane and the people who use Route 117. But
if he wants to send a message to the White House, I think Western
Union might be more appropriate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
