<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONALD G. SANDERS DIES AT 69; BROUGHT NIXON TAPING TO LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald G. Sanders, a former Senate lawyer who uncovered the
White House tapes that led to President Richard M. Nixon's
resignation, died on Sunday at a hospital in Columbia, Mo. He was
69.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who lived in Columbia, died of cancer, said his wife,
Dolores.
</P>
<P>
   A former FBI agent, Sanders was a Republican staff lawyer for
the Senate committee investigating the Watergate break-in when he
brought to light ``the smoking gun'' that eventually pointed to
Nixon's complicity in a cover-up of the break-in.
</P>
<P>
   It was during a closed-door preliminary interrogation that
Sanders' curiosity was aroused by seemingly apprehensive answers
from Alexander P. Butterfield, Nixon's former appointments
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders dug deeper and asked if it were possible that some sort
of recording system had been used in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield answered, ``I wish you hadn't asked that question,
but, yes, there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders then hurried to tell Fred D. Thompson, the lead minority
counsel who is now a Republican senator from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both knew then it was important,'' Sanders recalled in a
1997 interview.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in nationally televised hearings, Thompson asked
Butterfield about the recording system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually Don who discovered the existence of the White
House taping system, but he was too unassuming to ever mention
it,'' Thompson said on Monday in an interview with The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders had returned to his home state in the 1980s after more
than two decades of federal government service as a lawyer for
congressional committees, an FBI agent and an assistant secretary
of defense under President Gerald R. Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Gilbert Sanders was born on April 26, 1930, in St. Louis.
He graduated from the law school of the University of Missouri and
then spent two years in the Marines. From 1956 to 1959, he was city
attorney for Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   From 1959 to 1969, Sanders worked for the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, he started working as a lawyer for congressional
committees.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to Missouri, Sanders served as a commissioner in
Boone County in 1989 and 1990, but he did not seek re-election. He
had a private law practice in Columbia until his death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Sanders, while battling cancer, tried to start a
national campaign to draft Thompson for the 2000 Republican
presidential nomination, but Thompson declined to enter the race.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Sanders is survived by two sons,
Michael, of Dallas, and Matthew, of Monrovia, Calif.; a daughter,
Deborah Sanders, of Arlington, Va., and his mother, Ann Sanders of
Columbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
