<HEADLINE>
BUSH VISITS PHOENIX, GETS RHODES', HULL'S ENDORSEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER AND BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - George W. Bush swept into town Sept. 28 to stake
claims on Arizo na's political past and present, winning key
endorsements from former U.S. House Minority Leader John Rhodes and
Gov. Jane Hull.
</P>
<P>
   The venerable Rhodes, the last in a line of state political
giants that included the late Barry Goldwater and Morris Udall, all
but dismissed the candidacy of Arizona's Sen. John McCain, saying
he prefers Bush because McCain cannot be elected.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes' comments echoed those of retiring New York Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, who startled Democrats last week when he en
dorsed Bill Bradley after saying Vice President Al Gore could not
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no substitute for vic tory in politics. The number
two is also last. The campaign which Governor Bush is running is a
winning campaign. . . . Senator Mc Cain would be a good candidate
for anything except the presidency,'' Rhodes said of the man who
took his seat in the U.S. House of Representatives when he retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wanted to run for some thing else _ I have long
supported him, and I probably always would. But not at this time,''
Rhodes added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was honored to receive the endorsements and vowed
to wage an active campaign led by Hull in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got advice for anyone who's running for president: Make
sure you get the governor on your side, particularly if you've got
a governor with a record of accom plishment and a governor as
beloved by the people as Governor Hull,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming a lot to Ari zona. . . . This is a state that is
going to have a contested primary. I look forward to coming to
compete. I know I've got a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After the long buildup over the past week, Hull's endorsement
was something of an anticlimax. She sidestepped questions on
exactly why she picked Bush over McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The governor carefully praised McCain as a great senator and a
hero.
</P>
<P>
   Then she said of Bush, ``I'm supporting a gentleman who I think
is an extremely good governor, someone who I think has vision for
the future, and I believe has the capability of handling any
problem that comes his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hull and Bush took pains to say the event had been planned
for months and was not an attempt to ambush McCain as he traveled
the country for his presidential an nouncement tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been on my calendar for a long time. Never was there
any attempt to try to embarrass my friend. . . . He's a good man,''
Bush said in an interview. ``I've known him for a long time _ I
actually came in and campaigned for him. This was more coincidental
than planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes' comments on McCain prompted questions about whether
McCain would make a good vice president. Bush declined to answer,
saying it was ``presumptuous'' for someone who hadn't won the nomi
nation to talk about the GOP ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was in town to attend a $250,000 fund-raiser that was
ex pected to be attended by 300 people, including Hull, Rhodes,
golfer Tom Lehman, and Arizona businessmen Jim Click and Karl
Eller.
</P>
<P>
   A previous event for the Texas governor in Phoenix raised
$280,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, accompanied by his wife, Laura, seemed to enjoy himself
all day, schmoozing up reporters, vot ers, and just about anybody
he ran into.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Rhodes' house in Mesa, a neighbor shouted across the
street to Bush, asking for a picture. He obliged, delighting Doreen
Karr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best-looking thing I've seen in a long time,'' Karr
said, adding that she told Bush the same thing. ``I think they'll
vote him in on his looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Bushes spent the noon hour lunching with Hull and her
husband, Terry, at Tom's Tavern in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The two governors were seated in the restaurant's ``Governor's
Cor ner,'' which features a prominent picture of Hull and a
not-so-promi nent photo of Hull's predecessor, Fife Symington.
</P>
<P>
   After wolfing down a cheese burger, Bush worked the crowd,
shaking hands and talking baseball with restaurant patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Among those dropping by was Grant Woods, KFYI-AM talk show host
and former state attorney general. Woods, a former staff member of
McCain, said he is supporting Bush and Elizabeth Dole in the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really an impressive guy,'' Woods said of Bush. ``I think
there's a reason why he's winning in Arizona, and there's a reason
why he's winning everywhere else, be cause he's got the right stuff
for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods lauded Hull for having the political courage to endorse
Bush, though most prominent Arizona Republicans have lined up
behind McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Woods noted that he was in a similar position in 1996, when he
was pressured to endorse Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas for the
Republican nomination, but instead backed the eventual nominee, Bob
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about some Mickey Mouse thing,'' Woods said.
``We're talking about who's going to be president of the United
States. I think it's appropriate that you make your own mind up on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he doubts McCain will even survive until the Arizona
primary, which is preceded by the Iowa Caucus and primaries in New
Hampshire and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question about John Mc Cain is: Will he get to Arizona?,''
Woods said. ``He might. But he probably won't. . . . I think
there's a reasonable chance that he won't get here. Bush will be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, Bush visited the Thomas J. Pappas Elementary School
for the homeless in down town Phoenix. He was greeted by a
welcoming committee of students, then toured the school.
</P>
<P>
   Students asked Bush questions during an appearance on the
school's in-house ``radio station,'' which was piped into the
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   The questions were not softballs. The students asked about gun
con trol, education policy and other controversial topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you plan to stop abortions,'' one student asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, to remind people that they should abstain
from sex until they're married,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also read a story, The Very Hungry Caterpillar, to a group
of kindergartners, who kept yelling that he would soon turn into a
butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Bush said, ``you're skip ping ahead.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
