<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GM-UAW-CONTRACT-NYT &LR;      09-28 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-UAW-CONTRACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM AGREES TO 4-YEAR CONTRACT WITH UAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The General Motors Corp. and the United Automobile
Workers union reached agreement on a new, four-year labor contract
late Tuesday night that would give the company's 143,200 factory
workers annual raises of 3 percent plus adjustments for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The union and the company jointly announced the agreement, but
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is significant for workers, of course, because of the
hefty raises. But it is also notable because it might signal that
GM has turned the corner in its previously frosty relations with
the union. The agreement came without a strike, and without the
customary saber-rattling from a frustrated union struggling to get
the company's attention at top levels. Last year, GM lost $2
billion because of a 54-day strike, its 17th strike since 1993.
This year, both the company and the union seemed eager to avoid a
repeat of the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that GM is trying much harder to work with the
union,'' said John A. Casesa, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
``GM's position reflects a genuine desire to pursue a path of
cooperation rather than confrontation and an unwillingness to take
the market share loss that would come with a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes as the auto industry is selling vehicles
nearly as fast as it can build them and earning huge profits, which
it does not want to interrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the GM pact mirror those negotiated by the
DaimlerChrysler Corp., which reached agreement with the union Sept.
16. The union said Monday that DaimlerChrysler workers approved the
agreement by a margin of 86 percent. Later this month, GM workers
are expected to vote to ratify the contract language the union and
the company settled on Tuesday night, which, like the
DaimlerChrysler agreement, also provides for a $1,350 signing
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an expensive contract, but given the fact that the
companies are making record sales and earnings and have a strong
cash flow, it is hard for them to plead poverty,'' said David B.
Healy, an analyst at Burnham Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen P. Yokich, the union president, said last week that this
year's labor contracts would allow workers to share in the
prosperity of their companies, ``It is our turn now that things are
good,'' he said after briefing local union leaders on the deal
reached with DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good contract,'' he said of that agreement, which
has the same principal terms as the one reached with General Motors
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yokich personally negotiated with GM's chairman, John F. Smith
Jr., during the last three days to reach the deal, company
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The union is expected to turn its attention later this week to
the Ford Motor Co. Three-year labor agreements at the three
companies expired Sept. 14, but have been extended as the union
negotiations continue. The new, four-year contracts cover 400,000
factory workers at the three companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is likely to make a similar deal with the union, but
negotiations may not go as smoothly as they have at DaimlerChrysler
and GM. The reason is that workers building auto parts at Ford's
Visteon subsidiary are nervous that their jobs and wages will be
less secure if Ford follows through on its plans to sell Visteon.
</P>
<P>
   According to the union, DaimlerChrysler agreed to language in
the contract barring sales or spinoffs of assets, which had little
impact on DaimlerChrysler because it had no immediate plans to sell
chunks of the company. But because the union typically reaches
agreement with one company, then forces the others to accept the
same terms, the clause may make it more difficult, or more
expensive, for Ford to reach a deal with the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong anti-spinoff language in the DaimlerChrysler
contract is a real problem,'' Healy said. ``I don't know how they
are going to solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is that the union will agree to allow Ford to
sell Visteon provided it follows the example of General Motors,
which spun off its Delphi auto parts division to shareholders in
May. The terms of the new GM contract apply to Delphi's 48,000
workers, according to the announcement Tuesday that the union had
reached a deal with GM.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to at least temporarily put its past antagonistic labor
relations behind, GM last year put Gary L. Cowger in charge of
negotiations as GM's group vice president for labor relations.
Cowger is a former factory manager with excellent union contacts
who was running GM's German operations at the time.
</P>
<P>
   GM's president, G. Richard Wagoner Jr., and its senior vice
president for North American manufacturing, Donald E. Hackworth,
handled much of last summer's negotiations with the UAW but did not
get along well with union leaders. Hackworth in particular ended up
on poor terms with the union, mainly because he strongly criticized
union leaders in several voice mail messages that he recorded and
put on a toll-free number for GM employees to call. Union leaders
also found that they tended to be considerably older and had little
in common with Wagoner, who is only 46.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McAlinden, an auto industry labor economics expert at the
University of Michigan, said that GM's personnel change had
improved matters. ``The important thing at GM was the personalities
there changed from Wagoner and Hackworth to Cowger, and that made
the difference,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
