A9697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GOLD-PRICE-RALLY-NYT &LR;      09-28 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLD-PRICE-RALLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLD PRICE RISES $28.20, ITS HIGHEST IN ABOUT 2 DECADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of gold surged $28.20, or 9 percent, to $308.10 an
ounce Tuesday, the biggest one-day rally in almost two decades.
Since last Tuesday, the price of gold has jumped $53.10, or 20.8
percent, wiping out all the losses for this year, and it is now the
highest it has been since April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's rally followed a $14 jump in the price Monday after 15
European central banks said Sunday that they would limit their
sales of gold to 400 tons a year for the next five years. That
pledge removed the fear that central bank gold sales would swamp
the market, pushing the price lower.
</P>
<P>
   The central banks also said they would limit their leasing of
gold. Borrowed gold is needed by speculators to bet on price
declines and by producers to sell gold now to lock in prices.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's buying, according to analysts, was fueled by
speculators who had bet that the price of gold would continue to
fall and by producers who are now waiting to see where the price
will settle.
</P>
<P>
   The speculators, known as short sellers, borrowed gold and sold
it. If the price declined, they could buy it back at the lower
price, return the borrowed gold and profit on the difference
between the two prices. But with the price of gold rising rapidly
they had to buy back gold as quickly as possible to limit their
losses. This kind of panic buying often pushes markets higher
rapidly and then peters out.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, producers who had been selling borrowed gold
to lock in prices against future production seem to be standing on
the sidelines. Although they were not buying, the absence of their
selling removed a barrier to the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Ward, the mining analyst at Lehman Brothers, said the
investors who thought the price had moved too high too fast were
also unwilling to bet against it because the cost of borrowing the
gold needed for such a short sell is so high. Tuesday, short-term
leasing rates for gold were 5 percent, Ward said, well above the
average of just of 1 percent since 1992, according to Gold Fields
Mineral Services, a London-based precious metals research firm.
``It is not that attractive for shorts to re-establish their
positions at this level,'' Ward said, because the borrowing rate
for gold is so high.
</P>
<P>
   Ward also said that a rising seasonal demand for jewelry would
give an added impetus to the gold price now.
</P>
<P>
   The question is how much further this rally can go. In the
longer term, Ward said he did not think the price could stay above
$300 an ounce because demand for jewelry would drop off and more
gold mines would keep producing rather than shutting down. Both
moves, he said, would add to the overall supply of gold and push
the price lower.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the limit on gold sales agreed to by the 15 central
banks actually would allow for more sales than he had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   While the rally in gold pushed up many gold mining stocks, some
fell Tuesday. Barrick Gold Corp. slipped 25 cents, to $23.875,
after jumping $3.9375 on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
