r a BC-BRADLEY-STUMP-LADN     09-28 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-STUMP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY OFFERS SWEEPING HEATH CARE PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Presidential hopeful Bill Bradley came to the San
Fernando Valley on Tuesday to unveil what he admits is a costly,
$65 billion plan that would guarantee health care for every
American, part of his ``big ideas'' approach in seeking the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The former U.S. senator from New Jersey said every American has
a right to good health care from birth through their senior years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of my father, who had health problems, when I think
about health care because I believe that every American deserves
what my father got _ the helping hands to a productive life,''
Bradley said to about 500 students and supporters inside an
assembly hall at Los Angeles Valley College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good health is a blessing, not a guarantee. But good health
care is a right, and it is up to us to ensure that right to every
American.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is seeking the nomination against Vice President Al
Gore, who has proposed a more modest plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's plan would allow Americans to enroll in the same
coverage provided members of Congress and federal employees. There
would be subsidies for the poor and tax breaks for all Americans
who pay insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Parents would be required to enroll children in their
employee-provided health plans or a federally approved system of
private health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare would be expanded to provide the elderly with uncapped
prescription drug benefits for chronic and catastrophic illnesses,
and the plan provides a system of integrated medical and social
services to reduce nursing home admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley acknowledged the high cost but contended no new taxes
would be needed. He said it could be paid for from federal budget
surpluses without touching Social Security surpluses, and through
savings on costs for unnecessary care, redundant tests and
excessive administration costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to America's health, this is not the time to be
timid. It requires bold action and a national commitment from the
president on down to make certain that every American has what
should be an American birthright.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign countered that Bradley's plan is too costly and
won't leave funding for the Medicare Trust Fund or other
investments, such as education and reducing the national debt. The
Gore campaign also said Bradley's plan would create a new federal
bureaucracy and could give employers an incentive to drop current
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed giving states more money to provide health
coverage for children. Children in families earning up to 250
percent of poverty-level income would qualify for federally
supported state coverage, up from 200 percent now. Families earning
more and lacking insurance could buy into the state program. There
is no cost estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the leading Republican candidate, has
called for expanding medical savings accounts and strengthening tax
incentives to small businesses that provide health care to
employees. Another possible change is limiting Medicare benefits
for seniors with higher incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Those reforms don't go far enough for Bradley, who said the 45
million uninsured Americans shouldn't have to face illness alone.
``The time has come to right these wrongs in our health care
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said, in a reference to Gore's plan, that ``it is
irresponsible to commit to new programs without also laying the
costs before the public so that we can decide together how to pay
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   By unveiling such a critical issue in Los Angeles, Bradley
demonstrated how important California is in his bid to upset Gore
for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Valley College crowd who said they weren't Bradley
supporters indicated he could do well in California because he
doesn't seem like a politician making promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems real down to earth. He seems to have real
solutions,'' said Jeremy Oberstein, a freshman. ``He made us feel
he wasn't a politician on a stage, but someone talking to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandra Mundon, a freshman from nearby Sherman Oaks, said,
``I've had lots of health problems the past few years and I liked
what he said about the patients being first. Politicians, when they
speak, it's really rare that someone my age can connect with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's appearance opened a four-day swing through the state.
He is one of several candidates, including Republicans Bush, Steve
Forbes and Elizabeth Dole, in California this week.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
