<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO PICKS FIVE FAB FROSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Twelve members of UCLA's 18-man freshman class are
sitting out the season as redshirts. Asked recently to name the
best of the dozen, coach Bob Toledo mentioned five:
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; !off! &LR; Dave and Mat(cq) Ball, the identical twins from
Dixon, Calif. Dave plays defensive end, Mat plays linebacker, and
unlike the Webb twins, both have an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to contribute quite a bit,'' Toledo said.
``They're going to be leaders. They're very athletic and they have
a mean streak.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; !off! &LR; Defensive tackle Rodney Leisle, a 300-pounder from
Bakersfield who missed the start of training camp with a broken
foot. The Bruins hope he'll evolve into a dependable run stopper at
what has traditionally been their weakest position.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hadn't been hurt at the start, he might have been an
impact guy,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; !off! &LR; Shane Lehmann, a 285-pound guard from Corona.
Talent isn't the reason freshman Bryce Bohlander plays while
Lehmann sits. It's a matter of need. The Bruins were short one
tackle (Bohlander's position) early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; !off! &LR; Jerry Owens, a 180-pound receiver from Hart High.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really pleased with him,'' Toledo said. ``He has
excellent hands and good speed. He's going to be a good receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!You look marvelous:!off! The Bruins want quarterback Cory
Paus to wear a sternum jacket under his shoulder pads to protect
his bruised ribs, but he's resisting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a bulletproof vest,'' Paus said. ``And it looks
funny. If you don't feel like you look good, you don't play good.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Arizona State update:!off! Sun Devils quarterback Ryan
Kealy also has bruised ribs and is questionable for Saturday's
game. He suffered the injury against Cal and did not finish the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't know until later in the week,'' ASU coach Bruce Snyder
said of Kealy's availability.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!The highs and lows:!off! One of the most common football
injuries is the high ankle sprain. It's considered more serious
than low sprains and has slowed receiver Danny Farmer, tailback
DeShaun Foster and guard Mike Saffer this season.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``high sprain'' is a relatively new term, UCLA head
athletic trainer Geoff Schaadt said it's not a new injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the ACL (anterior cruciate ligament) was 10 years
ago _ we just understand much better what we're dealing with,''
Schaadt said.
</P>
<P>
   A low sprain occurs when the ankle rolls inward and the outside
of the foot almost touches the ground. Athletes usually recover in
a few hours or days, depending on the severity.
</P>
<P>
   A high sprain occurs when the ankle rolls outward and the inside
of the foot hits the ground. This causes the fibula to separate
from the tibia _ the large, weight-bearing bone in the lower leg _
and damages the ligaments above the ankle bone. Players often need
weeks to recover from high sprains.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Injury update:!off! Foster (sprained ankle) did not
practice Tuesday and probably won't today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very iffy and if he doesn't practice (today), I'll
probably start Keith Brown,'' Toledo said. ``We'll be very lucky to
get him by game time.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Brian Poli-Dixon (broken wrist) might not require
surgery because the damaged bone has not been displaced. He'll wear
a cast for a month, then doctors will re-examine the break. At that
point, he'll either have surgery or spend another month in a cast.
</P>
<P>
   Of cornerback Jason Bell's injured right heel, Schaadt said:
``It's taking a lot longer (to heal) than I anticipated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
