<HEADLINE>
WAIT PAYS OFF FOR LANDRIGAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Last spring, Charlie Landrigan was told he might
want to consider transferring to another school. This week, he's
USC's starting fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently buried behind Brennan Ochs and Chad Pierson last May,
it was suggested to Landrigan by coaches he might want to look
elsewhere if he didn't like playing on the scout team. But
Landrigan said he never considered leaving USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just sat down and talked about my role,'' Landrigan said.
``I think they wanted to see if I was happy. Is (the scout team)
something I'd want or would I be happier somewhere else?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't look at it that way. I was optimistic about the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Landrigan's persistence paid off this week, when he will start
his first game at fullback after a good performance against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get used to things for two years and then thrust into a
new role,'' Landrigan said. ``I'm thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   __ A real comic: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward had a career-high
12 catches against Oregon but joked afterward that USC did better
when he wasn't the focal point of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they should keep taking me out of the offense, because
we were winning before,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   Was Soward referring to the USC coaches or opposing teams?
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Line woes: Offensive line coach Steve Greatwood is among the
coaches exasperated over the penalties, especially after the line
committed nine against Oregon. So he has threatened to pull a
player out of a game if an infraction is committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as coaches right now are exhausted. We don't know what else
to do,'' Greatwood said. ``I just have to make a conscious effort
to come down on guys who get sloppy with their hands. We have
developed a reputation, whether it's earned or not. Other teams get
away with it. We don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Greatwood was also disappointed by the line's reaction to the
crowd noise at Autzen Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't keep our poise as well as I expected to,'' Greatwood
said. ``I'll take the blame for that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Position changes: USC has moved sophomore Darryl Knight from
linebacker to tight end, and tight end Pat Swanson will no longer
play the position, so he can concentrate on long-snapping. He had
problems snapping against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are zeroing in on playing tight end, human nature
says you split your focus,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``We've
got to give the kicker the best chance to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Swanson caught two passes for 37 yards against Oregon, his first
receptions of his career. Scott Huber will be the blocking tight
end and Antoine Harris the pass-catching tight end in double-tight
end situations.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hayes doubtful: Wide receiver Windrell Hayes (sprained ankle)
remains doubtful this week. Offensive guard Donta Kendrick has a
sprained ankle, but it is not considered serious.
</P>
<P>
   __ Denmon examined: Center Eric Denmon has a nagging knee injury
that caused him to miss the second half against Oregon and had team
doctors mulling a magnetic resonance imaging test Tuesday night.
His status for the game is uncertain.
</P>
</TEXT>
